<TITLE>Campaign slogan wit's not dead; it just faded away</TITLE>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<!--Connections 32 Template - Features Menu Page--><!--Use the Headline for HTML Page Title--><!--Headline-->
<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i><!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Date Here--><!--Date--></i> </td>
        <td width="470"><!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Story Text Here--><!--FIRST STORY TEMPLATE--> <font size="6"><b>Campaign slogan wit's
        not dead; it just faded away</b></font><br>
<!--SUBHEAD-->        <p><font size="2"><i>By Sam Venable News-Sentinel
        Columnist</i></font></p>
        <p><font size="2"><!--dateline--></font><br>
        <font size="5">I</font>f you liked Ike or were madly for
        Adlai, you're probably quite lonely these days. </p>
        <p>Catchy political jingles and slogans have long since
        gone the way of Burma Shave signs and five-cent Cokes. If
        I'm not mistaken, Jimmy Carter's ''The Grin Will Win'' in
        1976 was the last decent campaign rhyme spoken from coast
        to coast. </p>
        <p>Ah, but back in the days of your father's politics,
        there were some gems. I perused Laurence Urdang's book,
        ''Slogans'' at Lawson McGhee Library the other day and
        found examples like: </p>
        <p>* ''Make the White House the Dwight House'' and ''The
        Mighty Tower -- Eisenhower.'' Dwight Eisenhower, 1952,
        1956. </p>
        <p>* ''Adlai and Estes are the bestes.'' Adlai Stevenson
        and Estes Kefauver, 1956. </p>
        <p>* ''My pick is Dick.'' Richard Nixon, 1960. </p>
        <p>* ''LBJ for the USA.'' Lyndon Johnson, 1964. </p>
        <p>But if you're looking for a jingle in the '90s, you'd
        better stick with grainy sit-coms on Nick At Night
        instead watching the 6 o'clock news. </p>
        <p>''It's something I hadn't thought much about, but it's
        true,'' said Dr. Bill Lyons, a political science
        professor at the University of Tennessee. ''Rhymes are
        relics.'' </p>
        <p>How come? </p>
        <p>''A variety of reasons,'' Lyons answered. ''They
        probably reached a saturation point with voters some
        years ago. In addition, jingles don't work as well on TV
        as they did on radio and on buttons. </p>
        <p>''For that matter, you don't see as many buttons and
        bumper stickers as you used to. Certainly not catchy
        ones. About all you see are the names of the candidates
        themselves. </p>
        <p>''A lot of campaigning is done by direct mail these
        days. Also, negative campaigning doesn't lend itself
        quite as well to jingles.'' </p>
        <p>I'm not so sure about that, prof. </p>
        <p>Flip through a few more pages of ''Slogans'' with me
        and you may recall some acidic zingers along the lines
        of: </p>
        <p>* ''In Hoover we trusted, now we are busted.''
        Franklin Delano Roosevelt, 1932. </p>
        <p>* ''Phooey on Dewey.'' Harry Truman, 1948. </p>
        <p>* ''Hari-Kari with Barry.'' Lyndon Johnson, 1964. </p>
        <p>* ''Nixon and Spiro -- Zero.'' Hubert Humphrey, 1968. </p>
        <p>For better or for worse, though, I'd like to see a
        jingle comeback. If Bob Dole can send the Dodgers back to
        Brooklyn, why can't we all turn back the clock a few
        years? </p>
        <p>Even yawners like ''I'm not hintin' -- I'm all for
        Clinton!'' or ''On a roll with Bob Dole!'' would be
        welcome. </p>
        <p>''Bill and Al -- they're my pal!'' mayhaps? </p>
        <p>No? Then how does ''Bob and Jack are on the right
        track!'' sound? </p>
        <p>Still no go? Then let's try it on the down-and-dirty
        side: </p>
        <p>''Throw Bill and Gore straight out the door!'' </p>
        <p>''Big bu$ine$$ $pent on Dole and Kemp!'' </p>
        <p>Hmmm. Yeah, you're right. They smell pretty bad. </p>
        <p>But not as much as the bovine-processed promises both
        candidates are delivering. </p>
        <p>Sam Venable's column appears in The News-Sentinel on
        Sunday, Tuesday, Thursday and Friday. His column also is
        available on our Web site at www.knoxnews.com. His latest
        book, ''I'd Rather Be Ugly Than Stuppid,'' is now
        available from The News-Sentinel and area bookstores. </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

<hr size="5">

