<TITLE>A rotten pumpkin won&#39;t roll very far without busting</TITLE>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<!--Connections 32 Template - Features Menu Page--><!--Use the Headline for HTML Page Title--><!--Headline-->
<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i><!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Date Here--><!--Date--></i> </td>
        <td width="470"><!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Story Text Here--><!--FIRST STORY TEMPLATE-->
				<FONT SIZE="+3"><B>A rotten pumpkin won&#39;t roll very far without busting</B></FONT><BR><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
				<FONT size="-1"><I>By Sam Venable, Columnist</I></FONT><P>
				<FONT SIZE="-1"><!--dateline--></FONT></DIV></B><BR>
				<FONT SIZE="+2">D</FONT>espite what politicians, military leaders and business executives might argue to the contrary, bigger isn&#39;t always better.
<P>   This is particularly true with pumpkins.
<P>   Sure, those jumbo jobs are something to look at. They make great newspaper photos this time of year. And they&#39;re worth some serious money.
<P>   Nathan and Paula Zehr of Lowville, N.Y., won $50,000 earlier this month from the World Pumpkin Confederation. The Zehrs submitted a 1,061-pounder, the heaviest ever recorded.
<P>   Bill Greer of Picton, Ontario, also topped the half-ton mark. His entry, certified by the Greater Pumpkin Commonwealth, weighed 1,006 pounds and won $3,000.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Prize money is just the start,&#39;&#39; says George Kilgore, agricultural extension agent in Fentress County and an expert on whopper pumpkins. &#39;&#39;The endorsements from seed companies and fertilizer manufacturers can really kick it on up.&#39;&#39;
<P>   The difference between a thousand-pounder and your average store-bought pumpkin is about like that of a pea and a watermelon.
<P>   Kilgore says a typical pumpkin, like the millions that will glow as jack-o&#39;-lanterns on porches throughout America tonight, weighs only about 20 pounds -- even if it seemed like 100 when you carried it in from the car.
<P>   But, fortunately for homeowners, that is the relative beauty of an average pumpkin: Once Halloween&#39;s over, there&#39;s not much to get rid of.
<P>   You can stuff it into the trash, compost it or turn it into pies. Try doing that with one of those sumo wrestler specimens that didn&#39;t quite make the short list.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Scotty Blair grew one this summer that weighed 641 pounds,&#39;&#39; Kilgore said with a laugh. &#39;&#39;It&#39;s sittin&#39; outside his home in Allardt. There&#39;s just not much else you can do with a pumpkin that size.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Especially when the stink sets in.
<P>   You know how bad a standard pumpkin smells when it goes bad? Multiply that by several hundred pounds.
<P>   &#39;&#39;There ain&#39;t nothing you can step in that&#39;s any worse,&#39;&#39; said Steve Jones, a Clinton grower who supplies thousands of pumpkins for the East Tennessee market. &#39;&#39;A rotten pumpkin is sorta like a Christmas tree in February, but at least the tree doesn&#39;t smell bad.&#39;&#39;
<P>   This is when bigger becomes badder.
<P>   &#39;&#39;The worst story I&#39;ve ever heard happened a couple of years ago to Martha Foster,&#39;&#39; Jones related. &#39;&#39;Her husband, Lynn, is agent manager for the Farm Bureau here.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I took a couple of 200-pounders to a Farm Bureau meeting, and Lynn won one of them as a door prize. He lugged it home and put it in a display in his front yard.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Like fish and house guests, the pumpkin eventually wore out its welcome. Near Thanksgiving, the Fosters noticed it was getting a little flat, so Martha tried to roll it to the driveway where Lynn could haul it off.
<P>   &#39;&#39;It busted and she went head-first inside,&#39;&#39; said Jones. &#39;&#39;The way Lynn tells it, she went in up to her shoulders.&#39;&#39;
<P>   It was definitely a door prize to remember.
<P>
<P>
<P><font size=2><strong>Sam Venable&#39;s column appears in The News-Sentinel on Sunday, Tuesday, Thursday and Friday. His column also is available on our Web site at www.knoxnews.com. His latest book, &#39;&#39;I&#39;d Rather Be Ugly Than Stuppid,&#39;&#39; is now available from The News-Sentinel and area bookstores.</strong></font>
<P>

        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

