<TITLE>Autumn fallout: Stubborn rakes make him bristle</TITLE>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<!--Connections 32 Template - Features Menu Page--><!--Use the Headline for HTML Page Title--><!--Headline-->
<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i>November 01, 1996</i></td>
        <td width="470"><font size="6"><b>Autumn fallout:
        Stubborn rakes make him bristle</b></font><br>
<!--SUBHEAD-->        <p><font size="2"><i>By Sam Venable News-Sentinel
        Columnist</i></font></p>
        <p><font size="2"><!--dateline--></font><br>
        <font size="5">D</font>eep thoughts that crossed my mind
        while I was engaged in hand-to-leaf combat: </p>
        <p>* This country can do without a five-cent cigar and a
        better mousetrap. But we desperately need a self-cleaning
        rake. </p>
        <p>Raking would be a much more enjoyable task if the
        hateful teeth wouldn't clog up every other stroke. </p>
        <p>It's bad enough when you are attacking mounds of big
        leaves like maple, oak or dogwood. At least they have the
        decency to give you a few swipes in relative comfort
        before balling up. </p>
        <p>But pine needles -- or ''pine straw,'' as some
        Southerners call this seasonal mess -- are a nightmare.
        Particularly the long, silky needles of white pines that
        shower down like a muddy waterfall. </p>
        <p>They might as well be iron filings and your rake a
        magnet. One pass and -- glooommm -- the rake is nothing
        but an amber fuzzball. You have to stop, pull the cussed
        things out, and make one more sweep before -- glooommm --
        everything jams up again. </p>
        <p>Between downsized cybernerds in California and nuclear
        physicists at Oak Ridge who don't have any more bombs to
        build, somebody oughta be able to design a rake that
        cleans itself. </p>
        <p>This close to election day, I'm surprised Bob Dole or
        Bill Clinton hasn't promised $50 million in rake
        research. </p>
        <p>* How come trees never grow until it's time to gather
        their leaves? </p>
        <p>You stick a sapling into the ground, stake it against
        the wind, water it faithfully and what happens? </p>
        <p>Nothing. The ingrate stands there twiddling its
        cambium, a fuzzy faced vegetative teenager who stubbornly
        refuses to mature. </p>
        <p>Then one October morning -- ziiiiiip -- that wimpy
        little broom switch suddenly evolves into a giant sequoia
        and drops 450 tons of leaves. By the next April --
        zuuuuuup -- it's back to a dwarf again. </p>
        <p>Botanists claim the process doesn't work this way, but
        don't believe 'em. I have seen this phenomenon occur,
        year after year, in my own yard. </p>
        <p>* Is this not the warmest autumn we've had in eons? </p>
        <p>A couple of days ago, I had to soak myself in
        repellent to keep the mosquitoes at bay. If this was the
        Deep South, perhaps I could understand. But clouds of
        skeeters in hillbilly East Tennessee in late October? </p>
        <p>And get this: I have two irises in the front yard that
        are pregnant with blooms, just like it was the first of
        May. </p>
        <p>I strongly suspect a link, direct or otherwise, to two
        consecutive victories over Alabama. </p>
        <p>* Since our yard contains many different species of
        deciduous trees that drop their leaves over a wide span
        of time, I ask myself this question every fall: </p>
        <p>Is it more efficient to make several light rakings as
        the leaves accumulate, or one mega-dose after the deed is
        finally done? </p>
        <p>I have tried both. And I've come to the conclusion
        that the best way is to pay someone else to do it. </p>
        <p>Sam Venable's column appears in The News-Sentinel on
        Sunday, Tuesday, Thursday and Friday. His column also is
        available on our Web site at www.knoxnews.com. His latest
        book, ''I'd Rather Be Ugly Than Stuppid,'' is now
        available from The News-Sentinel and area bookstores. </p>
        <p>-50 </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

