<TITLE>Southern manners irritating to some Yankee immigrants</TITLE>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<!--Connections 32 Template - Features Menu Page--><!--Use the Headline for HTML Page TITLE>--><!--Headline-->
<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i>November 03, 1996</i></td>
        <td width="470"><font size="6"><b>Southern manners
        irritating to some Yankee immigrants</b></font><br>
<!--SUBHEAD-->        <p><font size="2"><i>By Sam Venable News-Sentinel
        Columnist</i></font></p>
        <p><font size="2"><!--dateline--></font><br>
        <font size="5">C</font>onsider: </p>
        <p>* I was in the express line of a grocery store the
        other night, carrying a box of cereal and a half-gallon
        of milk. The clerk took one glance and said, ''Looks like
        you're doing the cooking tonight.'' We both chuckled and
        made small talk as the transaction was completed. </p>
        <p>* Driving away from the store, I reached an
        intersection and was preparing to turn left. As I rolled
        to a stop, another car approached from the left. Its blinker
        indicated the driver wanted to pull into my lane of
        traffic. I flicked my headlights to say ''OK.'' He
        accelerated and flicked his own headlights, ''Thanks.'' </p>
        <p>* On the road near home, I saw one of my neighbors
        standing under the light beside his garage. I toot-tooted
        my horn to convey ''Hi.'' He threw his head back to
        indicate ''Hi to you.'' </p>
        <p>Three typical events of everyday friendliness and
        courtesy, wouldn't you say? The sort of no-brainer
        manners your mama and daddy taught by example? </p>
        <p>Not according to The Wall Street Journal. </p>
        <p>To hear this learned publication tell it, our actions
        were ''primarily manipulative,'' designed to get what we
        wanted as quickly as possible. </p>
        <p>I am not making this up. Go look at last Tuesday's
        edition and see for yourself. </p>
        <p>A front-page article by WSJ staffer Eleena De Lisser
        described how Yankees who have moved to the South have
        found yet another quirk about Dixie that ticks them off:
        Courtesy. </p>
        <p>I quote from the article: </p>
        <p>''It's the most irritating thing I can think of,''
        complains Diane Kuhn, an ex-New Yorker now living in
        Nashville, referring to the South's idea of highway
        hospitality. ''Drivers will let 12 cars enter their lane.
        I say you let one in. Maybe. If you're in a good mood.'' </p>
        <p>There's more: ''On any given day in the melting-pot
        South, simple 'hellos' uttered by strangers perplex folks
        from elsewhere ('Who was that?'). 'Yes, ma'ams' and 'no,
        sirs' strike some outsiders not as signs of respect but
        as unwanted reminders of one's advancing age. Favors
        extended -- an offer to house-sit or an automobile ride
        across town -- arouse suspicion.'' </p>
        <p>And another: Tina Spencer, a Philadelphia native who
        now lives in Acworth, Ga., bristles when a checkout clerk
        engages her in conversation: ''First you try to give them
        The Look and don't respond. But there are times I've had
        to physically take stuff out of their hands to stop the
        chitchat.'' </p>
        <p>It's nothing new, of course. Those of us who grew up
        in the South are used to being bashed by Northern
        invaders. </p>
        <p>We've been told dozens of times how much faster the
        snow is removed where they came from. And how much better
        the streets are. And how much more progressive the
        schools are. And how everyone's a much better driver. </p>
        <p>And now, we buffoons discover, human life is better Up
        Yonder because the people are rude. </p>
        <p>I defer to the late Louis Grizzard's marvelous
        comeback for such instances: ''Delta is ready when you
        are.'' </p>
        <p>And Honey, we'd be more than happy to give y'all
        directions to the airport. </p>
        <p>Sam Venable's column appears in The News-Sentinel on
        Sunday, Tuesday, Thursday and Friday. His latest book,
        ''I'd Rather Be Ugly Than Stuppid,'' is now available
        from The News-Sentinel and area bookstores. </p>
        <p>-50 </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

