<!--Connections 32 Template - Features Menu Page-->

<html>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head><TITLE>&#39;Best laid schemes o&#39; mice and men gang aft a-gley&#39</TITLE>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i><!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Date Here--><!--Date--></i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
		<!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Story Text Here--><!--FIRST STORY TEMPLATE-->
				<FONT SIZE="+3"><B>&#39;Best laid schemes o&#39; mice and men gang aft a-gley&#39;</B></FONT><BR><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
				<FONT size="-1"><I>By Sam Venable, Columnist</I></FONT><P>
				<FONT SIZE="-1"><!--dateline--></FONT></DIV></B><BR>
				<FONT SIZE="+2">I</FONT>f anyone can sympathize with Knox County election officials these days, it&#39;s gotta be University of Tennessee Head Football Coach Phillip Fulmer.
<P>   Think about it: Both had plenty of time to prepare for The Big One They Absolutely, Positively Cannot Afford to Blow.
<P>   And yet what happened to both?
<P>   They blew it.
<P>   For Fulmer, disaster struck Sept. 21 when Florida manhandled the Vols, 35-29. Despite a year of overall preparation and two full weeks of beat-the-Gators intensity, UT spent the first two quarters of the game digging itself into a 35-0 canyon. A gallant Vol comeback effort helped carve the deficit for statistical purposes, but the damage was long-since done.
<P>   For election officials, the nightmare-come-true arrived Tuesday when they sat down to count votes in the Knoxville-Knox County unification referendum.
<P>   Never mind that the unification charter commission had been working for a year to set the election in motion. Never mind that anti-unification forces had rallied to fight back. Never mind that early voters had been marking their ballots for more than two weeks. Never mind that officials knew the measure had to pass in both the city and county to be adopted.
<P>   In spite of all those months of preparation, all that money spent by both sides, all those meetings, all those public hearings, all that planning, all those speeches, all those billboards, all those commercials for and against, and all the stories and editorials in newspapers and on radio and TV, everything -- boooiiing! -- blew a mainspring as the score was being tallied.
<P>   Why?
<P>   Because, incredibly, some of the machines used in early voting apparently weren&#39;t programmed to separate city residents from county residents.
<P>   Hoo-boy. And these boneheads are the experts we trust to run our elections?
<P>   This itty-bitty detail could have voided the entire unification decision and sent the proposal back before voters for yet another campaign. As it was, unification was defeated by a large-enough margin that the blunder didn&#39;t matter.
<P>   Still, the questions remain: How in the name of common sense can a mistake like this go undetected until the 11th hour? Was there no trial run, no shakedown to work out the bugs? Who&#39;s in charge? Who&#39;s on first?
<P>   As I type these words, I daresay everyone involved in the election process in Knox County is busily covering his or her rear end to blame this snafu on either: (1) a computer or (2) someone else. In the next couple of days, we&#39;ll see more buck-passing than occurred during the U.S. House banking scandal. And then the bloodletting will commence.
<P>   That, fortunately for Phillip Fulmer, is one major difference between running a football team and running an election.
<P>   Coaches get to blow The Big One They Absolutely, Positively Cannot Afford to Blow for at least five seasons before the moving van shows up.
<P>
<P><font size=2><strong>Sam Venable&#39;s column appears in The News-Sentinel on Sunday, Tuesday, Thursday and Friday. His column also is available on our Web site at www.knoxnews.com. His latest book, &#39;&#39;I&#39;d Rather Be Ugly Than Stuppid,&#39;&#39; is now available from The News-Sentinel and area bookstores.</strong></font>
<P>
<P>

	</tr>
</table>
