<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<TITLE>The 11th month, day, hour: Veterans Day urges remembrance</TITLE>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<!--Connections 32 Template - Features Menu Page--><!--Use the Headline for HTML Page Title--><!--Headline-->
<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i>November 10, 1996</i></td>
        <td width="470"><!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Story Text Here--><!--FIRST STORY TEMPLATE--> <font size="6"><b>The 11th month, day,
        hour: Veterans Day urges remembrance</b></font><br>
<!--SUBHEAD-->        <p><font size="2"><i>By Sam Venable News-Sentinel
        Columnist</i></font></p>
        <p><font size="2"><!--dateline--></font><br>
        <font size="5">C</font>harley Odom remembers when they
        called it ''Armistice Day.'' </p>
        <p>You may remember too -- the 11th hour of the 11th day
        of the 11th month of the year. The moment to commemorate
        the end of World War I. This was before the holiday got
        renamed Veterans Day, before it was bureaucratically
        designated as the fourth Monday in October, before a nationwide
        protest moved it back to its rightful place on Nov. 11. </p>
        <p>Strangely enough, Odom's most vivid memory of
        Armistice Day has nothing whatsoever to do with peace. On
        Nov. 11, 1943, he and 81 fellow Navy men were 600 feet
        deep in the South China Sea, praying to escape enemy depth
        charges. </p>
        <p>Odom was chief petty officer on the Billfish, a
        310-foot submarine assigned to patrol a 50-square-mile
        area on a 50-day mission. </p>
        <p>''Actually, we missed Armistice Day and several hours
        more,'' said the 83-year-old West Knoxvillian. ''We
        stayed down 29 hours.'' </p>
        <p>What's it like to be crammed inside a 19-foot-diameter
        tube with dozens of other men? </p>
        <p>''Smelly,'' he replied with a laugh. ''You breathe
        fumes from bilge water, battery exhaust, fear
        perspiration, diesel oil, unwashed bodies and, worst of all,
        odor from the heads (toilets). If that wasn't bad enough,
        you have to hear the same jokes over and over.'' </p>
        <p>Charley Odom is the E.F. Hutton of subs. When this old
        salt talks, people listen. </p>
        <p>He served in the Navy from 1934 until 1940. After the
        attack on Pearl Harbor, he re-enlisted and stayed with
        Uncle Sam until 1956. Some of the time he was on shore
        duty, helping teach the intricacies of diesel mechanics to
        other seamen, including a young Naval officer named Jimmy
        Carter. But there were plenty of months on -- or under,
        as the case may be -- the open sea. In fact, Odom
        estimates at least 10 solid years of his life have been spent
        beneath the surface of an ocean somewhere around the
        globe. </p>
        <p>Perhaps saltwater is the key to longevity. At an age
        when most folks have long-since slowed down, Odom doesn't
        miss a beat. </p>
        <p>As if he ever did. </p>
        <p>After discharge from the Navy, he earned a degree from
        the University of Tennessee and taught at Fulton High
        School for 20 years. He lap-swims at the Westside YMCA.
        He is an active ballroom dancer. He is completing his sixth
        semester of Spanish at Pellissippi State. And he
        participates in the writing group at the John T. O'Connor
        Senior Citizens Center. </p>
        <p>Charley recently sent me an account of Armistice Day
        titled ''Low on Food, Low on Water, Low on Oxygen.'' It's
        part of a book project he and his fellow senior writers
        are working on. Reading the piece, I was gripped -- again
        -- by the daily sacrifices men and women in military
        uniforms must make when there is a war to be fought. </p>
        <p>''What really had us worn out had been the depth
        charges,'' he writes of Nov. 11, 1943. ''As the
        destroyers roared over us like freight trains, we waited
        for the next one. Lights went out and valves flew open.
        While we crawled around in the dark, we were both macho
        and scared . . . </p>
        <p>''Deep water hovered over us like a mother hen, and
        shallow water was always our nemesis. Since enemy convoys
        carried oil and rubber from Borneo and other islands to
        Hong Kong and Japan, they hugged the coast. Sometimes we
        would go in on a dark night on the surface, fire on them,
        turn tail and fire from our tubes aft. Then we tried to
        outrun their escorts to get back to deep water.'' </p>
        <p>The Navy lost 52 subs and some 3,500 crewmen in World
        War II. Because of his extensive service, Odom says he
        had been shipmates with many of those who perished. </p>
        <p>''I think about them a lot,'' he told me. ''I'll
        remember a ship or someone's name and go look them up in
        a book. Many's the time, lying in bed at night, that I
        wonder whether they drowned, were crushed or
        suffocated.'' </p>
        <p>God bless them all. And bless folks like Charley Odom
        who make certain we never forget. </p>
        <p><font size="2"><strong>Sam Venable's column appears in
        The News-Sentinel on Sunday, Tuesday, Thursday and
        Friday. His column also is available on our Web site at www.knoxnews.com.
        His latest book, ''I'd Rather Be Ugly Than Stuppid,'' is
        now available from The News-Sentinel and area bookstores. </strong></font></p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

