<html>

<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<TITLE>Notes on some offbeat &#39;artists&#39; gracing our town</TITLE>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<!--Connections 32 Template - Features Menu Page--><!--Use the Headline for HTML Page Title--><!--Headline-->
<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i>November 10, 1996</i></td>
        <td width="470"><!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Story Text Here--><!--FIRST STORY TEMPLATE-->
				<FONT SIZE="+3"><B>Notes on some offbeat &#39;artists&#39; gracing our town</B></FONT><BR><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
				<FONT size="-1"><I>By Sam Venable, Columnist</I></FONT><P>
				<FONT SIZE="-1"><!--dateline--></FONT></DIV></B><BR>
				<FONT SIZE="+2">K</FONT>noxville, my hometown:
<P>   * If you haven&#39;t seen &#39;&#39;Stomp&#39;&#39; at the Civic Auditorium, you&#39;ve missed one of the most entertaining shows that has ever played this area. There are four more opportunities: two performances tonight, two on Saturday. I absolutely, positively promise you will not be disappointed -- unless you&#39;re too late and all four shows are sold out.
<P>   This is one of those rare situations where the cornball phrase &#39;&#39;you have to see it (or hear it, as the case may be) to believe it&#39;&#39; actually applies.
<P>   There&#39;s not one word of dialogue. Instead, a cast of dancer-musicians creates the most delightful rhythms imaginable with brooms, mops, match boxes, cigarette lighters, buckets, sticks, rubber tubes, wheels, trash cans, dust pans -- yes, even the kitchen sink.
<P>   Which leads to one more thing I absolutely, positively promise: You will not be able to sit still during this performance. No matter if you are as rhythm-impaired as Al Gore, your toes will tap.
<P>   What we are talking about is refined noise. Individually, the clongs and clangs, dings and dongs, are the sort of stuff neighbors call the police to complain about. But blended together on stage, they become a masterpiece.
<P>   Perhaps the same theory could apply to another art form that recently has been displayed in Knoxville. A 22-year-old University of Tennessee student has been charged with felony vandalism after the cops busted him for allegedly defacing a railroad abutment.
<P>   The cops call Noah Gross a &#39;&#39;tagger&#39;&#39; or &#39;&#39;graffiti artist.&#39;&#39; The people on whose property his work has appeared surely have another name for him, one that involves body parts and questions Gross&#39; ancestry.
<P>   I don&#39;t blame &#39;em. Every time I see a wall, sidewalk, overpass or trash container &#39;&#39;adorned&#39;&#39; by these spray-painting morons, I think the caning cops of Singapore have the right idea.
<P>   Based on police reports, through, Gross&#39;s work is a far cry from Kilroy-Was-Here. His drawings appear to be quite elaborate. Authorities claim he even signs his work with the name &#39;&#39;Wise&#39;&#39; and keeps a detailed scrapbook of his accomplishments, complete with photos.
<P>   Gross faces a hearing Monday in General Sessions Court. If I were sitting on the bench, I&#39;d lay two judgments on him.
<P>   First, I&#39;d hand him a bucket, a scrub brush and a box of soap powders and banish him to the bridges, buildings and interstate ramps for artistic removal. Second, I&#39;d do everything possible to encourage him to channel his talents in a more productive direction.
<P>   If the creators of &#39;&#39;Stomp&#39;&#39; can turn ordinary, everyday garage noise into a highly acclaimed musical performance, perhaps Noah Gross can find an eager, appreciative (translation: money in their hands and commissions on their mind) audience as well.
<P>   * Gosh dang the luck, I missed Sen. Fred Thompson&#39;s call-in show Wednesday night on Community Television&#39;s Channel 12.
<P>   Those who did tune in certainly got more than political droning. Thanks to a glitch in the satellite feed from Scripps Howard Cable TV Co., they saw a partially scrambled, X-rated movie.
<P>   Given the alleged state of bed-hopping in Washington these days, the good senator might be onto something here. Mayhaps other politicians should try it.
<P>   Jimmy Duncan gets a lot of votes with free barbecue. Think what he could do with porn!
<P>   * If it&#39;s any consolation to local election officials who bungled the city-county unification referendum, we aren&#39;t alone.
<P>   The folks who count the votes in Salt Lake City are just as red-faced.
<P>   According to the Associated Press, election workers had to recount 287,580 ballots -- using fingernails and tweezers -- after some punch-card ballots were not properly processed. Thus, a scanner used to read them would not work.
<P>   Said county clerk Sherrie Swensen: &#39;&#39;It&#39;s a very slow process, very tedious.&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P><B>Sam Venable&#39;s column appears in The News-Sentinel on Sunday, Tuesday, Thursday and Friday. His column also is available on our Web site at www.knoxnews.com. His ¯latest book, &#39;&#39;I&#39;d Rather Be Ugly Than Stuppid,&#39;&#39; is now available from The News-Sentinel and area bookstores.</B>

        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

