<TITLE>Area codes begin to multiply like uh, well, rabbits</TITLE>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<!--Connections 32 Template - Features Menu Page--><!--Use the Headline for HTML Page Title--><!--Headline-->
<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><em>November 19, 1996</em></td>
        <td width="470"><font size="6"><b>Area codes begin to
        multiply like uh, well, rabbits</b></font><br>
<!--SUBHEAD-->        <p><font size="2"><i>By Sam Venable News-Sentinel
        Columnist</i></font></p>
        <p><font size="2"><!--dateline--></font><br>
        <font size="5">I</font> guarantee this has happened. </p>
        <p>You're talking on the phone with someone from out of
        town, he or she asks for your number, and the first sound
        out of your mouth is, ''615, uh, I mean, 423 . . .'' </p>
        <p>Even though more than a year has passed since that
        abominable new area code was forced upon us, nobody is
        accustomed to it. Maybe we never will be. We are
        creatures of habit, and old habits die exceedingly hard. </p>
        <p>Now guess what? </p>
        <p>It's going to get worse. </p>
        <p>BellSouth announced the other day that Tennessee will
        probably be divided into seven area codes within the next
        10 years. </p>
        <p>According to company spokesman David May, the
        Nashville area (which has long been afforded
        most-favored-region status in matters of highways, parks
        and other government largess) will, of course, remain
        615. The rest of Middle Tennessee will become 931 in 1997
        or '98. </p>
        <p>Around the turn of the century, May estimated, 615
        will need further division, as will 901 (West Tennessee)
        and, you guessed it, 423. Meaning that before too many
        more years pass, we'll probably have to dial into different
        area codes to call Burlington from Farragut or Halls from
        Vestal. </p>
        <p>How can this be? </p>
        <p>According to BellSouth, Tennessee's current area codes
        can handle 8 million numbers -- each. That's a total of
        24 million. Now, consider that Tennessee's population is
        only 5 million. This means we already have the capacity
        for nearly five telephone numbers each! for every man,
        woman and child from Memphis to Mountain City. And yet
        we're running out of room? </p>
        <p>Apparently so. </p>
        <p>The main problem, officials say, comes from the recent
        boom in wireless communication -- pagers and cellular
        phones. When you combine that with all the business
        lines, fax lines, 800 numbers and everything else in the marketplace,
        the only alternative is to break existing area codes into
        smaller units. </p>
        <p>Far be it from me to argue with the experts. If we
        need more numbers, so be it. </p>
        <p>The question I want answered is this: What in the name
        of A.G. Bell do these cell-phoning, fax-sending people
        talk about all the time? </p>
        <p>You cannot walk into a supermarket, or drive along any
        street, or go to a football game, or grab a fast-food
        McMeal, without seeing folks yammering away on cell
        phones. Nor can you attempt to send or receive a letter,
        note or missive to or from anyone, anywhere without
        having them say, ''What's your fax number?'' </p>
        <p>How did these people exist 20 years ago? Were they
        mute? Did they not communicate with anyone else at all?
        And now, have they suddenly been smitten with the gift of
        gab? </p>
        <p>Oh, well. Everything that goes around, comes around.
        This cycle will repeat itself every few years, with more
        and more area codes and longer and longer telephone
        numbers, until one day some genius discovers an even newer,
        far more improved system: </p>
        <p>You just pick up the receiver and say, ''Sarah, get me
        the diner . . .'' </p>
        <p><font size="2"><strong>Sam Venable's column appears in
        The News-Sentinel on Sunday, Tuesday, Thursday and
        Friday. His column also is available on our Web site at www.knoxnews.com.
        His latest book, ''I'd Rather Be Ugly Than Stuppid,'' is
        now available from The News-Sentinel and area bookstores.</strong></font> </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

