<head>
<TITLE>Fans give 'ringing' endorsement in answer to column</TITLE>
<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<!--Connections 32 Template - Features Menu Page--><!--Use the Headline for HTML Page Title--><!--Headline--><p align=center><a href="/"><img src="../../../112196/FEATURES/../../images/flag.gif" alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" align=bottom border=0 width=595 height=176></a><br clear=all>
</p>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
<tr><td valign=top width=150><i>November 21, 1996</i></td><td width=470><font size=6><b>Fans give 'ringing' endorsement 
in answer to column</b></font><br>
<!--SUBHEAD--><p><font size=2><i>By Sam Venable News-Sentinel Columnist</i></font> </p>
<p><!--dateline--><br>
<font size=5>K</font>noxville, my hometown: </p>
<p><img src="../../../images/blkbul.gif" alt="*" align=bottom hspace=5 width=14 height=14> Jack Gillard, the Ann Arbor (Mich.) News columnist, picked himself 
quite a fight when he complained about the size of the University of 
Tennessee's Neyland Stadium. </p>
<p>His caustic comments of Nov. 3 apparently were faxed throughout Big 
Orange Country, riling the natives from Union City to Unicoi County. I 
wrote a reply to Gillard on Nov. 8. Phil Williams and Billy Kidd, two 
morning deejays on WIMZ-103.5, broadcast Gillard's telephone numbers -- 
home, office and fax -- and encouraged their listeners to give him a ringy. </p>
<p>They did. Big time. </p>
<p>A few days ago, the Ann Arbor paper devoted almost an entire section front 
to my column and the avalanche of angry responses from Down Here. The 
piece was headlined ''Big Jack Attack.'' </p>
<p>It was all in good fun, of course. Gillard has since sent me some News 
trinkets as a peace offering. I'm mailing him a copy of my latest book -- so, 
harrumph, he can see what real columning is all about. </p>
<p>As this fray ran its course, I received about a dozen letters from folks who 
had moved to East Tennessee from Up There. With only one exception, 
they cited their fondness for this region, its seasons, its people. Several 
writers, however, did mention our quirky figures of speech. Especially ''I 
don't care to.'' </p>
<p>As the natives know, when we say, ''I don't care to'' do something, it means 
we don't mind at all. But to ears that have never heard the expression, it 
sounds like, ''I don't want to.'' </p>
<p>In a spirit of warmth, cooperation and outreach to our brothers and sisters 
from foreign lands, I don't care to point this out. </p>
<p><img src="../../../images/blkbul.gif" alt="*" align=bottom hspace=5 width=14 height=14>It's official. The Christmas holidays are here, even if you haven't begun 
to thaw the Thanksgiving turkey. So, in keeping with America's commercial 
obligation to stay well ahead of the calendar, let me wish you and yours a 
Happy Easter. </p>
<p>I saw my first Christmas-decorated house on Sunday, Nov. 10, off Highway 
33 near the Knox-Union County line. Last Monday, I spied my first 
Christmas tree lot. Later that same morning, I saw my first ring-billed gull of 
the season. </p>
<p>Ring-bills are the sea gulls that invade our parking lots, sometimes by the 
hundreds, during winter. We see more every year. They summer in coastal 
areas but move inland when the weather turns cold and spend several 
months bumming potato chips and bread crumbs from hillbillies, who don't 
care to feed them. </p>
<p><img src="../../../images/blkbul.gif" alt="*" align=bottom hspace=5 width=14 height=14> If mention of the holidays puts you in a gift-giving mood, let me suggest 
a contribution to the Foothills Land Conservancy. </p>
<p>This is a private, not-for-profit group dedicated to buying fragile buffer zones 
around the Great Smoky Mountains National and preserving them from 
development. </p>
<p>The conservancy has its sights on the 1,516-acre Cochran Creek 
watershed. It's on the southern end of Chilhowee Mountain in Blount County 
and has been identified as an important fall feeding area for black bears. </p>
<p>If you and your friends, family or co-workers have grown weary of 
exchanging meaningless knick-knacks at Christmas, you might consider 
buying a piece of this land to protect it from chainsaws and bulldozers. This 
is truly a gift that will grow as the years go by. </p>
<p>For details, contact the Foothills Land Conservancy, 307 S. Washington St., 
Maryville, 37804. Phone (423) 681-8326. </p>
<p><img src="../../../images/blkbul.gif" alt="*" align=bottom hspace=5 width=14 height=14> Don Ferguson, chief deputy clerk of U.S. District Court in Knoxville 
and author of the ''Grammar Gremlins'' feature that appears in The 
News-Sentinel, wants to know why BellSouth's bills always arrive in an 
envelope that is printed upside down. </p>
<p>''This has been going on for two or three years,'' he told me. ''It's become 
obvious that this is more than a one-time printer's error. What's going on?'' </p>
<p>Beats me, Don. Ever since Ma Bell got busted apart, everything related to 
telephones seems topsy-turvy. </p>
<p><font size=2><strong>Sam Venable's column appears in The News-Sentinel on Sunday, Tuesday, Thursday 
and Friday. His column also is available on our Web site at www.knoxnews.com. His 
latest book, ''I'd Rather Be Ugly Than Stuppid,'' is now available from The 
News-Sentinel and area bookstores.</strong></font> </p>
</td></tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>
