<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<TITLE>Warning: These chess tips may ruin your game</TITLE>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>

<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i><!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Date Here-->November 22, 1996</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="+3"><B><!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Headline Here-->Warning: These chess tips may ruin your game</B></FONT><!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Subheadline Here--><!--SUBHEAD--></FONT><P>
		<FONT size="-1"><I><!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Byline Here-->By Sam Venable, Columnist</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="-1"><I><!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Dateline Here--></I></FONT><BR>
		<!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Story Text Here--><FONT SIZE="+2">T</FONT>he World Series of chess is coming to Knoxville, so unless you want to be left out of conversations with your friends and co-workers, learn the game now.
<P>   You&#39;ve got until April 25. That&#39;s when some 5,000 chess enthusiasts will square off at the convention center for the 1997 Super Nationals.
<P>   Nonetheless, the sooner you acquire the basics of this game, the better you&#39;ll be able to follow the action next spring.
<P>   I learned chess from my son, Clay. It was part of our lifelong commitment to cultural exchange.
<P>   I taught Clay valuable life skills -- how to propel green peas into the living room with a spoon, how to hold the maximum number of grapes in your mouth without (1) choking and (2) getting caught by Mom, how to generate the greatest volume from northern and southern portals of the body, important stuff like that. Clay taught me how to play chess, understand physics and identify the constellations. It&#39;s been a marvelous learning experience for both.
<P>   Chess is played on a checkerboard with a bunch of weird pieces. There is the pawn, which looks like a chocolate drop; the knight, which looks like a horse with its body chopped off; the rook, which looks like an unfinished chimney; the bishop, which looks like a chocolate drop wearing a beret; the queen, which looks like the column from a Civil War mansion; and the king, which looks like the queen with a cross on top.
<P>   Chess closely parallels the goings-on in corporate America. The pawns (employees) are supposed to protect the king (CEO). They are slaughtered off mercilessly as the game progresses. But just before the king (CEO) is slashed, someone says &#39;&#39;checkmate&#39;&#39; (golden parachute) and the two former adversaries go off to sip cognac or stuff grapes into their mouths.
<P>   The pawns can only move one space at a time, except on the first move when they can go two. They can only capture another piece by moving diagonally, unless accompanied by Col. Mustard into the billiard room while carrying a wrench.
<P>   The knights move in an L-shaped pattern, advancing down the board until they reach the opposite end, at which time the owner triumphantly announces, &#39;&#39;Crown me!&#39;&#39;
<P>   Rooks can move any number of spaces, vertically or horizontally. If, during the course of one of these moves, they land on Boardwalk they may collect $200. However, they have to give up one turn throwing the dice.
<P>   Bishops can only go diagonally, which should tell you something about their character from the beginning. Always keep a close eye on your opponent&#39;s bishop, especially if you suspect he&#39;s trying to draw to an inside straight.
<P>   The king and queen are typical bluebloods -- pampered and privileged, but without a clue. The queen can move in a straight line in any direction, but the king, his dorkness, can only stumble along one space at a time.
<P>   That, in a nutshell, is how chess is played. It gets more detailed as your skills increase, of course. On any given day next April, there will be hundreds of masters of the game in Knoxville.
<P>   And, boy, is it going to be loud if they all shout, &#39;&#39;Yahtzee!&#39;&#39; at the same time.
<P>
<P><B>Sam Venable&#39;s column appears in The News-Sentinel on Sunday, Tuesday, Thursday and Friday. His column also is available on our Web site at www.knoxnews.com. His latest book, &#39;&#39;I&#39;d Rather Be Ugly Than Stuppid,&#39;&#39; is now available from The News-Sentinel and area bookstores.
<P></B>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
