<html>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<TITLE>Time religion takes a back pew to cyberprayer</TITLE>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>

<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i><!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Date Here-->November 22, 1996</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
<!--FIRST STORY TEMPLATE-->
				<FONT SIZE="+3"><B>Ol&#39; time religion takes a back pew to cyberprayer</B></FONT><BR><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
				<FONT size="-1"><I>By Sam Venable, Columnist</I></FONT><P>
				<FONT SIZE="-1"><!--dateline--></FONT></DIV></B><BR>
				<FONT SIZE="+2">H</FONT>ear the words of Rev. Venob, brothers and sisters: If you&#39;re looking for a dose of that old-time religion, you might not find it in cyberchurch.
<P>   In case you haven&#39;t noticed, they&#39;re doing things a little differently in the pulpit these days, and I ain&#39;t talking about the Revised Standard Edition or the new Book of Common Prayer.
<P>   Up in Carrollton, Va., for example, one church has decided to blend the lottery with the Lord. At Sweet Haven Holy Church of God -- Rev. Venob is not making this up -- parishioners have a chance to pocket bucks for showing up.
<P>   According to a news dispatch I read a few days ago, Bishop Nathaniel Johnson hands out play money at the start of the service. Folks who find a bill with the preacher&#39;s initials on the back win between $10 and $100 in U.S. government cash. There are up to four winners each Sunday -- provided they stay until the end of the two-hour proceedings.
<P>   In Israel, a computer company has updated the concept of Dial-A-Prayer and Fax-A-Prayer by offering a Jewish prayer service via e-mail.
<P>   The company, Virtual Jerusalem, accepts on-line prayers from worshipers, prints them out, and takes them to the Wailing Wall. Since the web site (http://www.virtual.co.il) was established several months ago, it has forwarded more than 2,000 prayers to the wall. There is no charge for this service, by the way.
<P>   Said president Avi Moskowitz: &#39;&#39;You know that your prayer is going to the closest place that you can get to God.&#39;&#39;
<P>   No harm in either approach, I suppose. But they are going to take some getting used to. What&#39;s more, they raise some interesting questions.
<P>   At the Virginia church, for instance, are winners supposed to tithe immediately?
<P>   Probably. You might be able to hide from the church treasurer or the IRS, but when the preacher hisownself is counting out those greenbacks, right there in front of Gawd and everybody, it&#39;d take a certified Scrooge not to cough up a 10 percent rebate, minimum.
<P>   As for the e-mail prayer idea, what happens when the computer jams or crashes? Does this disconnect you with the Big Guy?
<P>   This is happening more and more. Louise Kehoe, writing about Internet congestion for The Financial Times, calls the World Wide Web the &#39;&#39;World Wide Wait.&#39;&#39;
<P>   You don&#39;t have to take her word for it. Anyone who tried to monitor election results via computer on Nov. 5 knows what I&#39;m talking about. Apparently the web was bound up so tight that night, two tons of Ex-Lax wouldn&#39;t have provided relief.
<P>   I know this makes Rev. Venob a born-again geezer, but religion sure was a lot more simple in the days before ministerial kickbacks and electronic praying.
<P>   Why, Rev. Venob even remembers back to a quaint, innocent time when the two most pressing worries on Sunday morning were how long the sermon would last and whether there&#39;d be enough funeral home fans to go around.
<P>   All the children say, &#39;&#39;Amen!&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P>Sam Venable&#39;s column appears in The News-Sentinel on Sunday, Tuesday, Thursday and Friday. His column also is available on our Web site at www.knoxnews.com. His latest book, &#39;&#39;I&#39;d Rather Be Ugly Than Stuppid,&#39;&#39; is now available from The News-Sentinel and area bookstores.
<P><B></B>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
