<TITLE>Thanksgiving has nation thinking of food, good service</TITLE>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<!--Connections 32 Template - Upfront Story Page--><!--Use the Headline for HTML Page Title-->
<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i><!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Date Here-->November 26, 1996</i> </td>
        <td width="470"><font size="6"><b><!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Headline Here-->Thanksgiving has nation thinking
        of food, good service<!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Subheadline Here--><!--SUBHEAD--></b></font><p><font size="2"><i><!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Byline Here-->By
        Sam Venable News-Sentinel Columnist</i></font></p>
        <p><font size="2"><i><!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Dateline Here--></i></font><br>
        <!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Story Text Here--><font size="5">I</font>t stands to reason that during
        this week of gluttony, we'd get to sink our choppers into
        two surveys of Americans' eating habits. </p>
        <p>It also stands to reason that one of these surveys was
        conducted on behalf of Kentucky Fried Chicken. </p>
        <p>Huh? Chicken? During turkey week? </p>
        <p>Yes. This is brilliant marketing strategy. </p>
        <p>Fifty-one weeks out of the year, chicken has to
        compete with turkey, beef, pork, lamb, fish, hamburgers,
        hot dogs and other meats on the menu. But during the
        Thanksgiving holidays, the only other player is turkey
        (with mayhaps a sugar-cured ham on the sidelines). Either
        way, the competition is thinner, and fried chicken has
        the potential for making a strong economic showing -- a
        case, you might say, of two birds in the hand beating a
        rack of ribs in the bush. </p>
        <p>(Then again you might not say anything of the kind, so
        pass me another serving of whatever's on the platter and
        forget I mentioned it.) </p>
        <p>The KFC survey was conducted by a company called RGA Communications
        Research and was made through telephone interviews with 1,815
        adults. It asked a bunch of boring questions about how
        often the family eats together, what they talk about, who
        prepares the meal, what they eat, who cleans up,
        blah-blah-blah. The findings are a statistician's dream,
        replete with percentages and probabilities that, if
        combined with the Colonel's secret spices and herbs and
        placed end-to-end, would stretch from the KFC restaurant
        on Cedar Bluff Road to the one in Halls. </p>
        <p>But one thing's perfectly clear: When it comes to
        meals, what Dad does best is eat. </p>
        <p>Without getting into the fine print, suffice to say
        that the father places a distant third to the mother and
        children in matters of deciding to cook or buy carry-out,
        what's on the menu, making mealtime conversation,
        cleaning up afterwards and other aspects of din-din. </p>
        <p>Sounds good to me. All in favor, say aye -- as soon as
        you finish chewing, I mean. Then let's wander on down to
        the den and try to find a football game on the tube. </p>
        <p>The second survey involved restaurant dining and was
        conducted by a company called SanPellegrino USA. The
        results were gleaned from interviews with 500 adults who
        eat out at least once a month. </p>
        <p>What was the number one factor these people cited in
        an enjoyable dining experience? </p>
        <p>Before you pick up a knife and fork, let me tell you
        it wasn't the food. Not by a long shot. </p>
        <p>Instead, a vast majority (70 percent) said it was an
        ''attentive waitstaff.'' Which oughta make a lot of chefs
        wonder why they spent all that time and money in cooking
        school. </p>
        <p>Oh, and another tasty morsel: In which part of the
        country do the most diners want to make their waiter's
        acquaintance? </p>
        <p>The South, of course. By a wide margin, folks Down
        Here shake and howdy with the hired help more than they
        do Up There and Out Yonder. </p>
        <p>I'm not sure what all this proves, but I let me remind
        you of one thing: Venob certainly has enjoyed serving you
        this morning, and he'll be more than happy to help you
        figure the tip. </p>
        <p><font size="2"><strong>Sam Venable's column appears in
        The News-Sentinel on Sunday, Tuesday, Thursday and
        Friday. His column also is available on our Web site at www.knoxnews.com.
        His latest book, ''I'd Rather Be Ugly Than Stuppid,'' is
        now available from The News-Sentinel and area bookstores.</strong></font> </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

