<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<TITLE>Thanksgiving has nation thinking of food, good service</TITLE>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<!--Connections 32 Template - Upfront Story Page--><!--Use the Headline for HTML Page Title-->
<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i><!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Date Here-->November 26, 1996</i> </td>
        <td width="470"><!--FIRST STORY TEMPLATE-->
				<FONT SIZE="+3"><B>Luck, laziness and libido combine to supply one turkey</B></FONT><BR><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
				<FONT size="-1"><I>By Sam Venable, Columnist</I></FONT><P>
				<FONT SIZE="-1"><!--dateline--></FONT></DIV></B><BR>
				<FONT SIZE="+2">W</FONT>hen the Venob clan sits down to a turkey dinner this afternoon, two of the things we should give thanks for are, in order, my lazy butt and the incredible power of sex.
<P>   Without either, we would not be savoring the smoked feast set before us.
<P>   The Venobs sometimes eat wild turkeys at Thanksgiving and Christmas -- &#39;&#39;sometimes&#39;&#39; being a critical word in this discussion. It depends on how successful I have been in the woods. Thanks to an aggressive wild turkey restoration program by the Wildlife Resources Agency and my skill at recognizing the dire need for vast amounts of &#39;&#39;field research&#39;&#39; during the turkey season, however, this hasn&#39;t been much of a problem in recent years.
<P>   Our bird came to dinner by his own undoing, and therein lies a tale. To appreciate it, you must understand a few givens about turkeys and turkey hunting.
<P>   Wild turkeys, despite the rubbish you hear around campfires and read in he-man outdoor magazines, are neither smart nor sly. They are paranoid.
<P>   Turkeys emerge from the egg convinced every sound and movement in the woods is an enemy, and they spend the rest of their lives worrying. Collectively, a flock of wild turkeys is jumpier than delegates to a Barney Fife convention.
<P>   Thus, when a wild turkey sees, hears or even suspects something is amiss, it runs or flies to the next ridge in approximately one-half second. If your only association with turkeys was a fifth-grade trip to Floyd Foster&#39;s fowl farm, you may not realize that a wild gobbler, when motivated, can outrun a veteran Washington lobbyist.
<P>   Ah, but the avian guard does drop briefly, just as it does in the human world with spies, TV preachers, politicians, corporate executives and others who ought to know better.
<P>   That is when sex enters the equation.
<P>   Turkeys breed in the spring. If, during that same period, you can (1) go without sleep, (2) lie successfully to your boss and wife, (3) spend hundreds of dollars driving to and from the mountains, (4) hike until you locate a gobbler on the prowl, (5) camouflage yourself to the max, (6) reasonably impersonate a hussy hen, (7) sit still while bugs drain your veins, and (8) pull a trigger, you can save the 10 minutes and $15 it takes to acquire a store-bought turkey in November.
<P>   Often, it happens rather quickly. I have sat down in the woods to call turkeys and been forced to swing into action almost as the leaves are settling at my feet. But this particular bird and I toyed with each other for almost two hours.
<P>   Why? Because of my aforementioned indolence and the awesome power of his libido.
<P>   I had watched this bird fly from a distant mountain to an adjacent ridge. I had listened to him gobble lustily to my calling. I was intimately familiar with this tract of forest and knew exactly how to creep downhill, cross the valley, and climb to his elevation undetected. But I simply was too lazy, too fat, too tired to make the hike.
<P>   So I did what any hard-to-get woman would do. I invoked The Rules. I shut up and paid no attention to him.
<P>   He couldn&#39;t stand it. Over the course of 60 minutes, he rattled the woods with gobbles. He marched to within 80 yards of where I sat and strutted for another 20 minutes. When the hussy hen didn&#39;t appear, he stormed off and refused to say another word.
<P>   Until I called to him one more time.
<P>   That fired him up again, and for nearly another half hour he stayed &#39;&#39;out there&#39;&#39; -- gobbling, puffing, strutting and swearing whips-and-chains sexual torment. Then he hushed. Five minutes later, he tip-toed into my gunsights.
<P>   Agreed, hunting has its cruel side. As much as I love being in the outdoors with rod and gun, and as rationally as I accept the role of predator and prey -- whether the predator creeps through the woods in Gore-Tex boots or pushes a shopping cart at Kroger -- taking the life of a wild, regal animal can be a perfectly awful thing to do.
<P>   But as Bill Clinton and Bob Dole both know, dabbling with hussies can get you in big trouble.
<P>
<P>Sam Venable&#39;s column appears in The News-Sentinel on Sunday, Tuesday, Thursday and Friday. His column also is available on our Web site at www.knoxnews.com. His latest book, &#39;&#39;I&#39;d Rather Be Ugly Than Stuppid,&#39;&#39; is now available from The News-Sentinel and area bookstores.
<P><B></B>
<P>
<P>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

