<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<!--Connections 32 Template - Upfront Story Page--><!--Use the Headline for HTML Page Title-->
<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i><!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Date Here-->November 29, 1996</i> </td>
        <td width="470"><!--FIRST STORY TEMPLATE-->
				<FONT SIZE="+3"><B>Be prepared for big shock at UT- Vanderbilt game</B></FONT><BR><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
				<FONT size="-1"><I>By Sam Venable, Columnist</I></FONT><P>
				<FONT SIZE="-1"><!--dateline--></FONT></DIV></B><BR>
				<FONT SIZE="+2">U</FONT>ntold thousands of University of Tennessee football fans will be driving to Nashville on Saturday to watch the Vols conclude their 1996 regular-season schedule at Vanderbilt.
<P>   And, boy, will they be surprised.
<P>   Life moves at a different pace in the land of the Commodore, so be forewarned.
<P>   If the length and breadth of your Tennessee football experience has occurred within the confines of Neyland Stadium, you will experience a fair amount of culture shock the moment you find your seat at Vanderbilt Stadium and gaze upon Dudley Field.
<P>   Correction. You&#39;ll experience the first shock before you even take a peek at the field. As soon as your buns hit the planks, you&#39;ll know what I mean.
<P>   There is room to sit comfortably. Honest. I&#39;ve been there myownself and know whereof I speak.
<P>   Even though the official capacity of Vanderbilt Stadium is 41,600 -- less than half the size of UT -- you will experience the same amazing freedom of movement munchkins feel the first time they stretch out on a king-size bed.
<P>   There are two reasons for this phenomenon.
<P>   First, the seats themselves are larger. Vanderbilt athletic officials don&#39;t adhere to the Crunch-O-Matic philosophy adopted by UT. They don&#39;t have to because, unlike the situation in Knoxville, 750,000 frenzied alums and supporters are not clamoring for tickets.
<P>   Which brings us to the second reason there is room to stretch at Vanderbilt: Even during a spirited game, there&#39;s usually an inordinate amount of space between spectators -- three, four, sometimes five seats.
<P>   It won&#39;t be that way Saturday, certainly. Rarely is for a Vol-Commodore clash. Shortly before kickoff, an orange tidal wave will roll eastward from Memphis and westward from Johnson City and flood the house.
<P>   Vanderbilt faithful -- yes, Virginia, there are a few -- don&#39;t like to see this Big Orange tsunami, of course. They think it clashes with their suits and sport coats.
<P>   You will notice that these people behave differently from typical Neyland Stadiumites in several ways.
<P>   For instance, they tend to make casual conversation about fluctuations in NASDAQ, not point standings in NASCAR.
<P>   When they want to catch the attention of a concessionaire, they don&#39;t stand up and yell, &#39;&#39;Hey! Coke guy! Hey! Over here!&#39;&#39; Rather, they quietly clear their throat, snap their fingers once and command, &#39;&#39;Steward!&#39;&#39;
<P>   Nor are they prone to get into shoving matches if tempers flare. Instead, they merely remove a cellular telephone from their vest pocket, call Daddy, and have him send a man over to do the job.
<P>   Nonetheless, in the event you do wind up sitting next to Buffy and Wellington from Belle Meade, don&#39;t ignore them. Despite their strange looks and awkward mannerisms, these are human beings too. Please be nice to them.
<P>   Why, you might even offer &#39;em a chew of your Red Man.
<P>
<P>Sam Venable&#39;s column appears in The News-Sentinel on Sunday, Tuesday, Thursday and Friday. His column also is available on our Web site at www.knoxnews.com. His latest book, &#39;&#39;I&#39;d Rather Be Ugly Than Stuppid,&#39;&#39; is now available from The News-Sentinel and area bookstores.
<P><B></B>
<P>
<P>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

