<TITLE>Bits of paper from the past signal changes good, bad</TITLE>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<!--Connections 32 Template - Features Menu Page--><!--Use the Headline for HTML Page Title--><!--Headline-->
<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i>December 01, 1996</i></td>
        <td width="470"><font size="6"><b>Bits of paper from the
        past signal changes good, bad</b></font><br>
<!--SUBHEAD-->        <p><font size="2"><i>By Sam Venable News-Sentinel
        Columnist</i></font></p>
        <p><font size="2"><!--dateline--></font><br>
        <font size="5">T</font>oday is a perfect opportunity to
        bring all you native Knoxvillians up to date on some
        old-time information. </p>
        <p>This stuff involves . . . huh? What's that? How do I
        know everyone out there in Readership Land right now is a
        certified, card-carrying native? </p>
        <p>Simple. Between last Wednesday afternoon and
        approximately 8 o'clock tonight, native Knoxvillians --
        along with homegrown folks who migrated to foreign lands
        -- have been the only occupants of this city. All the
        others have exited for a four-day holiday ''back home.'' </p>
        <p>The first matter we have to discuss is a picture
        postcard sent to me by Richard H. Beckett of Portage,
        Mich. </p>
        <p>This card shows a scene of Main Street, east of Henley
        Street. But it's nothing like you'd see today. The only
        buildings visible are the fronts of a couple of houses.
        Both sides of the street are lined with beautiful trees
        -- elms, I would suspect. And smack down the center of
        the wide thoroughfare are streetcar tracks. </p>
        <p>The card is addressed to Isabelle Hamilton, Lansing,
        Mich. The only message is ''Will be back Monday, Feb. 28.
        (signed) A.B.G.'' It is postmarked Feb. 23, 1910. </p>
        <p>A.B.G. -- whoever he or she was -- had it made. There
        was no Atlanta airport or Interstate 40/75 spider web to
        creep through back then. And, given the prompt mail
        delivery of that era, there's every chance Isabelle Hamilton
        received her postcard sometime before the Fourth of July. </p>
        <p>The next order of business is an old newspaper
        classified ad Beverly Riddell found in some belongings of
        her mother, who died two years ago. </p>
        <p>''It's from sometime in the '30s,'' said Riddell.
        ''Mother's sister was looking for a roommate.'' </p>
        <p>This room-for-lease was located in ''West Knoxville.''
        It's on Forest Avenue. </p>
        <p>Of course, back then the region of, say, West Town
        Mall, was so far out in the sticks that sunshine had to
        be piped in. And the tiny farm community of Farragut was
        adrift somewhere between Gay Street and downtown Chattanooga. </p>
        <p>Finally, I hold in my hands a photocopy of The New
        York Times from Sunday, Feb. 9, 1908. Fellow
        News-Sentinel staffer Jim Balloch came across it while
        doing some research at Lawson McGhee Library. </p>
        <p>The headline on one of the top stories shouts
        ''Knoxville's Ban on Liquor Fails.'' </p>
        <p>Check out the first paragraph: ''Knoxville has been
        for three months a prohibition town. While this is too
        early to judge the ultimate effect of prohibition in the
        largest Tennessee city that has yet been engulfed by the temperance
        wave, the trial here has been sufficient to demonstrate
        the axiomatic sociological truth that prohibition does
        not prohibit.'' </p>
        <p>The story goes into great detail about the mockery of
        trying to stamp out the liquor trade here. It describes
        the ''jug trains'' that came in daily from Middlesboro,
        Ky., as well as the farce of ''private clubs.'' </p>
        <p>''Many believe that almost as much liquor is drunk
        here as before prohibition went into effect,'' the Times'
        correspondent wrote. </p>
        <p>Given the daily drug reports from the cop shop, one
        wonders if anything has changed. </p>
        <p><font size="2"><strong>Sam Venable's column appears in
        The News-Sentinel on Sunday, Tuesday, Thursday and
        Friday. His column also is available on our Web site at www.knoxnews.com.
        His latest book, ''I'd Rather Be Ugly Than Stuppid,'' is
        now available from The News-Sentinel and area bookstores.</strong></font> </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

<hr size="5">

