<html>

<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<TITLE>'Tis the $eason to deck the halls of the local malls</TITLE>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<!--Connections 32 Template - Features Menu Page--><!--Use the Headline for HTML Page Title--><!--Headline-->
<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"></a><br
clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i>December 12, 1996</i></td>
        <td width="470"><!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Story Text Here--><!--FIRST STORY TEMPLATE--> <font size="6"><b>'Tis the $eason to
        deck the halls of the local malls</b></font><br>
<!--SUBHEAD-->        <p><font size="2"><i>By Sam Venable News-Sentinel
        Columnist</i></font></p>
        <p><font size="3"><!--dateline--></font><br>
        <font size="5">D</font>on't just stand there -- buy
        something! </p>
        <p>In case you have just arrived from another galaxy,
        planet Earth is in the midst of the Christmas shopping
        season. Meaning that anyone who cares one whit about the
        financial security of humankind should drop whatever he or
        she is doing, run to the nearest mega-mall or superstore
        and start throwing money around like a member of
        Congress. </p>
        <p>How much? </p>
        <p>According to one recent survey, the average U.S.
        shopper will spend $1,160 this Christmas season. Of that
        total, $900 will go for gifts, the balance for travel,
        entertaining and decorations. So if you haven't coughed up
        at least one measly grand since the Christmas shopping
        season officially started last July 4th, I urge you to
        limber up the ol' billfold and get cranking. </p>
        <p>(What's that? You say you have no intention of
        spending anywhere near $900 on presents this year? And
        you'd like to know who came up with those figures? Hmmmm
        . . .let me see. Ah, yes: It's a small cottage industry called
        ''American Express.'' You've probably never heard of
        them. They manufacture and distribute a thin plastic
        device. I looked at a sample of one of these quaint
        ''American Express'' products just now and can attest it bears
        no resemblance whatsoever to a silver bell, manger,
        angel, stocking, fruitcake, elf, ornament, sleigh,
        reindeer or other holiday icon. Thus, it is safe to
        assume (a) ''American Express'' has no vested interest in
        the Christmas season and (b) this was a completely
        impartial survey. There. Satisfied?) </p>
        <p>As you make your way toward the halls of commerce this
        time of year, it is important to remember the rea$on for
        the $ea$on. To assist in this important mission, I have
        listed the Ten Commandments of Christmas Shopping. </p>
        <p>I. Thou shalt worship the Gross National Product and
        National Consumer Spending Index with all thy heart and
        with all thy might. </p>
        <p>2. Thou shalt arriveth at thy mall before the cock
        crows and circleth the lot 70 times seven to findeth the
        parking space nearest the door. </p>
        <p>3. Thou shalt weareth thy holiday sweater, thy
        blinking Santa Claus necktie and thy Jingle Bell shoes
        and playeth ''Blue Christmas'' on thy car CD or stereo
        wherever thou shalt travel. </p>
        <p>4. Thou shalt not covet thy neighbor's Holiday Barbie
        and 101 Dalmatians CD-ROMs, lest thy neighbor cleave thy
        head with a Tonka truck. </p>
        <p>5. Thou shalt not buyeth a skillet nor a vacuum
        cleaner for thy wife, nor a hammer nor a lawn mower for
        thy husband, lest thou be labeled ''insensitive throwback
        from the Fifties.'' </p>
        <p>6. Thou shalt not buyeth any item that needeth
        assembly, lest thou be labeled ''ignoramus.'' </p>
        <p>7. Thou shalt bear in mind the term ''one size fits
        all'' applyeth only to gift certificates. </p>
        <p>8. Thou shalt keepeth all receipts. </p>
        <p>9. Thou shalt not thinketh about bills until January,
        when thou shalt wail and maketh loud lamentations. </p>
        <p>10. Thou shalt remember, ahem, that books maketh
        wonderful gifts. </p>
        <p>For much less than $900. </p>
        <p><font size="2"><strong>Sam Venable's column appears in
        The News-Sentinel on Sunday, Tuesday, Thursday and
        Friday. His column also is available on our Web site at www.knoxnews.com.
        His latest book, ''I'd Rather Be Ugly Than Stuppid,'' is
        now available from The News-Sentinel and area bookstores.</strong></font> </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

