<TITLE>'Tis the $eason to deck the halls of the local malls</TITLE>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../../images/flag.jpg"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"></a><br
clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i>December 12, 1996</i></td>
        <td width="470"><p><font size="6"><b>Brace for a weird
        holiday season if Friday 13th a sign</b></font><br>
<!--SUBHEAD-->        </p>
        <p><font size="2"><i>By Sam Venable, News-Sentinel
        columnist</i></font></p>
        <p><font size="3"><!--dateline--></font><br>
        <font size="5">N</font>ot that I'm superstitious or
        anything -- Yikes! Careful with that salt shaker! -- but
        has it dawned on you that this is the first Friday the
        13th we've had in December in quite awhile, and some very
        strange things are going on? </p>
        <p>The last time a December calendar fell this way was in
        1991, back when Bill Clinton couldn't get recognized
        outside of Little Rock -- why, shucks, you wouldn't even
        know him on a date -- and George Bush was beginning to
        toy with catchy new phrases for his second inaugural
        address, 13 months down the pike. </p>
        <p>Five years later -- get that black cat outta here! --
        Friday the 13th rears its ugly head in December once
        more, and look what's happening, particularly on the
        holiday front, at home and around the globe: </p>
        <p>* In East Tennessee, it's hot enough to be the middle
        of spring, not the middle of winter. Go for a sleigh
        ride? Naaa, we'd rather water ski. </p>
        <p>* For the first time in 18 years, Pope John Paul II
        has decided not to celebrate Christmas Day Mass in St.
        Peter's Basilica. </p>
        <p>* In Pensacola, Fla., shopping malls have banned
        caroling by church choirs and school choral groups
        because of complaints by merchants and customers. </p>
        <p>* Due to severe budget cutbacks, the city of
        Bethlehem, birthplace of Jesus Christ, announced it would
        have to scale down its Christmas decorations. </p>
        <p>* In Russia, 3,000 reindeer have died from starvation. </p>
        <p>Coincidences? I think not. </p>
        <p>This is one instance where triskaidekaphobia (the fear
        of the number 13) is well-founded. I am convinced that
        Friday, Dec. 13, 1996, has dedicated itself to
        Grinchizing the Christmas season for everyone. </p>
        <p>So be on your guard. In addition to triskaidekaphobia,
        there are several other fears you should be especially
        mindful of today. Among them: </p>
        <p><b>Ratholaphobia: </b>The fear TVA will blow $5.2
        million on a luxury private jet so its busy executives
        won't be burdened with having to travel on commercial
        airplanes like common members of the business community. </p>
        <p><b>Orlanaphobia:</b> The fear of going to the Citrus
        Bowl for the third time in four years. </p>
        <p><b>Pollutaphobia: </b>The fear that Champion
        International will continue to dump its foamy, brown,
        smelly toxic waste into the Pigeon River. </p>
        <p><b>Swissarmaphobia:</b> The fear, most commonly
        experienced by school students, of forgetting to leave
        your pocketknife at home. </p>
        <p><b>Peptobismaphobia:</b> The fear of catching the
        puke-and-poot bug that's going around town. </p>
        <p><b>Backorderaphobia:</b> The fear that every store in
        town has just sold out of the toys your child wants Santa
        Claus to bring. </p>
        <p><b>Cheeseballaphobia:</b> The fear of attending
        Christmas parties seven nights in a row. </p>
        <p><b>Decoraphobia:</b> The fear of untangling 21/2 miles
        of tree lights that were wadded into a fist-sized ball
        last Jan. 3 and have been cooking in the attic ever
        since. </p>
        <p><font size="2"><b>Sam Venable's column appears in The
        News-Sentinel on &127;Sunday, Tuesday, Thursday and
        Friday. His column also is &127;available on our Web site
        at www.knoxnews.com. His &127;latest book, ''I'd Rather
        Be Ugly Than Stuppid,'' is now &127;available from The
        News-Sentinel and area bookstores.</b></font></p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

