<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<TITLE>Lies, lies and more lies tend to turn on the teller</TITLE>
<!--Use the Headline for HTML Page Title-->
<!--Headline-->
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i>December 17, 1996</i></td>
        <td width="470"><!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Story Text Here--><!--FIRST STORY TEMPLATE--> <font size="6"><b>Lies, lies and more
        lies tend to turn on the teller</b></font><br>
<!--SUBHEAD-->        <p><font size="2"><i>By Sam Venable News-Sentinel
        Columnist</i></font></p>
        <p><font size="3"><!--dateline--></font><br>
        <font size="5">W</font>hen I read the news about Wes
        Cooley and David Michael Pecard, I remembered a bit of
        sage wisdom someone passed along years ago, back when I
        was a fledgling fisherperson: </p>
        <p>''Liars should have good memories.'' </p>
        <p>Your mother may have phrased it another way: ''Oh,
        what a tangled web we weave, when at first we start to
        deceive.'' </p>
        <p>However it's said, this is excellent advice. A good
        memory is an absolute must in the fabrication business.
        Without quick and accurate recall, a teller of tall tales
        begins to contradict himself. Before long, whenever he
        holds up his right hand and says, ''I swear to tell the
        whole truth,'' everyone else in the joint starts rolling
        on the floor in laughter. </p>
        <p>If you keep up with the news, you're probably familiar
        with Cooley and Pecard and their alleged skills at
        fibology. </p>
        <p>Cooley is a former U.S. representative from Salem,
        Ore. He won the office in 1994, partly because of his
        claim to have been a member of the Army Special Forces
        and a combat veteran in Korea. He also claimed to be a
        member of the academic honor society, Phi Beta Kappa. </p>
        <p>Cooley's story sounded good enough. But it didn't hold
        up to scrutiny. These claims, and others, turned out to
        be piffle. He subsequently withdrew from his re-election
        campaign and has since been indicted for making false
        statements. </p>
        <p>Pecard -- authorities in Arizona aren't even sure if
        that's his real name -- is in quite a pickle himself. He
        is jailed in Phoenix under $2 million bond on charges of
        fraud, forgery, theft and sexual abuse after allegedly
        using several fake ID's to bluff his way into a sheriff's
        department and fondle female prisoners. </p>
        <p>I don't know the details of either case, but I'd be
        willing to bet each hoax began to unravel when the
        perpetrators embellished once too often or nudged the
        envelope of believability half an inch too far. At that
        point, their lies imploded, bringing down the house. </p>
        <p>Far less serious and far more humorous was a situation
        I recall from the early 1970s, when I covered the
        outdoors for this newspaper. </p>
        <p>(Trust your Uncle Venob. He has a good memory,
        especially in matters of lies.) </p>
        <p>The story involves an angler and a fish that grew by
        several inches and pounds the longer it stayed out of the
        water. </p>
        <p>Nothing new about that, you say? Happens all the time
        around fish camps, sportsmen's lodges, sporting goods
        stores and boat docks? </p>
        <p>Of course it does. But this particular metamorphosis
        occurred within a matter of hours. By plotting the action
        on a map, I could chart its course, minute-by-minute,
        from Jefferson City to Knoxville. </p>
        <p>Rockfish were still a relatively new import to
        Tennessee waters in those days, and Cherokee Lake was the
        local hotspot. The current state record is a whopping
        601/2 pounds, but back then a 15-pounder was certified
        bragging material. Anything larger was spectacular. </p>
        <p>I was sitting at my desk one afternoon when an excited
        fisherman called from a dock on Cherokee. He had just
        caught a 17-pounder, by golly, and wanted to bring it by
        The News-Sentinel to show me. </p>
        <p>The guy apparently had friends scattered along Highway
        11-E, and they were just as anxious as he to spread the
        riveting news. About every 30-40 minutes, I'd get a phone
        call from one of them, each time closer to Knoxville. </p>
        <p>With each call, the fish grew. </p>
        <p>By the time the guy actually showed up at 208 W.
        Church Ave., I was certain he had smashed the state
        record, the U.S. record and, quite possibility, the world
        and galactic records. </p>
        <p>Instead, he produced a rockfish that -- I'm being
        generous here -- might have eclipsed 12 pounds. Thirteen
        at the outside. </p>
        <p>Alas, he didn't get his picture in the newspaper. </p>
        <p>Then again, he didn't find himself in the pokey under
        $2 million bond. </p>
        <p><font size="2"><strong>Sam Venable's column appears in
        The News-Sentinel on Sunday, Tuesday, Thursday and
        Friday. His column also is available on our Web site at
        www.knoxnews.com. His latest book, ''I'd Rather Be Ugly
        Than Stuppid,'' is now available from The News-Sentinel
        and area bookstores. </strong></font></p>
        <p><font size="2"><strong><b>¯</b></strong></font> </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

