<html>

<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<TITLE>Nature appears able to work with us in efforts to co-exist</TITLE>
<!--Use the Headline for HTML Page Title-->
<!--Headline-->
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i>December 22, 1996</i></td>
        <td width="470"><font size="6"><b>Nature appears able to
        work with us in efforts to co-exist</b></font><br>
<!--SUBHEAD-->        <p><font size="2"><i>By Sam Venable News-Sentinel
        Columnist</i></font></p>
        <p><font size="3"><!--dateline--></font><br>
        <font size="5">I</font> was in Orlando, Fla., a few years
        ago to visit my daughter who was interning at Walt Disney
        World. One afternoon while she helped Mickey Mouse make
        more money, I took a long walk around her apartment
        complex. </p>
        <p>At first glance, this was your stereotypic, stuccoed,
        tile-roofed, palm-treed hangout for Florida
        twenty-somethings. There was the obligatory pool and
        tennis court, each designed for social gatherings instead
        of geezer activities like swimming and tennis. Plus acres
        of asphalt -- lined-off, numbered and speed-bumped. </p>
        <p>But as I neared one intersection, something caught my
        eye behind a row of oleander bushes. I stepped to the
        edge of the sidewalk, peered through the foliage and saw
        a small marsh. </p>
        <p>I'm relying on memory here, but I'd guess the thing
        was roughly two or three times the size of the floor plan
        of a typical suburban house. Yet it was a full-fledged
        wetland. </p>
        <p>Red-winged blackbirds called from the cattails and
        willows. Wading birds stalked small fish and frogs in the
        shallows. Dragonflies skittered hither and yon. I heard
        the quiet ''szzchweep'' of a drake mallard and, cutting
        my eyes skyward, watched the greenhead coast in on
        motionless wings and settle gently on the surface of the
        water. </p>
        <p>In the midst of Metropolis? </p>
        <p>You better believe it. And the more I walked around
        the apartment complex, the more of these mini-marshes I
        found, each teeming with plants, fish and wildlife.
        Because of their location, they surely had been created
        as part of the apartment construction. I have no idea how
        many of these little refuges exist in the Orlando area,
        but if my daughter's complex is typical, they have to
        make a significant contribution to the native flora and
        fauna of that bustling tourist region. </p>
        <p>I mention that episode in hopes the two factions in
        the Turkey Creek wetland fight might make a sincere
        effort to find common ground. </p>
        <p>Surely you've heard of this controversy. It centers
        around a piece of marshy land in West Knox County that
        developers want to use for an extension to Parkside Drive
        and environmentalists want to preserve. Although I'm not
        intimately familiar with the fine print, I'm here to tell
        you a compromise is possible. </p>
        <p>No, not a win-win for everyone. But not a lose-lose
        either. </p>
        <p>Since this is the Christmas season, let me propose a
        wish list: </p>
        <p>I wish the pro-development side would drop the ''tree
        hugger'' and ''mosquito factory'' slurs and realize a lot
        of fine folks, who may or may not live in West Knoxville,
        are genuinely concerned about Mother Earth. Further, I
        wish the pro-developers would admit this is a NIMBY thing
        for them; everybody wants strict air and water law
        enforcement (do the words ''Pigeon River'' ring a bell?),
        just as long as their particular factory, highway plan,
        subdivision project or other high-dollar deal isn't
        stifled by them. I also wish the pro-developers would
        quit harping on the fact that the Turkey Creek wetland
        didn't used to be wet; geophysical changes constantly
        occur, by the hand of humans or not. And finally, I wish
        the pro-developers would understand that because American
        wetlands -- which are far from ''wastelands'' -- have
        been drained with reckless abandon for two centuries, the
        precious few remaining ones are that much more valuable. </p>
        <p>As for the environmentalists, I wish they would
        understand that not every piece of ''wildlife habitat''
        has to be vast, uncharted wilderness; the burgeoning deer
        population in Knox County is proof alone. Further, I wish
        they would realize that these developers have, as best I
        can tell, gone above and beyond the call of duty to
        soften the negative impact on the ecosystem. What's more,
        I wish they would appreciate that business interests,
        whether driven by conscience or regulation, are more
        willing than ever to incorporate wildlife mitigation into
        their plans instead of merely cranking up the bulldozers.
        </p>
        <p>Despite what you hear from both camps, this is not a
        black-white issue. There is an abundance of gray, if
        either side is willing to notice. </p>
        <p><font size="2"><strong>Sam Venable's column appears in
        The News-Sentinel on Sunday, Tuesday, Thursday and
        Friday. His column also is available on our Web site at
        www.knoxnews.com. His latest book, ''I'd Rather Be Ugly
        Than Stuppid,'' is now available from The News-Sentinel
        and area bookstores.</strong></font> </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

<hr size="5">

<p align="center"><font size="2">Return to </font><a href="/"><font
size="2">Main</font></a><font size="2">. Copyright © 1996 The
Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, send e-mail to our </font><a
href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size="2">webmaster</font></a><font
size="2">.</font></p>
</body>
