<TITLE>A true tale of an area artist who met Santa Claus</TITLE>
<!--Use the Headline for HTML Page Title-->
<!--Headline-->
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i>December 24, 1996</i></td>
        <td width="470"><font size="6"><b>A true tale of an area
        artist who met Santa Claus</b></font><br>
<!--SUBHEAD-->        <p><font size="2"><i>By Sam Venable News-Sentinel
        Columnist</i></font></p>
        <p><font size="3"><!--dateline--></font><br>
        <font size="5">I</font>'m going to tell you a story
        that's 121/2 years old. In the business of daily
        newspapering, this is ancient history. </p>
        <p>But it's not ancient to Dewey Wyrick. The events are
        as fresh in his mind right now as they were the June
        morning in 1984 when he met, alive and in the flesh,
        Santa Claus. </p>
        <p>Wyrick is an artist who lives in Rockford. You may
        remember his tender ''Storyteller'' portrait that was
        quite popular during the Tennessee Homecoming '86
        celebration. </p>
        <p>A copy of that painting is reproduced here. See the
        little girl sitting on her ''grandfather's'' lap? That's
        Wyrick's own daughter, Brooke, who is now a senior at the
        Webb School. The lad with the coonskin cap is an amalgam
        of the generic ''boy next door.'' </p>
        <p>But the old guy with the flowing white hair and beard?
        That's Santa. </p>
        <p>''That was his real name -- Santa C. Claus,'' says
        Wyrick. ''He had a driver's license and Social Security
        card to prove it.'' </p>
        <p>At one time, the man was known as LeRoy Scholtz. He
        had his name legally changed to Santa Claus in 1980. He
        lived in New York and worked for a modeling agency.
        Wyrick still has some old newspaper and magazine ads
        featuring Scholtz in his Santa attire. They're realistic
        enough to make you believe all over again. </p>
        <p>Scholtz/Santa came into Wyrick's life that June
        morning in '84 as he was working on a drawing of the Old
        Mill in Pigeon Forge. </p>
        <p>''He just walked up and started a conversation,''
        Wyrick recalled. ''Said he liked my work because it
        featured children. To be honest, I thought he was some
        kind of nut at first. Here it was the middle of summer,
        and he had on a long-sleeved shirt with Christmas
        decorations. His car even had a reindeer painted on the
        side.'' </p>
        <p>Santa gave Wyrick a photo of himself and his
        grandchildren and asked the artist to reproduce it.
        That's exactly what he did, creating a mock-up of what
        would later serve as the basis of his Homecoming piece. </p>
        <p>Wyrick tried to contact the old man and set up a
        promotional tour. Despite leaving messages at talent
        agencies, all he got were dead ends. </p>
        <p>''When I finally reached him, he was ill and somewhat
        incoherent,'' Wyrick said. ''I cancelled my production
        plans and altered the faces in my painting.'' </p>
        <p>The Homecoming portrait and poster were released in
        November 1985 and were well-received. Just one month
        later, however, Wyrick got word that Santa had died, sick
        and alone, in a Chicago hotel. The story ran in
        newspapers all over the country, including The
        News-Sentinel. </p>
        <p>Wyrick donated part of the proceeds from the sale of
        the poster to East Tennessee Children's Hospital and the
        Christian Academy of Knoxville. </p>
        <p>Said the artist: ''I always felt this would've made
        Santa happy.'' </p>
        <p>Sam Venable's<font size="2"><strong> column appears in
        The News-Sentinel on Sunday, Tuesday, Thursday and
        Friday. His column also is available on our Web site at
        www.knoxnews.com. His latest book, ''I'd Rather Be Ugly
        Than Stuppid,'' is now available from The News-Sentinel
        and area bookstores.</strong></font> </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

<hr size="5">

<p align="center"><font size="2">Return to </font><a href="/"><font
size="2">Main</font></a><font size="2">. Copyright © 1996 The
Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, send e-mail to our </font><a
href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size="2">webmaster</font></a><font
size="2">.</font></p>
