<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>Quarry mining reigns near Crab Orchard</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i>January 20, 1997</i> </td>
        <td width="470"><font size="6"><b><img
        src="../images/quarry.jpg" align="left" hspace="7"
        width="200" height="303"></b></font><p><font size="1"><b>Third
        generation quarryman Charles Davis sits atop thesandstone
        flagging which hisfamily mined near Crab Orchard for 40
        years.</b></font><font size="6"><b><br clear="all">
        <img src="../../images/v3/credits/PEcredit.gif"
        width="144" height="21"><br>
        Quarry mining reigns near Crab Orchard<!--SUBHEAD--></b></font></p>
        <p><font size="2"><i>By Morgan Simmons, News-Sentinel
        staff writer</i></font></p>
        <p><br>
        <font size="5">C</font>ROSSVILLE -- Normally, rock
        quarries are no place to take a vehicle, but on this day,
        with the help of a three-day cold snap and four-wheel
        drive, we drive through the sandstone depression across
        frozen mud and sheets of ice. </p>
        <p>The quarry belongs to Charles Davis, a native of
        Crossville and a third-generation quarryman and stone
        mason. The vehicle belongs to David Rose, also from
        Crossville, and president of Tennessee Building Stone,
        the largest supplier of Crab Orchard sandstone on the
        Cumberland Plateau. </p>
        <p>The quarry has been in Davis's family for 40 years.
        Davis inherited it from his father Cecil, a renowned
        stone mason. The quarry is known for producing
        earth-toned rock -- browns and buffs as opposed to pink
        and blues. </p>
        <p>A light dusting of snow covers the loose slabs and the
        multihued cross-sections of cap rock. With a little
        imagination, you could be standing in the Painted Desert
        of Arizona rather than in a three-acre rock quarry off
        Rock Quarry Road. </p>
        <p>''Seven years ago I thought this was played out,''
        said Davis. ''David here talked me into shooting just one
        more bench, and we found a fresh seam.'' </p>
        <p>''You find a place on a hill or a creek where there's
        an outcropping of stone, and you take your chances from
        there,'' said Rose. </p>
        <p>The rock is called Tennessee quartzite. Found within a
        50-mile radius of Crab Orchard, it ranges in color from
        pale red to gray-blue and is prized the world over for
        its tight grain and density. </p>
        <p>There are at least 20 stone companies in the
        Crossville-Crab Orchard area. The larger ones are
        equipped with industrial-sized saws that render 10-ton
        blocks into hearths and mantle pieces. Many, like Charles
        Davis', are family operations consisting of a phone, a
        rock yard and two or three people to work a small quarry.
        </p>
        <p>Davis has what's known as a flagging quarry. It
        produces flagstone and wafer-thin pieces of sandstone
        that can be used as wall veneer. There is a motorized saw
        that chops stone into brick-sized chunks, called rubble,
        but for the most part, the rock is separated into
        sections by hand, with a wedge and a maul. </p>
        <p>Rose, whose company owns or has contracts with a dozen
        quarries on the Cumberland Plateau, compared quarrying
        sandstone to surface mining. </p>
        <p>''It's a crap shoot,'' he said. ''You can spend weeks
        removing the overburden and never hit a good slab. The
        majority of quarries around here have been worked out and
        abandoned, but over the years the demand has grown to
        where people are coming back to work them some more.'' </p>
        <p>After the heavy equipment exposes a seam of sandstone,
        Davis and his crew bore a series of holes 5 feet deep and
        shoot the rock with explosives, breaking off a bench
        approximately 8 feet wide, 5 feet deep and 150 feet long.
        </p>
        <p>Working from the end, the quarry crew then skims off
        sheets of rock by hand, using wedges and mauls to
        separate the sandstone along its natural fissures. </p>
        <p>''The thinner rock is the money rock,'' said Davis.
        ''It lays flat. Also, nice square and rectangle pieces
        bring five times as much as irregulars.'' </p>
        <p>Rose said that while Tennessee quartzite costs a
        little more than brick -- about $90 a ton -- the real
        cost is in the installation since the rocks have to be
        individually cut on the building site. </p>
        <p>''It's not the kind of trade they teach in vocational
        school,'' he said. ''If you don't start as somebody's
        helper, there's no way to learn how to lay and cut rock. </p>
        <p>''Charles here and I were laying stone when we were
        teenagers. I was never fast enough, so I gave it up.'' </p>
        <p>Davis said his quarry has been a good provider for 11
        years and that he's keeping his fingers crossed it'll
        produce for several more. His quarry adjoins several
        others. In fact, an aerial view taken above Rock Quarry
        Road would reveal that all the quarries are essentially
        mining the same ridge. </p>
        <p>At the end of Rock Quarry Road is the old Crab Orchard
        quarry, which has been worked as hard as any. On this
        day, only one person is breaking rock in the freezing
        cold, and his name is Chester Stone. Using a chisel and
        maul, he splits the slabs horizontally into 100-pound
        sheets, which he wrestles into the back of his pickup
        truck. </p>
        <p>''He's probably being paid by the ton,'' said Davis.
        ''There are easier ways to make a living, but he's
        working at his own pace. If it wasn't so cold, there'd be
        others out here doing the same thing.'' </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

<hr size="5">

<p align="center"><font size="2">Return to </font><a href="/"><font
size="2">Main</font></a><font size="2">. Copyright © 1996 The
Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a
href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size="2">webmaster</font></a><font
size="2">.</font></p>
