<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>Budget the key, says McWherter</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 20, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>Budget the key, says McWherter</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Richard Powelson, News-Sentinel Washington bureau</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">W</FONT>ASHINGTON -- President Clinton will have a successful second term if he can keep cutting federal spending significantly every year and make steady progress toward a balanced budget, former Gov. Ned McWherter said.
<P>   McWherter, attending his third presidential inauguration, said in an interview: &#39;&#39;I think those are the (key) issues . . . to continue on the course of reducing the deficit, work toward a balanced budget.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Tennessee&#39;s governor from 1987 to 1995, McWherter said he was pleased that Clinton got on a middle-of-the-road approach to many issues in the last couple years of his first term and began reducing the deficits in the federal budget.
<P>   McWherter was among the more moderate Democrats who advised Clinton in 1995 and 1996 to keep on a centrist course.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I think he did that, and that overall is what really contributed to his re-election,&#39;&#39; McWherter said. &#39;&#39;People realized that he was governing from the center.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Another big need that the Clinton administration should address in its second term, he said, is getting the rising cost of the massive Medicare, Medicaid and Social Security programs under control.
<P>   &#39;&#39;They just absolutely need to be dealt with . . . in an orderly, responsible way that doesn&#39;t do tremendous damage to the people on the receiving end. I think you&#39;ll see that happen.&#39;&#39;
<P>   During McWherter&#39;s second term, the state got permission from federal officials to reform its Medicaid program into a lower-cost, managed-care system that was  renamed &#39;&#39;TennCare.&#39;&#39; McWherter said he hopes the federal government and all states will adopt similar Medicaid reforms across the country.
<P>   In the 1996 presidential campaign, McWherter was Tennessee chairman of the Clinton-Gore campaign. After Clinton carried Tennessee in 1992 by only five percentage points, and the state in 1994 elected more Republicans to the U.S. House and Senate and also gave them the governor&#39;s office, McWherter recommended that Clinton and Gore visit Tennessee often before the 1996 election. They did and carried the state, though narrowly.
<P>   McWherter said it will be very difficult but not impossible for Democrats and Republicans to agree on many more budget cuts to balance the budget. He said the budget problem is such a major one for the country that both parties must put aside partisanship to solve it.
<P>   Here is McWherter&#39;s approach to progress on the issue: &#39;&#39;The wishful thinking would be . . . (for) the Republicans and Democrats declare a political truce for 10 months, or 12 months or six months, and say: &#39;We&#39;re going to come together and do what needs to be done that&#39;s responsible and orderly to put the country in the right direction and not have any partisanship displays and not talk (critically) about each other.&#39;
<P>   &#39;&#39;And then, kind of like you do at a basketball game, blow the whistle and say: &#39;Toss the ball; we&#39;re ready to go.&#39; I don&#39;t know how they will ever do it unless they do something like that.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Clinton and McWherter both served as governors of adjoining southern states for a time and became friends. They still talk occasionally about federal and state issues, but McWherter continues to have no interest in moving to Washington to work, he said.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

