<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>Medical board to rethink ban on obesity medication</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 20, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>Medical board to rethink ban on obesity medication</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Tom Humphrey, News-Sentinel Nashville bureau</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">N</FONT>ASHVILLE -- Tennessee&#39;s ban on anti-obesity drugs that are widely used in other states will be reconsidered on Tuesday by the board that imposed it.
<P>    The state Board of Medical Examiners meeting comes as the crusade to repeal Tennessee&#39;s prohibition of so-called &#39;&#39;phen/fen&#39;&#39; treatments moves to the state Legislature. A bill to overrule the board&#39;s ban has already been introduced.
<P>    &#39;&#39;They&#39;re under political pressure,&#39;&#39; says Sharon Segal of Knoxville, who heads a coalition of phen/fen advocates. 
<P>    The board, which is responsible for enacting rules on the practice of medicine in Tennessee, has declared doctors may not write prescriptions for the controversial anti-obesity drugs. Tennessee is the only state with such a far-reaching prohibition, prompting those who want the drugs to get them in other states.
<P>    The Tennessee Medical Association, which represents doctors statewide, recently petitioned the board to reconsider its prohibition. A board subcommittee will take up the topic Tuesday morning in Nashville, followed by consideration of any recommendation by the full board that afternoon.
<P>    Segal says the TMA move was &#39;&#39;a great big plus for us,&#39;&#39; but she is none too optimistic that the board will backpeddle from its longstanding ban. The board listened to pleas from Segal and others for a repeal of the ban last year, but then board Chairman O.M. McCallum said the panel would await results of studies of the treatment before acting.
<P>    &#39;&#39;They&#39;re doing this under duress,&#39;&#39; she said. &#39;&#39;They may just throw us a bone.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Such a token move, she said, could involve changing state rules on the prescriptions but leaving them overly restrictive -- or announcing an intention to come up with new rules while postponing the effective date.
<P>    Sen. Steve Cohen, D-Memphis, has introduced a bill that would allow doctors to write prescriptions for phen/fen, more properly known as fenfluramine and phentermine, as appetite suppressants to treat chronic obesity.
<P>    In a letter to McCallum, Cohen said &#39;&#39;thousands&#39;&#39; of overweight Tennesseans are traveling to other states for phen/fen.
<P>    &#39;&#39;This is an inconvenience to our citizens, as well as, I would imagine, placing their health at risk as some of these (out-of-state) clinics apparently do very little for the patient except prescribe the drugs when there may be other medical needs,&#39;&#39; he wrote.
<P>    &#39;&#39;These decisions are best handled by a professional board and not by the Tennessee General Assembly, but 49 other states and our citizens tell us that the board has failed to meet the needs of Tennessee citizens.&#39;&#39;
<P>    McCallum said last year that the board wanted to see results of a recently launched study of phen/fen that is under way at the University of Tennessee School of Medicine in Memphis.
<P>    McCallum said there is much concern that phen/fen treatment aggravates pulmonary hypertension and causes death in a significant number of persons treated.
<P>    Advocates say there have already been adequate studies on the risks entailed in taking the diet pills and a decision on the risks vs. benefits should be left to treating physicians.
<P>    Seagle, who heads the Tennessee Coalition to Lift the Ban on Schedule Four Anti-Obesity Medications, said she has lost about 100 pounds, thanks to phen/fen. Many morbidly obese persons, who risk death without major weight loss, cannot afford to travel out of state for the drugs, she says.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

