<html>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>It&#39;s Radon Awareness Month</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 20, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>It&#39;s Radon Awareness Month</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">J</FONT>anuary is Radon Awareness Month, and in observance the American Lung Association and Knox County Health Department are urging all local residents to test their homes for dangerous levels of the radioactive gas.
<P>   Radon typically moves up through the ground to the air above and into your home through foundation cracks and other openings. Homes act like a vacuum and trap radon inside, where it continues to build up and can be deadly at high levels.
<P>   Unfortunately, any home could have a radon problem. The good news is the gas can be detected by testing, which is easy and inexpensive.
<P>   The Health Department is sponsoring a Radon Test Program, and Knox County homeowners may purchase a radon test kit for a nominal fee by participating.
<P>   The program is being funded by a $10,000 grant through the Washington, D.C.-based National Association of Counties.
<P>   The Health Department received the grant last May and will continue the program through April this year to promote radon awareness.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Our first year we concentrated on giving away the test kits to entice people to check their homes,&#39;&#39; said Frank Duncan, an environmentalist and radon program manager at the Health Department.
<P>   Duncan estimated some 750 kits have been given away. Now, the Health Department sells the kits for $4 and is focusing more on educating the community about the dangers of radon. The ALA also has kits available.
<P>   In addition, the Health Department and ALA offer booklets about radon -- &#39;&#39;Home Buyer&#39;s and Seller&#39;s Guide to Radon,&#39;&#39; &#39;&#39;Consumer&#39;s Guide to Radon Reduction: How to reduce radon levels in your home,&#39;&#39; and &#39;&#39;A Citizen&#39;s Guide to Radon.&#39;&#39;
<P>   To register for the Radon Program or for more information about acquiring kits or the booklets, call the Health Department at 544-4242 or the ALA at 602-7922.
<P>   
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

