<head>
	<title>Health Improvement Council to fund 19 projects</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 20, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Health Improvement Council to fund 19 projects</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Amy Smith, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">N</FONT>ineteen community projects will receive $521,969 in funding this year from the Knox County Community Health Improvement Council for work to increase access to health care, build violence-free communities and improve parenting skills among Knox Countians.
<P>   The council is a volunteer group concerned with community issues affecting the health status of Knox County residents, particularly children, because the council believes healthy children will grow to be healthy, productive adults. 
<P>   The council&#39;s activities and projects in seven counties are supported by Covenant Health and receive funds for approved projects through the Community Health Improvement Initiative.
<P>   Covenant Health is a health-care organization created last year by the merger of Fort Sanders Health System and MMC HealthCare System, parent company of Methodist Medical Center of Oak Ridge.
<P>   In August 1994, Fort Sanders committed $1.2 million to launch the Community Health Improvement Initiative.
<P>   The community health program&#39;s goal is to shift the focus of health care from treatment to prevention by addressing social issues that affect a community&#39;s health.
<P>   The projects, sponsoring agencies and funding amounts in 1997:
<P>
<P>   * Dogwood Elementary School-based clinic -- Continuation funding for a clinic staffed by a full-time nurse and a part-time pediatrician providing parent and social skills training and on-site mental health services, $28,000.
<P>   * Family Enrichment and Development Program -- An after-school program sponsored by Wesley House for kindergartners, pre-teens, teen girls and parents of participating children that focuses on non-violent conflict resolution behavior, enhancing education and improving parenting skills, $10,000.
<P>   * Family Friends -- An intergenerational program of Knoxville-Knox County Community Action Committee that matches trained older volunteers to families with at-risk children, $25,870.
<P>   * Family Services Program -- A service of the Knox County Juvenile Court that provides support to unruly youth and their families, $17,000.
<P>   * Greater Knoxville Kids on the Block -- A puppet outreach program of Child and Family Services that presents information about social issues for children, $10,000.
<P>   * Interfaith Health Clinic -- To help provide accessible and affordable primary health care, dental care and social services to the working poor and medically uninsured, $100,000.
<P>   * Knoxville Academy of Medicine Alliance -- To support the educational efforts of the Health Discovery program at KAMA Health Discovery Center, including classroom presentations and transportation costs for bringing children to the center, $5,000.
<P>   * Mechanicsville Health Clinic -- To Restoration Outreach to open a health clinic in the Mechanicsville community, $50,000.
<P>   * My Place -- A program of Knoxville&#39;s Community Development Corporation for children ages 5-12 with a focus on providing inner-city children with tools needed to survive and overcome the effects of violence, $40,000.
<P>   * The Parent Refuge -- A program of the Volunteer Ministry Center that provides early intervention for at-risk single-parent families, $45,500.
<P>   * The Parenting Center -- A program of Junior League of Knoxville that provides parenting classes for individuals referred from area social services agencies, $7,350.
<P>   * Positive Parents -- A program of Child and Family Services addressing family needs for violence-free, drug-free shelter; housing and food; and assessment, intervention, safety planning, medical care and parenting skills, $56,000.
<P>   * Positively Living -- A proposed day activity center for individuals living with catastrophic illnesses that is supported by a coalition of churches, synagogues, agencies and organizations, $8,000.
<P>   * Respond -- A program of Child and Family Services addressing parental substance abuse, $20,000.
<P>   * Summer Program for Inner City Youth -- a continuation grant to allow Emerald Avenue Urban Youth and Leadership Foundation to operate its summer youth program for pre-schoolers through 12th graders in three inner-city communities, $40,000.
<P>   * Teens as Teachers -- A program of the Knox County Health Department that trains teens to teach younger students about the dangers and consequences of tobacco use, $3,649.
<P>   * Think First Program -- A program to help reduce the incidence of non-fatal head and spinal cord injuries through education or youth, $6,250.
<P>   * West Knox County Senior Center -- To the Knox County Alliance of Seniors to establish a senior center in West Knoxville, $43,350.
<P>   * Youth at Risk After-School Program -- To support the Morningside Heights Homeowners Association in providing a structured after-school program, $6,000.
<P>   Agencies that are sponsoring projects were asked to submit proposals for funding, and then council members recommended appropriate projects to the Community Health Improvement Committee of the Covenant Health board of directors for approval.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
