<P><B>ADKINS, JOHN C. - </B>age 69, of West Knoxville, passed away January 18, 1997. He was of the Baptist faith. He was retired from U.T. as a tape network manager for the Radio Services Dept. Survivors: wife, Amelia Doris Adkins; sons, Lt. Lance Adkins, Grandforks, N.D., Alan Adkins, Knoxville, Tenn. Funeral service 8 p.m., Monday at Highland-West Funeral Home Chapel, Dr. Calvin Bailey officiating. The entombment will be 11 a.m. Tuesday at Highland-West Memorial Park Mausoleum. The family will receive friends 6-8 p.m., Monday at Highland-West Funeral Home, 9913 Sherrill Ln., 693-9547.
<P>
<P><B>BRANTON, MARY - </B>85, Cherokee Dr., Morristown, died January 18, at Heritage Center. Retired from Lea-Wayne Knitting Mills. She attended Kidwells Ridge Baptist Church. She was preceded in death by: brothers, John and Ben; and sisters, Addie and Cora. She is survived by: one sister, Orphia Trent; and sister-in-law, Willie Branton; nieces, Shelby Trent and Beverly Quillen; nephews, Randal Branton and Charles Branton; several great-nieces and nephews. Services will be 8 p.m. Monday at Stetzer&#39;s Chapel. Burial will be in the family plot at Kidwells Ridge Cemetery. The family will receive friends today from 6 until time of service. Stetzer Funeral Home, in charge of arrangements.
<P>
<P><B>BROWN, CLYDE A. - </B>age 83, of Lenoir City, passed away Sunday morning, January 19, 1997, at the Parkwest Hospital. He was a member of the Highland Park Baptist Church. He was a Mason, member of the Avery Lodge #593 F.& A.M. of Lenoir City, Scottish Rite of Knoxville. He was a Shriner and member of the Kerbela Temple of Knoxville. Preceded in death by: parents, J.L. and Myra Brown; daughter, Lucille Brown Rush; son, William C. Brown; and brother, Howard Brown. Survivors: wife, Kathryn Viars Brown; daughter, Carol Ann Hall; daughter-in-law, Thelma Brown, all of Lenoir City; grandsons, Chris Dutton, Frankie Hall, Phil, Brian, and Tony Rush; three great-grandchildren; sisters, Elsie Thompson, Ella Lethgo, both of Lenoir City, Elizabeth Mull of Knoxville, Stella James of Athens; several nieces and nephews. Funeral 8 p.m. Tuesday in the Hawkins Chapel with Rev. George Seay officiating. Entombment 2 p.m. Wednesday in the Lakeview Mausoleum. The family will receive friends from 6-8 p.m. Tuesday at the Hawkins Mortuary, Lenoir City.
<P>
<P><B>BYERS, JOSEPH EDWARD &#39;&#39;JOE&#39;&#39; - </B>age 71, of West Knoxville, passed away Sunday morning, January 19, 1997, at his home. He was retired from Knoxville Truck Sales. A member of Centerview Baptist Church. A veteran of World War II, serving in th Navy. Funeral arrangements are incomplete. Click Funeral Home, Lenoir City, in charge.
<P>
<P><B>CAUDILL, HUBERT (HUGH) HAMPTON - </B>71, of Oak Ridge, died Sunday, January 19, 1997, at UT Medical Center. Veteran of WWII, serving with the United States Marine Corp. A resident of Oak Ridge since 1954, Mr. Caudill was an active member of Kern Memorial United Methodist Church. He retired from Oak Ridge National Laboratory in 1989 after 37 years. Preceded in death by: parents, Herman and Essie Caudill; brother, Charles Lee Caudill; and sister, Hazel Deaton. He is survived by: wife, Betty Clotfelter Caudill; sons, Thomas David Caudill of Atlanta, Ga. and Robert Lee Caudill and wife, Paulette Lynam Caudill of Seymour, Tenn.; and their children, Nancy Kathleen Caudill and Jessica Lee Caudille; sister, Mary Howard and husband, Arlie Howard; and niece, Heather Howard of Delaware, Ohio. Funeral services are Tuesday, January 21, 1997, at 11 a.m. at Kern Memorial United Methodist Church with Rev. Ronald Ingram officiating. Burial in Oak Ridge Memorial Park. Memorials may be made to Kern Memorial United Methodist Church Building Fund, 451 E. Tennessee Ave., Oak Ridge, TN 37830. The family will receive friends Monday, January 20, 1997, from 7-9 p.m. at Weatherford Mortuary, Oak Ridge.
<P>
<P><B>COBBLE, HUGH C. - </B>age 78, of West McKee Street, Greeneville, passed away Sunday morning, January 19, 1997, in Northside Hospital, Johnson City. Mr. Cobble was a very active member of the Reformation Lutheran Church. He was a retired vice-president of Greene County Bank after 43 years service. He was a member of the East Tennessee Management Club, was a volunteer for the Greeneville-Greene County Community Ministries, Greeneville Exchange Club, former member of the Greeneville-Greene County Fair Board, former member of the Band Booster Club, and many other community activites. He is survived by: wife, Helen H. Cobble; three sons and daughters-in-law, Dr. Douglas and Brenda Cobble of Greeneville, Charles and Connie Cobble of Greeneville, Donald and Nadine Cobble of Knoxville; two stepsons and one stepdaugher-in-law., W.F. and Sharon Shumate of Knoxville, Mark H. Shumate of Johnson City; and one stepdaughter and stepson-in-law, Susan and Charles Essick of Texas; 15 grandchildren, Melissa Cobble, Matthew Cobble, Mrs. Robert Lee (Paula Jane) Morgan II, Carrie Ann Cobble, Kellie Cobble, Grant Cobble, Jon Southerland, David Southerland, Riess Shumate, Dean Shumate, Beth Sexton, Leigh Shumate, Hank Shumate, Chad Essick, Tommy Essick; one great-grandson, Davis Sexton; special sister-in-law, Kathleen Evans of the Orebank Community. Mr. Cobble was preceded in death by: his wives, Ruby Myers Cobble and Elizabeth Burleson Cobble; his granddaughter, Cristen Shea Cobble; his twin sister, Ruth Cobble; and his parents, Minnis Lee and Carrie Catron Cobble. Funeral services will be conducted at 2 p.m. Tuesday in the Doughty-Stevens Chapel. Interment will follow in Mt. Pleasant Cemetery with Pastor J. Howard Mettee officiating. Active pallbearers will be David Finchum, Buddy Kreeger, Dr. Dale Brown, Jr., Joe Brown, Steve Ottinger, Davis Stroud, Charles Lintz, and John Hendrix. Honorary pallbearers will be the men of Reformation Lutheran Church, Dr. Maynard Austin, Dr. A.K. Sen, and Dr. Robert Strimer. Memorials may be made to the Reformation Lutheran Church of to the Cancer Care Unit of the Laughlin Health Care Foundation, 1420 Tusculum Blvd., Greeneville, TN 37745. The family will receive friends from 2 p.m. until 4 p.m. Monday afternoon and from 7 p.m. until 9 p.m. Monday evening at Doughty-Stevens Funeral Home.
<P>
<P>h3815_0124
<P><B>COOK, ROBERT ERWIN - </B>died January 17, 1997, at his home in Knoxville, following a courageous struggle with cancer. A native of Knoxville, Mr. Cook was the son of the late May Rothe and John Robert Cook. He was a graduate of the University of Tennessee, Knoxville, Class of 1948, where he was a member of Sigma Alpha Epsilon Fraternity. Mr. Cook lived in Athens for 27 years, where he taught chemistry and physics at McMinn County High School and was later principal of Ingleside School before entering the insurance business. He was a member of Certified Property and Casualty Underwriters (CPCU), vice president of Athens Insurance Agency, served as president of The Insurers of Tennessee, member of The Executive Committee, and vice president of The National Association of Insurance Agents, was named Tennessee&#39;s Insurer of the Year, received the President&#39;s Award from The National Association of Insurance Agents, and won two national advertising competitions sponsored by The Insurance Advertising Conference. He served as board chairman of the Athens Housing Authority; president of the McMinn County Historical Society; chairman of the McMinn County American Revolution Bicentennial Commission; campaign chairman, Athens United Way; president, Athens Kiwanis Club; Deacon and choir member of Mars Hill Presbyterian Church, Athens; president, Smoky Mountains Hiking Club; president, East Tennessee Historical Society; president, The Meadows Condominium Association; member, Sons of the Revolution; and member of Westminster Presbyterian Church, Knoxville. He loved the Smoky Mountains and hiked all of its 900 miles of trails in both directions. He also hiked over 1,100 of The Applachian Trail. Mr. Cook was preceded in death by: sister, Margaret (Mrs. Charles Donald Rose), Kingston; and two brothers, John Rothe Cook, Knoxville and Lester Millan Cook, Los Angeles. He is survived by: wife, Barbara Small Cook; daughter, Sherry Lynn and husband, Charles Eugene Sabo, Greenville, S.C.; and daughter, Cynthiana and husband, Gary George Spangler, Knoxville; granddaughter, Rachael Lynn Spangler, Knoxville; sister, Helen (Mrs. R.A. Lawson, Jr.), Loudon, Tenn.; and nine nieces and nephews. The family has requested that in lieu of flowers, memorial contributions be made to the McClung Historical Collection, East Tennessee Historical Center, 314 Clinch Ave., Knoxville, TN 37902 or Westminster Presbyterian Church Memorial Fund, 6500 Northshore Drive, Knoxville, TN 37919. There will be a memorial service, Friday, January 24, 1997, at Westminister Presbyterian Church at 6 p.m. with the Rev. Dr. Friedrich J. Schilling, J.R. officiating. The family will receive friends from 7-9 p.m., January 24, at the home of Cynthiana and Gary Spangler, 6427 Westminister Road. Arrangements by Rose Mortuary Mann Heritage Chapel.
<P>
<P><B>DAVIS, JOHN G. - </B>age 79, of Murfreesboro, formerly of Blount Co., Tenn., passed away Saturday evening, January 18, 1997, at the family home. Retired from the Alvin C. York Medical Center in Murfreesboro. Retired veteran of the U.S. Air Force with 23 years of service, Veteran of World War II. He was a Mason. Preceded in death by first wife, Geneva Davis. Survivors: wife, Jane Alsup Christian Davis; son and daughter-in-law, William Norman and Deborah Davis of Abilene, Texas; three grandchildren; four great-grandchildren; stepdaughter and stepson-in-law, Janice and Jerry Benson of Murfreesboro; stepson and stepdaughter-in-law, Jackson and Mary Jo Christian of Murfreesboro; six step-grandchildren; one step-great-grandchild; several nieces and nephews. Family and friends will meet at Sherwood Memorial Gardens at 3 p.m. Tuesday for graveside service and interment, Rev. Eugene Gann officiating. The family will receive friends from 1-2:30 p.m. Tuesday at Miller Funeral Home, Maryville.
<P>
<P><B>DRUMMER, JOHN ULYESS - </B>age 66, of Knoxville, passed away 8:30 a.m. Sunday, January 19, 1997, at St. Mary&#39;s Medical Center. Member of Alice Bell Baptist Church and Burlington Lodge No. 763 F.& A.M. He was retired from Knox Cortage and Brown Transport. Preceded in death by: parents, Charlie and Blaine Drummer; sister, Clara Drummer; and brothers, Clark and Buford Drummer. Survivors: wife, Sue Drummer; son and daughter-in-law, Steve and Pam Drummer, Knoxville; daughter and son-in-law, Beth and Billy Crumley, High Point, N.C.; grandchildren, Evan and Katelyn Drummer, Sara and Hayley Crumley; sisters, Pauline Burkhart, Indiana, Kathleen Barney, Texas, Marie Arms, Knoxville; brothers, Homer Drummer, Knoxville, Earl Drummer, Indiana; several nieces and nephews. Funeral 8 p.m. Tuesday, McCarty Chapel, Dr. Doug White officiating. Family and friends will meet at 10:45 a.m. Wednesday at Caledonia Cemetery for an 11 a.m. committal service. Honorary pallbearers will be members of Adult II Mens Sunday School Class at Alice Bell Baptist Church. The family will receive friends 6:30-8 p.m. Tuesday at McCarty Mortuary, 4004 Holston Dr.
<P>
<P><B>FLOYD, MICHAEL L. - </B>age 48, formerly of Oklahoma, now living in Friendsville, passed away January 15, 1997, at his home. Attended Union Grove Methodist Church. Survivors: wife, Patricia Floyd; stepchildren, Clayton Rudder, Cheyenne Webb. Graveside service 2 p.m. Tuesday, Tennessee Veterans Cemetery with full military honors. Berry Funeral Home, Chapman Highway, in charge of arrangements.
<P>
<P><B>FORD, FRED A. - </B>age 75, of South Knoxville, passed away January 18, 1997. He was of the Church of Christ faith. He was a veteran of WWII. Survivors; wife of 50 years, Iva Sayne Ford; sons, William H. Ford, Hartford, Conn., Tom Ford, Knoxville, Rick Ford, Knoxville, Dean Ford, Knoxville, David Ford, Knoxville, Ernie Ford, Knoxville; daughter, Mary Sue Ford Davis, Seymour; brothers, Frank Ford, Knoxville, Henry Ford, Knoxville; sisters, Hazel Neubert, Knoxville, Evelyn Goddard, Knoxville, Audrey Bunch, South Carolina; 12 grandchildren; three great-grandchildren; several nieces and nephews. Funeral service 2 p.m. Monday at Holly Hills Chapel, Rev. Chuck Webb officiating. The interment will be in Holly Hills Memorial Park. Pallbearers: Jimmy Davis, Nick Ford, Bobby Williams, Lowell Cook, Richard Ford, Sammy Hatcher. Military honors will be presented by the East Tennessee Veterans Honor Guard. Arrangements by Holly Hills Funeral Home, 573-7300.
<P>
<P><B>GENTRY, CLAUDINE BATES - </B>age 92, of Pleasant Grove Community, passed away Sunday morning, at her home. She was the widow of Thomas Esco Gentry. Life-long member of Corryton Baptist Church; the Corryton Chapter of O.E.S.; Union County Retired Teachers Association; Union County Historial Society; was a teacher in Union County and Knox County Schools for 31 years before retirement. Survived by: son, John G. Gentry of Luttrell; granddaughter, Sonya Ernst, Boston, Mass.; and one great-grandson; sisters-in-law, Mrs. Clarence (Ruth) Bates and Mrs. L.D. (Ruth) Bates, both of Corryton; numerous nieces and nephews; a special caregiver, Faye Cooper of Luttrell. Family and friends will meet 2:30 p.m. Tuesday at Greenwood Cemetery for graveside services, Rev. Doyle M. Davis officiating. Pallbearers: Bill Hankins, Tom Monroe, John Monroe, Lynn Bates, David Bates, and Roy Willett. Friends may call at their convenience at
<P>Gentry-Griffey Chapel.
<P>
<P><B>HINES, B.L. - </B>77, of the Dante Community, died Friday, January 17, 1997. He attended Dante Church of God and was a Knoxville grading and excavating contractor for more than 30 years. Mr. Hines was preceded in death by his beloved wife of 54 years, Juanita. Survivors: sons, Gary Hines and Bary Dale Hines, both of Knoxville; grandchildren, Ellen Silver, Sherry Ammons, and Randy Hines; two great-grandchildren; brother, James Linville of Kentucky; sister, Edna Watkins of Alabama; aunt, Ila Rogers of Knoxville. Funeral service 7:30 p.m., Monday in Rose Mortuary Broadway Chapel with Rev. Robert L. Holmes and Rev. Joel Ammons officiating. Family and friends will meet at Bookwalter Cemetery for a 1 p.m. interment service. The family will receive friends 6-7:30 p.m., Monday at Rose Mortuary Broadway Chapel.
<P>
<P><B>HOSKINS, WANDA</B> <B>(RIDINGS) - </B>73, of Cumberland Gap, Tenn., passed away Thursday, January 16, 1997, at the University of Tennessee Medical Center of Knoxville. She was born June 18, 1923, a daughter of the late Chester and Bertha (Hubbard) Ridings. She was a member of First Baptist Church. In addition to her parents, she was preceded in death by her husband, Herbert Hoskins; a sister, Georgia Evelyn Ridings; two brothers, Charles Ridings, Lee Ridings; and a special friend, A.J. Drummond. Survivors include: her children and their spouses, Sandy and Jim Montgomery, Knoxville, Tenn., Linda and Leroy Keeling, Bardstown, Ky., Herbert, Jr. and Lee Hoskins, Knoxville, Tenn., Richard and Pam Hoskins, Tazewell, Tenn.; grandchildren and their spouses, Craig and Andrea Montgomery, Knoxville, Jane and Mark Russell, Maryville, Tenn., Julie Keeling, Amy Keeling, Kristen Keeling of Bardstown, Josh Hoskins, Hannah Hoskins, Patrick Hoskins of Knoxville, Brooke Hoskins and Richard Alan Hoskins of Tazewell; sisters, Edna Goley and Dorothy Hendrickson, both of Middlesboro; and several nieces and nephews. Services will be at 8 p.m. today at Creech Funeral Home with the Rev. Jeff Roberts presiding, and a special remembrance will be delivered by the Rev. Ellis Hoskins. Music will be provided by Jimmy Jackson, Dickie Siler, and her granddaughter, Jane Russell. Graveside service with burial will be at 1 p.m., Sunday in Green Hills Cemetery, Middlesboro with Rev. Jeff Roberts presiding. Pallbearers will be Craig Montgomery, Mark Russell, Randy Hoskins, Junior Hoskins, Billy Hendrickson, Josh Hoskins, Phillip Brooks, Tony King. Honorary pallbearers will be Murrell Davis, Willie Hendrickson, Bill Drummond, Michael Hoskins, Lee Wayne Ridings, Asher Hoskins, Ellis Hoskins, and the Seekers Sunday School Class. Visitation is from 5-8 p.m. today at Creech Funeral Home, which is in charge of arrangements.
<P>
<P><B>HOWARD, KATHLEEN (KATHY) JOHNSON - </B>63, of Riverview Dr., Loudon, died Saturday, January 18, 1997. Daughter of the late Frank (Jack) and Viola Selvidge Johnson. Arrangements will be announced later by Loudon Funeral Home.
<P>
<P><B>JONES, DAVID PAUL - </B>68, of East Knoxville, died Sunday, January 19, 1997. He was a U.S. Navy Veteran and a long-time Knoxville dry cleaner. Survivors: wife, Thelma; daughter and son-in-law, Tammy and Ronnie Davis of Blaine; son, Donnie Jones; sons and daughters-in-law, Dale and Judy Jones, Danny and Linda Jones, all of Knoxville; eight grandchildren; and four great-grandchildren; brothers and sisters-in-law, Ralph and Zella Anderson, Earl and Judy Anderson; sister, Mary Thomas; sisters and brothers-in-law, Helen and Bob Ganlding, Martha and Leslie Grant; stepchildren, Janice Henderlight and Cindy Lowery, Allen Bruner, Wayne Lowery and wife, Brenda, Jeff Lowery and wife, Lisa; nine stepgrandchildren; and 11 step-great-grandchildren. Funeral service 2 p.m. Tuesday in Rose Mortuary Broadway Chapel. Interment will follow at Highland Memorial Cemetery. The family will receive friends 6-8 p.m. Monday. Rose Mortuary Broadway Chapel, in charge.
