		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><h3>Police seize more than $1,300 in bogus money</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>   More than $1,300 in alleged counterfeit money was confiscated early Satruday morning, Knoxville Police Department officials said. 
<P>   KPD Officer Carlene Johnson answered the call Saturday to an unidentified East Knoxville location, where she was told she would find a bag of money, said Monty Boone, a KPD public information officer. 
<P>   Boone said Johnson found 27 $50 bills in the bag. Police realized the money was fake when they discovered, &#39;&#39;All the serial numbers (on the bills) were the same,&#39;&#39; Boone said. 
<P>   KPD has turned the money and the investigation over to the U.S. Secret Service, Boone said. 
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Girl who admitted killing mom competent for trial</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>   COOKEVILLE -- A 16-year-old girl who admitted stabbing her mother to death is mentally competent to stand trial, according to psychiatrists for the state.
<P>   Tiffany Taylor is charged with first-degree murder in the death of Teresa Parramoure, 38. The woman&#39;s body was discovered Nov. 26, a day after Taylor sought treatment for a stab wound. She told doctors she fell on a knife.
<P>   Authorities said the hospital notified the Putnam County Sheriff&#39;s Department and the girl changed her story, telling investigators she had been kidnapped and raped by a Jackson County man who had a knife.
<P>   Her father, Parramoure&#39;s ex-husband Ronnie Taylor, took the girl home with him.
<P>    The next day, he decided she needed some clothes and took her to Parramoure&#39;s trailer, where he discovered the body.
<P>   Judge John Hudson told defense lawyers at the hearing Friday that they can have the girl evaluated by psychiatrists of their choice. But he said the state should not have to pay for the second opinion.
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Cumberland Gap names Woods superintendent</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>   CUMBERLAND GAP -- A veteran park ranger and manager who is assistant superintendent at the Virgin Islands National Park will become superintendent of Cumberland Gap National Historic Park, officials said Friday.
<P>   Mark Woods, 36, will take over the post on Sunday, Jan. 26, said Jerry Belson, head of the National Park Service&#39;s southeast field area. 
<P>   Woods will succeed Charlie Vial, who recently retired after a 32-year Park Service career. 
<P>   Woods, a native of Greenville, S.C., began his career with the Park Service in 1980 as a seasonal park ranger at Ninety Six National Historic Site, a Revolutionary War park near Greenwood, S.C.
<P>   He also has been assigned to Kings Mountain National Military Park in South Carolina, Andrew Johnson National Historic Site in Tennessee and Cumberland Island National Seashore in Georgia.
<P>   Prior to his assignment in the Virgin Islands, Woods was superintendent for five years at Guilford Courthouse National Military Park at Greensboro, N.C.
<P>
