<head>
	<title>State Supreme Court more moderate</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 19, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>State Supreme Court more moderate</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Study: Changes on bench cause shift</FONT></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Randy Kenner, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">T</FONT>he Tennessee Supreme Court moved from being conservative to moderate following the 1990 elections, when three justices were replaced, according to a new study.
<P>   Also, if the state&#39;s high court agrees to hear an appeal, it tends to change the lower court&#39;s decision.
<P>   And its ruling will probably be a more liberal one than it would have been prior to 1990, the study contends.
<P>   According to University of Tennessee journalism professor Daniel J. Foley&#39;s survey of 610 opinions from 1989-1996, the court actually tends to be conservative in deciding criminal cases and liberal in civil ones, with one glaring exception -- death penalty cases.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I wouldn&#39;t ever say this court is a liberal one,&#39;&#39; Foley said last week. &#39;&#39;On criminal cases, it was a shift from very conservative to more moderate.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Foley&#39;s study shows a five-member court that&#39;s been badly split for years over the most publicized issue it faces -- the death penalty.
<P>   Former Justice Penny J. White was ousted from the court in a yes-no referendum last year, primarily because she sided with the majority in reversing the death penalty in the case of a man who raped and then stabbed to death a 79-year-old Memphis woman.
<P>   White&#39;s ouster was widely seen as an indicator of voter dissatisfaction with the court&#39;s decisions on the issue.
<P>   &#39;&#39;In no area was there greater contrast between the old and new courts, or among individual justices on the new court, than on capital punishment,&#39;&#39; Foley wrote in &#39;&#39;Tennessee Supreme Court: A Statistical Analysis of an Ideological Shift After the 1990 Election.&#39;&#39;
<P>   The article is included in the Tennessee Law Review.
<P>   &#39;&#39;This study included 12 death penalty cases that were appealed to the old court, of which the justices upheld the death penalty 11 times or 92 percent of the cases,&#39;&#39; Foley wrote. &#39;&#39;The study also included 16 cases appealed to the new court, of which the justices voted for the death penalty eight times or 50 percent of the cases.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Although few people have seen Foley&#39;s work, some are already raising concerns that it&#39;s difficult -- no matter what criteria is used -- to define a judicial decision as &#39;&#39;conservative&#39;&#39; or &#39;&#39;liberal.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Court of Criminal Appeals Judge Gary Wade also suggested that it wouldn&#39;t be hard to be considered more liberal than the pre-1990 court, which consisted of five white males, four of whom were older than 67.
<P>   &#39;&#39;That might be like saying Ronald Reagan was to the left of Attilla the Hun,&#39;&#39; Wade said.
<P>   Wade questioned the use of the terms in a letter to Foley.
<P>   &#39;&#39;For example, the use of traditional terminology such as &#39;liberal&#39; and &#39;conservative,&#39; while at one time reasonable classifications of judicial philosophy, in these days of political partisanship are charged with emotion,&#39;&#39; Wade of Sevierville wrote.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Where I come from, the word &#39;liberal&#39; in any context is a fighting word.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Foley, a Montanan who worked as a reporter and editor for 17 years before joining the faculty at UT five years ago, said the study grew out of a public affairs reporting class project about two years ago.
<P>   &#39;&#39;It started off as a classroom project, and when I got the numbers, they were so interesting that I thought maybe I can get something published out of this,&#39;&#39; he said.
<P>   As part of the survey, he used eight different criteria to determine whether a decision could be categorized &#39;&#39;liberal&#39;&#39; or &#39;&#39;conservative.&#39;&#39; Foley admitted that it&#39;s an inexact methodology and there will always be exceptions to each category.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I think if we get enough cases we can overcome those sort of defects,&#39;&#39; he added.
<P>   His main findings:
<P>   * The court, from 1989-1995, either reversed or modified the previous ruling in 62 percent of the cases it heard. Foley wrote that the justices and other court observers weren&#39;t surprised.
<P>   &#39;&#39;They don&#39;t grant &#39;cert&#39; (agree to hear a case) to tell the world that the Court of Criminal Appeals was right,&#39;&#39; Knox County Public Defender Mark Stephens said Thursday.
<P>   &#39;&#39;They grant &#39;cert&#39; in an effort to clarify the status of the law.&#39;&#39;
<P>   * Despite the high rate of reversal, a lot of cases aren&#39;t being reversed. For example, in fiscal year 1994-1995, the Supreme Court granted 98 of the 903 applications for permission to appeal.
<P>   * The court is almost always unanimous in its decisions. During the survey period, the court issued 550 unanimous opinions and 60 split decisions.
<P>   * There would be a whole lot more unanimity if it weren&#39;t for the death penalty. While such cases accounted for only 6 percent of the total decisions, those cases accounted for 40 percent of the split decisions.
<P>   * Foley&#39;s study indicated that 58 percent of the court&#39;s decisions between 1989-1995 were &#39;&#39;conservative&#39;&#39; on criminal appeals while 60 percent were &#39;&#39;liberal&#39;&#39; on civil appeals.
<P>   The old court voted liberal in 43 percent of its decisions, while the new one did 58 percent of the time.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

