<head>
	<title>Nepotism claims raise controversy in McMinn</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 19, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Nepotism claims raise controversy in McMinn</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Commissioner alleges registrar violated law by hiring in-law</FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Ron Clayton, Special to The News-Sentinel</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">A</FONT>THENS, Tenn. -- In the midst of nepotism allegations, a McMinn County Election Commission member is leaving her post and has asked that veteran 20-year Registrar Loretta Sliger also step down.
<P>   Willene Mason was appointed to the commission two years ago. Her stint ended when local election officials learned from a state policy manual that Mason, also a secretary at Niota Elementary School, couldn&#39;t sit on the commission without violating a state regulation barring county employees from serving on election commissions.
<P>   If she were a teacher, however, Mason wouldn&#39;t be barred from election commission service, she said. Mason said she wasn&#39;t aware of the policy when she was appointed.
<P>   Mason alleges Sliger has violated the law in hiring her daughter-in-law to work in the office and in her approval of relatives of other commission members for work in part-time paid positions.
<P>   When questions about Sliger&#39;s practices were raised late last year, the commission asked county attorney Vance Baker for an interpretation of the law.
<P>   A letter from Baker indicated Sliger could be in violation of the election law for hiring her daughter-in-law, Kathy Sliger, who has since left her job with the commission, officials said.
<P>   &#39;&#39;You told us this statute didn&#39;t apply to you,&#39;&#39; Mason told Sliger during a special called commission meeting Thursday.
<P>   Sliger said she understood her office was exempt from the nepotism law.
<P>   &#39;&#39;The commission told you that if they could not hire their relatives to work in the office or the election process, you should not have your relatives working in the office,&#39;&#39; Mason told Sliger at the meeting.
<P>   Mason also alleged that while she was a precinct officer in 1994, Sliger told her to dismiss one of that precinct&#39;s workers so a commission member&#39;s daughter-in-law could work the precinct.
<P>   &#39;&#39;You have put the commission in violation of the law,&#39;&#39; Mason told Sliger on Thursday.
<P>   After calling for the registrar&#39;s resignation, Sliger asked commissioners for their opinions.
<P>   Those officials, many of whom were apparently surprised by the controversy and asked for time to review the law, promised to review the matter and all pertinent records before making a decision.
<P>   &#39;&#39;My daughter-in-law was hired by the election commission,&#39;&#39; Sliger said, &#39;&#39;not by me.&#39;&#39;
<P>   The county has no nepotism laws, but a portion of the registrar&#39;s salary is paid through state funds, which is why the county attorney has said he believes the nepotism statute could apply to the office.
<P>   However, State Coordinator of Elections Brooks Thompson said Friday that election laws concern the hiring of election commissioners or their relatives and do not address relatives of the registrar.
<P>   Thompson said state law specifically classifies registrars as county employees and states &#39;&#39;nothing shall be construed on their status as state employees.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Further legal opinions may be sought.
<P>   &#39;&#39;All Mr. Baker did was issue a letter on general nepotism,&#39;&#39; Sliger said. &#39;&#39;This might take an attorney general&#39;s opinion.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Commissioners have until their February meeting to make a decision on Sliger, said Mason, who plans to seek an attorney general&#39;s opinion, if necessary.
<P>   Mason&#39;s resignation is effective Jan. 31.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
