<head>
	<title>Margie&#39;s back</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 19, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Margie&#39;s back</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> One of Knoxville's favorites is heating up the weather beat</FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Louise Durman, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">T</FONT>he wink is gone.
<P>   But Margie&#39;s back.
<P>   For years, Knoxvillians looked to television weather anchor Margie Ison for information, and a wink at the end of her broadcast.
<P>   Ison has been a weathercaster at WATE and at WBIR over the last 25 years.   She &#39;&#39;retired&#39;&#39; from weather reporting in 1989, but returned full time in November to WATE-Channel 6, for Good Morning Tennessee and noon news reports.
<P>   The wink she used to give came about when students at schools where she would speak asked her to say hello to them on television. She would tell them  time didn&#39;t permit that but she would give them a wink.
<P>   &#39;&#39;It became a trademark,&#39;&#39; she says, &#39;&#39;but no, I don&#39;t do it any more.&#39;&#39;
<P>   She&#39;s petite and a sharp dresser, hardly changed in appearance though she&#39;s a grandmother of four. Her easy, friendly approach is somewhat like &#39;&#39;comfort food.&#39;&#39; People believe her -- and quote her reports.
<P>    &#39;&#39;After her first day back we were inundated with phone calls, E-mail, cards and letters,&#39;&#39; says WATE news director Martha Dooley. &#39;&#39;It has been absolutely phenomenal. We are thrilled.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Ison has attended seminars and workshops across the country to learn technology, but decided against going to college to become a meteorologist. She now uses the vital information that comes to the station through computers to interpret reports.
<P>   Complete computer information was new when she returned to WATE, but she is learning quickly. &#39;&#39;It&#39;s getting easier and easier,&#39;&#39; she says.
<P>   &#39;&#39;The weather hasn&#39;t changed. I&#39;ve lived the weather. I can look at weather systems and spot patterns.&#39;&#39;
<P>   The station&#39;s two meteorologists, Matt Hinkin and Ken Weathers, give her support.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We have a team concept,&#39;&#39;  Hinkin says. 
<P>    &#39;&#39;Margie has a lot of experience doing weather in East Tennessee and has a repertoire with the audience.&#39;&#39; He adds, &#39;&#39;She&#39;s as sweet as sugar.&#39;&#39; Hinkin has been at WATE seven years.
<P>   Ison&#39;s known around the area simply as Margie and many viewers consider her a friend. She thinks that&#39;s partly because she learned to look in the camera and talk one-on-one: &#39;&#39;Hey, (thinking of a friend), you&#39;re going to need a jacket today,&#39;&#39; she&#39;ll report.
<P>   Besides giving the weather, Ison has a weekly series, &#39;&#39;Six Heroes with Margie.&#39;&#39; In it, she gives recognition to people in the community who &#39;&#39;make a difference with their giving.&#39;&#39;
<P>    In 1989, wanting a change of pace, she quit providing weather reports and began &#39;&#39;Margie on Location&#39;&#39; sessions with country music personalities. WBIR had decided to put &#39;&#39;heavy-duty concentration&#39;&#39; on celebrity interviews, says Jim Hart, who was station manager at WBIR for 13 years with Ison. He is now senior vice-president for television of Scripps-Howard Broadcasting.
<P>   Asked if it makes a difference that Ison is not a meteorologist, he replied, &#39;&#39;A different kind of credibility goes with the seal (of meteorology), but no one has greater connection with the audience.&#39;&#39; 
<P>   &#39;&#39;She had a great enthusiasm for what she did and viewers picked up on it,&#39;&#39; says Hart. He also cites her responsiveness to people when she is out in public.
<P>   WBIR-Channel 10 news anchor Bill Williams, who worked with Margie,  calls her a &#39;&#39;terrific communicator and broadcaster.&#39;&#39;
<P>   &#39;&#39;It was good to work with her. She knew weather patterns,&#39;&#39; he says.
<P>   Ison started as a weekend weather reporter in 1969 for Channel 10, left to join WATE full time in 1971, left WATE in 1979 to rejoin WBIR, remaining until July, 1995.
<P>   She spent the next year decorating their home in Fountain City and doing some freelance work until WATE wooed her back last fall.
<P>   The studio had an opening for a morning weathercaster and Martha Dooley viewed tapes of prospects from across the country. None were really &#39;&#39;right,&#39;&#39; she explains.
<P>     &#39;&#39;I kept thinking of Margie,&#39;&#39; Dooley says. They had been friends since working together at WATE previously.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Margie is from East Tennessee and people believe her,&#39;&#39; says Dooley. 
<P>   &#39;&#39;I was nervous about calling her, but finally I got the courage and left a message on the answering machine.&#39;&#39;
<P>   &#39;&#39;I have been so fortunate,&#39;&#39; Ison says of her career. &#39;&#39;Most of the time I am not looking for a change.&#39;&#39;
<P>    One of her endearing characteristics is her ability to remember people and names.
<P>    &#39;&#39;I use word association,&#39;&#39; she says, but says occasionally it backfires, such as a time she called a woman whose last name was Wolf, &#39;&#39;Mrs. Fox.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Margie arises at 3:15 a.m. at the home she and husband Jim, who is retired from TVA, have in Fountain City. She does her own makeup and dons her own clothes at home. (The performers do have a clothing &#39;&#39;allowance.&#39;&#39;)
<P>   She reports to work about 4:45 a.m. for Good Morning Tennessee, now expanded to 90 minutes, 5:30 to 7 a.m. She finishes after the noon weather reports. She&#39;s in bed by 7:30 p.m.
<P>   &#39;&#39;When you get up that early, 7 is like 11 p.m. I am learning to be a morning person.&#39;&#39; 
<P>   She says her friends asked how she would be able to handle the early hours since they know mornings aren&#39;t her best time. She laughs and says she signed a short-term contract to see how it works out.
<P>   Her current schedule doesn&#39;t give her time for speeches to the many groups who ask her (she used to do a lot of public speaking plus some singing). &#39;&#39;You have to be very selective about what you can do at night.&#39;&#39;.
<P>  Ison is 5 feet, 2 inches tall and thin. &#39;&#39;I watch my fats, but I have never had a weight problem,&#39;&#39; she says.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I think a positive attitude can lesson the character lines. When you&#39;re happy it shows.&#39;&#39;
<P>   She grew up in Cookeville where her father was the late Rev. S.E. Wood, a Baptist minister. Her mother, who was a teacher, is now 89.
<P>   She met future husband Jim while she was in high school and he was in Tennessee Tech.  They married before she graduated from high school. They lived in Chattanooga before moving to the Claxton community where they lived about 20 years before moving to Fountain City.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Jim has always been wonderful to support me and my career,&#39;&#39; she says. He stays involved in church and community organizations.
<P>   The Isons&#39;  have two daughters. Debbie is married to Dan Stidham and they have two sons, Alex and Josh, and live in Knoxville. Jill is married to Marine Major David McMillan, and their home is in Quantico, Va., with daughters Brigitte and Brittany.
<P>    All were here for Christmas holidays.
<P>   Asked how she&#39;d liked to be remembered, Ison replies, &#39;&#39;As a good communicator.&#39;&#39; 
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

