<head>
	<title>KPD security work nets no overtime</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 19, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>KPD security work nets no overtime</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Jamie Satterfield, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">T</FONT>he Knoxville Police Department is hoping to get more bang for taxpayers&#39; bucks in efforts to curb drug trafficking in the city&#39;s housing projects, authorities said.
<P>   The agency is phasing out its current method of paying officers overtime to work off-duty security for Knoxville&#39;s Community Development Corporation, which operates the city&#39;s housing projects, KPD Lt. Don Green confirmed this week.
<P>   Instead, the $1 million KCDC grant money will be used to pay officers at the normal &#39;&#39;straight-time&#39;&#39; rate, he said.
<P>   The amount of the grant is fixed, so the move won&#39;t necessarily save taxpayers&#39; money. It will, however, allow KCDC to stretch those dollars by paying more officers to patrol in and around the high-crime housing projects, Green said.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We&#39;re running more (security patrol) shifts than ever before,&#39;&#39; Green said.
<P>   KCDC operates the city&#39;s housing projects and administers the security grant, which requires that extra patrol efforts be designated to help eliminate drug trafficking. However, by mutual agreement, KPD provides the manpower for that security effort.
<P>   When the program was initiated, Green said KPD did not have enough officers to work both KCDC security and regular patrol shifts. So, he said, officers worked and were paid overtime to do the job.
<P>   Since then, KPD has received hundreds of thousands of dollars in community policing grants to fund salaries for more officers. The city also has provided funding for more KPD officers.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Now, we have the officers to assign to KCDC as part of the normal work week,&#39;&#39; Green said. &#39;&#39;The ranks have grown.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Green said KCDC officials also have promised to fund the security positions for the next three to five years even if the federal grant were eliminated.
<P>   Right now, the program is in transition, with some officers still earning overtime and others accepting permanent, straight-time security positions, Green said. He expects the change to be complete by spring.
<P>   The change has prompted some grumbling among KPD officers whose paychecks were boosted by the overtime pay. Green acknowledged that, saying, &#39;&#39;officers were dependent on it.&#39;&#39; 
<P>   But Green also noted officers were overworked by the overtime procedure. It was not unusual, under the current funding method, for officers to work a regular shift and then spend another six to eight hours patrolling for KCDC. Green said the new plan should eliminate officer fatigue and stress.
<P>   Police Chief Phil Keith said officers&#39; complaints were without merit.
<P>   &#39;&#39;You can&#39;t expect the taxpayer to pick up (the cost of paying officers) time and a half,&#39;&#39; he said. &#39;&#39;The benefit is to the taxpayer.&#39;&#39;
<P>   
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
