<html>
<head>
	<title>Parade to honor King set for today</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 19, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Parade to honor King set for today</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">K</FONT>noxvillians will take to the streets today to remember the late Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.
<P>   The local King Commemoration Commission&#39;s annual parade to honor the slain civil-rights leader will begin at 4:30 p.m. at Tabernacle Baptist Church, 2137 Martin Luther King Jr. Ave.
<P>   The parade will proceed along MLK to the Five Points intersection and down to the Burlington Community.
<P>   A memorial service will follow the parade at 6 p.m. at Greater Warner Tabernacle AME Zion Church, 3800 Martin Luther King Jr. Ave.
<P>Other activities in honor of King:
<P>   * On Monday, WSJK/WKOP-TV will present a tribute to Dr. King from 11 a.m. to 1 p.m.
<P>   Benjamin Hooks, retired executive director of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, will be the keynote speaker.
<P>   * Also on Monday, the University of Tennessee&#39;s Black Cultural Programming Committee will sponsor a unity march and program highlighting the works of Dr. King.
<P>   The march will begin at the Torchbearer statue on the corner of Yale Avenue and Volunteer Boulevard on the UT campus. 
<P>The program, which follows the march, will be held in the University Center auditorium.
<P>
<P>
