<head>
	<title>Police raid nets drugs, stolen property, 61-year-old suspect</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 19, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Police raid nets drugs, stolen property, 61-year-old suspect</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Jamie Satterfield, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">P</FONT>olice allege a 61-year-old Mechanicsville man arrested in a drug raid that yielded a cache of drugs and more than $20,000 in stolen property has been dealing drugs for nearly 50 years.
<P>   Hollis Nathaniel Ross allegedly greeted Knoxville Police Department officers with a loaded pistol when they kicked in his 1405 Boyd St. door during the Friday night raid, authorities said.
<P>   The raid, conducted by KPD&#39;s Repeat Offenders Program, or ROP, unit with help from officers working off-duty security for Knoxville&#39;s Community Development Corporation, yielded heroin, cocaine, synthetic morphine, tranquilizers and marijuana, as well as between $20,000 and $30,000 in stolen property and eight guns, ROP Officer Jeff Thornburg said.
<P>   According to Thornburg, Ross was first arrested for selling drugs in 1953. In between prison stints, Ross allegedly has been dealing drugs ever since, Thornburg said.
<P>   &#39;&#39;He&#39;s basically been dealing drugs his entire life,&#39;&#39; Thornburg said.
<P>   Thornburg said officers had a search warrant for the house. They &#39;&#39;started knocking on the door and didn&#39;t get a response,&#39;&#39; so they forcibly entered the house by kicking the door, he said.
<P>   &#39;&#39;(The officers) were met by Mr. Ross, who was standing there with a pistol pointed at them,&#39;&#39; Thornburg said.
<P>   Ross allegedly just had finished &#39;&#39;cooking and cutting&#39;&#39; 22 grams of crack cocaine, according to Thornburg. Crack is a crystalized and more potent form of powder cocaine. After pointing the pistol, Ross turned and ran into his kitchen, Thornburg said. Ross tossed the pistol into a trash can but was captured before he could flee from the house, the officer said.
<P>   Officers also discovered 18 grams of heroin, which Thornburg said is a &#39;&#39;heck of a lot of heroin for Knoxville.&#39;&#39; Also found in the house were 300 Dilaudid pills, a synthetic morphine that sells on the street for $60 a pill. Dilaudid, a highly addictive drug which is usually crushed and then injected by the user, was popular in the late 1970s and early 1980s but has waned in popularity in recent years.
<P>   &#39;&#39;He had a smorgasbord of drugs,&#39;&#39; Thornburg said.
<P>   Thornburg said it appeared Ross had been trading drugs for stolen loot, including shoplifted goods still in the original packaging, items stolen in burglaries and stolen guns.
<P>   Ross was charged with five felony drug charges, a misdemeanor marijuana possession charge and other state offenses. Thornburg said his case will be forwarded to federal authorities for possible prosecution because penalties in U.S. District Court are stiffer than those levied by state judges.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
