<head>
	<title>Five regional mussel species put on federal endangered list</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 19, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Five regional mussel species put on federal endangered list</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Morgan Simmons, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">F</FONT>ive freshwater mussels native to the Tennessee and Cumberland rivers in Tennessee, Kentucky and Virginia have been added to the federal endangered species list.
<P>   Listed in the endangered category are the Cumberland elktoe, oyster mussel, Cumberlandian combshell, purple bean, and rough rabbitsfoot.
<P>   Noreen K. Clough, U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service Southeast regional director, said the listing of the five mussels is not expected to have any significant impact on private landowners or on water projects.
<P>   &#39;&#39;There are 24 federally listed mussels presently in the Tennessee and Cumberland river systems, many of which have been listed for 10 years,&#39;&#39; said Clough. &#39;&#39;These listed species have had little effect on ongoing private land activities such as logging, agriculture, land development, and home construction.&#39;&#39;
<P>   The decision to list the species as endangered follows a comprehensive study on the impact of the listing on private landowners and consideration of public comments submitted during two public meetings.
<P>   The ranges of all five species have diminished significantly, and the mussels now exist in relatively small, isolated populations. The Cumberland elktoe inhabits very localized portions of the Cumberland River system in Kentucky and Tennessee, while small numbers of the oyster mussel and Cumberland combshell can be found in portions of the Cumberland and Tennessee River basins in Kentucky, Tennessee and Virginia.
<P>   The purple bean and rough rabbitsfoot currently survive in a few river reaches in the upper Tennessee River system in Tennessee and Virginia.
<P>   &#39;&#39;These species were eliminated from much of their historic range by impoundments, siltation, and water pollution that has degraded their habitat,&#39;&#39; said Clough. &#39;&#39;Poor land-use practices have contributed to a deterioration of water quality, and their restricted ranges now make these species very vulnerable to toxic chemical spills.&#39;&#39;
<P>   The United States has 297 recognized species and subspecies of freshwater mussels, and Native Americans once made extensive use of the mussels or their shells for food, tools and jewelry.
<P>   Mussels have been called &#39;&#39;Mother Nature&#39;s 911 call&#39;&#39; because they are generally the first animals to die when a river&#39;s water quality deteriorates.
<P>   In the 20th century, mussels have suffered a greater decline than any other wide-ranging animal group in the United States.
<P>   Clough said that now that these five mussels are federally listed, they will be eligible for Endangered Species Act funding for conservation and recovery activities.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Listing draws attention to their plight and encourages federal and state agencies, local governments, conservation organizations, and private citizens to take an active role in their protection,&#39;&#39; she said.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
