<P>
<P><B></B>
<P><B>ALEXANDER, JACK ROY - </B>age 62, of LaFollette, passed away Thursday, January 16, 1997, at the University of Tennessee Medical Center, Knoxville. He was a member of the LaFollette Church of God, LaFollette Masonic Lodge #623, and Campbell County Shrine Club. Mr. Alexander was a 32nd Degree Mason and Shriner. He served 22 years as County Judge/Executive and was currently serving as County Commissioner. He was a graduate of LMU and received his master in finance at the University of Tennessee. Preceded in death by parents, James Roy and Minnie Pierce Alexander. Survivors: wife, Kathy Alexander, LaFollette; daughters and sons-in-law, Sheila and Steve Lawson, Knoxville, Jackie and Raymond Jackson, Jacksboro, Angie Alexander, LaFollette; grandchildren, Rachel and Samanatha Jackson. Funeral service 8 p.m. Sunday, January 19, at LaFollette Church of God, Rev. Kenneth Stephens officiating. Interment 10 a.m. Monday, January 20 at Jacksboro Cemetery. The family will receive friends 6-8 p.m. Sunday at LaFollette Church of God. Nephews and Commissioners will be pallbearers. Arrangements by Cross Funeral Home.
<P>
<P><B>BARNARD, BOONE - </B>age 73, of Tazewell, Tenn., was born July 29, 1923, and passed away January 17, 1997, at the Claiborne County Hospital. He was preceded in death by: his parents, J.H. and Denta Barnard; one brother, Kyle Barnard; and one infant brother. He was a member of Howard&#39;s Quarter Baptist Church. He is survived by: his wife, Mae Barnard of Tazewell; sons and daughters-in-law, Jim and Audrey Barnard of Tazewell, Tenn., Mike and Shirley Barnard of New Tazewell, Tenn., David and Lynn Barnard of Tazewell, Tenn.; brothers, Wayland Barnard of Tazewell, Tenn., Jack Barnard of Tazewell, Tenn., Bill Barnard of Tazewell, Tenn.; sisters, Wonette Pearson of Tazewell, Tenn., Hattie Mae Young of Tazewell, Tenn., Patsey Rowe of Tazewell, Tenn.; grandchildren, Danny Barnard of Tazewell, Tenn., Randall Barnard of Tazewell, Tenn., Crystal Barnard of Tazewell, Tenn., Heather Barnard of New Tazewell, Tenn., David Allen Barnard of Tazewell, Tenn., Holly Barnard of Tazewell, Tenn., Haley Barnard of New Tazewell, Tenn.; several nieces and nephews; and a host of other relatives and friends. The family will receive friends Sunday, January 19, 1997, after 3 p.m. at the Claiborne Funeral Home. Funeral service will be conducted 1 p.m., Monday, January 20, 1997, in the Claiborne Funeral Home Chapel with the Rev. Steve Barnard and Rev. Johnny Lewis officiating. Music by the Liberty Quartet. The body will lie in state 30 minutes before services. Burial in the Irish Memorial Gardens. Pallbearers: nephews. Claiborne Funeral Home, New Tazewell, in charge of arrangements.
<P>
<P><B>BAYLESS, MARTHA EMMA - </B>age 80, of Halls, passed away January 16, 1997, at St. Mary&#39;s Medical Center. Member of Beaver Dam Baptist Church. Preceded in death by: husband, Charles A. Bayless. Survivors: daughter and son-in-law, Charlsie and Ronnie Hall; grandchildren, Kim and Kip Huston of Elliott City, Md., Rhonda and Herbert Holcomb of Rogersville and Michael Hall of Dunbarton, N.H.; five great-grandchildren; sisters, Leatha Wilkins of Knoxville and Retha Hankins of Knoxville. Family and friends will meet at Greenwood Cemetery, 2 p.m. Sunday for graveside service, Rev. Ralph Cox officiating. Arrangements by Mynatt&#39;s.
<P>
<P><B>BLAKELEY, OSSIE - </B>of Knoxville, departed this life, Saturday, January 18, 1997, at Brakebill Nursing Home. Funeral arrangements are incomplete and will be announced later by Unity Mortuary.
<P>
<P><B>CONNATSER, FRANCES MANNING - </B>age 76, of Maryville, died at 1:05 p.m., Friday, January 17, 1997, at Fort Sanders Regional Medical Center. She was a member of Everett Hills Baptist Church. She was preceded in death by: her husband, Bruce Connatser; parents, Blanco and Hattie Manning; sister and brother-in-law, Ruth and Lloyd Loveday. Survivors: daughters and sons-in-law, Wilma and Edward Gilbert of Maryville, Vickie and Michael Flynn of Maryville; four grandchildren, Darin and Gregory Gilbert, Zachary and Leighann Flynn; sisters and brothers-in-law, Irene and Paul Hicks of Alcoa, Marilyn and Bill Johnson of Maryville; several nieces and nephews. Funeral service 8 p.m., Sunday, January 19, 1997, Trinity Chapel, Smith Mortuary, with Rev. Allen Raines officiating. Interment 11 a.m., Monday at Grandview Cemetery. Memorial donations may be made to the National Kidney Foundation of East Tennessee, 4450 Walker Blvd., Suite 2, Knoxville, TN 37917-1523. The family will receive friends from 6 p.m. until 8 p.m, Sunday, Trinity Chapel, Smith Mortuary, Maryville.
<P>
<P><B>FARMER, HAZEL - </B>age 83, of Maryville, passed away Saturday morning, January 18, 1997, at Blount Memorial Hospital. Member of Maryville First Baptist Church. She attended Tusculum College and the University of Tennessee. She was an avid fan of Tennessee and Maryville High School Athletics. She enjoyed golf and bridge, and made many trips through Cades Cove with family and friends. Preceded in death by: parents, Walter and Lora Cureton; sisters, Elizabeth Cureton, Lagreatta Parrott. Survivors: husband of 62 years, John W. Farmer; son and daughter-in-law, John C. &#39;&#39;Butch&#39;&#39; and Sue Farmer of Murfreesboro; daughter and son-in-law, Elizabeth &#39;&#39;Betty&#39;&#39; and Allen England of Jacksonville, Fla.; granddaughters, Kristi Farmer, Lisa (Mrs. Ronnie) Mangrum of Murfreesboro, Margaret Ann Cameron of Knoxville, Catherine (Mrs. William) Kelsch of Alcoa; great-grandsons, Corey Kelsch of Alcoa, Alex Mangrum of Murfreesboro; sisters, Carolyn (Mrs. Joe) Sherlin of Sweetwater, Nedra (Mrs. F.E.) Bales of Maryville; sister-in-law, Ruby (Mrs. Robert) Farmer of Maryville; brother-in-law, Oscar Farmer of Newport. Funeral service 11 a.m. Tuesday at Miller Funeral Home Chapel, Rev. Carl White, Rev. Wilburn Hoglen officiating. Interment to follow in Bethel Cemetery in Townsend. Pallbearers: Oliver Spears, Maurice Stepp, Glenn Mason, Frank Farmer, Carl Eldridge, Robert Parrott. Honorary pallbearers: LeRoy Rogers, Hoyt Waters, Harry Myers, Coy Porter, Bob Farmer, Bobby Reagan. The family will receive friends from 6-8 p.m. Monday at Miller Funeral Home, Maryville.
<P>
<P><B>FORD, FRED A. - </B>age 75, of South Knoxville, passed away January 18, 1997. He was of the Church of Christ faith. He was a veteran of WWII. Survivors; wife of 50 years, Iva Sayne Ford; sons, William H. Ford, Hartford, Conn., Tom Ford, Knoxville, Rick Ford, Knoxville, Dean Ford, Knoxville, David Ford, Knoxville, Ernie Ford, Knoxville; daughter, Mary Sue Ford Davis, Seymour; brothers, Frank Ford, Knoxville, Henry Ford, Knoxville; sisters, Hazel Neubert, Knoxville, Evelyn Goddard, Knoxville, Audrey Bunch, South Carolina; 12 grandchildren; three great-grandchildren; several nieces and nephews. Funeral service 2 p.m. Monday at Holly Hills Chapel, Rev. Chuck Webb officiating. The interment will be in Holly Hills Memorial Park. Pallbearers: Jimmy Davis, Nick Ford, Bobby Williams, Lowell Cook, Richard Ford, Sammy Hatcher. Military honors will be presented by the East Tennessee Veterans Honor Guard. The family will receive friends 7-9 p.m. Sunday at Holly Hills Funeral Home, 573-7300.
<P>
<P>h3815_0124
<P><B>COOK, ROBERT ERWIN - </B>died January 17, 1997, at his home in Knoxville, following a courageous struggle with cancer. A native of Knoxville, Mr. Cook was the son of the late May Rothe and John Robert Cook. He was a graduate of the University of Tennessee, Knoxville, Class of 1948, where he was a member of Sigma Alpha Epsilon Fraternity. Mr. Cook lived in Athens for 27 years, where he taught chemistry and physics at McMinn County High School and was later principal of Ingleside School before entering the insurance business. He was a member of Certified Property and Casualty Underwriters (CPCU), vice president of Athens Insurance Agency, served as president of The Insurers of Tennessee, member of The Executive Committee, and vice president of The National Association of Insurance Agents, was named Tennessee&#39;s Insurer of the Year, received the President&#39;s Award from The National Association of Insurance Agents, and won two national advertising competitions sponsored by The Insurance Advertising Conference. He served as board chairman of the Athens Housing Authority; president of the McMinn County Historical Society; chairman of the McMinn County American Revolution Bicentennial Commission; campaign chairman, Athens United Way; president, Athens Kiwanis Club; Deacon and choir member of Mars Hill Presbyterian Church, Athens; president, Smoky Mountains Hiking Club; president, East Tennessee Historical Society; president, The Meadows Condominium Association; member, Sons of the Revolution; and member of Westminster Presbyterian Church, Knoxville. He loved the Smoky Mountains and hiked all of its 900 miles of trails in both directions. He also hiked over 1,100 of The Applachian Trail. Mr. Cook was preceded in death by: sister, Margaret (Mrs. Charles Donald Rose), Kingston; and two brothers, John Rothe Cook, Knoxville and Lester Millan Cook, Los Angeles. He is survived by: wife, Barbara Small Cook; daughter, Sherry Lynn and husband, Charles Eugene Sabo, Greenville, S.C.; and daughter, Cynthiana and husband, Gary George Spangler, Knoxville; granddaughter, Rachael Lynn Spangler, Knoxville; sister, Helen (Mrs. R.A. Lawson, Jr.), Loudon, Tenn.; and nine nieces and nephews. The family has requested that in lieu of flowers, memorial contributions be made to the McClung Historical Collection, East Tennessee Historical Center, 314 Clinch Ave., Knoxville, TN 37902 or Westminster Presbyterian Church Memorial Fund, 6500 Northshore Drive, Knoxville, TN 37919. There will be a memorial service, Friday, January 24, 1997, at Westminister Presbyterian Church at 6 p.m. with the Rev. Dr. Friedrich J. Schilling, J.R. officiating. The family will receive friends from 7-9 p.m., January 24, at the home of Cynthiana and Gary Spangler, 6427 Westminister Road. Arrangements by Rose Mortuary Mann Heritage Chapel.
<P>
<P><B>FREEMAN, FRANCES ORR - </B>of Highland Farms Retirement Community, Black Mountain, N.C., died January 17, 1997. Born Frances Anna Orr on November 19, 1900, in Mt. Vernon, Miss., she was the younger daughter of the late Alfred W. and Edith Dunlap Orr; her sister, Pauline Orr Keeley, died April 9, 1996. She married the Rev. D. Ralph Freeman on June 18, 1924. He preceded her in death on December 16, 1972. Together they served churches near Memphis, Tenn. and in the mountain areas of Virginia, North Carolina, and Tennessee. She is survived by: a daughter, Edith F. Patton of Columbus, Ohio; two sons, the Rev. Robert O. Freeman of Salisbury and the Rev. David R. Freeman of Greenwood, Miss.; a sister, Mrs. Jessie Glazener of Dallas, Texas; eight grandchildren, Elizabeth Freeman of Salisbury, Robert B. Freeman of Warner Robins, Ga., the Rev. James D. Freeman of Little Rock, Ark., John Patton of Birmingham, Ala., Stuart F. Patton of Tallahassee, Fla., Margaret Patton of Richmond, Va., Jean P. Rochelle of Jackson, Tenn., and Beth Patton of Albuquerque, N.M.; eight great-grandchildren; five nieces and nephews. She attended public school in Mt. Vernon, Columbus, and Fairfax, Mo., taught school during WWI and attended Rice Institute, Houston, Texas and the Presbyterian School of Christian Education, Richmond, Va. 1918-1922. As a pastor&#39;s wife she did &#39;&#39;church work&#39;&#39; all her life in addition to being a caring mother. A life-long Presbyterian, she was active in The Presbyterian Women of the Church serving on many committees and boards including presbytery and synod president and on The Board of Women&#39;s Work, PCUS. She was a delegate to the National Council of Churches for 12 years serving on the general board for 3 years. She was also active in Church Women United in Tennessee. A funeral service will be held on Monday, January 20, at 10 a.m. at Black Mountain Presbyterian Church. The body will lie in state 30 minutes prior to service. The Rev. Walter Styles and the Rev. Edwin Pickard will officiate. There will also be a graveside service on Monday, January 20, at 3 p.m. at Steele Creek Presbyterian Church Cemetery in Charlotte, N.C. The family will receive friends on Sunday, January 19, from 7-8:30 p.m. in the chapel of Miller Funeral Home. Memorials may be sent to Black Mountain Presbyterian Church or the Presbyterian Home for Children.
<P>
<P><B>GASTON, HAZEL MAE WICKER - </B>age 80, of Sweetwater, Tenn., passed away January 17. She was of the Baptist faith. Survived by: husband, Robert B. Gaston; son and daughter-in-law, James Robert and Nola Gaston; grandson, Patrick James Gaston; and granddaughter, Bernadette Nicole Gaston, all of Springfield, Va. Funeral service is 11 a.m. Monday in Sweetwater Funeral Home Memory Chapel with Rev. Anderson McCulley officiating. Interment in Loudon County Memorial Gardens. The family will receive friends 6-8 p.m. Sunday in Sweetwater Memory Chapel.
<P>
<P><B>HALL, MARY E. - </B>age 94, of Greenback, died Friday, January 17, 1997, at Blount Memorial Hospital. She was the oldest, and held the senoir membership at Bakers Creek Presbyterian Church. She was preceded in death by her husband, Gid Hall. Survivors include: a son and daughter-in-law, Ralph and Shirley Hall of Greenback; daughter and son-in-law, Jean and Ed Ellington of Kingsport; grandchildren, Ann and Dan Duncan of Memphis, Jane and Dan Dove of Bristol, Tenn., Bill and Sue Hall of Maryville, Linda and David Whitaker of Greenback, and Jim and Emily Hall of Greenback; great-grandchildren, Justin Hall, Tom Hall, Andrew Hall, Austin Hall, and Jennifer Whitaker; several nieces and nephews. Funeral service will be 2 p.m. Monday at Bakers Creek Presbyterian Church with Rev. Jon Faraone officiating. The interment will follow in Bakers Creek Cemetery. The family will receive friends from 7-8:30 p.m., Sunday at McCammon-Ammons Funeral Home. Memorials may be made to the Mary Hall Memorial Fund, Bakers Creek Presbyterian Church, 5501 Nine Mile Rd., Maryville, TN 37801. McCammon-Ammons Funeral Home, Maryville.
<P>
<P><B>HARRIS, REV. OTTIS (GAY) - </B>a retired Baptist minister, age 83, of Seymour, Tenn., passed away January 16, 1997, in Dayton, Ohio. Rev. Harris pastored several churches in Alabama, Florida, and Tennessee to include: Ellejoy Baptist Church, Riverdale Baptist Church, Lyons Creek Baptist Church, Valley Grove Baptist Church, First Baptist Church of Pompano Beach, Fla. (1953-1962). He also served as interim pastor at several area churches after his retirement in 1976. He was very active and lead several states enlargement campaigns for the Southern Baptist Sunday School Board. Rev. Harris had also served as a bereavement counselor at Holly Hills Funeral Home. He was a mason with the Sevier Lodge #334 and Scottish Rite Bodies, Knoxville. He was preceded in death by his wife, Lela Davis Harris. Survivors: son and daughter-in-law, Dr. John Edwin and Mary Louise Harris, Dayton, Ohio; grandchildren, Melissa and Mike and Michael Slamb, Sheri and Scott, Jordan and Christopher Coffman, Ross Harris; brothers, Aundis Harris, Atlanta, Ga., Willard Harris, Cleveland, Tenn., Windell Harris, Etowah, Tenn.; several nieces and nephews; and a host of friends. Funeral service 7 p.m. Sunday, January 19, 1997, at Valley Grove Baptist Church, Dr. William L. Blivens officiating assisted by Rev. Harry Mynatt. The interment will be 11 a.m. Monday at Chilhowee Cemetery. Pallbearers: Ed Rogers, Earl Ford, Robert Whitehead, Jim Pierce, Bill Pierce, Tom Rogers. Honorary pallbearers: Hubert Fox, Frank Toomy, Dana Howard, and Valley Grove Deacons. The family request that memorial contributions be made to the Ottis Gay Harris Ministerial Scholarship Endowment at Carson-Newman College in Jefferson City, Tenn. Contributions may also be sent to Valley Grove Baptist Church, 9000 Old Sevierville Pike, Knoxville, TN 37920. The family will receive friends 5-7 p.m. Sunday at Valley Grove Baptist Church. Arrangements by Holly Hills Funeral Home, 573-7300.
<P>
<P>
<P><B>HENLINE, WALTER C. - </B>age 82, of 500 E. Street, Lenoir City, passed away early Saturday morning, January 18, 1997, at U.T. Hospital, after a brief illness. He was born in Greene Co., but spent most of his life in Loudon Co. He was retired from Charles H. Bacon Co. A veteran of World War II serving with the Army. An avid sports fan and raised Beagle dogs. He organized The Fox Hunters Association of Loudon Co. He was preceded in death by: wife of 40 years, Adeline Hair Henline; parents, William Randolph Henline and Mattie Ledford Henline; brothers, Bill, Carl, and Ray Henline; nephew, Esten Henline. Survived by: son and daughter-in-law, Mike and Kathy Henline of Lenoir City; grandchildren, Charlie and Shelly of Lenoir City; brother, Jim Henline of Crossville; sisters, Hattie Babb of Lenoir City, Anna Nelle &#39;&#39;Sissy&#39;&#39; Deck of Crossville; sister-in-law, Exie Henline of Lenoir City; several nephews and nieces; very special friends, Della Packett and her family, Bruce and Ann Williams, Michael and Lori. Funeral service 4 p.m. Sunday, Click Funeral Home Chapel, Rev. Scott Cagle and Rev. Ken Johnson officiating. The family will receive friends immediately following the funeral. Graveside service 11 a.m. Monday, Lake View Cemetery. Honorary pallbearers: Jim Rollins, Clarence Cusick, Jacky Morton, Bill Keating, Bob Rhinehart, Jerry Spoon, Hubert Gilreath, and David Moats. Click Funeral Home, Lenoir City, in charge.
<P>
<P><B>HINES, B.L. - </B>77, of the Dante Community, died Friday, January 17, 1997. He attended Dante Church of God and was a Knoxville grading and excavating contractor for more than 30 years. Mr. Hines was preceded in death by his beloved wife of 54 years, Juanita. Survivors: sons, Gary Hines and Bary Dale Hines, both of Knoxville; grandchildren, Ellen Silver, Sherry Ammons, and Randy Hines; two great-grandchildren; brother, James Linville of Kentucky; sister, Edna Watkins of Alabama; aunt, Ila Rogers of Knoxville. Funeral service 7:30 p.m., Monday in Rose Mortuary Broadway Chapel with Rev. Robert L. Holmes and Rev. Joel Ammons officiating. Family and friends will meet at Bookwalter Cemetery for a 1 p.m. interment service. The family will receive friends 6-7:30 p.m., Monday at Rose Mortuary Broadway Chapel.
<P>
<P><B>HUMPHREYS, JOHN S. - </B>age 100, of Knoxville, passed away Thursday, January 16, 1997, at East Tennessee Baptist Hospital. He was a member of Central United Methodist Church. Member of Kiwanis Club. Lifetime member of N.E.A. (National Educational Asso.), T.E.A. (Tennessee Education Asso.), E.T.E.A. (East Tennessee Education Asso.). His first principalship was in 1916. He retired as principal of Rule High School after 30 years service. He served 12 years on the Knoxville City School Board having never missed a meeting. Survivors: wife, Florence C. Humphrey; daughter and son-in-law, Helen H. and Felix E. Knight, all of Knoxville; son and daughter-in-law, Dr. Jack B. and Judy Humphreys, Friendsville; grandsons, Don Humphreys, Knoxville, Wesley Humphreys, Ooltewah; five great-grandchildren; special niece, Nancy Cameron; special caregiver and friend, Billie Murrell, both of Knoxville. Funeral service 4 p.m. Sunday, Rose Mortuary Broadway Chapel, Rev. John Ellenburg officiating. Family and friends will leave Rose Mortuary at 10:30 a.m. Monday and proceed to Highland Memorial Cemetery for interment services at 11 a.m. Pallbearers: Reuben Hunter, D.M. Miller, Paul Kelley, Edwin Cloud, Tom Underwood, Tom Harrington, Louis Hofferbert. In lieu of flowers, memorials may be made to Central United Methodist Church, 201 East 3rd. Avenue, Knoxville, Tenn. 37917. The family will receive friends from 2-4 p.m. Sunday at Rose Mortuary Broadway Chapel.
<P>
<P><B>HUSKEY, PAULINE M. - </B>age 70, passed away Thursday, January 16, 1997, at Fort Sanders Parkwest Hospital. She was a member of Friendship Baptist Church; and was preceded in death by husband, Robert D. Huskey. Survivors: daughters and sons-in-law, Kaye and Bill Butcher, Knoxville, Janie and Bob O&#39;Leary, Charlotte, N.C.; granddaughters, Lindsey, Katie, and Megan O&#39;Leary, North Carolina; grandson, Eric Butcher, Knoxville; mother, Leona Eubanks, Knoxville; brother and sister-in-law, Walter and Linda Eubanks; brother-in-law, James Huskey and wife, Wanda; nephews, David and Regina Eubanks, Walter Eubanks, Jr., Scott and Randy Huskey, all of Knoxville. Family and friends will meet at 1:45 p.m. Sunday at Edgewood Cemetery for a 2 p.m. graveside service Rev. Tom Tomblin officiating. Pallbearers: David Eubanks, Walter Eubanks, Jr., Eric Butcher, Travis L. Brasfield, Atlee Hammaker, and Roy Wright. Arrangements by Weaver Funeral Home.
