		</basefont><h3>Store employees chase, capture man who allegedly took cash register</h3>
<P>
<P>   When a clerk at an area Weigel&#39;s store denied a would-be thief the money in the till, he made off with the whole cash register instead, authorities alleged.
<P>      Samuel Wolfenbarger, 31, who gave Glenda Lane and Townview Drive addresses, was charged with theft over $500 and aggravated assault in connection with the 11:17 p.m. at the Weigel&#39;s, 411 E. Summitt Hill Drive, police said.
<P>   Knoxville Police Department Patrol Officer Kristina Norris wrote in a report a man gave a Weigel&#39;s clerk money to buy a candy bar. However, when the clerk opened the cash register, the suspect reached in and tried to take money from the till, she wrote. The clerk unsuccessfully attempted to slam the suspect&#39;s hand in the drawer, but the suspect picked up the register and fled into the Townview Terrace apartment complex across the street, the report stated.
<P>   Two employees and the store manager chased the suspect, and the manager tackled him, police said. The suspect&#39;s head was cut in the fracas, according to police. KPD H-squad officers, including Norris, Ron Trentham, Ivan Green, Chris Baldwin, were at Townview on a &#39;&#39;crime suppression&#39;&#39; operation and quickly intervened, Trentham said.
<P>
<P><h3>Sevier Boys and Girls Club official fired for inappropriate behavior</h3>
<P>
<P>   SEVIERVILLE -- The executive director of the Boys and Girls Club of the Smoky Mountains has been fired for inappropriate behavior and is being investigated by police.
<P>   Jim Arwood, president of the Boys and Girls Club board of directors, said the group met Thursday and decided to fire Dale Bynum, who has been director of the club since January 1990.
<P>   Arwood declined to comment on what Bynum did that was inappropriate.
<P>   Sevierville Police Chief Robbie Fox confirmed Thursday that his department is investigating the allegations.
<P>
<P><h3>Two Virginia men are killed in 2-vehicle wreck in Hawkins County</h3>
<P>
<P>   Two Virginia men were killed Friday in Hawkins County when a tractor trailer pulled in front of their car on US Highway 11W, authorities said.
<P>   Thomas Freeman Jr., 41, of Emporia, Va. and Al L. Woodruff Jr., 33, were killed in the accident reported at 9:54 p.m., a dispatcher with the Tennessee Highway Patrol said.
<P>   The driver of the tractor trailer, James R. Baker of Jonesborough, Tenn., was not injured. Charges and citations are pending further investigation, the dispatcher said.
<P>
<P><h3>Ambulance driver involved in fatal wreck gets pretrial diversion</h3>
<P>
<P>    BLOUNTVILLE -- An ambulance driver accused of causing a fatal accident won&#39;t have to go to trial or serve any time behind bars.
<P>    The record of Earl Morphew, 38, of Chilhowie, Va., will be expunged if he successfully completes two years&#39; probation.
<P>    Prosecutors said Friday they had no legal standing to refuse his request for pretrial diversion. Morphew will be required to speak to emergency personnel groups about the dangers of emergency response. He will be banned from driving an ambulance.
<P>    Police said he ran a red light and struck a car while responding to a call in June. A 17-year-old girl died in the collision.
<P>
<P><h3>42-year-old Bluff City man is banned from Cherokee National Forest for year</h3>
<P>
<P>    GREENEVILLE -- A federal magistrate banned a hunter from the Cherokee National Forest for a year.
<P>    The ban against Ronnie Greene, 42, of Bluff City stemmed from charges he drove an all-terrain vehicle on a closed road in November. He had been cited previously on similar charges.
<P>    During the hearing Friday, Greene also was put on probation for a year and ordered to pay a $500 fine.
<P>
<P><h3>Jonesborough school suspends boy for allegedly trying to start gang
<P></h3>
<P>   JONESBOROUGH -- A fourth-grade boy was suspended from Jonesborough Elementary School by officials who said he was trying to start a gang.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I don&#39;t know if it meets the full definition, but the children involved were knowledgeable of gang activities, and this can plant a seed in young minds,&#39;&#39; said Assistant Principal Bill Bowman on Thursday.
<P>   Bowman conceded there was no evidence of any gang activity.
<P>   &#39;&#39;My son, the ringleader, is a kid who sleeps with the light on,&#39;&#39; said Danny Holmes. &#39;&#39;His only organized activity is playing baseball.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Holmes likened the situation to that of Johnathan Prevette of Lexington, N.C., the 6-year-old who was disciplined for kissing the cheek of a girl in his class in September.
<P>   The school has a zero-tolerance policy on gangs, Bowman said.
<P>   The Washington County Board of Education has no written policy on gang activity, said schools director Grant Rowland, but principals have discretionary powers.
<P>   The boy was suspended Wednesday for three days.
<P>
<P><h3>Bristol man sentenced to federal probation for computer crimes</h3>
<P>
<P>    GREENEVILLE -- A computer hacker got three years of federal probation for illegally trafficking computer passwords for access to a Middle Tennessee State University system.
<P>    Robert Hicks, 26, of Bristol also was fined $4,000 Friday. And he must pay restitution of $1,614 to MTSU. Prosecutors said he got computer account names and passwords from Wendell Dingus, which allowed him to get into the school&#39;s system. Dingus, 29, of Kingsport pleaded guilty earlier this month to similar charges. Sentencing for Dingus is scheduled for March 3.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

