<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>Sun Coal and Coke process low-cost, fume-free</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper Business News">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif" alt="Knoxville News-Sentinel Online -- Business News" align=bottom border=0 width=595 height=176></a><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td align=left valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 19, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Sun Coal and Coke process low-cost, fume-free</B></font><basefont size=6><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Knoxville firm's technology drives Indiana project</FONT></basefont></FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Jerry Dean, News-Sentinel business writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">A</FONT> Knoxville firm&#39;s proprietary technology is fueling a $350 million coke manufacturing and co-generation power project that promises to provide large, reliable quantities of coke and electricity to an Indiana mill while meeting environmental standards.
<P>   Federal Clean Air Act amendments of 1990 specified Knoxville&#39;s Sun Coal and Coke Co.&#39;s process by name as setting the standard for &#39;&#39;maximum achievable control technology.&#39;&#39; That is because its process is emission-free and generates none of the toxic byproducts of conventional coke ovens, according to Bud Davis, a spokesman for Sun Co. of Philadelphia, of which the Knoxville firm is a subsidiary.
<P>   Michael Dingus, president of the Knoxville firm, said construction is under way at the East Chicago, Ind. site on his firm&#39;s coke manufacturing plant. The plant, set for initial production by March 1998, is designed to provide Inland Steel Co. vast, reliable supplies of coke and electricity for at least 15 years.
<P>   Sun, Inland and Primary Energy Inc. of Merrillville, Ind., jointly announced their plans in November. Inland has signed a contract to buy 1.2 million tons of the plant&#39;s coke, used in iron manufacturing processes at Inland&#39;s Indiana Harbor Works.
<P>   Sun, under its agreement, is spending $185 million to design, build, finance and operate the cokemaking portion of the project, which incorporates Sun&#39;s proprietary nonrecovery coke technology on a 95-acre Indiana Harbor Works site. Inland has bought all its coke from other outside suppliers since 1993, when it closed the last of its operating coke oven batteries. 
<P>   Sun anticipates using the proprietary process to build more plants, making the company a signficantly larger player in the marketplace.
<P>   Sun&#39;s nonrecovery process burns all volatile gases produced in the coke-manufacturing process except sulfur, a residual contaminant removed from the flue gas during the electrical co-generation process. 
<P>  Dingus said the concept had been considered for nearly two decades, but only came together for this larger commercial project when the three firms agreed to pool their efforts, aided by governmental agency programs.
<P>   Sun and Primary Energy have worked with Indiana economic development officials and those of the City of East Chicago, the Northwest Indiana Forum and Northern Indiana Public Service Co. in obtaining economic development and tax incentives for the project. The project will receive EDGE (Economic Development for Growing Economies) credits, job-training grants, enterprise-zone expansion and tax credits and abatements. 
<P>   Primary Energy, a NIPSCO Industries subsidiary of Merrillville, Ind., will design, build, finance and operate the part of the project intended to remove sulfur from the coke plant&#39;s flue gas. Heat from the plant will be used to produce steam for electricity.
<P>   Inland President Dale E. Wiersbe said the project will cut Inland&#39;s coke costs significantly, thus making Inland iron production more competitive. 
<P>   Sun &#39;&#39;has been refining the technology for this environmentally benign method of making coke since the 1960s at a plant in Vansant, Va.&#39;&#39; Wiersbe said. 
<P>   &#39;&#39;Sun has successfully manufactured coke, using this process, for many years,&#39;&#39; he added.
<P>   Davis, the Sun spokesman in Philadelphia, said similar nonrecovery-process plants had been built for coke manufacture in Australia as early as 1914, and more recently in Mexico. But he said nothing on the scale of the Indiana project had been built using what is known as the Jewell-Thompson nonrecovery coke oven. It was designed by the late B. Ray Thompson, whose Elk River Resources Inc. of Knoxville was sold to Sun Co. and renamed Sun Coal and Coke.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
