<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>FYI</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper Business News">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif" alt="Knoxville News-Sentinel Online -- Business News" align=bottom border=0 width=595 height=176></a><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td align=left valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 19, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>FYI</B></font><basefont size=6><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Entrepreneurs try weird, wild</FONT></basefont></FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">W</FONT>hat&#39;s the wackiest small business in America?
<P>   Each year, NewsReach, a monthly small-business newsletter based in Jamison, Pa., compiles a list of some of the most unusual new business ventures. Some examples:
<P>   * Alligators under your bed. A bed and breakfast inn run by the operators of Wildlife Gardens in Houma, La., offers overnight stays in cabins built atop a well-stocked Southern swamp. The $60 fee includes breakfast and alligator views.
<P>   * Have Doggie, We&#39;ll Do. &#39;&#39;We pick up where your dog left off,&#39;&#39; promises this Chicago-based waste-removal business. Contract pooper-scoopers pay weekly visits to homes, condos, even some park district sites. 
<P>   * Divorce Magazine. Bridal magazines have succeeded without flocks of long-term subscribers. Why not a magazine for wedding bells gone sour -- those one-in-three marriages that don&#39;t last -- figures an enterprising publisher who hopes to fashion a city-by-city success with articles like &#39;&#39;Should I tell my ex about the affair?&#39;&#39;
<P>   * Ashes to asteroids. A Houston-based company called Celestis Inc. promises a high-tech approach to dispersing the ashes of a loved one. For $4,800, including a commemorative video of the launch and on-Earth memorial service, the company will send seven grams of an individual&#39;s cremated remains into space aboard a rocket.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>   <B>SURGING FORWARD -- </B>Knoxville is among the 140 markets where the Coca-Cola Co. is introducing &#39;&#39;Surge,&#39;&#39; a new &#39;&#39;fully-loaded citrus soda.&#39;&#39;
<P>   The beverage should be arriving in store shelves and vending machines this week, and Surge will be promoted with two commercials during Super Bowl XXXI.
<P>   Coke is targeting &#39;&#39;free-spirited youths&#39;&#39; ages 12-21 and &#39;&#39;hardworking young adults&#39;&#39; ages 21 to 34 as potential buyers for the green-colored concoction.
<P>   The &#39;&#39;fully-loaded&#39;&#39; apparently refers to the addition of maltodextrin, a complex carbohydrate. Also being promoted is its low carbonation and wide-mouth can that makes, the company said, for easy &#39;&#39;drinkability.&#39;&#39; 
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>   <B>ROOM FOR IMPROVEMENT -- </B>Even the best hotels can do better, according to a survey of business travelers.
<P>   Westin was ranked No. 1 among 11 upscale hotel chains rated by business travelers, according to J.D. Power and Associates and Frequent Flyer Magazine.
<P>   Out of a perfect score of 1,000, Westin got 670 points; followed by Renaissance, 642; Hyatt, 637; Marriott, 633; and Omni, 629.
<P>   &#39;&#39;While our readers may never need to buy another bar of soap or another bottle of shampoo . . . they are a very demanding group of people,&#39;&#39; John Migs, publisher of OAG Frequent Flyer Magazine.
<P>   J.D. Powers would not release results for hotels scoring below the industry average of 626. 
<P>   Factors driving travelers&#39; satisfaction and their contribution to the overall guest satisfaction survey, were: guest room, 33 percent; price and value, 22 percent; arrival process, 22 percent; departure, 13 percent; and food and beverage, 11 percent.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>    <B>ON THE ROAD</B> <B>--</B> The recreational vehicle industry is hoping for a big increase in sales in the coming years as baby boomers edge toward retirement. The Recreational Vehicle Industry Association says the average RV owner is 48 years old, with most of the purchases among 55- to 64-year-olds. The association says older RV buyers tend to purchase more expensive vehicles, most likely because they have more disposable income than people with young children.
<P>
<P>FYI is compiled by The News-Sentinel Business News staff from a variety of sources, including the Associated Press and New York Times wire services.
<P><B></B>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
