<head>
	<title>Schrader hopes his new start will be a winner</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 19, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470><BASEFONT SIZE="6">
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Schrader hopes his new start will be a winner</B></FONT><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Bill Luther, News-Sentinel sportswriter</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">C</FONT>HARLOTTE, N.C. -- New faces and names often lead to better results in auto racing.
<P>    Ken Schrader, 41, is excited about such an opportunity. After nine seasons with Hendrick Motorsports, the St. Louis native looks to owner/crew chief Andy Petree for guidance to victory lane.
<P>    Schrader, who enjoys just being in a race car, has four victories, 60 other top-five finishes and more than 100 from sixth to 10th. But those aren&#39;t the numbers anticipated when he departed the USAC midgets and sprint cars in 1983.
<P>    &#39;&#39;I&#39;ve had a lot of top 10s, but that&#39;s not what you race for even though I&#39;ve finished in the top 10 in points seven times since 1985,&#39;&#39; Schrader said. &#39;&#39;I haven&#39;t done as well as I wanted to.&#39;&#39;
<P>    With two years remaining on a contract with Rick Hendrick, Schrader chose to join Petree and the Skoal Bandit crew, and continue to drive Chevrolet Monte Carlos.
<P>    &#39;&#39;This was a change I wanted to make. Rick was kind enough to work with me and gave me an opportunity I wanted to pursue,&#39;&#39; said Schrader, who is winless in the last 170 Cup races. &#39;&#39;This move is not like I was shuffled out and looking for a ride.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Schrader doesn&#39;t take this opportunity as being another start in the sport.
<P>    &#39;&#39;Andy is a leader and I&#39;m by no means a rookie going into this deal,&#39;&#39; Schrader said. &#39;&#39;Andy knows what the car should be like, and basically I know the feel when I get in it. I think we&#39;ll be competitive and quickly.&#39;&#39;
<P>    As a crew chief, Petree has been a winner and expects to achieve the same accomplishments as an owner. He guided Dale Earnhardt to two championships (1993-94) and 15 victories during three years with Richard Childress Racing.
<P>    &#39;&#39;We have the talent and resources,&#39;&#39; said Petree, who led now-retired Harry Gant to nine wins in four seasons. &#39;&#39;We should win races, and I expect this team to be a top 10 in points. We want to be considered one of the top teams in this sport. When we accomplish that, then a NASCAR championship is in sight.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Schrader will enter the 1997 season with the same goal -- victories.
<P>    &#39;&#39;I don&#39;t feel that I&#39;ve had any highlights to this point of my career,&#39;&#39; Schrader said. &#39;&#39;I won the Busch Clash (at Daytona) a couple of times and had a good record in The Winston (currently held at Charlotte) -- second, second, second, third, fourth, third -- until the last two years.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Being part of a multi-car team had nothing to do with Schrader&#39;s decision to succeed Robert Pressley as Petree&#39;s driver.
<P>    &#39;&#39;This was just an opportunity to work with Andy, not the multi-car team,&#39;&#39; Schrader said. &#39;&#39;I can say I know because it&#39;s been like that ever since I&#39;ve been there. Rick has done better than anybody, and I think it&#39;s fairly obvious it works.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Schrader might have remained with Hendrick had Petree decided to step aside as crew chief.
<P>    &#39;&#39;Yes, that was most definitely what I wanted. It was a major concern,&#39;&#39; Schrader said. &#39;&#39;Andy also did a great job with Harry (Gant). That&#39;s what led to him going to the Childress operation. It was probably one of the better places for a crew chief to shine, but he had plenty of success before that, too.
<P>    &#39;&#39;Andy has everything in his shop that Rick Hendrick has,&#39;&#39; Schrader said. &#39;&#39;Quite frankly, I&#39;m looking forward to being the center of attention. I like the fact we have one team to concentrate on.
<P>    &#39;&#39;I have a lot to prove and I&#39;m with the team to do it. I have a lot of faith in Andy Petree.&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
