<head>
	<title>Lovely to step down as election registrar</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 18, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>Lovely to step down as election registrar</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Michael Silence, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">K</FONT>nox County Registrar at Large Irene Lovely said Friday she will retire &#39;&#39;shortly&#39;&#39; from that job of 18 years.
<P>   She would not be more specific on when, saying she was drafting a letter to notify Election Commission members of her intentions. She indicated that letter would be filed with the Election Commission office next week.
<P>   Already, one name has surfaced as a possible successor.
<P>   Laura Nichols, long active in Kids Voting and wife of Knox County District Attorney Randy Nichols, said Friday she is interested in the job that pays about $63,000 a year.
<P>   On Lovely&#39;s announcement, commission-member-to-be Mike McClamroch said, &#39;&#39;I think it is the appropriate action for this situation.&#39;&#39;
<P>   He was referring to last November&#39;s foul-up over early vote totals in the Knoxville-Knox County unification vote. No one in the election office made provisions for separating city and county votes -- a crucial mistake because in order for the question to pass, it had to win with both city and county voters.
<P>   But Lovely said her decision had nothing to do with that turmoil, which after the election she accepted responsibility for.
<P>   In fact, she told The News-Sentinel last summer the November election would be her last and that she was looking at retiring in Florida.
<P>   The voting fiasco, though, had created rampant talk about whether Lovely would retire or be fired. And that was fueled by Lovely taking off a number of days since the election in either vacation time or personal leave.
<P>   She said Friday she was using up that accumulated time before retiring. Her announcement follows a month of turnover for the Election Commission.
<P>   Last month, Republican Hazel Showalter died. This month, Republican Courtney Pearre resigned to take the position of legal counsel to Gov. Don Sundquist, and this week, Democrat Thomas &#39;&#39;Tank&#39;&#39; Strickland Jr. said he would resign before starting a job as the city&#39;s director of community relations.
<P>   Last week, Republicans nominated replacements for Pearre and Showalter. They are McClamroch and fellow lawyer Steve Roth.
<P>   Now the Knox County Democratic delegation must select a replacement for Strickland.
<P>   Knox County Election Commission Chairman Dennis Francis said Friday it will be up to the commission to select Lovely&#39;s replacement. Lovely is a Democrat, and the Election Commission is controlled by Democrats, 3-2, because the Democrats control the state House.
<P>   Nichols said she&#39;s interested in the job &#39;&#39;that&#39;s obviously something very important.&#39;&#39;
<P>   She said if the situation arose with her running the office and her husband appearing on the ballot, she would work with commissioners to handle that matter.
<P>   She said she&#39;s checked Tennessee law and found nothing to prevent her from serving as the registrar.
<P>   Randy Nichols was elected in 1994 to serve the remaining four years of the late Ed Dossett&#39;s term. Assuming he seeks re-election, he would run again in 1998.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
