<head>
	<title>Pollution hurts Cocke economy, official says</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 18, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>Pollution hurts Cocke economy, official says</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Morgan Simmons, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">C</FONT>ocke County&#39;s top executive said Friday the Environmental Protection Agency should give the county the same consideration it afforded Champion International when it granted the company a variance based on economic impact.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We have always had a very high number of families receiving food stamps, welfare, Medicaid and other benefits,&#39;&#39; said County Executive Harold Cates. &#39;&#39;To my knowledge, the socio-economic impact of this polluted river on Cocke County was never considered.&#39;&#39;
<P>   From the state line, 37 miles below Champion&#39;s Canton, N.C., paper mill, the Pigeon River flows 30 miles through Cocke County before emptying into the French Broad River, near Douglas Lake.
<P>   Cates said that pollution on the Pigeon River has hampered county efforts to recruit industry and develop recreation-based tourism.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We&#39;ve lived with the stigma of a dirty river for so long, it has hurt the whole community,&#39;&#39; he said. &#39;&#39;People want to locate industry where there is a good quality of life, not on a river with a reputation as one of the most polluted in the United States.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Cates said that prior to becoming Cocke County exective, he was employed by the Tennessee Department of Human Services, where he dealt with people on a daily basis who were economically deprived due to the county&#39;s weak economy.
<P>   Cocke County is one of nine counties in Tennessee that the state has classified as economically depressed. The Appalachian Regional Commission also named Cocke County as one of the eight most economically distressed counties in Tennessee.
<P>   &#39;&#39;This river has been a liability to Cocke County for 89 years,&#39;&#39; said Cates. &#39;&#39;It&#39;s now time for it to be turned into an asset for our community.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Twelve companies currently run raft trips down the Pigeon River&#39;s gorge section, where the size and quality of the rapids are comparable to the Ocoee River.
<P>   According to an economic study released by Walters State Community College, a clean Pigeon River could support a $7.3-million-a-year rafting industry.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We&#39;ve been able to develop a tourism program centered around whitewater activity on the Pigeon River,&#39;&#39; said Cates. &#39;&#39;If the river was cleaned up, the potential for recreational development would be even greater.&#39;&#39;
<P>   On Dec. 23, the EPA approved a new permit issued by North Carolina officials allowing Champion to continue operating its Pigeon River paper mill at pollution levels above what is allowed by federal law.
<P>   Tennessee is now pressing EPA to overturn the variance and issue a permit that protects the state&#39;s water-quality standards.
<P>   According to Loretta M. Ucelli, EPA associate administrator for public affairs, Champion&#39;s appeal for a variance, based on the social and economic impact to the company and the surrounding community, was answered by North Carolina.
<P>   &#39;&#39;There is a variance that was economically based, but those decisions were left up to the state,&#39;&#39; she said. &#39;&#39;North Carolina grants a variance to a particular facility, and it&#39;s EPA&#39;s job to make sure the variance meets the requirements of law and the water-quality standards of the states involved.&#39;&#39;
<P>   David McKinney, chief of environmental services for the Tennessee Wildlife Resources Agency, said Friday the Pigeon could be an outstanding smallmouth bass stream, with good walleye fishing as far up the river as Newport, and a put-and-take brown trout fishery through the winter and spring.
<P>   The Tennessee side of the Pigeon River carries consumption advisories on fish due to dioxin.
<P>   &#39;&#39;As long as the river is posted for dioxin, we&#39;re not inclined to promote it for fishing,&#39;&#39; said McKinney.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

	<P><center><font size=2>Return to </font><a href="/"><font size=2>Main</font></a><font size=2>. Copyright &#169; 1996 The Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size=2>webmaster</font></a><font size=2>.</font></center></p>
