<head>
	<title>Drive-by slaying defendant back in jail after misstep</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 18, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Drive-by slaying defendant back in jail after misstep</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Curfew violation bumps teen's bail</FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Skip Lackey, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">A</FONT> Knoxville teen charged in the drive-by shooting death of a 5-year-old girl watched his bond on an unrelated charge jump to $300,000 Friday after he failed to follow curfew restrictions imposed by the court.
<P>   Melvin &#39;&#39;Little Melvin&#39;&#39; Davis, also known as Melvin Tate, is charged in the May 18, 1996, slaying of Brittany Shenice Daniels, who was killed during a drive-by shooting in the Lonsdale Homes housing project.
<P>   Authorities allege Davis, 16, drove one of the cars used during the shooting.
<P>   After his arrest, Davis was released from the Knox County Jail on $50,000 bond with court-imposed restrictions, including a 6 p.m. to 6 a.m. curfew.
<P>   The murder charge remains in the hands of the Knox County district attorney general&#39;s office pending a grand jury decision.
<P>   Since the shooting, Davis has been charged with aggravated assault and on Christmas Eve he was shot by a teenager he allegedly robbed, which sparked another arrest charging Davis with aggravated robbery.
<P>   On Friday in Knox County Criminal Court, a Knoxville Police Department officer testified that at 9 p.m. on Oct. 1, she saw Davis at a concert at Thompson-Boling Arena and questioned him.
<P>   Because his presence at the show after 6 p.m. was a violation of his curfew, and because he was shot by an alleged robbery victim at 7:10 p.m., prosecutors asked Judge Richard Baumgartner to revoke the $50,000 bond that Davis posted when he was released on the aggravated assault charge.
<P>   Baumgartner complied and set a $300,000 bond -- sending Davis back to jail until he could post a new bond, routinely 10 percent of the amount set by the court.
<P>   Prosecutors said Davis has claimed he does not have enough money to hire a lawyer to defend him against the aggravated assault charge. His alleged lack of money has not stopped him from getting out of jail on the murder, aggravated assault and aggravated robbery charges, which have a combined bond of $170,000, prosecutors said.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
