<html>
<head>
	<title>Job Corps case convict won&#39;t testify in trial of co-defendant</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 18, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Job Corps case convict won&#39;t testify in trial of co-defendant</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Skip Lackey, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">C</FONT>hrista Gail Pike, on death row for the slaying of a Job Corps student, was in Knox County Criminal Court on Friday and declined to testify in next week&#39;s murder trial of co-defendant and former lover Tadaryl D. Shipp.
<P>   Appearing in shackles before Judge Mary Beth Leibowitz, Pike invoked her Fifth Amendment right to silence because her conviction is on appeal.
<P>   In March, Pike was convicted of first-degree murder and sentenced to die in the electric chair for her role in killing Colleen A. Slemmer, 19, on Jan. 12, 1995. Pike, 20, was to be executed five days ago, but on Nov. 18 her execution was stayed pending the completion of her appeal.
<P>   Pike, Shipp and co-defendant Shadolla R. Peterson were charged with killing Slemmer in a remote area of the University of Tennessee campus.
<P>   Authorities said Pike led the attack because she thought Slemmer was trying to steal Shipp from her.
<P>   Peterson, 20, pleaded guilty to being an accessory after the fact. Shipp, 19, wants a jury trial so his attorney, Chris Coffey, subpoeaned Pike to testify. Jury selection begins next week.
<P>   On Friday, Coffey told Leibowitz that he wants Pike to testify about &#39;&#39;facts related to the case&#39;&#39; -- but he was not specific.
<P>   After her conviction, Pike wrote Shipp a note telling him how to plan his own defense.
<P>   She also told him she would testify on his behalf.
<P>   Shipp has admitted he helped Pike carve a pentagram into Slemmer&#39;s chest, authorities said. Prosectors cannot seek the death penalty against him, because at the time of the murder he was a juvenile.
<P>   Slemmer of Orange Park, Fla., was a student at the Knoxville Job Corps Center, along with Pike, Peterson and Shipp.
<P>   The murder -- as well as other acts of violence committed by students -- forced a public outcry that led the U.S. Department of Labor to close the center, which was located on Dale Avenue.
<P>   Pike has appealed her conviction, claiming pre-trail publicity tainted the jury, introducing Slemmer&#39;s skull during the trial was inflammatory evidence that tainted the jury, and death by electrocution is barbarous.
<P>   Defense attorney William C. Talman said Friday if the state Court of Criminal Appeals does not overturn the conviction, he will appeal to the state Supreme Court. Talman said he will appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court if the state does not overturn the conviction.
<P>   Because the case is on appeal, Pike cannot testify for Shipp, because she might incriminate herself before the jury, Talman said.
<P>   Appearing before Leibowitz on Friday, Pike said if she was called to testify she would invoke the Fifth Amendment. Leibowitz announced Pike would not be forced to testify and ordered her returned to the Tennessee Prison for Women in Nashville.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

	<P><center><font size=2>Return to </font><a href="/"><font size=2>Main</font></a><font size=2>. Copyright &#169; 1996 The Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size=2>webmaster</font></a><font size=2>.</font></center></p>
</body>
