<head>
	<title>State revenues up enough to cut shortfall, not enough to save jobs</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 18, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>State revenues up enough to cut shortfall, not enough to save jobs</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Rebecca Ferrar, News-Sentinel Nashville bureau</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">N</FONT>ASHVILLE -- State revenue collections increased enough in December to reduce this year&#39;s shortfall by about $25 million, but not enough to stall layoffs.
<P>    Finance Commissioner John Ferguson said Friday the shortfall for the current budget now is $176 million, and the estimated deficit for the 1997-98 year starting July 1 also is down to about $260 million to $270 million.
<P> 
<P>   &#39;&#39;January will be the big banner month if it holds like this,&#39;&#39; he said.
<P>    Tax revenues collected in January reflect December activity and will show how well Christmas sales went.
<P>    &#39;&#39;There&#39;s a big expectation of sales tax collections because of Christmas,&#39;&#39; Ferguson said.
<P>    Still, Ferguson said layoffs proposed by Gov. Don Sundquist &#39;&#39;likely&#39;&#39; are still on track.
<P>    Despite the possibility of looming layoffs, state employees may get a pay raise this year.
<P>    The issue of raises is a sore subject with employees after Sundquist granted pay increases this week for some of his key staffers, ranging from 4 percent to 29 percent. The administration said those staffers had taken on additional responsibilities and the governor&#39;s office reduced costs this year by 15 percent.
<P>    Raises for rank-and-file employees are a &#39;&#39;high priority,&#39;&#39; Ferguson said.
<P>    &#39;&#39;We&#39;re trying to figure out a way to do that,&#39;&#39; he said, though he declined to target a percentage of increase. The Tennessee State Employees Association is asking for an 8 percent pay raise. 
<P>    Ferguson also responded to criticism by some legislators that the estimated shortfalls are inflated.
<P>    They are based, Ferguson said, on recommendations of the Funding Board made up of himself, the governor and the consitutional officers, who also receive advice from University of Tennessee economists.
<P>    The estimated shortfall for the current year was about $100 million and for the next budget year it was $300 million.
<P>    December revenue collections show:
<P>    * Overall collections for the five months of this fiscal year were $473 million, an increase of $30 over the previous fiscal year.
<P>    * Sales tax collections in December were more than $311 million, $7.1 million less than estimated.
<P>    * Franchise and excise taxes in December were almost $45 million, $11.5 million more than estimated.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

	<P><center><font size=2>Return to </font><a href="/"><font size=2>Main</font></a><font size=2>. Copyright &#169; 1996 The Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size=2>webmaster</font></a><font size=2>.</font></center></p>
