<head>
	<title>Tennessee Theater deeded to foundation</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 18, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Tennessee Theater deeded to foundation</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> restoration planned</FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Eleni Chamis, News-Sentinel business writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">K</FONT>noxville&#39;s historic Tennessee Theater has been deeded over to its foundation board, whose members plan a fund-raising drive to renovate the nearly 80-year-old structure.
<P>   The Historical Tennessee Theater Foundation now has control of the 1,500-seat building, which has capital improvement needs from a front curtain, costing around $40,000, to enlarged restrooms, and numerous cosmetic upgrades.
<P>   &#39;&#39;An awful lot needs to be done at this point, probably well over $1 million,&#39;&#39; said foundation president Bruce Hartmann, general manager of The News-Sentinel. &#39;&#39;We hope to hire a firm specializing in theater renovation that will come in and give us an estimate, so we can know what to do.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We&#39;re positioning it for success.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Last April, Jim Dick, whose Dick Broadcasting Co. owned the theater for about 12 years, offered it to the city of Knoxville.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I felt that theater should belong to the people of Knoxville instead of an individual or company who could sell it at their will,&#39;&#39; Dick said. &#39;&#39;The theater has operated at a very close to a break-even cash flow.&#39;&#39;
<P>   At the time, Knoxville Mayor Victor Ashe said he hoped the theater could be preserved and kept open as an important part of downtown. But he added the theater could be managed and financed better if it were operated by a public-private partnership.
<P>   &#39;&#39;So we set about to seeing the interest, and there was tremendous interest,&#39;&#39; Dick said.
<P>   Just this week, the theater was turned over to the 23-member, nonprofit foundation board, which will be expanded to 30 individuals.
<P>   &#39;&#39;The average person hasn&#39;t any idea how many people use that theater,&#39;&#39; said Dick, adding high schools have held graduations and proms there, and everything else from weddings to Christmas pageants have been performed there. It remains home to Knoxville&#39;s symphony and opera company.
<P>   Twenty-five of 31 dates in January are booked; 14 of 28 are already reserved for February, according to Ashley Capps, president of AC Entertainment, which books the theater&#39;s shows.
<P>   Hartmann added that in order to maintain the theater, the board will look into the possibility of adding a small surcharge per ticket for ticketed events and also may seek city, county and state funding.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We work in historic theaters throughout the Southeastern U.S.,&#39;&#39; Capps said. &#39;&#39;The Tennessee Theater is in pretty good shape. It needs constant maintenance; there are improvements that definitely need to be made. It&#39;s a very functional building, a very comfortable building.&#39;&#39;
<P>   
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
