<head>
	<title>Ashe wants White House to cut regulatory burden falling on cities</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 18, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Ashe wants White House to cut regulatory burden falling on cities</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Richard Powelson, News-Sentinel Washington bureau</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">W</FONT>ASHINGTON -- Knoxville Mayor Victor Ashe said Friday he hopes the Clinton administration in its second term will reduce the regulatory burdens that annually are heaped on local governments while also helping cities to preserve park areas and to reduce crime.
<P>   He currently is one of many mayors strongly opposed to a new federal regulation requiring more cities, including Knoxville, to greatly reduce auto-emission pollution.
<P>   &#39;&#39;There needs to be some cost-benefit analysis&#39;&#39; before any new regulations are approved, Ashe said.
<P>    He is one of about 260 mayors attending the winter meeting of the U.S. Conference of Mayors.
<P>   The conference&#39;s leadership chose Ashe and another mayor to appear on a panel today to discuss the air-pollution regulation and other federalism problems.
<P>   &#39;&#39;How many thousands of dollars do Knoxville taxpayers have to spend to reach a (new clean air) goal, and if we reach a goal, what are the benefits?&#39;&#39; Ashe asked.
<P>    &#39;&#39;I wasn&#39;t aware that where we are now is unclean.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Between mayors&#39; meetings Friday, Ashe and other mayors talked to President Clinton at the White House, where Clinton generally listened to their concerns, and they met with the Republican leaders of the House and Senate to discuss ways that mayors could work more closely with congressional leaders on issues of mutual interest.
<P>   Clinton generally has been good about seeking input from local government officials on federal issues affecting them, Ashe said.
<P>    But there continue to be too many new, expensive regulations being passed by Washington at the expense of local governments, he said.
<P>   The federal Land and Water Conservation Fund currently helps fund federal public lands. But Ashe said most people visit their city parks often and the nearest national park rarely, so cities also should be getting regular funding to acquire adequate park land before too much land is developed.
<P>   On another matter, Ashe said he hoped his Republican Party begins working more with local coalitions, including minorities and women, to improve its chances of winning the next presidential election.
<P>   &#39;&#39;They have to,&#39;&#39; Ashe said. &#39;&#39;Or they can just keep losing national elections. They can be what the Democrats were for 30 years, which was a congressional party.&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

	<P><center><font size=2>Return to </font><a href="/"><font size=2>Main</font></a><font size=2>. Copyright &#169; 1996 The Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size=2>webmaster</font></a><font size=2>.</font></center></p>
