<head>
	<title>Student expelled over knife will get a jury trial</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 18, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Student expelled over knife will get a jury trial</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By David Keim, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">I</FONT>n an unusual development for a juvenile case, a jury trial was set Friday for Jason Gaddy, the Karns High School student expelled last year for taking a butterfly knife to a track meet.
<P>   Chancellor Fred McDonald set the case for Jan. 27 after rejecting a motion to dismiss the case because it&#39;s taken longer than 45 days to be heard.
<P>   Jury trials are uncommon for juvenile cases unless a minor is tried as an adult; juvenile judges alone decide juvenile cases.
<P>   &#39;&#39;To my knowledge there has not been one case in Knox County where a juvenile -- who had not been transferred to Criminal Court to be tried as an adult -- had a jury trial,&#39;&#39; attorney Bill Davidson said.
<P>   McDonald and Criminal Court Clerk Martha Phillips concurred.
<P>   The trial will let a jury consider a case that has spurred criticism of Knox County&#39;s &#39;&#39;zero tolerance&#39;&#39; policy toward weapons on school grounds.
<P>   Gaddy, who was 17 when the incident occurred last March but turned 18 last November, said he had the knife because a track team member asked that a bothersome tag be cut out of his shirt. As in other incidents in which students claimed innocent motives, however, he was expelled.
<P>   Although he&#39;s due to be reinstated in March, Gaddy would remain on probation unless his juvenile conviction is overturned.
<P>   Davidson requested a jury trial but argued Friday the case should be thrown out because his appeal, received by Knox County Circuit Court on Oct. 1, wasn&#39;t heard within 45 days. McDonald ruled the time limit didn&#39;t apply if the child wasn&#39;t in custody, but agreed the case should be heard soon. Because a different trial set for Jan. 27 has been settled out of court, lawyers agreed to hear Gaddy&#39;s case then.
<P>   In turning down Davidson&#39;s motion for dismissal, McDonald said, &#39;&#39;Mr. Davidson, if you&#39;re successful doing this, all we&#39;ll see is appeals and requests for jury trials.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Davidson pointed out Gaddy&#39;s freedom has been restricted even if he&#39;s not in custody.
<P>   Gaddy must perform 80 hours of public service, has an 11 p.m. curfew, is forbidden from having &#39;&#39;anything to do with any weapons of any kind&#39;&#39; and is subject to random drug screens, according to the conditions of his probation.
<P>   The appeal of Gaddy&#39;s Aug. 28 juvenile conviction was delayed in part because 4th Knox County Circuit Judge Bill Swann recused himself from the case because he did not believe he could &#39;&#39;view the issues impartially,&#39;&#39; according to court records.
<P>   Asked to elaborate, Swann said, &#39;&#39;I&#39;m forbidden to do so because it&#39;s a pending case, under the canons of judicial ethics.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Asked if he would hear future &#39;&#39;zero tolerance&#39;&#39; appeals, Swann said, &#39;&#39;I can&#39;t imagine the circumstances under which I would be able to maintain an open mind. . . . I&#39;ll be recusing myself for the presiding judge to make such reference as appropriate.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Presiding Judge Dale Workman referred the Gaddy case to McDonald in mid-December. Davidson said the delays -- including delays with the original juvenile court case -- violate Gaddy&#39;s right to a speedy trial.
<P>   Said Gaddy&#39;s mother, Cathy: &#39;&#39;I just want all of this over. It&#39;s been a nightmare for a year. If Jason was a bad kid, I think I could understand it, but he has never in his life given us a bit of problems.&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

	<P><center><font size=2>Return to </font><a href="/"><font size=2>Main</font></a><font size=2>. Copyright &#169; 1996 The Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size=2>webmaster</font></a><font size=2>.</font></center></p>
