<head>
	<title>Tribe One offers young men structured path to better life</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 18, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Tribe One offers young men structured path to better life</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Stephanie Spellers, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">D</FONT>rugs, alcohol, money, violence. It was supposed to be fun.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We thought it was party, party, party,&#39;&#39; said 22-year-old Mechanicsville native Lawuni Roper of his younger days. &#39;&#39;That&#39;s the deception of the streets. You think it&#39;s just fun, that it&#39;s the way life has got to be. You don&#39;t know it&#39;s destroying you.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Dozens of young men are learning they have a choice. They&#39;re walking from the deadly streets and playgrounds and into Tribe One, an urban ministry that fights to rebuild spirits and lives.
<P>   &#39;&#39;This is leadership development at its core,&#39;&#39; Tribe One co-founder Danny Mayfield explained. &#39;&#39;It&#39;s not midnight basketball or even just changing people. This is getting people to devote their lives to changing lives.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Roper is one of the success stories. He&#39;s finished the program and plans to start his own ministry using the model he learned from Tribe One founders Mayfield and Chris Woodhull. They hope more youths will do the same.
<P>   Week after week, Woodhull and Mayfield offer their charges -- mostly young black men -- the chance to identify the destructive forces in their lives, let go of their emotional baggage and practice new rules for living.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We tell the guys, &#39;Hey, if you want the jail or the grave, then stay with that path. But if you want to be alive and free, then stick with us,&#39; &#39;&#39; Woodhull said. &#39;&#39;It&#39;s a treatment process. It&#39;s not easy -- like Jesus said, it&#39;s a narrow gate -- but it will keep them alive and free.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Eventually, Woodhull said, he and Mayfield would like to see the young men take the Tribe One message and commit to spreading it to save even more young lives.
<P>   It&#39;s a commitment these men share. Mayfield, 27, grew up in Camden, N.J., where he learned firsthand the troubles of the black youths he helps now. He graduated from Knoxville College in 1994, a year after he and Woodhull gave birth to Tribe One.
<P>   Woodhull, 37, is an Air Force child raised in the white middle class. Leaving behind troubles with drugs and alcohol, he gave his life to Christ and to ministry in the inner city.
<P>   In their three years together, Mayfield and Woodhull have tested a variety of approaches. They&#39;ve tried scaring their charges into sobriety and offering mentors who testify to a different way of life. They&#39;ve told them about Christian love and hoped the rest would fall into place. No approach was as complex as the problems they faced.
<P>   The Tribe One model features fun stuff like gymnastics, soccer and trips to McDonald&#39;s. Then there are the weekly meetings at the house on University Avenue or the Episcopal Church of the Ascension on Northshore Drive.  Most gatherings run like this recent one:
<P>   Start with prayer, a simple plea for God&#39;s presence, for safety and patience and love and a measure of joy.
<P>   Mayfield and Woodhull coach the boys through a recitation of the mission. After a few tries, they come up with the right words: &#39;&#39;Preparing people to be neighbors for God&#39;s neighborhood.&#39;&#39;
<P>   &#39;&#39;It&#39;s simple,&#39;&#39; Woodhull said. &#39;&#39;We&#39;re preparing ordinary, regular people. They&#39;ll be neighbors, and it&#39;s all for God&#39;s neighborhood, which is an all-inclusive community where everyone receives the care they need.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Then they define the disease these young men face: HIV, &#39;&#39;Hood Infectious Virus.&#39;&#39; It&#39;s a term Woodhull and Mayfield picked up at an urban ministry conference this fall.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Violence is a disease, and they&#39;re infecting each other,&#39;&#39; Woodhull said. &#39;&#39;It&#39;s all about money and power and my posse. Christian brothers call it sin. Whatever it is, it&#39;s leading to death and incarceration.&#39;&#39;
<P>   From this painful discussion they move to hope: the &#39;&#39;treatment model.&#39;&#39; The first stage, Mayfield says,  is eliminating destructive forces like drugs, guns, alcohol, misogyny and violent language.   The boys remind Mayfield and Woodhull that guns and drugs are often just part of their lives. Mayfield doesn&#39;t accept that.
<P>   &#39;&#39;You can&#39;t be clearheaded if you&#39;ve still got a gun in your hand,&#39;&#39; Mayfield said.
<P>   From there, Mayfield and Woodhull help the youths understand the pain, fear and anger that drive them to violence. They may write about it, discuss it or just share strategies for resolving it.
<P>   Finally, youths learn a new set of values and habits for new lives. This is the part Grant, 13, likes best. &#39;&#39;They tell you about respect and how to stay out of trouble,&#39;&#39; he said. &#39;&#39;You don&#39;t have to get into bad stuff on the street.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Tribe One encourages youths to respect human life and respect themselves, to make friends who won&#39;t lead them into danger, and to make change by changing themselves first.
<P>   If they want to remain alive and free, they can adopt new habits like responding instead of reacting, thinking win/win, staying prepared and seeking to understand others.
<P>   All these lessons are posted on a flip chart and reviewed at every meeting. Woodhull said he hopes the simple format will encourage young people to spread the message.
<P>   &#39;&#39;There&#39;s nothing we&#39;re doing that they couldn&#39;t do,&#39;&#39; Woodhull agreed. &#39;&#39;It&#39;s all about setting the captives free, and that&#39;s just Jesus&#39; mission. I don&#39;t think it has to be more complicated than that.&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

	<P><center><font size=2>Return to </font><a href="/"><font size=2>Main</font></a><font size=2>. Copyright &#169; 1996 The Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size=2>webmaster</font></a><font size=2>.</font></center></p>
</body>
