		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><h3>Nashville lawyer tapped for Tennessee AG post</h3>
<P>
<P>
<P>   NASHVILLE -- John Knox Walkup, who has previously served as second-in-command of the state attorney general&#39;s office, was chosen by the state Supreme Court on Friday night to succeed his former boss as Tennessee&#39;s top lawyer.
<P>    Walkup, who left his post as deputy attorney general two years ago to join a Nashville law firm, was picked by the five Supreme Court justices from 11 lawyers who applied to succeed Attorney General Charles Burson.
<P>   Burson is resigning effective Feb. 14.
<P>   Walkup will fill the remainder of Burson&#39;s term, which expires after the Supreme Court election in 1998.
<P>    Walkup, whose law practice has included some lobbying since he left the attorney general&#39;s office, had presented himself in the public hearings as well qualified because of his experience in state government legal matters.
<P>    The Supreme Court has traditionally picked attorneys general in secret. In the current selection process, the open public presentations on Thursday were followed by private interviews with each of the 11 candidates on Friday. The justices then met in secret session to make their final decision.
<P>    The selection also comes with proposals pending in the state Legislature to allow the attorney general to be chosen by popular election. Tennessee is now the only state in the nation with an attorney general picked by its state Supreme Court.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Knoxville teen accused of molesting children</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>   A 15-year-old boy accused of molesting children has been released to his parents on $3,000 bond.
<P>   Derek Baron of North Knoxville was released Thursday on bond on condition he remain under house arrest and stay under a protective plan that assures he will not be alone, Knox County Assistant District Attorney Steve Sword said Friday. A Feb. 27 hearing date has been set.
<P>   Baron was arrested Jan. 13 on two charges of rape of a child and one count of indecent exposure. The rape charges are felonies that involve victims under the age of 13, Sword said. Court records allege Baron raped children between June 1995 and December 1996. The indecent exposure allegedly occurred in November 1996.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Jefferson family loses home, belongings in fire</h3>
<P>
<P>
<P>   TALBOTT -- An early morning fire on Friday destroyed the newly purchased, uninsured home of a Jefferson County couple and their four children, officials said.
<P>   Tommy Rogers was at work at the time of the 4:50 a.m. fire. His wife, Mary Lou Rogers, and their daughters, Meredith, 12, and Mattie, 5, and sons McKinley, 8, and 6-month-old Micah, all escaped without injury.
<P>   Single-digit temperatures hampered the efforts of the Kansas Talbott Volunteer and White Pine fire departments. Water runoff created as firefighters worked to extinguish the blaze left a sheet of ice over a portion of nearby state Highway 66, requiring road crews to salt the roadway.
<P>   Jefferson County Sheriff&#39;s Department Deputy Tony Cody broke an ankle when he slipped on a patch of ice as he hurried to determine if anyone was trapped inside.
<P>   The fire destroyed the three-bedroom, two-story house, and its cause hadn&#39;t been determined Friday.
<P>   Family members said the Rogers would accept any donations of food, clothing, baby items, furniture, household supplies or other items.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Sevier Boys and Girls club official under probe</h3>
<P>
<P>
<P>   SEVIERVILLE -- The executive director of the Boys and Girls Club of the Smoky Mountains has been fired for inappropriate behavior and is being investigated by police.
<P>    Jim Arwood, president of the Boys and Girls Club board of directors, said the group met Thursday and decided to fire Dale Bynum, who has been director of the club since January 1990.
<P>    Arwood declined to comment on what Bynum did that was inappropriate.
<P>    Sevierville Police Chief Robbie Fox confirmed Thursday his department is investigating the allegations.
<P>
<P>
