<P><B>COWAN, RAYMOND LEE, JR. - </B>48, of Louisville, died Thursday night at Blount Memorial Hospital. He was preceded in death by: his parents, Lee Raymond Cowan, Sr. and Arlie McKee Cowan; brother, James Earl Cowan. He is survived by: his wife, Rose Cowan of Louisville; sons, Jerry Lee Cowan of Clifton, Tenn., James Brandon Cowan of Louisville; daughter, Samantha Lee Ann Cowan of Kingsport, Tenn; stepchildren, Ryan and Jason McKinney, Monica Earley, all of Louisville, Scott Haun of Nashville; brother, Rev. Gary Cowan of Maryville; grandsons, Steven Cowan of Louisville, Austin Cowan of Kingsport; special friend, Cory Toth of Maryville. Funeral service will be at 8 p.m. Saturday at Memorial Funeral Home in Maryville with Rev. Gary Cowan officiating. The family will receive friends from 6-8 p.m. Saturday at Memorial Funeral Home in Maryville.
<P>
<P><B>CURRY, WILMA WING - </B>age 81, of Maryville, died Friday, January 17, 1997, at Blount Memorial Hospital. She was a member of St. John United Methodist Church and was preceded in death by her husband, John Curry; parents, James and Mabel Wing; sister, Grave Truscott. Survivors include: daughters and sons-in-law, Pat and Jack Myers, Kay and Bill Pearson; grandchildren, Johnny Myers and wife, Missy, Kevin Myers, Staci Myers, Mike Pearson and wife, Judy, Patrick Pearson; great-grandchildren, Micah and Rebekah Pearson, all of Maryville; brother, James Wing of Norfolk, N.Y.; sisters, Bernice Eddy of Carthage, N.Y., Frances Harland of Walland; several nieces and nephews. Funeral service will be held on Sunday at 8 p.m. in the funeral home chapel with Rev. Edward Sykes officiating. The family will receive friends and visitors from 7 p.m. until funeral time. Interment will follow on Monday at 11 a.m. at Grandview Cemetery. Arrangements are by McCammon-Ammons Funeral Home.
<P>
<P><B>ELEDGE, COY HASHMERE - </B>age 82, of Sevierville, died Thursday, January 16, 1997. He was born January 27, 1914, and was preceded in death by his parents, John and Effie Eledge; sister, Edna Harvel and granddaughter, Melissa Lethco and was a veteran of World War II. Survivors: estranged wife, Florence; daughters and sons-in-law, Willena and Onain Roberts, Sue Lethco, Charolene and Vacy Turner, Talbott, Tenn., Doris and Jan Shoaf, Clara and Frank Bohanan, Rhonda and Mike Shultz; former son-in-law, Elgar Lethco; grandchildren, Cynthia Phillips, Claudine Adams, Glenda Rennison, Norma Breeden, Carroll Lethco, Judy Huffaker, Vacy Turner, Jr., Sheila Parker, Lina Howell, Stacie Cameron, Tosha Turner, Kim Whited, Jama Franklin, Jennifer Dixon, Jeremy Hurst; 17 great-grandchildren; five step-grandchildren; six step-great-grandchildren; brother and sister-in-law, Hubert and Eunice Eledge, Sevierville; sisters and brothers-in-law, Ruby Smith, Sevierville, Ruth Patterson, Jefferson City, Mabel and Jim Bailey, Melbourne, Fla.; several nieces and nephews; special cousin, Fount Baxter; special friends, employees of C & B Market, Triple C Market. The family will receive friends 6-7 p.m. Saturday in the West Chapel of Atchley Funeral Home followed by funeral service at 7 p.m. Rev. Earl Lane, Rev. Andy Ball and Rev. Curtis Wells officiating. Interment 1 p.m. Sunday in Sims Cemetery. Pallbearers will be Jeremy Hurst, Jason Lethco, Josh Lethco, Carroll Lethco, Vacy Turner, Jr., Charles T. Howell, III, Lee Parker, Teddy Cameron. Atchley Funeral Home, 
<P>Sevierville, in charge.
<P>
<P><B>EWING, JOE A. - </B>passed away at Fort Sanders Hospital, January 17, 1997. Son of the late Roy and Fanny Ewing. He was a long standing member of St. Paul Presbyterian Church, the Farm Bureau, the Hamblen County Cattlemen&#39;s Association, and an active member of the democratic party. He attended Tusculum College and was a life-long resident of Springvale Community. Survivors: wife of 51 years, Elizabeth Ewing; son, Joe Ewing, Jr. and wife, Tracy of Russellville; daughters, Martha Lacy and husband, Robert &#39;&#39;Buz&#39;&#39; Lacy of Morristown, Marianna Gooding and husband, Bill of Dumfries, Va., Margaret Reed and husband, John of Roan Mountain, Tenn., Susie Stevens and husband, Andrew of Durham, Maine; sisters, Virginia Stoffell and husband, Earnie of Burlington, N.C., Marjorie Beets and husband, Bob of Morristown; several nieces and nephews; grandchildren, Todd Lacy, Michell Gooding, Ashley Gooding, Matt Lacy, Craig Browning, Seth Ewing, and Jessica Ewing. The family will receive friends from 2-3 p.m. Sunday at Mayes Mortuary. Funeral service will be at 3 p.m. at Mayes Mortuary with Rev. Jim Gray officiating. Interment will be in St. Paul Cemetery. Honorary pallbearers will be members of his Sunday School Class at St. Paul Presbyterian Church. In lieu of flowers, family request donations be made to St. Paul Presbyterian Church. Mayes Mortuary, in charge of arrrangements.
<P>
<P><B>HARRIS, REV. OTTIS (GAY) - </B>a retired Baptist minister, age 83, of Seymour, Tenn., passed away January 16, 1997, in Dayton, Ohio. Rev. Harris pastored several churches in Alabama, Florida, and Tennessee to include: Ellejoy Baptist Church, Riverdale Baptist Church, Lyons Creek Baptist Church, Valley Grove Baptist Church, First Baptist Church of Pompano Beach, Fla. (1953-1962). He also served as interim pastor at several area churches after his retirement in 1976. He was very active and lead several states enlargement campaigns for the Southern Baptist Sunday School Board. Rev. Harris had also served as a bereavement counselor at Holly Hills Funeral Home. He was a mason with the Sevier Lodge #334 and Scottish Rite Bodies, Knoxville. He was preceded in death by his wife, Lela Davis Harris. Survivors: son and daughter-in-law, Dr.John Edwin and Mary Louise Harris, Dayton, Ohio; grandchildren, Melissa and Mike and Michael Slamb, Sheri and Scott, Jordan and Christopher Coffman, Ross Harris; brothers, Aundis Harris, Atlanta, Ga., Willard Harris, Cleveland, Tenn., Windell Harris, Etowah, Tenn.; several nieces and nephews; and a host of friends. Funeral service 7 p.m. Sunday, January 19, 1997, at Valley Grove Baptist Church, Dr. William L. Blivens officiating assisted by Rev. Harry Mynatt. The interment will be 11 a.m. Monday at Chilhowee Cemetery. Pallbearers: Ed Rogers, Earl Ford, Robert Whitehead, Jim Pierce, Bill Pierce, Tom Rogers. Honorary pallbearers: Hubert Fox, Frank Toomy, Dana Howard, and Valley Grove Deacons. The family request that memorial contributions be made to the Ottis Gay Harris Ministerial Scholarship Endowment at Carson-Newman College in Jefferson City, Tenn. Contributions may also be sent to Valley Grove Baptist Church, 9000 Old Sevierville Pike, Knoxville, TN 37920. The family will receive friends 5-7 p.m. Sunday at Valley Grove Baptist Church. Arrangements by Holly Hills Funeral Home, 573-7300.
<P>
<P><B>HEISER, MICHAEL C. - </B>43, of Powell, passed away suddenly at his home Wednesday, January 15, 1997, of an apparent heart attack. Survived by his daughter, Angela Heiser of Knoxville; parents, John and Grace Heiser of Powell; brother, Daniel Heiser, Powell; sisters, Faith Thompson Canty Dunn N.C., Chris Dale Minor of Morristown, Tenn., Susan Heiser Lary of Powell; several nieces and nephews; great niece and great-nephews; aunts, uncles and cousins. Receiving family and friends 7 p.m. Friday, January 17 at Weaver&#39;s Funeral Home with the service to follow at 8 p.m. Interment to be at the Heiser Family Cemetery at 2 p.m. Saturday.
<P>
<P><B>HILL, MRS. MONROE (OLVA) - </B>age 79, of Maryville, died Thursday, January 16, 1997, at Colonial Hills Nursing Home. She was preceded in death by her husband, Monroe Hill; parents, John and Pearl Ousley; sister, Ortha Tatum; brothers, Titus and Earnest Ousley. Survivors include: sisters, Mrs. Jack (Ada) Woodby, Mrs. Clyde (Ova) Loveday; three nieces; one nephew. Funeral services will be held at 2 p.m. Saturday in McCammon-Ammons Funeral Home Chapel with Dr. Marvin Gass officiating. The interment will follow in Grandview Cemetery. The family will receive friends from 1-2 p.m. Saturday at McCammon-Ammons Funeral Home, Maryville.
<P>
<P><B>HINES, B.L. - </B>of the Dante Community, died suddenly Friday, January 17, 1997, at his home. He was preceded in death by his wife, Juanita Houser Hines. Funeral arrangements are incomplete and will be announced later by Rose Mortuary Broadway Chapel.
<P>
<P><B>HUMPHREYS, JOHN S. - </B>age 100, of Knoxville, passed away Thursday, January 16, 1997, at East Tennessee Baptist Hospital. He was a member of Central United Methodist Church. Member of Kiwanis Club. Lifetime member of N.E.A. (National Educational Asso.), T.E.A. (Tennessee Education Asso.), E.T.E.A. (East Tennessee Education Asso.). His first principalship was in 1916. He retired as principal of Rule High School after 30 years service. He served 12 years on the Knoxville City School Board having never missed a meeting. Survivors: wife, Florence C. Humphrey; daughter and son-in-law, Helen H. and Felix E. Knight, all of Knoxville; son and daughter-in-law, Dr. Jack B. and Judy Humphreys, Friendsville; grandsons, Don Humphreys, Knoxville, Wesley Humphreys, Ooltewah; five great-grandchildren; special niece, Nancy Cameron; special caregiver and friend, Billie Murrell, both of Knoxville. Funeral service 4 p.m. Sunday, Rose Mortuary Broadway Chapel, Rev. John Ellenburg officiating. Family and friends will leave Rose Mortuary at 10:30 a.m. Monday and proceed to Highland Memorial Cemetery for interment services at 11 a.m. Pallbearers: Reuben Hunter, D.M. Miller, Paul Kelley, Edwin Cloud, Tom Underwood, Tom Harrington, Louis Hofferbert. In lieu of flowers, memorials may be made to Central United Methodist Church, 201 East 3rd. Avenue, Knoxville, Tenn. 37917. The family will receive friends from 2-4 p.m. Sunday at Rose Mortuary Broadway Chapel.
<P>
<P><B>HUSKEY, PAULINE M. - </B>age 70, passed away Thursday, January 16, 1997, at Fort Sanders Parkwest Hospital. She was a member of Friendship Baptist Church; and was preceded in death by husband, Robert D. Huskey. Survivors: daughters and sons-in-law, Kaye and Bill Butcher, Knoxville, Janie and Bob O&#39;Leary, Charlotte, N.C.; granddaughters, Lindsey, Katie, and Megan O&#39;Leary, North Carolina; grandson, Eric Butcher, Knoxville; mother, Leona Eubanks, Knoxville; brother and sister-in-law, Walter and Linda Eubanks; brother-in-law, James Huskey and wife, Wanda; nephews, David and Regina Eubanks, Walter Eubanks, Jr., Scott and Randy Huskey, all of Knoxville. Funeral service 4 p.m. Saturday at Weaver&#39;s Chapel, Rev. Tom Tomblin officiating. Family and friends will meet at 1:45 p.m. Sunday at Edgewood Cemetery for a 2 p.m. graveside service. Pallbearers: David Eubanks, Walter Eubanks, Jr., Eric Butcher, Travis L. Brasfield, Atlee Hammaker, and Roy Wright. The family will receive friends 2-4 p.m. Saturday at Weaver Funeral Home.
<P>
<P><B>IVANOV, DR. KONSTANTIN MILOV -</B>of Knoxville, fomerly of Bulgaria, passed away Friday evening, January 10, 1997, at home. Survived by: sons and daughter-in-law, Stacho C. and Becky Milov of Powell, Oleg Milov of Bulgaria; granddaughters, Jessica and Stephanie Milov, Powell; two great-grandsons in Bulgaria. Memorial service will be Sunday, January 19, 1997, at 8 p.m. Sharon Baptist Church, Dr. James Robertson officiating. The family will receive friends following the service at the church. Arrangements by Gentry-Griffey Chapel.
<P>
<P><B>LAWHORN, SAMUEL T., SR. -</B> age 81, passed away January 16, 1997. He was retired chief of police from University of Tennessee and a veteran of WWII. Preceded in death by: parents, Oscar and Cora Ann Lawhorn; sisters, Jessie Lawhorn and Irene Hatley; stepmother, Dora Prater-Lawhorn; stepbrother, Joe Prater. Survivors: wife, Neta C. Lawhorn; son and daughter-in-law, Sam and Miriam Lawhorn, Jr.; grandchildren, Sam Lawhorn III and wife, Jennifer, Andrew Lawhorn, Matthew Lawhorn; brother, Howard Lawhorn; sisters, Nell McKelvey, Lillian Hall, Karen Sisk; stepbrothers, Tom, Gary, Robert, and Eugene Prater; several nieces and nephews. Funeral service 8 p.m. Saturday, January 18, 1997, Berry Chapel with Rev. David Lovelace and Rev. James Benson officiating. Graveside service and interment 2 p.m. Sunday at Pleasant Forest Cemetery. Pallbearers: Charles Broyles, Ray Hagerman, Bob Gibson, Harold Bledsoe, Col. Tom Whitehead, and Joe Cates. In lieu of flowers, please make memorials to a charity of your choice or Colonial Heights United Methodist Church. The family will receive friends from 6-8 p.m. Saturday at Berry Funeral Home, Chapman Highway.
<P>
<P><B>MANNERS, LUTHER F. JR. - </B>age 66, of Maryville, died January 16, 1997, at the Blount Memorial Hospital in Maryville. He was a member of the New Providence  Presbyterian Church where he had served on the Christian Education Committee, in leadership of the Presbyterian Men, and was a member of the New Providence Softball Team.  He was vice-chairman  of Child and Family Services of Blount County. A Marine Veteran of the Korean Conflict and founder and co-owner of Tennessee Harvest, Inc. He was preceded in death by parents, Luther F. and Elizabeth Barry North Manners; daughter, Cindy; brother, Monroe; brothers-in-law, Jesse Ramsey and Luther Conatser; sister-in-law, Ann North. He is survived by: wife, Jane Loy Manners and daughter, Jenny Anne Manners of Maryville; daughter and son-in-law, Mylisa and Calvin Halcomb of Seymour; son and daughter-in-law, Terry and Debbie Manners; daughter and son-in-law, Vivian and Michael Christian; sister, Martha Conatser; brother and sister-in-law, Raymond and Dimple Manners; sister-in-law, Alice Ewing Custer, all of Lebanon; sisters, Edna Mullins of Tampa, Fla., Cornelia Ramsey of Pleasant Hill; brother, Barry North of Gallatin; several grandchildren and great-grandchildren. Family and friends willmeet at the Ligon & Bobo Funeral Home, 241 West Main Street, Lebanon, at 3:30 p.m. CST Sunday, January 19, 1997, to proceed to the Conatser Cemetery in Lebanon for graveside services to be conducted by Rev. Kevin Frederick. Memorial services will be conducted Tuesday, January 21, 1997, at 4:30 p.m. EST from the New Providence Presbyterian Church in Maryville. Rev. Patrick Willson, Rev. Kevin Frederick, and Randy Adair will officiate. The family will receive friends following the memorial service in Westminster Hall. In lieu of flowers, family requests memorials be made to the Christian Education Dept. or Presbyterian Men of the New Providence Presbyterian Church or to the Child and Family Services Boys Group Home of Blount County. Ligon & Bobo Funeral Home, Lebanon, Tenn., Directors (615) 444-2142.
<P>
<P><B>MODE&#39;, GENNARO MARIO (JERRY) - </B>42, of 504 1/2 Church St., Loudon, died suddenly Friday, January 17, 1997, at St. Mary&#39;s Hospital. Member of First Baptist Church. Presently a student at Roane State College. Survivors: parents, Fred and Aileen Mode&#39;; sister, Brenda Perdue, Las Vegas, Nev.; brother, Darrell Glass, Lenoir City; special friend, Donna Brooks, Knoxville. Funeral service 7:30 p.m. Sunday, Loudon Funeral Home Chapel, Rev. Fred Cook officiating. Graveside services 11 a.m. Monday, Corinth Cemetery. The family will receive friends 6-7:30 p.m. Sunday, Loudon Funeral Home.
<P>
<P><B>MORGAN, COY V. - </B>age 62, passed away Thursday, January 16, 1997. Mr. Morgan retired from Baptist Hospital after 17 years of service. He is survived by: wife, Bonnie Morgan; daughters, Karen Longmire, Kathy Joy; sister, Margie Clevenger; special aunt, Lula Viles; four grandchildren. Funeral services will be Saturday, January 18 at 8 p.m. at Holly Hills South Funeral Home. Rev. Archie Kelley will be officiating. Interment will be Sunday, January 19, at 1 p.m. at Woodlawn Cemetery. The family will receive friends Saturday from 6-8 p.m. Holly Hills South Funeral Home is in charge of arrangements. (573-7300)
<P>
<P><B>MORROW, CHRISTINE J. - </B>age 80, passed away Tuesday, January 14, 1997, at St. Mary&#39;s Hospital. Attended Fellowship Evangelical Free Church and was a former member of Bible Study Fellowship. Preceded in death by husband, John C. Morrow; and brother, Cline Jordan. Survivors: son and daughter-in-law, Stephen and Ann Morrow, Knoxville; daughter, Dale M. Marsh, Titusville, Fla.; sister, Marteal Trulock, Lakeland, Fla.; four grandchildren; 16 great-grandchildren. Memorial service 3 p.m. Sunday at Lynnhurst-Greenwood Chapel, Pastor Gary Peacock officiating. In lieu of flowers, memorial donations may be made to Alzheimer&#39;s Association. Lynnhurst-Greenwood Chapel of Berry Funeral Home, in charge of arrangements.
<P>
<P><B>MURPHY, ADA RAMSEY INGLE - </B>73, of Fountain City, died Friday, January 17, 1997, at her home. Member of Church Street United Methodist Church and was active in the Acheivement Sunday School as well as many other community affairs and projects. She served as first president of the Knoxville Homebuilders Auxiliary and was named in 1976 as the Secretary of the Year by the Knoxville Legal Secretary Assoc. Survivors: husband, Col. Robert M. Murphy; daughter and son-in-law, Janie and David Pollard; son and daughter-in-law, David and Gail Ingle; sister, Mary Carringer, all of Knoxville; grandchildren, Ernie Ingle and his wife, Brooke of Knoxville, Laura Beth Ingle of Knoxville and David Pollard, Jr. of Nashville; also several nieces. Funeral service 2 p.m. Monday in Rose Mortuary Broadway Chapel with Rev. William Fowler officiating. Interment will follow at Lynnhurst Cemetery. Pallbearers: David Pollard, Jr., Ernie Ingle, Richie and Doug Sexton, Edward  Ingle and Eric New. In lieu of flowers, memorials may be made to Church St. United Methodist Church, 900 Henley Street, Knoxville, Tenn. 37902 or American Cancer Society. The family will receive friends 7-9 p.m. Sunday at Rose Mortuary Broadway Chapel.
<P>
<P><B>MURR, NANCY L. - </B>age 86, of Maryville, passed away Friday morning, January 17, 1997, at Blount Memorial Hospital. Preceded in death by husband, Oliver Murr; and son, Kenneth Murr. Survivors: daughter and son-in-law, Helen and Herbert Page of Maryville; son and daughter-in-law, Kenneth Ray and Lucy Murr of South Carolina; daughter-in-law, Johnnie Murr of Maryville; eight grandchildren; and numerous great-grandchildren; sister, Viola Woodall of Maryville; several nieces and nephews. Family and friends will meet at 2:30 p.m. Sunday at Clark&#39;s Grove Cemetery for graveside services and interment, Rev. Russ Maples officiating. Friends may call at their convenience from 10 a.m.-5 p.m. Saturday at Miller Funeral Home or friends may call at their convenience at the family home. Arrangements by Miller Funeral Home, Maryville.
<P>
<P><B>OWENS, HOMER STANLEY - </B>age 76, of Knoxville, passed away 2:10 p.m. Wednesday at Fort Sanders Hospital. He was a member of Friendship Baptist Church and was a veteran of WWII in the U.S. Army. He was preceded in death by his parents, James and Josie Owens; brother, Ottis Owens and a sister, Reba Rudder. He is survived by his wife of 51 years, Margaret Owens of Knoxville; sons, Fred Owens and wife, Patsy Harris Owens of Sevierville, Rick Allen Owens and wife, Dorothy Owens of Blount County, Dennis M. Owens of Albequerque, N.M.; daughter, Cherie Breedwell of Nashville; sisters, Ola Rudder and Myrtle Ford; grandsons, D. Wayne, Dustin and Zachary Owens, Dylan Breedwell; granddaughters, Tiffany Webster and Kendall Owens; two great-grandsons. Family and friends will meet 12:45 p.m. Saturday in the Holly Hills Memorial Park for a 1 p.m. graveside service with Rev. Wayne Gibson officiating. Arrangements by Holly Hills South Funeral Home. (573-7300)
<P>
<P><B>PHILLIPS, ELZIE LOWE - </B>age 98, of Clinton, passed away Thursday, January 16, 1997, at Park West Hospital. She was a member of Antioch Baptist Church and enjoyed flower gardening and flower arranging. She was born in Scott County, Tenn. on December 7, 1898, the daughter of Jacob and Polly Byrd Lowe. Her husband, Grance Phillips, died in 1983. She was also preceded in death by two children, Udeana and Homer; and sisters, Stella Miller, Hazel Raines, Linda Miller, and Faye Coveahouse; and brothers, McKinley, Ramsey, Boyd, and Walter Lowe. She is survived by: daughters, Zelma and husband, Lake Blankenship of Oliver Springs, Christine Teague of Asheville, N.C., Wanda Patterson of Clinton; sons, Chester and wife, Edna of Clinton, Odis and wife, Glenna of Brandon, Fla., and Robert and wife, Dora of Clinton; and sisters, Leona McGhee and Vivian Blankenship; and brothers, Don and Phillip Lowe; she is also survived by 20 grandchildren; 25 great-grandchildren; 10 great-great-grandchildren; and several nieces and nephews. Funeral services 2 p.m. Monday, January 20, 1997, at Holley-Gamble Funeral Home with Rev. Edwin Phillips officiating. Burial will be in Raines Grove Cemetery in Caryville, Tenn. The family will receive friends Sunday from 6-8 p.m. at Holley-Gamble Funeral Home Chapel, in Clinton.
<P>
<P><B>RADER, DONALD GENE - </B>age 62, passed away Wednesday, January 15, 1997, at his home. He was of the Baptist faith and was a painting contractor. Survived by wife, Eleanor Harkleroad Rader; son, Randy Rader; daughter and son-in-law, Pam and Dennis Rousseau; grandson, Brandon Rader; brothers, George Rader of Chattanooga and Allen Rader of Knoxville; brother-in-law, Rodney Harkleroad of Knoxville; and several nieces and nephews. Family and friends will meet 1:15 p.m. Saturday at McCarty Mortuary and proceed to Asbury Cemetery for graveside services at 2 p.m. The Rev. Robert A. Hobbs will officiate. Arrangements by McCarty Mortuary, 4004 Holston Drive.
<P>
<P><B>RADFORD, MRS. BEATRICE ABBOTT - </B>age 72, of McKee Circle, Somerset, Ky., died Thursday, January 16, 1997, at C.L.C.R.H, Somerset, after a short illness. She was born December 28, 1924, in Maryville, Tenn. Preceded in death by parents, Elizabeth Davis Abbott and Ira Abbott; sister Dorothy Ogle. She came to Somerset from Detroit, Mich. in 1968. She was retired manager of Goodie Shack in Burnside. Member of Order of Eastern Star Fidilis No. 545. Held office of Associate Matron. Member of Duke Memorial Baptist Church. Survivors: husband, Oran E. Radford; daughters, Rhonda (and Jerry W.) Shadoan, Owen Ferry Road, Susan Gale Radford, McKee Circle; brothers, Tommy Abbott, Ronnie Abbott, both of Maryville; sisters, Eloise Pickens, Estelle Cable, Janice Green, all of Maryville, Carolyn Galloyn of Sevierville, Tenn.; two grandchildren, Scott Shadoan and Shane Radford. Funeral service Sunday, January 19, 1997, at 2 p.m. in the chapel of New Brothers Funeral Home, Rev. David Morris officiating. Burial Lakeside Memorial Gardens. Friends may call until time for services.
<P> 
<P><B>RANGE, AUSTIN MICHAEL - </B>three month infant son of Wayne Range and April Dotson Range of Lenoir City, passed away suddenly January 15, 1997, at Loudon Hospital. Preceded in death by great-grandfathers, Charles E. Range and W.H. Stout. Survivors: parents; sister, Ashley Allen; grandparents, Arnold and Helen Stout, Charles and Angie Range, Tim Dotson, all of Lenoir City; great-grandparents, Maggie Elkins of Loudon, Barbara Onks of Conroe, Texas, Wanda C. Range and Amy Lee Shubert of Lenoir City; several aunts, great-aunts and great-uncles. Funeral services 11 a.m. Saturday, Click Funeral Home Chapel, Rev. Jackie Bunch officiating. Interment Lake View Cemetery. Pallbearers: Jeremy Johnson and Travis Salyers. The family will receive friends 6-8 p.m. Friday at Click Funeral Home, Lenoir City.
<P>
<P>h3809_0120
<P><B>SAAH, PAULA SUE - </B>age 31, of Knoxville, passed away at 9:27 a.m. Thursday at St. Mary&#39;s Medical Center. She was a member of Holy Ghost Catholic Church. Survived by husband, Adell Saah; sons, John Lee and Adam Adell Saah; father, Paul Wright; mother, Birdie Wright; sister and brother-in-law, Peggy and Joe Greene; brother and sister-in-law, Kenny and Carlene Hill; brother, Bobby Hill; mother and father-in-law, John and Dalal Saah; sister-in-law and brother-in-law, Ruba and Joe Saah; several nieces and nephews; and a host of other relatives and friends. Funeral Mass 10 a.m. Monday at Holy Ghost Catholic Church with Father John Dowling officiating.  Interment will be in Greenwood Cemetery. The family will receive friends 6-9 p.m. Sunday with an 8 p.m. Rosary service at Rose Mortuary Broadway Chapel.
<P>
<P><B>SMITH, MARIAN CECELIA - </B>age 84, of Knoxville, passed away Friday, January 17, 1997, at St. Mary&#39;s Medical Center. She was a member of Holy Ghost Catholic Church, Knoxville. Born July 2, 1912, in Chattanooga, Co., N.Y. Preceded in death by: parents, George and Susan Madaras; sister, Regina Demree. Survivors: daughter and son-in-law, Marian and Clarence Miller, Clinton; grandchildren, Michael R. Beres and wife, Kim, West Mifflin, Pa., Andrew Beres, San Francisco, Calif., Marian Beres, Pittsburg, Pa.; great-granddaughters, Rachel and Clarice; sister, Helen Galvin, Hudson, Fla.; brothers and sisters-in-law, John and Mary Madaras, Florida, George and Ginny Madaras, Elizabeth, Pa. Services will be private. Cox Funeral Home, Lake City, in charge of arrangements.
<P>
<P><B>TARWATER, MILDRED M. - </B>age 76, of Sevierville, died Friday, January 17, 1997, at Sevier Medical Center. She was preceded in death by: her husband, Winfred Tarwater; daughter, Sondra Tarwater; brothers, Bob, Bill, and Carl Matthews. She was a member of Pleasant Hill United Methodist Church. Survivors: daughter, Janie Williams and husband, Johnnie; son, Larry Tarwater and wife, Pat; grandchildren, Lisa Berry, Mike Tarwater, Sandi Ogle, Kevin Williams; great-grandchildren, Derick Tarwater, Lucas and Latrisha Berry; sisters, Fama Flynn, Elizbeth Smelcer, Joy Belle Pickens; brothers, Judd, Elmer, and C.D. Matthews. The family will receive friends 6-7:30 p.m. Saturday in the East Chapel of Atchley Funeral Home, followed by funeral service at 7:30 p.m., Rev. Herman Cate and Rev. Kenneth Stansberry officiating. Interment 2:30 p.m. Sunday in Pleasant Hill Cemetery. Atchley Funeral Home, in charge.
<P>
<P>THACKER, EFFIE PAULINE &#39;&#39;DRIS<B>KILL&#39;&#39; - </B>age 98, a resident of Kingston, passed away Friday, January 17, 1997, at Roane Medical Center, following a long illness. Mrs. Thacker was preceded in death by: her parents, William Newton Driskill and Janie Fritts Driskill; and by her husband, James J. Thacker, Sr. Survivors: stepson, James G. Thacker, Jr. and wife, Marie &#39;&#39;Sissy&#39;&#39; Thacker of Kingston, Tenn.; special nephew, Allen Murray of Knoxville, Tenn.; special niece, Betty Reed and husband, Bob of Kingston, Tenn. Mrs. Thacker was born June 26, 1898 in Roane County. She lived in Kingston for 80 years. She is a retired teacher having taught at the Wheat Community for 22 years, and in the Roane County School System for 30 years. She is a member of Dyllis Baptist Church where she taught Sunday School for many years. Funeral services will be held Saturday at 8 p.m. in the chapel of Sharp Funeral Home with Rev. E.M. Sherwood and Dr. James Cox officiating. Friends may call at the funeral home Saturday, between the hours of 6:30 and 8 p.m. Burial and graveside service will be held Sunday at 2 p.m. at Poplar Springs Cemetery. Sharp Funeral Home is in charge of the arrangements.
<P>
<P><B>TRIPLETT, PAUL C. - </B>73, of Corryton, passed away Friday, January 17, 1997. He was a U.S. Army veteran serving in Europe during World War II. Survived by his wife, Anne; sons, Larry Triplett of South Carolina, Terry Triplett and Russell Dalton of Ohio; daughter, Patricia Dingus of Kingsport; sisters, Ethel Massey of Kingsport and Bonnie Dinkins of Williamsburg, Ky.; brother, Toby Triplett of Kingsport; also several grandchildren and one great-grandson. Funeral service 12 noon Monday in Rose Mortuary Broadway Chapel with Rev. John Lawson officiating. Interment will follow at Eastview Memorial Gardens. Friends may call at their convenience at Rose Mortuary Broadway Chapel.
<P>
<P><B>WEBB, DAVID C. - </B>age 59, of Knoxville, passed away Thursday, January 16, 1997, at St. Mary&#39;s Medical Center. He was a member of Inskip United Methodist Church. Survivors: wife, Jeanne B. Webb; son, David Lawson Webb, both of Knoxville; daughter, Jennifer D. Webb, Oklahoma; sisters, Sandra W. Lloyd, Pennsylvania, Polly W. Long, Knoxville; several nieces and nephews. Funeral service 2 p.m. Sunday, Inskip United Methodist Church, Rev. Lee-Lee Castor and Rev. Paul Castor officiating. Interment Greenwood Cemetery. In lieu of flowers, memorials may be made to Inskip United Methodist Church, 714 Cedar Lane, Knoxville, TN 37912. The family will receive friends from 7-9 p.m. Saturday at Rose Mortuary Broadway Chapel.
<P>
<P><B>WORTHAM, COL. JAMES TILFORD, US ARMY RETIRED - </B>76, of Cecilia, Kentucky, died Friday, January 17, 1997, at Louisville, Ky. Col. Wortham was a native of Stephensburg, Ky. and graduated from White Mills High School and the University of Nebraska, Omaha. He had an extensive and distinguished military career of over 34 years. He retired from the military in 1976 and was a member of Cecilia Baptist Church in Cecilia, Ky. He is survived by: his wife, Frances Cralle Goodman Wortham of Cecilia; two sons, James T. Wortham, Jr. of Framingham, Mass. and Dr. Dale C. Wortham of Knoxville, Tenn.; three grandchildren, Brooke Danielle Wortham, James Keller Wortham, and John Taylor Wortham. The funeral will be Saturday at 7 p.m. at Brown Funeral Home in Elizabethton, Ky. with Rev. Mark Boes officiating. Burial will be in Arlington National Cemetery, Washington, D.C. with immediate family members. Expressions of sympathy may take form of contributions to the donors favorite charity.
