	<td align=left width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Business Briefs</B></font><basefont size=6><!--SUBHEAD--></basefont></FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<h3>Krystal settles wage suits</h3>
<P>
<P>
<P>   CHATTANOOGA -- The Krystal Co., the Chattanooga-based fast-food hamburger chain, announced Friday it has settled the wage claim lawsuits brought against it by current and former employees.
<P>   The settlement, subject to federal court approval, was approximately $13 million.
<P>   Krystal filed Chapter 11 bankruptcy in December 1995 in order to resolve the wage claim litigation brought against it.
<P>   Krystal said it expects its reorganization plan to be approved by the U.S. Bankruptcy Court by the end of the first quarter of 1997 and that shortly thereafter it would emerge from Chapter 11 proceedings.
<P>   Almost 7,000 current and former employees filed lawsuits against the company, claiming they were never paid for overtime they worked, a violation of the Fair Labor Standards Act.
<P>
<P><h3>First American income up</h3>
<P>
<P>   First American Corp. reported fourth quarter 1996 net income of $33.5 million, or $1.13 per share, a 31 percent increase over the fourth quarter of 1995.
<P>    First American earned $121.6 million, or $4.11 per share in 1996, compared to $103.1 million, or $3.64 per share in 1995. The 1996 earnings include the 17 cents per share impact of a one-time assessment many depository institutions were required to pay to increase the Savings Association Insurance Fund. Similarly, the 1995 earnings include a 26 cents per share impact of one-time charges related to its fourth quarter acquisition of Heritage Federal Bancshares.
<P>    First American is a $10.4 billion financial services holding company headquartered in Nashville.
<P>
<P><h3>Mergers affect Union Planters&#39; results</h3>
<P>
<P>
<P>   Union Planters Corp. reported 1996 net earnings of $133.7 million, or $1.92 per fully diluted common share, compared to net earnings of $172.8 million, or $2.64 per share in 1995.  For the fourth quarter of 1996, net earnings were $11.4 million, or 15 cents a share compared to $35.3 million, or 53 cents for the same quarter a year earlier.
<P>    The Memphis-based banking company said results for 1996 were reduced by merger-related and other charges of approximately $66 million after taxes.
<P>   The results reflect the acquisitions of five financial institutions in the fourth quarter, including Memphis-based Leader Financial Corp. Union Planters bought eleven banks in all in 1997, becoming the largest banking company based in Tennessee with $15.2 billion in assets.
<P>
<P><h3>NCBC net income up 17.3%</h3>
<P>
<P>   National Commerce Bancorporation reported net income of $57.5 million for 1996, an increase of 17.3 percent over 1995. Earnings per share were $2.30 in 1996, compared with $1.94 in 1995, an 18.6 percent increase.  Fourth quarter net income was $15.7 million, a 19.4 percent increase over the  same period a year earlier.  Earnings per share for the quarter rose to 63 cents from 52 cents. Consolidated assets totaled $4.2 billion at the end of 1996, up 13.7 percent from the same time a year earlier.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
