<head>
	<title>Runts have their day for West</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 18, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470><BASEFONT SIZE="6">
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Runts have their day for West</B></FONT><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Paul McAfee, Special to The News-Sentinel</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">C</FONT>hris Lindsay would love to add a little size to his roster, but he wasn&#39;t complaining about his mighty mites Friday night.
<P>    The West High basketball coach&#39;s undersized team, known as the Rebel Runts (no starter stands taller than 5-11), used superior quickness to overcome a huge size disadvantage in an 81-69 victory over South-Doyle at West.
<P>    Undaunted by the Cherokees&#39; 6-8 post Tehran Gary, the Rebels (9-6, 6-4) used a full-court pressure game to win the District 4-AAA matchup. South-Doyle (8-8, 6-3) rallied in the fourth quarter to make things interesting, but numerous turnovers against a brutal press ruined the comeback bid.
<P>    &#39;&#39;When you don&#39;t have a guy 6-foot out there, you&#39;ve got to find a way to compensate,&#39;&#39; said Lindsay. &#39;&#39;I don&#39;t know any other way to do it. If you play half-court with them we&#39;re beat by 20.
<P>    &#39;&#39;It&#39;s (full-court pressure) been good to us. The last couple of year&#39;s we weren&#39;t mentally committed to it. These guys realize the logic behind it.&#39;&#39;
<P>    The Rebels harrassed the Cherokees into 11 second-quarter turnovers to take a 38-27 halftime lead. They built the lead to 21 in the the third period and held off the Cherokees in the fourth.
<P>    &#39;&#39;That (turnovers) was the difference in the game,&#39;&#39; said South-Doyle coach Eddie Hodge. &#39;&#39;We&#39;ve got to handle pressure better. We didn&#39;t do it tonight.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Marlon Bussell, who converted many of the South-Doyle turnovers into easy layups, led West with 22 points. He also had five steals and eight assists. Post player Scott Oderson, whose defense against Gary helped earn the win, scored 17. Rickey Davis added 13.
<P>    Gary finished with 21 points. Chris Tate hit four 3-pointers and scored 12 points.
<P>    West was able to stretch its halftime lead with quickness on defense. A 12-6 run to open the quarter gave the Rebels a 50-34 lead at 3:48. A 3-point play by Davis and a tip-in by Bussell pushed the lead to 55-34 at 3:20.
<P>    South-Doyle began its comeback late in the third period. Treys by Blair Dillinger and Tate helped the Cherokees claw back to within 59-46 entering the fourth quarter.
<P>    Two free throws by Johnny Finch midway through the quarter got South-Doyle within seven, but West outscored the Cherokees 13-10 down the stretch.
<P>    &#39;&#39;You can come back against a quick team when they make mistakes,&#39;&#39; said Hodge. &#39;&#39;But you&#39;ve got to score on every possession and we missed some easy ones.&#39;&#39;
<P>    The Rebels fell behind 16-12 after one quarter. Gary scored the first six points for the Cherokees, who jumped to an 8-4 lead.
<P>    But West&#39;s swarming full-court pressure became a problem for South-Doyle in the second period. The Rebels scored the first seven points and took a 19-16 advantage.
<P>     Tate nailed a 3-pointer for South-Doyle, but Adams answered with a trey for West and the Rebels used a 9-3 run totake a 28-23 lead at 3:57.
<P>    Six turnovers in the final 3-1/2 minutes of the half cost South-Doyle dearly.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
