<head>
	<title>Sports Briefs</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 18, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470><BASEFONT SIZE="6">
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Sports Briefs</B></FONT><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<h3>Final Four format set for TSSAA basketball </h3>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>    The 1998 basketball champions from Tennessee high schools will be crowned after a Final Four playoff in Murfreesboro, the governing body for prep sports decided Friday.
<P>    The Tennessee State Secondary Athletic Association&#39;s Board of Control made changes in playoffs for basketball and football and picked six sports to have separate champions for Division 1 and Division 2.
<P>    Division 1 includes all public schools and 22 private schools which choose not to provide students with needs-based financial aid.
<P>    Division 2 is made up of 33 private schools which do offer student financial aid.
<P>    The &#39;&#39;most tremendous change&#39;&#39; will be in the basketball playoffs, said TSSAA executive director <B>Ronnie Carter</B>.
<P>    Following the district and regional basketball playoffs, the regional winners and runners-up will meet in sectional playoffs, with the winners advancing to a Final Four tournament for the title.
<P>    Both boys and girls will play the same weekend. Previously, eight teams in each classification came to the state tournament. Boys played one weekend after the girls&#39; title was decided.
<P>    In football, new brackets were adopted to pair regions during the first two rounds of the playoffs. Teams from Regions 1 and 2 will compete, as will Regions 3 and 4, 5 and 6, and 7 and 8.
<P>    In March, the TSSAA will decide whether to alternate games in the first two rounds between Thursday and Friday nights.
<P>
<P><h3>College basketball</h3>
<P>
<P>* Tusculum College star <B>Susan Starnes </B>hit a career-high 47 points, a school record, in an 84-76 victory against Piedmont in Demorest, Ga., on Thursday night. Starnes made 16-of-28 shots from the floor and 14-of-14 free throws, and also had 20 rebounds. She has made 24 of her last 25 free throws. Tusculum (10-6) plays host to Maryville College today.
<P>* Knoxville College (5-11) will play host to Virginia Intermont (10-7) in a makeup game tonight at 7 at the KC gym.
<P><h3>
<P>Boxing</h3>
<P>
<P>* Welterweight <B>Thomas &#39;&#39;June Bug&#39;&#39; Davis,</B> who hasn&#39;t fought since the 1996 U.S. Olympic Trials, will face <B>Brad Austin </B>of Johnson City in the main event on tonight&#39;s 15-bout amateur card at Golden Gloves Arena. Bell time is 7:30 and admission is $5 (children 16 and under are free).
<P>
<P><h3>Baseball</h3>
<P>
<P>* The New York Mets gave <B>Todd Hundley </B>got a $21 million, four-year contract. His 41 homers last season broke <B>Roy Campanella&#39;s </B>record for home runs in a season by a catcher.
<P>* The Cleveland Indians, hedging their bets on a starting second baseman, signed <B>Robby Thompson </B>to a minor-league contract. Thompson, 34, is a career .257 hitter in 11 seasons with San Francisco.
<P>* <B>Tim Ringler,</B> trainer for the Knoxville Blue Jays in 1988-89, died unexpectedly in the Tampa, Fla., area Monday, the Knoxville Smokies were informed by the parent Toronto Blue Jays.
<P>
<P><h3>Basketball</h3>
<P>
<P>* <B>Richard DeVos,</B> 70, owner of the NBA&#39;s Orlando Magic, is seeking a heart transplant. DeVos has a history of heart problems, including two bypass surgeries. He retired as president of Amway Corp., a direct-sales company with annual sales of $7 billion, after a triple bypass was performed in 1992.
<P>
<P><h3>Hockey</h3>
<P>
<P>* For the first time since they led Canada to victory over the Soviet Union in the 1987 Canada Cup,  <B>Wayne Gretzky </B>and <B>Mario Lemieux </B>are on the same team tonight in the National Hockey League All-Star Game at the San Jose Arena. They&#39;ll play on the Eastern Conference team; Gretzky played his previous 15 all-star games for the West.
<P>
<P><h3>Track</h3>
<P>
<P>* Tennessee&#39;s Lady Vols earned three of the eight spots in the 60-meter dash finals at the Virginia Tech Invitational in Blacksburg, Va. <B>Kelli White</B> ran the distance in 7.55 seconds, followed by<B> Heather Sumpter </B>(7.62) and <B>Anissa Campbell </B>(7.65). <B>Mindy Watkins, Marquita Knight, Janelle Riggs </B>and<B> Kristen Ritter</B> placed second in the distance medley relay (12:22.51 for 2.5 miles), and <B>Kelly Smith</B> was fifth in the 20-pound-weight throw (43-41/4).<B> Kim Smallwood</B> qualified for the 60 hurdles with an 8.81 semifinal run.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
