<title>Knoxville clinics on guard every day</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i>January 17, 1997</i> <p align="left">&nbsp;</p>
		
		<font size=2><strong>For the latest on the bombings in Atlanta, please see AP's The Wire.</strong></p>
		<!--webbot bot="HTMLMarkup" startspan -->
		<p align="center"><a href="http://ww2.knoxnews.com/cgi-bin/gotoap.pl?section=HOME&SLOG=knoxnews"><img src="../../images/logos/wirelogo.gif" width="90" height="36" alt="The Wire" border="0" align="bottom"></a> 
		</p>
		<!--webbot bot="HTMLMarkup" endspan -->
		</td>
        <td width="470"><p align="left"><!--FIRST STORY TEMPLATE--> <font size="6"><b>Knoxville
        clinics on guard every day</b></font><br>
<!--SUBHEAD-->        </p>
        <p><font size="2"><i>By Gina Stafford, News-Sentinel
        staff writer</i></font></p>
        <p><font size="3"><!--dateline--></font><br>
        <font size="5">C</font>aution is a daily watchword for
        workers at Knoxville's two abortion clinics, where
        officials said Thursday's clinic bombing in Atlanta
        didn't cause any local changes. </p>
        <p>''We certainly are on heightened awareness, but
        unfortunately we have learned we have to be and keep
        fully at that level because one never knows,'' said
        Corinne Rovetti, family nurse practitioner at Knoxville
        Center for Reproductive Health, 1547 Clinch Ave. </p>
        <p>''We're very disturbed by this, of course, because we
        condemn domestic terrorism designed to intimidate women
        from seeking legal services they have access to, but we
        have no plans to change our operating schedule.'' </p>
        <p>Both Rovetti and Lisa Thomas, director of Volunteer
        Medical Clinic, 313 Concord St., said their facilities
        have been infrequent targets of bomb threats that never
        resulted in discovery of any explosive devices. For
        years, workers at both facilities haven't accepted or
        opened suspicious-looking packages or those from
        unfamiliar sources. </p>
        <p>While it was a rare occurrence and hasn't happened in
        years, officials said, patients at the clinics have been
        verbally harassed by protesters. Picketers and protests
        continue to be a regular feature at both facilities. </p>
        <p>Thomas said weekends are the choice of Volunteer
        Medical Clinic's picketers. Protesters regularly gather
        outside the Center for Reproductive Health on days that
        clinic sets aside each week for conducting abortions,
        Rovetti said. </p>
        <p>''They're familiar faces by now, and we even dialogue
        at times,'' Rovetti said. ''It's fairly civil most of the
        time, because at this point, we've finally created a
        distant level of respect. </p>
        <p>''We advise patients to expect them and to walk on by.
        As long as they don't breach legal requirements, we can
        put up with them.'' </p>
        <p>A condemnation of antiabortion violence was issued in
        a statement Thursday by C. Fletcher Armstrong, president
        of the Knoxville chapter of Tennessee Right to Life. </p>
        <p>''Our organization exists to promote the most basic
        right in our society -- life itself,'' Armstrong stated.
        ''We oppose violence against our fellow man -- outside
        these clinics as well as the violence that takes place
        inside. </p>
        <p>''We ask people who want to save unborn children to
        join us in using peaceful, legal means to bring an end to
        abortion.'' </p>
        <p>A prayer service and march to the Rachael abortion
        memorial in Lynnhurst Cemetery takes place at 2 p.m. on
        Sunday, Jan. 19, Armstrong said. </p>
        <p>Wednesday, Jan. 22, marks the 24th anniversary of the
        U.S. Supreme Court's 1973 decision legalizing abortion. </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

