<html>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>Woman named to chair House panel is a first</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 17, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>Woman named to chair House panel is a first</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Tom Humphrey, News-Sentinel Nashville bureau</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">N</FONT>ASHVILLE -- In the 200th year that Tennessee&#39;s Legislature has existed, a woman was named Thursday to chair a state House committee for the first time.
<P>   Other legislative committee assignments, while less of a landmark than the title bestowed upon Rep. Brenda Turner, include changes that could impact everything from Knoxville&#39;s voice in state money matters to the status of striped bass in Norris Lake.
<P>   Turner, D-Chattanooga, was named by House Speaker Jimmy Naifeh to head the newly created Children and Family Affairs Committee.
<P>   &#39;&#39;To all the women who came before me and all the women who come behind me, it is truly an honor,&#39;&#39; said Turner, a House member since 1982.
<P>   Turner and Naifeh said no woman has ever chaired a standing state House committee since Tennessee became a state in 1796. The General Assembly is now in its 100th two-year session.
<P>   Turner holds more seniority than any other Democratic woman House member except Rep. Lois DeBerry of Memphis, who serves as House speaker pro tempore.
<P>   There were several other notable changes in the House committee lineup, though the status quo generally prevailed in the Senate. Most of the House changes were due to retirement of veteran legislators who held key posts in the past.
<P>   The House Finance Committee, widely viewed as the most powerful of panels since it oversees taxes and spending, will be chaired by Rep. Matt Kisber, D-Jackson, who succeeds the retired former Rep. John Bragg, D-Murfreesboro.
<P>   From the Knoxville perspective, however, it may be more significant that four representatives from the city got seats on the Finance Committee. They are Democratic Reps. Joe Armstrong, Harry Tindell and Wayne Ritchie along with Republican Rep. H.E. Bittle.
<P>   Armstrong, who last session chaired the Consumer and Employee Affairs Committee, was shifted by Naifeh to chairmanship of the Health and Human Resources Committee for this session. Rep. Ben West, D-Nashville, got the consumer committee chair.
<P>   Armstrong&#39;s new post makes him the point man on legislation involving TennCare and Gov. Don Sundquist&#39;s new Department of Public Health. Armstrong said he now opposes Sundquist&#39;s plan to abolish the Department of Mental Health and put its functions under the new department.
<P>   Another East Tennessean given new power by Naifeh is Rep. Jerry Cross, D-Caryville, named to head the Conservation and Environment Committee. He succeeds the retired former Rep. J.B. Napier, D-Columbia. Cross has gained fame as a leading legislative critic of the Tennessee Wildlife Resources Agency, once engineering an effort that threatened TWRA&#39;s existence.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I&#39;m going to be fair, but I&#39;m going to be sure that they (TWRA officials) do their job and do it right,&#39;&#39; Cross said.
<P>   The focal point of Cross&#39; criticism has been TWRA&#39;s stocking of striped bass, or striper, into Norris Lake. Many fishermen believe the striped bass eat too many smaller game fish. A compromise reached last year calls for a moratorium on striper stocking while a study is conducted.
<P>   Naifeh also has overhauled the House Calender Committee, which must approve all bills before they are scheduled for floor votes. Under the new plan, membership on the Calendar Committee is reduced from 44 to 25.
<P>   Republicans had just three of 44 members under the old setup. They will have four of 25 under the new arrangement, which Naifeh said is intended to &#39;&#39;streamline&#39;&#39; the panel.
<P>   Naifeh stuck by his past tradition of naming only Democrats to committee officer positions, prompting House Minority Leader Steve McDaniel to deliver a speech accusing Naifeh of &#39;&#39;disenfranchising those who dare elect a representative from other than the majority party.&#39;&#39; He said that amounts to about 2 million of 5 million Tennesseans.
<P>   In the Senate, Lt. Gov. John Wilder -- who had Republican help in winning a crucial re-election bid in 1985 -- gives committee officer positions to both Republicans and Democrats.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
