<head>
	<title>Teen pleads innocent to theft charges</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 17, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>Teen pleads innocent to theft charges</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Michelle Williams, Associated Press</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">M</FONT>ANCHESTER, Tenn. -- A California teen pleaded innocent to attempting to bilk her grandparents of their life savings and funneling nearly $23,000 to boyfriends she met on the Internet.
<P>    But in a letter sent to her grandparents after her arrest, Jenivive Sterling said: &#39;&#39;I am so frightened and am so sorry that I ever did this. I hope god (sic) and Jesus can forgive me.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Sterling, 19, was arraigned Tuesday in Coffee County Criminal Court on 17 counts of fraud, forgery and theft charges. Her pretrial motion hearing was set for Feb. 11.
<P>    Sterling was arrested Dec. 30 after a Pennsylvania minister contacted authorities, saying his son had received about $4,000 in checks from Sterling and he feared her grandparents didn&#39;t know about the drafts.
<P>    Dawson and Stella Bearden of Tullahoma never suspected anything.
<P>    &#39;&#39;She was acting like a little sweet thing. We even let her have our bedroom,&#39;&#39; said Stella Bearden, 75. &#39;&#39;Now we know it was all lies.&#39;&#39;
<P>    The drama began in late November when the Beardens received a call from Sterling, their only granddaughter. They had not seen her since her father died of cancer eight years ago, Bearden said.
<P>    Sterling said her mother, Tara Sterling, ordered her out of their home in Culver City, Ca. Bearden, who was estranged from her daughter, said she later learned Jenivive Sterling had also stolen money and credit cards from her mother.
<P>    Although apprehensive about a reunion, the Beardens met their granddaughter at the Nashville airport on Dec. 1 and took her to Tullahoma, about 70 miles southwest.
<P>    Soon after, Charles McBride, an 18-year-old office supply store worker in Chambersburg, Pa., started receiving checks from Sterling, which she said were a combination of gifts from her grandparents and her own money.
<P>    McBride stayed in contact with Sterling while she was in St. Claire Shores, Mich., with another Internet boyfriend. McBride said he and the man were friends through GemStone, a medieval, role-playing fantasy game on the Internet.
<P>    McBride&#39;s father, Donald, a United Church of Christ minister and former journalist, became suspicious. He questioned not only the check amounts but why they were written out of sequence and in inconsistent handwriting on an account that wasn&#39;t hers.
<P>    He contacted authorities. The Beardens&#39; credit union then stopped payment on the checks.
<P>
<P>
<P><font size=2><strong><p>Copyright 1997 by the Associated Press. All Rights Reserved. Unauthorized use is probihited. </p</strong></font>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
