<head>
	<title>Election board expects opening</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 17, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Election board expects opening</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Mayor to hire one member</FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Michael Silence, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">K</FONT>nox County Election Commission member Thomas &#39;&#39;Tank&#39;&#39; Strickland Jr. is expected to be hired by Mayor Victor Ashe, creating another opening on the commission.
<P>   Strickland said he likely will resign from the commission Jan. 25 and start his new job as director of Community Relations on Jan. 27.
<P>   He will replace Kelsey Finch, who recently stepped down from that position.
<P>   Strickland, 43, a Knoxville native and graduate of Austin-East High School and of the University of Tennessee, has been a boxing promoter, consultant and trainer in Knoxville.
<P>   His departure from the commission creates the third opening in a month.
<P>   Last month, Hazel Showalter died and last week, Courtney Pearre announced he was taking the position of legal counsel to Gov. Don Sundquist.
<P>   This is the first opening for Democrats, though. They control the five-member commission because their party is the majority in the state House.
<P>   Since Strickland is a Democrat, the Knox County Democratic legislative delegation will have the say in his replacement, just as the Republicans recently did in the replacements for Pearre and Showalter.
<P>   On Tuesday, the state Election Commission appointed as new GOP members for the Knox County Election Commission lawyers Mike McClamroch and Steve Roth.
<P>   This was after the seven-member GOP delegation in secret ballots nominated the two from a list of 16 candidates.
<P>   Strickland said he&#39;s not heard any names surface as a possible replacement but anticipates a number of people being interested.
<P>   The foul-up in last year&#39;s early voting on unification sparked more interest in the GOP positions, and Strickland said he anticipates the same interest from Democrats.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
