<head>
	<title>Vintage auto museum/school proposed for Pigeon Forge</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 17, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Vintage auto museum/school proposed for Pigeon Forge</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Eleni Chamis, News-Sentinel business writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">A</FONT> $34 million, 220,000-square-foot museum for vintage automobiles and school of restoration is being proposed for Pigeon Forge.
<P>   Called the Heritage Automotive Museum and Center for Learning, the entire structure would be under glass. Developers say it would be a strong family attraction.
<P>   A partner in the development, Jeff Kluss, a graduate of Bearden High School and the University of Tennessee who now lives in Nashville, estimated annual revenues would reach $35 million, with an economic impact of $140 million.
<P>   A 39,000-square-foot center for learning will offer an apprenticeship program and hopes to train 160 students a year in restoration and customization. Museum displays will be devoted to racing, and domestic and foreign-made antique and collectible cars.
<P>   The display area will showcase about 170 cars at a time. Many of them will be set in vignettes, or period exhibits with other items and memorabilia from that particular era.
<P>   The 59,000-square-foot restoration area will have a public viewing area.
<P>   &#39;&#39;This will draw people from all over,&#39;&#39; said Kluss. &#39;&#39;What we&#39;re looking to bring into Pigeon Forge is diversity. This is not a retail outlet, not a theater, not a restaurant; it&#39;s something that will enhance everybody&#39;s business.&#39;&#39;
<P>   The development group has an option on a 48.8-acre tract on Sugar Hollow Road, which would be visible from the Parkway.
<P>   The complex would hire the equivalent of 120 to 130 full-time employees, Kluss said.
<P>   Kluss&#39; partners in the project are Ted Douthitt, who has a restoration shop in Duluth, Ga., and Rod Wortham, who owns AMC Marketing in St. Louis.
<P>   A preliminary plan was presented to the Pigeon Forge City Commission earlier this week. 
<P>   &#39;&#39;I think the city is definitely interested in working with them,&#39;&#39; said John Jagger, director of the Pigeon Forge Tourism Development Agency. 
<P>   The group asked the city to consider several financing options, including the authorization of industrial revenue bonds, or the setting up of an educational trust, through which corporations could pay for students&#39; tuition.
<P>   
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

