<head>
	<title>Phone scam: Calls promise bogus sweepstakes wins</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 17, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Phone scam: Calls promise bogus sweepstakes wins</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Brian Courtney, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">T</FONT>hey say there&#39;s a sucker born every minute. 
<P>   Fortunately, David Galbraith wasn&#39;t born yesterday, and he wasn&#39;t taken in by a telephone sweepstakes scam being worked in the Knoxville area.
<P>   Last week, Galbraith received a call from a man who informed him that he was one of the lucky &#39;&#39;bonus sweepstakes&#39;&#39; winners from Publisher&#39;s Clearing House. 
<P>   His prize: $75,000.
<P>   The catch: he had to pay a 3 percent gift tax or $2,200 before his check would be delivered.
<P>   &#39;&#39;(The bogus representative) said my name was a sure winner and that the delivery men had to deliver the certified check that day,&#39;&#39; Galbraith said, recalling the conversation that lasted more than 30 minutes. &#39;&#39;He said the gift tax money had to be paid up front.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Galbraith said the man instructed him to go to the nearest Kroger store and send the money via Western Union to his area &#39;&#39;CPA representative&#39;&#39; who would handle tax payment.
<P>    When Galbraith told the man he didn&#39;t have the &#39;&#39;foggiest notion&#39;&#39; who his &#39;&#39;CPA representative&#39;&#39; was, the man paused and then informed him it was a woman located at International Boulevard in Atlanta.
<P>   For authenticity purposes, Galbraith said the man also gave him a code number that was to be shown to the deliverers of his check for $75,000.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I wasn&#39;t believing a word of it,&#39;&#39; he said.
<P>   Skeptical, Galbraith asked a series of probing questions.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Just what did I do to win this money?&#39;&#39;
<P>   The man&#39;s reply: &#39;&#39;It was a random computer drawing.&#39;&#39;
<P>   &#39;&#39;Who did you say you&#39;re with?&#39;&#39;
<P>   &#39;&#39;Publisher&#39;s Clearing House,&#39;&#39; the caller said. 
<P>   &#39;&#39;Why can&#39;t you just take the tax money off the top and cut a new check?&#39;&#39;
<P>   Pause.
<P>   &#39;&#39;For someone who won all this money, you don&#39;t sound too enthusiastic.&#39;&#39; 
<P>   Galbraith said he decided to play along and told the man he would send the money. At that time, Galbraith said the man abruptly ended the conversation, telling him he had to go to a meeting.
<P>   Galbraith immediately alerted the Knox County Sheriff&#39;s Department, which referred him to the FBI. Galbraith said a local FBI agent took down a report of the incident but informed him the scam was out of his jurisdiction. The agent told Galbraith the information would be forwarded to Atlanta.
<P>   The bogus representative called Galbraith a short time later asking why he hadn&#39;t sent the money.
<P>   Galbraith told the man he couldn&#39;t accept the money under the current circumstances. With that, the man hung up, he said.
<P>   Richard Voiles, fraud and forgery investigator for the Knoxville Police Department, said he&#39;s received a half dozen calls about the sweepstakes scam last week.
<P>   &#39;&#39;That&#39;s just the one&#39;s that we&#39;re aware of,&#39;&#39; he said. &#39;&#39;All we have to go by is what people report to us.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Voiles said none of the people he has talked to so far have sent money.
<P>    &#39;&#39;I&#39;ve been a firm believer in the rule that says there&#39;s no such thing as a free lunch,&#39;&#39; said Jeff Blevins, Knox County&#39;s assistant district attorney general in charge of the White Collar Crime Unit. &#39;&#39;If it sounds to good to be true, it probably is.&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

	<P><center><font size=2>Return to </font><a href="/"><font size=2>Main</font></a><font size=2>. Copyright &#169; 1996 The Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size=2>webmaster</font></a><font size=2>.</font></center></p>
