<head>
	<title>Frist in Israel promoting talks with Palestine</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 17, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Frist in Israel promoting talks with Palestine</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Richard Powelson, News-Sentinel Washington bureau</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">W</FONT>ASHINGTON -- U.S. Sen. <B>Bill Frist,</B> R-Tenn., in his second overseas trip since taking office in 1995, is visiting officials in Israel this week on progress toward peace talks with the Palestinians.
<P>   A new member of the Foreign Relations Committee, Frist began meetings with Israeli officials Monday, including <B>Dore Gold,</B> senior policy adviser to the prime minister. He also plans to meet with former Prime Minister <B>Shimon Peres</B>. Frist plans to return to the United States this weekend, his staff said.
<P>   Frist&#39;s last overseas trip was to Southeast Asia in November to work on economic development issues.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>   Rep. <B>John J. Duncan Jr.</B> of Knoxville has returned from his first foreign business trip after eight years in Congress, flying to four republics of the former Yugoslavia -- Serbia, Bosnia, Croatia and Montenegro -- to check on conditions before a vote on whether to send perhaps $2 billion more there in U.S. aid.
<P>   Duncan&#39;s trip with three other House members did not involve U.S. taxpayers&#39; funds. It was paid for by a private group, the National Security Caucus Foundation.
<P>   The seven-day trip ended Wednesday. Duncan&#39;s office did not announce the trip until after he left because it was not clear if his schedule would allow it, aide <B>Judy Whitbred </B>said.
<P>   Duncan generally opposes foreign aid, maintaining the United States cannot afford it. He has opposed sending U.S. troops to the former Yugoslavia because he does not believe there is a vital U.S. interest at stake or a threat to U.S. national security. He said in a statement that with U.S. troops in this part of the world for an indefinite period, he should learn as much as possible about the situation there.
<P>   The private group invited all 535 House and Senate members to make the trip at the foundation&#39;s expense, according to a foundation employee, <B>Jim Dickey</B>. Four agreed to make the current trip, he said, including Reps. <B>Bruce Vento,</B> D-Minn., <B>Rick Boucher,</B> D-Va., and <B>Mark Sanford,</B> R-S.C.
<P>   Dickey, asked why the foundation was paying for members to visit the former Yugoslavia, said: &#39;&#39;It&#39;s our opinion that the better informed members of Congress are about foreign policy issues, the better off the country is.&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>   Duncan has hired a former advance man from the Bob Dole presidential campaign as his news media liaison.
<P>   <B>David Balloff,</B> who also was part owner of the former Balloff clothing stores in Knoxville, joined Duncan&#39;s Washington staff a couple days ago. Before joining the Dole campaign last summer, he worked for a year as a broker for Morgan Keegan in Knoxville, he said.
<P>   Balloff said he earlier did advance work also for Vice President <B>George Bush </B>and later for President Bush&#39;s re-election campaign.
<P>   Whitbred said Balloff was hired because of his experience in dealing with the news media during his advance work.
<P>   He replaces Dub Maines, who is leaving Duncan&#39;s staff for another job, Whitbred said.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>   Sen. <B>Fred Thompson</B>, R-Tenn.,<B> </B>has chosen <B>J. Mark Tipps,</B> the chief of staff to Frist, to be one of three senior counsels looking into alleged improprieties by the Democratic National Committee in fund-raising last year.
<P>   Thompson, new chairman of the Governmental Affairs Committee, named another Tennessee attorney, <B>Harry &#39;&#39;Sandy&#39;&#39; Mattice</B> of Chattanooga, as another senior counsel.
<P>   Both Tipps and Mattice are graduates of the University of Tennessee College of Law.
<P>   Tipps earlier worked nine years at Bass Berry and Sims law firm in Nashville in the trial section, focusing on commercial and corporate litigation. Thompson is expected to start holding committee hearings into the Democrats&#39; fund-raising activities soon.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

	<P><center><font size=2>Return to </font><a href="/"><font size=2>Main</font></a><font size=2>. Copyright &#169; 1996 The Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size=2>webmaster</font></a><font size=2>.</font></center></p>
</body>
