<head>
	<title>Reintroduced river otter population is thriving in Middle, East Tennessee</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 17, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Reintroduced river otter population is thriving in Middle, East Tennessee</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Marti Davis, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><P>
<P>   Three years after the state and the National Park Service reintroduced river otters into East Tennessee, the playful carnivores appear to be thriving.
<P>    That&#39;s according to Ed Warr of the Tennessee Wildlife Resources Agency, who spoke Thursday at the Wilderness Wildlife Week in Pigeon Forge.
<P>    Some 400 otters -- purchased from a professional river otter supplier in Louisiana -- were released into major river and stream systems in Middle and East Tennessee, said Warr.
<P>    The elusive otters are hard to count, but sightings of their droppings and tracks indicate they&#39;re still around in substantial numbers.
<P>    &#39;&#39;We&#39;ve had a few road kills, but other than that, they seem to be doing quite well,&#39;&#39; he said.
<P>    A few fishing docks have complained the otters get into their minnow stores for a fast-food feast. The state also has some complaints from fishermen who think the quick otters compete for trout. Actually, Warr said the animals feed mainly on other slower fish, rodents and smaller mammals, such as weasels.
<P>    River otters are slow to multiply because pregnancy can be delayed as much as a year before the fertilized ovum is implanted in the uterine wall.  
<P>    Bear and other mammals also delay pregnancy after mating but none for as long as 12 months, said Warr.
<P>    River otters were declared a threatened species in Middle and East Tennessee during the 1950s.
<P>    Efforts to restore them to rivers and streams began during the 1980s but were mostly unsuccessful.
<P>   The state and park finally chose to purchase the otters at a cost of $400 each from the Louisiana dealer.
<P>    About 400 otters were released in Tennessee outside the park. The national park has released 137 more since 1989, said park spokesman Bob Miller.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

	<P><center><font size=2>Return to </font><a href="/"><font size=2>Main</font></a><font size=2>. Copyright &#169; 1996 The Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size=2>webmaster</font></a><font size=2>.</font></center></p>
