<head>
	<title>Newest member of state appeals court is sworn in</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 17, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Newest member of state appeals court is sworn in</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Governor: Witt will be `exemplary jurist'</FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Stan DeLozier, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">M</FONT>ADISONVILLE -- You might say the newest member of the Tennessee Court of Criminal Appeals was born for the job.
<P>    James Curwood Witt Jr., 48, the fourth generation of the Monroe County family to wear a judicial robe, was given the oath of office Thursday by his father, retired Circuit Court Judge James C. Witt Sr. 
<P>    &#39;&#39;I&#39;m glad to get around to it (administering the oath),&#39;&#39; the elder Witt said. &#39;&#39;It&#39;s been on my docket for 48 years.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Gov. Don Sundquist selected Witt over Paula Voss, an assistant public defender in Knoxville, and Thomas Wright, a federal public defender in Greeneville.
<P>    &#39;&#39;I chose him because I thought he was the right person,&#39;&#39; Sundquist said before Thursday&#39;s ceremony. &#39;&#39;The most serious thing I do as governor is to appoint members of the judiciary. Curwood Witt will be an exemplary jurist.&#39;&#39;
<P>    The new judge&#39;s great-grandfather, Bascom Witt, was the county judge in the 1920s. His grandfather, Beecher Witt, was district attorney general from 1926 to 1958, and his father was a Circuit Court judge from 1958 to 1982.
<P>    Witt said another notable lawyer from Monroe County, the late Ray Jenkins, influenced him to enter the profession.
<P>    &#39;&#39;As district attorney general, my grandfather was one of the best-known courtroom attractions around,&#39;&#39; he said. &#39;&#39;He was very colorful and theatrical in some ways. When he and Ray Jenkins opposed each other, they say it was something to see.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Witt says he has no specific recollection of the two adversaries, since he was a small child at the time, yet it was some years later that he was influenced by Jenkins during a trial in Loudon.
<P>    &#39;&#39;He defended a woman who was charged with killing her husband&#39;s paramour,&#39;&#39; he recalled. &#39;&#39;She was charged with first-degree murder, but she was convicted of manslaughter.
<P>    &#39;&#39;I was only 13 or 14 at the time, but Ray Jenkins was spellbinding. That was the thing that helped galvanize me into going to law school.&#39;&#39;
<P>    In presiding over Thursday&#39;s ceremony, James Witt&#39;s pithy remarks nearly stole the show.
<P>    &#39;&#39;In this town, I doubt that 95 percent of the people have ever seen an appellant judge,&#39;&#39; he said. &#39;&#39;In fact I&#39;ve always been a little scared of the appellant court. I&#39;ll have to admit that I plowed my own furrow sometimes with my own mule. Nowadays, they&#39;ll make you plow it over and use their mule.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Curwood Witt is one of three criminal appellant judges whose seats were authorized last year by the Legislature.
<P>    In 1998, Witt will be up for re-election in a yes-no vote. If rejected, a new judge would be appointed by the governor.
<P>    Witt said the concern is &#39;&#39;accountability. I don&#39;t have a problem with accountability. However, I do not feel a partisan election would go very far in enhancing the integrity and quality of the judiciary.&#39;&#39;
<P>    As for the death penalty, Witt simply said, &#39;&#39;I don&#39;t see any choice about it. We have a death penalty. It&#39;s the law in Tennessee.&#39;&#39;  
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
