<title>Kroger buys Chilhowee Pharmacy</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<p><a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif"
alt="Knoxville News-Sentinel Online -- Business News" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i>January 17, 1997</i> </td>
        <td width="470"><font size="6"><b>Kroger buys Chilhowee
        Pharmacy</b></font><font size="5"><br>
        Store will continue delivery of drugs, add groceries,
        videos</font><p><font size="2"><i>By Amy Geisel,
        News-Sentinel business editor</i></font></p>
        <p><br>
        </p>
        <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"
        width="250">
            <tr>
                <td><a href="../images/pharmacyco.jpg"><img
                src="../images/pharmacyco.jpg"
                alt="Chilhowee Pharmacy" border="0" width="250"
                height="168"></a><br>
                <img src="../../images/v3/credits/COcredit.gif"
                alt="Photo by Clay Owen, News-Sentinel Staff"
                width="144" height="21"><br>
                <font size="2"><strong>Hogan Harrison, left,
                owner of the former Chilhowee Pharmacy which is
                merging into the new Kroger store on Asheville
                Highway, works with Kroger pharmacist Natalie
                Miller to input his customer list into the
                computer in the new facility Thursday.</strong></font></td>
            </tr>
        </table>
        <p><font size="5">K</font>roger has purchased the
        50-year-old Chilhowee Pharmacy, but will continue to
        deliver prescriptions -- in addition to groceries, videos
        and flowers -- from its new East Knoxville store. </p>
        <p>Currently Kroger delivers prescription drugs from its
        Marketplace and Farragut stores. If things bode well at
        the East Knoxville store, the delivery concept may be
        expanded to other Knoxville stores as well, said Hunter
        MacWilliams, area manager for Krogers. </p>
        <p>Kroger has such programs in place in the Cincinnati
        area and in the Western United States, MacWilliams said.
        ''This is a test, and I am confident that in 1997 we can
        expand it into some other areas where we operate,'' he
        added. </p>
        <p>The Chilhowee Pharmacy, owned for the last 15 years by
        Hogan and Sally Harrison, will close its Asheville
        Highway store at 7 p.m. today and reopen at the new
        Kroger store at 7 a.m. Sunday. The new Kroger is located
        across the street from its existing 21-year-old store,
        which will close at 8 p.m. Saturday. The Harrisons and
        three of their employees will join the Kroger pharmacy
        staff, said Sally Harrison. Three of their employees
        recently retired. </p>
        <p>The delivery service begins Monday, and will be
        available Monday through Friday. Deliveries will be
        offered within a 3-mile radius of the store. No minimums
        exist for pharmacy deliveries, but other items must total
        at least $35. Orders delivered by 1 p.m. will be
        delivered the same day, and orders will only be delivered
        until dark. </p>
        <p>The 60,000-square-foot store is twice the size of the
        existing store, and the staff will be doubled to about
        210 full- and part-time employees, said Ken Slagle, store
        manager. </p>
        <p>In addition to the pharmacy and delivery service,
        other new amenities include an NBC Bank; video shop;
        16-foot self-service salad bar; a full-scale baby center,
        including clothes; and a full-scale pet center. </p>
        <p>Grand opening activities on Sunday include a visit
        from residents of the Knoxville Zoo from 2:30 p.m. to 4
        p.m. and an autograph session with University of
        Tennessee cheerleaders from 5 p.m. to 6 p.m. </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

<hr size="5">

