<title>State business mission to Israel 'a bargain'</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<p><a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif"
alt="Knoxville News-Sentinel Online -- Business News" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i>January 17, 1997</i> </td>
        <td width="470"><font size="6"><b>State business mission
        to Israel 'a bargain'</b></font><font size="5"><br>
        Gov. Sundquist led group of 72</font><p><font size="2"><i>By
        Jerry Dean, News-Sentinel business writer</i></font></p>
        <p><br>
        </p>
        <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"
        width="175">
            <tr>
                <td><a href="../images/sttripmc.jpg"><img
                src="../images/sttripmc.jpg"
                alt="Annette Winston" border="0" width="175"
                height="291"></a><br>
                <img src="../../images/v3/credits/MCcredit.gif"
                alt="Photo by J. Miles Cary, News-Sentinel Staff"
                width="144" height="21"><br>
                <font size="2"><strong>Annette Winston, a Vice
                President with First Vintage Bank-Tennessee in
                Knoxville, has just returned from a six-day trip
                to Israel as part of Gov. Sundquist's business
                trade mission there.</strong></font></td>
            </tr>
        </table>
        <p><font size="5">T</font>ennessee got ''a real bargain''
        in a 72-member delegation's recent business mission to
        Israel, according to delegation member Annette E.
        Winston. </p>
        <p>Winston is vice president for commercial lending and
        private banking with Knoxville's First Vantage
        Bank-Tennessee. </p>
        <p>The state, she said, spent less than $10,000 in
        financing the six-day trip last week by Gov. Don
        Sundquist, state Commissioner Bill Dunavant and others.
        Hosting the visit were the Israel-America Chamber of
        Commerce and the Israel Export Institute. </p>
        <p>''This was the largest, most diverse group ever there
        on a trade mission from the U.S.,'' Winston said. ''Nine
        Tennessee companies attended meetings with 26 Israeli
        companies.'' The Israeli government, she said, paid half
        Sundquist's expenses and many other costs of the visit.
        Individuals on the trip paid about $4,000 each to
        participate. </p>
        <p>Winston who, like half the participants, is Jewish,
        said her own involvement resulted from her 1996
        appointment to the Tennessee-Israel Cooperation Committee
        and a recommendation by the Knoxville Jewish Federation. </p>
        <p>Others from the area in the delegation were Dr. Gilya
        Schmidt, a UT religious studies professor; Dr. Miriam L.
        Weinstein, a physician and associate pediatrics professor
        at the UT Medical Center; Maribel Koella of Maryville, a
        partner in Collins, Sharp &amp; Koella Inc.; Dr. Linda
        Maxson, UT associate vice chancellor for academic
        affairs, and Dr. Marcia Katz, a UT physics professor. </p>
        <p>Also, Sidney A. Blalock of Charles Blalock &amp; Sons
        Inc., Sevierville; Carol Kiener of Johnson City Schools:
        Shannon W. Greene, vice president of ABG Caulking &amp;
        Waterproofing, Morristown; Dr. Harry J. Reynolds,
        Chattanooga Public Schools superintendent, and Claire E.
        Binder, co-chairman of the Arts Culture and Education
        Committee in Chattanooga. </p>
        <p>The delegation was divided into groups concerned with
        arts and culture, education, Israel: Past and Present,
        and business-economic development, which included
        Winston. She said most of the session consisted of tours
        of manufacturing firms and business meetings. </p>
        <p>Winston's ''business'' group met with such Israeli
        industrial leaders as Stef Wertheimer, board chairman of
        the ISCAR Group of Cos., world leaders in metal cutting
        technology. The firm is based in the Tefen Industrial
        Area of Galilee where a lucrative business incubator for
        entrepreneurial businesses is making major inroads in
        Israeli economic development. Tefen has spawned 52 new
        companies in the last decade. </p>
        <p>The Tennesseans also visited Electric Fuel Ltd. in
        Jerusalem, a 6-year-old corporation marketing a zinc-air
        battery technology that powers vehicles with rechargeable
        electric motors. </p>
        <p>Also visited were Perio Products, a dental and
        pharmaceutical producer that markets a polymer chip
        worldwide to help deter periodontal disease, and Elscint
        Corp., which produces equipment for magnetic resonance
        imaging already used by Vanderbilt University's Medical
        Center. </p>
        <p>Tennessee exports to Israel totaled $15.2 million for
        the first six months of 1996, up 9 percent from the
        comparable 1995 period. Nearly half the 1995 exports to
        Israel were paper products. </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

