<html>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>Business Briefs</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper Business News">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif" alt="Knoxville News-Sentinel Online -- Business News" align=bottom border=0 width=595 height=176></a><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td align=left valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 17, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Business Briefs</B></font><basefont size=6><!--SUBHEAD--></basefont></FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<h3>Columbia/HCA to purchase Value Health for $1.3 billion</h3>
<P>
<P>
<P>    Columbia/HCA Healthcare Corp. said it will buy managed care company Value Health Inc. for $1.3 billion, canceling Value Health&#39;s plans to spin off its lucrative pharmacy benefit management business to shareholders.
<P>    The business, ValueRx, manages prescription benefit plans for big companies and also distributes prescriptions by mail. It accounted for about $1.5 billion of Value Health&#39;s $1.9 billion in revenue last year.
<P>    Columbia/HCA plans to pay about 35 million of its shares to buy all the shares of Value Health, valuing those shares at about $23.35, a 15 percent premium.
<P>    The Nashville-based hospital chain has been gobbling up hospitals during its rapid expansion over the past three years. Last year alone, Columbia/HCA has acquired or formed joint ventures to operate 28 hospitals with annual revenue of about $1.3 billion. It now operates 344 hospitals and 368 other facilities in 37 states.
<P>
<P><h3>Sevier plant to stay open</h3>
<P>
<P>   Dan River Inc. said Thursday that it has contractually agreed to keep New Cherokee Corp.&#39;s manufacturing facilities, including the Sevierville plant, open for at least one year.
<P>  The Danville, Va.-based company announced Monday it intended to buy New Cherokee, which employs about 600 in Sevierville and another 600 in Rutherford County, N.C., where it&#39;s headquartered.
<P>   At the time of the announcement, Dan River officials declined to say whether the plants would remain open, saying an evaluation would take place &#39;&#39;to identify ways to maximize production efficiencies and improve our ability to serve our customers.&#39;&#39;
<P>   The sale of employee-owned New Cherokee is contingent on shareholders&#39; approval. A special meeting has tentatively been scheduled for Feb. 3.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

