<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>Mock, Mast join in hunt for wins</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 17, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470><BASEFONT SIZE="6">
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Mock, Mast join in hunt for wins</B></FONT><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Bill Luther, News-Sentinel sportswriter</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">M</FONT>OORESVILLE, N.C. -- When Butch Mock and Rick Mast agreed on a contract to go Winston Cup racing they had one thing in common -- long winless streaks.
<P>    Mock has fielded teams since 1978. The late Neil Bonnett gave Mock his last victory in 1988. Mast made his Cup debut the same year and hopes to end a 216-race drought.
<P>    Mock is excited to have Mast at the wheel.
<P>    &#39;&#39;This is not a new team and Rick is not a rookie and we didn&#39;t lose any team members during the offseason,&#39;&#39; he said. &#39;&#39;We can go out and win some races. This team&#39;s spirit is like the (Charlotte) Panthers. If we keep it together we&#39;ll be in the top 10 in points. If we finish there we&#39;ll be up on that stage (at the New York banquet in December).&#39;&#39;
<P>    Mast knows Cup success doesn&#39;t come easily. Earning a berth in the race-day lineup is the initial move to success.
<P>    &#39;&#39;That&#39;s the bottom line. You have 40 or more drivers out there every week wanting to get into the race,&#39;&#39; Mast said. &#39;&#39;It&#39;s neat (if you make it). You get a fuzzy feeling for about 30 seconds, then it&#39;s back to where you started.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Mast hasn&#39;t come up short on race day in the last six years.
<P>    &#39;&#39;You have to keep things even keel. There have been races I could have won or should have won,&#39;&#39; he said in regard to the string of 181 starts with owner Richard Jackson.
<P>    When asked if he was interested in driving Mock&#39;s Ford, Mast knew the cars ran well, but he knew little about the owner.
<P>    &#39;&#39;When we passed from time to time I&#39;d say, &#39;Hi,&#39; &#39;&#39; Mast said. &#39;&#39;When we did get together we didn&#39;t talk finances . . . about paying me more than other guys (owners). That&#39;s one example of how important it was to be with this team. There are a lot of things to look at as a driver, but I felt I had a better chance with the Remington (Mock) team.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Mock&#39;s corporate sponsorship doesn&#39;t match many of the Cup teams.
<P>    &#39;&#39;We&#39;re trying to share things,&#39;&#39; he said. &#39;&#39;It&#39;s important to find a way to share the wind tunnel tests because they costs so much. It makes for good business in this sport if you&#39;re going to keep up. It&#39;s a concept which would cut costs in half. If you&#39;re not careful you can wind up bankrupt.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Mast&#39;s theory on Cup racing is to get there first, then learn to win.
<P>    &#39;&#39;If you haven&#39;t won, you didn&#39;t get the job done on the track,&#39;&#39; he said. &#39;&#39;There have been times when I&#39;d think back and ask why we didn&#39;t win last week. Winning can become a habit,&#39;&#39; he said, &#39;&#39;and the same basics have been around for 20 years. Every little thing means so much . . . everything is so close.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Mock agreed.
<P>    &#39;&#39;There&#39;s not a bad team out there.&#39;&#39; he said. &#39;&#39;You have to run well to finish 34th, just to be here. It&#39;s gotten to the time that if you finish 30th in points it is a big deal.
<P> 
<P>   &#39;&#39;When I looked for Rick I knew I was getting a good qualifier. Those little things make the difference.&#39;&#39;
<P>  
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
