<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>Fishing Report</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 17, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470><BASEFONT SIZE="6">
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Fishing Report</B></FONT><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<B>CHEROKEE:</B> This note applies everywhere: If you&#39;re fishing this weekend you need another hobby and/or a good psychiatrist. Cherokee is muddy and water levels are fluctuating day-to-day. With that in mind, pick a fish and chances are it&#39;s hitting &#39;&#39;fair.&#39;&#39; Bass are fair near the bank and in creek beds 3-12  feet deep. Crankbaits and Carolina rigs are producing a few fish. Some are  being caught in deeper water over humps, but they are not as consistent. Smallmouth are fair around bluffs and gravel banks. Crappie are fair in creek beds 10-20 feet deep. Plain minnows are the best bait, but fish are scattered. Trollers are catching a few crappie on tube jigs and jigs tipped with minnows off points. Striper fishing is fair in the main river channel from the dam to the steam plant. Live shad are working best fished shallow early, deep late.
<P><B>
<P>DOUGLAS:</B> Crappie continue to be good, but the weather and good sense has chased most fishermen indoors. Good catches are being reported from Nina Creek to Muddy Creek, with trollers doing about as well as still fishermen. Best action is coming in 15-20 feet on jigs, jigs tipped with minnows and, for still fishermen, just plain minnows. Depth/fish finders can make up for a lot of guesswork for deep fish. Bass are improving, but that was before the most recent front moved in. Muddy Creek has been providing some good fishing, but action is about the same over most of the lake. Sauger fishing is good in the Leadvale area and above Swann&#39;s Bridge. Minnows, jigs and crankbaits are  catching sauger. Most fish are small, but keepers are not rare.
<P><B>
<P>FORT LOUDOUN/TELLICO:</B> Bass on Fort Loudoun are still the best game in town.  Murky water is making things good for jig fishermen just about anywhere on the lake. Like last week, most fish are coming off the main channel structure on Fort Loudoun. High, muddy water is making the going tough in creeks. Sauger fishing has been excellent below the dam, but may have tailed off some in the past week. Keeper-sized sauger have been caught from the dam to just below the A-frame hole on plain minnows and large hair jigs tipped with minnows. Striper fishing below the dam is inconsistent. Crappie are fair to good on either lake, but that was before more rain and snow. Bat Creek on Tellico was especially good in 6-12 feet. Some crappie have been caught by trollers off points. Sauger and walleye have been good below Chilhowee Dam on large jigs, minnows and crankbaits.
<P>
<P><B>MELTON HILL:</B> Duck hunters have been common on the lake; fishermen have been scarce. Best action is in the warm water discharge at Bullrun Steam Plant. Most fishermen are going after stripers with live shad, but some white bass, crappie and even a few bass are showing up on crankbaits, jigs and smaller live baits. Best fishing has been early morning, but action has been consistent through the day. Most creeks are muddy, high and running fast. Some bass are being caught on the lower end of the lake, but not too many fishermen are going after them. Sauger and stripers are fair to good in  tailwaters, best when at least one generator is running. Live shad or large jigs are working best on the stripers, minnows and small yellow or blue jigs on sauger.
<P><B>
<P>NORRIS:</B> The lake is clear to lightly stained, with creeks muddy. Surface temperatures are 44-48 degrees. Smallmouth continue to be very good with just plain minnows and a split shot. The best fishing is 20-25 feet deep off steep, boulder banks on the main channel. Stump beds are also good. This past week 3- and 4-pound fish continue to be common. Stripers are also good from Point 12 to Point 10 on the Powell side, near Lost Creek, the Loyston Sea near Woodduck Island and from Big Ridge to Andersonville Boat Dock. Alewifes and large shad are best baits drifted at forage school depth. Best fishing is 35-50 feet deep. Walleye are slow, but few fishermen are going after them. Some bass fishermen are lucky and catching 2- or 3-pounders, but that&#39;s about it. However, those fishing for walleye say they are holding off clay/gravel points at night, especially near Loyston and Cove Creek.
<P><B>
<P>WATTS BAR:</B> Surface temperatures are averaging 45 degrees and water is stained to muddy. Bass are fair to good on points and secondary points on jigs and crankbaits. A few fish are being caught in shallow water, but most action is coming at about 15 feet. For the most part fishing has been steady through  the day. Crappie are good in 20 feet over brush or blow downs. Plain minnows are best. A few are being caught by trollers in creek channels using small jigs or twisters. Trollers are getting their fish off bottom. Sauger fishing is good below Watts Bar Dam and in the lake, but fish are small. Below the dam minnows and jigs are working well; in the lake minnows, jigs or crankbaits are producing fish. Stripers are off and on at the Kingston Steam Plant. Shad tightlined or drifted under balloons are working best. Action is  good in the discharge at night.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

	<P><center><font size=2>Return to </font><a href="/"><font size=2>Main</font></a><font size=2>. Copyright &#169; 1996 The Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size=2>webmaster</font></a><font size=2>.</font></center></p>
