<head>
	<title>4 OR buildings on Top 10 risk list</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 16, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>4 OR buildings on Top 10 risk list</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Uranium-storage structures need major repairs, DOE says</FONT></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Richard Powelson, News-Sentinel Washington bureau</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">W</FONT>ASHINGTON -- Oak Ridge has four of the country&#39;s 10 &#39;&#39;most vulnerable&#39;&#39; facilities storing highly radioactive uranium, needing major building repairs and thousands of new containers for the bomb-grade material, according to a federal report released Wednesday.
<P>   The Department of Energy reported Wednesday that four of the Oak Ridge buildings are on its Top 10 list for environmental and safety work but had no estimate of the additional cost. DOE already is spending hundreds of millions of dollars a year on cleaning up environmental problems from World War II and post-war defense projects.
<P>   &#39;&#39;It&#39;s too soon to tell&#39;&#39; the cost, said Tara O&#39;Toole, a DOE assistant secretary.
<P>   The worst of the Oak Ridge buildings, the report states, is Building 9212, which could pose dangers to plant workers, the public and the environment. The risks to the public were limited to an unusual event, such as a tornado, fire or earthquake, which could rip open the building and scatter some radioactive material into communities beyond the federal reservation, analysts reported.
<P>   Ralph Hutchison, coordinator of the Oak Ridge Environmental Peace Alliance, a frequent critic of Oak Ridge&#39;s defense work, said in a statement that the report echoed many of his group&#39;s concerns in recent years.
<P>   &#39;&#39;DOE&#39;s top priority,&#39;&#39; Hutchison said, &#39;&#39;should be the construction of a new, safe, secure facility for the dismantlement, processing and storage of highly enriched uranium.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Patricia Greeson, of Lockheed Martin, the contractor operating DOE&#39;s Y-12 weapons production plant, said DOE owns the buildings on the reservation and would have to pay for any needed repairs and upgrades.
<P>   She emphasized that the report did not raise any problems the contractor was not aware of, adding, &#39;&#39;Safety is a primary concern for our workers at Y-12.&#39;&#39; She said the contractor agreed with the DOE report&#39;s conclusion that there was a &#39;&#39;low or very low possibility&#39;&#39; of Oak Ridge buildings posing any threat to the public.
<P>   DOE workers at Oak Ridge always dress properly in protective suits to handle radioactive materials, she said, so workers also face low risks of health hazards.
<P>   DOE focused on the vulnerable buildings and storage containers in inspections earlier this year. Oak Ridge already has ended some of the threats, such as keeping large amounts of combustible materials near storage containers of highly radioactive uranium, DOE officials said.
<P>   Building 9212 at Oak Ridge was mentioned repeatedly in the report.
<P>   The building has &#39;&#39;many internal and external contaminated areas . . . with no permanent barriers between the worker and the contamination,&#39;&#39; the study said.
<P>   Also, &#39;&#39;known structural weaknesses&#39;&#39; in Building 9212 &#39;&#39;make them susceptible to earthquake and wind damage.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Open containers in the building &#39;&#39;pose the threat of significant spills during earthquakes,&#39;&#39; the report said.
<P>   To show the large quantity of materials at the Y-12 Plant, the report said there are 26,000 containers there containing highly radioactive uranium in a solid or liquid state.
<P>   An unspecified number of the containers &#39;&#39;are degrading, tape seals are falling off, and labels are becoming unreadable.&#39;&#39; Corroding cans could release uranium dust into the air in the building, endangering workers, the report said.
<P>   Energy Secretary Hazel O&#39;Leary said she ordered the study of all DOE facilities with radioactive materials to make sure the department&#39;s field offices were giving problems enough attention. The cost of the problems next will have to be determined and put into funding requests given to Congress.
<P>   The other three Oak Ridge buildings on the Top 10 list are: Building K-1420, part of the K-25 plant, a former processing facility for uranium; Building 9206, part of Y-12; and Building 3019, part of the Oak Ridge National Laboratory research complex.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
