<head>
	<title>Holding on to the dream</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 16, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>Holding on to the dream</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Events to honor Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.</FONT></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">S</FONT>tudents at the Sam E. Hill Family and Community Service Center honored Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. on Wednesday with songs and a parade around the Lonsdale facility.
<P>   The slain civil-rights leader would have been 67 years old Wednesday.
<P>   Preschool student Michael Widener Jr., 3, is shown taking part in Wednesday&#39;s birthday celebration for King.
<P>   Other events commemorating King&#39;s achievements begin today and extend through Monday&#39;s holiday:
<P>   * The Eighth Annual Leadership Symposium and Labor, Business, Industry and Government Awards Luncheon today at the Radisson Hotel.
<P>   Symposium registration begins at 8 a.m. The luncheon, featuring syndicated columnist Deborah Mathis as the speaker, will begin at noon.
<P>   Tickets for the symposium and luncheon are $30 per person.
<P>   * &#39;&#39;Pride and Peace: Positive Pathways to Community&#39;&#39; is the focus of the annual Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. Youth Symposium to be held from 8:30 a.m. to 2:30 p.m. Saturday, Jan. 18, at Austin-East High School.
<P>   The symposium is free, and lunch will be provided. Sam Kirk, chief executive officer of CES Associates in Nashville, will be the keynote speaker.
<P>   * The local King Commemoration Commission&#39;s annual parade will begin at 4:30 p.m. Sunday, Jan. 19, at Tabernacle Baptist Church, 2137 Martin Luther King Jr. Ave.
<P>   The parade will proceed along MLK to the Five Points intersection and down to the Burlington community. A memorial service will follow the parade at 6 p.m. at Greater Warner Tabernacle AME Zion Church, 3800 Martin Luther King Jr. Ave.
<P>   * WSJK/WKOP-TV will present a tribute to Dr. King from 11 a.m. to 1 p.m. Monday, Jan. 20. Benjamin Hooks, retired executive director of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, will be the keynote speaker.
<P>   * The University of Tennessee&#39;s Black Cultural Programming Committee will sponsor a unity march and program highlighting the works of Dr. King on Monday, Jan. 20. The march will begin at the Torchbearer statue on the corner of Yale Avenue and Volunteer Boulevard on the UT campus.
<P>   The program, which follows the march, will be held in the University Center auditorium.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
