<html>
<head>
	<title>Sundquist authorizes staff pay raises up to 29 percent</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 16, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Sundquist authorizes staff pay raises up to 29 percent</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> State employee leader calls action `unconscionable'</FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Tom Humphrey, News-Sentinel Nashville bureau</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">N</FONT>ASHVILLE -- Gov. Don Sundquist&#39;s approval of new pay raises for some of his key staff members generated criticism from state employee leaders and Democratic legislators on Wednesday.
<P>    The Sundquist staff pay raises, effective Jan. 1, come with the state facing a budget shortfall that has raised the possibility of no pay raise for other state workers -- and perhaps layoffs of some.
<P>    Sundquist said the higher pay is coupled with an overall reduction in the governor&#39;s office budget of 15 percent. Beth Fortune, the governor&#39;s press secretary, said four vacant staff jobs have been abolished.
<P>    Combined, the raises total about $70,000 in annual increases and are spread over 18 positions.
<P>    The top pay raise in dollars went to David Locke, the administration&#39;s chief lobbyist. His salary was upped by $10,260 per year -- from $64,380 to $75,000 for a 16 percent increase.
<P>    The highest percentage pay raise went to Brooke Pinkerton, who carries the title of assistant for correspondence. Pinkerton&#39;s pay was raised from $22,356 to $28,848 -- a 29 percent increase.
<P>    The smallest percentage increase went to Wendell Moore, installed last fall as the governor&#39;s chief administrative officer. His salary was boosted from $80,000 to $83,000, or 3.7 percent.
<P>    &#39;&#39;It&#39;s unconscionable,&#39;&#39; said Linda McCarty, executive director of the Tennessee State Employees Association.
<P>    McCarty noted that Sundquist adjusted pay upward for several key positions shortly after taking office in 1995 and raised salaries of some key staffers again in January 1996.
<P>    TSEA has called for an 8 percent pay raise in the 1996-97 fiscal year. McCarty noted that Sundquist called that proposal &#39;&#39;outrageous&#39;&#39; in a time of revenue shortfalls -- projected at $100 million this year and $300 million in 1996-97. 
<P>    Sundquist, however, has said the raises reflect a management philosophy of getting by with fewer people who work harder and deserve better salaries.
<P>    House Speaker Jimmy Naifeh, D-Covington, said the governor has the right to determine his staff salaries but said &#39;&#39;the timing of it is not appropriate at all.&#39;&#39;
<P>    About 90 persons are being laid off in the state Department of Mental Health and Mental Retardation. Sundquist has not said how many may be laid off as a result of budget cuts, which are to be formally proposed in a Feb. 10 budget presentation.
<P>    Both Naifeh and Lt. Gov. John Wilder, speaker of the Senate, said they have not increased salaries for any legislative staff this year, though a new pay scale system implemented last year resulted in some pay increases.
<P>   Fortune said that, in most cases, the pay raises reflect increased responsibilities -- as with Hardy Mays, who has become deputy governor and chief of staff instead of legal counsel. Mays made $77,160 as legal counsel and now gets $85,000. That is still $3,600 less than the salary of his predecessor as deputy governor, Peaches Simpkins.
<P>    The legal counsel post, now held by Courtney Pearre of Knoxville, was boosted to $80,000. Assistant Legal Counsel Natasha Metcalf, also a former Knoxville lawyer, got an increase from $43,260 to $45,000.
<P>    At least six of those with pay raises, including Locke, have the same duties as last year. In Locke&#39;s case, the increase puts him on a level with other cabinet-level officials, Fortune said.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

