<head>
	<title>Footing proves tricky for state&#39;s top Democrats</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 16, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Footing proves tricky for state&#39;s top Democrats</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Tom Humphrey, News-Sentinel Nashville bureau</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">T</FONT>he two top state House Democrats have fallen -- literally.
<P>    House Speaker <B>Jimmy Naifeh</B> slipped on ice outside a hotel Tuesday night, striking his head and leaving him unconscious. He was taken to St. Thomas Hospital for an examination, which revealed what aides described as &#39;&#39;a mild concussion.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Naifeh, wearing a large white bandage on his forehead, returned to preside over Wednesday&#39;s House session. As a show of sympathy, several other legislators -- including Reps. <B>Bob McKee</B>, R-Athens; Doug Gunnels, R-Lenoir City; and <B>Ronnie Cole</B>, D-Dyersburg -- donned similar bandages and posed for pictures with the speaker.
<P>    A day earlier, House Majority Leader <B>Jere Hargrove</B>, D-Cookeville, slipped on icy steps and badly skinned his arm.
<P>    While ice encounters seem to have been a Democratic problem to date, a group of starlings that somehow got into the House chamber on Monday acted on a bipartisan basis. Before they were chased out of chamber windows, the birds distributed their &#39;&#39;mess&#39;&#39; fairly evenly on Republican and Democratic desks.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>    State Rep. <B>Jerry Cross</B>, D-Caryville, says he was surprised as anyone to see a crowd walking through state Capitol corridors wearing baseball caps emblazoned with &#39;&#39;Jerry Cross for Governor, 1998&#39;&#39; across the front.
<P>    Cross says a busload of friends and supporters from Anderson and Campbell counties decided upon the gimmick when they traveled to Nashville to attend formal swearing-in ceremonies for legislators.
<P>    &#39;&#39;I told them, &#39;Just keep the word out there, boys. It&#39;s a start,&#39; &#39;&#39; Cross said Wednesday.
<P>    Cross, who has faced tough re-election campaigns in recent years, said he is not ready to formally announce his candidacy for governor. But he said supporters already have a slogan just in case: &#39;&#39;He&#39;s going to keep the jam on the lower shelf so the little man can reach it.&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>    Knoxville Rep. <B>Bill Dunn</B> angered Speaker Pro Tempore <B>Lois DeBerry </B>when he refused to vote for her re-election to the powerful House position.
<P>    &#39;&#39;He asked me &#39;Have you been reborn again?&#39; &#39;&#39; said DeBerry, obviously angered. &#39;&#39;What gives him the right to ask me if I&#39;ve been reborn again?&#39;&#39;
<P>    DeBerry, a Memphis Democrat, was elected by 98 votes out of the 99 House members with only Dunn abstaining.
<P>    Dunn, a Knoxville Republican, sees the encounter differently.
<P>    &#39;&#39;I didn&#39;t ask her that,&#39;&#39; he said. &#39;&#39;I asked her if she&#39;d had a pro-life conversion. I said it in a way to break the ice. She said she&#39;d been too busy this summer to think about it.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Dunn said he didn&#39;t vote for DeBerry at the start of his first term two years ago either.
<P>    &#39;&#39;She&#39;s a liberal, and I&#39;m a conservative,&#39;&#39; he said. &#39;&#39;She&#39;s been instrumental in defeating almost all pro-life legislation so in good conscience, I couldn&#39;t vote for her.&#39;&#39;
<P>    DeBerry has sat on a important House subcommittee that has sidetracked bills to limit abortion rights in Tennessee.
<P>   Dunn may need to watch out for more than his abortion bills being killed.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
