<head>
	<title>Lobbyists get 2 extra days to woo lawmakers</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 16, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Lobbyists get 2 extra days to woo lawmakers</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Rebecca Ferrar, News-Sentinel Nashville bureau</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">N</FONT>ASHVILLE -- It&#39;s almost like two extra shopping days for legislators and lobbyists.
<P>   Under a loophole in state ethics laws, members of the 100th General Assembly get two additional days to receive contributions from lobbyists.
<P>   The unexpected bonus came when Peggy Catalano, director of the Registry of Election Finance, ruled the ban on in-session fund-raising does not apply until today -- when the Legislature begins formally meeting.
<P>   Lawmakers met Tuesday and Wednesday in organizational sessions to elect the speakers of the Senate and House and constitutional officers.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Until the time the regular session starts, legislators may continue to accept contributions,&#39;&#39; Catalano said. &#39;&#39;It may provide a couple more days for lobbyists or PACs (political action committees) to provide fund-raising activities.&#39;&#39;
<P>   In 1995, the Legislature banned special interest contributions, both individually and by PACs, while all 132 members are in session to stop efforts to influence legislation.
<P>   &#39;&#39;This loophole -- allowing the old money-raising, lobbying, wining and dining so close to the beginning of the term -- strikes me as being very much out of the spirit of the law,&#39;&#39; said Phil Schoggen, state chairman of Common Cause, an ethics watchdog group.
<P>   State Sen. Bud Gilbert, R-Knoxville, who helped impose the ban, said: &#39;&#39;Certainly, the intent was to cease all fund-raising once we get to Nashville in a legislative mode. The spirit of the law was to stop the fund-raising.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Also Wednesday, the Senate and House in joint session unanimously re-elected the constitutional officers: Comptroller William Snodgrass, Treasurer Steve Adams and Secretary of State Riley Darnell.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

	<P><center><font size=2>Return to </font><a href="/"><font size=2>Main</font></a><font size=2>. Copyright &#169; 1996 The Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size=2>webmaster</font></a><font size=2>.</font></center></p>
