<head>
	<title>Beautiful birds</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 16, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Beautiful birds</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Masterpieces of Gould, Audubon on exhibit at McClung</FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By J.B. Owen, News-Sentinel columnist</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><P>
<P>
<P>   Birds are beautiful, and artists have long strived to preserve their splendor on printed pages.
<P>   At first, printing could only be done in black and white, and color had to be added tediously by hand, one brush stroke and one page at a time. Yet the results often were masterpieces.
<P>   Starting Saturday and continuing through March 23, 250 years of such hand-colored prints of birds will be commemorated by the Frank H. McClung Museum at the University of Tennessee when 100 of these rare and historic pictures will be on display.
<P>   The exhibition is possible because of two extensive collections that have been given to the museum.
<P>   In 1967 the late Mr. and Mrs. John L. Greer of Knoxville gave the museum 2300 prints of the work of England&#39;s John Gould that were published between 1830 and 1881.
<P>   These featured birds of Europe, Asia, Australia, Great Britain, and hummingbirds from South America. This collection is now valued at over $3 million.
<P>   Last year Mr. and Mrs. Joel E. Rynning of Atlanta enhanced the museum&#39;s collection by contributing 287 lithographs and engravings, ranging from works of Eleazar Albin and Mark Catesby of the 1730s to Rex Brasher who hand-colored a book as recently as 1932.
<P>   Included were 200 prints by John James Audubon, from his first royal octavo edition of Birds of America published in Philadelphia from 1840 to 1844.
<P>   Mark Catesby was the first painter of American birds, publishing &#39;&#39;The Natural History of Carolina, Florida, and the Bahama Islands&#39;&#39; in 1731. It was more than a hundred years before he was overshadowed by Audubon.
<P>   Eleazer Albin&#39;s work in 1731-1738 featured British birds. 
<P>   Rex Brasher did his painting after color printing had been invented, but the cost for his 875 oversize pages was more than he could manage in those great depression years, so he hand-painted 100 copies in 1929-1932. Thirty years later his work was reprinted on modern color presses.
<P>   The Gould prints are larger, and many are of especially colorful species, so his work may stand out from the others. He didn&#39;t find all of the birds himself but received collections of mounted specimen and dried skins from naturalist explorers.
<P>   He was able to study the birds collected by Charles Darwin on his five year, round-the-world voyage on the Beagle and illustrated one of the books Darwin published.
<P>   Gould&#39;s association with Darwin contributed to one of the most significant events in scientific history -- the theory of evolution. The theory did not suddenly burst upon Darwin while collecting the Galapagos Island birds that later became known as &#39;&#39;Darwin finches.&#39;&#39; It developed gradually after Gould pointed out the birds&#39; similarity in his paintings.
<P>   The Frank H. McClung Museum is located in the Circle Park portion of the University of Tennessee. The museum has no admission charge and is open from 9 to 5, Monday through Friday; 10 to 3 on Saturdays; and 1 to 5 on Sundays.
<P>   Parking is free by permit which can be obtained at the information booth on Circle Park Drive.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

	<P><center><font size=2>Return to </font><a href="/"><font size=2>Main</font></a><font size=2>. Copyright &#169; 1996 The Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size=2>webmaster</font></a><font size=2>.</font></center></p>
</body>
