<head>
	<title>Books tell tales of hard times in East Tennessee</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 16, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Books tell tales of hard times in East Tennessee</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Carson Brewer, News-Sentinel columnist</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><P>
<P>   One of the saddest pictures I&#39;ve seen lately is of the G. W. Winstead family in Hawkins County in 1870. It shows G. W., gaunt and bearded, standing between a horse and a work steer, with his eight children, in front of the small house that had been their home.
<P>   The caption says: &#39;&#39;He lost his wife to TB, his farm to the bank . . .and he&#39;s leaving for Texas to start a new life.&#39;&#39;
<P>   The picture is one of many interesting ones in &#39;&#39;Hawkins Couny Tennessee,&#39;&#39; a county history by Henry R. Price, a Rogersville lawyer.
<P>   Talk about hard times, that picture tells the story. G. W. Winstead could have been the fellow who wrote the recipe for meat skin soup. But he wasn&#39;t. The folks who know how to make meat skin soup are a couple of Cherokees, William Crowe and Goingback Chiltoskey. The Cherokees also have known hard times.
<P>   The meat skin soup recipe is one of many in a new cookbook called &#39;&#39;Food & Recipes of the Smokies.&#39;&#39; Rose Houk did a great job of collecting the recipes from Great Smokies oldtimers and making a book  out of them. Great Smoky Mountains Natural History Association is the publisher. 
<P>   The covers of both books are outstanding. The cover of the Hawkins Couny book is a picture of the old Courthouse, one of the oldest and most beautiful in the state.  The cookbook cover, front and back, is a color photograph of home-canned vegetables and fruits.
<P>    Though Hawkins County is one of the oldest counties in Tennessee, Henry Price is the first person to collect its history and put it in a book. I did some of my growing up in Hawkins County, but I didn&#39;t know until I read Henry&#39;s book what a hectic early governmental history it had. Listen to this:
<P>   &#39;&#39;. . .First, it was part of North Carolina&#39;s western lands; then it became part of Washington District; then part of Washington County; then part of Sullivan County; then Spencer County in the State of Franklin; then Hawkins County, North Carolina; then Hawkins County in the Territory South of the River Ohio; and finally, in 1796, when Tennessee gained statehood, Hawkins County, Tennessee.&#39;&#39; Early Hawkins Countians surely could be forgiven if they forgot what return address to put on a letter.
<P>   The Hawkins County book is more than 200 very large pages long. Besides containing Henry&#39;s historical account, it has more than 275 pictures. It costs $34.95, plus $5 for shipping and handling. Order it from (and make checks to) The Rogersville Heritage Association, 415 South Depot Street, Rogersville, Tennessee 37857. Proceeds from the book go to the Heritage Association, to finance its preservation-restoration work in the city.
<P>   Among the stories in the book that I liked is the one about John T. Walker who came to Rogersville with only a file in his pocket and soon owned a sawmill. His mill whistle blew promptly at 6 every morning and at 4 in the afternoon. People in town depended on the whistle to keep time for them. Walker set his watch every day from jeweler E. S. Clifton&#39;s large clock on Main Street, and Clifton set his clock by Walker&#39;s whistle. &#39;&#39;Together they kept remarkably good time.&#39;&#39;
<P>   You can learn lots and lots more from Rose Houk&#39;s Smoky cookbook than how to make meat skin soup. It takes you through hog killing, the making of souse meat, red-eye gravy, backbones and ribs and hog jowls and peas. You can try Beuna Winchester&#39;s recipe for cooking groundhog and Duane Oliver&#39;s for cooking bear steak stew, plus many, many others. The cookbook costs $11.95 plus tax. You can buy it at Great Smokies visitor centers and, I suppose, at various book stores. It&#39;s a goodie.
<P><B>
<P>Carson Brewer, a retired News-Sentinel reporter, writes a column twice a month for The News-Sentinel. </B>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

	<P><center><font size=2>Return to </font><a href="/"><font size=2>Main</font></a><font size=2>. Copyright &#169; 1996 The Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size=2>webmaster</font></a><font size=2>.</font></center></p>
</body>
