<head>
	<title>Opera Company director ready to meet funding challenges</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 16, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Opera Company director ready to meet funding challenges</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Barbara Aston-Wash, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><P>
<P>
<P>   Susan Arp has a lot on her mind these days. 
<P>   She moved from community fundraiser -- concentrating on United Way -- to becoming director of development and administration of an arts organization -- the Knoxville Opera Company.
<P>   In her eight-year tenure as executive director and chief professional officer of the United Way of Greater Kingsport, the organization raised over $18 million for charitable services. 
<P>   Now she is involved with the most expensive of the art forms to produce. Ticket sales account for only 43 percent of the funding.  Corporate sponsors, patrons, Opera Guild benefits and fund raising must provide the additional monies, she says.
<P>   The transition is proving an easy one for Arp, and happily the new role promises some welcome challenges, she says.
<P>   &#39;&#39;It is really exciting to arrive on the scene at a time when long-range planning is being undertaken. It offers one a chance to quickly learn the many facets of operating an opera and the opportunity to help make a difference in its move into the new century.
<P>   &#39;&#39;The fund raising and managerial skills needed for my work with United Way are necessary for this job as well,&#39;&#39; she adds.  
<P>   Admittedly she has no long-time romance with opera, but having studied piano for most of her formative years, and always having been a music appreciator, she feels quite comfortable in music circles.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Opera is such a complex, yet complete art form that it is exciting to see how it all goes together, to be involved in it.&#39;&#39; 
<P>   Arp is a community-minded person as well. 
<P>   She and husband Bennie, whom she met and married while both were students at Middle Tennessee State University, moved to Knoxville from Kingsport, for him to assume the State Farm office in the Fountain City.
<P>   The couple, now married 29 years, are parents of two sons. Ken is a sales rep with Eastman Chemical, and lives in Chicago with his wife Camille. Brett Arp, who received an MBA from The Thunderbird, an international management group in Phoenix, is just back from Madrid, where he worked on fluency in Spanish. 
<P>   The Arps also brought up two nephews, Jashon Hall of Oak Ridge, who is just out of the Marines and is entering college, and Wesley Hall of Nashville, who is working at Mercury Records.
<P>   At home now are the couple&#39;s two dogs, Tessa, a border collie, and Shadow, a springer spaniel.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

	<P><center><font size=2>Return to </font><a href="/"><font size=2>Main</font></a><font size=2>. Copyright &#169; 1996 The Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size=2>webmaster</font></a><font size=2>.</font></center></p>
</body>
