<head>
	<title>Tanker spills toxic chemical on road</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 16, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Tanker spills toxic chemical on road</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Highway 68 closed an hour</FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">C</FONT>OPPERHILL, Tenn. -- A tanker truck spilled up to 250 gallons of sulfuric acid on state Highway 68 on Wednesday after failing to secure the container&#39;s top lid, authorities said.
<P>    The truck, owned by K&S Tank Line of Copperhill, was hauling the sulfuric acid from the local B.I.T. Manufacturing plant to J.M. Huber Co., a chemical plant about 50 miles northwest in Etowah, said Gray Gibson, dispatcher for the Tennessee Highway Patrol&#39;s Chattanooga district.
<P>    After loading the acid into the truck about 9:30 a.m. EST, a lid on the top of the tanker wasn&#39;t secured.
<P>    When the truck pulled out of the plant, 50 to 250 gallons of the chemical spilled onto the roadway, Gibson said.
<P>    A portion of the highway was closed about an hour so emergency crews could neutralize the chemical with dry lime.
<P>    Gibson said the chemical spill was contained to the highway&#39;s asphalt and did not reach soil or water.
<P>    No one was injured and no one was evacuated, he added.
<P>    Sulfuric acid is a strong, corrosive and hazardous chemical widely used by industries for numerous purposes, including the making of fertilizers.
<P>    The odorless, clear chemical can cause breathing problems if inhaled and severe burns if it touches skin tissue.
<P>    Vapors are irritating to the eyes and throat and can cause nausea.
<P>    Gibson said the driver, whose name wasn&#39;t immediately available, was issued a ticket for driving a commercial vehicle with a container leak.
<P>    Boliden Intertrade Inc., known as B.I.T., is owned by the Sweden-based Trelleborg. The company took over the old copper smelting works in this tiny town on the southeast border of Tennessee in 1990.
<P>    The U.S. offices are based in Atlanta.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

