	<title>HUD gives $310,000 to Overlook Center for complex</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 16, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>HUD gives $310,000 to Overlook Center for complex</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Federal grant to aid area's mentally ill</FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Amy Smith, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">T</FONT>he U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development has awarded at $310,000 grant to Overlook Center to build a six-unit apartment complex for individuals with mental illness.
<P>   Overlook is a community mental health center that serves people with persistent and serious mental illnesses, as well as providing substance abuse services in Knox, Blount, Loudon, Monroe and Sevier counties.
<P>   &#39;&#39;This grant allows us to continue the expansion of housing options to the people we serve,&#39;&#39; said Shirley Hill, Overlook&#39;s director of HUD projects. &#39;&#39;We are looking forward to serving our communities and our consumers through this project.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Overlook will oversee the construction and management of the apartments, which will be located in Maryville. The apartments will house six residents who have a serious and persistent mental illness.
<P>   Two other HUD projects to build housing for the mentally ill are pending -- a $432,000 grant request for an eight-unit complex in Knoxville and a $324,000 grant for a six-unit complex in Monroe County.
<P>   With the most recent grant, Overlook has received more than $1 million to construct and manage 20 apartments for the mentally ill.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We are in the housing business to help persons with mental illness and other disabilities to find decent, safe, affordable and permanent housing,&#39;&#39; said Overlook Grant Development Director Penny Driver. &#39;&#39;These HUD projects and properties help us meet the needs of persons with mental illness and give them the opportunities and choices for housing.&#39;&#39;
<P>   According to Driver, the housing options for mentally ill within communities will allow those individuals to receive services within their home communities, near their families and other supportive people. Each resident will have their own apartment, which includes a bedroom, bathroom, living room and kitchen/dining area.
<P>    There will be a common laundry room and office where residents may meet with staff memebers who direct and coordinate their support services.
<P>   Overlook, a member of Covenant Behavioral Health, has five other HUD properties, three apartment complexes for the elderly in Knoxville, Sweetwater and Lenoir City, and two eight-bed group homes for adults for mental illness in Knoxville and Maryville.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

