	<title>Citing budget crunch, safety chief sends back his new state vehicle</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 16, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Citing budget crunch, safety chief sends back his new state vehicle</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">N</FONT>ASHVILLE -- Safety Commissioner Mike Greene had second thoughts about spending $33,000 on a new Ford Expedition that would be his second state car.
<P>    High-performance radios and blue lights had been added to the 4-by-4 sport-utility vehicle when Greene sent it back to Town and Country Ford in Madison, a Nashville suburub.
<P>     The purchase ultimately cost the state $1,400, but the timing drew a rebuke from the Legislature.
<P>    Gov. Don Sundquist has ordered some departments to cut their expenses more than 20 percent to help make up an expected $100 million shortfall in the current budget.
<P>    &#39;&#39;It&#39;s a terrible example,&#39;&#39; said Rep. Gary Odom, D-Nashville and a member of the Legislature&#39;s watchdog Fiscal Review Committee.
<P>    In his belt-tightening campaign, Sundquist has pointed to small successes like the $8,000 saved by discontinuing phone lines that are no longer used.
<P>    In Greene&#39;s case, the state paid $28,168 for the truck, which had a manufacturer&#39;s suggested retail price of $32,975. Ford Motor Co. bought the truck back for $26,768, said Ed Jones, deputy general services commissioner.
<P>    Greene realized the time was not right to take on the new truck as state employees fear for their jobs in the wake of reorganization and budget shortfalls, Sundquist said.
<P>    &#39;&#39;It&#39;s not wrongdoing. It&#39;s the appearance of it. I mean, it just didn&#39;t look right in a year when we were crunching dollars and saving money,&#39;&#39; Sundquist said. &#39;&#39;He called me and said, &#39;I feel bad about this. I ordered it before the budget crunch&#39; . . . He said he&#39;d recommend we sell it, and I said, &#39;I agree with that.&#39; &#39;&#39; Sundquist said.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
