<head>
	<title>Ex-TVA employee has labor hearing</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 16, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Ex-TVA employee has labor hearing</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Woman: Fired due to whistle-blowing</FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Jerry Dean, News-Sentinel business writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">C</FONT>HATTANOOGA -- When Glenda Kay Miller, an ex-TVA employee and soft-spoken mother of three, returned to college in 1982, she hoped to parlay training into a career in computer analysis.
<P>   And when she landed a systems analyst&#39;s job with TVA in 1987, Miller felt success was imminent.
<P>   But her testimony Wednesday in a Department of Labor administrative hearing revealed how her eight-year TVA work experience soured, allegedly because of a supervisor&#39;s perception that Miller once mentioned a handgun and thus jeopardized her coworkers&#39; safety.
<P>   Miller, despite an exemplary work record, suddenly found herself psychologically tested, her TVA security access revoked. And she was told no other jobs within TVA were available to her.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I lost my name,&#39;&#39; a tearful Miller told Administrative Law Judge Robert L. Hillyard. &#39;&#39;It was the most traumatic experience of my life. I grew up in a proud, middle-class family where your name means everything. When they take that away, you lose everything.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Miller said she has sought other jobs since her August 1995 dismissal from her $50,000 a year job. But when employers ask if she has been fired or denied security clearance, she answers honestly. Then doors close, she added.
<P>   Miller, 50, said she did not know at first why TVA fired her, since the federal agency only said medical tests showed her ineligible for security clearance she needed to enter work areas. But she said Wednesday TVA targeted her for dismissal once she voiced concerns about installation of an unproven &#39;&#39;hand-geometry&#39;&#39; identification system at Sequoyah, Browns Ferry and Watts Bar nuclear plants.
<P>   Federal laws prohibit nuclear licensees from retaliation against workers who question nuclear plant safety. In such a case, TVA recently was fined $100,000 for forcing the resignation of William Jocher, a Sequoyah Nuclear plant official and once TVA&#39;s chief of chemistry.
<P>   Miller said TVA in 1995 was pressed to meet a spring startup date of long-delayed Watts Bar. After she refused to approve hand-geometry, her work was closely scrutinized, Miller said.
<P>   Questioned by TVA attorney Thomas F. Fine, Miller said she first thought she was fired for efforts to upgrade her job. Later, she learned she was psychologically tested because of January 1995 remarks made to her supervisor Barbara McKenna.
<P>   When McKenna asked about her recent illness, Miller described how she, home alone and ill, retrieved her husband&#39;s gun after hearing a possible intruder. Miller later told a TVA intern she better understood how workplace stress made some postal workers resort to violence.
<P>   The utterances, Miller said, were used as pretext for finding her &#39;&#39;unfit for duty&#39;&#39; after she noted &#39;&#39;incompatibility&#39;&#39; between plant security and the unproven hand-geometry system.
<P>   Fine noted none of Miller&#39;s first complaints to TVA had attributed her firing to her having voiced safety concerns. But Miller said she was &#39;&#39;confused&#39;&#39; then by events of her firing.
<P>   Dr. Thomas M. Pendergrass, who examined Miller, said she showed&#39;&#39;depression and nervousness&#39;&#39; but &#39;&#39;no suggestion of psychotic disorder.&#39;&#39;
<P>   The hearing continues at 9 a.m. today in Chattanooga&#39;s federal courthouse.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

	<P><center><font size=2>Return to </font><a href="/"><font size=2>Main</font></a><font size=2>. Copyright &#169; 1996 The Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size=2>webmaster</font></a><font size=2>.</font></center></p>
