<head>
	<title>Fraser firs making a comeback in Smokies, expert says</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 16, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Fraser firs making a comeback in Smokies, expert says</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Marti Davis, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">P</FONT>IGEON FORGE -- Almost half a century after the balsam woolly adelgid began to attack the Fraser fir throughout the highest regions of the Great Smoky Mountains National Park some of the trees are beginning to make a comeback.
<P>    &#39;&#39;It will never be the same as it was,&#39;&#39; said Kristine Johnson, a park tree specialist speaking to participants at Wilderness Week activities at the Heartlander Country Resort in Pigeon Forge. However, she said small groups of seedlings are growing in high elevations.
<P>    She added the fir&#39;s future is not as bleak as that of the American chestnut, which was  wiped out by the Chinese chestnut blight in the 1930s and 40s.
<P>    &#39;&#39;There could be some Fraser fir forest in the future,&#39;&#39; Johnson said.
<P>    Because the insects mainly attack only mature trees, Johnson said the seedlings will have a chance to develop. Park wildlife managers hope that among them will be some of the few Fraser firs that have a natural genetic resistance to the pests.
<P>    &#39;&#39;We just have to wait and see,&#39;&#39; she said, adding the park is keeping a close eye on the developing trees.
<P>    The balsam woolly adelgid, a tiny, fuzzy, sucking insect, kills the fir by enlarging and hardening cells, eventually blocking the ability of each tree to transfer fluids from one part to another.
<P>    The species is entirely female, and each female can lay 400 or more eggs per year. 
<P>   &#39;&#39;They can completely coat a tree,&#39;&#39; Johnson said.
<P>    The insect infestation has killed a great majority of the mature fir trees in the Great Smoky Mountains National Park. The adelgid is a European insect imported to the United States around 1908 and possibly brought into this region on Christmas trees from other regions.
<P>    While not a problem yet, the national park plant specialists are concerned that another, similar adelgid insect will begin attacking hemlock trees. The adelgid haven&#39;t yet appeared in the park. They are in other parts of the country and could arrive any time on wind currents or migrating birds.
<P>    The hemlock adelgid doesn&#39;t attack the bark but goes for the base of the needles.
<P>    Some of the park&#39;s largest and oldest trees are eastern hemlock. The park has at least one that is over 400 years old, Johnson said.
<P>    Because hemlock often grows along the edges of streams, plant specialists in other parts of the country are concerned their demise could lead to a rise in stream temperature, a result that could have an adverse impact on aquatic life forms in the park.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

	<P><center><font size=2>Return to </font><a href="/"><font size=2>Main</font></a><font size=2>. Copyright &#169; 1996 The Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size=2>webmaster</font></a><font size=2>.</font></center></p>
</body>
