<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>Kees&#39; defense disappears again in 7-4 defeat</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 16, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470><BASEFONT SIZE="6">
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Kees&#39; defense disappears again in 7-4 defeat</B></FONT><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Nick Gates, News-Sentinel sportswriter</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<P>        The Knoxville Cherokees are as defenseless as a chicken in a henhouse filled with foxes.
<P>        The East Coast Hockey League team took it on the chin again Wednesday night at the Civic Coliseum. The Richmond Renegades won 7-4 to saddle the Cherokees with their third consecutive loss.
<P>        Mike Rucinski scored two goals, including a backbreaker 8:40 into the third period that put the Renegades (25-10-1) in front 6-3.
<P>        Rucinski wasn&#39;t the only Richmond defenseman to beat Knoxville goalie Trent Cavicchi. Dallas Ferguson got his first in 13 games with the Renegades in the second period to put Richmond ahead to stay.
<P>        Mike Harding, Scott Burfoot, David Dartsch and Tom Holmes also had goals for the Renegades.
<P>        The Cherokees (13-22-2) bunched goals by Dave Neilson, Vaclav Nedomansky and Stephane Soulliere in the first period. But only Jim Brown could beat goalie Tripp Tracy the rest of the way.
<P>        Brown, Knoxville&#39;s leading scorer, got his 23rd in the third period.
<P>        Knoxville is crippled on defense. The prospects of an immediate reversal aren&#39;t good, but the Cherokees displayed the possibility of long-range improvement with the addition of defenseman Greg Bailey.
<P>        Bailey, 6-foot-5 and 228 pounds, started the season with San Antonio of the Central League. He has ECHL experience (two years) with Huntington and Birmingham. He didn&#39;t mind throwing his weight around.
<P>        Bailey&#39;s arrival couldn&#39;t come at a more opportune time for the league&#39;s most-porous defense. The defensive corps is beat up.
<P>        Mike Vandenberghe (wrist) missed his third straight game and Sean Halifax sat out the Richmond game, while Jamie Bird played at less than 100 percent. Dan Chaput, who started, didn&#39;t return to the ice after the first period.
<P>        Captain Wayne Anchikoski, normally a forward, skated on defense. So did Dean Moore. Moore wasn&#39;t around for the third period. He was accidentally struck in the face by a puck at Richmond&#39;s blue line.
<P>        Richmond scored three goals in span of 3:13 in the first period to build a 3-1 lead. Rucinski cruised down the slot unchecked and got his 11th.
<P>        Harding added his 16th. Burfoot collected his 16th at 10:56 only 29 seconds after Bird went to the penalty box for slashing.
<P>        But Knoxville caught up twice before the first intermission.
<P>        Neilson&#39;s got his 12th on a low shot inside the post 43 seconds after Rucinski put The Renegaades ahead. Soulliere chipped the puck over Tracy for his ninth and 45 seconds later, Nedomansky, using Richmond&#39;s Andrew Shier as a shield, slapped home his 13th.
<P>        Ferguson put Richmond ahead 4-3 with 2:38 gone in the second period, and the defenseman proved anyone can score when left unattended in the circle.
<P>        The Renegades had outscored the Cherokees 13-2 in winning the two earlier meetings.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
