<head>
	<title>Sports Briefs</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 16, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470><BASEFONT SIZE="6">
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Sports Briefs</B></FONT><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<h3>Hamiton returning to ETSU as head coach</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>     <B>Paul Hamilton,</B> who coached receivers and quarterbacks at East Tennessee State University 1983-87, is back as head coach.
<P>    &#39;&#39;I know a lot of great football coaches around the country were interested in this job and I know how blessed I am to have this opportunity,&#39;&#39; said Hamilton, who has been offensive coordinator at Air Force Academy.
<P>    <B>Keener Fry,</B> ETSU&#39;s athletic director, told the Johnson City Press there were many candidates to replace <B>Mike Cavan,</B> who left last month for SMU, &#39;&#39;but I don&#39;t think any had this much passion and love for this university.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Fry and an advisory search committee spent about three weeks narrowing the field to four candidates, then picked Hamilton after less than a day of deliberating.
<P>    Hamilton, 38, from Charleston, S.C., graduated from Appalachian State in 1981. He coached at Wofford for two seasons before moving to Air Force for the past seven years. Air Force made it to four bowl games during his tenure and was one of the top rushing teams in the nation, using a wishbone attack.
<P>    Hamilton will make $76,000 a season for four years in base salary. TV and radio shows would put the package at over $100,000.
<P>    ETSU, which made the NCAA Division I-AA playoffs this year for the first time in 72 years, finished the season at 10-3.
<P>
<P><h3>In other college football news:</h3>
<P>* Tennessee middle linebacker <B>Tyrone Hines</B>, who led the Vols with 110 tackles, has been added to Saturday&#39;s Senior Bowl in Mobile, Ala. Hines was UT&#39;s defensive MVP in the Florida Citrus Bowl. He joins two other Vols in the Senior Bowl, tailback <B>Jay Graham </B>and receiver<B> Joey Kent.</B>
<P>* UT running back <B>Brian Darden</B>, who was suspended for the Florida Citrus Bowl<B> </B>because of a conduct problem, has returned to Knoxville and attended classes on Wednesday.
<P>* <B>Carl Reeves</B>, a 6-4, 240-pound outside linebacker at Knoxville College, has been invited to participate in the Senior Bowl, said KC athletic director <B>Raleigh Wynn.</B>
<P>* Wisconsin will play Syracuse in the Kickoff Classic at Giants Stadium on Augu. 24 in college football&#39;s traditional opener. Each school is guaranteed a minimum $675,000 payday.
<P>* The Arizona Board of Regents approved a new contract for Arizona State coach <B>Bruce Snyder</B> that will increase his annual pay to $500,000, plus potential bonuses.
<P>* <B>Rocky Hager</B>, who coached North Dakota State to five North Central Conference titles and two national championships, was forced out after a series of off-the-field problems with Bison players.
<P>* According to his attorney, former Vanderbilt offensive lineman <B>Allen DeGraffenreid</B> will plead not guilty to assault of a former girlfriend and trespassing charges at an arraignment later this month in Franklin, Tenn. DeGraffenreid, a senior this past season, is from Dunwoody, Ga.
<P>
<P><h3>Swimming<h3>
<P>
<P>* Tennessee&#39;s men swimmers will be one of the nation&#39;s top six ranked teams competing in the Dallas Morning News Classic on Friday and Saturday in Dallas. The Vols will warm up with a dual meet at Texas A&M tonight.
<P>
<P><h3>Golf<h3>
<P>
<P><B></B><B>Larry Rinker,</B> nearing his 40th birthday and still struggling to make a living at golf, shot one of the best rounds of his life, a 9-under-par 63 that gave him the opening-day lead in the Bob Hope Chrysler Classic. U.S. Open winner <B>Steve Jones,</B> a former Hope winner, and <B>Mark Calcavecchia </B>shot 64s; <B>John Daly </B>opened with a 65. <B>Jimmy Johnston </B>of Farragut was last in the field with a 79.
<P><B></B><B>Arnold Palmer,</B> who was operated on Wednesday for prostate cancer, officially withdrew from the Senior Skins Game on Jan. 25-26 on the Big Island of Hawaii and was replaced in the four-man field by <B>Lee Trevino</B>. He&#39;ll face <B>Jack Nicklaus, Raymond Floyd </B>and <B>Hale Irwin.
<P></B>* <B>David Reed,</B> a former standout at Jefferson County High School and Middle Tennessee State University, has qualified for this year&#39;s Hooters Tour by placing third in a field of 127.
<P>
<P><h3>Tennis<h3>
<P>
<P>* <B>Chris Woodruff </B>of Knoxville teamed with <B>Kent Kinnear</B> of Greenwood, Ind., to beat<B> Allen Belobrajdic</B> and <B>Grant Doyle </B>of Australia 7-6 (7-4), 6-3 in the first round of the doubles at the Australian Open. Woodruff plays today in the second round of singles.
<P>* <B>Ignacio Truyol</B> has announced his intention to challenge the ATP Tour&#39;s decision to suspend him for alleged violation of its anti-doping rule.
<P>
<P><h3>Track and field<h3>
<P>
<P>* University of Tennessee women&#39;s team will open indoor competition Friday and Saturday in a 14-team field at the Virginia Tech Invitational, a non-scoring meet in Blacksburg, Va. UT will be led by four sprinters, junior <B>Anissa Campbell </B>and sophomores <B>Heather Sumpter, Kelli White </B>and <B>Erica Witter</B>.
<P>
<P><h3>Auto racing<h3>
<P>
<P>* Driver <B>Ernie Irvan </B>will be reunited with longtime friend <B>Marc Reno,</B> who replaces <B>Larry McReynolds </B>as crew chief of the oldest of two Winston Cup teams owned by <B>Robert Yates</B>. Irvan and Reno are California natives and competed on West Coast short tracks. Most recently Reno has been crew chief for <B>Jeff Purvis&#39; </B>Busch Series.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
