<head>
	<title>TVA fined $100,000 for job bias</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 15, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>TVA fined $100,000 for job bias</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> NRC levies penalty in Jocher case</FONT></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Jerry Dean, News-Sentinel business writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">T</FONT>VA has received a maximum fine for its discrimination against a nuclear whistleblower, while a vice president who received steady performance bonuses has been barred from nuclear operations.
<P>   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission proposed Tuesday that TVA be fined $100,000 in the aftermath of job discrimination that forced the 1993 resignation of TVA&#39;s former nuclear chemistry chief, William F. Jocher, who voiced nuclear safety concerns.
<P>   Jocher won an unspecified legal settlement in the case after the U.S. Department of Labor and the NRC concluded last July that TVA officials -- including Joseph R. Bynum, formerly TVA vice president of nuclear operations -- discriminated against Jocher, once TVA&#39;s director of corporate chemistry and manager of TVA&#39;s Sequoyah Nuclear plant near Soddy-Daisy, Tenn. The NRC inquiry found Jocher was forced to resign because he had raised safety issues in the course of discharging his duties. Jocher, threatened with firing, resigned instead on July 29, 1993.
<P>   The NRC&#39;s order Tuesday also bars Bynum, now TVA&#39;s vice president for fossil operations, from NRC-licensed activities through April 1998 -- a five-year period dating from May 1, 1993, the date of TVA&#39;s corporate discrimination against Jocher.
<P>   Jocher was generally pleased with the size of the fine.
<P>   &#39;&#39;That&#39;s one of the biggest NRC fines ever levied in an individual&#39;s case,&#39;&#39; Jocher said Tuesday. NRC spokesman Roger Hannah confirmed it was the maximum civil penalty NRC could assess for a one-time violation.
<P>   The NRC fined TVA $80,000 last February in a Watts Bar nuclear inspector&#39;s case, and it fined TVA a total of $150,000 late in 1996 for lapses in Sequoyah Nuclear Plant operations.
<P>   Jocher commended NRC Chairman Dr. Shirley Ann Jackson &#39;&#39;for sending a clear message to the nuclear industry.&#39;&#39;
<P>   &#39;&#39;The NRC clearly is taking steps to inform the industry that honesty and integrity count for something -- that the NRC won&#39;t tolerate (nuclear officials) impeding employees from doing their jobs.&#39;&#39;
<P>   According to TVA, Bynum&#39;s move to fossil operations in 1993 was unrelated to Jocher&#39;s case. Bynum this year is earning $115,000, plus was awarded a $25,000 bonus; a TVA spokesman said he received bonuses during his tenure in nuclear operations.
<P>   NRC and Labor Department investigators found Jocher had resigned from TVA under threat of dismissal after he voiced concern over nuclear safety, an activity federal law protects. Jocher had questioned Sequoyah&#39;s operational safety, especially its post-accident sampling, on-line chemistry instrumentation and adequacy of its chemistry training effort. NRC Southeast Regional Administrator Luis Reyes, in a letter Tuesday to TVA, said the NRC considers TVA&#39;s violation of Jocher&#39;s rights at &#39;&#39;the highest level of severity&#39;&#39; since it entailed &#39;&#39;employee discrimination by a senior corporate manager.&#39;&#39;
<P>   &#39;&#39;Discrimination at this level (can) affect the environment throughout the company. The NRC places a high value on nuclear industry employees&#39; freedom to raise potential safety concerns to licensee management or to the NRC.&#39;&#39;
<P>   TVA has 30 days to pay the $100,000 fine or protest it..
<P>   TVA, in a prepared response issued Tuesday, said the fine was &#39;&#39;to address a situation that took place four years ago.&#39;&#39;
<P>   &#39;&#39;TVA has the violation under review,&#39;&#39; according to Kay Whittenburg, TVA nuclear communications manager in Chattanooga. TVA Nuclear, she said, &#39;&#39;has a comprehensive program to ensure that employees feel free to raise potential safety issues without fear of reprisal. TVA has re-emphasized the need for open communication.&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
