<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>EPA pledges to work to clean up Pigeon</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 15, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>EPA pledges to work to clean up Pigeon</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Champion mill variance may stand</FONT></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Rebecca Ferrar, News-Sentinel Nashville bureau</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">N</FONT>ASHVILLE -- EPA officials assured Tennessee environmentalists Tuesday they would work to clean up the polluted Pigeon River, but they may not  overturn a variance approved for Champion International paper mill.
<P>    Environmental Protection Agency administrators from Atlanta, in a meeting with the Tennessee Environmental Council, also said they are waiting to hear Tennessee&#39;s proposal for tougher state water quality standards to improve the Pigeon River 37 miles downstream from the North Carolina paper plant at the Tennessee state line.
<P>    Tennessee filed a petition Monday with North Carolina asking that the variance to its water quality standards be reversed and that the state comply instead with Tennessee&#39;s standards for color in the river.
<P>    The EPA already has agreed to review its approval of the North Carolina variance, despite the slim likelihood of a reversal.
<P>    &#39;&#39;Our lawyers are looking at that,&#39;&#39; said Mike McGhee, director of the water division for the EPA&#39;s Region IV in Atlanta. &#39;&#39;I don&#39;t know of that ever happening before. We&#39;re looking at the possibility of reconsidering the variance.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Should that happen, the variance would &#39;&#39;still be valid&#39;&#39; under North Carolina law, but the EPA would move to establish a tougher federal, water quality standard for that state, McGhee said.
<P>    Meanwhile, John Hankinson Jr., EPA&#39;s regional administrator, who has been corresponding with Attorney General Charles Burson, said it&#39;s now up to Tennessee to propose new state water quality standards to apply to the Pigeon River and to &#39;&#39;make the best call on that.&#39;&#39;
<P>    &#39;&#39;If EPA wants us to define the standard for the purposes of the 1996 permit, we will do it,&#39;&#39; said Justin Wilson, deputy to the governor for policy and former Environment and Conservation commissioner. &#39;&#39;We want to clean up the river.&#39;&#39;
<P>    When he receives a proposal, Hankinson said, contacting Burson would be &#39;&#39;the first phone call I make.&#39;&#39;
<P>    &#39;&#39;When we get that standard I will ask to convene a meeting between Tennessee and North Carolina, and we will try to find a way to see that Tennessee water quality standards are met,&#39;&#39; Hankinson said.
<P>    Tennessee has an &#39;&#39;observable standard&#39;&#39; based on 50 color units, and Tennessee Environmental Council wants that lowered to 10 color units (a measure of the darkness of the water).
<P>    TEC Director Allan Jones said that improved standard is &#39;&#39;the typical color for an unpolluted stream in the Smoky Mountains.&#39;&#39;
<P>    &#39;&#39;EPA ultimately has the hammer,&#39;&#39; Jones said. &#39;&#39;EPA could step in and take over the permit.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Wilson said Tennessee will not propose a standard but will &#39;&#39;interpret that standard for the EPA in connection with the particulars of the North Carolina permit and variance.&#39;&#39;
<P>    The variance was granted last month, and EPA Director Carol Browner wrote Burson noting Tennessee&#39;s concerns came to EPA&#39;s attention late in the permitting process. Also, Vice President Al Gore has written Browner expressing concern that the state&#39;s waters be kept clean.
<P>    Jones said he learned from EPA officials that Champion&#39;s stated reason for getting a variance was because of the &#39;&#39;substantial economic and social impact,&#39;&#39; he said. That means &#39;&#39;profitability,&#39;&#39; he said.
<P>    &#39;&#39;We don&#39;t see where when it comes to clean water, an economic variance is allowed,&#39;&#39; Jones said.
<P>    Members of the Dead Pigeon River Council also attended the meeting, which the EPA asked be closed to the media.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
