<html>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>Monitoring the court</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 15, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>Monitoring the court</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Volunteers needed for drunken driving program</FONT></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">A</FONT> court monitoring program that targets drunken driving cases in Knox County is seeking volunteers as it enters its second year of operation.
<P>   Volunteers will be introduced to the program in a two-hour seminar to be conducted at 6:30 p.m. Tuesday, Jan. 21, in the Small Assembly Room of the City County Building. Cookies and beverages will be provided by AAA East Tennessee.
<P>   At the seminar, a Knox County judge, prosecutor and defense attorney will provide insights and perspectives on the legal process that reviews drunken driving cases. Terri Lynn Corder, who oversees the court monitoring program, will provide information about duties of volunteers.
<P>   While most volunteers are needed to watch cases being heard in court during normal business hours Monday through Friday, some volunteer work also is available at other times.
<P>   The court monitoring program started in the fall of 1995 through the Metropolitan Drug Commission and the DUI Task Force. Its goal is to record how drunken driving cases are handled in the Knox County court system.
<P>   For more information about the court monitoring program and how to volunteer, contact Ron Hanaver at the MDC at 588-5550.
<P>   About a dozen court monitoring volunteers were honored Saturday at a ceremony in Alcoa. Corder presented them with certificates of appreciation for their efforts to record the disposition of each drunken driving case in Knox County.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

	<P><center><font size=2>Return to </font><a href="/"><font size=2>Main</font></a><font size=2>. Copyright &#169; 1996 The Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size=2>webmaster</font></a><font size=2>.</font></center></p>
