<head>
	<title>Naifeh expects tough sells for governor</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 15, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Naifeh expects tough sells for governor</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Tom Humphrey and Rebecca Ferrar, News-Sentinel Nashville bureau</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">N</FONT>ASHVILLE -- As the 100th General Assembly convened on Tuesday, House Speaker Jimmy Naifeh signaled that Gov. Don Sundquist may have a tough time selling some of his initiatives in the state House.
<P>    In the Senate, meanwhile, Lt. Gov. John Wilder cautioned senators against swapping votes and being &#39;&#39;bought&#39;&#39; by friends with a special interest agenda.
<P>    An Oak Ridge minister added a prayer asking God&#39;s help for lawmakers to avoid unneeded infighting or influence by lobbyists.
<P>    The 1997 session began officially at noon with legislators being duly sworn into office and then proceeding to unanimously re-elect Naifeh as head of the House and Wilder as speaker of the Senate.
<P>    Naifeh, presiding over a chamber where Democrats have a 61-38 majority, declared in his opening speech that Sundquist maneuvers in higher education, budget-cutting and government restructuring will be closely scrutinized by House committees.
<P>    Naifeh said his confidence in the Tennessee Higher Education Commission had been shaken by &#39;&#39;recent developments&#39;&#39; -- a reference to the THEC board firing Exeuctive Director Bryant Millsaps at Sundquist&#39;s behest. He said he asked the House Education Committee to &#39;&#39;determine whether the current governance structure addresses the needs of our state.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Rep. Les Winningham, D-Huntsville, who is vice chairman of the Education Committee, said later in an interview that one option to be considered is stripping the governor of power to appoint THEC members and giving it to Wilder and Naifeh instead. The speakers could choose from nominees submitted by the House and Senate education committees, he said.
<P>    As an alternative, Winningham said THEC board appointments by the governor could be made subject to &#39;&#39;meaningful&#39;&#39; confirmation by the House and Senate, with members not allowed to vote on THEC business until after confirmation. Before Millsaps ouster, Sundquist made four appointments to the board -- which then voted to fire Millsaps by one vote.
<P>    Sundquist noted later that he has already vowed to name a special committee to recommend changes in higher education structure, which now has THEC overseeing both the University of Tennessee system and the Board of Regents system. He said the legislative scrutiny could dovetail with that work.
<P>    Naifeh, in his speech, expressed willingness to work with the governor -- though never mentioning Sundquist by name and referring on occasion to accomplishments of former Democratic Gov. Ned McWherter.
<P>    Other Naifeh points:
<P>    * The House Finance Committee will get extra &#39;&#39;resources and assistance&#39;&#39; to check Sundquist&#39;s budget figures and provide &#39;&#39;assurances the state budget is responsible and without waste&#39;&#39; at a time when &#39;&#39;the latest administration&#39;s estimates&#39;&#39; indicate a $100 million revenue shortfall this year and $300 million in the next year.
<P>    * Because &#39;&#39;we should not make wholesale moves in departments just for the sake of making moves,&#39;&#39; the House Government Operations Committee will scrutinize Sundquist plans to abolish the state Department of Mental Health and Mental Retardation and to consolidate state department lawyers into a central office.
<P>    Wilder, meanwhile, declared in his opening speech that many people think legislators can be bought with money.
<P>    &#39;&#39;But that&#39;s not what will buy you. What will buy you is two things. One is friendship. That will get you before anything that I know. You have a friend ask you to do something, a friend . . . who helps you get elected. You got to be careful.
<P>    &#39;&#39;The other, and it&#39;s wrong, is when someone says, &#39;I got a good old bill here. I can help you. Swap it out.&#39; Those two are totally wrong.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Pastor Michael Wood of St. Mary&#39;s Catholic Church in Oak Ridge, who offered the opening prayer at the Senate chamber, suggested in the prayer that the Legislature may need God&#39;s blessing even as he asked it.
<P>    Wood asked that God help lawmakers when their &#39;&#39;ideologies and egos clash&#39;&#39; and when &#39;&#39;programs and politics part company, as they surely will.&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

	<P><center><font size=2>Return to </font><a href="/"><font size=2>Main</font></a><font size=2>. Copyright &#169; 1996 The Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size=2>webmaster</font></a><font size=2>.</font></center></p>
</body>
