	<title>Rain, then more arctic air in East Tennessee forecast</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 15, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Rain, then more arctic air in East Tennessee forecast</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Gina Stafford, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">F</FONT>reezing rain and sleet have been dropped from today&#39;s forecast, which calls for this afternoon&#39;s rain to be met by temperatures too warm to cause icy driving conditions.
<P>   After a forecast low near 20 for today, the National Weather Service expects temperatures to peak in the 40s and puts today&#39;s chance of rain at 60 percent and ups the odds to 70 percent for tonight.
<P>   &#39;&#39;It&#39;ll be becoming warmer through the day, and temperatures when the rain falls will be the critical factor,&#39;&#39; NWS meteorologist Susan Faust said.
<P>   Temperatures are forecast to fall into the mid-30s tonight, go no higher than the upper 30s on Thursday and then continue to drop under partly cloudy skies.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We&#39;re expecting some more cold, arctic air to start moving into the region starting Thursday,&#39;&#39; Faust said. 
<P>   &#39;&#39;Through the weekend, the extended forecast calls for lows in the teens on Friday and Saturday morning. Highs are likely to be only in the 20s on Friday and maybe in the 20s or 30s on Saturday.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Currently, Friday and Saturday also are expected to bring only partly cloudy -- and not sleeting or snowing -- skies.
<P>   More than half the state&#39;s 95 counties kept schools closed or operated on delayed schedules Tuesday because of lingering ice on secondary roads following last week&#39;s wintry blast.
<P>   In the Middle Tennessee town of Hohenwald, officials with the Elephant Sanctuary were busy caring for three residents unaccustomed to wintry temperatures.
<P>   Barbara, Jenny and Tara -- three Asian elephants -- were outfitted with vinyl pillow cases to serve as elephant-sized ear muffs. Carol Buckley, executive director of the center, said the elephants are used to temperatures between 32 degrees and 120 degrees and are being confined to a barn when necessary. For trips outside, the animals don blankets.
<P>   &#39;&#39;They were not created to live in subfreezing climates,&#39;&#39; she said. &#39;&#39;Their ears are so thin, and their trunk is an extension of their nose, so you want to keep it moist inside. They have a thick layer of body fat, but it&#39;s not for protecting them.&#39;&#39;
<P>    
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
