<head>
	<title>Man gets 9 years for tubing theft</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 15, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Man gets 9 years for tubing theft</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Gina Stafford, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">A</FONT> former deliveryman who pleaded guilty to stealing $67,000 worth of copper tubing from his employer was given a nine-year prison sentence Monday by Knox County Criminal Court Judge Mary Beth Leibowitz.
<P>   James Roland Cupp, 37, of Corryton was a driver/deliveryman for Engert Plumbing and Heating Inc. from 1990 until he was fired on June 8, 1995, according to Knox County Assistant District Attorney Lew Walton.
<P>   Cupp&#39;s termination followed an internal company investigation by Engert officials, who had noticed materials shortages and conducted an audit, Walton said.
<P>   The theft with which Cupp was charged occurred between November 1994 and June 8, 1995, Walton said.
<P>   &#39;&#39;It is a white-collar crime in the sense it was committed by an employee against an employer,&#39;&#39; Walton said, &#39;&#39;and it was investigated and handled by the white-collar crime unit of the district attorney&#39;s office.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Cupp was charged with Class D felony theft -- stealing property worth $1,000 to $10,000 -- in a warrant on June 9, 1995. Further investigation resulted in an indictment by a grand jury in November 1995 on the highest level of felony theft, Class B, for stealing property valued in excess of $60,000, Walton said.
<P>   Cupp, a husband and father of two children, previously had been charged with misdemeanor offenses, including writing worthless checks, secreting goods and public intoxication, Walton said.
<P>   On Oct. 29, 1996, Cupp pleaded guilty to stealing $67,208.24 worth of materials from his employer. He sold the stolen tubing to a Knoxville scrap metal dealer, Walton said.
<P>   Cupp faced an eight- to 12-year sentence at Monday&#39;s hearing, which lasted more than an hour. Leibowitz denied Cupp&#39;s request for probation and ordered his sentence to be served in a state penitentiary. Restitution to his former employer was not ordered.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
