<head>
	<title>Air Force administrator is named new president of ORAU by board</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 15, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Air Force administrator is named new president of ORAU by board</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">O</FONT>AK RIDGE -- Dr. Ronald D. Townsend will be the new president of Oak Ridge Associated Universities, the ORAU board announced Tuesday following a six-month search.
<P>    His appointment is effective April 7.
<P>    Townsend is commandant of the U.S. Air Force Institute of Technology, which is located at the Wright-Patterson Air Force Base in Ohio. The military institute includes two graduate schools for advanced degrees in aerospace technology and management, as well as an engineering research laboratory and continuing education programs.
<P>    He will become the fifth person to take the helm of ORAU, which is celebrating its 50th year as a not-for-profit consortium of universities and contractor for the federal government. Along with providing services to its 88 member colleges and universities, ORAU manages the Oak Ridge Institute for Science and Education for the U.S. Department of Energy.
<P>    Townsend succeeds Dr. Jon Veigel, who resigned last year as ORAU president, citing health reasons. Since then, Dr. Jim Drewry has been acting ORAU president, as well as holding his position of director of ORISE.
<P>    &#39;&#39;The future of ORAU is filled with opportunity, and I am delighted to be part of it,&#39;&#39; Townsend said in his acceptance letter.
<P>    A search committee reviewed the backgrounds of more than 125 potential candidates, making recommendations to the board.
<P>    ORAU has an annual budget of more than $75 million, with a staff of about 700, most of whom work in Oak Ridge. The consortium also maintains offices in Washington, D.C., Aiken, S.C., and Albuquerque, N.M.
<P>    Townsend, a native of Kansas, spent 24 years in the Air Force and previously served as director of weather operations for the Headquarters Air Combat Command. He holds degrees in mathematics from Kansas State University and a Ph.D. in meteorology from the University of Wisconsin-Madison.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
