<head>
	<title>Council OKs $12 million in bonds to meet expanding demand for gas</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 15, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Council OKs $12 million in bonds to meet expanding demand for gas</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Jim Balloch, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">K</FONT>noxville City Council voted Tuesday to authorize the issuance of up to $12 million in bonds to allow KUB to meet its expanding demand for gas service.
<P>   &#39;&#39;All money (from the bonds) wil be used to extend gas services to the customers who are asking for it,&#39;&#39; said Jim Carmon, head of KUB&#39;s gas division.
<P>   &#39;&#39;The revenues will pay for the bonds.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Carmon said increased demand for gas service is for the most part evenly distributed throughout KUB&#39;s service area.
<P>   In another matter, council voted 8-1 to overrule the Board of Zoning Appeals and allow Chrysler automobile dealer Harry Lane to erect a second sign on his lot at 240 N. Peters Road.
<P>   Lane said the second sign, which will be about 35 feet high, will promote the KIA line of imported cars from Korea.
<P>   There was some opposition to the measure, but Lane said he was not going to erect a &#39;&#39;junky-looking&#39;&#39; sign.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I see nothing wrong with putting up a nice looking sign. In fact, it is a pretty sign,&#39;&#39; Lane told council.
<P>   Councilwoman Jean Teague&#39;s motion to deny Lane&#39;s request failed, as only Councilwoman Carlene Malone supported it. However, when a motion to approve Lane&#39;s request was made, Teague voted for it, and Malone was the sole dissenting vote.
<P>   In other business, council unanimously approved the appointment of Robert &#39;&#39;Bob&#39;&#39; Booker to fill an unexpired term on the Historic Zoning Commission.
<P>   Council also unanimously re-appointed Donnie Lee and David Draper to their posts on the Better Building Board.
<P>   Ashe reported to council that the city has recovered its costs in eliminating a ramshackle motel that many South Knoxvillians regarded as a danger and an eyesore.
<P>   Ashe said the elimination of the structure at 4916 Chapman Highway began in 1991 with citizen complaints to Councilman Gary Underwood, who pressed the issue.
<P>   When the building was declared &#39;&#39;unsafe for human habitation,&#39;&#39; the owner refused to rehabilitate it or demolish it.
<P>   The city then hired a private firm to demolish it for $28,100.
<P>   The city then sued in Chancery Court to recover its costs, won a judgment, and shortly after a lien was attached on some of the owner&#39;s other properties, the city was paid the $28,100, Ashe said.
<P>   Underwood said that after the building was demolished, several citizens indicated to him that the crime rate in the vicinity was noticeably reduced.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
