<head>
	<title>S.C. man sentenced in bank fraud</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 15, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>S.C. man sentenced in bank fraud</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Randy Kenner, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">A</FONT> Greenville, S.C., man was sentenced Tuesday in federal court to a year in prison for committing bank fraud in which he stole $28,500 from First Tennessee Bank.
<P>   Thomas William Bledsoe, who resided in Knoxville when the offenses occurred in 1994, was sentenced by U.S. District Judge James Jarvis.
<P>   Bledsoe, 51, got the money by opening accounts for fictitious businesses at both Home Federal Bank and First Tennessee and sending checks between the accounts. 
<P>   He blamed his troubles on drug and alcohol abuse and said he had intended to pay back the money with the proceeds of an investment in a Mexican venture.
<P>   Asked if he had anything to say before the sentence, Bledsoe told Jarvis, &#39;&#39;Uh, no sir. I swear that nothing like this will ever happen again. I&#39;m sorry.&#39;&#39;
<P>   According to court documents, Bledsoe opened the accounts in September 1994 and committed the offense the next November.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Bledsoe stated that during the latter part of November 1994 he needed funds for another business venture in Mexico,&#39;&#39; states a factual basis prepared by Assistant U.S. Attorney Jimmie Baxter and signed by Bledsoe.
<P>   Bledsoe, using the alias Landon Bryant, had opened a Home Federal account in the name of Smokie Mountain Advertising and an account at First Tennessee in the name of Direct Mail Associates using small deposits.
<P>   On Nov. 22, 1994, he deposited three checks supposedly written by Smokie Mountain payable to Direct Mail Associates totaling $28,500.
<P>   First Tennessee credited the amounts and the following day Bledsoe, using the Landon Bryant alias, obtained checks totaling $27,050 from three different First Tennessee branch banks in Knoxville.
<P>   Jarvis also ordered Bledsoe to make $28,500 restitution to First Tennessee.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
