<head>
	<title>Ex-TVA engineer gets hearing on firing</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper Business News">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif" alt="Knoxville News-Sentinel Online -- Business News" align=bottom border=0 width=595 height=176></a><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td align=left valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 15, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Ex-TVA engineer gets hearing on firing</B></font><basefont size=6><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Psychological testing challenged</FONT></basefont></FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Jerry Dean, News-Sentinel business writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">A</FONT> former TVA security systems engineer<B> </B>says she will testify in a Department of Labor hearing today that she was psychologically tested and then fired by TVA after she balked at approving an advanced security system for nuclear plants.
<P>   Glenda Kay Miller, former security engineer at TVA&#39;s Browns Ferry Nuclear plant, alleges TVA made her undergo hostile interviews that led to her dismissal.
<P>   Miller, 50, of Chattanooga, said she questioned reliability of a proposed &#39;&#39;hand geometry&#39;&#39; employee identification system which TVA since has installed in its nuclear plants near Athens, Ala., and at Watts Bar and Sequoyah plants in East Tennessee.
<P>   Miller said Dr. Tom Saiwaj, TVA lead psychologist, and Dr. Lynn Boatwright, contracted to TVA, asked her about such personal matters as church attendance, whether she missed her husband when he traveled, and whether she had unpaid parking tickets exceeding $100.
<P>   Miller told The News-Sentinel the psychologists sought to provoke a response TVA could use as a basis for revoking the security clearance she had to have to work at TVA.
<P>   By the time of her dismissal, Miller, a 1987 UT-Chattanooga honors graduate, had eight years&#39; experience in development, implementation and support of real-time computer systems. She said her performance evaluations reflected no adverse reports until a Feb. 6, 1995 &#39;&#39;service review&#39;&#39; suddenly noted work problems TVA considered &#39;&#39;aberrant behavior.&#39;&#39;
<P>   TVA spokesman John Moulton said the Department of Labor&#39;s Wage and Hour Division initially ruled against Miller and for TVA in October 1996. Miller appealed and was granted an administrative hearing.
<P>   TVA fired Miller Sept. 11, 1995. Branded &#39;&#39;unreliable and untrustworthy,&#39;&#39; Miller said she has since been unable to find any work. Income loss, she said, made her sell a 34-acre farm she owned at LaFayette, Ga. 
<P>   She filed a January 1996 complaint with the U.S. Department of Labor&#39;s Wage and Hour Division, alleging TVA harassed her for questioning management officials&#39; assertions. The Wall Street Journal, in a March 20, 1996, article, said complaints of being pressured to undergo psychological testing, like Miller&#39;s, are increasingly common among whistleblowers at U.S. nuclear plants.
<P>   Miller, in a January 1996 letter to Carol Merchant of DOL&#39;s Wage and Hour Division, said TVA hired her in July 1987 at a $27,320 salary. By 1990, her salary exceeded $50,000 after she received excellent work evaluations.
<P>   Miller, as corporate project leader in TVA&#39;s Nuclear Group, was to upgrade integrated security computer systems at Browns Ferry, Sequoyah and Watts Bar nuclear plants. Her duties included evaluating computer system design and supervising regulatory compliance.
<P>   But beginning in January 1995, Miller said, she refused to approve untested systems for the physical security upgrade project manager at Browns Ferry. 
<P>   Miller said she told superiors she had insufficient time to examine a &#39;&#39;hand geometry&#39;&#39; infrared identification system.
<P>   She was &#39;&#39;systematically removed&#39;&#39; from her job, she said, &#39;&#39;under pretext of my so-called inability to maintain a security clearance as required.&#39;&#39;
<P>   A Browns Ferry manager, Miller alleged, in January 1995 called her at Sequoyah Nuclear to seek her verbal approval of the hand geometry ID system. Miller told The News-Sentinel:
<P>   &#39;&#39;I told him I was tired of these hot-shot, nontechnical TVA managers flying around the country buying high-tech toys to brag about at their cocktail parties -- then telling us to &#39;make them work&#39; after the fact.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Miller said her persecution was part of a &#39;&#39;pattern&#39;&#39; of abuses in which psychologists purge from TVA Nuclear ranks any workers who &#39;&#39;refuse to participate in unlawful acts.&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P>
<P>
