	<title>Business Briefs</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper Business News">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif" alt="Knoxville News-Sentinel Online -- Business News" align=bottom border=0 width=595 height=176></a><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td align=left valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 15, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Business Briefs</B></font><basefont size=6><!--SUBHEAD--></basefont></FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<h3>Proffitt&#39;s names group execs in Alabama</h3>
<P>
<P>   Proffitt&#39;s Inc. has announced management appointments to its newly formed Proffitt&#39;s Merchandising Group headquartered in Birmingham, Ala.
<P>   Sharron Williams has been promoted to senior vice president and corporate general merchandise manager of cosmetics for the merchandising group. She previously served as senior vice president and general merchandise manager of cosmetics, fashion accessories, intimate apparel, children&#39;s and shoes for the McRae&#39;s Division.
<P>   Peggy Eskenasi has been named senior vice president of private label and brand development. She was formerly a merchandising executive with Frederick Atkins Inc., a New York buying cooperative. She was responsible for developing private brands for member stores.
<P>   Mike Molitor, who has held the post of senior vice president of merchandise planning and analysis since February, has been named to the same position in the merchandising group. Molitor served as vice president of merchandising strategies at Younkers from March 1994 to January 1996.
<P>   Fran Jose has been promoted to vice president of marketing and visual for the group. Jose joined the Younker Division of Proffitt&#39;s Inc. in June, as vice president of merchandising strategies. He formerly served in merchandise and financial planning roles with May Department Stores Co. and Saks Fifth Avenue.
<P>   Robert Mosco, the former president and chief executive officer of the Younkers Division, was named president and chief executive officer of the merchandising group in October.
<P>
<P><h3>Bank sees profits increase</h3>
<P>
<P>   First Central Bank reported ending 1996 with a 51 percent rise in net income over the previous year.
<P>   Net earnings were $765,142, up from $505,262. Total loans outstanding increased 27.3 percent to $57.5 million, and year-end deposits were $67.8 million, up 12.1 percent.
<P>   First Central, based in Loudon County, was established in 1991 and includes branches in Lenoir City, Farragut, Loudon and Tellico Village.
<P>
<P><h3>Asarco taps new managers</h3>
<P>
<P>   Asarco Inc. has named Donald H. Walters, general manager of Asarco&#39;s Tennessee Mines Division, to a special management process team, and Taie Li has been named to succeed him at the Tennessee Mines Division.
<P>   The division includes three operating zinc mines and one mine currently on standby near Knoxville.  Li, 38, has been manager of Asarco&#39;s Globe plant in Denver.
<P>    Walter, one of three senior Asarco executives named to the Management Process Team, will design, develop and guide the implementation of a state-of-the-art environmental management system. Walter, 51, has been general manager of the Tennessee Mines Division since 1994.
<P>
<P><h3>State&#39;s outlook good</h3>
<P>
<P>   Although the rapid economic growth Tennessee enjoyed from 1990 through 1995 has ended, the state&#39;s economy remains strong, a University of Tennessee economist said Tuesday.
<P>    Bill Fox of the UT Center for Business and Economic Research offered the assessment as he explained the state&#39;s projected shortfall in revenue collections at a meeting of a UT-Knoxville advisory group.
<P>    &#39;&#39;Revenue growth in Tennessee does not really keep pace with the economy,&#39;&#39; Fox said. &#39;&#39;It is our particular choice of tax structures that has led to this result.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Fox said Tennessee&#39;s economy now has entered a mature phase when state revenues will grow less quickly than in the previous period of rapid expansion. 
<P>    &#39;&#39;Because we have a tax base that relies heavily on taxation of sales and consumption, revenues are going to grow at only about 85 to 90 percent of the economy at this point in the business cycle,&#39;&#39; Fox told the Chancellor&#39;s Associates.
<P>    Estimates of the state&#39;s revenue shortfalls range from $80 million during the current budget year, which ends June 30, to $300 million next fiscal year.
<P>
<P><h3>Names in the news</h3>
<P>
<P>   Knoxville-based Home & Garden Television has promoted <B>Dusty Schmidt </B>to vice president. He will oversee the network&#39;s creative services department. He formerly was HGTV&#39;s director of creative services. . . . <B>Paige von Hoffmann </B>has been promoted to senior account executive for StaffingSolutions&#39; Knoxville offices. Previously, she served as an account executive. . . . <B>Marilyn Cobble</B>, a vice president of BankFirst, has been elected vice president of the Southern Chapter of Robert Morris Associates, a group of financial service institutions and professionals that promotes credit risk identification and management. . . .<B> Thomas H. Lee</B>, formerly of Knoxville, has joined the Nashville law firm of Waller Lansden Dortch & Davis and will be practicing in the firm&#39;s litigation group. He was a judicial clerk for U.S. Dist. Judge Tom Wiseman, and received his law degree from Vanderbilt University. 
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
