<head>
	<title>Sports Briefs</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 15, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470><BASEFONT SIZE="6">
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Sports Briefs</B></FONT><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<h3>English League goalies cash in on &#39;mistakes&#39;?</h3>
<P>
<P>     Premier League goalkeepers <B>Bruce Grobbelaar </B>and <B>Hans Segers </B>were handed huge sums of cash by a Far Eastern betting syndicate to make sure their teams lost games, a jury was told Tuesday at Winchester, England.
<P>    &#39;&#39;In front of 30,000 or 40,000 or 50,000 fans and a TV audience of millions a goalkeeper can&#39;t simply let the ball roll in between his legs,&#39;&#39; prosecutor <B>David Calvert Smith </B>said. &#39;&#39;However, goalkeepers do make mistakes sometimes and therefore it may be that the odd deliberate mistake may escape attention.&#39;&#39;
<P>    The prosecutor said Grobbelaar, goalkeeper on Zimbabwe&#39;s national team, was able to buy two Mercedes with the money he received.
<P>    &#39;&#39;He was embittered by the fact that Liverpool was not paying him enough, especially compared with other newer players, and he wanted to make as much as he could over the next couple of years,&#39;&#39; the prosecutor said.
<P>    Grobbelaar was earning $270,000 a year at Liverpool, he said.
<P>    Segers deposited two large sums of cash into a Swiss branch of an American bank during the 1993 and 1994 seasons, the prosecutor said.
<P>    Grobbelaar and Segers went on trial Tuesday along with Segers&#39; former Wimbledon teammate <B>John Fashanu </B>and Malaysian businessman <B>Heng Suan Lim.</B>
<P>    The four were accused of conspiracy to give or accept cash to rig the results of certain Premier League games between 1991 and 1994, in the biggest match-fixing scandal in English soccer in 32 years. The four have denied the charges.
<P>
<P><h3>Football</h3>
<P>
<P>* <B>Todd Kirk</B>, an offensive lineman on Tennessee&#39;s 1985 SEC championship team, has accepted a job as offensive line coach at Presbyterian College in Clinton, S.C. New Presbyterian coach <B>Daryl Dickey</B>, also a former Vol, hired Kirk, who recently was offensive line coach at Tennessee-Martin.
<P>
<P><h3>Figure skating</h3>
<P>
<P>* Olympic champion <B>Oksana Baiul </B>was arrested in Bloomfield, Conn., on charges of drunken and reckless driving stemming from a car crash early Sunday. The 19-year-old Ukranian surrendered to police and was released without bond. No date was immediately set for her appearance in court. She apologized in a statement released after her arrest.
<P>
<P><h3>Golf</h3>
<P>
<P>* <B>Arnold Palmer </B>will undergo surgery today for prostate cancer, the Mayo Clinic  in Rochester, Minn., has announced. Palmer, 67, who has been at the clinic for two days of tests, will remain in the hospital for several days and continue recovering as an outpatient.
<P>
<P><h3>Tennis</h3>
<P>
<P>* Prosecutors in Mannheim, Germany, sought a jail term of six years and nine months for <B>Peter Graf,</B> the father of <B>Steffi Graf,</B> charged with evading taxes on more than $26.5 million of his daughter&#39;s tennis earnings. Final defense arguments in his trial will start Friday. The verdict is expected Jan. 24.
<P>* <B>Ignacio Truyol </B>of Spain became the first tennis player to be suspended for drug use, testing positive for an anabolic steroid and a stimulant. Truyol, 23, who violated ATP Tour rules established in 1990, will be banned from all tournaments for one year. He will forfeit $39,985 in prize money and ranking points earned since July 1996.
<P>
<P><h3>Baseball</h3>
<P>
<P>* The Chicago White Sox, looking to shore up their starting rotation, signed Cy Young Award winning pitcher <B>Doug Drabek </B>to a one-year contract. The 34-year-old, 137-112 lifetime with a 3.41 ERA, spent the last four seasons with Houston.
<P>* <B>Ozzie Smith,</B> after a 19-year career at shortstop, is turning broadcaster. He will be host of &#39;&#39;This Week In Baseball,&#39;&#39; a weekly TV show of highlights produced by Major League Baseball.
<P>* Kansas City signed left-handed reliever <B>Mitch Williams </B>to a minor league contract and have invited him to spring training camp. Williams, 32, last year aborted a comeback attempt with Philadelphia.
<P>
<P><h3>Basketball</h3>
<P>
<P>* <B>LeRon Williams,</B> who played for Florida the past two seasons, has registered for classes at South Carolina and will play for the Gamecocks next December. The 6-7 junior forward started 24 of 28 games last season and averaged 10 points and 4.8 rebounds.
<P>
<P><h3>Boxing</h3>
<P>
<P>* <B>Sugar Ray Leonard,</B> whose charisma and virtuoso style endeared him to boxing fans, and flamboyant promoter <B>Don King,</B> often regarded as a ring rogue, will be enshrined into the International Boxing Hall of Fame. Former light heavyweight champion <B>Jose Torres </B>was the other living honoree in the 1997 induction class of 13.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
