<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>TennCare net for kids expanded</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 14, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>TennCare net for kids expanded</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> All children without insurance now eligible for coverage</FONT></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Tom Humphrey, News-Sentinel Nashville bureau</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">N</FONT>ASHVILLE -- All Tennessee children without medical insurance will be eligible for enrollment in TennCare on April 1 under a plan announced on Monday by Gov. Don Sundquist.
<P>    &#39;&#39;We could be the first state, and rightfully so, to have universal health care for children,&#39;&#39; said Sundquist.
<P>    The proposal requires approval by the state Legislature. Initial reaction from lawmakers Monday was highly favorable for the proposal, with criticism limited to concerns that TennCare is not made available to enough adults.
<P>    The Sundquist administration estimated that about 68,000 children will become eligible for enrollment in TennCare because of the policy change. They projected that about 75 percent of those eligible -- or 51,000 -- will be signed up and push total TennCare enrollment past 1.2 million again.
<P>    When that happens, the governor said about 95 percent of all Tennesseans will then be covered by insurance. The state had hit that level previously, but the coverage rate slipped to 94.2 percent last year.
<P>    The remaining 5 percent without coverage would amount to about 260,000 persons -- almost all adults.
<P>    Opening the door to persons under age 18 will cost the state about $20 million, Sundquist said. When federal matching money is added, the total new spending will be about $55 million, he said.
<P>    The governor said that state funding will be a priority in the budget for the coming year but that allowing adults to enroll as well &#39;&#39;would be beyond the money we have.&#39;&#39;
<P>    The administration is already looking at ways to cut about $300 million in state spending for the 1997-98 fiscal year because of a projected revenue shortfall.
<P>    TennCare replaced Medicaid as a system of providing health care to the poor on Jan. 1, 1994. Initially, the state&#39;s &#39;&#39;working poor&#39;&#39; -- who did not qualify for Medicaid but had no insurance otherwise -- were allowed to enroll as well, with premium payments based on income. Those with income below the federal poverty level pay no premiums.
<P>    Enrollment to such persons was closed on Jan. 1, 1995, and there has been considerable discussion over when to reopen it. Monday&#39;s move amounts to something of a compromise and was widely hailed.
<P>    &#39;&#39;Nobody is going to be against covering kids,&#39;&#39; said Tony Garr, executive director of the Tennessee Health Care Campaign. &#39;&#39;It is a wonderful movement to have universal access for kids. . . Hopefully, (uninsured) adults will someday have access, too.&#39;&#39;
<P>    There was also praise for the initiative among legislators attending a meeting of the TennCare Oversight Committee on Monday, even from lawmakers critical of remaining shortcomings in TennCare coverage. The committee meeting was called to discuss TennCare Partners, the problem-plagued program that last year expanded TennCare&#39;s umbrella to cover those suffering mental as well as physical illness. 
<P>    Sen. Robert Rochelle, D-Lebanon, said that opening access to children was &#39;&#39;appreciated and noteworthy.&#39;&#39; But he said the mental health program is now open only to persons on TennCare while a growing number of persons -- some of them in dire need of preventative mental health treatment -- are ineligible for TennCare.
<P>    &#39;&#39;They&#39;re the ones who are going to be shooting their spouse tomorrow. They&#39;re the ones who are going to be beating up on their kids tonight,&#39;&#39; he told the committee.
<P>    &#39;&#39;This golden goose is going to be killed unless we go a lot further in opening up enrollment,&#39;&#39; Rochelle said.
<P>    State Finance Commissioner John Ferguson said the opening of TennCare to all youngsters, with its accompanying infusion of funds, should help relieve financial problems of the behavioral health organizations, or BHOs, that have complained of inadequate state funding.
<P>    Sundquist said the new policy of allowing children to enroll is seen as a permanent change with no time limit.
<P>    The proposal was made with the support of federal Health Care Financing Administration (HCFA) officials, who oversee such programs. 
<P>    &#39;&#39;This is great news for families who haven&#39;t been able to afford health insurance for their children,&#39;&#39; said HCFA Administrator Bruce C. Vladeck.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
