<html>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>Autopsy reports boy shot four times</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 14, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>Autopsy reports boy shot four times</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Amy Smith, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">A</FONT> final autopsy report shows 12-year-old Donald Edward &#39;&#39;Dewayne&#39;&#39; Kesterson was shot in the head at close-range and another time -- fatally -- behind his left ear.
<P>   The autopsy report, made public Monday, also shows Kesterson was shot two more times from behind -- once in his left shoulder and again in his left arm.
<P>   And a final autopsy released earlier on his mother, 29-year-old Anita Gregg, shows she was shot three times. The fatal shot in the right side of her head caused multiple skull fractures, hemorrhaging and brain injury. Gregg also was shot in the left back of her neck and the back of her left wrist and hand.
<P>   Gregg and her son were shot and killed the evening of Nov. 7, 1996, the day they were moving back into the Nubbin Ridge Road home of her estranged husband, Gregory Gene Gregg, in an effort to save the marriage.
<P>   The shootings came a week after Anita Gregg obtained an order of protection against her husband of 16 months.
<P>   In her petition for the order, Anita Gregg alleged her husband previously had shot at her, shoved her and tried to strangle her.
<P>   Gregory Gregg, the son of Buddy Gregg who owns Buddy Gregg Motor Homes, has been charged with shooting his wife and stepson with a 9mm pistol.
<P>   The autopsy on Kesterson showed stippling, or powder tattooing, around the shot to the left top of his head, which indicates the gun was fired at close range, according to Knox County Medical Examiner Dr. Sandra Elkins.
<P>   The presence of stippling generally indicates a gun has been fired within 12 to 18 inches, Elkins said, although in some, but very few handguns, stippling will occur out to 24 inches.
<P>   The autopsy reported no stippling around the other gunshot wounds, but that doesn&#39;t mean they couldn&#39;t have been fired at close range because some of those had gone through clothing that could have filtered stippling, Elkins said.
<P>   &#39;&#39;The stippling is always a significant finding because it indicates a wound is no longer considered to be caused from a distance,&#39;&#39; said Elkins. &#39;&#39;Someone has to be pretty much on top of them so you see that type of wound.&#39;&#39;
<P>   First-degree murder charges against Gregg are pending before a grand jury, according to John Gill, special counsel to Knox County District Attorney General Randy Nichols.
<P>   Gregg claimed he fired on the victims after they armed themselves, but in murder warrants the Knox County Sheriff&#39;s Department says physical evidence inside the house does not support Gregg&#39;s story.
<P>   &#39;&#39;The autopsy reports are by their nature graphic and speak for themselves as to the physical evidence,&#39;&#39; said Tom Dillard, Gregg&#39;s attorney. &#39;&#39;We are certainly reviewing the reports. It&#39;s early in the investigation.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Gregg remains in the Knox County Jail on a $1 million bond.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

	<P><center><font size=2>Return to </font><a href="/"><font size=2>Main</font></a><font size=2>. Copyright &#169; 1996 The Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size=2>webmaster</font></a><font size=2>.</font></center></p>
