<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>Manhunt nabs 2 burglary suspects, but third slips through net on ATV</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i>January 14, 1997</i> </td>
        <td width="470"><font size="6"><b>Manhunt nabs 2 burglary
        suspects, but third slips through net on ATV<!--SUBHEAD--></b></font><table
        border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="250"
        align ="right">
            <tr>
                <td><img src="../images/bloodhoundsMC.jpg"
                width="250" height="149"><br>
                <img src="../../images/v3/credits/MCcredit.gif"
                width="144" height="21"><p><font size="2"><strong>Deputies
                from several counties enter a Briceville home on
                Slatestone Road in Anderson County Monday in
                search of two suspects after a bloodhound
                followed the scent to this location. No one was
                found and the search continues.</strong></font></p>
                </td>
            </tr>
        </table>
        <p><font size="2"><i>By Stan DeLozier, News-Sentinel
        staff writer</i></font></p>
        <p><br>
        <font size="5">A</font>nderson County officers caught two
        burglary suspects Monday, but a third eluded them on an
        all-terrain vehicle in rugged coal-mining country near
        Briceville. </p>
        <p>Charles R. ''Chuck'' Daugherty, 24, and Chris
        ''Skeeter Bill'' Moser, 19, were arrested after Anderson
        County Sheriff's Department Investigators Dale Brown and
        Jeff Peterson saw them in a vehicle on Slatestone Road,
        said sheriff's spokesman Mark Whaley. Officers from
        several agencies late Monday were looking for Johnnie
        Mack Wilson. Whaley said Wilson was on an ATV and hiding
        in north Anderson County mountains. </p>
        <p>''We've used a helicopter to try and spot him from the
        air,'' Whaley said. ''But there are miles and miles and
        miles of old mining roads he can get on.'' </p>
        <p>A fourth suspect, Deena Leinart, 22, of Halls, was
        arrested Saturday in Roane County. Officers say the four
        are believed to have committed burglaries in Roane,
        Meigs, Anderson, Morgan and Loudon counties. </p>
        <p>Officers from several agencies began searching for the
        three men after they were flushed from a Meigs County
        home when the owners returned. They are believed to have
        committed three earlier burglaries Saturday afternoon,
        two of them in Roane County. </p>
        <p>Meigs County Sheriff Walter Hickman said Steve Woodby
        and his wife returned to their home on state Highway 58
        late Saturday afternoon and saw three men run from the
        back of the building. Woodby gave chase across a field.
        His wife drove along the road to try to see what was
        going on and eventually returned home. </p>
        <p>''The girl (Leinart) had pulled into the driveway,''
        Hickman said. ''Mrs. Woodby blocked her in, and we caught
        her right there.'' </p>
        <p>He said Moser, Daugherty and Wilson fled into woods
        and officers could not find them by nightfall. Sunday
        morning a van owned by Shiloh Baptist Church was
        discovered stolen. It later was found parked along a road
        in Briceville. </p>
        <p>Hickman said the four are suspected of burglarizing
        another home. prior to the Woodby home burglary. </p>
        <p>In Roane County, Sheriff's Department Detective Linda
        Booth said the group is believed to have broken into
        residences on River Road and Grigsby Hollow Road. Loot
        taken from the four homes included video equipment,
        cameras, guns and jewelry, Booth said. She said most of
        it was recovered in Roane County. </p>
        <p>''They ditched it -- literally threw it into a ditch
        along Keylon Hollow Road,'' Booth said. ''They planned to
        pick it up later.'' </p>
        <p>Whaley said Brown and Peterson were patroling in the
        area when they saw a car they believed two of the
        suspects were in and began to follow it. </p>
        <p>''They (Moser and Daugherty) got suspicious and bailed
        out,'' Whaley said. ''They caught Daugherty first right
        along the road, but Moser got away on the steep
        terrain.'' </p>
        <p>In the melee, Peterson suffered a broken ankle that
        will require surgery, Whaley said. Brown injured his
        knee. Whaley said Moser surrendered to officers about
        three hours later along Slatestone Road. ''He had gotten
        a car,'' he said. ''He just drove up to the officers and
        said, 'I'm the one you're looking for.' '' </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

