<head>
	<title>Frist to focus on balanced budget</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 14, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Frist to focus on balanced budget</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Richard Powelson, News-Sentinel Washington bureau</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">W</FONT>ASHINGTON -- Sen. Bill Frist said he will spend much of his time this year working with fellow Budget Committee members on ways to balance the budget by 2002, and also to help pass a constitutional amendment requiring a balanced budget annually.
<P>   &#39;&#39;By just getting the deficit down to zero,&#39;&#39; he said, Americans could look forward to more jobs and lower interest rates on mortgages and loans.
<P>   The Tennessee Republican said he hopes President Clinton&#39;s 1998 budget proposal for Congress, which will become public next month, will contain suggestions and goals in all federal programs and not just appear to cut spending through &#39;&#39;smoke and mirrors.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Balanced budget planning is his top priority, Frist said.
<P>   As part of that goal, he said Congress must pass major Medicare reforms that will lower exploding cost increases. The reforms will take a couple of years to produce major savings, so they should be passed soon to avoid excessive change later, he said.
<P>   A former heart and lung transplant surgeon, Frist said he will push again this year for his bill to improve managed care. Currently, he said, physicians often are kept from the decision-making process on ways to lower costs, leading to ill-advised insurance policies such as the one that pushed many maternity patients out of hospital rooms after only one night&#39;s stay.
<P>   His bill would allow physicians to set up managed-care plans to compete with those administered by insurance companies. Insurance company plans sometimes are based primarily on lowest cost options and not on best-health options, he said.
<P>   Frist said the government should not &#39;&#39;micromanage&#39;&#39; health insurance plans, and his backing last year to allow 48 hours of hospital coverage for maternity patients -- rather than just one day -- was a one-time regulation for him. Future complaints about quality of care should be addressed in comprehensive health-care reforms, he said.
<P>   The Senate this year may consider legislation to bar insurance companies from insisting that mastectomies for breast cancer patients be done on an outpatient basis with no overnight hospital stay. Frist has not supported the bill so far, he said, and would prefer the Senate work on broad, long-term solutions.
<P>   Another problem has been insurance companies that bar physicians from telling patients about certain expensive procedures that would remedy their problems.
<P>   Many of these quality care concerns could be eliminated if physicians were more involved in setting policies, Frist said.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I want to give physicians a seat at the table&#39;&#39; where health-care plans are designed and administered, he said.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

	<P><center><font size=2>Return to </font><a href="/"><font size=2>Main</font></a><font size=2>. Copyright &#169; 1996 The Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size=2>webmaster</font></a><font size=2>.</font></center></p>
