<head>
	<title>Gavels fall at noon to open 100th General Assembly</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 14, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Gavels fall at noon to open 100th General Assembly</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Tom Humphrey, News-Sentinel Nashville bureau</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">N</FONT>ASHVILLE -- As legislators set the stage for today&#39;s opening of the 100th Tennessee General Assembly, activities ranged from a final fling at political fund-raising to formation of a new committee to concentrate on children.
<P>    House Speaker Jimmy Naifeh and Lt. Gov. John Wilder, speaker of the Senate, are scheduled to pound the session-opening gavels at noon. Their formal election to new terms in their posts will follow shortly afterwards.
<P>    Lawmakers plan to devote this week to organizational activities and filing of bills, then recess until Feb. 3. Gov. Don Sundquist&#39;s state budget will be presented then, complete with his plans for coping with revenue shortfalls of $100 million in the current year and $300 million in the 1997-98 fiscal year that begins July 1.
<P>    Since a 1995 state law forbids legislators from accepting political contributions during a legislative session, both Democratic and Republican legislative caucuses held fund-raisers Monday night.
<P>    Republicans centered their fund-raising festivities at the governor&#39;s residence while Democrats gathered at a hotel near the Legislative Plaza.
<P>    Naifeh announced Monday that a 12th House committee is being created for the session. It will be known as the Children and Family Affairs Committee.
<P>    Juvenile crime will be one focus of the panel, Naifeh said, noting commitments of youngsters to state custody for crimes has risen by 73 percent in Tennessee since 1990. Sundquist has announced he will introduce a package of legislation dealing with juvenile crime this year.
<P>    Naifeh said his move will &#39;&#39;work hand in glove with what the governor is proposing.&#39;&#39; Neither the governor nor legislators have unveiled specifics of legislation to combat juvenile crime.
<P>    &#39;&#39;What has caused our young people to lose respect for our laws?&#39;&#39; Naifeh asked. &#39;&#39;This is an area that needs specific attention and the Children and Family Affairs Committee will do just that.&#39;&#39;
<P>    The House already had 11 standing or permanent committees, which Naifeh said is a small number compared to many other states. He said, for example, that Mississippi has 34, Missouri 43.
<P>    The new committee will not require additional staff, he said. Much of the legislation it will handle -- domestic violence, adoption, divorce and child custody matters -- is now handled by the Judiciary Committee.
<P>    The Judiciary Committee typically handles about 800 bills per year and often needs longer to wrap up its work than other committees.
<P>    Naifeh and Wilder both have indicated they will assign legislators as members on their various committees Thursday. Naifeh declined to say who will chair the new panel until then.
<P>    In the Senate, little change in committee chairmanships is expected this year since most top-ranking senators were re-elected. Some top posts in House committees, however, are vacant and there has been considerable private jockeying for the prestigious positions.
<P>    Traditionally, only Democrats have been named to leadership positions in the House. House Republican Leader Steve McDaniel said he had asked Naifeh to change that policy this year, but acknowledged he is not optimistic the Democratic speaker will do so.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
