<head>
	<title>Dead man&#39;s sister says officer had no choice but to shoot</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 14, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Dead man&#39;s sister says officer had no choice but to shoot</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Don Jacobs, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">A</FONT> Knoxville police sergeant had no other choice when he fatally shot a man charging with a butcher knife, according to the dead man&#39;s sister.
<P>   Another Knoxville Police Department officer who witnessed the shooting said he thought the Oct. 10, 1996, slaying of Michael Christopher Painter, 29, was an example of &#39;&#39;suicide by police officer.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Statements from witnesses and family members included in the Internal Affairs report compiled by KPD showed Sgt. Randy Carman acted properly when he killed Painter.
<P>   &#39;&#39;He pointed at the relatives and friends with the knife in a threatening gesture and asked the officers if he was going to have to hurt one of the group in order to get the officers to shoot him,&#39;&#39; the internal probe states.
<P>   The 12:03 p.m. death of Painter ended a 30-minute standoff at his Reagan Avenue residence. During the standoff the 6-foot, 1-inch tall, 415-pound Painter had wielded a butcher knife with a 12-inch blade.
<P>   Before officers arrived Painter had flattened tires on his car, used cinderblocks to smash windows on his brother&#39;s car and used his bare hands to bend over double a car steering wheel.
<P>   Painter, who had undergone mental counseling in the past but refused to take prescribed medication, had begun terrorizing friends and relatives the night before, records show. He had tried three times in 1996 to commit suicide, family members told police.
<P>   When officers arrived at the West Knoxville residence, they found Painter sitting on a concrete picnic table in the front yard holding the knife. Officers&#39; questions about how they could help Painter were answered by, &#39;&#39;You&#39;re going to have to kill me,&#39;&#39; the officers stated.
<P>   Painter told the officers several times, &#39;&#39;I want to die,&#39;&#39; the probe states.
<P>   Officer John Shelton armed himself with a 12-gauge shotgun because he feared a handgun would not stop Painter because of the man&#39;s bulk. &#39;&#39;I was remembering the training film I saw while in the academy on how fast a subject with a knife could charge you and kill you before the officer can react and fire his weapon,&#39;&#39; Shelton told officials.
<P>   Brandi Corbin, 21, of Sutherland Avenue, who was a longtime friend of Painter&#39;s, tried to talk the man into putting down the knife.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I&#39;ve seen him mad, but not this mad,&#39;&#39; Corbin told officers. &#39;&#39;He would have killed us if he&#39;d got us. I just know the cop had to do it or somebody else was gonna get hurt.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Painter&#39;s sister, Kathyn Sue Lamons, 42, of Yarnell Road called police about her brother&#39;s actions that day. She had tried to wrest the knife from Painter but couldn&#39;t because of his size.
<P>   &#39;&#39;The policemen were being very kind,&#39;&#39; Lamons said of her brother&#39;s death. &#39;&#39;They was trying to talk to him. He was just bent on not living anymore.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Painter was within four feet of Carman when the officer fired into the man&#39;s head, witnesses said. Carman was the only thing between Painter and a group of his friends and relatives as he advanced with the knife raised.
<P>    &#39;&#39;We had backed up about as far as we could go,&#39;&#39; Carman said of the fatal shot.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
