	<title>Weather&#39;s forecast is warmer</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 14, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Weather&#39;s forecast is warmer</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Stan DeLozier, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">A</FONT>fter the coldest weather of the season last weekend, today&#39;s predicted high in the mid-30s -- and Wednesday&#39;s high of 40 degrees -- will seem downright balmy.
<P>   However, the National Weather Service is also forecasting a 60 percent chance of rain throughout the day Wednesday, possibly beginning as sleet or freezing rain.
<P>   Lows this morning are expected to be in the teens. But the forecast calls for mostly sunny skies and a high in the mid-30s before falling back into the upper teens tonight.
<P>   Monday morning, Crossville was the state&#39;s cold spot with a low of 5. It was 8 in Bristol; 9 in Nashville; 10 in Morristown; 15 in Memphis and Knoxville; and 19 in Chattanooga.
<P>   Some school systems dismissed classes or started late on Monday; Knox County students begin an hour later than normal today.
<P>
<P>
