<head>
	<title>East Tennessee briefs</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 14, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>East Tennessee briefs</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><h3>Lockheed Martin reveals second layoff phase plan</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>   OAK RIDGE -- Lockheed Martin, the Department of Energy&#39;s chief contractor in Oak Ridge, outlined Monday the second phase of layoffs to deal with federal budget reductions in 1997.
<P>    Another 250 to 300 Lockheed Martin workers will get their pink slips beginning Jan. 29 and must leave the payroll two months later.
<P>    In November, DOE said that about 1,680 Oak Ridge employees would lose their jobs over the next year as a result of the downsizing program.
<P>    Lockheed Martin Energy Systems, which manages DOE&#39;s Y-12 and K-25 plants, earlier handed out 439 layoff notices to workers, and most of those will leave the payroll at the end of January.
<P>   Lockheed Martin Energy Research Corp., which manages Oak Ridge National Laboratory, announced plans to lay off about 170.
<P>    Marty Goolsby, a company spokeswoman, said most layoffs in the latest phase at Energy Systems will come from the environmental management programs.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Man escapes from bank with cash in pillowcase</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>   OAK RIDGE -- A man armed with a small pistol robbed the Oak Ridge office of Home Federal Bank on Monday morning, according to the FBI.
<P>   After stuffing an undetermined amount of cash into a pillowcase he brought with him, the man fled in a maroon Chrysler LeBaron with a half-vinyl top, said Virgil Young, special agent in charge of the FBI&#39;s Knoxville office.
<P>   The robbery of the Oak Ridge Turnpike bank occurred about 9:50 a.m.
<P>   The man was described as 5-feet-6 to 5-feet-9-inches tall, weighing 150 to 175 pounds, with brown eyes and medium length brown hair and wearing jeans and a long-sleeved, brown checkered shirt. He also had several days growth of beard and a moustache. Young said the man was dirty and spoke with a country accent.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Campbell County man ID&#39;d as fatal fire victim</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>   CARYVILLE -- Authorities have ruled out foul play in the death of a 43-year-old Campbell County man killed in a house fire on Sunday.
<P>   The victim was identified as Ronnie A. Lawson by Campbell County Sheriff&#39;s Department Detective Scott Smith. An autopsy on Monday determined Lawson died from smoke inhalation, Smith said.
<P>   The victim&#39;s body was found Sunday in the charred remains of his house on Lawson Lane, officials said.
<P>   A Sheriff&#39;s Department report indicated the fire was reported at 12:25 p.m.
<P>   Smith said a witness reported seeing flames coming from the house, which had no electricity, as early as 6 a.m.
<P>   An investigation to determine the fire&#39;s cause is continuing.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Mayor appoints Adcock to administrative post</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>   Ellen Adcock has been appointed director of administration for the city of Knoxville.
<P>   Mayor Victor Ashe announced the appointment Monday.
<P>   Adcock&#39;s duties will include coordinating special projects &#39;&#39;that cross traditional city department lines&#39;&#39; and helping assure city services &#39;&#39;are delivered in the most efficient and cost-effective manner possible,&#39;&#39; Ashe said.
<P>   Adcock currently serves on the Civil Service Merit Board, from which she will resign effective Jan. 26. Ashe likely will nominate someone to City Council to replace her on the board within a couple of weeks, city spokesman Charlie Barker said.
<P>    Adcock has worked for the state for 18 years. Currently, she is director of special projects for Lakeshore Mental Health Institute. She has been active in several community organizations and activities for several years and is a past president of the West View Community Action Group.
<P>   She replaces Susan Edwards, who left the city to take a position with KUB.
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Knife-wielding suspect attacks Knoxville clerk 
<P>
<P>
<P>   A convenience store clerk told police he was accosted early Sunday by a man who came into the South Knoxville market, inquired about the weather and then brandished a butcher knife.
<P>   The 33-year-old clerk told Knoxville Police Department Patrol Officer Darrell Johnson he fended off the knife-wielding suspect with an ax handle during the 12:20 a.m. incident at the Kenjo Market, 3600 Sevier Ave., according to a police report.
<P>   The clerk claimed the suspect walked into the store and &#39;&#39;stated, &#39;Why did you let it get so cold?&#39; &#39;&#39; At that moment, the suspect pulled a butcher knife and reached for the clerk, the report stated.
<P>   According to the report, the clerk &#39;&#39;pulled away, grabbed an ax handle and chased the suspect from the store.&#39;&#39;
<P>   The suspect was described as a white male between 28 and 30 years old with brown hair and brown eyes. He was 6-feet, 1-inch-tall, weighing 150 pounds and wearing an old blue-and-gray South Young High School jacket and a dark blue hat.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
