<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>Marketing of Knoxville may capitalize on its neighbors</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper Business News">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif" alt="Knoxville News-Sentinel Online -- Business News" align=bottom border=0 width=595 height=176></a><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td align=left valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 14, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Marketing of Knoxville may capitalize on its neighbors</B></font><basefont size=6><!--SUBHEAD--></basefont></FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Lois Reagan Thomas, N-S executive business editor</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">F</FONT>or years, the focus on tourism in Knox County has been that we need to attract more conventions, and to do that we need better convention facilities.
<P>   The operative mentality seems to be that there&#39;s little to draw tourists to Knoxville as a destination -- except on Saturdays during football season, or perhaps in April during the Dogwood Arts Festival.
<P>   Think about it. If you were a tourist, what would draw you to Knoxville to stay? If you were here, you might visit the historical sites around, such as Blount Mansion and James White Fort, but would you come here just for that? Or to look at the Sunsphere? Or shop and eat in the Old City? Or visit the Knoxville Zoo?
<P>   The city lost its bragging rights years ago as the gateway to the Great Smokies, when tourists were able to bypass it on the interstate. Probably the last time a major move was made to market the city as a destination site was during the 1982 World&#39;s Fair.
<P>   Now, under new leadership, the Knoxville Convention and Visitors Bureau is embarking on a campaign to entice tourists to come to Knoxville for a vacation. Not that it&#39;s giving up on the conventions, stresses Mike Wilds, new executive director of the bureau. It&#39;s just that he sees a &#39;&#39;virtual smorgasbord&#39;&#39; of attractions that can lure tourists to stay in Knoxville&#39;s hotels and motels and eat and shop here.
<P>   The bureau recently commissioned The Tombras Group to develop a marketing plan for the city -- the first ad agency so commissioned in 15 years, according to Wilds. Focus groups of civic and business leaders have provided input. The state has promised participation in as much as $100,000 in cooperative advertising.
<P>   The strategy this time is not insularity, but rather to draw upon the resources of the whole region. Wilds says the idea is not to compete with the surrounding markets but to complement and capitalize on them.
<P>   If you look at what Knoxville can offer visitors within an hour&#39;s drive, you come up with that &#39;&#39;virtual smorgasbord,&#39;&#39; says Wilds. You get not only the Smokies and all its attrations, but also the Big South Fork National Recreation Area, Cumberland Gap National Park, whitewater rafting in a variety of locations, lots of lakes, a bunch of historial sites, and museums such as Knoxville Museum of Art, Sequoyah Museum, Museum of Appalachia and the Museum of Atomic Energy -- not to mention that ineffable friendliness and quality of life that Knoxville is so well-known for.
<P>   Also being proposed is partnering with Knoxville&#39;s Resource Valley, the Greater Knoxville Chamber of Commerce and Knoxville Airport Authority in efforts, such as &#39;&#39;strategic conferencing&#39;&#39; to draw people to Knoxville. In &#39;&#39;strategic conferencing,&#39;&#39; you, for example, go after meetings related to industries identified as driving economic development efforts.
<P>   Wilds also sees cooperating with other regional tourism groups such as Smoky Mountain Visitors Bureau in Blount County, and eventually perhaps with Chattanooga, Tri-Cities, and those in Sevier County in marketing the region.
<P>   Does this mean that the bureau is giving up on getting a new convention center?
<P>   &#39;&#39;Our job is to sell what we&#39;ve got, and if the citizens and leaders come to realize we need a new convention center, then we&#39;ll fill that too,&#39;&#39; said Wilds.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>   A few weeks ago, it seemed that everybody was agreeing that it would be a good idea to study how to better coordinate the various economic development groups in Knox County. Now it seems that not everybody agrees how to go about it.
<P>   Knox County Commission in December unanimously voted to ask County Executive Tommy Schumpert to name a five-member task force to evaluate the agencies&#39; effectiveness, and encouraged City Council to do the same.
<P>    Well, City Council members didn&#39;t go along with the idea. Seems their view is that an outside task force would take too long to get up to speed, and that the evaluation could be better handled from the city&#39;s end by the mayor, appropriate city directors and representatives of the agencies involved.
<P>   At Monday&#39;s County Commission agenda meeting, it was generally agreed that the county will proceed with its task force, appointing 10 people instead of five in order to have more diversity. So stay tuned.
<P>
<P>
<P>Lois Reagan Thomas is executive business editor of The News-Sentinel.
<P><B></B>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
