<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>&#39;95 mortgage foreclosures in state lowest in decade</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper Business News">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif" alt="Knoxville News-Sentinel Online -- Business News" align=bottom border=0 width=595 height=176></a><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td align=left valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 14, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>&#39;95 mortgage foreclosures in state lowest in decade</B></font><basefont size=6><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Tennessee's conventional, VA foreclosures below national average</FONT></basefont></FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Jerry Dean, News-Sentinel business writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<P>
<P>   Foreclosures on conventional mortgages in Tennessee during 1995 reached their lowest levels in a decade, according to data in a December report compiled by PMI, a Fairfax, Va. mortgage insurance firm.
<P>   PMI also said Knoxville&#39;s metropolitan area competed well with comparably sized cities in other regions for housing affordability, based on the ratio of regional median income to home prices. 
<P>   Statistics compiled by 25-year-old PMI and based on the latest complete data available, showed that Tennessee single-family mortgage activity had subsided from a decade-high 1993 level of $21.78 billion to $12.1 billion in 1995. That was still more than the $3.94 billion to $7.76 billion levels common in the state during the late 1980s. Declines from the 1993 peak were common in most states in 1994 and 1995, PMI reported.
<P>   Foreclosures in 1995 occurred on 0.2 percent of Tennessee conventional mortgages. The level nationwide was 0.65 percent. VA mortgage foreclosures flirted with the one percent mark, where it has been in Tennessee since 1990. That was below the national level of 1.27 percent. 
<P>   In New Jersey, VA loan foreclosures reached 3.45 percent -- highest among the states and third highest annual level in the decade.
<P>   Among FHA foreclosures, Tennessee&#39;s 1995 level of 0.95 percent was well below the 1.4 percent national average. New Jersey and Maine led all states in that foreclosure category with rates of 3.75 and 3.6 percent respectively.
<P>    Average FHA foreclosure rate among 17 Southern states was 1.18 percent, lower than rates for the Northeast, Midwest or Western states.
<P>   PMI, the National Associations of Realtors and Home Builders reported 1995 sales of 667,000 new homes and 3.8 million existing homes. The new homes mark was second highest in seven years. Sales of existing homes exceeded any year of the decade except 1995.
<P>    NAHB projected 3,802,000 sales of existing homes in 1995, about the 1993 level and below the 3.95 million in 1995.
<P>   Austin, Texas, led the nation&#39;s most active housing markets.
<P>    Atlanta, Ga., was 16th; Louisville, Ky., 22nd; Nashville, 35th; Memphis, 57th; and Knoxville, 69th in affordability rates.
<P>   Barney Thompson, executive vice president of the Knoxville Association of Realtors, said late-year residential sale closings should send Knox County&#39;s single-family home sales beyond the 7,000 mark, making 1996 a banner year, even after a seasonal autumn lag.
<P>   Single-family home sales here remain healthy, Thompson said, because Knoxville, since 1983, has had steady growth that averts a devastating &#39;&#39;boom or bust&#39;&#39; economy.
<P>    Thompson said Richard Scarbrough, 1997 KAR president succeeding James R. Lee, will report more specific home sales totals at a Friday KAR installation banquet.
<P>   PMI and the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corporation reported that the 7.03 percent average mortgage finance rate in January 1996 was the lowest for 30-year, fixed-rate mortgages since the early 1970s.
<P>    Rates climbed from 8.87 percent in 1976 and 11.2 percent in 1979 to peak at 16.63 percent in 1981.
<P>     The 30-year rate nationwide average declined to 10.13 percent in 1990, 8.38 in 1994 and 7.93 in 1995. Meanwhile, one-year adjustable rate mortgages, which averaged 11.5 percent in 1984, reached an all-time low of 5.3 percent in February 1996.
<P>   Jim Ewing, Tennessee Valley Home Builders Association executive vice president, said final 1996 totals will show numbers of Knox County building permits for single-family homes will exceed 1995&#39;s 2,794 by 20 to 25 percent.
<P>   Thus, 1996 will become the 13th consecutive year in which the number of residential permits issued countywide has increased.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
