<html>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>New Cherokee board votes sale</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper Business News">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif" alt="Knoxville News-Sentinel Online -- Business News" align=bottom border=0 width=595 height=176></a><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td align=left valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 14, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>New Cherokee board votes sale</B></font><basefont size=6><!--SUBHEAD--></basefont></FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Amy Geisel, News-Sentinel business editor</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">T</FONT>he board of directors of The New Cherokee Corp., a textile manufacturer with a 600-employee mill in Sevierville, has agreed to sell the company to competitor Dan River Inc.
<P>   Privately held Dan River will pay $65 million for New Cherokee, and the sale is expected to close in early February, said John Lambert, a spokesman for Dan River Inc.
<P>   New Cherokee, Sevier County&#39;s largest manufacturing employer, is an employee-owned company, and the sale is contingent on a shareholders&#39; approval. A special meeting has tentatively been scheduled for Feb. 3. The ESOP was developed about seven years ago, and shares are distributed to employees based on a formula in which years of service play a large role, said a New Cherokee spokesman. The company is still working to ascertain the purchase price on a per share basis, he said.
<P>   New Cherokee, which merged in 1989 with Spindale Mills Inc. of North Carolina, is a manufacturer of woven products for shirts and sportswear. It has about 600 employees in Rutherford County, N.C., where it&#39;s headquartered, in addition to those in Sevierville. Annual sales total about $50 million. The company traces its roots to the Cherokee Textile Mills, which were founded in 1916 in Knoxville.
<P>   Dan River is a major producer of woven fancy yarn-dyed fabrics and piece-dyed frabrics of cotton, man-made fibers and blends. Most of its 4,700 workers are employed in Danville, Va., where the company is based.
<P>   Lambert was noncommittal about whether New Cherokee plants would remain open after the sale. &#39;&#39;Anytime any two companies come together management must evaluate operations,&#39;&#39; he said. &#39;&#39;Dan River will be conducting an evaluation to identify ways to maximize production efficiencies and improve our ability to serve customers.&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P>   Joseph Lanier Jr., chairman and chief executive officer of Dan River, said the combined operations would make Dan River the leading producer of lightweight yarn-dyed woven fabrics in the western hemisphere.
<P>   Lanier, formerly chairman of WestPoint Pepperell, led a group that purchased in Dan River in 1990.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
