	<title>Business briefs</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper Business News">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif" alt="Knoxville News-Sentinel Online -- Business News" align=bottom border=0 width=595 height=176></a><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td align=left valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 14, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Business briefs</B></font><basefont size=6><!--SUBHEAD--></basefont></FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<h3>Sample named KUB chairman</h3>
<P>
<P>   Charles M. Sample, retired district manager of corporate and community affairs for South Central Bell, has succeeded William A. Fortune as Knoxville Utilities Board chairman.
<P>   Sample, who has been the board&#39;s secretary and vice chairman since his 1993 appointment, also is a board member of Leadership Knoxville, the Salvation Army and Fort Sanders Regional Health System.
<P>   Also elected were Thomas A. Siler, a managing partner of J.C. Bradford & Co. as vice chairman, succeeding Sample; and Lynne G. Fain, community volunteer, re-elected KUB secretary.  KUB&#39;s Board elected Clifford H. Ross, former teacher and coach, as assistant secretary and swore in Gloria Ray, president of Knoxville Sports Corp., as a new commissioner. 
<P>   Other KUB Board members are Sharon J. Miller, president of The Trust Co., and A. Coleman Piper, executive vice president for Proffitt&#39;s Inc. 
<P>   Miller now heads KUB&#39;s Audit and Finance Committee, and Piper is Nominating Committee chairman.
<P>
<P><h3>NationsBank earns $2.19 per share</h3>
<P>
<P>   NationsBank Corp. said fourth-quarter earnings rose 24 percent to $632 million, or $2.19 a share, from the same period last year, but Chief Financial Officer James Hance told analysts that 1997 earnings will be lower than previously predicted as a result of its $9.78 billion acquisition of Boatmen&#39;s Bancshares Inc.
<P>   The bank is merging the two units faster than anticipated, resulting in higher-than-expected costs and savings.
<P>   Still, NationsBank expects to meet or exceed net income goals it set last August when it announced the acquisition, bank spokeswoman Susan Carr said. At that time, the bank estimated 1997 cash earnings would exceed $3.3 billion while net income would reach $2.94 billion.
<P>First Central sees 51 percent increase
<P>   First Central Bank reported ending 1996 with a 51 percent rise in net income over the previous year.
<P>   Net earnings were $765,142, up from $505,262. Total loans outstanding increased 27.3 percent to $57.5 mllion, and year-end deposits were $67.8 million, up 12.1 percent.
<P>   First Central, based in Loudon County, was established in 1991 and includes branches in Lenoir City, Farragut, Loudon and Tellico Village.
<P>
<P><h3>Asarco makes management changes</h3>
<P>   Asarco Inc. has named Donald H. Walters, general manager of Asarco&#39;s Tennessee Mines Division, to a special management process team, and Taie Li has been named to succeed him at the Tennessee Mines Division.
<P>   The division includes three operating zinc mines and one mine currently on standby near Knoxville.  Li, 38, has been manager of Asarco&#39;s  Globe plant in Denver. He joined Asarco in 1986 as a research engineer at the Technical Services Department in Salt Lake City and was named technical service manager and high-purity metals manager at Globe in 1989.  He previously was a consultant, research assistant and teaching assistant at the Colorado School of Mines, Golden, Colorado, from 1981 to 1986. He is a native of Mineola, New York.
<P>    Walter, one of three senior Asarco executives named to the Management Process Team, will design, develop and guide the implementation of a state-of-the-art environmental management system.  Walter, 51, has been general manager of the Tennessee Mines Division (TMD) since 1994.
<P>
<P><h3>Rowland expands, adds staff</h3>
<P>
<P>   Expanding to better meet the needs of its growing client base,Knoxville-based Rowland Productions, Inc. has promoted and added several positions to its staff.
<P>   Chad Kennedy has been promoted to design director and will operate a new division, Rowland design/animation. Two animators, Martin Coven and Karl Ricker, have joined the new division and are working under Kennedy in 3-D and 2-D animation.
<P>   Rowland&#39;s production staff has grown to a total ofeight employees, with the announcement of four new hires. Mary Helen Brower is a new producer; Steven C. Henderson joins the company as editing assistant. Chris Bryan and Alicia Robeson are additions to studio operations and client services. Mimi Tucker also has come on board in marketing and business development.
<P>
<P><h3>Knox firm gets fair contract</h3>
<P>
<P>   Bullock, Smith & Partners, a Knoxville architectural and planning firm, has been hired to overhaul the Tennessee State Fairgrounds in Nashville.
<P>   About $2.5 million has been budgeted to buy land around the fairgrounds in order to expand, which the Metro Fair Board has said it wants to do to add more parking and event buildings.
<P>   David Forkner, cqvice president of Bullock, Smith & Partners, will be the principal planner for the project. He isn&#39;t sure an expansion is necessary to accomplish the board&#39;s goals.
<P>   Three public meetings are scheduled to discuss changes to the 110-acre fairgrounds.
<P>   Bullock, Smith has designed fairgrounds in 29 states and three countries.
<P>
<P><h3>Names in the news</h3>
<P>
<P>   Paige von Hoffmann cqhas been promoted to senior account executive for StaffingSolutions&#39; cqKnoxville offices. Previously, she served as an account executive. . . . Marilyn Cobble, a vice president of BankFirst, has been elected vice president of the Southern Chapter of Robert Morris Associates, a group of financial service institutions and professionals that promotes credit risk identification and management. . . . Thomas H. Lee, formerly of Knoxville, has joined the Nashville law firm of Waller Lansden Dortch & Davis and will be practicing in the firm&#39;s litigation group. He was a judicial clerk for U.S. Dist. Judge Tom Wiseman, and received his law degree from Vanderbilt University. . . . Judy Penry has been named chief financial officer at the Department of Energy&#39;s Oak Ridge field office. Since 1986, Penry has been DOE&#39;s budget director. . . . Jennifer L. Woods has joined Digital Color Inc., a graphic arts pre-press service in Knoxville, as an account executive. She previously was with J.P. Hogan & Co.
<P> 
<P>
