<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>Non-winners weeded out of The Winston Select</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 14, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470><BASEFONT SIZE="6">
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Non-winners weeded out of The Winston Select</B></FONT><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Bill Luther, News-Sentinel sportswriter</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<P>    Winners only!
<P>    It&#39;s the new format for The Winston Select all-star race scheduled May 17 at Charlotte Motor Speedway.
<P>    The top five finishers in the Winston Open preliminary event have qualified in the past. Now only the winner advances to the $1 million race sponsored by R.J. Reynolds.
<P>    As in the past The Winston will consist of a minimum 20-car field and is open to several groups of winners.
<P>    Effective with the Daytona 500 on Feb. 16, the 1997 season the following will be eligible:
<P>
<P>   * Drivers and car owners who have won races in the preceding and current years.
<P>    * Any active driver who has won the Winston Cup championship.
<P>    * Any active driver who has won The Winston within the preceding five years.
<P>    * The winner of the Winston Open.
<P>    * If 20 drivers are not eligible winners from previous seasons still active on the Cup circuit become eligible. All active drivers during the season become eligible, even if the field exceeds 20 competitors.
<P>    The elgibility requirements are the only changes for The Winston, which consists of two 30-lap segments and a closing 10-lap shootout.
<P>    Going into the season 14 drivers were guaranteed starting berths for posting Winston Cup wins: Terry Labonte, Jeff Gordon, Dale Jarrett, Dale Earnhardt, Ricky Rudd, Rusty Wallace, Sterling Marlin, Bobby Hamilton, Ernie Irvan, Bobby Labonte and Geoff Bodine.
<P>    Darrell Waltrip, Bill Elliott and Michael Waltrip are eligible for having won the Winston Select.
<P>    Mark Martin, Kyle Petty and Ward Burton (1995), Jimmy Spencer (1994) and Morgan Shepherd (1993) are winners from previous seasons and could get a berth based on those victories.
<P>    Michael Waltrip won the 1996 Winston Select.
<P>    If the Select winner captures the pole position and each of the three segments the purse will be $325,000 for 105 miles of racing. Earnhardt and the late Davey Allison are the only drivers to have made a sweep.
<P>
<P>    <B>IROC FOURSOME:</B> Defending champion Mark Martin, Terry Labonte, Jeff Gordon and Dale Jarrett have accepted invitations to participate in the four-race International Race of Champions series.
<P>    &#39;&#39;Being invited is a big deal for me,&#39;&#39; said Martin, who will be making his sixth appearance. &#39;&#39;Winning the IROC title in 1994 was a real highlight of my career. To win again last year was important to me to prove it wasn&#39;t a fluke.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Labonte and Gordon gave team owner Rick Hendrick back-to-back Winston Cup championships. Labonte won the title by 37 points. Four victories were a huge part of Jarrett taking third place in points.
<P>    Labonte was the 1989 IROC champion and will be remembered for substituting for Dave Allison in the final race ofthe 1993 series to clinch the title for Allison.
<P>    Another group of four drivers will be announced next week.
<P>    The series opens at Daytona on Feb. 14. Later events are scheduled May 16 at Charlotte, June 21 at the new California Speedway in Fontana, and July 23 at Michigan Speedway.
<P>
<P>    <B>RECORD?:</B> Cup driver Brett Bodine is among six comprising a $60 million Close Call program sponsored by Catalyst and Frontier Communications. Others are NHRA top fuel champ Jim Head, John Myers and Angelle Seeling of the NHRA pro stock motorcycle division, Mark Tate in Unlimited Hydroplane and Toby Robertson in late model stock car racing.
<P>    Close Call, a prepaid telephone card that features a scratch and win section, will be offered at retail outlets across the country. It also involves a sweepstakes. A cardholder can tell immediately if the card is a winner. There are 16 grand prizes, each including $250,000 and a new car.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
