<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 14, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470><BASEFONT SIZE="6">
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Sports briefs</B></FONT><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<h3>Ex-Braves announcer Mann dies of cancer</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>    <B>Marshall Mann</B> found out he had lung and kidney cancer just a month after retiring as the Atlanta Braves&#39; public-address announcer last fall.
<P>    Mann died Sunday night in Griffin, Ga. He was 63.
<P>    &#39;&#39;All of us at the Braves will miss Marshall greatly,&#39;&#39; team president <B>Stan Kasten</B> said Monday. &#39;&#39;We all enjoyed and appreciated every game he ever worked over his 30 years with the team. We extend our heartfelt sympathy to his family.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Mann had decided some time ago that he would retire before the Braves changed homes, moving from Atlanta-Fulton County Stadium to a new stadium across the street for the 1997 season.
<P>    He had wanted to remember baseball the way it was for the 30 seasons his booming voice introduced starting lineups at all Braves home games.
<P>    In October, following Atlanta&#39;s Game 5 loss to the New York Yankees in the World Series, he stepped down.
<P>   In other sports-related deaths:
<P>
<P>* <B>Carol Habben</B>, a former player in the women&#39;s professional baseball league in the early 1950s, has died in Ridgewood, N.J., following a lengthy illness. She was 63.
<P>* <B>Jackie McCoy</B>, a longtime boxing manager and trainer who helped develope five world champions, including lightweight <B>Mando Ramos</B>, died Monday in California after a long battle with cancer. McCoy was 73.
<P>
<P><h3>Outdoors</h3>
<P>
<P>* <B>Sen. Larry Craig</B> wants the chief of the Forest Service to explain why auto racing legend <B>Bobby Unser</B> is being prosecuted for snowmobiling in a protected wilderness area. Unser, lost for two days in a blizzard last month, said he&#39;s unsure, but he might have strayed a quarter-mile or half-mile into Colorado&#39;s South San Juan Wilderness while snowmobiling with a friend. The two nearly died after their snowmobile broke down in the national forest.
<P>
<P><h3>College football</h3>
<P>
<P>* Virginia Military Institute selected North Carolina State offensive coordinator <B>Ted Cain</B> to replace <B>Bill Stewart</B>, who resigned as head football coach on Dec. 12 after being accused of directing a racial slur at a player.
<P>
<P><h3>Colleges</h3>
<P>
<P>* An Ohio Valley Conference committee will study the league&#39;s uncertain football future as league members Austin Peay and Morehead State have dropped football scholarships and Middle Tennessee State prepares to move up to Division I in 1999.
<P>
<P><h3>Baseball</h3>
<P>
<P>* General Motors Corp. will drop its complaint against Cincinnati Reds owner <B>Marge Schott</B> if she goes through with a planned sale of her Chevrolet-Geo dealership, a GM lawyer told a state hearing examiner.
<P>* The San Diego Padres have acquired negotiating rights to <B>Hideki Irabu</B>, who is described as the <B>Nolan Ryan</B> of Japan. The 27-year-old power pitcher went 12-6 with a league-low 2.40 earned run average last season with the Chiba Lotte Marines. The New York Daily News reported that an agent is seeking $6 million a year for Irabu.
<P>* Baltimore signed former UT shortstop <B>Augie Ojeda</B> to a minor-league contract.
<P>
<P><h3>Figure skating</h3>
<P>
<P>* <B>Oksana Baiul</B> was driving under the influence when she ran her Mercedes off a road while returning home from a night out in Hartford, Conn., a hospital report shows. Baiul, who at 19 is two years under the legal drinking age in Connecticut, had a blood-alcohol level of .168 percent after the accident early Sunday morning. Baiul had a cut to her scalp that required 12 stitches, while passenger Ararat Zakarian, 30, a fellow Ukrainian skater living in New York City, had a broken finger.
<P>
<P><h3>Tennis</h3>
<P>
<P>* City tennis director <B>Patsy Stair</B> has been selected to the nine-state Southern Tennis Association public relations committee. Stair is vice president and on the boards of the Tennessee Tennis Assocation and the Greater Knoxville Tennis Association.
<P>
<P><h3>Boxing</h3>
<P>
<P>* The bout between <B>Sugar Ray Leonard </B>and <B>Hector Camacho </B>has been rescheduled from Feb. 28 to March 1, but it will remain in Atlantic City, N.J. One other change: wrestling promoter <B>Vince McMahon </B>will supervise the pay-per-view.
<P>
<P><h3>Golf</h3>
<P>
<P>* <B>Arnold Palmer </B>remained hopeful about his chances of beating prostate cancer after receiving encouraging test results at the Mayo Clinic in Rochester, Minn. It was unclear how long Palmer, 67, would remain at the medical center for more tests.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
