<html>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>3 lawmakers greatly increased mass mailings in &#39;96, files show</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 13, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>3 lawmakers greatly increased mass mailings in &#39;96, files show</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Richard Powelson, News-Sentinel Washington bureau</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">W</FONT>ASHINGTON -- Three of Tennessee&#39;s winners in last November&#39;s U.S. House elections greatly expanded their use of taxpayer-paid mass mailings, new postal records show.
<P>    Two of the incumbents more than doubled their 1995 level of mailings.
<P>    Reps. John J. Duncan Jr. of Knoxville, Van Hilleary of Grandview and Bart Gordon of Murfreesboro said there was nothing political about their decision to boost their taxpayer-paid mass mailings last election year. Republican Duncan and Democrat Gordon more than doubled their mailings to roughly 600,000 each, costing taxpayers $70,000 for Duncan&#39;s and $94,000 for Gordon&#39;s.
<P>    Duncan&#39;s and Gordon&#39;s 1996 challengers and the National Taxpayers Union, a national group promoting budget cuts, were critical of the mail-subsidy perk.
<P>    &#39;&#39;It seems to be a relatively routine practice for many members to increase the number and the expenditures on mass mailings in election years,&#39;&#39; said NTU spokesman Pete Sepp. &#39;&#39;A well-written mass mailing can give a tremendous boost to an incumbent.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Both of Tennessee&#39;s reform-minded senators, Republicans Fred Thompson and Bill Frist, began their terms two years ago by deciding against the expense of blanketing the state with unsolicited mail.
<P>    &#39;&#39;It works pretty well&#39;&#39; without the mass mailings, Frist aide Keith Still said. Still said Frist gets out his views on issues by writing to those inquiring, weekly columns and press releases faxed to state media and by making himself available to news outlets wherever he goes.
<P>    Thompson aide Alex Pratt said they use similar methods.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We&#39;ve been successful without it,&#39;&#39; Pratt said of the mass mailings of newsletters and meeting notices that other members use.
<P>    Last year Duncan increased his use of mass mailings throughout his district to 586,000, compared to 290,000 in 1995, according to U.S. Postal Service records.
<P>    The mass mailings cost taxpayers $70,000, not counting expenses for paper, printing and staff time preparing the publications. That cost is in addition to the $24,000 postage expense for answering constituents&#39; mail.
<P>    Gordon, the House delegation&#39;s most frequent mailer who was expecting a tough re-election battle last year, boosted his mass mailings to 621,000 last year compared to 310,000 in 1995. His postage bill last year: $94,000 for mass mailings, $23,000 for other mailings.
<P>    Hilleary had a big increase, too. His mailings shot up to 583,000 from 334,000 in 1995, costing $78,000 for the blanket mailings and $9,000 for other postage.
<P>    Postage rates for such mailings vary, usually from 11 to 15 cents each, depending on whether expedited delivery is requested and if presorting is done, postal official Thomas Dale Jr. said.
<P>    Republican Steve Gill, a Brentwood lawyer who challenged Gordon the last two elections, said the taxpayer-paid mailings are an unfair perk.
<P>    &#39;&#39;The problem for the public is that the guys who have the chance to vote on whether to ban mass mailings in an election year are the guys who benefit from sending mass mailings in an election year. Think of what it would save&#39;&#39; if the practice were banned for all members of Congress, Gill said.
<P>    Democrat Stephen Smith, a veterinarian who opposed Duncan last year, agreed.
<P>   &#39;&#39;This is one of many advantages of incumbency. I don&#39;t think it&#39;s a wise use of taxpayers&#39; money.&#39;&#39;
<P>    The $70,000 that taxpayers paid for Duncan&#39;s mass mailings last year through Oct. 31 was about $20,000 more than Smith&#39;s entire campaign budget. Overall, Duncan&#39;s campaign raised and spent about five times what Smith did.
<P>    Rep. Zach Wamp, a Chattanooga Republican, blanketed his district&#39;s households in 1995 with newsletters, but not last year.
<P>    &#39;&#39;The 1995 mass mailing was not as effective as we&#39;d hoped&#39;&#39; in making recipients aware of what Wamp and Congress were doing, Wamp aide Dick Kopper said. So, Wamp has been trying other communications methods: radio interviews, computer hook-ups, speeches and various public events.
<P>    Duncan said people have told him they like his mailings.
<P>    &#39;&#39;I do think that they are legitimate if they are done in the way that I do them,&#39;&#39; Duncan said. It comes out to just a few pennies per constituent for each one of those mailings that I do.
<P>    &#39;&#39;My newsletters have not just been puff pieces. I have tried to inform my constituents about what is going on in the House . . . votes that I have cast . . . where I stand on particular issues.&#39;&#39;
<P>    The National Taxpayers Union annually praises Duncan and a few other members as the top budget-cutters. Duncan said he appreciates NTU&#39;s work, but disagrees with its leaders over mass mailings.
<P>    Hilleary said he has the largest land area of any House member and believes that newsletters are a necessity to get out his views.
<P>    Like Duncan, he said he gets positive feedback from readers of his newsletters. &#39;&#39;I don&#39;t think there&#39;s a whole lot of political advantage&#39;&#39; from the taxpayer-subsidized mailings, Hilleary said, because House rules ban them within 90 days of an election, and he does not believe that most voters focus on their candidate choices until three weeks before election day.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
