<head>
	<title>City&#39;s donation to park kicks off Wildlife Week</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 13, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>City&#39;s donation to park kicks off Wildlife Week</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Marti Davis, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">P</FONT>IGEON FORGE -- Mayor Ralph Chance opened the sixth annual Wilderness Wildlife Week of Nature this past weekend by presenting the Friends of the Smokies with a $16,000 check from the city.
<P>    The donation brings to $30,000 the total cash donation the city has given to benefit the Great Smoky Mountains National Park in the last two years.
<P>    &#39;&#39;It&#39;s time for us to start paying back and helping the park,&#39;&#39; Chance said.
<P>    Karen Wade, superintendent of the park, said the park will benefit from about $1 million in donations this year -- half from the Friends and the other half from the Great Smoky Mountains Natural History Association, which donates proceeds from book sales inside park visitor centers.
<P>    &#39;&#39;Last year was the survival course -- we survived,&#39;&#39; Wade told a large audience during Saturday night&#39;s opening ceremony for Wildlife Week at the Heartlander Country Resort.
<P>    &#39;&#39;This year we can get to do some of the things we&#39;ve been hoping to do,&#39;&#39; she added. The most major item on that list is a new science research laboratory at the Twin Creeks Natural Resource Center in Gatlinburg.
<P>    Park rangers and retired park personnel are among the many volunteers who are helping this week to put on what has become one of the area&#39;s most major park-related events. The week includes 88 expert speakers on a wide variety of topics, ranging from bird calls to Appalachian homesteading. All events are free and take place at or originate from the Heartlander.
<P>    While the snowy and cold weather has forced some hikes to be rerouted, it hasn&#39;t seemed to discourage any of the event&#39;s early participants.
<P>    Richard Haiman, a Florida man who paid to repair the Alum Cave Bluff Trail in the Smokies last year, traveled from Orlando for Wilderness Wildlife Week.
<P>    Sylvester Kiger and Cathy Lowe drove from Lexington, Ky., through blizzard conditions Friday to get to the event.
<P>    &#39;&#39;We wondered if we were the last car on the road from Lexington,&#39;&#39; said Lowe, who said the beauty of the snow-frosted park was more than worth the harrowing road trip.
<P>
<P>Today&#39;s schedule
<P><B>
<P></B>
<P><B>   9 a.m.</B><B> </B>-- Establishing a Buffer Zone around the National Park, by Randy Brown, Foothills Land Conservancy; <B>9:15 a.m. Ä </B>The Gray Wolf: How They Exist in the Wild, by David Taylor of Bays Mountain Park;<B> 11:30 a.m. Ä </B>Exotic Forest Insects and Diseases, Kristine Johnson, national park staff;<B> 2 p.m. Ä </B>Culture and Wildlife in the Cove, by Ranger Steve McCoy;<B> 3:15 p.m. Ä </B>Wild Turkey Restoration, by Joe Fowler, regional director of Wild Turkey Federation;<B> 4:30 p.m. Ä </B>Acid Deposition and Effects on the Fish Population, by biologist Steve Moore;<B> 7 p.m. Ä </B>The Weirdest Fish in Tennessee, by professor David Etnier;<B> 8:15 p.m. Ä </B>Spring Flora of the Southern Appalachians, by Bill Hooks.<B>
<P>    Hikes and field trips:  7:45 a.m. to 2 p.m. Ä</B> Old Settlers Trail (5 miles); 8:15 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. <B>Ä </B>Rich Mountain Loop (8 miles);<B> 9:45 a.m. to 3 p.m. Ä</B> Natural history field trip (1-2 miles);<B> 1:15 p.m. to 4 p.m. Ä </B>Little River Road historical tour;<B> 6:30 to 9 p.m.</B> <B>Ä</B> Night Owl Prowl (1 mile). 
<P>   For more information, call 453-4106, ext. 1019.<B>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P></B>
<P>
