<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>New license plate design honors and benefits the Smokies</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i>January 13, 1997</i> </td>
        <td width="470"><font size="6"><b>New license plate
        design honors and benefits the Smokies</b></font><p><img
        src="../images/plate.jpg" align="left" hspace="7"
        vspace="7" width="250" height="175"><font size="1"><strong>Charles
        Morris, Jr. of Renaissance Communications Group with <br>
        his design of a new Tenneessee license plate.</strong></font><br
        clear="all">
        <img src="../../images/v3/credits/COcredit.gif"
        width="144" height="21"></p>
        <p><font size="2"><i>By Gina Stafford, News-Sentinel
        staff writer</i></font></p>
        <p><br>
        <font size="5">T</font>he order was unusual: Turn a
        mountain range into a license plate, and one that would
        sell. </p>
        <p>But -- with the Great Smoky Mountains National Park
        serving as both inspiration and beneficiary of the
        project -- graphic designer Chuck Morris happily tackled
        the task for free. </p>
        <p>Morris, along with fellow designer Steve Simpson and
        their colleagues at Knoxville's Renaissance
        Communications Group, provided artwork for the new
        Tennessee tag expected to make its public debut in April.
        </p>
        <p>''It's not a real easy medium to work in, but I think
        I was more excited about it than any other project I've
        done because it was so unique,'' Morris said. </p>
        <p>''It was also a little hard reconciling the two big
        considerations -- that it's an attractive plate and that
        police officers can read it. A lot of people may not
        realize that, but all the state cares about is
        function.'' </p>
        <p>The design order came after the Legislature, led by
        Rep. Bill Clabough, R-Maryville, and Sen. Bud Gilbert,
        R-Knoxville, approved the new plate last spring. It will
        cost $25 more than a standard plate, and officials
        estimate that all but $3 of the extra fee will benefit
        the national park. </p>
        <p>Morris said he expects motorists who love the
        mountains as he does will feel buying the tag ''is the
        right thing to do.'' </p>
        <p>''I know the mountains, for me, are simply at top of
        my list of the best things about living here, and we all
        have some responsibility to make sure the park stays with
        us and in good condition,'' he said. ''Translating that
        feeling onto a license plate was a little complicated,
        though.'' </p>
        <p>Morris got help from Charles Maynard, executive
        director of Friends of the Smokies, which works with park
        staffers to determine areas of need and coordinates park
        fund-raising. </p>
        <p>''Charles helped to make sure the design embodied all
        the wonderful things we feel about the mountains -- how
        they feel like home and even when you're away from them,
        there's something about them that brings you back,''
        Morris said. </p>
        <p>Morris said designers started with a ''generic photo''
        of a mountain range and decided on inclusion of a rising
        sun and color gradations reflective of the Smokies'
        characteristically misty horizon. </p>
        <p>A handful of designs were submitted to officials. The
        winner also will bear the line, ''Preserve &amp; Protect
        Our National Park.'' </p>
        <p>John McAdams, assistant director of the Title and
        Registration Division of the Tennessee Department of
        Safety, predicts the new tag will be a hit. </p>
        <p>''That's based as much on the way it looks as its
        affiliation with the park,'' McAdams said. </p>
        <p>Commonly known as ''the Iris plate'' for the
        purple-hued image it bears of the official state flower,
        the tag that benefits Tennessee's state parks is
        currently the hottest-selling non-standard plate, McAdams
        said. </p>
        <p>That tag, with 25,000 units issued to date, is
        unpopular with many state officials, however. </p>
        <p>''The design was voted one of the very worst in the
        country at a recent convention of the American
        Association of Motor Vehicle Administrators because of
        the inability to read it well,'' McAdams said. </p>
        <p>Friends of the Smokies secured the initial minimum
        order of 100 tags required to begin production of the new
        tag, and McAdams said once samples have been approved,
        manufacturing will begin at Cold Creek Correctional
        Facility in Henning, Tenn. </p>
        <p>''Yeah, a bunch of those death-row inmates will be
        stamping out these new Smokies plates, like they do all
        the state's others,'' McAdams said. ''Some have probably
        never even seen the Smokies, but it'll be a prestigious
        job to them.'' </p>
        <p>Charles Maynard said he hopes the work is plentiful. </p>
        <p>''We're just going to have to wait and see how it goes
        this first year, but whatever is generated will be used
        for something on the park's needs list,'' he said. ''The
        things on that list this year add up to about $1
        million.'' </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

