<head>
	<title>Telling criminals from victims can be difficult</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 13, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Telling criminals from victims can be difficult</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> KPD unit strives to keep lid on crimes against persons</FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Jamie Satterfield, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">P</FONT>lacing his hand over his heart, the 22-year-old murder suspect declared his innocence.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I wasn&#39;t planning on shooting,&#39;&#39; he insisted. &#39;&#39;That&#39;s not me. I ain&#39;t got that in my heart.&#39;&#39;
<P>   His eyes misted with tears, Anthony Foster Ligon was selling sincerity, but Knoxville Police Department Investigator Edd Stair wasn&#39;t buying.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Back up now,&#39;&#39; Stair replied. &#39;&#39;There were two guns laying right beside you.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Ligon was nonplussed.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I do not know what happened to them guns,&#39;&#39; he responded, shrugging his shoulders. &#39;&#39;For real.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Some might find this seemingly fruitless line of questioning frustrating. But for Stair, a 25-year veteran of KPD&#39;s Crimes Against Persons unit, it&#39;s what makes the job fun.
<P>   &#39;&#39;To me, it&#39;s a cat-and-mouse game,&#39;&#39; Stair said later. &#39;&#39;You&#39;ve got to outsmart these people. I like the excitement.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Stair&#39;s partner, Investigator Cindy Gass, agreed.
<P>   &#39;&#39;There&#39;s a lot of self-gratification in that,&#39;&#39; she said.
<P>   The Crimes Against Persons unit probes the &#39;&#39;worst of the worst&#39;&#39; crimes committed in Knoxville. Sgt. Dan Brock, who heads the unit, said investigators handled 1,674 cases in 1996, including 24 homicides and hundreds of robberies, shootings, stabbings and rapes.
<P>   &#39;&#39;(Per investigator) it averages about 118 (cases) a year -- probably about 10 a month,&#39;&#39; Brock said.
<P>   It is the most experienced group within the KPD ranks, a key in the unit&#39;s estimated 80 percent success rate in solving homicides, according to Brock. Most investigators in the unit have an average of 25 years of experience, he said.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I think we&#39;ve got good teamwork,&#39;&#39; he said. &#39;&#39;I think they know one another. A lot of them ran a (patrol) beat together before coming (to the unit).&#39;&#39;
<P>   They work 10-hour shifts, and Brock said his investigators spend &#39;&#39;about every day off in court.&#39;&#39; The stress level is high, and the amount of gratitude low, the veteran sergeant said.
<P>   As Capt. Charles Coleman pointed out in a recent pep talk to some of the investigators: &#39;&#39;This unit takes the brunt of everything that happens. When the shooting and the killing starts, this is the unit everybody starts yakking about.&#39;&#39;
<P>   In many cases, particularly those involving gang-related crime, eyewitnesses &#39;&#39;go blind,&#39;&#39; refusing to admit what they know for fear of retaliation from gang members, Brock noted. Even crime victims aren&#39;t always cooperative, he said.
<P>   For example, Gass and Stair spent hours interviewing witnesses, gathering evidence and writing reports to file charges against an East Side gang member who shot one of his buddies.
<P>   The shooting victim tearfully described the shooting from his hospital bed but refused to answer when Gass repeatedly asked him if he planned to go to court.
<P>   The investigators also must wear a variety of hats. They are advisors to the less experienced patrol officers, psychologists to the victims and their families and verbal punching bags to angry suspects and their relatives, Brock said.
<P>   Brock said the investigators also must battle a justice system that often is a revolving door for criminals.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We see a lot of repeat offenders up here,&#39;&#39; he said.
<P>   The investigators also must fill out mounds of paperwork. Investigator Ken Slagle recently joked that the &#39;&#39;real work begins when we put the bad guys in jail,&#39;&#39; referring to the notebooks full of reports and forms a case can generate.
<P>   So why do these folks stick with it?
<P>   &#39;&#39;We like to put the bad guys in jail,&#39;&#39; Brock said simply. &#39;&#39;You have to be dedicated to that job.&#39;&#39;
<P>   On a recent Friday night, Gass and Stair battled wits with Ligon, who had admitted driving a car used in a drive-by shooting that killed a man in the Lonsdale Homes housing project. Gass and Stair suspected Ligon knew more about that crime -- and others -- than he was willing to say. But Ligon, an East Side gang member, denied it and, instead, plied the two investigators with tales of remorse.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I pray, I wish there was a way I could go back to that day,&#39;&#39; Ligon insisted. &#39;&#39;I wish I&#39;d never been in that car. . . . I have to hold my momma and apologize to my momma because I know it&#39;s my fault.&#39;&#39;
<P>   After nearly an hour of questioning, Ligon was taken back to jail. Gass and Stair had learned little but were hopeful Ligon eventually would be more forthcoming.
<P>   As Investigator Terry Clowers pointed out, the job requires patience, but the payoff is high.
<P>   &#39;&#39;When you finally get these guys and you put them away, it gives you a great sense of pride,&#39;&#39; he said.
<P>   Investigator Larry Vineyard added: &#39;&#39;It&#39;s like doing a 3-D puzzle. You have to put all the pieces of the puzzle together. Even if it&#39;s a little piece, it&#39;s important.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Investigators contend they spend most of their time sifting stories -- from suspects and victims -- for grains of truth.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Sometimes, the victims lie as much or more than the bad guys,&#39;&#39; Investigator Dwight Loop said.
<P>   A case in point: A man told Stair and Gass a group of men forced him into a car and took him to a store, where one of the assailants took him inside to cash the man&#39;s government-benefits check. After the check was cashed, the man claimed, the group of men forced him back into the car, drove him to a wooded area, robbed him of his money, ripped his clothes and rolled him down a hill.
<P>   &#39;&#39;The fact of it was, I was trying to stay alive,&#39;&#39; the man said.
<P>   One of the alleged robbers, whom Stair and Gass tracked to a Magnolia Avenue motel, insisted the man wanted drugs and willingly got in the car. After changing his story several times, the alleged robber admitted taking the man to the store to get his check cashed.
<P>   His only bounty, the alleged robber contended, was the $5 the man gave him for helping him get his check cashed.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I just did that man a favor,&#39;&#39; the man accused of robbery insisted.
<P>   Gass and Stair returned to their victim and confronted him with the robber&#39;s tale. The victim then said he had forgotten to tell the investigators one of the robbers asked him for $5 in gas money.
<P>   &#39;&#39;If they were going to take all your money, why would he ask you for gas money?&#39;&#39; Gass queried.
<P>   Shrugging, the victim said, &#39;&#39;I&#39;m just proud they didn&#39;t kill me.&#39;&#39;
<P>   After the accused and accusor were sent home with a promise of a district attorney&#39;s review of their claims, Stair offered a frustrated shrug of his own when asked which of the two men&#39;s tales were closer to the truth.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Who knows?&#39;&#39; he said.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
