<head>
	<title>Prosecutors ask bond be revoked for Knox youth</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 13, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Prosecutors ask bond be revoked for Knox youth</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By John North, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">A</FONT> 16-year-old Knoxville youth accused of taking part in the murder last year of a 5-year-old girl is in danger of losing his bond privileges.
<P>   Knox County prosecutors are seeking to revoke bond for Melvin E. &#39;&#39;Little Melvin&#39;&#39; Davis because he picked up an aggravated robbery charge last month while awaiting a grand jury review in the murder case and a trial in Knox County Criminal Court on a charge of aggravated assault.
<P>   Davis, who was shot the day after the alleged robbery, is scheduled to appear today before Knox County Criminal Court Judge Richard Baumgartner, records show. Last fall, a judge raised his bond after he was charged with aggravated assault.
<P>   An alleged member of Knoxville&#39;s East Side gang, Davis is accused of being an accessory to the May 18 slaying of Brittany S. Daniels, who was killed in a drive-by shooting in the Lonsdale Homes neighorhood. Police say he drove a car involved in the shooting.
<P>   The charge was transferred last year from Juvenile Court so Davis could stand trial as an adult. The case is pending before the grand jury, court records show.
<P>   In October, while he was out on bond, Davis and a 20-year-old man were charged with assaulting a woman in the Walter P. Taylor Homes housing project. As a consequence, Criminal Court Judge Ray L. Jenkins raised Davis&#39; bond from $35,000 to $50,000.
<P>   On Dec. 23, police allege Davis robbed William &#39;&#39;Junebug&#39;&#39; Martin of $200 in Taylor Homes. The next day someone shot him.
<P>   Davis was released from Baptist Hospital of East Tennessee last week, booked into the Knox County Jail and allowed to post another bond. 
<P>   Knox County Assistant District Attorney General Jo Helm is seeking to revoke Davis&#39; bond on the grounds he picked up the robbery charge while out for the other alleged crimes.
<P>   Helm, in court papers filed in Criminal Court, alleges Davis also was in violation of his curfew when he was shot. He was supposed to be in by 6 p.m. and was shot at 7:10 p.m., Helm alleges.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
