<P><B></B>
<P><B>BEBERGAL, DAVID - </B>age 79, of Knoxville, passed away at approximately 9:15 a.m. Sunday morning at Ft. Sanders Park West Regional Medical Center after a lengthy battle with cancer. He was born in 1917, in Charleston, S.C., where he lived before moving to Knoxville in the early &#39;40s. He was a longstanding member of Heska Amuna Synagogue and a member in good standing for 50 years in the Scottish Rite. Mr. Bebergal was a past general manager of the original General Products Corp. on Gay St. He later worked with Carlyle and Co. and Jewelry Box in Maryville and West Town Mall as manager. Preceded in death by parents, Esther and Samuel Bebergal. Survivors: wife of 50 years, Reva Jane Gurwin Bebergal; son, Steven Jay; daughter and son-in-law, Helene and Jay Markus of Memphis; grandchildren, Aaron Ross and Joshua Ben; several nieces and nephews including Pessa Brody and Esther Webster of Knoxville, and Harry Goldberg of Roanoke Island; several nieces and cousins from Columbus, Ohio; and special sister-in-law, Gladys Caller of Florida. Family and friends will meet for graveside services 2 p.m. Tuesday, January 14, 1997, at New Jewish Cemetery on Keith and Glenn Sts., Rabbi Shlomo Levine officiating. Active pallbearers: Bart Brody, Jerry Miller, Harold Shersky, Norbert Slovis, Gilbert Levinson, Zeke Freemin, Richard Keen, Jerome Salomone. Honorary pallbearers: Harold Brown, Monte Abrams, Monte Miller, Isadore Abrams, Dr. Haraf, Barry Wolf, Al Merlin, Sam Abrams, Lawrence Abrams, Irv Russoto, Charles Coffin, Leonard Shersky, Bill Noelton, Jeff Siegel, Phil Gurwin and Doug Binkley. In lieu of flowers, please make donations to Heska Amuna Synagogue or Knoxville Cancer Society. Arrangements by Rose Mortuary Mann Heritage Chapel.
<P>
<P><B>BINGHAM, GLEN F. - </B>age 80, of Knoxville, formerly of Dandridge, passed away Sunday afternoon, January 12, 1997, at U.T. Medical Center, Knoxville. He was a retired farmer and was of the Baptist faith. Preceded in death by parents, Calvin and Maggie Pointer Bingham; brothers, Floyd and David Bingham; sister, Shirley Bingham; children, Thelma Faundee Miller, Ervin and Brenda Bingham; stepson, Edward Graham; wives, Lillie Black Bingham and Edith Bingham. Survivors: wife, Pauline Moore Bingham of Knoxville; children, Barbara Turner and Jerry Bingham, both of Howell, Mich., C.C. &#39;&#39;Bud&#39;&#39; Bingham of Decatur, Ala., Mary Magalene Bingham and Ronnie Bingham, both of Somerset, Ky.; 37 grandchildren and nine great-grandchildren; brother, Delbert Bingham of Somerset, Ky.; sisters, Devonna Isam of Clarkston, Mich., Claudene Owen of Cincinnati, Ohio, Byrlene Bumgardner of Somerset, Ky., Julia Mae Haney of Florida; daughter-in-law, Maxine Graham of Rogers, Ark. Funeral service 11 a.m. Tuesday at Farrar Dandridge Chapel with Rev. Ernest Condee and Rev. Mike Seager officiating. Interment in Piedmont Cemetery. The family will receive friends 6-8 p.m. Monday evening at Farrar Funeral Home, Dandridge.
<P>
<P><B>BLAKNEY, DONALD EUGENE &#39;&#39;DON&#39;&#39; - </B>age 49, of Lookout Mountain, formerly of Lenoir City, passed away Sunday morning, January 12, 1997, at Memorial Hospital in Chattanooga. He was a member of Lookout Mountain Presbyterian Church. A former dispatcher with the Knoxville Police Department. The Goodwill Worker of the Year for 1977. He was preceded in death by his father, George E. Blakney. Survivors: wife, Suzanne Dickas Blakney of Lookout Mtn.; mother, Mary Blakney of Lenoir City; sister and brother-in-law, Susan and Ron Borden of Fayetteville, N.C.; niece, Erin Borden; nephew, Stephen Borden, both of Fayetteville, N.C.; father-in-law, Charles H. Dickas of Chattanooga; sisters-in-law and spouses, Dani and Pete Van Slyke of Signal Mtn., Caroline and Bernie Westner of East Ridge, Cathy Dickas Andrews of Georgetown; brother-in-law and wife, Charlie and Cindy Dickas of Chattanooga; uncles and aunts, Charles and Mildred Long, Vera Bivens, all of Lenoir City, Sue Stockton of Harrison, Dora Blakney of Wartburg; several cousins. The family will receive friends 5:30-7 p.m. Monday followed by funeral services at 7 p.m. in the Click Funeral Home Chapel, Rev. Joe Jenson and Rev. Joe Novenson officiating. Graveside services 11 a.m. Tuesday, Loudon County Memorial Gardens, Rev. Scott Cagle officiating. Click Funeral Home, Lenoir City, in charge.
