<P><B>
<P>MAPLES, WILLIAM CLOYD &#39;&#39;BILLY&#39;&#39; -</B>age 58, of Route 2, Rutledge, died early Saturday morning, January 11, 1997, at his residence in Rutledge after a lenghty illness.  He was a member of the Blue Springs Baptist Church and was preceded in death by his mother, Thelma Letha Maples.  Survivors include his son and daughter-in-law, Roger and Suzy Maples of Rutledge; daughters and sons-in-law, Sandy and Steve Vineyard of Blaine, Debra and Jeff Walker of Blaine, and Tammy and Dean Conley of Knoxville; father, Thomas Cloyd Maples of Rutledge; grandchildren, Amanda and Jonathan Vineyard, Brooke and Emily Berry, and Tyler and Chelsie Walker; brother, Bobby Maples of Rutledge; sisters, Barbara McDaniel, Bonnie Carter, Rhonda Spradling, and Wanda Coffman, all of Rutledge; many nieces and nephews and friends. Funeral services will be held at 8 p.m. Monday evening, January 13, 1997, from the Smith Funeral Home Chapel in Rutledge with Rev. Don Edwards, Rev. Mike Lee and Rev. Lee Wayne Grubb officiating. Graveside funeral services 1 p.m. Tuesday conducted by the East Tennessee Veterans Honor Gaurd in the Grainger Memorial Gardens. Pallbearers will be Tim Carter, Tim Corum, Shannon Coffman, Jamie McDaniel, Jerry Hancock, and Jarvis Hancock.  The family will receive friends from 6-8 p.m. Monday evening prior to services at the funeral home. Arrangements by Smith Funeral Home, 123 Water St., Rutledge, TN 37861 Phone (423) 828-5555.
<P>
<P><B>MARSHALL, THE REVEREND JAMES A. - </B>of Whitesburg, Tenn., passed from this troublesome life into the next on January 11, 1997, after an extended illness. He was 63 years old. He was preceded in death by his first wife, Fran. His survivors include his wife, Linda; his daughter, Carolyn Mahan and her husband, Greg; his son, Kevin S. Marshall; his grandchildren, Jacob and Rachel Goan; his stepchildren, Tina Tipton and her husband, Jeff, Jeff McClanahan, Wendy Lipe and her husband, Micheal; his step-grandchildren, April Tipton, Dylan Lipe, Halley McClanahan; his sisters, Dixie Cowden, Betty Faye Rokosky, Tresia Crowfoot, Brenda Chapman; his brothers, Tommy Marshall, Ronald Marshall, Donald Marshall; his special aunt, Beulah Hightower; several nieces and nephews; and a host of friends and relatives. During his career as a minister he pastored several area churches and was a longtime member of Lee Valley Missionary Baptist Church. He served in the U.S. Army and the U.S. Marine Corps during the Korean Conflict, and was decorated for service. He was a 32 Degree Master Mason, a member of Tate Springs Masonic Lodge #438 F&AM, a member of Kyle Masonic Lodge #422 F&AM, and an honorary member of several East Tennessee Masonic Lodges. He was a founding member of the Tennessee Lodge of Research and served as its secretary from its inception until his death. He was a member of the Knights Templar, York Rite, Scottish Rite, the Royal Order of Scotland, the Jericho Shrine Club and the Fraternal Order of the Oddfellows. A few of his many accomplishments include being a founding leader of the Clinch Mountain Association of Missionary Baptist Churches, a &#39;&#39;Fellow of the Craft&#39;&#39; of the Tennessee Lodge of Research, a staunch supporter of local charities, serving as the Right Worthy Grand Chaplain of the Grand Lodge of the State of Tennessee in 1983 and again in 1986, and serving as secretary of the Nuclear Veterans Association. In lieu of flowers, the family requests memorial donations be sent to either of the following: The Masonic Widows and Orphans Fund, Tate Springs Scholarship Fund, Lee Valley Missionary Baptist Church or Three Springs Missionary Baptist Church. Funeral services 8 p.m. Tuesday at Stubblefield Funeral Home with Rev. Willard Wilder, Rev. Dwain Brewer, Rev. Sonny Davis and Rev. Tommy Marshall officiating. Masonic service 11 a.m. Wednesday at Stubblefield Funeral Home with burial to follow in Creech&#39;s Chapel Cemetery. The family will receive friends 7-9 p.m. Monday and 6-8 p.m. Tuesday at Stubblefield Funeral Home, 5421 E. Andrew Johnson Hwy., Morristown, Tenn.
<P>
