		<h3>Philippoussis latest big name to ask out of Australian Open </h3>
<P>
<P>    If the Australian Open doesn&#39;t hurry up and start, nobody may be left to play.
<P>    The year&#39;s first Grand Slam event lost its biggest name, or at least the one with the most letters in it and the most appeal to hometown fans, when <B>Mark Philippoussis</B> withdrew with an arm injury on the eve of today&#39;s first-round matches at Melbounre.
<P>    A year ago, Philippoussis put on a dazzling show of power tennis to knock out top-seed <B>Pete Sampras</B> in the third round. On Sunday, Philippoussis pulled out of what looked like the best opening-round match, a center court duel against Britain&#39;s rising star, <B>Tim Henman</B>.
<P>    The injured-and-out camp is getting pretty full: defending women&#39;s champion <B>Monica Seles</B>, French Open champion <B>Yevgeny Kafelnikov</B>, Wimbledon champion <B>Richard Krajicek, Todd Martin, Cedric Pioline, Jason Stoltenberg</B>.
<P>    The don&#39;t-feel-like-playing camp already claimed 1995 champion <B>Andre Agassi</B> and <B>Jana Novotna</B>.
<P> Among those scheduled to play today are defending champion <B>Boris Becker</B> and women&#39;s No. 1 <B>Steffi Graf</B>. The men&#39;s top seed, Sampras, has the first day off.
<P>
<P><h3>Baseball</h3>
<P>
<P>* <B>Jerry Neudecker </B>-- the last major league umpire to wear a balloon chest protector -- has died of cancer at age 66. Neudecker, who died Saturday at Columbia-Fort Walton Beach (Fla.) Medical Center, was an American League umpire from 1965 to 1986.
<P>* Multimillion-dollar salaries weren&#39;t enough for some Dominican major leaguers who have been selling U.S. visas on the black market to would-be illegal immigrants, a Santo Domingo newspaper reported Sunday. According to El Nacional, the baseball players and scouts would request visas for family members to attend games in the United States, and then sell them for as much as $6,000 on the street. The paper did not release any names.
<P>
<P><h3>Running</h3>
<P>
<P>* Sweden&#39;s <B>Ake Eriksson </B>and late entry <B>Claudia Dreher </B>of Germany overcame freezing rain and icy streets to win the men&#39;s and women&#39;s divisions of the 25th Houston Marathon. Eriksson  finished in 2 hours, 19 minutes, 21 seconds.
<P><B></B>
<P><h3>Skiing</h3>
<P>
<P>* Six years after her first World Cup victory, an extremely fit <B>Pernilla Wiberg </B>won a Super G race at Bad Kleinkiirchheim, Austria.
<P>* Even a healthy <B>Alberto Tomba </B>would have had trouble beating Austria&#39;s <B>Thomas Sykora,</B> whose victory at Chamonix, France, was the most convincing in the last two years of World Cup slalom skiing.
<P><B></B>
<P><h3>College basketball</h3>
<P>
<P>* <B></B>Former Bearden High School standout <B>Turner Emery</B> scored 19 points to lead Sewanee (8-2, 2-0) to a 70-59 victory over Oglethorpe University in a Southern Collegiate Athletic Conference game.
<P>
<P>
