<head>
	<title>Inner city arson</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 12, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>Inner city arson</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Church can get $800,000 government loan to rebuild</FONT></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Wesley Loy, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">T</FONT>he Inner City Church, burned by arsonists a year ago, can count on Uncle Sam to guarantee a bank loan of up to $800,000 to help rebuild.
<P>   The loan guarantee from the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development bolsters an already lucrative pot of rebuilding money reaped by the church. Inner City has accepted big checks from an insurance company, a national church organization and admirers of Reggie White, the pro football star who served as an associate pastor for Inner City.
<P>   All totaled, Inner City already has received at least $800,000. If it uses the federal guarantee to get an $800,000 bank loan, Inner City ostensibly would have $1.6 million to rebuild its church, which was destroyed in a bizarre arson fire on Jan. 8, 1996.
<P>   Since the day of the blaze, church leaders have vowed to do just that -- rebuild. But today, one year after the blaze on a cold and snowy night, the lot occupied by the doomed church at 3536 Skyline Drive remains vacant, aside from a stack of cement blocks that arrived with visiting civil-rights leader the Rev. Jesse Jackson in July.
<P>   And the fire remains a vexing mystery, one that has spawned intense speculation in Knoxville as to who burned the multiracial church and why.
<P>   The FBI and the U.S. Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco & Firearms say they still have substantial forces devoted to investigating this fire, which by dint of its famous member, White of the Green Bay Packers, was prominent in last year&#39;s national string of church burnings.
<P>   Federal agents remain underwhelmed by public response to a hefty reward for information in the Inner City case. If somebody has key information, $105,000 apparently is not enough to talk.
<P>   But it&#39;s never too late to step forward, said ATF Special Agent Michael Durham. &#39;&#39;Any lead that comes up, we are definitely going to pursue it,&#39;&#39; Durham said.
<P>   Neither the FBI nor ATF are willing to say whether they have suspects in the blaze. Nor are they ready to say whether the fire is linked to a fake bomb planted at the back door of the church&#39;s business offices in August.
<P>   But federal agents did take the unusual step months ago of publicly displaying materials used to torch the Inner City Church. The arsonists shotgunned gasoline, gunpowder and Molotov cocktails all through the building, which housed not only the sanctuary but a planned day-care center and radio station.
<P>   Racist graffiti was sprayed on walls, too, leading to speculation that the church fell to bigots intent on terrorism.
<P>   Federal agents say they&#39;ve not ruled that out. But church leaders have complained that they, too, have been targeted in the investigation.
<P>   Inner City is far more than a church. The Inner City organization operates a novel community bank, staked by $1 million in seed from White, plus a housing rehabilitation program and an &#39;&#39;entrepreneur school.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Since the fire, these business activities have continued apparently unabated, while church services have relocated to Austin-East High School.
<P>   If church members are suspects in the blaze, it hasn&#39;t affected Inner City&#39;s relationship with the city&#39;s Department of Community Development. In July, the city reconfirmed Inner City Community Development Inc. as one of its two designated &#39;&#39;community housing development organizations,&#39;&#39; good for a $47,700 grant.
<P>   Inner City Community Development Inc. is an umbrella organization headed by Jerry Upton, whose brother, the Rev. David Upton, is chief pastor for the Inner City Church.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We feel they&#39;re doing great work in the community,&#39;&#39; said Laurens Tullock, director of the city&#39;s Community Development office. &#39;&#39;There&#39;s an incredible need for folks committed to rebuilding the inner city, doing affordable housing and job creation in the inner city.&#39;&#39;
<P>   The Rev. R.N. McGhee, a cousin of the Uptons and president of the Knoxville Baptist Ministerial Alliance, an organization of black ministers, said he&#39;s troubled by speculation that someone connected to the church might have set the blaze.
<P>   If that is so, asked McGhee, where are the indictments?
<P>   &#39;&#39;I feel like had it been an inside job, they would have uncovered evidence of it long ago,&#39;&#39; he said.
<P>   Last week, Inner City leaders hinted that an announcement was imminent about the church&#39;s rebuilding plans. A local architectural firm, McCarty Holsaple McCarty, has designed a new multipurpose church building, which Inner City leaders have said might cost up to $1.4 million.
<P>   But Inner City&#39;s exact rebuilding plans are unclear. The Uptons have been reticent about discussing their plans, routinely declining to return phone calls.
<P>   Inner City has made moves to prepare the old church site for a new building, but staffers with the Metropolitan Planning Commission have rejected the church&#39;s request to close an adjacent side street.
<P>   David Upton, reached Friday on the request line at his church&#39;s recently reactivated radio station, said an offer was made on an existing building and a deal was near. He said more information would be forthcoming.
<P>   Loranne Ellis, a HUD official in Washington, D.C., who oversees the federal loan guarantee program, said Inner City, if it secures a bank loan, is free to use the money to buy rather than build a new home.
<P>   The loan guarantee program was part of the Church Arson Prevention Act, passed by Congress last year to combat a perceived rash of church arsons.
<P>   Inner City is one of about 80 churches to qualify for a federal loan guarantee. The idea is that, with the muscle of the government&#39;s good word, burned churches can go to private banks for low-interest rebuilding loans.
<P>   The loan guarantees complement grants to arson-plagued churches from the New York-based National Council of Churches. The Inner City Church has tapped that source of funding, too, for $50,000 so far.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

