<head>
	<title>TVA awards computer service contract to BTG</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 12, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>TVA awards computer service contract to BTG</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Jerry Dean, News-Sentinel business writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">F</FONT>or the third time in four months, TVA has awarded a multimillion dollar computer services contract to BTG Inc., a computer hardware and services contractor based in Vienna, Va.
<P>   BTG Senior Program Manager Sue Miller said the most recent TVA-BTG contract, for $10 million worth of goods and services to be delivered to TVA during the coming year, also has an option for an extension to four additional years. Thus, the potential total contract value could be up to $50 million.
<P>   John Moulton, TVA&#39;s media relations manager, said Thursday that the new BTG contract, approved by the Board in late December, was for BTG to perform maintenance on computer hardware known as servers.
<P>   A previous computer services contract expired, Moulton said, and after an interim contract was approved, BTG submitted the best technical offer and low bid among 10 computer services firms responding to TVA&#39;s invitation for proposals. 
<P>   TVA also has concluded extensive, multimillion dollar computer contracts with Oracle Systems Corp. of Redwood City, Calif., for its Oracle Office systems and database management services; and with Microsoft Corp. of Redmond, Wash., which provides TVA with e-mail, Windows and other computer software used throughout TVA&#39;s seven-state service area.
<P>   Last August, the TVA Board approved a $4.4 million Oracle computer contract, in addition to a previous $27.1 million Oracle computer services and software contract already in force. 
<P>   That mid-year contract approval came despite a TVA Inspector General&#39;s inquiry that had resulted in Oracle&#39;s refunding more than $8 million on alleged overbillings from its earlier TVA contract.
<P>   The BTG contract was the third major contract BTG had received from TVA since September. Prior TVA contract awards to BTG were to provide TVA information technology services and microcomputers. BTG in 1995 acquired a previous TVA supplier, Chattanooga-based Concept Automation Inc.
<P> 
<P>   TVA also in 1995 had contracts of $8.1 million and $1.37 million with SCB Computer Technology of Germantown to help the federal power-producing agency upgrade and cut costs of its information services systems. SCB, in 1996, was under federal investigation for having overbilled TVA on a $10 million information systems contract, yet TVA&#39;s Board routinely approved SCB&#39;s second contract at an April 1996 meeting in Asheville, N.C.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
