<html>

<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="keywords"
content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>Snow Skiing --- Southern Style</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i>January 12, 1997</i> <p><a
        href="4056.htm"><font size="2"><b>Ski-inspired fashions
        leave the slopes, hit the streets</b></font></a></p>
        </td>
        <td width="470"><font size="2"><i><img
        src="../images/Living2.jpg" width="460" height="317"><br
        clear="all">
        <br>
        </i></font><p><font size="6"><b>Snow Skiing --- Southern
        Style</b></font><font size="5"><br>
        In Dixie, they don't need a lot of snow to ski</font></p>
        <p><font size="2"><i><br>
        John Gaylon Doty, special to the News-Sentinel</i></font></p>
        <p>Grab almost any copy of a ski magazine off the local
        magazine rack and you might think the South has seceded
        again. Or, at least, that there is no downhill skiing to
        be had south of the Mason-Dixon Line. </p>
        <p>Think again. </p>
        <p>While there may not be a Vail, Aspen, Jackson Hole or
        Killington equivalent for diehard skiers in the Sunbelt,
        there are 22 ski areas in seven Southern states that
        provide close-to-home skiing opportunities, the chance to
        enjoy the sport without mortgaging the house, and a
        varying range of skiing terrain and apres' ski
        activities. </p>
        <p>Together, these areas register well over a million
        visits a year and chances are one or more of them will
        suit your tastes. </p>
        <p>A gravity sport, downhill skiing's success in the
        South necessarily depends on the slopes of the
        Appalachian mountains and foothills and the region's
        fickle weather. Southern areas set records for skiers and
        skiing conditions during last season's cold winter and
        there is optimism for this season. </p>
        <p>''If you believe in woolly worms and fogs then we
        should have another good year,'' said one ski area
        operator. </p>
        <p>Not surprisingly, North Carolina, with its 4,000- to
        5,000-foot-plus summits, offers the most numerous
        opportunities, with seven ski areas. West Virginia runs a
        close second with six, Virginia boasts four and Kentucky,
        Tennessee, Georgia and Alabama each have one. </p>
        <p>These areas run the gamut from West Virginia's
        Snowshoe/Silver Creek, only a seven-hour drive from
        Knoxville and recognized by skiing enthusiasts as the
        crown jewel of Southern skiing, to the tiny, southernmost
        ski area, the 26-year-old Cloudmont Ski and Golf Resort
        in Mentone, Ala. </p>
        <p>The adage among Southern skiers is ''if you learn to
        ski well in the South, you can ski well anywhere in the
        world.'' This is a veiled, but somewhat valid, reference
        to the region's fickle winters. Warm days can melt snow
        and cold nights freeze it into a sheet of solid ice that
        requires excellent skiing technique and sharp ski edges
        to maintain control. </p>
        <p>But Southern ski resorts are doing more than ever to
        battle icy conditions with more attention to the
        ''grooming'' of slopes -- breaking up and smoothing the
        surface with specialized machinery, sometimes twice a day
        -- and expansion of snowmaking capacity to keep fresh
        snow cover on the slopes. </p>
        <p>For the most part, snowmaking and grooming are what
        keep Southern ski areas viable and increasingly
        competitive in the face of uncertain weather. ''One thing
        that has happened is that all the Southern areas have
        made huge investments in snowmaking capacity and have
        dramatically improved the sophistication of their
        snowmaking equipment,'' said Tony Waddell, president of
        the Southeastern Ski Association. ''Everyone always tells
        me they bet I'm wishing for a lot of snow this winter. I
        tell them the best snow is an inch in Atlanta or
        Nashville or some other metropolitan area in the South.
        That gets the interest cranked up. Natural snow has
        almost become window dressing in terms of skiing.'' </p>
        <p>''The South is head and shoulders above everyone in
        the Northeast and West in the ability to make and
        maximize the use of man-made snow,'' says Joe Stevens, of
        Snowshoe/Silver Creek, which adds to or improves its
        snowmaking capabilities nearly every year. ''Southern
        areas have been at it a long time because we've had to.
        It can be 40 or 50 degrees or raining in the backyards of
        most Southerners and ski areas in the mountains can have
        great skiing.'' </p>
        <p>One of the newest trends this year is the introduction
        of the new ''shaped'' ski to the rental equipment of some
        Southern ski areas, such as Wintergreen in Virginia,
        Cataloochee in North Carolina and others. These skis have
        an hour-glass shape, a new design which makes carving
        turns easier. They are to downhill skiing what oversized
        rackets were to tennis. </p>
        <p>Also look for more opportunities to snowboard. A
        growing number of Southern ski areas are capitalizing on
        the biggest growth in the Southern market, especially
        among young people, by offering snowboarding lessons and
        rentals in addition to the traditional ski lessons.
        Snowboards are, in some respects, similar to surfboards,
        which allow participants to ''surf'' their way down snowy
        slopes. While many Southern ski areas have opened all or
        portions of their slopes to snowboarding, others, like
        Wintergreen, have made major capital investments in the
        development of specialized ''snowboard parks.'' </p>
        <p>Wintergreen's Mark Glickman said their snowboard park,
        which opened last year, was so popular they have expanded
        it for this season and added more terrain challenges. </p>
        <p>Waddell says snowboards and shaped skis ''putting fun
        back in skiing again. Naturally, teenagers started the
        snowboard trend, but now we're seeing adults and families
        participating. I see a lot of father-son and
        mother-daughter pairings snowboarding together now.'' </p>
        <p>Lift tickets in the region range from $10 for
        afternoon sessions and night skiing under lights during
        the week, to $40 for daytime skiing on weekends and/or
        holidays. </p>
        <p>Best values are late in the season and mid-week.
        Martin Luther King's birthday, as well as the Christmas
        holiday season, normally commands premium rates for both
        lift tickets and accommodations. Many areas offer an
        array of special packages that can trim costs up to 50
        percent, especially near season's end. </p>
        <p>Generally, most areas open in mid-November and many
        remain open into April. In fact, some areas close in late
        March not because of the lack of snow, but because of
        lack of interest. </p>
        <p>In addition, many Southern ski areas are full-service,
        year-round resorts, which offer not only skiing, but also
        accommodations and other amenities and activities, such
        as restaurants, indoor pools, saunas and whirlpools,
        exercise rooms, child care, shopping and a variety of
        special winter activities and events. They make enjoyable
        winter getaways even if skiing isn't your main winter
        pursuit. </p>
        <p>Full-service resorts with good instruction programs
        are not the only way to sample skiing for the first time.
        Another cost-effective approach is membership in a local
        ski club, many of which not only provide instruction but
        also single and multi-day ski trips. The Knoxville Ski
        Club, for instance, organizes trips to ski destinations
        all over the world, including slopes in the South. </p>
        <p>Here's a representative sampling of the range of
        Southern ski destinations: </p>
        <p><img src="../../images/blkbul.gif" alt="*" hspace="5"
        width="14" height="14">Snowshoe/Silver Creek -- Located
        in Snowshoe, W.Va., these are two separate but adjacent
        areas under a single ownership. They represent the
        ultimate in the Southern skiing experience, as indicated
        by the 410,000 skier visits last year. The area averages
        180 inches of natural snow each year (292 inches last
        year) on its 53 slopes and trails, has a 4,848-foot
        summit, a 1,500-foot vertical drop and a long run of 1.5
        miles. There are 100 ski instructors, six full-service
        restaurants, nine nightclubs and 1,500 rooms and condos. </p>
        <p><img src="../../images/blkbul.gif" alt="*" hspace="5"
        width="14" height="14"> Ober Gatlinburg -- This is really
        close-to-home skiing for Knoxvillians and is a favorite
        among Floridians as well. Located above and connected to
        the resort community of Gatlinburg via both paved road
        and aerial tram, Ober Gatlinburg has an average annual
        snowfall of 50 inches on eight slopes that reach a summit
        elevation of 3,300 feet with a vertical drop of 600 feet.
        The longest run is 5,000 feet. At the base of the
        mountain in the town is more than 150 motels and numerous
        chalets and a range of shopping and dining opportunities
        now that the community has become a truly year-round
        resort destination. Smoky Mountain Lights, a
        multi-million light display in Gatlinburg and Pigeon
        Forge, runs through February. </p>
        <p><img src="../../images/blkbul.gif" alt="*" hspace="5"
        width="14" height="14"> Wintergreen -- Off the Blue Ridge
        Parkway southwest of Charlottesville, Va., Wintergreen is
        one of that state's premier skiing destinations. The
        shopping and village complex is at the top of the
        3,515-foot summit and skiers ski down 10 slopes to catch
        lifts back up. Make your last run and get to the lift
        before it closes because it's a long walk up. The area
        features a 1,000-foot drop, a long run of 4,450 feet,
        four restaurants and 350 slopeside condos. The
        Wintergreen Spa has an indoor pool, Jacuzzi, hot tubs,
        saunas, exercise room and restaurant. </p>
        <p><img src="../../images/blkbul.gif" alt="*" hspace="5"
        width="14" height="14"> Sugar Mountain -- Located near
        Banner Elk, N.C., Sugar is the state's largest ski area
        with 18 slopes and 115 skiable acres, a summit elevation
        of 5,300 feet, a 1,200-foot vertical drop, a single run
        of 1.5 miles and a lift capacity of over 8,800 skiers per
        hour. There are two cafeterias, a lounge/restaurant and
        an outdoor grill. Just three miles away is Banner Elk,
        which offers a variety of cuisine and shopping
        opportunities. Accommodations vary from the 32-room
        Slopeside Inn to a variety of condos and homes located
        within the confines of the Sugar Mountain Resort complex.
        </p>
        <p><img src="../../images/blkbul.gif" alt="*" hspace="5"
        width="14" height="14"> Appalachian Ski Mountain --
        Located between Blowing Rock and Boone, N.C., Appalachian
        is one example of an area that does not feature on-site
        accommodations or non-skiing activities. The area does
        provide a restaurant and ski/gift shop. Visitors come
        here strictly for skiing -- day or night -- on nine
        slopes that have 100 percent snowmaking coverage to
        augment the 60 inches of natural snow each year. The
        longest run is one-half mile with a 356-foot drop from
        the 4,000-foot summit. </p>
        <p><img src="../../images/blkbul.gif" alt="*" hspace="5"
        width="14" height="14"> Cloudmont Ski and Golf Resort --
        Located on the Little River below Desoto Falls in
        northeast Alabama, Cloudmont is part of the Shady Grove
        Dude Ranch and the South's southernmost ski area. It
        features two 1,000-foot slopes with a 150-foot drop from
        the 1,900-foot summit, chalet and lodge accommodations
        and a snack bar. If skiing conditions are marginal, which
        they often are in this part of the country even with the
        area's nine snowmakers, you can saddle up a horse and
        ride through some beautiful countryside. </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

<hr size="5">

