<html>

<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="keywords"
content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>Ski-inspired fashions leave the slopes, hit the streets</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i>January 12, 1997</i> <br>
        <p><a href="4062.htm"><font size="2"><b>Snow Skiing ---
        Southern Style</b><br>
        In Dixie, they don't need a lot of snow to ski</font></a></p>
        </td>
        <td width="470"><font size="6"><b>Ski-inspired fashions
        leave the slopes, hit the streets</b></font><table
        border="0" cellpadding="2" align="right">
            <tr>
                <td width="144"><font size="2"><i><img
                src="../images/Living1.jpg" width="144"
                height="214"></i></font></td>
            </tr>
        </table>
        <p><font size="2"><i>From staff reports</i></font></p>
        <p><br>
        <font size="5">T</font>his season, winter fashion is
        taking its cue from the slopes. </p>
        <p>From shimmering anoraks to body-hugging fleece
        unitards, the look is cropping up in magazines and
        stores. </p>
        <p>Some fashion forecasters say the increased popularity
        of skiing and snowboarding have inspired the trend. What
        used to be only found in outdoor shops and catalogs are
        now on the racks of clothing and department stores. </p>
        <p>From Mossimo and Adrienne Vittadini to Victoria's
        Secret and Talbots, designers are fusing the funky and
        the functional. </p>
        <p>Some of the styles are more snow bunny than
        slope-ready. And a word of caution: Some of the slim
        shapes and sexy silhouettes require a steady diet of that
        other ski-inspired novelty -- the Nordic Track. </p>
        <p>Even if you can't make it to Vail this winter, you can
        borrow some of the style. Here's how: </p>
        <p>Layering is the key to winter dressing. Big, quilted
        parkas stuffed with Polyfil keep you dry during wet
        weather in water-resistant nylon. There are brightly
        colored jackets in shades of caution-light yellow, red,
        metallic silver, and electric blue, with zip fronts that
        hit at the waist or longer stadium coats secured with
        drawstring waist. </p>
        <p>Parkas and pullover anoraks are lined with Polar Tech
        fleece or Thermolite insulation to keep you warm during
        sub-zero temperatures. Some parkas feature a removable
        vest of fleece lining. Look for styles with fur trim. </p>
        <p>Body-hugging ski pants in fleece are hot paired with
        faux furry snow boots. The form-fitting pants are also
        cool with platform street boots or shoes. </p>
        <p>Down-filled vests over stretchy cotton/Spandex pants
        are slope-ready with a color block turtleneck. Horizontal
        stripes adorn ski-chic gear. </p>
        <p>GirlStar, a division of GOTCHA Sportswear calls their
        winter line, inspired by snowboarding, the ''Snow Bunny''
        collection. The teen-targeted fashions feature ''the
        requisite baggy pants, loose tops, and thick-soled
        shoes,'' for street-slope chic. </p>
        <p>Keep the little ones dry and warm with quilted bib
        overall snow pants and water-resistant nylon mittens. </p>
        <p>Vibrant colors like lemon, lime, burnt orange and
        fuchsia move against black backdrops. Toboggans in fur,
        wool and Polar Tech keep those noggins warm when exposed
        to the elements. </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

<hr size="5">

