<html>
<head>
	<title>TVA audit questions $2.6 million in costs, eyes contract savings</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 12, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>TVA audit questions $2.6 million in costs, eyes contract savings</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Jerry Dean, News-Sentinel business writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">T</FONT>he TVA inspector general has questioned nearly $2.6 million spent by TVA and found that another $28.2 million could have been used more effectively in its audit of TVA for the first six months of fiscal 1996.
<P>   The audit charges that Onyx International Inc. of Knoxville, a TVA coal supplier, has incurred costs and damages to TVA exceeding $1.9 million as a result of contract noncompliance.
<P>   The audit also identified $2.9 million in potential savings on a proposed $28 million contract with TVA&#39;s Fossil and Hydro Power.
<P>   TVA IG George T. Prosser, in a semiannual report to Congress and the TVA board, reported that 105 IG investigations during mid-1996 led to recovery of $2.3 million for TVA, as well as 12 convictions. As of Sept. 30, the office still had 158 cases under active investigation.
<P>   Much of the report focused on IG investigations of TVA coal purchases. Among the audit findings:
<P>   * TVA concessions to Onyx International listed $706,489 in &#39;&#39;unrecoverable&#39;&#39; costs after TVA tried to help the minority-owned vendor, whose president and chief executive officer is John A. Sibley, become a coal producer. 
<P>   TVA spokesmen said negotiations are ongoing.<B> </B>But the IG&#39;s report urged that TVA seek to recover $161,057 from the vendor for overbillings and delinquencies -- then assess chances of collecting $970,234 more from Onyx.
<P>   * One coal contractor, Pyramid Mining Inc. of Owensboro, Ky., regularly had turned off a mechanical coal sampler designed to evaluate coal quality, while crews loaded less desirable high-sulfur coal onto barges.
<P>   That practice invalidated a coal sampling quality analysis the contractor sent to TVA, whose contract required coal meet specific lab analysis standards. So TVA received $1.8 million in a civil suit settlement. The U.S. attorney&#39;s office in Louisville, Ky., is also investigating the matter.
<P>   Ted R. Ping, assistant TVA IG for Audit Operations, said TVA still has nine coal contract investigations pending. 
<P>   * In an audit of Fossil and Hydropower Group contractor cost proposals -- for providing fire protection systems under a 3-year, $28 million contract -- the IG found that F.E. Moran Inc. had overstated costs of eight such projects, totaling $8.35 million, by $251,075.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Contractors&#39; actual profits on the firm-price projects,&#39;&#39; the IG found, &#39;&#39;have significantly exceeded the profits disclosed in its project proposals.
<P>   The IG concluded TVA could save $2.1 million &#39;&#39;by negotiating cost reimbursement payment terms rather than paying fixed prices for remaining contract projects.&#39;&#39; 
<P>    * In an inquiry into TVA providers of information technology, the IG did &#39;&#39;pre-award audits&#39;&#39; of six top offers which, the IG said, led to a $611,000 savings on three contractor awards totaling $44 million. Audited were National Systems and Research Co., CDI Information Services, Distributed Information Systems Inc., Millennium Computer Technology Inc., Roberts & Schaefer Co. and BTG Inc.
<P>   * An audit also reported that TVA as of March 1995, had overpaid Gilbert/Commonwealth Inc., an engineering services contractor, $349,389 beyond costs that a subcontractor, United Energy Services Corp., incurred on work done for TVA&#39;s Fossil and Hydropower Group. TVA now seeks recovery of the overpayment. 
<P>   * The IG also investigated fraudulent expense vouchers filed by TVA contractors&#39; employees at Watts Bar and Browns Ferry nuclear plants. 
<P>   In a Watts Bar case, TVA Nuclear agreed to recover $236,500 from five contractors. During the six months, TVA Nuclear withheld more than $600,000 from two contractors and had another company reimburse TVA more than $28,600.
<P>   Three former WBN contract employees were prosecuted for $12,000 in false claims. TVA&#39;s IG said seven other former Watts Bar contract employees will be prosecuted for various types of fraud totaling more than $271,800.
<P>   At Browns Ferry Nuclear Plant in Alabama, two TVA contractors&#39; ex-employees pled guilty to federal fraud charges. Three were ordered to repay TVA more than $108,200. Five other contract employees will be prosecuted for fraud totaling $220,000.
<P>   * IG investigations of workers&#39; compensation cases led to convictions of four former TVA employees and termination of benefits for others, resulting in a $3.1 million savings to TVA.
<P>     * The IG also studied use of TVA&#39;s $12 million, 1,300-vehicle passenger car fleet. Operating that fleet, the IG said, costs TVA $5.7 million a year or 20.8 cents a mile -- compared with the 15 cents a mile TVA reported. The IG said TVA understated fleet costs by omitting depreciation and capital costs.
<P>   Maintaining a TVA fleet, the IG found, remains more cost-effective than leasing vehicles commercially or from the General Services Administration, or reimbursing employees&#39; for their business mileage.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
