<head>
	<title>Many problems await 100th General Assembly</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 12, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Many problems await 100th General Assembly</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Budget shortfall heads list</FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Tom Humphrey, News-Sentinel Nashville bureau</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">N</FONT>ASHVILLE -- As Tennessee enters its third century of statehood, its Legislature meets for a landmark 100th session this week to grapple with a lot of old issues given new twists.
<P>    For example, the budget and partisanship have been historic staples in the creation of lawmaking controversy. But the 100th General Assembly, which officially convenes at noon Tuesday, finds state money running unusually low and partisanship running unusually high.
<P>    That potentially volatile mix may spill over into other arenas, causing some unease in the 500-member lobbyist corps that seeks to sway the thinking of 132 legislators on matters of clients&#39; interest.
<P>    &#39;&#39;It&#39;s going to be a year to keep your head low and be ready to play defense,&#39;&#39; surmised one veteran lobbyist in assessing the 1997 legislative landscape.
<P>    The most prominent feature of that landscape is a mountainous projected budget shortfall of around $400 million -- $100 million in the current fiscal year and $300 million in the 1997-98 fiscal year that begins July 1.
<P>    The shortage appears against a backdrop of some bitter partisan rivalry during the 1996 legislative campaigns. Democrats emerged victorious overall, reclaiming control of the state Senate with an 18-15 majority and building their advantage in the House to 61-38.
<P>    Republican Gov. Don Sundquist actively campaigned against some of the Democratic winners, though he avoided personal involvement in campaigns against sitting Democrat lawmakers.
<P>    Sundquist has hinted strongly that his budget proposal -- which remains officially under wraps for three more weeks -- will include no pay raise for teachers and state employees and may call for some state workers to be laid off.
<P>    Most of the $14 billion state budget is immune from cuts -- either because it comes from federal sources or is used to fund programs deemed &#39;&#39;essential services&#39;&#39; by the governor. Those include health care, prisons and education -- all expected to have spending increases.
<P>    The biggest increase is for education, where $200 million in new monies is slated to complete the last stage of school improvements provided in an education reform law enacted five years ago. All told, Sundquist&#39;s figures project $240 million in new revenue for 1997-98, but that is more than offset by some $540 million in new spending requirements.
<P>    The Tennessee State Employees Association&#39;s leadership has voiced skepticism about Sundquist&#39;s financial figures despite the governor&#39;s assurance that &#39;&#39;we&#39;re not playing games with anyone.&#39;&#39;
<P>    House Speaker Jimmy Naifeh says lawmakers are not taking the governor&#39;s word on the financial crisis either. They plan, he said, to bring in &#39;&#39;new expertise of our own . . . so we don&#39;t have to rely on the administration&#39;s expertise&#39;&#39; in calculating the state of financial affairs. 
<P>    As for layoffs, Naifeh said: &#39;&#39;I don&#39;t think the General Assembly will respond very favorably to that.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Sundquist, Naifeh and Lt. Gov. John Wilder, who presides over the Senate, all profess willingness to work together in bipartisan fashion. But there is clearly the potential for strife on several fronts.
<P>    Naifeh, for example, said he expects legislators to put the possibility of abolishing the Tennessee Higher Education Commission &#39;&#39;on the front burner.&#39;&#39; Sundquist in November orchestrated the firing of THEC&#39;s executive director, Bryant Millsaps, who contends he aroused gubernatorial wrath by not tailoring THEC action to Sundquist&#39;s political agenda.
<P>    &#39;&#39;I don&#39;t know where you&#39;d get an executive director -- who&#39;s qualified to serve -- with the political climate they have now,&#39;&#39; Naifeh said of THEC.
<P>    The idea of reforming or abolishing THEC has been around for years but was never seriously considered until recent twists of political fate.
<P>    Some other old issues that may get new attention this session include:
<P>    * Getting tougher on crimals, ranging from drunken-driving offenders to murderers. Proposals in Republican and Democratic anti-crime packages range from chemical castration of child molesters to trying to speed up death penalty appeals.
<P>    * Giving local governments more power to raise their taxes without approval of the Legislature. Sundquist recently indicated to the Tennessee Municipal League that legislation &#39;&#39;dealing strictly with a local tax matter&#39;&#39; would not violate his pledge to enact no new taxes because that is different from state taxes.
<P>    The governor and Democratic legislators have quarrelled over local tax bills in the past, and Sundquist has refused to sign them. Votes on such bills have been hot issues in some campaigns.
<P>    * Trying again to authorize a statewide referendum on repealing a state constitutional provision that forbids lotteries. The proposal must pass both the House and Senate by two-thirds majorities either this year or next to get on the 1998 ballot. As usual, the measure is expected to pass the House but has virtually no chance in the Senate.
<P>    * Reforming campaign finance laws and ethics rules for officeholders or lobbyists. Naifeh, irritated by recent Republican campaign tactics, says he wants a close look at &#39;&#39;where does the libel start and just plain campaigning stop.&#39;&#39; The idea is to forbid outright lies in campaign literature without infringing on free political speech -- a difficult proposition to legally define, according to many lawyers.
<P>    * Overhauling the structure of the state government bureaucracy.
<P>    Sundquist has proposed to abolish the state Department of Mental Health and Mental Retardation, putting its functions within an expanded Department of Public Health, along with TennCare and some other programs. He needs legislative approval for the move, and Democrats have questioned the idea. Naifeh says he believes the U.S. Department of Justice, which has battled the state in court over conditions at some mental-health institutions, &#39;&#39;is not going to allow that to happen.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Naifeh also was dubious about a Sundquist plan to consolidate state lawyers into a central office while Sen. Robert Rochelle, D-Lebanon, has openly attacked the plan. Attorney General Charles Burson has said that legislators must approve that move, too, though Sundquist aides say the governor can act without legislative approval.
<P>    * Changing the method of selecting state Supreme Court justices and the state attorney general.
<P>    After the defeat of Supreme Court Justice Penny White last August in a yes-no retention vote, state Democratic Chairman Will Cheek called for a return to the pre-1995 system of chosing justices by partisan nomination and popular election.
<P>    While that has been a Democratic idea, Republicans have taken the lead in pushing for popular election of the attorney general, who is now selected by the Supreme Court.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
