	<title>Two area schools are among 12 trade schools in Tennessee that face losing their eligibility to participate in the Federal Family Education Loan Program and the Direct Loan Program.</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 12, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Two area schools are among 12 trade schools in Tennessee that face losing their eligibility to participate in the Federal Family Education Loan Program and the Direct Loan Program.</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Brian CourtneyNews-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">T</FONT>wo area schools are among 12 trade schools in Tennessee that face losing their eligibility to participate in the Federal Family Education Loan Program and the Direct ,Loan Program
<P> the nation&#39;s principal federal student loan programs.
<P>    Tennessee School of Beauty programs in Knoxville and Oak Ridge and 327 other schools nationwide have had default rates of 25 percent or more for three consecutive years -- fiscal 1992, 1993 and 1994. This means that in each of these three years, 25 percent or more of the loan recipients at the school defaulted in the first or second year of repayment.
<P>    The schools can appeal this action.
<P>    Adam Brown, president of the Knoxville and Oak Ridge schools, said the  appeal process has already begun and that he feels certain neither school will be eliminated from the program.
<P>    &#39;&#39;If you asked me, I&#39;d bet any amount of money we will not be eliminated from this program,&#39;&#39; he said. 
<P>    Brown said figures for the Knoxville school were miscalculated and do not reflect five students who have repaid their loans. At the Oak Ridge school, he said they were penalized because they only had 25 borrowers instead of 30.
<P>    Brown stressed that the schools&#39; default rates have no reflection on their educational curriculum. 
<P>   &#39;&#39;We still have a 100 percent passing rate on the state board exam and a 100 percent placement rate,&#39;&#39; he said.   
<P>    Current student loans will not be jeopardized by or during the appeal process, Brown said.
<P>
