<head>
	<title>River&#39;s advance threatens Shiloh</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 12, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>River&#39;s advance threatens Shiloh</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Erosion, funding hurt battlefield</FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">P</FONT>ITTSBURG LANDING, Tenn. -- Nearly 135 years after hosting a historic Civil War battle, the nation&#39;s second-oldest major Civil War battlefield is waging a war of its own against Mother Nature.
<P>    The Shiloh Battlefield in West Tennessee is struggling to preserve its shoreline from the encroaching erosion of the Tennessee River. 
<P>    A popular access road has already been closed, and a 30-foot-high earthen causeway is near collapse.
<P>    And now the site of a 1,500-year-old Indian village is in jeopardy as the river has already sliced into the largest of seven prehistoric mounds.
<P>    &#39;&#39;It&#39;s a terrible situation,&#39;&#39; superintendent Woody Harrell says. &#39;&#39;The full force of the river is hitting right at the Indian mounds. It&#39;s just not safe to send visitors down there anymore.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Nearly 24,000 soldiers from both the North and the South were either wounded, killed or missing in action after the Battle of Shiloh on April 7, 1862. The Union army was victorious.
<P>    The two-day battle turned out to be a hint that the Civil War would last longer than initially thought.
<P>    &#39;&#39;It was a highly dramatic chapter in American history,&#39;&#39; says author and historian Shelby Foote of Memphis, known for his Civil War commentaries. &#39;&#39;There were more American casualties in two days at Shiloh than in all of America&#39;s previous wars put together -- the Revolutionary War, the War of 1812 and the Mexican War.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Among major Civil War sites, only Chickamauga near Chattanooga has held federal designation long than the 3,960-acre Shiloh site. Chickamauga was created in 1890 and Shiloh in 1894.
<P>    Local preservationists say the Tennessee Valley Authority&#39;s Kentucky Dam project in the 1930s raised the level of the Tennessee River, which may have started the erosion process.
<P>    &#39;&#39;We&#39;re not against the dams or want to stop traffic on the river,&#39;&#39; says Jerry Lessenberry of Humboldt, whose Sons of Confederate Veterans group raises money to help maintain the park.
<P>    &#39;&#39;But this park brings 750,000 people in a year into this area. The tourist value, the historic value outweighs all the other.
<P>    &#39;&#39;God made the land, soldiers fought on it, the federal government accepted it, and now it looks like Kentucky is going to get it.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Park officials lobbied various federal agencies for the funds to fix the problem, and two years ago Shiloh was placed on the priority list for $4.5 million in funds to cure the park&#39;s ills.
<P>    But federal budget cutbacks pushed the funding date back from 1998 to 1999. Now there is only a glimmer of hope that any money will come by the turn of the century.  Unless something unexpected happens, Harrell says they can only allow the causeway to wash away.
<P>    TVA officials aren&#39;t sure if any money will be available to help Shiloh. They&#39;re hoping other federal agencies will step in.
<P>    Harrell&#39;s not counting on it.
<P>    &#39;&#39;We&#39;ve had folks who are good about coming down and talking, but we haven&#39;t seen a pot of money,&#39;&#39; he says. &#39;&#39;The later we wait, the more difficult it will be to fix the problem.&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
