<head>
	<title>Thieves posing as utility workers, police say</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 12, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Thieves posing as utility workers, police say</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Jamie Satterfield, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">W</FONT>hile Edward Hollaway tapped a spoon against his kitchen faucet and his wife, Ella, stared at the water in her washing machine, a con artist was busy stealing the couple&#39;s valuables, authorities contend.
<P>   The Hollaways, both of whom are in their 60s, are believed to be the first reported victims of a couple of professional con artists whom police fear are running their scam in the Knoxville area.
<P>   Knoxville Police Department Patrol Officer Eli Landro said the two con artists, who posed as workers with the Knoxville Utilities Board, are targeting people who are in their mid-50s or older because they consider them most vulnerable to the scam.
<P>   &#39;&#39;They&#39;re professionals,&#39;&#39; Landro said.
<P>   The Hollaways were at their Chicamauga Avenue home Thursday afternoon when a Hispanic man and woman knocked on the door and identified themselves as KUB workers, Landro wrote in a police report.
<P>   The pair told the Hollaways &#39;&#39;there was gas in the water and they had to check it,&#39;&#39; the report stated. The man took Edward Hollaway to the kitchen and asked him to turn on the faucet.
<P>   According to Landro&#39;s report, the man told Edward Hollaway to &#39;&#39;stand by it and hit the faucet with a spoon to tell if there was gas in the water, that it would make an unusual sound,&#39;&#39; according to the report.
<P>   The woman then took Ella Hollaway downstairs and asked her to turn on the couple&#39;s washing machine. Ella Hollaway was told to watch the water as it filled the machine to see if it showed signs of discoloration, Landro wrote.
<P>   The woman stayed with Ella Hollaway while the man ransacked the couple&#39;s house, selectively searching for loot to steal, according to Landro. Landro said the con artists stole food stamps, cash and jewelry.
<P>   When the man was finished choosing items to steal, he called out to the woman to join him and told the Hollaways to &#39;&#39;leave the water running for an additional five minutes while they go test the neighbor&#39;s house,&#39;&#39; Landro wrote in his report.
<P>   The con artists made their getaway in a white car believed to be a mid-80s model, the report stated. Several minutes passed before the Hollaways realized they had been duped by the couple, according to the report.
<P>   The Hollaways gave Landro a partial description of the Hispanic couple. The man had black hair, was about 5 feet, 8 inches tall and weighed between 150 and 155 pounds. He was believed to be between 28 and 30 years old. The woman also had black hair, weighed 115 pounds and was between 5 feet, 2 inches and 5 feet, 3 inches tall. She was thought to be in her mid 20s.
<P> 
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

