<head>
	<title>Knox Briefs</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 12, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Knox Briefs</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><h3>Claiborne County woman dies in early morning trailer fire</h3>
<P>
<P>
<P>   A Claiborne County woman died in her home Saturday in an early morning fire, authorities with the Claiborne County Sheriff&#39;s Department said.
<P>   Donna Irene Ellis, a 55-year-old resident of the Arthur community located just off Highway 63 near Harrogate, was killed in the blaze that occurred about 3:10 a.m., said Lt. Phillip Johnson. Ellis&#39; daughter and her daughter&#39;s boyfriend escaped unharmed, he said.
<P>   Johnson said an autopsy revealed Ellis died from smoke inhalation. The cause of the trailer fire is still under investigation.
<P>   The North Claiborne County Volunteer Fire Department and the Claiborne County Emergency Medical Service responded to the scene. 
<P>
<P><h3>Beer truck stolen outside store, later found in complex parking lot</h3>
<P>
<P>
<P>   A beer truck stolen from a downtown convenience store early Saturday was found minutes later crashed in the parking lot of an apartment complex known for its high crime rate, according to a police report.
<P>   A truck and trailer full of Eagle Distributing Company beer products was stolen at 7:15 a.m. from the parking lot at the Weigel&#39;s, 411 E. Summitt Hill Dr., after the driver left the vehicle unlocked with the keys in the ignition, a Knoxville Police Department report stated.
<P>   Officers found the truck and trailer 15 minutes later in the parking lot of Townview Terrace Apartments, 300 Mulvaney St., which is across the street from the Weigel&#39;s store.
<P>   &#39;&#39;The vehicle was ran partially over the curb and down a hill,&#39;&#39; the report stated. The roads and parking lot were covered with snow and ice at the time.
<P>   Stolen from the truck were three 12-packs of Busch beer, four 12-packs of Bud Light, 24 quart bottles of Natural Light and 24 quart bottles  of Natural Ice. Townview has been termed by police as a crime trouble spot.
<P>
<P><h3>Meigs, Roane authorities search for suspects in string of burglaries</h3>
<P>
<P>
<P>   Police were searching the woods near the Meigs and Roane county line Saturday night for a pair of armed men believed to be responsible for a rash of burglaries in five counties, authorities said.
<P>   Doug Cook with the Roane County Sheriff&#39;s Department said the men allegedly made off with a load of guns from a Roane County residence shortly before 3 p.m. The pair fled into the woods after a woman, believed to be driving their getaway car, was stopped by authorities as she drove up and down the road in front of the house. The car the woman was driving matched the description of one used in previous burglaries, Cook said.
<P>   Cook said the suspects may be responsible for a string of burglaries in Anderson, Claiborne, Grainger, Roane and Morgan counties.
<P>   A Tennessee Highway Patrol helicopter was aiding authorities in Roane and Meigs counties with the search, Cook said. 
<P>   
<P>
<P><h3>Suspect in armed robbery sought by Oak Ridge police</h3>
<P>
<P>
<P>   A masked gunman who robbed an Oak Ride check cashing business Saturday walked away with more than $3,000 in cash, authorities said.
<P>   According to Oak Ridge Police Department Lt. Don Johnson, a white male entered Checkmate Inc., 1590 Oak Ridge Turnpike, brandished a blue-steel handgun and then produced a note that read: &#39;&#39;Give me all your money. Lay down on the floor, and no one will get hurt.&#39;&#39;
<P>   After taking the cash, the suspect fled. The clerk did not see the gunman&#39;s getaway car, Johnson said.
<P>
<P><h3>Former NAACP official Hooks to speak at King tribute Monday</h3>
<P>
<P>
<P>   Benjamin Hooks, retired executive director of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, will be the keynote speaker at a tribute to Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. from 11 a.m. to 1 p.m. Monday, Jan. 20 at Knoxville&#39;s Greater Warner African Methodist Episcopal Zion Church.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
