<head>
	<title>State urges TVA to share expertise with Israel and Jordan</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper Business News">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif" alt="Knoxville News-Sentinel Online -- Business News" align=bottom border=0 width=595 height=176></a><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td align=left valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 12, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>State urges TVA to share expertise with Israel and Jordan</B></font><basefont size=6><!--SUBHEAD--></basefont></FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Robert Danieland Jessica Steinberg<BR>Bloomberg Business News</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">T</FONT>EL AVIV, Israel -- Tennessee will try to bring together officials from TVA, Jordan and Israel to discuss possible water and power projects in the Jordan Valley, a top state economic official said.
<P>    The official, William A. Dunavant Jr., commissioner of the Tennessee Department of Economic and Community Development, spoke with Bloomberg during a fact-finding visit to Israel by a delegation led by Gov. Don Sundquist.
<P>    Officials and executives from the state, hosted by the Israel-America Chamber of Commerce and the Israel Export Institute, are looking for opportunities to export products and to encourage Israeli businesses to invest in Tennessee.
<P>    The U.S. Embassy has suggested that TVA might find opportunities to bring its expertise to bear on the Jordan Valley area, Dunavant said.
<P>   (TVA, since the 1940s, has been interested in assisting the governments of Jordan and Israel in completing a project to link Jordan&#39;s Dead Sea with the Red Sea at Aqaba. TVA has contracted with a Maryland firm, Edgar C. Harrell Associates, to consider Rift Valley project feasibility and to work with the Builders for Peace program in developing an industrial park on the West Bank or in Gaza.)
<P>    One of the Middle East&#39;s thorniest problems is scarce water resources and the need for technological solutions to water distribution.
<P>    Last October, Dunavant said, TVA officials conducted a weeklong series of meetings with Chinese officials, touching on water-resource management.
<P>    Israel is attracting attention from a number of U.S. states that want to explore investment in Israel and the Middle East.
<P>    Eight U.S. states -- California, Florida, Georgia, Maryland, Massachusetts, New Jersey, North Carolina and Ohio have established representative offices here. The offices offer advice to companies in their home states and make connections to Israel agencies and companies.
<P>    Tennessee has no current plans to open a permanent office, said Andrew J. Pelych, director of the Export Office within the state economic development agency.
<P>    The state does have a committee dedicated to fostering economic and cultural ties between Tennessee and Israel. The panel was formed last February by the governor and Israel&#39;s consul general for the Southeast, Aryeh Mekel.
<P>    The state&#39;s exports to Israel totaled $15.2 million for the first six months of 1996, up 9 percent from the year-earlier period, U.S. Commerce Department figures show. Of the nearly $30 million of exports from the state to Israel in 1995, $13 million were paper products.
<P>    Two major Tennessee companies represented on the tour are Federal Express Corp. of Memphis, the giant express package delivery company, and Service Merchandise Co., a catalog retailer in Brentwood. FedEx works in Israel through a local partner, Flying Cargo of B&#39;nei Brak.
<P>    Smaller businesses also sent officials. One of the executives on the tour was Sidney Blalock, president of road developer Charles Blalock & Sons Inc. of Sevierville. During this visit, he&#39;s looking at Israel&#39;s developing road infrastructure, particularly Road 6, the Cross-Israel Highway connecting the Galilee in the north with the Negev desert in the south.
<P>    &#39;&#39;We have some of the same problems that Israel faces with this highway,&#39;&#39; he said. &#39;&#39;There are the environmental issues, and then there are those archeological artifacts. You keep on finding pottery shards, and in Tennessee we dig up Indian arrowheads.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Shannon Greene, vice president of ABG Caulking & Waterproofing of Nashville, is interested in the tunnel infrastructure Tel Aviv will need if it goes through with plans to build a subway.
<P>    The 28-year-old company, with annual sales around $15 million and 225 employees, says that his company has done business in the Caribbean, but with plenty of building in the southern states, ABG hasn&#39;t had to look far outside.
<P>    &#39;&#39;We want to find out if it&#39;s the right time&#39;&#39; for an Israel investment, he said. At the same time, &#39;&#39;maybe you have something in technology and sealants, a better way of doing it,&#39;&#39; that ABG could take back home.
<P>    Hanan Achsaf, president of the Israel-America Chamber of Commerce and president of Motorola Israel, said the U.S. is Israel&#39;s largest export market, even with the shekel strong against the U.S. dollar. A strong shekel makes Israeli exporters&#39; products more expensive for overseas buyers.
<P>    Israel exports to the U.S. in 1996 were about $6 billion, against $5.7 billion in 1995.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
