<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>Infomercials: Success story for strong sales</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper Business News">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif" alt="Knoxville News-Sentinel Online -- Business News" align=bottom border=0 width=595 height=176></a><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td align=left valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 12, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Infomercials: Success story for strong sales</B></font><basefont size=6><!--SUBHEAD--></basefont></FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Linda Castrone, Scripps Howard News Service</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">I</FONT>f you work a normal day shift, keep yourself busy on the weekends and sleep soundly, you may not be familiar with infomercials.
<P>    They&#39;re the &#39;&#39;paid programs&#39;&#39; that pepper the airwaves in the off-hours, purporting to teach viewers while -- coincidentally -- selling them everything from facial creams to miracle ab flatteners.
<P>    Last year they generated an estimated $1.8 billion in sales and did especially well with home fitness products. 
<P>    Between 1990 and 1993, NordicTrack sold $225 million worth of Pro Ski machines with infomercials, and Soloflex sold $150 million worth of home gyms. Last year&#39;s hits were riders/gliders; this year&#39;s are ab machines.
<P>    Why do the ads disguised as TV shows work so well? Marc Rabinoff, professor of Human Performance, Sport and Leisure Studies at Metropolitan State College of Denver gives his best guess: &#39;&#39;People are looking for a magic bullet, and these products offer to deliver it.&#39;&#39;
<P>    He and the seniors in his Comparative Fitness Programs class spent the fall studying fitness infomercials. They found misinformation disguised as fact to be the mainstay of infomercials. For example:
<P>    &#39;&#39;Create rock-hard abdominals in just three minutes a day, three days a week with Denise Austin&#39;s Ab Coach.&#39;&#39; &#39;&#39;After one session on the Pilates Performer you can feel 10 pounds lighter and an inch taller.&#39;&#39; &#39;&#39;Perfect for every age and every lifestyle.&#39;&#39; &#39;&#39;The last piece of fitness equipment you&#39;ll ever need.&#39;&#39; &#39;&#39;You&#39;ll get maximum results with minimal effort.&#39;&#39; &#39;&#39;It&#39;s a total body workout.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Those claims are gross distortions, if not downright lies, Rabinoff and his students assert. 
<P>    In addition to raising people&#39;s hopes, the ads raid their pocketbooks. The &#39;&#39;Jane Fonda &#39;Walk to the Music&#39; Treadmill&#39;&#39; that sold for $409.40 on TV, for example, was available in national discount stores for only $299. Most items hawked on infomercials can be found at discounted prices in local discount and sporting goods stores.
<P>    High TV prices are made more palatable with easy payment plans, usually $50 a month for up to 10 months. And virtually all infomercials offer a money-back guarantee, although following the details can be tricky.
<P>    Only a few dissatisfied consumers take the sponsors up on their money-back guarantees, writes Consumer Reports, while many more blame themselves -- not the product -- if they don&#39;t get the promised results.
<P>    Why do manufacturers use infomercials?
<P>    &#39;&#39;It gives us a half hour to educate people instead of a quick 60 seconds,&#39;&#39; said Mike Smith, public relations manager of Nordic Track in Chaska, Minn. In its infomercials, Nordic Track is careful to stress that diet and aerobics are key ingredients in achieving fitness, Smith added.
<P>    Recently, the Federal Trade Commission filed a fraudulent-advertising complaint against Nordic Track. The company settled, but it &#39;&#39;took no blame,&#39;&#39; Smith said. &#39;&#39;We run everything by the legal department first.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Others argue that governmental restrictions on infomercials is censorship; America is a free country, they point out, and consumers who buy products advertised in infomercials do it of their own free will.
<P>    Overall fitness sales are down and sales of home fitness equipment are flat, but infomercial sales continue to grow. They now account for about 6 percent of all sales, up from 5 percent in 1994, according to the Fitness Products Council.
<P>    They also are relatively cheap to produce, late night and early morning airtime is cheap and return is lucrative. 
<P>    Nine out of 10 TV stations now air infomercials because the money is too good to pass up, reports Broadcasting and Cable magazine. It&#39;s a $400 million business for broadcasters and cable networks, and can mean the difference between profit and loss.
<P>    And although two federal agencies are assigned to police infomercials -- the Federal Trade Commission and the Federal Communications Commission -- they don&#39;t monitor the programs and only enforce the rules when consumers complain.
<P>    Rabinoff and his students&#39; findings about infomercials:
<P>     Although many promise to deliver &#39;&#39;total fitness,&#39;&#39; none can. &#39;&#39;We define &#39;total fitness&#39; as proper nutrition, exercise, flexibility, strength and coordination, and you can&#39;t get that from any one machine,&#39;&#39; says Rabinoff.
<P> 
<P>    Most contain bizarre statements &#39;&#39;that knock professionals out of their seats.&#39;&#39; In her Ab Coach infomercial, for example, Denise Austin comments that &#39;&#39;it takes four years to sculpt a statue, but it&#39;s easier to sculpt your abs.&#39;&#39; Tell that to bodybuilders who have spent years creating the perfect set of washboard abs.
<P>     The inherent risks aren&#39;t mentioned. People with bad backs shouldn&#39;t use rider/gliders, for example, and people with bad hearts should be cautious about anything that raises their heart rates.
<P> 
<P>    The products are expensive. At the time, it may sound like a steal to pay $400 for a home gym or $100 for an ab machine. But a stroll through local stores can drive home the point that much more can be had for much less.
<P>
<P>Linda Castrone is a staff writer at The Rocky Mountain News in Denver.
<P><B></B>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
