<html>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>Public ET companies shine</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper Business News">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif" alt="Knoxville News-Sentinel Online -- Business News" align=bottom border=0 width=595 height=176></a><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td align=left valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 12, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Public ET companies shine</B></font><basefont size=6><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Value of stocks increases in 1996</FONT></basefont></FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Amy Geisel, News-Sentinel business editor</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">A</FONT> majority of East Tennessee&#39;s publicly owned companies saw their stock increase in value over 1996, and a drop in the stock price of one historically good performer was blamed on the vagaries of Wall Street.
<P>   Goody&#39;s Family Clothing Inc. placed first on the scorecard, with its stock more than doubling in value over the year. Regal Cinemas Inc., the movie theater chain, continued to please investors with a 57 percent increase, while Proffitt&#39;s Inc.&#39;s stock rose 42 percent as the department store chain completed two major acquisitions and announced a third.
<P>   A marked anomaly was Clayton Homes Inc., which posted a nearly 70 percent increase in value in 1995. The company&#39;s stock price fell 22 percent over 1996.
<P>   Clayton Homes&#39; third-quarter earnings fell a penny below expectations, giving rise to fears among some traders that the cyclical manufacturing industry may begin experiencing a downturn.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We have seen a lot of these (manufactured housing) companies drop between 25 to 40 percent in value over the last quarter since Wall Street has become concerned over the late stage of the manufactured housing cycle,&#39;&#39; said Tom Underwood, an analyst with Morgan Keegan & Co.
<P>   But Underwood just recently upgraded Clayton from a hold to a buy. And Barron&#39;s magazine featured Clayton Homes in a favorable light in both a story and The Trader column in last Monday&#39;s issue. One money manager was quoted as describing the company as a &#39;&#39;compelling buy.&#39;&#39;
<P>   East Tennessee&#39;s two publicly owned apparel chains, meanwhile, shine among their industry group.
<P>   Goody&#39;s Family Clothing, expecting 1996 sales to top $800 million, completed a turnaround that began with Chairman Robert Goodfriend lured President Harry Call and other top executives back to the chain in 1995 after a year of legal battles and internal turmoil.
<P>   The management team refocused the merchandising strategy to include a broad selection of women&#39;s and junior clothing, and also vamped up the private label program.
<P>   Goody&#39;s sales for all-important Christmas season, November and December, were up 16 percent on a comparable store basis.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We still have a strong buy on it,&#39;&#39; said Eliot Laurence, an analyst with J.C. Bradford & Co, of Goody&#39;s stock. &#39;&#39;Our feeling is this: The operating margins are still way below peak levels and they have a lot of wind in their sails because of a strong December. We think the company could continue to surprise people in the sales and earnings and if they do that the valuation will continue to expand.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Proffitt&#39;s, meanwhile, went on a 
<P>buying spree, completing its purchase of Younkers, now a division with 48 stores, and Parisian, with its 38 upscale stores, and announcing the acquisition of G.R. Herberger&#39;s with 40 stores in the Midwest. After making some adjustments -- including selling seven underperforming stores in Virginia to Dillard&#39;s -- Proffitt&#39;s Inc. in 1997 will operate 174 stores with revenues of more than $2.2 billion.
<P>   Its Christmas sales weren&#39;t spectacular, but they were solid -- up 3 percent in November and December on a comparable store basis.
<P>   Many are impressed by Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Brad Martin&#39;s aggressive approach in the consolidating industry.
<P>   &#39;&#39;He&#39;s executing his game plan of growth with careful attention to the strategic implications of market share dominance and he&#39;s done an admirable job,&#39;&#39; said Craig Weichmann of Morgan Keegan.
<P>   Other results for the year include:
<P>    Regal Cinemas, headquartered modestly in Halls, is now the sixth largest North American movie theater chain. Since its initial public offering in 1993, Regal Cinemas has grown at least 30 percent annually.
<P>   &#39;&#39;They&#39;ve been a spectacular performer and continue to outpace everyone in the industry,&#39;&#39; said Gary Dennis, who follows the company for J.C. Bradford.
<P>   Grumblings began in 1995 that the stock may be overpriced, and such growth could not be sustained. The naysayers were proved wrong, Dennis said.
<P>   &#39;&#39;It&#39;s our contention that they are so much better managers, have so much better growth and are so much more profitable, that the premium has held in place and we don&#39;t see any reason for that not to continue,&#39;&#39; he added.
<P>    Computational Systems Inc. completed its first full year as a public company, and saw its stock increase by nearly 29 percent. The company earned $2.6 million, or 52 cents per share, on revenues of $33.1 million for the first nine months of 1996. CSI designs and builds maintenance instruments to detect problems that could lead to a breakdown in industrial machinery.
<P>   The brokerage house Wheat First Butcher Singer initiated coverage of CSI with a buy recommendation last week.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We think they have a leading position in a growing market,&#39;&#39; said Walt Glazer of Wheat First. &#39;&#39;They are a beneficiary of downsizing and outsourcing and they have a strong management team, the vision to see where the industry is headed and the discipline and focus to succeed.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Glazer is predicting that earnings will be up 30 percent in 1997, earnings should grow 20 to 25 percent for the next several years.
<P>    Plasti-Line Inc. posted improved sales and earnings for the first nine months of this year, and as a result its stock climbed more than 37 percent.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We are optimistic when we look at some of the new customers we&#39;ve added and the opportunities in the market we see out there for 1997,&#39;&#39; said Mark Deuschle, chief financial officer.
<P>    Shop At Home Inc., the Knoxville-based home shopping network, saw its stock rise about 10 percent in value on improved sales and earnings. The network, broadcast to 30 million homes, has outgrown its current facilities and is shopping for a new headquarters.
<P>   Last week, the company reported second-quarter revenues rose 70 percent to $16.1 million over the previous quarter. Net income is expected to improve over last year&#39;s loss, officials said.
<P>   Morgan Keegan&#39;s Weichmann said the company is at an &#39;&#39;an early stage of development and they are trying to put together the critical mass they need. . . . It&#39;s an interesting opportunity to monitor, but obviously it&#39;s at the very early stages.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Kingsport-based Eastman Chemical&#39;s stock price dropped as the prices for PET plastic -- the material used for soft drink bottles and the like -- became very competitive during the year. The price drop occurred just as the company was coming online with additional capacity, said James Wilbur, of Smith Barney&#39;s New York office.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We would expect that collapse in prices is pretty much behind them although they will have to rebuild that business,&#39;&#39; Wilbur said.
<P>    Landair Services Inc., headquartered in Greeneville, Tenn. although the bulk of its operations are in Columbus, Ohio, decreased in value as as profits and sales fell below 1995 levels.
<P>   The trucking company, which specializes in air cargo, has said it&#39;s been impacted by higher fuel costs and insurance and claim expenses.
<P>    United Petroleum was the big loser on the scorecard, as some shareholders unloaded the stock causing the price to plunge in early November. The company said investors began abruptly converting debentures -- general debt obligations -- into common stock and began selling short. In December, the company named four new directors and announced that several measures would be studied in an effort to increase the stock&#39;s value.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
