<head>
	<title>NCBC, other bank stocks return high yields to investors</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper Business News">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif" alt="Knoxville News-Sentinel Online -- Business News" align=bottom border=0 width=595 height=176></a><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td align=left valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 12, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>NCBC, other bank stocks return high yields to investors</B></font><basefont size=6><!--SUBHEAD--></basefont></FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Lois Reagan Thomas, News-Sentinel executive business editor</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">N</FONT>ational Commerce Bancorporation (NCBC), the Memphis-based banking company that pioneered supermarket banking, led publicly traded Tennessee-based banks in stock performance in 1996, returning a 45.4 percent gain to its shareholders.
<P>   The return was well above that of the three other Tennessee-based banking companies and also above the average for the industry group. Dow Jones overall financial group returns averaged 32.37 percent, while regional banks averaged 33.33 percent and Southern banks in particular 35.27 percent.
<P>   While the returns were less for the three other Tennessee-based banking companies, Tennessee banks in general did very well in 1996, averaging returns around 30 percent, as did bank stocks in general, noted John B. Moore Jr., first vice president of Morgan Keegan & Co. in Memphis.
<P>    &#39;&#39;If anybody&#39;s wealth is up 30 percent in a year, they&#39;re doing very well,&#39;&#39; said Moore. &#39;&#39;It&#39;s been a very good year for banks, especially when you consider they were also up a lot in 1995, a little in 1994, a lot in 1993 and a lot in 1992.&#39;&#39;
<P>   NCBC in 1996 launched First Market Bank, a new concept for locating in-store banks in small to medium-sized towns without other in-store banks. The first branches are to open in six north Georgia communities. The concept comes under NCBC&#39;s Knoxville bank, NBC Bank FSB.
<P>   NCBC, with $3.9 billion in assets, has consistently performed well, capitalizing on its low-cost way of expanding banking services, Moore noted.
<P>   Union Planters Corp. became the largest Tennessee-based bank in 1996 with $15 billion in assets after the acquisition of the $3.1 billion-asset Leader Financial in Memphis. The merger is expected to further boost the Memphis-based commmunity banking company&#39;s earnings, according to Morgan Keegan&#39;s analysis.
<P>   First Tennessee National Corp., with $12.8 billion in assets, saw its earnings slow a bit in 1996, but they should pick back up in 1997, said Moore. The Memphis-based company is labeled a &#39;&#39;special products&#39;&#39; company, with more than half its business in something other than traditional banking. Morgan Keegan recently raised its rating of the bank&#39;s stock from &#39;&#39;hold&#39;&#39; to &#39;&#39;accumulate.&#39;&#39;
<P>   First American Corp., with $10 billion in assets, has made a big turnaround over the past several years, and the fundamentals continue to be solid, according to analysts. 
<P>   As for 1997?
<P>   &#39;&#39;The issue in 1997 for a lot of these banks is credit quality,&#39;&#39; said Moore. &#39;&#39;We haven&#39;t had credit problems in many years, but consumer loan past-dues are going up and delinquencies are going up. This is one of the things most banks are concerned about.&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P>   
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
