<head>
	<title>Electronics firms must please public</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper Business News">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif" alt="Knoxville News-Sentinel Online -- Business News" align=bottom border=0 width=595 height=176></a><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td align=left valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 12, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Electronics firms must please public</B></font><basefont size=6><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Speaker says consumer demand is the top priority</FONT></basefont></FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Pam Park, News-Sentinel business writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">L</FONT>AS VEGAS -- Consumer electronics makers&#39; most compelling need is to make the print on their machines big enough to read and the buttons big enough to push, Michael Bloomberg of Bloomberg Financial Services said in a keynote address to the Winter Consumer Electronics Show in Las Vegas, which ends today.
<P>Bloomberg, who was the first keynote speaker from outside the industry to address CES in its 30-year history, wasn&#39;t making a joke. He was making a point.
<P>&#39;&#39;The customer doesn&#39;t care what we have to sell,&#39;&#39; Bloomberg said. &#39;&#39;They only care that we have what they want.&#39;&#39;
<P>There&#39;s danger in being overconfident, he said.
<P>&#39;&#39;You can get carried away with your own brilliance,&#39;&#39; he said.
<P>Customer preferences are also unpredictable, he said.
<P>For example, who would expect that 1.5 million citizen-band radios were sold last year in the United States? Who would guess that bottled water would be the hottest fad on the ski slopes?
<P>&#39;&#39;We live in a world where 250 million people watch &#39;&#39;Bay Watch,&#39; &#39;&#39; he said.
<P>What they are looking for now is the ability to watch &#39;&#39;Bay Watch&#39;&#39; any time they want .
<P>Video-on-demand is where the industry is headed, Bloomberg said. With video-on-demand, the consumer has the ability to chose a program or movie from an extensive list of titles and watch it on their own schedule.
<P>Bloomberg also predicted newspapers have a future, even if it&#39;s in a different format.
<P>Newspaper readers probably couldn&#39;t tell you what they like about the newspaper, Bloomberg said, but he contends it&#39;s the fact that newspapers are random access devices that makes them appealing to readers.
<P>If consumers want to read the sports page, they don&#39;t have to tune in at a certain hour and wait through the news, features and weather to get it. They can fold up the newspaper and carry it around. They can read it when they want to.
<P>They get news &#39;&#39;peripherally&#39;&#39; from a newspaper as well. As they are thumbing through to the sports page, they may notice headlines in other sections that are important to them .
<P>Electronic services that are being designed to give consumers only the news they want, by categories, will not be satisfactory, Bloomberg said.
<P>How can you know in advance what news will be important to you, he asked?
<P>Maybe the consumer said he or she did not want war stories because they&#39;re depressing.
<P>&#39;&#39;If World War III breaks out, I&#39;m in big trouble because I&#39;m not going to know about it,&#39;&#39; he said.
<P>On the flip side, if consumers choose to follow the Susan Smith story, they&#39;ll get lots of stories about parents killing children.
<P>Newspapers have a future, but they may look different a few years from now, Bloomberg said.
<P>He foresees they may be made of some sort of cloth or a flexible screen that can be loaded with content from different media organizations and updated constantly.
<P>&#39;&#39;What you are going to as (electronics) manufacturers is increase the internal complexity of your products . . . so that we (who) look at the exterior will see something simpler,&#39;&#39; he said.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

	<P><center><font size=2>Return to </font><a href="/"><font size=2>Main</font></a><font size=2>. Copyright &#169; 1997 The Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size=2>webmaster</font></a><font size=2>.</font></center></p>
