<head>
	<title>Labonte tops All-Pro team</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 12, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470><BASEFONT SIZE="6">
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Labonte tops All-Pro team</B></FONT><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Jarrett blasts no-shows</FONT></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Bill Luther, News-Sentinel sportswriter</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">C</FONT>HARLOTTE, N.C. -- Winston Cup champion Terry Labonte and four teammates are first-team members of the 1996 Copenhagen/Skoal All Pro team.
<P>    The awards were announced late Friday night at the annual banquet.
<P>    Dale Earnhardt, who finished fourth in the Cup points race, was selected for the runner-up position and Dale Jarrett, who was third in points, placed third.
<P>    Crew chief Gary DeHart, jack man Walt Smith, tire specialist Mike Bumgarner and gear/transmission specialist and general mechanic Dan Ford were other first-team honorees on the championship Kellogg team.
<P>    &#39;&#39;This is a night for the mechanics,&#39;&#39; said Labonte, who won two races, posted an average finish of eighth and rallied down the stretch en route to overtaking teammate Jeff Gordon. &#39;&#39;The mechanics make my job easy, and I&#39;m fortunate to be a part of this team.&#39;&#39;
<P>    No-shows were plentiful and that irritated Jarrett, who drives for Robert Yates.
<P>    &#39;&#39;I challenge the teams that don&#39;t have their members show up,&#39;&#39; Jarrett said after accepting his award. &#39;&#39;They should be here.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Each of the three finalists on the Yates team accepted his awards, including 74-year-old mechanist James Lewter. It was the 10th consecutive year Lewter been honored.
<P>
<P>   <B>POSTHUMOUS HONOREES:</B> Crew chief Harry Hyde, driver/chassis builder Banjo Matthews and driver/team owner Elmo Langley, who dedicated their lives to NASCAR, were honored with the Mike Rich Award of Excellence.
<P>   The trio died during the 1996 season. Rich, a member of Harry Melling team, was killed in a pit road accident at Atlanta  Motor Speedway in 1990.
<P>
<P>    <B>STILL SLEDDING:</B> Cup driver Geoff Bodine, who became involved with the U.S. Bobsled team in the 1992 Olympics, is back in the business. His sled returns to World Cup competition in Konigssee, Germany, on Tuesday.
<P>
<P>    <B>TRUCKER:</B> Youngster Kelly Denton, who resides in Bristol, Va., has been selected the replacement for Jimmy Hensley on the SuperTruck series. Richard Petty hired Hensley as his driver for 1997. The truck series opens Jan. 19 at Orlando, Fla.
<P>
<P>    <B>SHAPING UP:</B> Team owner Darrell Waltrip has filled the key positions for the SuperTruck series.
<P>    Dave McCarty is the crew chief, Scott Grant the fabricator and Rick Elberts engine tuner. Driver Rick Bickle was<B> </B>selected two months ago.
<P>
<P>    <B>HIGH RISE:</B> Martinsville Speedway will celebrate its 50th anniversary by adding 5,000 seats between turns three and four. The new section is expected to be completed in time to sell tickets for the April race.
<P>    &#39;&#39;They will be great seats,&#39;&#39; speedway president Clay Campbell. &#39;&#39;Fans will be right on top of the action and they can watch the entire race without turning their heads.&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
