<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>Fishermen can pick brain of experts during UT visit</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 12, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470><BASEFONT SIZE="6">
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Fishermen can pick brain of experts during UT visit</B></FONT><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Bob Hodge, News-Sentinel outdoors editor</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">B</FONT>ack in 1974, Gary White thought it would be a good idea to get together some professional bass fishermen, put them in a classroom setting, and let other fishermen pick their brains.
<P>     White was right. It was a good idea.
<P>     In 23 years, the Fishing Techniques Institute has visited more than 160 college campuses, and has been attended by more than 150,000 fishermen. Three years ago White was bought out by the Bass Anglers Sportsman&#39;s Society and he now serves as the program&#39;s director.
<P>     &#39;&#39;I was working as the financial aide director at Rose State College in Midwest City, Okla., when we got it started,&#39;&#39; White said. &#39;&#39;Jimmy Houston was an insurance salesmen then and Ken Cook was a biologist for the state of Oklahoma.
<P>     &#39;&#39;Now we&#39;ve been to schools from coast to coast in the United States and Canada. We&#39;ve been to the University of Texas 23 times.&#39;&#39;
<P>     For the third time, the B.A.S.S. Fishing Techniques comes to the University of Tennessee on Feb. 1-2 as part of UT&#39;s Division of Continuing Studies and Distance Education. The program will feature 12 one-hour sessions with six professional bass fishermen.
<P>     The two-day course costs $89.00. Spouses and children 16 and under can attend for half-price with a paying adult. Registration can be made by phone at (423) 974-0280 or by mail to: UT Conferences, P.O. Box 2648, Knoxville, TN 37901. 
<P>     Each session runs 8 a.m.-5 p.m. each day with breaks for lunch.
<P>     &#39;&#39;This is not just a seminar-type situation,&#39;&#39; White said. &#39;&#39;The way this thing is geared to get the participants in a classroom environment with the best bass fishermen in the world and let them learn what they know.&#39;&#39;
<P>     Each of the pros will teach his individual specialty:
<P>     * Larry Nixon, two-time B.A.S.S. Angler of the Year and B.A.S.S. Masters Classic Champion, will teach plastic worm techniques.
<P>     * Jay Yelas, 195 Superstars Champion and six-time B.A.S.S. Masters Finalist, is a jerk bait expert.
<P>     * Randy Fite, seven-time B.A.S.S. Masters Finalist, is a deep water specialist.
<P>     * Tony Bean is host for the Smallmouth U.S.A. television series and is a smallmouth expert.
<P>     * Bernie Schultz, two-time Canadian champion and author of Techniques Illustrated, is a renowned spinnerbait fisherman.
<P>     * Mike Terry, two-time B.A.S.S. Masters finalist, is considered one of the best at locating bass in deep open water.
<P>     &#39;&#39;The idea is to cover every technique in existence and some you don&#39;t know about,&#39;&#39; White said. &#39;&#39;Fishermen are notorious for coming up with new techniques and terminology that applies to other techniques that are spun off in to even more techniques . . .
<P>     &#39;&#39;There is something for everybody. If you&#39;ve been before, you&#39;ll probably still learn a thing or two. For the novice, this is a treasure trove of information.&#39;&#39;
<P>     But White cautions fishermen not to go looking for consensus answers from the pros.
<P>     All the classes are unscripted and open to the teachers&#39; ideas and opinions. If two of them have exactly opposite answers to the same question, that&#39;s what White is looking for.
<P>     &#39;&#39;You get a lot of contradictions, but these guys are telling anglers what they have learned through trial and error and what works for them,&#39;&#39; White said. &#39;&#39;These guys fish 300 days a year and they&#39;ve learned a lot&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

	<P><center><font size=2>Return to </font><a href="/"><font size=2>Main</font></a><font size=2>. Copyright &#169; 1996 The Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size=2>webmaster</font></a><font size=2>.</font></center></p>
