<head>
	<title>Sports Briefs</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 12, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470><BASEFONT SIZE="6">
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Sports Briefs</B></FONT><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<h3>East Shrine defense denies West&#39;s star QBs </h3>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>    <B>Matt Finkes </B>returned an interception 17 yards for a touchdown and led a defensive effort that stymied three of the best quarterbacks in the nation as the East beat the West 17-13 Saturday in the Shrine all-star game at Stanford, Calif.
<P>    The East&#39;s win in the 72nd annual edition of the Shrine game snapped a three-year winning streak by the West, which saw its rotation of Arizona State&#39;s <B>Jake Plummer,</B> BYU&#39;s <B>Steve Sarkisian </B>and California&#39;s <B>Pat Barnes </B>held without a touchdown pass. The three had thrown for a total of 86 touchdowns this season.
<P>    Sarkisian, the nation&#39;s top-rated passer, was intercepted by Finkes of Ohio State, and Plummer threw a fourth-quarter interception that wiped out the West&#39;s last chance.
<P>    Down 14-0, the West rallied to 14-13 when California&#39;s <B>Ryan Longwell,</B> who missed a 47-yard try earlier, came back to make a 48-yarder on the first play of the fourth quarter.
<P>    With East Carolina&#39;s <B>Marcus Crandell </B>at quarterback, the East answered with a 57-yard march that culminated in a 28-yard field goal by <B>Wayne Boyer </B>of Southwest Missouri State.
<P>    The West drove to the East 5, but failed to score with under six minutes remaining, then lost another chance from the East 12 when Jackson State&#39;s <B>Sean Woodson </B>made an end-zone interception of a Plummer pass.
<P>
<P><h3>Swimming</h3>
<P>
<P>* The 13th-ranked Tennessee Lady Vols took their fourth victory of the season, beating No. 14 Northwestern 192-160 at UT Student Aquatic Center. Auburn cancelled out of the meet. UT double winners were <B>Sarah Nichols </B>(500- and 1,650-yard freestyles), <B>Fabiola Molina </B>(100- and 200-yard backstrokes) and <B>Tracy Bonner </B>(1- and 3-meter diving). <B>Tori DeSilvia </B>was second in the 200 breaststroke and 200 butterfly, and <B>Kathy Pesek </B>and <B>Dawn Burton </B>finished 2-3 in both diving events.
<P>
<P><h3>Men&#39;s college basketball</h3>
<P>
<P>* <B>King Rice,</B> an assistant coach at Illinois State who charged into the stands after a fan has been suspended with pay for one game. He will sit out today&#39;s game against Southern Illinois. He left the bench during a Thursday overtime loss to Northern Iowa after exchanging words with a fan.
<P>
<P><h3>Women&#39;s college basketball</h3>
<P>
<P>* <B>Marion Jones </B>scored 26 points and had four of North Carolina&#39;s season-high 21 steals as the No. 16 Tar Heels (12-1, 3-0 ACC) beat Georgia Tech 80-53.
<P>* <B>Raegan Scott </B>and <B>LaShena Graham </B>each scored 12 points as Colorado (8-4, 3-0 Big 12) beat No. 7 Texas Tech 63-49. The Lady Red Raiders (9-4, 1-2) shot 35 percent from the field.
<P>* <B>Pietra Gay </B>scored 31 points -- including nine in a row in the second overtime -- to lead No. 22 LSU (13-0, 3-0 SEC) to an 88-80 victory over Mississippi (10-4, 1-2). LSU&#39;s Elaine Powell hit a running bank shot at the buzzer to tie it 64-64 at the end of regulation.
<P>
<P><h3>Pro basketball</h3>
<P>
<P>* <B>Jackie Joyner-Kersee </B>has left the Richmond Rage of the American Basketball League to concentrate on her track and field career. She had been with the Rage for 17 of 29 games, scoring 16 points and grabbing 10 rebounds.
<P>* Former Tennessee star <B>Nikki McCray,</B> leading scorer in the ABL, hit 28 points for the Columbus Quest, which ran its record to 22-3 Thursday night with a 100-95 victory over the Seattle Reign.
<P>
<P><h3>Boxing</h3>
<P>
<P>* Former welterweight champion<B> Carlos Palomino,</B> 47, back in the ring for the first time since 1979, stopped <B>Ismael Diaz </B>in eight rounds of their scheduled 10-round welterweight match Friday night in Los Angeles.
<P>* Also in L.A., heavyweight <B>Gerrie Coetzee,</B> 41, a former WBC champion from South Africa, stopped <B>Dan Kosmicki </B>at 2:02 of the third round. Coetzee retired with a 32-5-1 record and 20 knockouts.
<P>* In Montville, Conn., former world heavyweight champion <B>James &#39;&#39;Buster&#39;&#39; Douglas </B>won a unanimous decision over <B>Rocky Pepeli </B>in a 10-round bout Friday.
<P>
<P><h3>Tennis</h3>
<P>
<P>* <B>Michael Chang </B>got the new year off to a positive start by beating <B>Pete Sampras </B>4-6, 6-4, 6-2, in the final of the Colonial Classic in Melbourne, Australia, and winning the exhibition for the third consecutive year.
<P>* <B>Jennifer Capriati</B>, who scored a couple of significant victories during the week, is ready to continue her comeback in the Australian Open starting Monday, even though she lost 6-1, 5-7, 6-1 to <B>Martina Hingis </B>in the Sydney Invitational final.
<P>* In the men&#39;s final at Sydney, <B>Tim Henman </B>of Britain defeated <B>Carlos Moya </B>of Spain 6-3, 6-1.
<P>
<P><h3>Hockey</h3>
<P>
<P>* Atlanta, which had a National Hockey League team through most of the 1970s, is considered by most observers close to the sport to be an overwhelming favorite to land a team in the NHL&#39;s latest round of expansion. The league will look at bids from nine prospective cities on Monday and Tuesday in New York. Billionaire <B>Ted Turner,</B> who owns the baseball Braves and NBA Hawks, is ready to spend the $75 million or so for an NHL team in the new 20,000-seat downtown arena on the site of the aging Omni, which will be torn down next summer.
<P>
<P>Obituaries
<P>
<P>* <B>Dan Gooden,</B> father of New York Yankees pitcher <B>Dwight Gooden,</B> died Friday  in Tampa at age 69. The elder Gooden had been hospitalized since May when he had open heart surgery the day after his son pitched a no-hitter against  Seattle. Dwight was with his father in the hospital every day since the season ended.
<P>* <B>Angelo Drossos,</B> 68, credited with bringing professional basketball to San Antonio and the 3-point shot to the NBA, died Thursday. The former San Antonio Spurs owner had a lengthy battle with a form of Parkinson&#39;s disease.
<P>
<P><h3>Miscellany</h3>
<P>
<P>* A bankruptcy trustee in Pittsburgh said he will not oppose a bankruptcy petition filed by former Steelers running back <B>Rocky Bleier </B>in an attempt to rid himself of $1.3 million in debt.
<P>* A group called Citizens for More Important Things has filed a lawsuit in U.S. District Court to try to stop King County from issuing $336 million in bonds to pay for a new ballpark for the Seattle Mariners.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
