<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>Why do college recruiters avoid the KFL?</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 12, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470><BASEFONT SIZE="6">
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Why do college recruiters avoid the KFL?</B></FONT><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<P>   
<P>To paraphrase Jerry Glanville, a marginal coach and horrible football commentator, the capital letters in Knoxville Football League have been contorted into something else.
<P>   Like &#39;&#39;<B>K</B>eep <B>F</B>inding <B>L</B>ame&#39;&#39; players.
<P>   In terms of potential recruits as evaluated by Division I schools, the KFL is running neck-and-neck with the four powder puff teams at Karns High School.
<P>   It&#39;s a scoreless struggle:
<P>   Guys 0, Girls 0.
<P>   Sure, some KFL athletes have received letters with big-time logos. Others get the standard, &#39;&#39;Why don&#39;t you just walk on and we&#39;ll talk later&#39;&#39; sales pitch.
<P>   But this fact remains: Nary a KFL player is expected to sign a Division I scholarship this year.
<P>   To make matters worse, only a handful of kids have official visits to Division I-AA or Division II schools.
<P>   This really irks a growing number of local and area coaches. Just last month, they watched and cheered in Nashville as Webb School won a state championship while Halls and Jefferson County reached the title game.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We&#39;ve pretty much been ignored, but I do not know why it is,&#39;&#39; Karns coach David Bankston said. &#39;&#39;There are some good football players here, especially in terms of I-AA and Division II.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Bankston, a former quarterbacks coach at Carson-Newman, put the plight in perspective: &#39;&#39;I haven&#39;t even heard from anybody at Maryville College.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Times are tough when a nearby, non-scholarship Division III program with a losing record isn&#39;t sampling your coffee.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I think it&#39;s Knoxville they don&#39;t like,&#39;&#39; Bankston said, speaking generally. &#39;&#39;We can blame it on the town of Knoxville. It&#39;s either that or they are scared John Adams is going to write something about it and it isn&#39;t going to be nice.&#39;&#39;
<P>   A sense of humor comes in handy. Good kids who&#39;ve stayed in the weight room -- and out of trouble -- aren&#39;t receiving even a glimmer of just rewards.
<P>   Go figure, if you can.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I have no theory . . . I really don&#39;t,&#39;&#39; said Bearden&#39;s Bill Young, one of the most-respected coaches in the state. &#39;&#39;I was kind of taking it personal. I&#39;m kind of glad to hear other people are having the same problem, but it&#39;s really been a shock to me.&#39;&#39;
<P>   The situation is so bad that a prep football &#39;&#39;scholarship fair&#39;&#39; probably will be proposed for next season. Numerous coaches would set up booths in the same building where college scouts could evaluate video tapes. Copies could be made on the spot.
<P>    This could be held at Golden Gloves Arena at Chilhowee Park in conjunction with the popular recruiting combine at Fulton.
<P>   &#39;&#39;It might be something we need to take a look at,&#39;&#39; Young said. &#39;&#39;I know some of our kids can play and I&#39;m sure other coaches around town feel the same way. But for whatever reasons, I am not getting as much flow (from college coaches) as we need to for the kids.&#39;&#39;
<P>   There are several plausible explanations:
<P>  <B></B><B>ßÜFacts of life:</B> Young says it best. &#39;&#39;I try and remind our kids that some people can be great high school football players -- and not be a college player,&#39;&#39; he said. &#39;&#39;That does not mean they are not any good.&#39;&#39;
<P>   It does mean they need to do well academically.
<P>   <B>ßÜNFL filter-down theory:</B> The new catchword is prototype. In high school, this means a lineman who isn&#39;t at least 6-foot-3 and 230 pounds might as well forget about playing college ball.
<P>    The same can be said for &#39;&#39;team speed.&#39;&#39; Jimmy Johnston used this as the main ingredient in turning the Dallas Cowboys from a 1-15 laughingstock into repeat Super Bowl champions.
<P>   Here&#39;s what a KFL coach said: &#39;&#39;Too bad they don&#39;t have a 40-yard dash for heart, desire or character.&#39;&#39; Too bad, indeed.
<P>  <B></B><B>ßÜCoaching shuffles: </B>The decision of East Tennessee State coach Mike Cavan -- and several Bucs&#39; assistants -- to take jobs at SMU has caused a whiplash.
<P>    On the heels of a banner season that included a I-AA playoff victory, ETSU was a good bet to recruit several players to enhance its strong in-state foundation. These players have been left out in the cold.
<P>   &#39;&#39;They&#39;ve had our film since before Christmas,&#39;&#39; Halls coach Gary Shephard fumed. &#39;&#39;I don&#39;t know whether it&#39;s in Johnson City or Dallas or on Mockingbird Lane or Lover&#39;s Lane.&#39;&#39;
<P>  <B></B><B>ßÜAthletic downsizing:</B> Austin Peay&#39;s recent announcement it will no longer offer football scholarships was a blow statewide.
<P>    Just ask Sevier County coach Steve Brewer how he could have turned out if this had happened 20 years ago. Brewer was a standout quarterback at Austin Peay after making All-KFL at Fulton.
<P>  <B></B><B>ßÜPoor timing:</B> An assistant coach at UT-Chattanooga said the Mocs have fewer than eight full scholarships available.
<P>  <B>ßÜPoor judgment:</B> The financial decision to drop junior high football in Knoxville is going to hurt for years to come.
<P>   Unlike recruiting mistakes, lost time can&#39;t be changed.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

	<P><center><font size=2>Return to </font><a href="/"><font size=2>Main</font></a><font size=2>. Copyright &#169; 1996 The Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size=2>webmaster</font></a><font size=2>.</font></center></p>
