<html>

<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>State to reword Pigeon standard</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"></a><br
clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i>January 11, 1997</i> </td>
        <td width="470"><font size="6"><b>State to reword Pigeon
        standard</b></font><font size="5"><br>
        Stronger stance on color expected</font><p><font size="2"><i>By
        Morgan Simmons, News-Sentinel staff writer</i></font></p>
        <p><br>
        <font size="5">T</font>he Environmental Protection Agency
        said Friday it expects to receive a reworded
        interpretation of Tennessee's water quality standard for
        color on the Pigeon River within the next few days. </p>
        <p>''Tennessee is saying they will provide documentation
        to back up a stronger color interpretation,'' said
        Loretta M. Ucelli, EPA associate administrator for public
        affairs. ''That documentation will give EPA the ability
        to take action on the concerns of Tennessee.'' </p>
        <p>Confirmation of the state's position regarding
        revisions in its color standard came in a Jan. 9 letter
        from Attorney General Charles Burson to EPA Administrator
        Carol Browner. </p>
        <p>Burson wrote: ''Tennessee has the authority to make
        administrative interpretations of its narrative water
        quality standards. This administrative interpretation
        will be technically and legally supportable, and this
        office has the authority to render an opinion to that
        effect should you desire.'' </p>
        <p>Tennessee, like other states, expresses its color
        standard as a narrative, calling for ''no objectionable
        color.'' </p>
        <p>Eight years ago the EPA and Tennessee agreed on 50
        color units at the state line to be the correct
        interpretation of ''no objectional color.'' </p>
        <p>Tennessee argues that the river is still too dark, and
        it wants Champion's new permit to include stricter color
        limits at the state line. </p>
        <p>''Our purpose is to clean up the Pigeon River, and
        we'll do what's needed to get that result,'' said Justin
        Wilson, outgoing commissioner of the Tennessee Department
        of Environment and Conservation. ''Tennessee's narrative
        standard has always been protective of our waters. We
        don't believe we have to strengthen it, but we might want
        to articulate in a way that EPA can deal with.'' </p>
        <p>On Dec. 26, the EPA approved a new permit issued by
        North Carolina officials allowing Champion to continue
        operating its Canton, N.C., paper mill and polluting the
        Pigeon River at a level above what is allowed under
        federal law. </p>
        <p>Tennessee's main objection has been that the new
        permit, like the old one, calls for 50 color units at the
        state line, allowing the Pigeon River to look anything
        from green to almost black. </p>
        <p>EPA officials said Tennessee could switch to a
        numerical color unit standard but will most likely
        provide a different interpretation of its narrative
        standard, one in which EPA finds technical and legal
        justification for setting a stricter color standard than
        50 units at the state line. </p>
        <p>''This is something extremely important to Carol
        Browner (EPA administrator) and the vice president,''
        said Ucelli. ''Everyone agrees that the concerns of
        Tennessee need to be addressed, and this is an important
        vehicle for doing that.'' </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

<hr size="5">

<p align="center"><font size="2">Return to </font><a href="/"><font
size="2">Main</font></a><font size="2">. Copyright © 1996 The
Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a
href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size="2">webmaster</font></a><font
size="2">.</font></p>
