<html>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>100-acre gift</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 11, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>100-acre gift</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Brothers donate forest land to Foothills Conservancy</FONT></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Marti Davis, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">T</FONT>wo Maryville brothers have made the largest gift of land ever received by The Foothills Land Conservancy.
<P>   The 100 acres of forest land will expand the group&#39;s growing wilderness zone around the Great Smoky Mountains National Park.
<P>    The land, bordering Montvale Road on Chilhowee Mountain, was donated by real estate developers Michael and Evelyn Ross and Pat and Dale Ross of Maryville.
<P>    &#39;&#39;With this gift, we would like to honor our father and mother, Frank and Lila Rose Ross, lifelong residents of Maryville,&#39;&#39; the brothers said in their letter accompanying the gift. &#39;&#39;Their love of this community and us has always been our greatest inspiration. The Foothills Land Conservancy and its goal of preservation of our heritage is a wonderful cause and we are proud to be a small part.&#39;&#39;
<P>    The land, which is near the YMCA&#39;s Camp Montvale, will help expand the buffer zone around the Great Smoky Mountains National Park.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We need this for the wildlife. They&#39;re not making bear habitat anymore,&#39;&#39; said Randy Brown, director of the land conservancy.
<P>    The Ross brothers actually own a 1,000-acre tract of land bordering the 100 acres of land just donated. &#39;&#39;We hope to eventually give all of it to the land conservancy,&#39;&#39; said Michael Ross.
<P>    Brown said he was flabbergasted when the Ross brothers called to tell him about their gift. &#39;&#39;When they said &#39;It&#39;s 100 acres, my jaw dropped. It&#39;s inside the buffer zone we have targeted on our map, therefore its a high priority to us,&#39;&#39; said Brown. &#39;&#39;This is by far the largest gift of land the Conservancy has ever received. And the fact that it lies on Chilhowee, so near the Foothills Parkway and Camp Montvale only makes it more important. It&#39;s wonderful.&#39;&#39;
<P>    The acreage will be turned over to the Tennessee Wildlife Resources Agency. It will be made available for public recreational use along with the rest of the Foothills Wildlife Management Area overseen by the TWRA.
<P>    The Foothills Conservancy is a local, nonprofit land trust with offices in Maryville. It has protected more than 6,200 acres in the Foothills of the Great Smoky Mountains. The Conservancy is undertaking a $500,000 fund-raising campaign to purchase 1,500 acres on the southern end of Chilhowee Mountain.
<P>    In 1995, the Conservancy purchased 4,700 acres and donated 400 to the Great Smoky Mountains National Park and 4,300 acres to the Tennessee Wildlife Resources Agency, which created the Foothills Wildlife Management Area.
<P>    The conservancy&#39;s long range goal is to establish a permanent &#39;&#39;buffer zone&#39;&#39; between the National Park and the Knoxville Metro Area. For more information, call 681-8326.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
