<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>Overlooked double pay error, says prosecutor</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 11, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>Overlooked double pay error, says prosecutor</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Rebecca Ferrar, News-Sentinel Nashville bureau</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">N</FONT>ASHVILLE -- Knox County District Attorney General Randy Nichols says it was &#39;&#39;stupidity&#39;&#39; that led him to improperly charge the state for mileage while driving a county car.
<P>    While the amount -- $649.92 -- was relatively small compared to the $17,743.43 wrongly charged in travel expenses by the Memphis District Attorney General&#39;s office, it still was a crucial finding in the recent audit by the Comptroller&#39;s office.
<P>    &#39;&#39;If I was going to steal, I would steal more than that,&#39;&#39; Nichols said. &#39;&#39;It was a lack of oversight on my part. I sign those travel expenses, and I didn&#39;t pay very close attention.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Travel was just one area the audit focused on in its critical review of the financial oversight by the Tennessee District Attorneys General Conference.
<P>    In Nichols&#39; case, the audit says he submitted travel claims while using a county-assigned car. He kept payment for those claims &#39;&#39;for mileage expenses he did not personally incur&#39;&#39; during five trips in 1994 and 1995.
<P>    Nichols says he signed for reimbursement of expenses that included hotel, meals and mileage and was &#39;&#39;negligent&#39;&#39; in not noticing that mileage should have been excluded when using a county car.
<P>    He repaid the money Friday following the release of the audit on Thursday.
<P>    &#39;&#39;I apologize for these mistakes and accept full responsibility,&#39;&#39; he commented in the audit.
<P>    The claims in question were among 16 submitted by Nichols for which he received payment from 1992 to 1996.
<P>    Nichols originally told auditors that he put gas in the car for one of the five trips and said he &#39;&#39;would expect&#39;&#39; that amount to be deducted from the total he owes. He said he changed his mind because he had no receipts.
<P>    In Memphis&#39; case, the audit accused former Shelby County District Attorney General John Pierotti and Phyllis Gardner, an assistant district attorney general, of charging the state for $17,743 in travel expenses they already had paid for with a county credit card.
<P>    Pierotti retired in November. Both repaid the money, according to the audit.
<P>    The District Attorneys General Conference is the umbrella organization for all district attorneys general in Tennessee, coordinating lobbying, the state budget and other activities.
<P>    Other audit findings about the conference:
<P>    It should &#39;&#39;more closely manage&#39;&#39; the financial operations of the office and better monitor the district attorneys general. &#39;&#39;Management of the conference did not ensure that the district attorneys general&#39;s offices were operated properly,&#39;&#39; the audit says. The report found &#39;&#39;serious weaknesses&#39;&#39; in the fiscal operations.
<P>    It did not provide &#39;&#39;adequate guidance&#39;&#39; of the proper use of state expense funds. The district attorneys general in Knox, Hamilton, Davidson and Shelby counties received money for office expenses as authorized under state law. But the conference monthly issued warrants for the expenses &#39;&#39;negotiated for cash by the district attorneys general or deposited into both personal and governmental bank accounts controlled by the district attorneys general.&#39;&#39;
<P>    It did not adequately control property, equipment and leased office space.
<P>    It did not maintain adequate leave records.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
