<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>3 families left homeless</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i>January 11, 1997</i> </td>
        <td width="470"><font size="6"><b>3 families left
        homeless</b></font><font size="5"><br>
        2 firefighters injured in blaze at apartments</font><table
        border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="250"
        align="right">
            <tr>
                <td><img src="../images/Firebs.jpg" width="250"
                height="192"><br>
                <img src="../../images/v3/credits/BScredit.gif"
                width="144" height="21"><p><font size="2"><strong>Rural/Metro
                paramedic Brett McElroy treats an injured
                Knoxville firefighter, Rick Harrell, right, at an
                apartment fire in North Knoxville. Three families
                were left homeless by the blaze.</strong></font></p>
                </td>
            </tr>
        </table>
        <p><font size="2"><i>By Jamie Satterfield, News-Sentinel
        staff writer</i></font></p>
        <p><br>
        <font size="5">T</font>wo firefighters were hurt and
        three families left homeless when a fire broke out at a
        North Knoxville apartment complex Friday, authorities
        said. </p>
        <p>Two apartments were damaged by fire and a third
        sustained heavy smoke damage in the 2:14 p.m. blaze at
        Forest Creek Apartments, 322 Forestal Drive, Knoxville
        Fire Department spokesman Norman Hammitt said. </p>
        <p>Hammitt said at least three families were left
        homeless by the blaze. </p>
        <p>''In any situation like this, the Red Cross is
        contacted,'' Hammitt said. </p>
        <p>He added most of the affected apartment dwellers had
        family members in the area and were making arrangements
        to find places to stay. However, much of their belongings
        were damaged or destroyed in the fire, which Hammitt said
        likely started when a dryer vent overheated. </p>
        <p>Barbie Manis, 19, and her 11-month-old baby lost most
        of their clothing and furniture in the blaze. She said
        the overheated vent was inside the apartment she shared
        with her mother. </p>
        <p>''My mom was in there cleaning, doing some laundry,''
        she said. ''All of a sudden I heard her hollering for me
        that there was a fire.'' </p>
        <p>Manis said she gave her baby, Joshua, who already
        suffers from respiratory trouble and has to use a
        breathing machine, to her mother to take him outside
        while Manis frantically searched for a fire extinguisher.
        </p>
        <p>''It was black (from smoke) in the kitchen in 10
        seconds,'' Manis said. </p>
        <p>Manis said her sister and nephew also lived in the
        apartment. </p>
        <p>''We lost everything, and we didn't have that much to
        begin with,'' she said. </p>
        <p>As firefighters battled the blaze, snow fell and cold
        winds blew across the parking lot, where other residents
        gathered to comfort Manis and the others whose apartments
        were damaged. Two firefighters, Rick Harrell and Marcus
        Yarbrough, had to be taken to area hospitals to be
        checked for possible injuries after part of a ceiling
        fell on them. </p>
        <p>Hammitt said it appeared the firefighters would be OK.
        </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

<hr size="5">

