<head>
	<title>Pigeon Forge goes wild</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 11, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Pigeon Forge goes wild</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Wilderness Week begins today with experts, trips</FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Marti Davis, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">S</FONT>piders, snakes, hummingbirds and old logging camps of the Appalachians are among the topics to be covered in a weeklong program in Pigeon Forge.
<P>   Regardless of the weather, Wilderness Wildlife Week starts this afternoon. The free event will feature 80 of the area&#39;s top experts on the culture, plants and wildlife of the Great Smoky Mountains National Park and beyond. Several speakers and presenters are also coming from outside the region.
<P>    Visitors from all over the nation began arriving Friday at the Heartlander Country Resort, host of the event featuring back-to-back speakers from 8 a.m. until about 10 p.m.
<P>    Several dozen hikes and field trips led by park rangers and other experts are planned. Trips are expected to fill up fast during registration today, said Bob Easton, Pigeon Forge director of special events.
<P>    Every year the event&#39;s organizers plan more hikes and field trips but never seem to have enough, regardless of the weather, said Easton. Registration begins at  3 p.m. today at the Heartlander County Resort on the Parkway in Pigeon Forge. The Heartlander will be the site of most talks, slide shows and other non-outdoor events. 
<P>    The week begins officially at 5:30 p.m. with a reception, and a talk on wild bear research in the Smokies by Dr. Mike Pelton of the University of Tennessee.
<P>    Well-known nature photographer Ken Jenkins will present a slide show on the Smokies and Wildlife Week.
<P>    The evening will be capped off by two presentations on birds of prey. Robert Hatcher of the Tennessee Wildlife Resources Agency will present a show and lecture &#39;&#39;Rise up on the Wings of Eagles.&#39;&#39; Al Cecere of the Foundation to Protect America&#39;s Eagles will follow with a presentation involving live birds, an event that has come to be one of the favorites at wildlife week.
<P>    Among the new presenters this year are Walker Calhoun, who will present legends, songs and dances of his Cherokee ancestry at 2 p.m. Tuesday; and national hummingbird experts Bob and Martha Sargent, who will present their program at  2 p.m. next Saturday, Jan 18.
<P>    Jenkins helped start Wilderness Wildlife Week six years ago. &#39;&#39;It was a one-day event with about 65 people,&#39;&#39; the photographer said.
<P>    Last year, more than 8,000 people attended, more than half of them from at least 100 miles away.  A few came from as far away as California.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
