<head>
	<title>Oak Ridge robbers bind 10, take cash, jewels</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 11, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Oak Ridge robbers bind 10, take cash, jewels</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Bob Fowler, Anderson County editor</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">O</FONT>AK RIDGE -- After binding 10 family members with duct tape and cord, three men ransacked an Emory Valley home and stole a large amount of jewelry and cash Friday morning, police said.
<P>    The robbery at gunpoint occurred at the Dansworth Lane home of Vietnam native Huu Duc Dinh, founder of Oak Ridge-based American Technologies Inc., said Oak Ridge Police Department Detective Steve Speelman.
<P>    A similar robbery of another Vietnamese family living in Emory Valley occurred Nov. 16, when more than $20,000 in jewelry and cash was taken.
<P>    &#39;&#39;The pattern is the same,&#39;&#39; ORPD Lt. Jack Mansfield said. &#39;&#39;To us it looks like the same folks are involved.&#39;&#39;
<P>    In Friday&#39;s robbery, family members ranging in age from a 2-year-old boy to a couple in their 70s were bound while the robbers looted Dinh&#39;s home. Two family members were struck in the head by one of the robbers but didn&#39;t sustain serious injuries, Speelman said.
<P>    Speelman said eight family members were at home when the ski-masked trio came in the unlocked front door shortly after 8 a.m. Two other family members who arrived during the robbery also were tied up, Speelman said.
<P>    Family members said all three robbers spoke Vietnamese. The suspects spent from 30 to 45 minutes inside the residence searching for jewelry and money, Speelman said.
<P>    Mansfield estimated jewelry valued in the &#39;&#39;six-figure&#39;&#39; range was taken. Several diamond rings and a six-carat diamond necklace were stolen.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We&#39;re talking about high-dollar jewelry,&#39;&#39; he said.
<P>    Speelman said the robbers fled in a dark-colored, early 1980s model station wagon.
<P>    The Nov. 16 robbery occurred at an apartment in Emory Valley. A Vietnamese woman was bound and gagged while two men, described as Vietnamese, stole money and jewelry, police said.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
