<html>
<head>
	<title>East Tenessee briefs</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 11, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>East Tenessee briefs</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><h3>Pregnant wowan charged with endangering fetus</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>   A pregnant prostitute accused of injecting herself with crack cocaine was charged Friday with reckless endangerment, records show.
<P>   Tammy Lynn Moody, 32, who listed a Walker Boulevard address but told police she has been living out of her car, was booked into the Knox County Jail after she was released Friday afternoon from the University of Tennessee Medical Center.
<P>   Knoxville Police Department Investigator Edd Stair charged Moody in connection with a Jan. 4 incident in which Moody, whom police said was a prostitute, was seen by another prostitute allegedly injecting herself with crack cocaine.
<P>   The charge stems from allegations her actions could harm the fetus.
<P>   Moody also was served Friday with three outstanding warrants, including one for violation of probation, so she will not be allowed to post bond.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Judge with Blount ties reassigns Koella lawsuit</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>   A federal judge in Knoxville has recused himself from presiding over a wrongful death lawsuit brought against state Sen. Carl Koella by the widow of an Ohio man.
<P>   U.S. District Judge James Jarvis, the chief judge for the federal Eastern District of Tennessee, recused himself from the case Thursday and reassigned it to U.S. District Judge Curtis Collier in Chattanooga.
<P>   No reason was given for the decision.
<P>   Jarvis is a longtime Blount County resident and a former judge there.
<P>   The other Knoxville-based federal judge, U.S. District Judge Leon Jordan, is also a Blount County resident.
<P>   Koella of Townsend has long represented Blount County in the state Legislature.
<P>   Joyce Heinz Barnard, the widow of Terry R. Barnard, filed the $15 million wrongful death action earlier this week.
<P>   Barnard, 52, of Huron was killed when Koella turned his van into the path of Barnard&#39;s motorcycle in October on U.S. Highway 321 in Townsend. The lawsuit claims Koella was negligent in the operation of his vehicle, and that resulted in Barnard&#39;s death.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Knoxville man accused of firing gun inside house</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>   A North Knoxville man whom police said was in a drunken rage has been charged after he allegedly threatened friends with a gun and fired the weapon inside his house early Thursday, authorities said.
<P>   Curtis Butrum, 50, was charged with reckless endangerment in connection with the incident, which began just before 4 a.m. and ended more than an hour later, reports showed.
<P>   Knoxville Police Department spokesman Foster Arnett Jr. said Butrum had been drinking &#39;&#39;pure grain alcohol&#39;&#39; most of the morning when he went into a rage, breaking things inside his Gratz Street house. Butrum allegedly brandished a .38-caliber handgun and threatened to kill the other occupants of the house, according to Arnett.
<P>   Two of those occupants fled the home and called police, he said.
<P>   Arnett said Butrum remained inside the house with two other people when three shots were heard. KPD&#39;s Special Operations Squad leader Lt. Jim Kennedy was called to the site and &#39;&#39;banged on the door very loudly for several minutes,&#39;&#39; Arnett said.
<P>   Butrum was arrested when one of the occupants opened the door, Arnett said.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
