<P><B>ADAMS, VAN B. - </B>age 86, of Powell, passed away Thursday, January 9, 1997, at Ft. Sanders Regional Medical Center. He was a member of Wallace Memorial Baptist Church. Member of O.E.S. Areme #460. Past presiding officer and past secretary of Masters Masonic Lodge #244 F&AM, member of the York Rite, Royal Order of Scotland and a 33rd degree Scottish Rite Mason where he served many years as chaplain. He was selected Man of the Year for 1980 from a membership of over 10,000 in East Tennessee. Preceded in death by son-in-law, David E. Bean; four brothers and one sister. Survivors: wife, Frankie W. Adams, Powell; sons and daughters-in-law, James V. and Patricia Adams, Glendale, Ariz., Donald R. and Carolyne Callahan, Powell; daughter, Norma C. Bean, Louisville, Tenn.; sister, Pauline Ezell, Chattanooga; grandchildren, Rebecca Adams, Colorado, Jeffrey Callahan, Knoxville, Suzette Lacy, Lisa Watson, Christian Callahan, all of Powell; seven great-grandchildren; brother-in-law and sister-in-law, Glenn and Etta Killion; several nieces and nephews. Funeral service 3:30 p.m. Sunday, Rose Chapel, Rev. Bruce Forlines officiating. Interment in Woodlawn Cemetery. In lieu of flowers, memorials may be made to the American Heart Association. Masonic services will be conducted Sunday prior to funeral services by Masters Masonic Lodge #244 F&AM. Friends may call at their convenience at Rose Mortuary Broadway Chapel.
<P>
<P><B>ALLEN, J.C. - </B>born April 26, 1924, in Knoxville, Tennessee. Graduated from Austin High School, enrolled in the Army June 2, 1943 to May 3, 1946. He received a Bronze Star, a Victory Medal and Good Conduct Medals. Later he made his home in Washington, D.C. where he expired January 6, 1997. Preceded  in death by parents, J.D. and Ruth Allen; sisters, Juanita Vernon and Willa Harris; brother, Marvin Allen; nephews, Aaron and Shannon Allen; several aunts, uncles and cousins to include the Tuggle and Goins families. Survivors: brothers and sisters-in-law, Joshua and Ida Allen, Miami, Fla., Aaron and Barbara Allen Sr., Knoxville; sisters and brothers-in-law, Mary and Oscar Middleton, Miami, Fla., Nedda and Edlin Vernon, Savannah, Ga., Lottie Allen, Miami, Fla.; a host of nieces and nephews in Miami, Fla., including Sharon and John Glass, Miramar, Fla., LaGale and Marion Warren, Savannah, Ga., Alex and Lynda Tetteh, Madison, Ala., Tracey Fields, Denise Allen, Michael and Rose Allen, all of Knoxville; a host of cousins including Jessie and George Jackson, Waukegan, Ill., Calvin Tuggle, Maxcine Tuggle, Evelyn Daniels, Jewell and Zellie Fannin, all of Knoxville. Very devoted friends, Jon McBride and Keggie Pound. Receiving friends from 6:30-7 p.m. with  memorial service 7 p.m. Monday, January 13, 1997, at Unity Mortuary Chapel, Chester Green Jr. officiating. Arrangements by Unity Mortuary, 1425 McCalla Avenue, Knoxville.
<P>
<P><B>ALLEY, LENNIE CARMICHAEL - </B>age 86, of Dandridge, passed away Friday, Jan. 10, 1997, at Jefferson County Nursing Home in Dandridge. Widow of Bill Alley and the daughter of the late William H. and Cora Link Carmichael. Also preceded in death by sister and brothers, Rhulla Mease, Shirley and Ernest Carmichael. Former employee of the Allen-Baker Clinic in White Pine. Survived by brother, O.D. Carmichael of Talbott; several nieces and nephews. Funeral services will be held 7 p.m. Saturday at the Farrar&#39;s White Pine Chapel with Rev. Ronald Spires, Rev. Ronald Wine and Rev. Rufus Smith officiating. The family will receive friends 6-7 p.m. prior to services. Family and friends will meet at 2:30 p.m. Sunday at Ebenezer United Methodist Church Cemetery for the graveside services. Farrar&#39;s of White Pine in charge.
<P>
<P><B>BELLAMY, THOMAS WOODROW - </B>age 80, of Sweetwater, passed away Friday morning, January 10, 1997, at the family home. He was retired from ALCOA and a U.S. Army veteran of WWII. Survivors: wife, Edith Thomas Bellamy; sons and daughters-in-law, Thomas L. and Lucille Bellamy, William K. and Joan Bellamy, Woodrow F. and Sheila Bellamy; brother, Charles T. Bellamy, all of Sweetwater; five grandchildren; two step-grandchildren; eight great-grandchildren; one great-great-grandchild; several nieces and nephews. The body is at Kyker Funeral Home, Sweetwater, where the family will receive friends 6-8 p.m. Saturday. Graveside service and interment 1 p.m. Sunday in West View Cemetery with Rev. G.L. Geren officiating. Military honors will be provided by the Sweetwater VFW Gold Post 5156.
<P>
<P><B>BERRY, FRED ALLAN, SR. - </B>age  80, of 728 Burem Road, Rogersville, passed away Friday, January 10, 1997, at Hawkins County Memorial Hospital after an extended illness. He was a member of Rogersville Presbyterian Church where he served as elder for many years and was presently serving as chairman of the scholarship committee. He was owner and operator of Two-Way Radio Service. He was a school teacher for Hawkins and Washington County School Systems. For many years, Mr. Berry was engineer and morning announcer for WRGS Radio Station. Mr. Berry was preceded in death by infant son, Robert Crockett Berry and his parents, Robert Rexford and Fornia Jackson Berry. Survivors include  his wife, Jane Forgey Berry; one daughter and son-in-law, Janeil and Richard L. Hill, II of Huntsville, Ala.; one son and daughter-in-law, Fred Allan and Patricia Berry, Jr. of Huntsville, Ala.; one brother, Mr. Samuel Harold Berry of Johnson City, Tenn. and two grandchildren, Jana Luanne Berry and Jonathan Allan Berry, both of Huntsville, Ala. Calling hours will be from 2 p.m. to 3:30 p.m. Sunday, January 12, 1997, at the Rogersville Presbyterian Church, Rogersville, Tennessee, with the Dr. David L. Hale officiating. Burial will follow in McKinney Cemetery, Rogersville, Tenn. Memorials may be made to Wilheim Memorial Scholarship Fund at Rogersville Presbyterian Church, 309 West Kyle Street, Rogersville, Tenn. 37857.
