<P><B>HENSLEY, WILLIAM - </B>age 67, of Knoxville, passed away January 10, 1997, at Windwood Health Care after an extended illness. Member of Wallace Memorial Baptist Church. Navy veteran of the Korean Conflict. Member of Plumbers and Steamfitters Local Union 102. Preceded in death by parents, Pearl and Estelle Hensley; and brother, Jimmy Hensley. Survived by son and daughter-in-law, Joe and Lori Hensley; daughter and son-in-law, Conni and Davis Skidmore; nephew, David Hensley of Atlanta; grandchildren, Misty Heatherly, Autumn Hensley, Matthew Hensley and Jonathan Skidmore. Family and friends will meet at 1:45 p.m. Sunday at Lynnhurst Cemetery for a 2 p.m. graveside service, Rev. James McCluskey officiating. The family will receive friends 7-9 p.m. Saturday at Weaver Funeral Home.
<P>
<P><B>HILL, CHARLES &#39;&#39;BUD&#39;&#39; - </B>age 76, of Maryville, died Thursday, January 9, 1997, at his home. He was a member of Lamp Light Full Gospel Church. He was a retired veteran serving in the U.S. Army during World War II. He received the Purple Heart. Mr. Hill was preceded in death by his mother, Iva Lorene McCarter Hill; father, Charles L.  Hill, Sr.; sister, Aurelia Hill Perry; brother, Robert Lee Hill; twin brothers who died at birth; and granddaughter, Miranda Marie Wilburn. Survivors include wife, Julie Marie Hill; daughters and sons-in-law, Janice and Butch Sayers of Texas, Sharon and Bill Seals of Texas, Kathy and David Hall of Maryville; son and daughter-in-law, Michael and Sherry Wilburn of Maryville; seven grandchildren; one great-grandson; sisters, Frances Ruth Hill Teffeteller of Maryville, Edna Grace Potts of Nashville; several nieces and nephews. Funeral services will be held at 12:30 p.m. Saturday in McCammon-Ammons Funeral Home Chapel with Rev. Ronald Morton officiating. The interment will follow in Louisville Cemetery with full military honors.  The family will receive friends 11-12:30 Saturday at McCammon-Ammons Funeral Home, Maryville.
<P>
<P><B>HODGE, MARY BERTIE LUCILLE - </B>age 87, of Route 1, Rutledge, died at 4:45 a.m. Friday morning, January 10, 1997, at Holston Health Care Center in Knoxville. She was a longtime resident of the Buffalo Springs Community and was a lifelong member of the Buffalo Baptist Church where she taught Sunday School for many years. She was preceded in death by her parents, Mr. and Mrs. E.H. Clowers, and her husband, Howard Hodge; brothers, Mack and Jess Clowers; sisters, Georgia Roach and Bessie Perrin. Survivors include her brother, William Clowers of Knoxville; sisters, Monda Fortner of Florida, Emma James of Seymour and Mabel Davis of Corryton; several nieces and nephews; special friends, David and Cindy Evans, Reese Morgan and Hazel Acuff; a host of friends and neighbors. Funeral services will be held at 8 p.m. Saturday evening, January 11, 1997, from the Smith Funeral Home Chapel in Rutledge with Rev. Kirk Wallace officiating. Graveside services and interment will be at 2:30 p.m. Sunday afternoon, January 12, 1997, in the Sunrise Cemetery. Pallbearers: Bud Perrin, Harold Perrin, Billy Ray Perrin, Troy Roach, Reese Morgan and David Evans. The family will receive friends 6-8 p.m. Saturday evening prior to services at the funeral home. Arrangements by Smith Funeral Home, 123 Water Street, Rutledge, Tennessee 37861, Phone (423) 828-5555.
<P>
<P><B>JOHNSON, ROXIE - </B>age 81, passed away January 9, 1997, at the home of her daughter. She was a member of Wesleyan United Methodist Church. Survivors: children, James R. Johnson, Carol Davis, Janice Lunsford; grandchildren, Debbie Carr, Timmy Martin, Tommy Davis, Marvin Davis, Michael Davis, Michael Lunsford, Amie Lunsford, Amanda Lunsford; great-grandchildren, Tommy Davis, Jr., Byron Martin, Candice Jones, Marcus Lunsford, Justin Jones, Courtney Lunsford, Shane Jones. Funeral service 2:30 p.m. Monday, Berry Chapel, Rev. Howard Fields officiating. Interment Sherwood Memorial Gardens. Pallbearers will be grandsons and friend, Michael Hayes. The family will receive friends 6-8 p.m. Sunday at Berry Funeral Home, Chapman Highway.
<P>
<P><B>JONES, ESKER - </B>age 76, of South Knoxville, passed away January 8, 1996 at U.T. Medical Center. He was a member of Friendly Chapel Baptist Church, retired from Robertshaw and was a veteran of World War II. Preceded in death by brothers, Claude, Burl, Aliss Jones and sisters, Odessa Bolton, Evelyn Hatfield. Survivors: Daughter, Linda Galyon; sons, Lester and Lonas Jones; grandchildren, Wendy Smith, Shawn Jones; great-grandchildren, Travis, Trevor and Megan; brothers, Goldie Jones, Durl Jones; sisters, Myrie Hawkins, Zelma Norman; special friend, Louise McCarroll; several nieces and nephews. Funeral service 2:30 p.m. Saturday, January 11, 1997, Berry Chapel with Rev. Fred McGill and Rev. Bill Acuff officiating. Interment to follow in Mt. Olive Cemetery. Arrangements by Berry Funeral Home, Chapman Highway.
<P>
<P><B>KIRKLIN, CLAUDIA LEE - </B>age 79, formerly of Evarts, died Jan. 10, 1997, at the Corbin Christian Health Center following a long illness. She was the daughter of the late Ben and late Mary Brown Stringer; and the widow of Luther McKinley Kirklin. She is survived by two children, a son and daughter-in-law, Luke and Becky Kirklin of LaFollette, and Mrs. Alene Horner of Jeffersonville, Ind.; two sisters, Wanda Carter of Dearborn, Mich., and Lavone Bush of Jackson, Mich.; a brother, Kenneth Stringer of Dearborn, Mich. She was blessed with four grandchildren, Sean McKinley and Meredith Alene Kirklin, Lynn Krammes and Sandy Mikonowiez; four great-grandchildren and one great-grandchild. She was preceded in death by two sisters and one brother. Mrs. Kirklin was a member of the Harlan Christian Church and a former employee of Highslpint Coal Co. and Macks Supermarket, and a member of the Yocum Creek Order of the Eastern Star. Visitation will be 5-7 p.m. Sunday at Harlan Christian Church. Funeral services will be 7 p.m. Sunday at the church with the Revs. Don Thomas, Charlie Morris and Sean Kirklin officiating. Graveside services will be conducted 10 a.m. Monday at Resthaven Cemetery. Pallbearers will be Rufus Mills, Grady Lee, Wayne Hensley, Don Parsons, Rick Fox, Harold Parsons, John Myers and Phillip Smith. In lieu of flowers, contributions are suggested to the Harlan Christian Church or the LaFollette United Methodist Church. Mount Pleasant Funeral Home is in charge of arrangements.
<P>
<P><B>KITTS, CHARLES N. - </B>age 76, Knoxville, passed away at Knoxville Convalescent Center Friday, January 10, 1997. Member of the Baptist faith. WWII Veteran. Preceded in death by parents, Ross and Elizabeth Sexton Kitts. Survived by one sister, Gertrude Bledsoe, Knoxville. Funeral services 1 p.m. Monday, McCarty Mortuary Chapel, Rev. Glenn Suffridge will officiate. Interment will follow in Beeler Cemetery, Union County. The family will receive friends 6-8 p.m. Sunday at McCarty Mortuary, 4004 Holston Drive.
<P>
<P><B>LOY, EMMA BOOHER - </B>age 84, passed away at Hillcrest North Nursing Home, Jan. 9, 1997. She was a member of Philippi Baptist Church in Cleveland, Tenn. Preceded in death by husband, Delmer Loy. Survivors: sons, Don Loy of Knoxville, Charles Loy of Las Vegas, Nev.; sisters, Maddie Wade, Blanche Traugott, Reva Edis, all of Knoxville; brothers, Woodrow Booher of Knoxville, Jay Booher of Edgewater, Md., Harvey Booher of Cleveland, Tenn.; several grandchildren and great-grandchildren; numerous nieces and nephews. Family and friends will meet at Pleasant View Cemetery in Maynardville 1:45 p.m. Monday for graveside services at 2 p.m. with Rev. Dan Moore and Rev. Harvey Booher officiating. The family will receive friends 6-8 p.m. Sunday at Rose Mortuary Broadway Chapel.
<P>
<P><B>MARSH, CHARLES FRANKLIN, SR. - </B>age 76, formerly of Knoxville, passed away Wednesday, January 8, 1997, in Lake Worth, Fla. He was born 8/24/1920 in Browntown, Tenn. He lived in Dayton, Ohio for 38 years, most recently of Lake Worth, Fla. He was a former member of the Civilian Conservation Corps. He was a decorated veteran of WWII, serving from June 8, 1944 until January 6, 1946 in Company E, 1st Platoon, 22nd infantry, 4th Division U.S. Army. Received the Purple Heart, Theater Ribbon with three Bronze Stars, Victory Medal WWII and the M1SS for Sharpshooting and expert gunmanship STMM. Retired driver, lastly in Eastern Express in Ohio. Longtime member Master&#39;s Masonic Lodge #0244 F&AM in Knoxville, Tenn. and the Antioch Temple A.A.O.N.M.S. of Dayton, Ohio. Survivors: He was the beloved husband of  Annie M. (Varnes) Marsh for 57 years and the loving father of Cynthia J. (Marsh) Pryor, Glenna R. (Marsh) Stanhouse, Charles F. Jr, James E. Marsh; six grandchildren and nine great-grandchildren. Funeral services 2 p.m. Sunday, Rose Chapel, Rev. David Smith officiating. Interment in Lynnhurst Cemetery with full military honors conducted by the Volunteer State Veterans Honor Guard. Masonic Services will be Saturday at 8 p.m. in Rose Chapel conducted by Masters Masonic Lodge #0244 F&AM. The family will receive friends from 6-8 p.m. Saturday at Rose Mortuary Broadway Chapel in Knoxville, Tenn.
<P>
<P><B>MARTIN, TERESA - </B>of Knoxville, passed away Jan. 9, 1997, at Ft. Sanders. Preceded in death by mother, Pauline B. Yard; and father, Thomas Phillips Martin. Survivors: brother and fiancee, James Stephen Martin and Marci L. Cannon; brother and sister-in-law, Thomas Martin Jr. and Shalonn; niece, Amy Elizabeth Martin; nephew, Christopher Matthew Martin; aunts and uncles, Bill and Gwen Martin, Alma and Louis Freyre, June and David Linville; several other aunts, uncles and cousins; special friend, Ruby Hart. Funeral service 1 p.m. Sunday, Rose Garden Chapel with Rev. David Loveless officiating. Interment Lynnhurst Cemetery. Memorials should be made to Juvenile Diabetes Foundation. The family will receive friends 6-8 p.m. Saturday at Rose Mortuary Broadway Chapel.
<P>
<P><B>MASHBURN, LUNA CARTER - </B>age 87, of Pinehurst, N.C., formerly of Knoxville, passed away Jan. 9, 1997. She was of the Baptist faith. Preceded in death by parents, Cloyd and Cynthia Carter. Survivors: daughters and sons-in-law, Mildred and Robert Watkins, Pinehurst, N.C., Joan and Joseph Trotter of Orange Park, Fla.; son and daughter-in-law, Earl and Barbara Mashburn of Knoxville; three grandchildren, Gary, William and Robert Ellis; five great-grandchildren. Family and friends will meet at 9:45 a.m. Sunday at the West Adair entrance to Lynnhurst Cemetery for graveside services at 10 a.m. with Rev. Dave Ward officiating. The family will receive friends 6-8 p.m. Saturday at Rose Mortuary Broadway Chapel.
<P>
<P><B>O&#39;DELL, PHILLIP - </B>age 74, of Maryville passed away Thursday morning January 9, 1997 at St. Mary&#39;s Medical Center, Knoxville. Veteran of the U.S. Army having served during World War II, member of the disabled American Veterans. Preceded in death by granddaughter, Deana Beasley; parents, Phillip and Mary O&#39;Dell. Survivors: Children Debbie O&#39;Dell, Diane Beasley, Donna O&#39;Dell, all of Maryville, Dan O&#39;Dell of Michigan, Patty McDonald of Missouri; grandchildren, Kelsy O&#39;Dell, Kelly Orr, Donnie Orr, Dotty Beasley-Church, Ashley O&#39;Dell; great-grandson, Justin Orr; sisters, Tuck Bates, Pearl Anderson, Lois Bell, all of Missouri; special people, the Poplin family, Ruth, Jack, Barbara, Bob, David Poplin, Mike Webb; numerous nieces and nephews. Funeral service 8:00 p.m. Saturday at Miller Funeral Home Chapel, Rev. Beecher Whitehead officiating. Family and friends will meet at Chilhowee Primitive Baptist Church Cemetery (Red Top) at 2:00 p.m. Sunday for the interment service. The family will receive friends from 6:00 p.m. to 8:00 p.m. Saturday at Miller Funeral Home.
<P>
<P><B>RHINEHART, TIMOTHY G. - </B>age 18, of South Knoxville, passed away Friday morning at his home. Graduate of Ft. Sanders Development School. Survivors: mother, Sonya Rhinehart Creswell; father, Charley Creswell; sisters, April and Kimberley Creswell; grandmother, Ellen Rhinehart; grandparents, C.L. and Mary Creswell; several aunts, uncles, cousins. Graveside service 1:30 p.m. Monday, Mt. Olive Cemetery, Rev. Doyle Seal officiating. The family will receive friends 7-9 p.m. Sunday at Berry Funeral Home, Chapman Highway.
<P>
<P><B>SHOFFNER, ISAAC &#39;CHARLES&#39; - </B>age 74, of Harrogate, Tenn., passed away Thursday, January 9, 1997, at 11:17 p.m. at the James H. Quillen Medical Center in the Veterans Hopsital in Johnson City, Tenn. He was born April 11, 1922, at his family&#39;s farm on Indian Creek in the Forge Ridge Community. Charles attended Forge Ridge High School, was a World War II veteran and a successful businessman in his community for the past 25 years. He had worked for E&L Car Transport, was a 32 degree Mason and a member of the Elks Lodge. Member of the Gibson Station Primitive Baptist Church in Virginia, which was founded by his grandfather, Rev. H.A. Shoffner. He was preceded in death by his parents, Isaac Shoffner and Susie Keck Shoffner; brothers, Roy Shoffner, Sr. and Golie Shoffner of Middlesboro, Otis Shoffner of Monroe, Mich., and Tyson Shoffner, Harrogate. Survivors: wife, Juanita Mason Shoffner of 54 years; daughter, Janie Turnblazer Conley and husband, Jerry Conley; son, Charles Eddie Shoffner and wife, Betsy McCollough Shoffner, Tazewell, Tenn. Grandchildren are Autumne Edmonds and husband, Mark, Jill Shoffner-Brown and husband, Mike, Wendy M. Shoffner of Tazewell, Jason and Rachel Turnblazer of Knoxville; great-grandchildren, William Mason Edmonds, Thomas Chandler Edmonds, Kelsey Elizabeth Brown; sister, Hazel Shoffner Felix of Moore Park, Calif.; sisters-in-law, Warren Shoffner Woodby and Maureen Mason Shoffner, Harrogate; a host of friends and relatives. The funeral will be held at 8 p.m. Sunday at Reece Valley Chapel with Rev. Calvin Chesney officiating. Eulogy by Mark Edmonds. Music by Wayne Goforth. Graveside services 11 a.m. Monday in the Shoffner Cemetery with military rites by the Volunteer State War Era Veterans Honor Guard. Pallbearers: Jason Turnblazer, Larry Cadle, Pete Cosby, Troy Crockett, Billy Montgomery, Marty Edds, James Ramsey, Jay Shoffner, Jerry Shoffner and Johnny Shoffner. Honorary pallbearers: Steve Mason, Ray Haskew, Bill Hall, Earl Ledford, Bill Cardwell, Denny Peters, Woody Keck, Bobby Ramsey, David Ramsey, Joel Collins, Bill Ray Russell, Bill Muncy, Homer Sowders, George Cadle and John C. Russell. The family will receive friends 6-8 p.m. Sunday, Jan. 12, 1997, at Reece Funeral Home & Valley Chapel 869-3651 or 626-4249.
<P>
<P><B>SNAPP, KATHERINE MARIE - </B>age 78, of Louisville, died Wednesday, January 8, 1997, at the family home after a lingering illness. She was a member of Magnolia Avenue United Methodist Church. Preceded in death by infant daughter, Darlene and sister, Eula Slagle. Survivors: husband, John P. Snapp; son and daughter-in-law, Steve and Carol Snapp; son, Roger Snapp; grandsons, Mike, Doug and David Snapp; step-grandson, Jeff Hutchison; great-grandchildren, Morgan, Emily and Cade Snapp, Alexandria Hutchison; sister, Doris Treece; sister-in-law and brother-in-law, Ruby and Tommy Sherrod; sister-in-law, Cleo Snodgrass; several nieces and nephews. Family and friends will meet 1:45 p.m. Saturday at Highland Memorial Cemetery for a 2 p.m. graveside service. Rev. Walter Willis and Rev. Ron Fisher officiating. Pallbearers: Tom Sherrod, Lynn Griffin and grandsons. In lieu of flowers, donations may be made to Magnolia Avenue United Methodist Church, 2700 Magnolia Avenue, Knoxville, Tenn. 37914. Arrangements by Stevens Mortuary, Oglewood Avenue at Broadway.
<P>
<P><B>TALAMANTES, LOUISE MINTON - </B>age 69, of New  Market, passed away Thursday, Jan. 9, 1997, at Ft. Sanders Regional Medical Center. She was a member of Talbott Church of God. Survived by husband, Ray Talamantes of New Market; daughters, Paula McKivitt of Florida, Laura Masters of Arizona; sons, Kennith Hensley of California, Tom Talamantes of Canada; seven grandchildren; one great-granddaughter; sisters, Barbara Farmer and Margaret Keeling of New Market, Glenna Keck of Seymour, Kathleen Lonas, Johnnie Conaster and Cynthia Harb, all of Knoxville, Ramona Sharp, Washington State, Beatrice Ward of Talbott and Ruth Byrd of Etowah; brothers, Bob Hubard of Maryland, John Hellard of Texas, Gordon Landerth of Pigeon Forge, Franklin Landerth of Etowah; many nieces and nephews. Funeral service 2 p.m. Sunday, Talbott Church of God with Revs. James McFalls and Clay Ward officiating. Interment in Jefferson Memorial Gardens. The family will receive friends 1-2 p.m. Sunday at the church prior to funeral service. Arrangements by Fielden Funeral Home, New Market.
<P>
<P>TAYLOR, BESSIE (ANN) WEBB MER<B>CER - </B>age 80, died Friday, January 10, 1997, at Hillcrest West Nursing Home. Member of the Baptist faith. Preceded in death by parents, Oscar and Bessie Webb; brothers, Orville, Wallace, Cecil and Victor Webb; daughter, Patti Sue Mercer. Survivors: sons, Ronald Mercer and Steven Darrell Taylor, both of Texas; three grandchildren; sister, Margaret Garrison, Powell, Tenn.; sister and brother-in-law, Evelyn and Jack Hubbs, Knoxville; brother and sister-in-law, Oscar J. and Kathy Webb, Las Vegas, Nevada. Funeral arrangements incomplete. Rose Mortuary Mann Heritage Chapel in charge.
<P>
<P><B>TAYLOR, MR. RAYMOND D. - </B>age 70, of Sallings Road, Luttrell passed away suddenly 5:30 a.m. Thursday, January 9, 1997 at his home. He attended the Trinity Church of God in Luttrell. Survivors: Wife, Doris Gene Taylor, Luttrell; aunts, Georgia Phillips, Agnes Cockrum, both of Knoxville, Lundy Sands of Baltimore, Maryland; special cousins: Ann and Dub Ford, Hornersville, Missouri. Funeral services 2:00 p.m. Sunday, Cooke Mortuary Chapel, Rev, Stanley Washam officiating with music by Trinity Church of God Singers. Interment will follow in Luttrell Cemetery. Pallbearers: Harlan Lynch, Buddy Baker, Paul Wyatt, Jay Lynch, Scott Hill, Richie Rose. Arrangements by Cooke Mortuary, Maynardville.
<P>
<P><B>TEFFETALOR, HELEN ROEHL IDOL - </B>age 69, of Knoxville, went to be with the Lord Wednesday morning at her residence. She attended Buffat Heights Baptist Church. Survivors: daughter, Judy Pannell Idol of Knoxville; daughters and sons-in-law, Eugenia and Earl Hoskins of Oklahoma, Vickie and David Mahan of Knoxville, Sharon and Donald Parkhurst of Oklahoma, Karen and Edd Zachary of Knoxville, (Becky) Rebecca and Chris Kirk of Knoxville; grandchildren, Michael and Julie Pannell, Melissa Turner, Derrick and Brandon Hoskins, Shawn and Shannon Mahan, Amy Weaver, Chad, Brittney and Tyler Parkhurst, Kristi Z. Phipps and Heather Zachary, Candance and Carmen Kirk; 11 great-grandchildren; sister, Annette Bryan of Knoxville; brother, Charles Roehl of Knoxville; sisters-in-law, Johnnie, Ruby, Hazel and Pauline Roehl; special friend, Oliver Letsinger; several nieces and nephews. The family will receive friends Sunday night from 6-9 p.m. Chapel service Monday, 11 a.m., Rev. Dana Matheson. Interment immediately following at Lynnhurst Cemetery.    Lynnhurst-Greenwood Chapel of Berry Funeral Home, 2300 W. Adair Drive in charge of arrangements.
