	<title>Business Briefs</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper Business News">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif" alt="Knoxville News-Sentinel Online -- Business News" align=bottom border=0 width=595 height=176></a><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td align=left valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 11, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Business Briefs</B></font><basefont size=6><!--SUBHEAD--></basefont></FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<h3>Comcast to control E!</h3>
<P>
<P>
<P>    NEW YORK -- Comcast Corp. announced Friday it has won the right to buy Time Warner Inc.&#39;s controlling stake in E! Entertainment Television, the celebrity news cable network, for $321 million.
<P>    Comcast, the nation&#39;s fourth-largest cable company, is one of five cable operators that are partners in the network. The partners late last year triggered a provision in their partnership agreement allowing for a change of control.
<P>    They still have about a month to resolve the issue.
<P>    Under the provision, each of the four minority partners can buy out Time Warner&#39;s 58.4 percent ownership stake, sell their combined stake to Time Warner or decide to leave the ownership structure unchanged.
<P>    Comcast emerged after talks with the partners with the right to buy out Time Warner. It will now decide whether to proceed with a purchase.
<P>    If Comcast chooses to buy out Time Warner, bringing its stake to 68.8 percent, it will also have the right to buy out the other partners after five years.
<P>    For Comcast, which is based in Philadelphia and has 4.3 million subscribers, the purchase would represent yet another expansion in cable programming.
<P>    The company recently took control of the Philadelphia Flyers and 76ers with an eye toward airing games on its own sports network, which is scheduled to debut in fall 1997. Comcast recently purchased Scripps Howard Cable in Knoxville.
<P>
<P><h3>Hyatt Regency gets new GM </h3>
<P>
<P>   Tom Mason has been named general manager at the Hyatt Regency Knoxville.
<P>   It is the first general manager assignment for the 37-year-old, who comes to Knoxville from Chicago, where he was corporate director of the rooms division for Hyatt Hotels.
<P>   He has been with Hyatt for 15 years.
<P>   He replaces Patrick Donnelly, who served as general manager for 21 months and recently relocated to Milwaukee, Wis., to take a general manager&#39;s position there.
<P>   Mason and his wife, Pam, have three children.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
