<head>
	<title>IceGators&#39; jersey might fit Reeves</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 11, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470><BASEFONT SIZE="6">
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>IceGators&#39; jersey might fit Reeves</B></FONT><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Smith attempts to find team for ex-Cherokee</FONT></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Nick Gates, News-Sentinel sportswriter</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">T</FONT>he latest episode of &#39;&#39;As the Cherokees Turn,&#39;&#39; the East Coast Hockey League soap opera starring suspended scoring machine Kyle Reeves, could take a new twist.
<P>   Knoxville coach Barry Smith tried to peddle the 29-goal scorer to the Jacksonville Lizard Kings in a four-player trade Monday. But Reeves, who got into a heated shouting match with Smith and left the team during the first intermission of a game against the Roanoke Express a week ago, chose not to report and scuttled the deal.
<P>   Smith said following the Cherokees&#39; 5-3 loss Thursday night to the Hampton Roads Admirals -- Knoxville&#39;s 13th defeat in the last 14 games -- he was attempting to send Reeves to a team he&#39;d agree to play for.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I hope in the next day or so to have something done for Reeves,&#39;&#39; Smith said. &#39;&#39;I&#39;ve been working on it. We&#39;re trying to accommodate him and get the players I need.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Reeves and little-used defenseman Ron Paleczny were to go to the Lizard Kings, who are in last place in the South Division. The Cherokees would get rookie defenseman Tobias Ablad and forward Francois Leroux in return.
<P>   A possible alternative destination for Reeves might be the Louisiana IceGators. The IceGators (14-17-3) are in seventh place in the South, but nine of their losses are forfeits. The league penalized Louisiana for using one more veteran (players with 200 or more games of professional experience) than rules allow.
<P>   Doug Sheddon, coach and director of player personnel of the IceGators, is doing everything he can to overcome the stiff penalty imposed by the ECHL. Not only does he want to qualify for the playoffs, but he wants to overtake first-place Tallahassee.
<P>   Louisiana recently reacquired the rights to goalie Bryan Schoen which would make Sergei Tkachenko (5-2-1, 4.25 goals-against average) expendable.
<P>   The IceGators are at the veteran limit (four), so if Reeves were brought on board, another veteran would have to be let go. Defenseman Jack Williams (two goals, two assists and 11 penalty minutes in four games with the IceGators) is likely to be the odd man out.
<P>   But so much for speculation. The facts aren&#39;t so nebulous.
<P>   The Cherokees have disintegrated since defenseman Kent Fearns was loaned to the Las Vegas Thunder of the International League. Coupled with an injury to captain Wayne Anchikoski and the loss of Reeves, the team has started struggling on offense as well as defense.
<P>   However, the Cherokees showed signs of life against the Admirals. Consider:
<P>   *  Knoxville held Hampton Roads scoreless for the first 18 minutes and 11 seconds before a turnover and a coverage breakdown resulted in two backbreaking goals 69 seconds apart to wipe out a 1-0 lead.
<P>   &#39;&#39;They were mistakes on our part and the guys shouldn&#39;t be making those mistakes,&#39;&#39; Smith said. &#39;&#39;We had good coverage, broke down and they took advantage of it.&#39;&#39;
<P>   * Goaltender Trent Cavicchi came back from injury and played well.
<P>   * The power play was 1-for-4 and had several other good chances.
<P>   * Los Angeles Kings farmhand Stephane Soulliere contributed two goals.
<P>   * The penalty-killers looked as good as they have at any time this season in foiling a four-minute disadvantage. While Dan Chaput was in the box for high-sticking, Jim Brown had two short-handed scoring chances and forechecked the Admirals out of their skates along with Martin Tanguay and Matt Turek.
<P>   * The Cherokees, although frustrated, have shown no signs of quitting on the coach or themselves.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We&#39;ve got to continue to work,&#39;&#39; Smith said. &#39;&#39;Nobody said it was going to be easy getting out of this thing and Hampton Roads is a good hockey team.&#39;&#39;
<P>   The only mistake the Cherokees made was allowing Victor Gervais, one of the league&#39;s all-time leading scorers, from speeding through their defensive zone unchecked. He burned them three times.
<P>   Tonight&#39;s game against the Raleigh IceCaps -- the only team Knoxville has beaten during its freefall -- at Civic Coliseum is arguably the biggest game to date.
<P>   A victory and the Cherokees will terminate a six-game slide, including five on home ice. It also would move them two points closer to the sixth-place IceCaps.
<P>   But more importantly, it would give them a jolt of confidence. Another defeat and they would have to ask themselves this question: If you can&#39;t beat Raleigh (13-19-3) at home, who can you beat?
<P>   The answer is very disconcerting.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
