		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Sports briefs</B></FONT><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<h3>Edwards picks returns to Georgia over NFL</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>    Georgia running back <B>Robert Edwards </B>said Friday he plans to return for his senior season. But Georgia Tech is losing its top rusher, <B>C.J. Williams.</B>
<P>    Williams, who ranks fourth on the Yellow Jackets&#39; career rushing list, surprisingly entered his name for the NFL draft despite an injury-plagued season in which he gained only 663 yards.
<P>    &#39;&#39;I think he&#39;s making a big mistake,&#39;&#39; Tech coach <B>George O&#39;Leary </B>said Thursday of Williams&#39; decision. &#39;&#39;I think C.J. needs to stay one more year to mature.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Edwards, a junior who rushed for 800 yards last season but briefly lost his starting job because of fumbling problems, decided he needed another year of college even though he is set to graduate this summer.
<P>    &#39;&#39;I feel that I have some unfinished business here and I want to help Georgia get back on the map,&#39;&#39; Edwards said. &#39;&#39;It&#39;s not about the money, but playing for fun and having fun at Georgia.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Edwards, who should earn a degree in consumer economics in June, may pursue a second degree in the real estate or housing fields. For that reason, he&#39;s not concerned about getting hurt on the football field and ruining his NFL hopes.
<P>    &#39;&#39;Everything happens for a reason, but I will have my degree,&#39;&#39; he said. &#39;&#39;I will be the first person in my family to earn a college degree. I can&#39;t do anything about getting hurt.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Also declaring for the NFL draft was defensive end <B>Derrick Rodgers,</B> who helped Arizona State go 11-0 during the regular season and reach its first Rose Bowl in a decade.
<P>
<P><h3>In other college football news:</h3>
<P>* <B>Earl Young,</B> a backup defensive back for Fresno State, died Thursday after he collapsed while walking to class. Young, 21, of Marrero, La., complained of breathing difficulties to a passerby and was rushed by ambulance to a hospital, where he died a short time later. Authorities did not issue a cause of death.
<P>* <B>Kent Green </B>has been named the new offensive coordinator at Tusculum College. He was offensive coordinator at Middle Georgia College, which went 10-2 this past season and was ranked seventh nationally.
<P>* West coach <B>Ted Tollner&#39;s </B>problem today in the East-West Shrine all-star game today in Stanford, Calif.: Find playing time for quarterbacks <B>Jake Plummer </B>of Arizona State, <B>Steve Sarkisian </B>of BYU and <B>Pat Barnes </B>of California. The East will be quarterbacked by <B>Marcus Crandell </B>of East Carolina and <B>Lance Funderburk </B>of Valdosta State.
<P>
<P><h3>Baseball</h3>
<P>
<P>* Tennessee team will begin spring practice Monday at 10 a.m. at Lindsey Nelson Stadium. The Vols open the season in the Olive Garden Classic in Kissimmee, Fla., against Oklahoma State.
<P>
<P><h3>Hockey</h3>
<P>
<P>* Former Los Angeles Kings owner <B>Bruce McNall </B>was sentenced Thursday to five years, 10 months in prison and ordered to repay $5 million for his admitted role in a scheme to bilk banks, a securities firm and the NHL team of more than $236 million.
<P>
<P><h3>Tennis</h3>
<P>
<P>* <B>Jennifer Capriati </B>continued her comeback with a 2-6, 6-4, 6-2 upset over <B>Lindsay Davenport </B>to reach the women&#39;s final of the Sydney International, where she scored her last tournament victory in 1993. Capriati will face second-seeded <B>Martina Hingis </B>of Switzerland, who eliminated <B>Mary Joe Fernandez </B>6-3, 6-2.
<P>* In men&#39;s play at Sydney, Britain&#39;s <B>Tim Henman </B>upset top seed <B>Goran Ivanisevic </B>4-6, 7-6 (7-1), 6-1 to reach his second final in two weeks. Henman will meet <B>Carlos Moya </B>of Spain, who beat third-seeded <B>Albert Costa </B>of Spain 3-6, 6-3, 7-6 (8-6).
<P>
<P><h3>Boxing</h3>
<P>
<P>* <B>Mike Tyson </B>will not take a tuneup fight before his rematch with <B>Evander Holyfield,</B> which could be held as early as May 3 at the MGM Grand hotel in Las Vegas. Sources close to the event say the bout may be moved back a week or two at Holyfield&#39;s request.
<P>
<P><h3>Running</h3>
<P>
<P>* The Norris Dam Challenge -- 12- and 5-kilometer runs -- scheduled for this morning has been postponed until Feb. 22.
<P>
