<head>
	<title>$15 million suit filed against Koella in crash</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 10, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>$15 million suit filed against Koella in crash</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Randy Kenner, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">T</FONT>he family of an Ohio motorcyclist killed when state Sen. Carl Koella turned into his path last October has filed a $15 million wrongful death lawsuit against the Blount County legislator.
<P>   Joyce Heinz Barnard, the widow of Terry R. Barnard and the administratrix of his estate, filed the action in federal court here late Wednesday afternoon.
<P>   Barnard, 52, of Huron, Ohio, suffered fatal injuries when he struck the right rear side of Koella&#39;s van on U.S. Highway 321 in Townsend and careened into another vehicle on Oct. 22, 1996.
<P>   The lawsuit contends that Koella&#39;s actions directly led to the fatal accident.
<P>   &#39;&#39;At and immediately prior to the time of collision that caused the death of Terry R. Barnard, the minivan was being operated in a negligent manner by the defendant Koella,&#39;&#39; the lawsuit states. &#39;&#39;Such negligence was the proximate cause of the collision. . . .&#39;&#39;
<P>   Knoxville lawyer Sidney Gilreath represents Joyce Barnard.
<P>   &#39;&#39;It&#39;s an unfortunate event for the family, and they just want to see that justice is done in the court system,&#39;&#39; he said
<P>   According to police reports, Koella stopped only briefly following the accident before proceeding on to his residence. He was later charged with leaving the scene of a fatal accident and faces a hearing on the misdemeanor charge later this month.
<P>   Koella said in a statement the following day that he heard a &#39;&#39;thunk&#39;&#39; and thought he had perhaps &#39;&#39;run over a rock or something on the side of the road.&#39;&#39;
<P>   He said he noticed what appeared to be an accident on the other side of the road after stopping to examine his van, but after finding no damage, he left.
<P>   Koella, did however, stop to tell Grady Lindsey at the Tuckaleechee Campground -- the wreck occurred at the entrance to the campground from 321 -- that an accident had occurred but he wasn&#39;t involved.
<P>   A closer examination of the van by Koella and Lindsey, a friend of Koella&#39;s who manages the campground, revealed tire marks on the right rear of the van, according to Lindsey. Koella subsequently called authorities.
<P>  Following the incident, Koella said he was innocent of leaving the scene of the accident, and his lawyer, Jerry Cunningham, said he was looking for a witness who indicated that Barnard was driving recklessly and speeding.
<P>   Cunningham indicated that Koella neither saw Barnard nor realized that Barnard had hit the van. Cunningham said Thursday he had not seen the lawsuit and couldn&#39;t comment on it.
<P>   But he added, &#39;&#39;I have a witness relative to the speed and to his (Barnard&#39;s) passing three vehicles at one time.&#39;&#39;
<P>   When asked how fast Barnard was going, Cunningham replied, &#39;&#39;I&#39;m talking 80 miles per hour, estimated.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Gilreath, however, noted that even if someone is speeding you still can&#39;t pull into their path if you see them.
<P>   &#39;&#39;But we have witnesses that said he wasn&#39;t going too fast,&#39;&#39; Gilreath said.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
