<html>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>Trimming death row will cost, panel told</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 10, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>Trimming death row will cost, panel told</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> $2 million called needed for speedup</FONT></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Rebecca Ferrar, News-Sentinel Nashville bureau</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">N</FONT>ASHVILLE -- If Tennesseans want death row inmates executed, it will cost more money, legislators were told Thursday.
<P>    Tennessee Supreme Court Justice Adolpho A. Birch Jr. said spending $2 million to &#39;&#39;opt in&#39;&#39; to a federal law would speed up federal appeals of death penalty cases.
<P>    Birch testified before the legislative committee looking into why the death penalty has not been carried out in Tennessee since the law was re-enacted in 1977.
<P>    And Post Conviction Defender Donald Dawson, who defends death row inmates, said pumping more money into better defense attorney work would avoid trial errors and the subsequent reversals of verdicts.
<P>    &#39;&#39;If Tennessee wants to have a death penalty, Tennessee has to decide it&#39;s time to pay,&#39;&#39; Dawson said.
<P>    House Speaker Jimmy Naifeh, D-Covington, said $2 million &#39;&#39;does not seem excessive.&#39;&#39; The Legislature convenes Tuesday and will take up the budget next month.
<P>    The $2 million would permit Tennessee to participate in the federal Anti-terrorism and Effective Death Penalty Act of 1996.
<P>    The law passed by Congress last spring establishes a six-month statute of limitation for filing federal appeals of the death penalty, permits federal district courts six months to dispose of the appeals and allows another four months for federal appellate courts to dispose of appeals.
<P>    &#39;&#39;The death penalty has been a dominant political issue in Tennessee,&#39;&#39; Birch said. &#39;&#39;The focus of this issue has been the judicial branch of state government. However, less than half of 1 percent of the state budget is dedicated to funding the courts, despite the amount of income we generate.&#39;&#39;
<P>    He also noted that in 1995, at Gov. Don Sundquist&#39;s urging, the Capital Case Resource Center was abolished. The center funded lawyers with state and federal money who defended death row inmates and was replaced by the Post Conviction Defender&#39;s Office. 
<P>    &#39;&#39;One certain way to ensure delay in death penalty cases is to eliminate or reduce the adequacy of legal representation for criminal defendants,&#39;&#39; Birch said.
<P>    To speed up appeals, Birch said the high court closely monitors death penalty cases, assigning new judges to cases where needed.
<P>    In addition to funding, Birch blamed some of the &#39;&#39;unjustifiable delay&#39;&#39; in carrying out the death penalty on the &#39;&#39;heightened review&#39;&#39; by the Court of Criminal Appeals.
<P>    He further blamed delays by the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, which many victims rights&#39; advocates have attacked for being opposed to the death penalty. Those advocates also have criticized the state Supreme Court as too liberal on the death penalty and helped defeat former Justice Penny White in last year&#39;s election.
<P>    &#39;&#39;Since 1984, no death penalty conviction in a Tennessee case has completed federal review through the 6th Circuit Court of Appeals,&#39;&#39; Birch said.
<P>    Dawson stressed the importance of assuring a sound defense at the trial level. He cited a case in which the death penalty was reversed because the defendant&#39;s attorney prepared only 17 hours for trial.
<P>    Tennessee&#39;s law also is &#39;&#39;constitutionally vague,&#39;&#39; he said. For example, persons may only be convicted of the death penalty if found guilty of felony murder. That means he or she must have committed the murder during the commission of a separate felony.
<P>    Dawson said prosecutors often use aspects of the murder to enhance the conviction and, thus, the verdict is reversed.
<P>    &#39;&#39;There&#39;s going to be a death penalty, but let&#39;s get it fair,&#39;&#39; he said.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

