<head>
	<title>Y-12 plant delivers B-61 bomb parts ahead of time</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 10, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Y-12 plant delivers B-61 bomb parts ahead of time</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Frank Munger, News-Sentinel Oak Ridge bureau</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">O</FONT>AK RIDGE -- The Y-12 nuclear weapons plant completed its first delivery of modified parts for the B-61 bomb ahead of schedule, a plant spokeswoman said Thursday.
<P>    Patricia Greeson said the bomb components were delivered in mid-December, a couple of weeks before the program&#39;s deadline.
<P>    Although Y-12 no longer produces warhead parts for new weapon systems, some replacements or modifications are manufactured at the Oak Ridge facility.
<P>    Units for the B-61, Mod-11, a modified version of an atomic bomb that&#39;s been in the U.S. arsenal for decades, were one of the first production jobs to be conducted at Y-12 since operations returned to normal.
<P>    A &#39;&#39;stand-down&#39;&#39; went into effect at Y-12 in late 1994 because of problems identified during an inspection by the Defense Nuclear Facilities Safety Board, although some weapons activities continued with special approvals. Processing of enriched uranium is the only Y-12 operation still bound by the stand-down order.
<P>    Greeson said Y-12 has met or exceeded delivery timetables many times in years past, but the B-61 delivery was special because of the hard work and preparations involved. Since the 1994 stand-down, employees have undergone thousands of hours of training, and safety procedures were revised throughout the plant.
<P>    &#39;&#39;This is a morale boost for our employees to see how good they still are,&#39;&#39; the Y- 12 spokeswoman said. &#39;&#39;It feels really good.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Additional deliveries of B-61 parts will be made later this year, Greeson said. She declined to release dates or number of parts involved. 
<P>    The B-61 is sometimes known as the &#39;&#39;granddaddy&#39;&#39; of atomic bombs because it has been in the arsenal so long.
<P>    Y-12 is engaged in other weapons tasks, including production of &#39;&#39;limited-life&#39;&#39; components for Trident II warheads, as well as retrofit projects for the Peacekeeper system.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

	<P><center><font size=2>Return to </font><a href="/"><font size=2>Main</font></a><font size=2>. Copyright &#169; 1996 The Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size=2>webmaster</font></a><font size=2>.</font></center></p>
</body>
