<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="keywords"
content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>Nature aiming another wintry blast at East Tennessee</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i>January 10, 1997</i> </td>
        <td width="470"><font size="6"><b>Nature aiming another
        wintry blast at East Tennessee<!--SUBHEAD--></b></font><table
        border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="250"
        align="right">
            <tr>
                <td><img src="../images/0109weatherJH.jpg"
                width="504" height="328"><br>
                <img src="../../images/v3/credits/JHcredit.gif"
                width="144" height="21"><p><font size="2"><strong>Evan
                Pringle, 18 months, is more interested in what's
                going on outside than playing at Cedar Bluff Play
                School. The weather was too cold to permit the
                children to play outside. </strong></font></p>
                </td>
            </tr>
        </table>
        <p><font size="2"><i>By Stan DeLozier, News-Sentinel
        staff writer</i></font></p>
        <p><br>
        <font size="5">E</font>ast Tennessee dodged Mother
        Nature's icy bullet, but she appears to be reloading. </p>
        <p>For Knoxville, upper East Tennessee and the Cumberland
        Plateau, the National Weather Service is forecasting a 30
        percent chance of snow today with steadily falling
        temperatures this afternoon. There is only a 20 percent
        chance of snow in the Chattanooga area. </p>
        <p>There is a slight possibility any snowfall today will
        come on top of some already on the ground. The NWS said
        there was a 30 percent chance of rain or snow overnight. </p>
        <p>The high temperature today is expected to be in the
        low to mid-30s. The predicted low Saturday morning is in
        the teens. </p>
        <p>Forecasters had thought there might be a layer of
        sleet and ice over the area by late Wednesday night or
        early Thursday morning. However, the temperature remained
        in the mid-30s. The low at Knoxville Thursday morning was
        34. </p>
        <p>There may be a brief respite from the gloomy weather
        Sunday when the sun may peep through the clouds. But it
        won't last long, the forecasters say. The outlook for
        Monday is mostly cloudy skies with a chance of snow or
        freezing rain. </p>
        <p>U.S. Highway 441 across the Great Smoky Mountains
        between Gatlinburg and Cherokee, N.C., is the only road
        that has been closed by the weather. </p>
        <p>Although East Tennessee escaped the bad weather
        Wednesday night and Thursday morning, Signal Mountain, 10
        miles northwest of Chattanooga, was hammered by heavy
        ice. Officials said ice-laden tree branches fell across
        power lines and left hundreds of electric customers
        without power. Service was restored by midmorning
        Thursday. </p>
        <p>The Tennessee Highway Patrol reported many roads in
        Middle and West Tennessee were slick and treacherous for
        travelers. A Kentucky woman was killed Wednesday when she
        lost control of her car on icy U.S. Highway 45 near Union
        City and it crashed into a tractor-trailer truck. </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

<hr size="5">

