<head>
	<title>U.S. to mull letters on Cherokee plan</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 10, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>U.S. to mull letters on Cherokee plan</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> 700 respond to Forest Service</FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Morgan Simmons, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">T</FONT>he public comment phase of the Cherokee National Forest plan revision process has come and gone, leaving the U.S. Forest Service with over 700 letters to read.
<P>   The 120-day comment period ended Dec. 2, giving citizens their first opportunity to provide input into a planning process that will determine how the 632,348-acre Cherokee National Forest will be managed over the next decade.
<P>   &#39;&#39;The comments and petitions we received reflect a broad cross section of views on how the forest should be managed,&#39;&#39; said Keith Sandifer, U.S. Forest Service planner.
<P>   On Monday, Jan. 13, Forest Service planners will begin analyzing each written comment. A summary of the issues will be out by the end of March, followed by a draft forest management plan and environmental impact statement in about a year.
<P>   Sandifer said a final land management plan for the Cherokee National Forest should be completed next year.
<P>   The U.S. Forest Service is required by law to update its land management plans for each of its national forests every 10 to 15 years.
<P>    The Cherokee National Forest is one of five national forests in the Southern Appalachian region currently revising its plan.
<P>   Sandifer said the written comments reviewed so far indicate a growing interest in recreation on the Cherokee National Forest.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We&#39;ve seen a significant number of letters from folks interested in greater access,&#39;&#39; said Sandifer. &#39;&#39;These include horseback riders, mountain bikers and people who ride all-terrain-vehicles.
<P>   &#39;&#39;And then there are folks who&#39;d like to see less access but more areas for primitive-type recreational experiences. This isn&#39;t a voting process; what it boils down to is the capability of the forest to support a particular activity, or mix of activities.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Pete Kirby, southeast regional director of the Wilderness Society, said the Forest Service is seeking greater participation from the public this time around than it did for the current plan developed 10 years ago.
<P>   &#39;&#39;The process is much improved,&#39;&#39; said Kirby. &#39;&#39;There has been a great deal of learning among the public about the planning process, and people have gotten involved.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Kirby said the upcoming plan will benefit from the Southern Appalachian Assessment, an inventory of conditions on private as well as public lands that allows national forest decisions to be made in context of the overall landscape.
<P>   &#39;&#39;The Forest Service has taken care of the basics,&#39;&#39; said Kirby. &#39;&#39;They&#39;ve inventoried potential old-growth and roadless areas not identified 10 years ago, and they&#39;ve switched to eco-system management to better sustain the eco-system of the Southern Appalachians.&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

	<P><center><font size=2>Return to </font><a href="/"><font size=2>Main</font></a><font size=2>. Copyright &#169; 1996 The Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size=2>webmaster</font></a><font size=2>.</font></center></p>
