<head>
	<title>Kroger helping zoo fund African lion exhibit</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 10, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Kroger helping zoo fund African lion exhibit</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Amy McRary, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">T</FONT>he Knoxville Zoo will announce today that Kroger is giving both money and promotional help to build the zoo&#39;s new African lion exhibit &#39;&#39;Pridelands.&#39;&#39;
<P>   The half-acre natural habitat exhibit is set to open Monday, April 10. The zoo&#39;s three-man design crew has renovated an old lion exhibit once circled by chainlink fence into an area surrounded by manmade but realistic rocks.
<P>   John Wade, Tennessee Department of Tourism Development commissioner, is scheduled to attend today&#39;s 10 a.m. press conference at the zoo.
<P>   Kroger&#39;s $30,000 donation will help fund the exhibit&#39;s first phase of $125,000. The zoo earlier received a $25,000 construction grant from the non-profit, Knoxville-based Aslan Foundation. But the park still needs to net another $70,000 to help pay for &#39;&#39;Pridelands&#39;&#39; first phase.
<P>   Zoo officials hope to raise that money by selling $100 to $1,000 tiles that can be decorated with animals and/or inscribed with donors&#39; names. Those tiles will be embedded in a wall at the exhibit.
<P>   Kroger also made a year-long commitment to several promotional ties with the zoo, said Nancy Young, the park&#39;s marketing and development director. Those tie-ins include placing the &#39;&#39;Pridelands&#39;&#39; logo on area Kroger grocery bags and decorating storefronts with &#39;&#39;Pridelands&#39;&#39; art, she said.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Their partnership has been terrific,&#39;&#39; Young said.
<P>   &#39;&#39;The Knoxville Zoo is an integral part of our community,&#39;&#39; said Hunter MacWilliams, area manager for the Kroger Company. &#39;&#39;All of our Kroger associates throughout East Tennessee are very proud and excited to be part of the new African lion exhibit.&#39;&#39;
<P>   The zoo hopes to acquire three young African lions for the exhibit next month. The Aslan Foundation has donated another $25,000 to help buy the animals. Zoo officials hope to acquire two young lions from South Africa and will likely find the third at another U.S. zoo.
<P>   In addition, the zoo will be working to fund the project&#39;s second phase that includes a new off-exhibit holding building. Young said the second phase raises the exhibit&#39;s total cost to $207,000.
<P>   The lion exhibit will be the latest in a series of renovated or new natural habitat areas constructed almost totally by the zoo design crew.
<P>   Lions have a historical importance for the zoo. A lion named Joshua was the impetus for changing the zoo from a roadside menagerie into an accredited facility.
<P>   The late Guy Smith III bought the lion cub Joshua in 1970. When Joshua grew too large for his home, Smith took the animal to the zoo. Zoo conditions were so poor at the time that Smith, then a television executive, decided to improve the failing attraction. His efforts led him to become zoo director, a post he held until his death in 1987.
<P>   Joshua lived at the zoo until his death in 1989 at the age of 19.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

	<P><center><font size=2>Return to </font><a href="/"><font size=2>Main</font></a><font size=2>. Copyright &#169; 1996 The Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size=2>webmaster</font></a><font size=2>.</font></center></p>
