<head>
	<title>Gatlinburg residents filing suit over Tunica investment</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 10, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Gatlinburg residents filing suit over Tunica investment</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Marti Davis, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><P>
<P>   SEVIERVILLE -- Three Gatlinburg residents are among 11 investors from Tennessee, Ohio, Mississippi and the Carolinas suing a group of Tunica, Miss., developers for $70 million.
<P>   The lawsuit also is asking for commissions Gatlinburg real-estate agents received.
<P>   The lawsuit filed in Sevier County Circuit Court said 11 investors gave the developers $250,000 each to build motels in the gambling-casino boom town on the Tennessee-Mississippi border. The suit also says they paid $19,000 each for operating costs.
<P>    The lawsuit indicates some of the investors took money from their retirement accounts to invest in the two motels.
<P>    The motels were never constructed, the suit said.
<P>    According to a summary brief filed with the lawsuit, Gatlinburg residents Lloyd and Betty Link, doing business as Link and Associates, held a meeting in Gatlinburg during 1993 to solicit new customers for purchases of real estate owned by Tunica, Miss., developers.
<P>    The lawsuit estimates that 11 investors in the two proposed motels responded and that in addition to their actual initial investments, each plaintiff lost $50,000 per month in potential earnings. The three investors from Gatlinburg are Darlene Reiner and Arthur and Glenda Creek
<P>    H. Earl Allen III, one of the defendants who is described as a &#39;&#39;promoter&#39;&#39; by the lawsuit, is also from Tennessee.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
