<html>
<head>
	<title>East Tennessee briefs</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 10, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>East Tennessee briefs</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><h3>Two wanted on Maryland charges waive extradition</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>   Two men wanted for sexually abusing boys in Maryland waived extradition from Tennessee on Thursday in Knox County General Sessions Court.
<P>   Samuel L. Glover, 49, and Marshall M. Kirkpatrick, 32, were arrested Tuesday in Knoxville. The fugitives were featured in November in an episode of TV&#39;s &#39;&#39;Unsolved Mysteries.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Knox County authorities said they expect Maryland officials to pick up the men soon.
<P>   Glover and Kirkpatrick, who allegedly posed as father and son, face more than two dozen sexual assault and child abuse charges in Carroll County, Md., in incidents involving three victims. The abuse is alleged to have occurred in the late 1980s and early 1990s.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Knox school board votes to reinstate 2 students</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>   The Knox County school board voted unanimously Wednesday to reinstate Whitney Davidson, the West High School student expelled a year ago for carrying a friend&#39;s trick cane into Powell Middle School.
<P>   The cane contained a sword, and possession of it on school grounds violated the school system&#39;s zero-tolerance policy toward weapons. The board expelled Davidson and her friend for one year.
<P>   Davidson&#39;s father, lawyer Bill Davidson, unsuccessfully sued the school system after the expulsion. He and the Powell High School student who owned the cane expressed regret for the incident Wednesday and with the one-year expulsion served, the board reinstated the students.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Good luck this year and welcome back,&#39;&#39; board Chairwoman Margaret Maddox told both students.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Robbery charges against men sent to grand jury</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>   A grand jury will consider aggravated robbery charges against two young Knoxville men, a judge ruled Thursday.
<P>   Knox County General Sessions Court Judge Geoff Emery, after a preliminary hearing, said he thought there was probable cause to believe Zavian R. Hill, 19, and Donald E. McCoy, 19, robbed a woman at gunpoint early Nov. 27 at a Weigel&#39;s convenience store at 3900 Pleasant Ridge Road.
<P>   Police stopped Hill and McCoy near the store in a Mercury within minutes after the woman was robbed by two masked men, testimony showed. Inside the car they found a telephone and wallet organizer taken from the victim.
<P>   Last year, Hill, McCoy and McCoy&#39;s cousin, Bobby A. McCoy, were among several young men charged in the Feb. 19 drive-by slaying of Samuel Martin. In September, authorities dropped the charges against the trio in Sessions Court.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Body of woman found along I-75 in Campbell</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>   JACKSBORO -- The Campbell County Sheriff&#39;s Department was investigating the apparent slaying of a woman whose body was found near Interstate 75 on Thursday afternoon.
<P>   Detectives said the body, clad only in a black top, was seen by a traveler about 20 yards off the Stinking Creek exit. Sheriff Ron McClellan said there appear to be stab wounds to the chest.
<P>   The unidentified woman was described by authorities as 25 to 45 years old, weighing 110 to 120 pounds, 5-feet, 3-inches to 5-feet, 4-inches tall and with long dark hair. She had the following tattoos: a peacock on the left shoulder; the word &#39;&#39;MOM&#39;&#39; and &#39;&#39; &#39;77&#39;&#39; on the right shoulder; the name &#39;&#39;Ricky&#39;&#39; on the left thumb with an arrow drawn through a heart; a rose on the left elbow; the initials &#39;&#39;D A D&#39;&#39; with a scar near the last letter on the left lower arm; the name &#39;&#39;Delila&#39;&#39; near the left ankle; and the letters &#39;&#39;RT&#39;&#39; and a box on the right ankle.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>2 Clinton teens indicted in beating death of man</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>    CLINTON -- Two Clinton teenagers have been indicted in connection with the bludgeoning death last month of a Clinton senior citizen.
<P>    Curtis Jason Ely, 19, was charged with both felony murder and first-degree murder in indictments returned Tuesday by an Anderson County grand jury.
<P>    Trinity David Carden, 18, was indicted on a charge of felony murder.
<P>   William C. Bond, 70, who was killed Dec. 3, was beaten to death with a piece of brick that the killer allegedly picked up in Bond&#39;s yard just before entering his home, police said.
<P>    Both Ely and Carden are being held without bond in the Anderson County Jail.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Maury using chain gangs for inmate road work</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>   COLUMBIA  -- Maury County began using chain gangs again Thursday on a road work detail.
<P>    Four felons and seven misdemeanor offenders -- all shackled -- were on the detail Thursday.
<P>    Plans to use the chain gangs have been in the works for several months.
<P>    &#39;&#39;We started it on a small scale this morning with some of the felons,&#39;&#39; Maury County road superintendent Van Boshers said.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
