<P><B>BUTCHER, VERSA RICH - </B>age 81, of Fountain City, passed away Wednesday morning in NHC Fort Sanders. She was a member of First Baptist Church of Fountain City. She was the widow of Carl L. Butcher, Sr. Preceded in death by sister, Nishie Noe; and foster parents, Mr. and Mrs. H.C. Cantwell. Survived by: son and daughter-in-law, Carl L., Jr. and Kerissa Butcher of Knoxville; granddaughters, Melissa Swisher of Carboro, N.C., Leslie Butcher of Knoxville, and Angie Graves of Knoxville; grandson, Richard Alan Butcher of Columbus, Ohio. Friends will meet at 1:45 p.m. Friday at Lynnhurst Cemetery for graveside services at 2 p.m., Rev. Larry Beeler officiating. In lieu of flowers, memorials may be made to Alzheimer&#39;s Association, 1924 Alcoa Hwy., Knoxville, TN 37920. Friends may call at their convenience at Gentry-Griffey Chapel.
<P>
<P><B>CARNES, J.B. - </B>age 64, passed away Monday at his residence. Retired from South Central Bell. Member of Masters Lodge #244 F.& A.M. and The American Legion. Survivors: daughters, Tammi Mence, Clinton, Tenn., Tracey Temple, Richmond, Va.; grandchildren, Jennifer, Stephanie, and Christopher Mence, all of Clinton, Charlie, Canden and Correy Temple, all of Richmond, Va.; sister, Francis Carr, Knoxville. Masonic memorial service at 8 p.m. Friday with funeral service immediately following at Lynnhurst-Greenwood Chapel with Rev. Roscoe Oxendine officiating. Interment 11 a.m. Saturday at Lynnhurst Cemetery. The family will receive friends 6-8 p.m. Friday prior to the service at the Lynnhurst-Greenwood Chapel of Berry Funeral Home, 2300 W. Adair Drive.
<P>
<P><B>CARPENTER, RUTH B. - </B>age 91 of Maryville, died Wednesday, January 8, 1997 at Fairpark Healthcare Center. She was a member of Fairview United Methodist Church and was preceded in death by her hasband, Clarence R. Carpenter. Survivors include: Daughter and son-in-law, Juanita and Don Stafford; grandchildren, Pam Cannon, Donna Stafford Turner; great grandchildren, Rachel Cannon, Jared Cannon; brother and sister-in-law, Sam and Maxine Blevins of Maryville; several nieces and nephews. Funeral services will be held at 2:30 p.m. Saturday in McCammon-Ammons Funeral Home Chapel with Dr. Jerry Russell officiating. The interment will follow in Carpenter&#39;s Campground Cemetery. Friends may call at their convenience at McCammon-Ammons Funeral Home, Maryville.
<P>
<P><B>COLE, MARY LUNTSFORD - </B>age 88, of 1317 W. Main Street, Rogersville, passed away Thursday, January 9, 1997, at Holston Valley Hospital and Medical Center, following a brief illness. She was a lifelong member of the First Baptist Church of Rogersville. She was preceded in death by her husband, Charles E. Cole; parents, Will and Clara Luntsford; brothers, L.J. Luntsford, Jack Luntsford, Bill Luntsford, Hubert Luntsford and Jess Luntsford; sisters, Grace Watkins, Nola Fannon and Pearl Wilson. She is survived by two sons and daughters-in-law, Charles D. (Ann) Cole of Jefferson City and Michael F. (Evelyn) Cole of Kokomo, Ind.; two daughters, Myrna C. Searcy of the home and Mrs. Jimmy C. (Elizabeth) Bible of Rogersville; seven grandchildren, David B. Cole of Erlanger, Ky., Jenny A. Cox of Union, Ky., Mary Sam Searcy of the home, Alicia Cole and Kimberly Cole, both of Charleston, S.C., James H. Miller, III of Surgoinsville and Michael J. Miller of Camp Lejeune, N.C.; sister, Mrs. Maggie L. Bradley of Rogersville; brother, Charles Luntsford of Chattanooga; several nieces and nephews. Funeral services will be held 8 p.m. Saturday at Colboch-Price Chapel with Rev. Ronell Owensby officiating. Graveside services will be held 2 p.m. Sunday at Highland Cemetery. Memorial contributions may be made to the First Baptist Church Scholarship Fund. The family will receive friends from 6-8 p.m. Saturday, prior to the services at Colboch-Price Funeral Home in Rogersville.
<P>
<P><B>COLEMAN, JOSH - </B>11, Cosby, died Wednesday at U.T. Medical Hospital, Knoxville. He was a fourth grade student at Smoky Mountain Elementary School. Survivors include his mother, Tina Webb Coleman, Cosby; half brother, William Coleman, Newport and half sister, Hope Coleman, White Pine; grandparents, Clarence and Ima Webb, Cosby, Burr and Stella Lewis, Chestnut Hill, Hoyt and Sandy Coleman, Waterman, Wis.; special family, Don Roderick, Michael, Natasha and Stoney Lee; several aunts, uncles and cousins and a host of friends. Funeral service will be 2 p.m. Saturday at the Brown Funeral Chapel with Rev. Gary Henderson officiating. Interment will be in the Waters-Large Cemetery. The family will receive friends 7-9 p.m. Friday evening at the Brown Funeral Home. Brown&#39;s, Newport, in charge.
<P>
<P><B>COX, JOHN A. - </B>age 78, of Knoxville, died Wednesday, January 8, 1997, at his home. Mr. Cox retired from Southern Railway in 1979 after 38 years of service. He was a combat veteran of WWII receiving a Purple Heart for wounds suffered in The Battle of The Bulge. Mr. Cox served in County Court from 1971-1976. He also served on the Election Commission in 1977. Mr. Cox was a Knox County School Board Member for 15 years, retiring in 1992. He was a trustee for the Juvenile Detention Center, chairman of the 39th. precinct voting district for 23 years from 1969-1992. An active member of Dante United Methodist Church. Preceded in death by parents, Mr. and Mrs. John A. Cox, Jr.; brothers, Carl, Ralph and Edward Cox. Mr. Cox is survived by his loving, devoted wife of 55 years, Margaret Whedbee Cox; sons and daughters-in-law, John Douglas and Susan Cox, Terry Lynn and Susan Cox; six grandchildren, Stephanie Cox Coiner and husband, Kevin, Chad and Amanda Cox, Courtney Cox and Heath Morgan, all of Knoxville, Cadet Justin D. Cox, West Point, N.Y.; one great-grandchild, Makenzie Coiner. Funeral service 11:30 a.m. Saturday at Stevens Chapel. Rev. John Brewster officiating. Interment Sherwood Memorial Gardens. Pallbearers: Chad Cox, Heath Morgan, Kevin Coiner, George Steele, Bud Lewis, Robert Province, Hal Worsham and David Clapp. Honorary pallbearers: Congressman John Duncan, Allen Morgan, Earl Hoffmeister, Ron Thomas, A.B. Bell, Bill Clabo, Lee Griswold, E.S. Bevins, Howard Ferguson and Alan Gill. In lieu of flowers, memorials may be made to Dante United Methodist Church, 6700 Kern Road, Knoxville, Tenn. 37918. Family will receive friends 6-9 p.m. Friday at Stevens Mortuary, Oglewood Avenue at Broadway.
<P>
<P><B>EDMONDS, HELEN E. - </B>of Knoxville, departed this life Wednesday, January 8, 1997, in<B> </B>Los Angeles, Calif. The body will be returned to Knoxville for funeral and interment. Funeral arrangements are incomplete and will be announced later by Unity Mortuary.
