	<title>Christmas sales termed &#39;moderate&#39;</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper Business News">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif" alt="Knoxville News-Sentinel Online -- Business News" align=bottom border=0 width=595 height=176></a><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td align=left valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 10, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Christmas sales termed &#39;moderate&#39;</B></font><basefont size=6><!--SUBHEAD--></basefont></FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Amy Geisel News-Sentinel Business editor</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">C</FONT>onsumers bought up clothes, jewelry and home furnishings this Christmas, but otherwise watched their spending, handing many of the nation&#39;s retailers a disappointing holiday season.
<P>   Goody&#39;s Family Clothing, with its new merchandising strategy now firmly in place, reported comparable store sales up 16 percent for November and December combined.
<P>   Proffitt&#39;s Inc.&#39;s same-store sales rose 3 percent for the period, about what the Alcoa-based retailer had planned. Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Brad Martin  described the sales as &#39;&#39;solid,&#39;&#39; and the company is comfortable with previous per share earnings estimates of $2.24 for the year.
<P>   Across the country, strong results were reported by many upscale retailers and discounters outpacing weak sales at some department stores and apparel chains.
<P>    &#39;&#39;Moderate growth in the economy translates into moderate retail sales,&#39;&#39; said Wayne Hood, a retail analyst at Prudential Securities Inc. in Atlanta. 
<P>    The Salomon Brothers retail index, the investment firm&#39;s barometer of sales performance, rose 6.1 percent last month after a 3.9 percent gain in November. In December 1995, the index rose 1.8 percent.
<P>    Because of the late Thanksgiving this year, retailers used different measures to report their holiday sales. Some merchants reported four-week results ending the last days of December. Others are comparing the five weeks ended Jan. 4 to the five weeks ended Jan. 6, 1996, while some are comparing the five weeks ended Jan. 4 with the month ended Dec. 30, 1996.
<P>   Goody&#39;s Family Clothing said sales in December totaled $145.9 million, up 18.9 percent over last year. For November, the moderately-priced apparel chain reported sales of $71 million, up 28.9 percent. Same store sales were up 18.9 percent in December, and up 7.6 percent in November.
<P>   Proffitt&#39;s Inc. said for the combined November and December period, company sales were $547.4 million, a 45 percent increase, including $170.6 million in sales from its newly acquired Parisian stores. For the two-month period, comparable stores sales increased 4 percent at the Proffitt&#39;s and Younkers divisions; were flat at McRae&#39;s; and decreased 1 percent at Parisian.
<P>    May Department Stores Co. said its same-store sales for the five-weeks ended Jan. 4 rose 2.7 percent and total sales gained 8.8 percent. Gap Inc. said its same-store sales for the five-week period ended Jan. 4 rose 2 percent, while total business was up 14 percent.
<P>    Apparel retailer Limited Inc. said same-store sales for the five-week period ended Jan. 4 fell 1 percent and total sales rose 7 percent.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
