	<title>Best Buy to open store in Knoxville</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper Business News">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif" alt="Knoxville News-Sentinel Online -- Business News" align=bottom border=0 width=595 height=176></a><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td align=left valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 10, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Best Buy to open store in Knoxville</B></font><basefont size=6><!--SUBHEAD--></basefont></FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">B</FONT>est Buy Co., a 272-store consumer electronics chain, annnounced it will open its first store in Knoxville this summer.
<P>   The 45,000-square-foot store will be on North Peters Road at the southwest corner of I-40/75 and Cedar Bluff Road in West Knoxville. The company will hire about 120 full- and part-time employees.
<P>   The Knoxville store is one of 10 to 15 stores the Minneapolis-based retailer plans to open this year.
<P>   Best Buy bills itself as a full-service retailer offering customer credit, technical service, performance service plans, home delivery and installation, computer software training, an in-store computer technician, and car stereo and mobile electronics installation.
<P>   Its stores are outfitted with an entertainment software area equipped with listening posts with more than 60,000 compact discs, 10,000 movies and 2,000 computer software titles; an in-store arcade for hands-on play of the latest video games; installation bays for car audio; a surround sound display; specialized speaker listening rooms; and a &#39;&#39;virtual car&#39;&#39; to experience car audio sound.
<P>   The company is celebrating its 30th anniversary this year.
<P>   As a result of a soft computer market, Best Buy reported a loss of more than $6.7 million, or 25 cents per share, on sales of $5.423 billion for the first nine months of 1996.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
