<head>
	<title>Philips announces plans for HDTV</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper Business News">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif" alt="Knoxville News-Sentinel Online -- Business News" align=bottom border=0 width=595 height=176></a><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td align=left valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 10, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Philips announces plans for HDTV</B></font><basefont size=6><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Digital video disk player also on way</FONT></basefont></FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Pam Park, News-Sentinel business writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">L</FONT>AS VEGAS -- A Federal Communications Commission endorsement of standards for high definition television has opened the door for Philips Consumer Electronics Co. to launch an HDTV product by late 1997 or early 1998, company&#39;s president announced at the Winter Consumer Electronics Show in Las Vegas Thursday.
<P>   More than 80,000 were expected for the annual show, which brings together retail buying and consumer electronics suppliers and manufacturers. The show started Thursday and continues through Sunday.
<P>Robert Minkhorst said Philips was among the founders of the Grand Alliance that began a struggle  to establish standards for this new technology nine years ago. With industry standards for the products in place, the door is open for creative business models in interactive television, he said.
<P>Minkhorst expects the 230 million televisions in American homes to be replaced with these digital movie-quality televisions in 7 to 10 years. 
<P>Another new product from Philips is the Digital Video Disc player headed for retail stores in spring.
<P>    It is expected to cost about $600. DVD&#39;s introduction has been delayed by lack of commitment from content providers who must provide a sufficient number of entertainment and movie options to make this new format viable. Manufacturers now feel they have  sufficient support from video, audio and software providers to begin marketing the machines.
<P>Content providers such as Polygram are expected to announce DVD titles in the second or third quarter.
<P>Doug Dunn, chairman and chief executive officer of the consumer electronics division of Dutch Electronics giant, Philips NV, the Knoxville company&#39;s parent, said he expected 250 million laser-based devices to be on the market by the turn of the century. He thinks as many as 10 percent of those will be DVD products.
<P>The Philips Magnavox Internet TV Terminal for WebTV hit sales floors in September and is selling in numbers beyond internal projections, Minkhorst said.
<P>The terminal allows consumers to access the Internet through their home televisions and costs about $400 including a cordless keyboard.
<P>Some 97 percent of  purchasers have expressed total satisfaction with the product, Minkhorst said.
<P>Minkhorst says of the people who bought WebTV, 60 percent had never been on the Internet before.
<P>Philips sees opportunities for the product, since its research shows that of the 65 percent of the  American public that does not own a personal computer, 40 percent are interested in getting on the Internet, Minkhorst said.
<P>Philips Consumer Communications, a player in the European cellular phone industry,  announced plans to aggressively compete in the United States market.
<P>     At the Consumer Electronics Show, PCC  announced several new communications products for the United States market. They include a hand-held personal computer and a screen phone with built-in computational power. PCC intends to take advantage of Philips&#39; technological experience and its brand strength to win a place in the United States market, said Mike McTighe, general manager.
<P>Philips has headquartered PCC&#39;s American operations in Dallas. The product development center is in Fremont, Calif. -- close to another Philips research and development facility in Sunnydale, Calif. 
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
