	<title>Business briefs</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper Business News">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif" alt="Knoxville News-Sentinel Online -- Business News" align=bottom border=0 width=595 height=176></a><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td align=left valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 10, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Business briefs</B></font><basefont size=6><!--SUBHEAD--></basefont></FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<h3>SunTrust earnings up 9.4%</h3>
<P>
<P>
<P>   SunTrust Banks Inc. said its fourth-quarter earnings rose 9.4 percent on strong loan growth and increased fees from customer accounts and trust services.
<P>   The nation&#39;s 19th-largest bank company said fourth-quarter net income rose to $158.5 million, or 72 cents a share, from $144.9 million, or 64 cents, in the same period last year.
<P>   That beat the average estimate of 71 cents a share of 20 analysts surveyed by IBES International Inc. 
<P>   Net interest income rose $28.3 million to $472.2 million in the fourth quarter from a year earlier as loans and securities rose 11.1 percent to $45.2 billion.  Noninterest income, led by service fees on accounts and trusts, rose 15 percent to $207 million from $179.4 million. 
<P>   Net income for 1996 rose $51.1 million, or 9 percent, to $616.6 million, or $2.76 a share, a record for the company. SunTrust Banks of Tennessee contributed $100.1 million to the total, up from $88.5 million in 1995
<P>
<P><h3>Civic center studied</h3>
<P>
<P>   LEBANON -- Chamber of Commerce officials are studying the feasibility of building a civic center.
<P>    It would seat up to 9,000 for concerts and could also be used for trade shows and conventions.
<P>    Chamber of Commerce officials have begun making trips to study such centers in other cities.
<P>    &#39;&#39;We don&#39;t have a facility that will seat over 300 people,&#39;&#39; said Mark Lee, the chamber president. &#39;&#39;At the Agricultural Center, they are turning groups away.&#39;&#39;
<P>    He said he hopes both public and private funds could be used to finance the center.
<P>
<P><h3>Disney extends Eisner pact</h3>
<P>
<P>    LOS ANGELES -- Walt Disney Co. has extended Michael D. Eisner&#39;s contract as chairman and chief executive for 10 years and granted him 8 million stock options it valued at $195 million.
<P>    Eisner also has stock options he can exercise at any time that Disney valued at $303 million as of Sept. 30, 1996, when the new contract took effect. The company valued other options not yet exercisable by Eisner at an additional $61 million.
<P>    The disclosures, made Thursday in Disney&#39;s proxy for its annual meeting next month, seemed certain to stir up more questions about whether the company&#39;s executive compensation is excessive.
<P>    The company proxy also confirmed that, as previously reported by The Associated Press, the severance awarded Michael Ovitz for 14 months as Disney president was $38.8 million in cash and options to buy 3 million Disney shares at $57 a share.
<P>
<P><h3>Names in the news</h3>
<P>
<P>   <B>Chad Lehman</B> has been promoted to senior project manager-estimator, and <B>Fred Atkins</B> has been promoted to geneal superintendent at J.S. Ridenour Construction Co. in Knoxville. The general contracting firm, with offices on Commercial Park Drive, also has hired <B>Kevin Alley</B> as senior project manager-estimator. . . . <B>C. Steven Maples </B>has been appointed distribution manager for the Metron Corporation. He previously served as ISO/Quality Manager with USCO Distribution Services, Inc. in Mascot. . . . <B>Carole Burnett Ireland </B>has been appointed account manager for Creative on Call, a sales, marketing and advertising company in Franklin Square. She previously was office manager for a Baptist Eye Institute medical office. . . . <B>Sheila L. Walker </B>has joined the staff of The Willow Group as client services coordinator. She most recently was employed as a technical assistant for a federal defense group in Johnston Atoll, Hawaii.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
