<head>
	<title>Sports briefs</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 10, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470><BASEFONT SIZE="6">
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Sports briefs</B></FONT><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<h3>Lady Vols&#39; guard Jolly given clearance to resume practice</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>   <B>Kellie Jolly&#39;s </B>preseason knee injury was not season-ending after all. The sophomore guard has been released by <B>Dr. William Youmans,</B> UT&#39;s orthopedic specialist, and returned to full practice Thursday.
<P>   Jolly, who is back on the court about three months after her Oct. 14 surgery to repair a torn anterior cruciate ligament in her right knee, could play in a game as early as Sunday against Kentucky.
<P>   &#39;&#39;If this had been a couple of weeks later, I&#39;d have been in a mental struggle,&#39;&#39; Jolly said, referring to choosing between a redshirt season and a comeback. &#39;&#39;I&#39;m still giving up a half year for this team. I want to come back.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Lady Vols trainer <B>Jenny Moshak </B>said no timetable is in place for Jolly&#39;s return to game action. That comeback will be determined by how Jolly&#39;s knee responds to more practice.
<P>
<P>In other college basketball news:
<P>* The Walters State Lady Senators (14-0) have moved up one spot to No. 17, in the NJCAA Division I poll.
<P>
<P><h3>Pro basketball</h3>
<P>
<P>* <B>Sheryl Swoopes, </B>perhaps the biggest star of the fledgling Women&#39;s NBA, will miss most of its inaugural season for a reason that never plagued the men&#39;s league: She is pregnant. Swoopes, 25, said she and husband <B>Eric Jackson,</B> her high school sweetheart whom she married in 1995, are looking forward to their new arrival in June.
<P>* <B>Red Auerbach </B>and <B>Red Holzman </B>will be coaching for the first time in decades in the Schick Rookie Game on Feb. 8 as part of the NBA All-Star Weekend in Cleveland.
<P>
<P><h3>Wrestling</h3>
<P>
<P>* Carson-Newman College remained No. 14 in the NCAA Division II rankings. Defending national champion Pittsburgh-Johnstown (Pa.) is ranked No. 1.
<P>
<P><h3>Boxing</h3>
<P>
<P>* The Golden Gloves Charities of Knoxville will hold a Golden Gloves show on Saturday, Jan. 18, at Golden Gloves Arena in Chilhowee Park, beginning at 7:30 p.m. Teams will come from Upper East Tennessee, Chattanooga, Virginia, Cleveland, Tellico and Athens. It will be the last local card until the East Tennessee Golden Gloves tournament Feb. 14-15. For information, phone 522-5885.
<P>* Heavyweight <B>Andrew Golota </B>received a two-year suspended prison sentence and a $7,000 fine for beating up a man in a May 1990 disco brawl in his native Poland.
<P>
<P><h3>Swimming</h3>
<P>
<P>* When Tennessee&#39;s Lady Vols, 13th-ranked nationally, go up against Auburn and Northwestern on Saturday at UT Student Aquatic Center, the meet will be in two segments. The first will begin at 10 a.m. After breaking for lunch, teams will resume at 4 p.m., with warmups starting at about 2:30. The Lady Vols returned to UT this week after training a week at Clearwater and Largo in Florida.
<P>
<P><h3>Tennis</h3>
<P>
<P>* No. 2 <B>Martina Hingis </B>of Switzerland and a revitalized <B>Jennifer Capriati </B>won their quarterfinal matches at the Sydney International. Capriati extended her winning streak with a 6-4, 6-1 victory over fellow American <B>Amy Frazier</B>.
<P>* In men&#39;s play at Sydney, top-seeded <B>Goran Ivanisevic </B>led the advance to the  semifinals with a 6-4, 6-2 victory over <B>Sandon Stolle </B>of Australia.
<P>* <B>Michael Chang </B>beat <B>Boris Becker </B>2-6, 6-4, 7-6 (7-5)  in the semifinals of the Colonial Classic and will try to win the event for the third consecutive year against either <B>Pete Sampras </B>and French Open champion <B>Yevgeny Kafelnikov </B>of Russia.
<P>
<P><h3>Football</h3>
<P>
<P>* The future of the Montreal franchise in the Canadian Football League should be decided in 30 days, the league has announced. The league has taken over the Montreal franchise from Maryland surgeon <B>Michael Gelfand</B>.
<P>* <B>Wilford &#39;&#39;Crazy Ray&#39;&#39; Jones,</B> 65, the fan who had been a fixture at Dallas Cowboys games since 1960, was hospitalized in fair condition after having his right foot amputated because of complications of diabetes.
<P>
<P><h3>Jurisprudence</h3>
<P>
<P>* Minnesota Timberwolves rookie <B>Stephon Marbury </B>is moving from the basketball court into Family Court, where he faces charges that he has failed to financially support his 22-month-old daughter in New York City.
<P>* Three-time Indianapolis 500 winner <B>Bobby Unser,</B> who survived two nights of a blizzard in the wilderness, now must face the legal fallout. A U.S. Forest Service official said that Unser was cited for violating the federal Wilderness Act by driving a snowmobile into a wilderness area.
<P>
<P><h3>Baseball</h3>
<P>
<P>* The Heartland League, an independent professional  league, will double in size for the 1997 season, expanding from four to eight teams. The new franchises include three Tennessee teams formerly of the Big South League -- the Clarksville Coyotes, Columbia Mules and (Winchester) Tennessee Tomahawks.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
