<head>
	<title>Cheering squad&#39;s discipline backed by board</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 09, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>Cheering squad&#39;s discipline backed by board</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Alcohol led to suspension</FONT></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Gina Stafford, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">A</FONT> group of junior varsity cheerleaders disciplined for alleged use of alcohol on a December school trip will remain suspended through the current academic year, Jefferson County officials decided Wednesday.
<P>   Parents of the seven girls accused of &#39;&#39;possession and consumption of alcoholic beverages&#39;&#39; had an opportunity at Tuesday night&#39;s Jefferson County School Board meeting to appeal the disciplinary action, an official said.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We had the regular board meeting, then heard from all these parents and everyone who wished to have input,&#39;&#39; Dr. Steve Burcham said on behalf of Superintendent Ken Scott, who was unavailable on Wednesday. Burcham is the school system&#39;s supervisor of elementary instruction.
<P>   &#39;&#39;All of (the parents) appealed the decision made by the disciplinary hearing committee and the board heard all their cases, and it was past midnight by the time they&#39;d decided to uphold the disciplinary hearing committee&#39;s decision.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Affected parents initially could have appealed the matter to the school board at its regular December meeting, Burcham said. That meeting, however, had to be cancelled when a minimum number of board members were unable to attend.
<P>   Parents who had to leave before Tuesday&#39;s meeting concluded were able to call officials Wednesday morning to learn their daughters would remain suspended.
<P>   The students involved were in Nashville for a cheerleading competition Dec. 7-8, according to Burcham. He said the trip occurred about the time the varsity cheerleading squad also was in Nashville for Jefferson County High&#39;s participation in a state championship football game.
<P>   None of the varsity cheerleaders apparently was involved in the incident.
<P>   &#39;&#39;The trip the junior varsity cheerleaders were on had nothing to do with the football game,&#39;&#39; Burcham  said.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Apparently, there was evidence that the young ladies involved had violated policy against possession and consumption of alcoholic beverages at any school function.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Burcham said he couldn&#39;t provide details of the offenses or what further recourse is available to affected students.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
