<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>School board OKs building plan</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 09, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>School board OKs building plan</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> 3 options to be sent to county executive</FONT></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By David Keim, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">K</FONT>nox County school officials are leaving it up to County Executive Tommy Schumpert and County Commission to decide how much money to spend on school construction for the next five years.
<P>   The school board voted 7-1 Wednesday to send three options to Schumpert -- a $110.9 million base request, $115.9 million that will get some projects done sooner and a top request of $181 million.
<P>   The building program -- a source of conflict between the school board and commission for several years -- aims to keep pace with growing enrollments, to upgrade deteriorating schools from the defunct city system and to provide facilities for magnet programs aimed at desegregating the schools.
<P>   Some commissioners already have indicated the school board&#39;s top request is unlikely to be granted, but school officials hope to get any new money they can.
<P>   &#39;&#39;The reason we need more money is to do the projects more quickly,&#39;&#39; Superintendent Allen Morgan said Wednesday.
<P>   &#39;&#39;These are three requests that I believe give people very accurate information on what we are able to do with the monies we have available today and what we would be able to do if we get additional funds.&#39;&#39;
<P>   If commissioners agree to fund one of the school board&#39;s two more expensive requests, Sequoyah Elementary, Holston Middle, Whittle Springs Middle, Karns Middle, Brickey Primary and a new Northwest Elementary school at Hardin Valley would be completed faster.
<P>   Schumpert will weigh school needs against other county projects in the five-year capital plan, like roads and a new downtown justice center.
<P>   &#39;&#39;In the next three to four weeks we will be looking to see what kind of (debt) capacity we do have available as we update our plan,&#39;&#39; Schumpert said. &#39;&#39;It&#39;s hard to say at this point how much additional money we might be able to commit to schools. We do think there are some additional dollars, but there are some other requests also.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Asked whether the county might approve the top request of $181 million, Schumpert said, &#39;&#39;That&#39;d be a pretty extreme number I think, but until we really look at our numbers and our financial adviser gives us our capacity, what we could do, that&#39;s kind of premature to comment on.&#39;&#39;
<P>   School board member Steve Hunley was the only member to vote against the superintendent&#39;s proposal. Member Cecil Kelly was absent.
<P>   &#39;&#39;There are no specific dollars for specific schools,&#39;&#39; Hunley said. &#39;&#39;If I go to Home Federal and say, &#39;I want to borrow $70,000,&#39; what are they going to ask me? (They&#39;ll ask), &#39;What are you gonna do with the money?&#39; &#39;&#39;
<P>   In the same way, he wondered, &#39;&#39;How can I expect (commissioners) to allocate $70 million (extra) when I haven&#39;t told them what I&#39;m going to do with the money?&#39;&#39;
<P>   The $181 million request includes the $110.9 million base, plus $6.9 million for Karns Middle, Brickey and Hardin Valley; $36.5 million for &#39;&#39;future projects to be defined;&#39;&#39; $25.5 million for capital maintenance; and a $1.2 million contingency.
<P>   In past years, commissioners have criticized school officials for putting specific dollar figures on projects, then discovering they require more money.
<P>   Darlene Smolik, controller with the Public Building Authority, which is helping the schools with the building program, said it&#39;s hard to pin specific costs to specific schools because material costs vary from year to year. Also, it&#39;s hard to predict school needs three or four years in advance, and a systemwide master plan isn&#39;t yet completed.
<P>   The $181 million request will stabilize school construction spending at about $36 million a year. If commission doesn&#39;t approve more funding, money available for school construction will plummet from $32.9 million this year to $7.2 million in fiscal 2000.
<P>   County Commission Chairman John Griess, elected in 1994, expects commissioners to want plenty of information.
<P>   &#39;&#39;My limited experience with County Commission and school board matters is it needs to be justified and specific before they make a decision to vote for it, so somebody&#39;s going to have to be specific with County Commission. . . .&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

