<head>
	<title>Icy, dicey</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 09, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>Icy, dicey</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Sleet is expected to give way to rain</FONT></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Stan DeLozier, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">E</FONT>ast Tennesseans went to bed Wednesday night not knowing if they would need an umbrella or ice skates when they awoke.
<P>   The National Weather Service was predicting sleet mixed with freezing rain with some accumulation likely. However, in Knox, Blount, Loudon, Roane, Sevier and Union Counties, the precipitation was expected to change to all rain during the night.
<P>   Sleet was reported in some parts of Knox County shortly after 4 p.m. Knoxville Public Service Director Bob Whetsel said the regular night road crews were prepared to monitor bridges and overpasses overnight and to deal with any icing that occurs.
<P>   Up to 65 day shift employees were placed on standby.
<P>   According to the National Weather Service, the outlook for counties north and east of Knox is not as optimistic. Sleet and freezing rain is expected to continue this morning before changing to all rain.
<P>   Counties southwest of Knoxville were expected to get mostly rain, although some sleet was falling in the Chattanooga area by mid-afternoon. At Crossville, Cumberland County officials dismissed school at 12:30 p.m. CST, and freezing rain and light snow began falling across the Cumberland Plateau a short time later.
<P>   Many other schools in Middle and West Tennessee also closed early as the rain, sleet and snow moved in from the west.
<P>   Look for low temperatures this morning in the low 30s. Occasional rain is anticipated today with the mercury creeping up to around 40.
<P>   Forecasters said the brunt of the storm would hit the northwest corner of Tennessee along the Missouri and Kentucky borders by late Wednesday. Three to five inches of snow was predicted for that region.
<P>   In Memphis, forecasters warned of an expected ice build-up of as much of a quarter of an inch on trees and power lines.
<P>   At least one weather-related death occurred in Tennessee Tuesday. A Middle Tennessee woman discovered dead beside a creek died of hypothermia, authorities said.
<P>   Sharon Gail Farris, 45, of Columbia was found by a motorist next to the Little Bigby Creek.
<P>   Investigators said she had been riding around and drinking with friends before she died. They said the group&#39;s pickup truck got stuck and Farris was left behind when the vehicle was able to drive away.
<P>   Cold temperatures are expected to dominate the weather picture for the weekend.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

	<P><center><font size=2>Return to </font><a href="/"><font size=2>Main</font></a><font size=2>. Copyright &#169; 1996 The Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size=2>webmaster</font></a><font size=2>.</font></center></p>
</body>
