<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>New security gun is truly stunning device</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i>January 09, 1997</i> </td>
        <td width="470"><font size="6"><b>New security gun is
        truly stunning device</b></font><font size="5"><br>
        Deputy/pal volunteers as target</font><table border="0"
        cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="200" align="right">
            <tr>
                <td width="175"><img
                src="../images/010997stungunPE.jpg" width="180"
                height="318"><p><img
                src="../../images/v3/credits/PEcredit.gif"
                width="144" height="21"><br>
                <font size="2"><strong>Jefferson County Sheriff's
                Deputy Monty Bowen goes down after receiving a
                shock from an Air-Taser stun gun during a
                demonstration Wednesday in White Pine.</strong></font></p>
                </td>
            </tr>
        </table>
        <p><font size="2"><i>By Morgan Simmons, News-Sentinel
        staff writer</i></font></p>
        <p><br>
        </p>
        <p>WHITE PINE, Tenn. -- Rick Clark could have used a
        promotional video tape to demonstrate the effectiveness
        of the Air-Taser stun gun, but then he would have missed
        out on the fun of shooting his friend. </p>
        <p>Clark owns R.R. Distributors, a security company in
        White Pine that sells devices such as pepper spray, alarm
        systems, and stun guns. To demonstrate the Air-Taser, a
        new type of stun gun, he called on his friend Monty
        Bowen, a deputy with the Jefferson County Sheriff's
        Department, who agreed to let Clark zap him in the back. </p>
        <p>''If this will help home defense and show people
        there's an alternative to having firearms in the house,
        it'll be worth it,'' said Bowen, moments before the
        Air-Taser buckled his knees. </p>
        <p>Unlike conventional stun guns, which must make direct
        contact with the assailant, the Air-Taser uses a gas
        propellent to fire two metal probes as far as 15 feet.
        The probes are attached to thin wires, and deliver a
        high-voltage, low-amperage shock with an 86-percent
        knockdown ratio. </p>
        <p>At 1 p.m., Wednesday, a small crowd gathered in front
        of the White Pine Police Headquarters to witness the live
        demonstration. </p>
        <p>''Though the shock is painful, the device does not
        rely on pain,'' said Clark. ''The electricity makes the
        body reverse what it's doing. All the muscles collapse,
        and you hit the ground.'' </p>
        <p>Clark said he would donate an Air-Taser to the White
        Pine Police Department. To satisfy his own curiosity, he
        asked his wife to shoot him with the Air-Taser before the
        demonstration. </p>
        <p>''I put on a heavy blue-jean jacket, and she shot me
        in the back,'' he said. ''In two seconds I hit the
        ground, flopping like a bluegill, screaming at her to
        shut it off. </p>
        <p>The Air-Taser is set to automatically shock for 30
        seconds, pausing every eight seconds to let the victim
        catch his breath. </p>
        <p>A few minutes after 1 p.m. Clark fired the Air-Taser
        at Bowen's back, and Bowen, who weighs 196 pounds,
        dropped like a sack of laundry. </p>
        <p>The ordeal ended after a few seconds when Bowen, lying
        prone on the ground, yelled at Clark to turn it off. </p>
        <p>''That felt like a lifetime,'' said Bowen, raising
        himself to one knee. ''I lost control. I thought I was
        going to pass out.'' </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

<hr size="5">

<p align="center"><font size="2">Return to </font><a href="/"><font
size="2">Main</font></a><font size="2">. Copyright © 1996 The
Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a
href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size="2">webmaster</font></a><font
size="2">.</font></p>
