<head>
	<title>Dispatcher facing discipline as result of Koella case probe</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 09, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Dispatcher facing discipline as result of Koella case probe</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> THP actions ruled proper</FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">T</FONT>he Tennessee Highway Patrol properly handled the investigation of a fatal traffic accident involving state Sen. Carl Koella, according to internal documents released by the Department of Safety.
<P>   The investigation did find, however, that a dispatcher provided &#39;&#39;misleading&#39;&#39; information to the media and withheld information.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We are taking appropriate action to correct that situation, including disciplinary action,&#39;&#39; Safety Commissioner Mike Greene wrote in a Dec. 30 letter to The News-Sentinel.
<P>   Additionally, as a result of the investigation, the Department of Safety internal affairs unit has been relocated under Greene&#39;s office.
<P>   The investigation stemmed from a complaint by The News-Sentinel about the withholding of information by the dispatcher after the Oct. 22 wreck in Blount County.
<P>   Koella&#39;s van turned in front of motorcyclist Terry R. Barnard, 52, on Highway 321 at the entrance of Tuckaleechee Campground, which also leads Koella&#39;s residence in Townsend.
<P>   The motorcycle struck the right rear of the van, and Barnard was thrown from his bike and died. Koella left the scene and was arrested nearly four hours later at his home.
<P>   When a News-Sentinel reporter called the THP office in Knoxville to inquire about the accident, she was told by dispatcher Vena K. Carter the THP was not working a fatal accident in Blount County.
<P>   The Department of Safety internal investigation found that Carter later gave varying answers to other media inquiries about the wreck, including she had not been given information, she did not have the accident report completed and the troopers were still working the wreck.
<P>   Carter was to have referred all media calls to a THP lieutenant, but she didn&#39;t.
<P>   &#39;&#39;She did not follow instructions,&#39;&#39; Greene said. Carter is now on medical leave.
<P>   After an initial internal investigation, Greene asked the Tennessee Bureau of Investigation to join the probe.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We felt more questions needed to be asked, so we involved the TBI,&#39;&#39; Greene said.
<P>   As a result, the internal affairs unit now reports directly to Greene&#39;s office. 
<P>   It is being supervised by Brian Grisham, an attorney and assistant to Greene.
<P>   Formerly, the unit reported to assistant commissioner Col. Jerry Scott, who is in charge of the THP.
<P>   Hardy Mays, deputy to the governor, said the relocation was necessary &#39;&#39;because the appearance was wrong.&#39;&#39;
<P>   &#39;&#39;If you&#39;re going to have an internal affairs division, it ought to be separate from the officers it investigates.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Koella faces a preliminary hearing Jan. 28 on a charge of leaving the scene of a fatal accident.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
