<head>
	<title>2 Maryland sex-abuse suspects arrested here</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 09, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>2 Maryland sex-abuse suspects arrested here</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Authorities say foster-care ruse used to gain 3 victims</FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Randy Kenner, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">T</FONT>wo men who fled Maryland in 1994 after being charged with the long-running sexual abuse of three boys have been arrested in Knoxville.
<P>   Samuel L. Glover, 49, and Marshall Monquie Kirkpatrick, 32, allegedly have been posing as father and son and living under assumed names in a North Knoxville trailer park. 
<P>   They were arrested in separate locations on Tuesday by FBI agents.
<P>   The agents were acting on a tip the two were here after they were featured on a November episode of TV&#39;s &#39;&#39;Unsolved Mysteries&#39;&#39; program.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We&#39;ve been looking for them for the past two-and-a-half years,&#39;&#39; said Marcie Wogan, a deputy state&#39;s attorney in Carroll County, Md. &#39;&#39;We were desperate to find them.&#39;&#39;
<P>   She said authorities there heard the two men were everywhere from Canada and Mexico to nearby Pennsylvania.
<P>   The two spent at least the last year in Knoxville, according to FBI agent Scott Nowinski, spokesman for the Knoxville FBI office.
<P>
<P>      According to Wogan and Maryland court documents, the pair face more than two dozen sexual assault and child abuse charges in Carroll County. Three alleged victims are involved.
<P>    Wogan said at least a dozen male children had been assigned to Glover, acting as a foster parent, by the Maryland Department of Social Services.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We&#39;re certain there are other victims,&#39;&#39; Wogan said.
<P>    She added the alleged victims&#39; placement in a foster home &#39;&#39;was supposed to be improving their lives. It&#39;s not a pretty story.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Glover allegedly posed as a minister in Maryland to reach the arrangement to act as a foster parent. According to the times the alleged offenses occurred -- the late 1980s and early 1990s -- and the dates of birth of the three victims, all of them would have been in their teens.
<P>   Wogan said authorities believe Glover and Kirkpatrick to be homosexual lovers and &#39;&#39;pedophiles.&#39;&#39;
<P>   She said one of the foster children told authorities he felt like &#39;&#39;he was a slave, he was living in slavery. It was horrific, the conditions.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Wogan said the three alleged victims were sexually abused, beaten and forced to live in filth.
<P>   &#39;&#39;They forced the kids to do things . . . and to watch,&#39;&#39; she said.
<P>   Social services made periodic home visits to the Glover residence but informed him prior to visits, Wogan said.
<P>   &#39;&#39;The kids told us when the DSS called, the place was cleaned up, the boyfriend would leave and they were allowed to take baths,&#39;&#39; she said.
<P>   She said the alleged victims were terrified of the pair, were threatened and were told not to tell anyone. 
<P>   The police investigation followed an anonymous tip.
<P>   Glover and Kirkpatrick were initially held on $75,000 bonds, according to court documents, but the bonds were later reduced to $10,000 and the two men left Maryland after being released on bond.
<P>   Wogan said the Maryland state&#39;s attorney&#39;s office approached &#39;&#39;Unsolved Mysteries&#39;&#39; about featuring the two men in the hopes it would produce some leads.
<P>   Nowinski said the Nov. 22 episode produced numerous leads throughout the country, including &#39;&#39;several leads in the Knoxville area.&#39;&#39;
<P>   One of them was that Kirkpatrick worked at a Knoxville convenience store.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We determined that he was no longer working at that store but at another store,&#39;&#39; Nowinski said.
<P>   David E. Parker, assistant special agent in charge of the Knoxville FBI office, said Kirkpatrick was arrested around 2 p.m. at work and denied being the wanted man. His identity was confirmed by his fingerprints, however, officers said.
<P>    Glover was arrested at the pair&#39;s trailer at about 6 p.m.
<P>   
<P>   Both men face possible life sentences, according to Wogan.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

	<P><center><font size=2>Return to </font><a href="/"><font size=2>Main</font></a><font size=2>. Copyright &#169; 1996 The Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size=2>webmaster</font></a><font size=2>.</font></center></p>
</body>
