<head>
	<title>City to clarify role in Haley project</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 09, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>City to clarify role in Haley project</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Jim Balloch, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">K</FONT>noxville City Council will review what the city&#39;s role is, and should be, in helping a private group develop the proposed Haley Heritage Square in Morningside Park.
<P>   Council will meet in a workshop at 5 p.m. today at the request of Evon Easley, project director for Citizens for Haley Heritage Square (CHHS).
<P>   &#39;&#39;We hope the city will recognize us as the developmental agency for this project and continue to work with us,&#39;&#39; said Easley. &#39;&#39;We feel the city needs to clarify what its role is going to be.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Haley, author of the highly acclaimed &#39;&#39;Roots&#39;&#39; and other works, died in 1992. Originally from West Tennessee, he later made his home in Norris and was an adjunct professor at the University of Tennessee.
<P>   In December, council unanimously approved payment of $168,700 to sculptor Tina Allen for completion of a 13-foot, 6,500-pound statue of Haley, and agreed to accept a $200,000 grant from the state Legislature for Haley Heritage Square.
<P>   Easley said the statue purchase was made outside the city&#39;s original agreement with CHHS, and before CHHS was able to renew its own contract with the sculptor. She also said that the city should turn the $200,000 over to CHHS, since it was CHHS that persuaded the Legislature to provide the money.
<P>   CHHS says its goal is for Haley Heritage Square to eventually include a 300-seat amphitheater and a genealogical research center. CHHS has recently received a federal grant to pay for a consultant to develop a marketing and tourism strategy for the project, Easley said.
<P>    City Council earlier authorized the expenditure of up to $375,000, mainly to buy land on the south side of Dandridge Avenue to enlarge Morningside Park to accommodate the Haley project. The sculptors&#39; fee will be paid out of that $375,000, city Finance Director Randy Vineyard said.
<P>   Vineyard said the $200,000 state grant may have to be used to pay for the statue&#39;s base.
<P>   &#39;&#39;It&#39;s going to have to be mounted on something,&#39;&#39; he said.
<P>    Sculpture of the Haley statue has been completed, but it has yet to be cast in bronze, Easley said. It is now expected that the statue will be delivered to Knoxville this summer.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

