	<title>Trial for last Job Corps killing defendant set to start Jan. 21</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 09, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Trial for last Job Corps killing defendant set to start Jan. 21</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By John North, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">L</FONT>awyers confirmed Wednesday they are ready to proceed with a Jan. 21 trial for the last of three defendants charged in the Job Corps murder case.
<P>   Unless he reaches an agreement with prosecutors in the interim, Tadaryl D. Shipp, 19, will face a sequestered jury in Knox County Criminal Court. The trial, which is expected to take one to two weeks, could feature an appearance by co-defendant and death row inmate Christa Gail Pike, 20.
<P>   Criminal Court Judge Mary Beth Leibowitz told lawyers Wednesday she wants to try to select a jury in Knox County before looking elsewhere for a panel, as defense attorney Chris Coffey has requested. Coffey argues the sensational 1995 murder case has generated so much publicity his client will have a hard time finding an unbiased jury.
<P>   Pike, Shipp&#39;s girlfriend, was convicted and sentenced to death in March for the bloody and violent murder of 19-year-old Colleen A. Slemmer of Orange Park, Fla. Shipp has confessed to helping Pike cut Slemmer and carve a pentagram in her chest Jan. 12, 1995, near a jogging path in a remote area of the University of Tennessee Agricultural campus.
<P>   Shipp, Pike, Slemmer and Shadolla R. Peterson, another co-defendant, were students at the Knoxville Job Corps Center. Federal officials closed the Dale Avenue facility in 1995 in part because of the slaying.
<P>   Prosecutors and Coffey have discussed a possible plea deal for Shipp, who could face life in prison without parole. By law, the prosecution cannot seek the death penalty against the Memphis man because he was a juvenile when Slemmer was killed.
<P>   Jury selection last year for Pike took about a week. Considering the publicity that arose from her trial, Coffey said he expects it will take at least that long to pick a Knox County panel.
<P>   Deputy District Attorney General Bill Crabtree agreed the case has generated publicity. The prosecutor said he prefers to try to seat a jury from here first.
<P>   At Coffey&#39;s request, Leibowitz agreed to prepare an order transporting Pike for the trial. Pike, who is at the Nashville Prison for Women, told Shipp in a letter last year she would testify for him.
<P>   Her case is on appeal, however, and defense attorney William C. Talman said he would advise her not to testify for Shipp. Her execution, once set for this month, has been stayed pending court appeals.
<P>   Shadolla R. Peterson, 20, who was with Shipp and Pike when Slemmer was killed, was allowed to enter a plea last year that saved her from going to prison. She is on probation and lives in southeast Tennessee.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
