	<title>Board OKs $75,000 for land at Bearden High</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 09, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Board OKs $75,000 for land at Bearden High</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By David Keim, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">I</FONT>t appears Knox County is prepared to give a West Knoxville property owner a hefty profit for 11.5 acres adjacent to Bearden High School.
<P>   The Knox County School Board voted 8-0 Wednesday to spend $750,000 on land that will initially provide student parking and additional room for growth at the crowded school.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We&#39;ve had three people look at it, give us independent appraisals, and they say it&#39;s a very fair price,&#39;&#39; Superintendent Allen Morgan said. The contract needs to be finalized, and the purchase could go to County Commission for approval this month.
<P>   The acreage is part of a 22.4-acre tract along Gleason Road that was owned by East Tennessee Natural Gas Co. until Dec. 14, 1995.
<P>   That&#39;s when Harry and Mary Lane purchased the 22.4 acres for $400,000, according to a deed filed in the Register of Deeds office. The next day -- Dec. 15, 1995 -- Harry Lane transferred the acreage to Michael E. Schaad, trustee, for $475,000.
<P>  Schaad could not be reached Wednesday, but school officials said they&#39;re getting a fair deal by paying $750,000 for about half the tract, which is the last undeveloped property adjacent to Bearden High.
<P>   The school system isn&#39;t getting a retention pond that could present liability problems, and it&#39;s avoiding the risk that the land&#39;s value will rise if property nearer to Gleason Road is developed.
<P>   &#39;&#39;If Bearden is to remain a viable school for the next 25 to 30 years, we&#39;ll need additional auxiliary space,&#39;&#39; Morgan said.
<P>   School board member Sam Anderson said condemning the property isn&#39;t a real option since the county still would end up paying at least the appraised value.
<P>   A spokesman for East Tennessee Natural Gas Co., said the company sold the entire 22.4 acre tract in December 1995 for &#39;&#39;well under&#39;&#39; appraised value.
<P>   Joe O&#39;Steen, a right-of-way agent for El Paso Energy Corp. in Brentwood, which operates East Tennessee Natural Gas, declined to give a specific appraisal amount and didn&#39;t know why the firm sold below the appraisal.
<P>   He did say the firm no longer needed the property because of scaled back operations and the move of regional headquarters to Brentwood.
<P>   
<P>   
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
