            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>East Tennessee briefs</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><h3>Slain girl&#39;s family boost campaign against judge</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>    A northwestern Tennessee couple has received 180 letters in their 10-day-old campaign against U.S. District Court Judge John Nixon of Nashville.
<P>    Mickey and Charlotte Stout of Greenfield (about 15 miles south of Martin in Weakley County) are seeking to have Nixon investigated for overturning the 1981 conviction of Robert Glen Coe. 
<P>   Coe was sentenced to death in the 1979 rape and murder of 8-year-old Cary Ann Medlin, Charlotte Stout&#39;s daughter.
<P>    Meanwhile, a Jan. 19 rally is scheduled for Greenfield&#39;s high school gymnasium to begin a petition drive against the judge.
<P>    Nixon in November cited several mistakes by the trial judge in overturning the conviction and sentence of Coe.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Teenage murder suspect free on $70,000 bond</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>      A 16-year-old murder suspect -- jailed over the weekend after he was hospitalized for treatment of gunshot wounds -- is free after posting a $70,000 bond.
<P>   Melvin &#39;&#39;Little Melvin&#39;&#39; Davis was released Tuesday from the Knox County Jail after posting bond on charges of aggravated robbery and aggravated assault, jail records show.
<P>   Davis had been jailed Sunday after being released from Baptist Hospital of East Tennessee. 
<P>   Davis, also known as Melvin Tate, had been shot on Christmas Eve, allegedly by reputed fellow gang member William &#39;&#39;Junebug&#39;&#39; Martin.
<P>   Davis, who police contend is a member of the East Side gang, is charged in the May 18 shooting death of Brittany Shenice Daniels, 5. 
<P>   Brittany was shot as she played on a sidewalk in the Lonsdale Homes housing project.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Report: Daughter heard accused killer&#39;s threat</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>    BRISTOL -- A pharmacist accused of killing his wife told her she deserved to die, according to a report involving one of his daughters.
<P>    Harry David Johnson of Bristol is charged with fatally shooting Katherine Johnson, 46, in the face in 1995.
<P>    His trial is scheduled for Feb. 3.
<P>    Prosecutors are expected to use the psychological report to rebut Johnson&#39;s insanity claims.  
<P>   In the report by  Dr. James C. Ballenger of the Medical College of South Carolina at Charleston, one of the couple&#39;s daughters says she overheard her father say, &#39;&#39;This is what you deserve. I&#39;m going to shoot you in the face.&#39;&#39; 
<P>   The daughter told Ballenger she then heard shots.
<P>    The report said Johnson became violently angry when his wife drank and was concerned about the public image of her drinking.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Putnam man accused of taking tracker device</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>   COOKEVILLE -- A Cookeville man is in jail after being accused of stealing a $500 electronic device he was wearing so his probation officer could monitor his whereabouts.
<P>   Robert D. Fulton was arrested at a residence New Year&#39;s Eve after authorities received a tip he was in town.
<P>   He reportedly had skipped out on his probation last April and allegedly took the bracelet with him.
<P>   Fulton, a construction worker, had been on probation since December 1995. Prior to that, he was jailed on a six-year sentence for various crimes, including theft, possession of marijuana, introducing contraband into the jail, burglary and passing a forged instrument.
<P>   He is jailed without bond in connection with violating probation and theft.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Chattanooga officer&#39;s vest deflects bullet</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>    CHATTANOOGA -- A police officer shot in the chest during a traffic stop Wednesday lived, thanks to his bulletproof vest.
<P>    Officer Reginald Finley stopped three youths about 5:30 a.m. after noticing their 1979 Oldsmobile Cutlass had no license plate, police spokesman Eyo Efiom said.
<P>    As the officer sat in his car, one of the youths shouted at him and asked why they were being stopped.    One of them pulled a handgun and fired three times at Finley, Efiom said. One bullet hit the front of Finley&#39;s bulletproof vest.
<P>    The shooter and one youth ran from the car while the driver sped away.    Finley called his dispatcher to report he&#39;d been shot but said the vest deflected the bullet and he was not wounded.     Police were still searching for the three youths.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
