	<title>Business briefs</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper Business News">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif" alt="Knoxville News-Sentinel Online -- Business News" align=bottom border=0 width=595 height=176></a><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td align=left valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 09, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Business briefs</B></font><basefont size=6><!--SUBHEAD--></basefont></FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<h3>Food City relocates in North Gate</h3>
<P>
<P>   The Food City supermarket in North Gate Plaza will relocate and expand to the Winn-Dixie location in the same shopping center, K-VA-T Food Stores Inc., the parent company, announced Wednesday.
<P>   Winn-Dixie closed in the location Wednesday.
<P>   The location will be remodeled into a &#39;&#39;state-of-the-art superstore&#39;&#39;, said Steve Trout, executive vice president for the Knoxville division of K-VA-T Food Stores Inc., parent of Food City.
<P>   The present Food City store will remain open until the new location opens. No date was given for the opening.
<P>
<P><h3>Fayetteville plant closing to idle 109</h3>
<P>
<P>    FAYETTEVILLE, Tenn. -- A plant that makes specialty yarn will close in March, putting 109 people out of work.
<P>    Elk Spinners Inc., a division of Uniblend Spinners, has made yarn in the same location since the turn of the century.
<P>    Randy Jenkins, Uniblend&#39;s vice president of manufacturing, blamed &#39;&#39;slow business conditions&#39;&#39; in the textile industry for the plant closing.
<P>    Elk Spinners made yarn that goes into home furnishings, apparel and other specialty product markets. The mill will close March 10, said Jim Gray, Lincoln County&#39;s industrial recruiter.
<P>    Gray said the company approached city and county officials in early December requesting financial aid to keep the plant afloat.
<P>    &#39;&#39;We developed a package of low-interest loans for them because the understanding was, if they could modernize the plant, they could dig themselves out of this hole,&#39;&#39; he said. &#39;&#39;But their creditors were unwilling to extend that kind of capital.&#39;&#39;
<P>    In addition to the Fayetteville, Tenn., plant, Uniblend announced it would close its Fayetteville, N.C., plant. About 160 people work at that plant. Uniblend is based in Union, S.C.
<P>
<P><h3>Philips rethinks control of Grundig</h3>
<P>
<P>    EINDHOVEN, Netherlands -- Philips Electronics NV announced Wednesday it would back away from control of Germany&#39;s Grundig AG to be a passive minority shareholder in the money-losing consumer electronics maker.
<P>    Grundig&#39;s years of losses have been a drag on profit at Philips, which has run Grundig despite owning merely 30 percent of the company.
<P>    Analysts said the move fits with the tough cost-cutting stance of Philips&#39; new chief executive, Cor Boonstra. When Boonstra took office in October, he vowed to slash expenses and said Philips&#39; massive restructuring of the early 1990s, which cut 60,000 jobs, hadn&#39;t gone far enough.
<P>    Philips shares rose more than 3 percent after the Grundig news was announced. The company had said in February it would no longer cover Grundig&#39;s losses, which analysts estimate at about 300 million German marks ($191.4 million) in 1996.
<P>
<P><h3>Names in the news</h3>
<P>
<P>   <B>Brenda Roan </B>has been named director of information systems at Clayton Homes Inc. Roan previously worked as an independent consultant and also served as director of information systems for Coca Cola Enterprises in Knoxville. . . . <B><B>Mitch Burnett</B>, a 13-year real estate sales veteran employed since 1992 at Knoxville&#39;s Volunteer Realty, has been named managing broker of that firm&#39;s Farragut office. Burnett, a Farragut resident and University of Tennessee graduate, previously was broker-owner of Gallery of Homes in Farragut. . . .<B> Andrew &#39;&#39;Drew&#39;&#39; Seery</B> is the new owner of the local franchise of BW-3 Grill & Pub in the Old City. He relocated from Cincinnati. Previously, he was in pharmaceutical sales.
<P>
<P>
<P>
