<head>
	<title>Sports briefs</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 09, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470><BASEFONT SIZE="6">
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Sports briefs</B></FONT><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<h3>NFL may help CFL with money, players</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>    
<P>    The NFL is discussing plans to bankroll the struggling Canadian Football League as a player-development league, The Toronto Star has reported.
<P>    The newspaper, citing unidentified sources, said the NFL would provide a limited number of players per team for the entire season. The NFL would pay the salaries of those players as well as provide marketing money.
<P>    &#39;&#39;There have been preliminary discussions along marketing lines with some player development discussed,&#39;&#39; Toronto Argonauts president <B>Bob Nicholson </B>said. &#39;&#39;But to suggest we are selling the league to the NFL, well, that certainly is not our intention.&#39;&#39;
<P>    <B>Jeff Giles,</B> the CFL&#39;s chief operating officer, also confirmed &#39;&#39;discussions are taking place,&#39;&#39; but offered no details. The newspaper, which said a deal could be announced late this month, added that the NFL has no interest in changing the CFL&#39;s rules or Canadian-content regulations.
<P>
<P><h3>Golf</h3>
<P>
<P>* The Mercedes Championship, the first PGA Tour event of 1997, was scheduled to begin today in Carlsbad, Calif.. The tournament is limited to the 33 players who won tournaments last year. The lone absentee is <B>Greg Norman</B> (sore back).
<P>
<P><h3>College football</h3>
<P>
<P>* Alabama defensive tackle <B>Michael Myers </B>will return to the Crimson Tide for his senior season, the Mobile (Ala.) Register reported. Linebacker <B>Dwayne Rudd </B>was expected to announce his plans today.
<P>* Another first-team All-America honor for Carson-Newman linebacker <B>Mike Clowney</B>. This time it&#39;s on The Football Gazette&#39;s NCAA Division II team. C-N junior strong safety <B>Jon Jon Simmons </B>and freshman return specialist <B>Jacques Rumph </B>were third-team selections.
<P>* Arizona State&#39;s <B>Bruce Snyder </B>was chosen NCAA Division I-A coach of year by  the American Football Coaches Association.
<P>* Kentucky&#39;s 1997 schedule has two consecutive open dates after the season opener against Louisville on Aug. 30. The open dates were created by Cincinnati dropping its game because of scheduling commitments in Conference USA.
<P>
<P><h3>Swimming</h3>
<P>
<P>* Tennessee&#39;s Lady Vols remain No. 13 in the Speedo America&#39;s College Swimming Coaches Poll released this week. Stanford is No. 1, followed by SMU, Southern Cal, Georgia and Michigan. Florida is No. 7 and Auburn No. 11.
<P>
<P><h3>Women&#39;sbasketball</h3>
<P>
<P>* George Mason freshman point guard <B>Kristeena Alexander </B>set an NCAA Division I women&#39;s record for most free throws in a game after a 20-for-20 performance.
<P>* Only four Sullivan (Ky.) College players scored Wednesday night, but it was enough to defeat the host Roane State women 65-59. Sullivan (18-0) remained undefeated and Roane State dropped to 4-7.
<P>* The Walters State Lady Senators (14-0) have moved up one spot, to No. 17, in the NJCAA Division I poll.
<P>
<P><h3>Wrestling</h3>
<P>
<P>* Carson-Newman College remained No. 14 in the NCAA Division II rankings. Defending national champion Pittsburgh-Johnstown (Pa.), which opened the season with a victory over C-N, is ranked No. 1.
<P>
<P><h3>Boxing</h3>
<P>
<P>* Boxer <B>Christy Martin </B>says someone is giving promoter <B>Don King </B>false information. King announced last weekend that the popular Martin would not fight in Nashville this Saturday because of a mouth injury. However, Martin said she is not hurt. 
<P>
<P><h3>Colleges</h3>
<P>
<P>* The number of black athletes enrolling in Division I schools that grant scholarships is on the rebound after falling off when Proposition 48 was adopted 10 years ago, the NCAA said. The first long-term study of the academic standards rule&#39;s impact was released on the same day the NCAA was hit with a federal lawsuit alleging discrimination against black athletes from the use of SAT scores to determine freshman eligibility.
<P>
<P><h3>Baseball</h3>
<P>
<P>* <B>Brett Butler</B>, 39, whose 1996 season for the Los Angeles Dodgers was cut short by a bout with throat cancer and a fractured hand, has decided to go ahead with his attempt to play this season.
<P>* Cleveland Indians pitcher <B>Jose Mesa </B>and a friend pleaded innocent in Lakewood, Ohio, to charges of gross sexual imposition. A preliminary hearing is set for Jan. 17 and both men remain free on $5,000 bonds.
<P>* First baseman <B>Eric Karros,</B> who had been eligible for free agency after the 1997 season, agreed to a $20 million, four-year contract with the Dodgers. He  hit .260 last season and set career highs with 34 homers and 111 RBI.
<P>* The Toronto Blue Jays have signed 16-year-old shortstop <B>Josephang Bernhardt </B>for a $1.1 million bonus, a record for a Dominican amateur.
<P>
<P><h3>Jurisprudence</h3>
<P>
<P>* Former Pittsburgh Steelers quarterback <B>Joe Gilliam, </B>46, has been placed on six months probation after pleading guilty to a misdemeanor drug charge in Nashville. He was found holding a pipe with crack cocaine and admitted he had smoked from it.
<P>
<P>
<P>
