<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>Justices question ex-judge&#39;s status in W. Tennessee sex assault case</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 08, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>Justices question ex-judge&#39;s status in W. Tennessee sex assault case</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Misconduct stirs hourlong debate</FONT></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By The Associated Press</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">W</FONT>ASHINGTON -- A closely watched Supreme Court dispute over a rogue West Tennessee judge and the Constitution&#39;s protection against sexual assaults by public officials took a curious turn Tuesday.
<P>    The justices were expected to focus on whether freedom from sexual attack ever has been recognized as a constitutional right. But most of their questions during an hourlong argument session instead sought guidance on whether a former West Tennessee judge&#39;s misconduct amounted to abuse of judicial power.
<P>    David Lanier, once a state judge in Dyersburg and a member of a politically powerful family, was convicted in federal court of sexually assaulting five women in his courtroom chambers from 1989 to 1991. Prosecutors said he forced one woman to perform oral sex.
<P>    Nine women testified at his trial that Lanier, now 61, repeatedly pressured them for sex, grabbed their breasts or buttocks, or exposed himself to them.
<P>    The local prosecutor, Lanier&#39;s brother, had not filed state criminal charges against him.
<P>    Because there was no federal rape law, federal prosecutors charged Lanier under an 1874 law that makes it a crime for government officials to use their official authority to willfully deprive someone of rights &#39;&#39;protected by the Constitution.&#39;&#39;
<P>    That law was used in the federal prosecutions of two former Los Angeles police officers convicted in the videotaped beating of motorist Rodney King.
<P>    Lanier&#39;s conviction and 25-year prison sentence were overturned when a federal appeals court ruled that freedom from sexual assault never had been recognized as a federally protected right.
<P>    Justices Anthony Kennedy and Antonin Scalia appeared to agree Tuesday as they voiced grave doubts about the Constitution&#39;s protection in such cases.
<P>    But they and other justices confined most questions to the issue of whether Lanier was acting in his capacity as a judge in his dealings with the women who either worked for him or had cases in his court.
<P>    Scalia acknowledged that the 1874 law can be used against police officers whose duty is to keep the public peace and take people into custody, but he questioned whether it could be invoked, for example, against a motor vehicles clerk who punched a citizen in the nose.
<P>    Kennedy asked whether a courthouse janitor who rapes someone has violated any constitutional right. &#39;&#39;Is there a specific right of bodily integrity outside of people in custody?&#39;&#39; Kennedy at one point asked in incredulous tones.
<P>    Justice Department lawyer Seth Waxman, seeking to have Lanier&#39;s conviction and prison sentence reinstated, replied that it was easy to draw distinctions between the offered examples and Lanier&#39;s case.
<P>    Lanier &#39;&#39;was properly and constitutionally convicted,&#39;&#39; Waxman said.
<P>    But Nashville lawyer Alfred Knight, representing Lanier, said the women had submitted to his advances because of his prominence in a small town, not because of his judicial authority.
<P>    His conduct, therefore, could not be attributed to Lanier&#39;s official authority, Knight argued.
<P>    But Chief Justice William Rehnquist, noting that Lanier reminded one woman that a custody case involving her child was pending before him, suggested, &#39;&#39;Surely a jury could conclude there was an implied threat.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Among the court&#39;s nine members, only Justice Clarence Thomas asked no questions from the bench. He did at times whisper to Justice Stephen Breyer, who sits beside him.
<P>    A decision is expected by July.
<P><font size=2><strong><p>Copyright 1997 by the Associated Press. All Rights Reserved. Unauthorized use is probihited. </p</strong></font>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
