<html>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>Apparent moves to consolidate state&#39;s lawyers criticized</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 08, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>Apparent moves to consolidate state&#39;s lawyers criticized</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Burson, some in Cabinet opposed</FONT></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By The Associated Press</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">N</FONT>ASHVILLE -- A plan by Gov. Don Sundquist to consolidate state lawyers under one division has been called illegal and is under attack from his Cabinet.
<P>   Sundquist is trying to create a new legal division apparently by consolidating and cross-training all lawyers now serving state departments.
<P>   The plan is expected to reduce the staff and provide savings as the state faces a huge budget shortfall.
<P>   Not so fast, said state Attorney General Charles Burson, who argued that a new department would be illegal; Sen. Bob Rochelle, D-Lebanon, who said the governor must bring the matter to the Legislature; and many in the governor&#39;s Cabinet, who said it&#39;s actually inefficient.
<P>   Rochelle criticized the governor Tuesday and released both Burson&#39;s opinion and a survey by the comptroller&#39;s office showing that a majority of the governor&#39;s commissioners oppose a central legal department.
<P>   &#39;&#39;A central legal department for the state would paralyze rather than empower departments,&#39;&#39; said Commerce and Insurance Commissioner Douglas Sizemore in a response to the proposal in report by the Tennessee Commission on Practical Government. 
<P>   &#39;&#39;While it may save money on the front end, it would greatly impair the ability of the departments to render services in an efficient manner.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Other responses from commissioners:
<P>   * &#39;&#39;Disagree that establishing a law department is the way to go,&#39;&#39; said Health Department Commissioner Fredia Wadley. 
<P>   &#39;&#39;I have worked under this system in Metro (Nashville government) and it was the pits. Our department did not have a good lawyer, and he never had time to handle our problems.&#39;&#39;
<P>   * &#39;&#39;Strongly disagree,&#39;&#39; said Revenue Commissioner Ruth Johnson.
<P>    &#39;&#39;The legal division in Department of Revenue plays a critical role in the administration of the tax laws, and the effectiveness of those attorneys would be severely curtailed if they were taken out of the organization of the department.&#39;&#39;
<P>   * &#39;&#39;The proposal would decrease familiarity, responsiveness and expertise, especially to those departments, such as the Tennessee Department of Correction, which require intensive daily interaction with staff counsel,&#39;&#39; said Correction Commissioner Donal Campbell.
<P>   The governor, a Republican, sought to replace lawyers&#39; specialization with cross-training and have them work for all departments; that would reduce their numbers from 164 to 100. 
<P>   Already, the number of lawyers has been reduced by about 30 through attrition, said Beth Fortune, the governor&#39;s press secretary.
<P>   &#39;&#39;The governor asked the Cabinet for input, and they obliged,&#39;&#39; Fortune said. 
<P>   &#39;&#39;It&#39;s the governor&#39;s ultimate decision, and he believes they should be centralized in one location.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Already, the lawyers are moving into one building in downtown Nashville, but Fortune insisted it would not mean cross-training in a new legal department.
<P>   Burson opined that state law permits departments and agencies to employ staff attorneys who &#39;&#39;work solely under the supervision&#39;&#39; of the departments who hired them or for the attorney general, but that creating a &#39;&#39;new, centralized law department&#39;&#39; would not be legal without legislation.
<P>   The administration may, Burson said, move state attorneys into one physical location as long as they still answer to their assigned departments.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We&#39;re going to do everything by the book,&#39;&#39; Fortune said. The governor has not yet planned legislation seeking a change,  she said.
<P>   Rochelle, in a press statement, accused the governor of attempting to establish a &#39;&#39;second set of lawyers.&#39;&#39;
<P>   &#39;&#39;Will he also need a second set of personnel officers or a second set of purchasing officers?&#39;&#39; Rochelle asked.
<P>   He criticized Sundquist for providing no study or explanation to legislators.
<P>   The commissioners&#39; responses were compiled, at Rochelle&#39;s request, by the comptroller&#39;s office, which reviewed commissioners&#39; comments to the idea of centralizing all lawyers in the Tennessee Commission on Practical Government. 
<P>   The commission was established by the administration.
<P>   Rochelle also asked for an attorney general&#39;s opinion, which he promptly forwarded, along with the Cabinet&#39;s comments, to the governor.
<P>
<P>
<P><font size=2><strong><p>Copyright 1997 by the Associated Press. All Rights Reserved. Unauthorized use is probihited. </p</strong></font>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
