<head>
	<title>Sterchi Hills parents oppose rezoning of students</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 08, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>Sterchi Hills parents oppose rezoning of students</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Move from Powell would `fracture' neighborhood</FONT></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By David Keim, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">A</FONT>bout 40 parents and children from the Sterchi Hills area told the school board Tuesday they don&#39;t want students rezoned from Powell to Gresham Middle or Central High schools.
<P>   &#39;&#39;It just seems that it would fracture Sterchi Hills,&#39;&#39; said parent Scott Nicley, who spoke for residents of the still-developing subdivision. &#39;&#39;We have a tight-knit, close, comfortable little neighborhood, and we would like to keep it that way.&#39;&#39;
<P>   The rezoning aims to relieve overcrowding at Powell schools, as do rezonings of 102 students from four schools to West Hills Elementary and 41 students from Karns Middle to Bearden Middle.
<P>   The board will vote on the rezonings next month. They would take effect next school year.
<P>   Only 19 children -- those who will enter middle or high school for the first time next school year -- would be required to go to Gresham or Central instead of Powell, although as many as 96 could be affected.
<P>   Students currently at Powell Middle or High schools would be allowed to finish school there, but they would need to find their own transportation.
<P>   Those who depend on bus service would have to go to Gresham or Central, reducing enrollment by about 49 students at Powell Middle and 47 at Powell High, according to Assistant Superintendent Roy Mullins.
<P>   Parents at Tuesday&#39;s school board work session said they purchased homes in Sterchi Hills in large part because of the quality of the Powell schools.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Not to insinuate one school is better than another,&#39;&#39; Nicley said, but parents look carefully at schools before buying a home. &#39;&#39;We feel like we moved into the Powell community and that&#39;s where we would like to commit our resources&#39;&#39; even beyond the schools.
<P>   Parents want school officials to be sure Powell schools aren&#39;t filled with transfers from other counties or other zones. They also want to be sure Powell schools are truly at capacity and that Gresham and Central can handle new students.
<P>   Powell Middle has 880 students. &#39;&#39;The capacity of the school is 800,&#39;&#39; Mullins said. He said Powell High is similarly overcrowded, while Central has a capacity of 1,375 with only 1,296 students.
<P>   School Board Chairwoman Margaret Maddox told parents, &#39;&#39;We as a board will certainly be assured that the need and the questions that have been raised tonight will be answered.&#39;&#39;
<P>   In the other rezonings:
<P>   * Students would be shifted into West Hills Elementary from four schools: Rocky Hill Elementary (21 students), Ball Camp Primary (33), Karns Intermediate (39) and Karns Primary (9).
<P>   Those numbers could be lower. The rezoning requires children who will be in kindergarten through third grade starting in 1997-98 to change schools. Those who will be in fourth or fifth grades next year don&#39;t have to change schools if their parents provide transportation.
<P>   * Mullins said 41 students could be shifted from Karns Middle to Bearden Middle. Students who will be in seventh or eighth grade at Karns, however, can continue attending if they can get their own rides.
<P>   
<P>   
<P>   
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
