<head>
	<title>TVA says Watts Bar deserves superior, not average rating</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 08, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>TVA says Watts Bar deserves superior, not average rating</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Michelle Williams, Associated Press</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">S</FONT>PRING CITY -- Watts Bar Nuclear Plant got a good performance rating during its first year of operation, but the Tennessee Valley Authority believes it deserves superior marks.
<P>    The Nuclear Regulatory Commission, which oversees the nation&#39;s 110 nuclear plants, gave Watts Bar top rankings for engineering and maintenance, but found plant operations and plant support were average.
<P>    During a meeting Tuesday with NRC officials, TVA nuclear chief Oliver Kingsley said employees deserved a higher grade after working years to complete a now successfully-running plant.
<P>    &#39;&#39;The fact that this was a start up year should have factored in more heavily than it did,&#39;&#39; Kingsley said. &#39;&#39;This sends the wrong message to our people, who&#39;ve worked so hard for so long.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Luis Reyes, who this month replaced Stewart Ebneter as regional administrator for the NRC, said Watts Bar exceeded the national average for first-year operations, but &#39;&#39;we have to be cautious with our ratings because we want them to keep it up.&#39;&#39;
<P>    The plant&#39;s weaknesses were for configuration controls, attention to detail and some procedural problems.
<P>    The one-year review started November 1995 and was released last month.
<P>    Reyes added, however, that Watts Bar has operated at a high capacity since it began generating power for sale in May, which is a testament to the equipment and workers.
<P>    He&#39;s also &#39;&#39;never seen such a low level of waste in the first year.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Watts Bar is one of the nation&#39;s most watched nuclear plants because of two decades of safety and construction problems. Equipment and design flaws forced TVA to spend the past decade verifying the plant&#39;s systems to meet NRC standards.
<P>    By the time it finally started generating power, the plant&#39;s price tag was $7 billion, making it also the nation&#39;s most expensive.
<P>       A second reactor at the plant was canceled.
<P>    Since June, Unit 1 has reached a capacity of 85 percent; the industry average is 65 percent for first-year plants.
<P>    The reactor also operated for 117 straight days until a scheduled outage this fall and continuously since then.
<P>    Reyes told Kingsley he could petition the NRC to reconsider the overall rating by writing a letter and supplying documents to support why Watts Bar deserved a superior rating. 
<P>   Kingsley hasn&#39;t decided whether he will officially challenge the rating.
<P>    While Watts Bar seems to be performing well, another TVA plant just 20 miles away isn&#39;t.
<P>    Last month, the NRC proposed a $100,000 fine against the Sequoyah Nuclear Plant in Spring City for problems with equipment and electrical breakers.
<P>    Earlier in the year, NRC proposed another $130,000 in fines for problems, including fire protection.
<P>       Kingsley said most of those problems have been corrected. However, since September, there have been at least four reactor malfunctions.
<P><font size=2><strong><p>Copyright 1997 by the Associated Press. All Rights Reserved. Unauthorized use is probihited. </p</strong></font>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
