<head>
	<title>Man ordered to prison for bankruptcy fraud plea</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 08, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Man ordered to prison for bankruptcy fraud plea</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Randy Kenner, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">S</FONT>aying people don&#39;t take bankruptcy laws seriously, a federal judge sentenced a former Knoxville businessman to 10 months in prison despite sentencing guidelines that would have allowed no jail time.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We&#39;ve got to stop this bankruptcy fraud, it&#39;s rampant in this country,&#39;&#39; U.S. District Judge James Jarvis said Monday just before sentencing Jerry A. Bruno. &#39;&#39;People don&#39;t pay attention to their oath is all it is.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Bruno, the former president of the Knoxville-based Copy Systems Inc., pleaded guilty to bankruptcy fraud last summer. Under federal sentencing guidelines, he faced a range of 10-16 months, but it could have been served at a halfway house or even on home detention.
<P>   Jarvis wasn&#39;t amenable to either option during a hearing in which he appeared to become increasingly unhappy with Bruno, who he said had a prior fraud conviction in North Carolina.
<P>   &#39;&#39;People get in trouble and they go into bankruptcy and don&#39;t pay attention to the court&#39;s orders,&#39;&#39; Jarvis said. &#39;&#39;They try and circumvent the court&#39;s order, and sometimes, they do.&#39;&#39;
<P>   He noted the guidelines, adding, &#39;&#39;But in this case, and this case alone, the court finds that it would be in the best interest of justice&#39;&#39; that Bruno be sentenced to 10 months in prison.
<P>   According to court documents, Bruno, who lives in Florida and does most of his business in Atlanta, was chief operating officer of a company that bought and sold copy machines and office equipment. He and his wife were the sole stockholders.
<P>   The business apparently wasn&#39;t faring very well because Bruno filed for Chapter 11 -- or reorganization -- bankruptcy protection in April 1991.
<P>   A month later, a bankruptcy judge ordered Copy Systems Inc. to pay Bruno an annual salary of $45,000 and that the salary payments be made only after it had paid the payroll, taxes and payments to First American National Bank, according to court documents prepared by Assistant U.S. Attorney Hugh Ward.
<P>   Bruno, however, received more than that -- approximately $66,550, according to his plea agreement.
<P>   According to documents filed by Bruno&#39;s attorney, Michael P. McGovern, Copy Systems made certain payments to Bruno for things like car payments, apartment rent and other expenses before the bankruptcy was filed.
<P>   It continued to do that even after the bankruptcy order limiting Bruno&#39;s salary to $45,000.
<P>   &#39;&#39;It is those continued payments that gave rise to the indictment,&#39;&#39; McGovern wrote.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
