<head>
	<title>Law may restrict election-job nominees</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 08, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Law may restrict election-job nominees</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Michael Silence, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">A</FONT> state law may prevent two educators from serving on the Knox County Election Commission, but a clarifying opinion is being sought from the Tennessee Election Commission, state Sen. Bud Gilbert said Tuesday.
<P>   That prospect is troubling to Gilbert, R-Knoxville, because the two candidates who are educators are female. All things being equal, he said, he supports a female for the commission because all other members are male.
<P>   Also Tuesday, Gilbert said he&#39;s considering asking for a delay in the Saturday vote on a replacement for Commissioner Hazel Showalter, who died last month. She was a Republican.
<P>   Gilbert said he may seek a delay in order for the GOP caucus members to get more information on candidates and allow time for others to express interest.
<P>   The seven members of the Knox County Republican legislative delegation are scheduled to vote Saturday at the annual Legislative Delegation meeting.
<P>    That meeting begins at 8:30 a.m. in the Small Assembly Room of the City County Building.
<P>   The seven-member caucus makes the recommendation for a replacement to the state Election Commission, which then makes the appointment. The state commission meets on Tuesday, Jan. 14.
<P>   On Monday, state Rep. Jim Boyer, R-Corryton, said the three &#39;&#39;serious&#39;&#39; candidates he knows of are Donna Wright, principal at West High School; Rebecca Longmire, a librarian at Gibbs High School; and John Tindell, a member of the Knox County Republican Executive Committee.
<P>   Boyer is chairman of the selection process. Tindell served as Boyer&#39;s Halls campaign coordinator in Boyer&#39;s first successful run for office.
<P>   All three candidates live in either North or Northeast Knox County, an important factor to state Sen. Ben Atchley, R-Knoxville. He said it has been many years since that area of the county has been represented on the commission.
<P>   Gilbert said Commissioner Courtney Pearre, a Republican, is seeking an interpretation on the state law from the state panel.
<P>   That law begins by stating: &#39;&#39;Neither an elected official nor an employee of a state, county, municipal or federal governmental body or agency or of an elected official may serve as a member of a county election commission.&#39;&#39;
<P>   A subsection of the law, however, exempts &#39;&#39;schoolteachers.&#39;&#39; That may save the chances for Wright and Longmire. He said elsewhere in state statutes &#39;&#39;schoolteacher&#39;&#39; is defined as essentially an educator holding a teacher&#39;s certificate. 
<P>   That would likely apply to a principal and a librarian, Gilbert speculated.
<P>   State Election Coordinator Brook Thompson on Tuesday said the commission is attempting to get an answer to the Knox County delegation in a day or two.
<P>   Gilbert said that, based on his initial reading of the law, a government-employed janitor could not serve on the commission but a teacher could.
<P>   He said clarification is needed because the public&#39;s confidence in the election process was shaken enough by last November&#39;s foul-up on early votes in the unification question.
<P>   &#39;&#39;There have been a lot of discussions going on among legislators&#39;&#39; about a replacement, said Gilbert. &#39;&#39;We want to do right by the public. The public is concerned about the election. The appointment should not be patronage. It should be based on merit.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Gilbert said he thinks Wright would be an &#39;&#39;excellent&#39;&#39; choice. He said he does not know Longmire but has heard her credentials are strong, too.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
