	<title>Busy computer delays licensing</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 08, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Busy computer delays licensing</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By The Associated Press</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">N</FONT>ASHVILLE -- Thousands of Tennesseans were turned away from driver&#39;s license testing centers because of a computer snafu.
<P>    The Monday foul-up affected all testing centers, but they are back online now, Department of Safety spokesman Anthony Kimbrough said Tuesday.
<P>    &#39;&#39;We were not able to use driver&#39;s license data bases virtually all day Monday, which means we could not issue driver&#39;s licenses,&#39;&#39; he said. &#39;&#39;The only alternative we had was to issue temporary licenses for 90 days.&#39;&#39;
<P>    An average 7,300 people apply for driver&#39;s licenses on an average day.
<P>    Those who received the temporary license must go through the process again.
<P>    &#39;&#39;It was a production job that began running late Sunday and should have been completed Monday morning,&#39;&#39; Kimbrough said. &#39;&#39;The production job couldn&#39;t be stopped in the middle of the job. What was running was a commercial driver&#39;s license report.&#39;&#39;
<P><font size=2><strong><p>Copyright 1997 by the Associated Press. All Rights Reserved. Unauthorized use is probihited. </p</strong></font>
