<head>
	<title>Man pleads guilty to helping sell methamphetamine to agent</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 08, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Man pleads guilty to helping sell methamphetamine to agent</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Randy Kenner, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">A</FONT>n Indiana man has pleaded guilty in federal court to helping sell a pound of methamphetamine to an undercover U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration agent.
<P>   Chester Wayne Hamilton, 51, of Indianapolis drove his Ford Bronco around a restaurant parking lot &#39;&#39;in a counter-surveillance- type manner&#39;&#39; while the DEA agent waited patiently inside before the buy, according to court documents.
<P>   Hamilton entered his guilty plea Monday before U.S. District Judge Leon Jordan to a single count of conspiracy to possess methamphetamine with intent to distribute it.
<P>   A co-defendant in the case, Sharon Kay Lester, earlier pleaded guilty to drug charges in the case.
<P>   According to court documents prepared by Assistant U.S. Attorney Mike Mitchell, the case developed from telephone conversations that Lester had with a DEA confidential informant regarding the purchase of methamphetamine.
<P>   The secretly recorded calls occurred between Dec. 15-20, 1995.
<P>   &#39;&#39;During these conversations, an agreement was reached between Ms. Lester and the (informant) whereby the informant would supply Ms. Lester with one pound of methamphetamine through his associate, (DEA Agent) Mark Poag, acting in an undercover capacity, for a total price of $17,500,&#39;&#39; Hamilton&#39;s plea agreement states.
<P>   Lester arranged to make a $2,500 down payment with the remaining $15,000 to be paid after she sold the methamphetamine.
<P>   On Dec. 22, 1995, she and Poag met at the Burger King Restaurant on Merchant Drive where Poag &#39;&#39;made arrangements to sell Ms. Lester the previously agreed upon one pound of methamphetamine at this location&#39;&#39; later that night, according to records.
<P>   Just before Poag arrived, however, he received a page and after reaching the restaurant returned the call from a nearby pay phone.
<P>   Lester answered from a pay phone at a service station across the street where she was standing beside a Bronco driven by Hamilton. She told Poag to drive across the street and meet her there. Poag responded by telling her to get over to Burger King.
<P>   Before she did, Hamilton drove around the area for approximately 15 mintues before dropping Lester off and returning to his position across the street.
<P>   Once inside, Lester handed Poag the money in an envelope and went outside to wave Hamiltion over.
<P>    She and Poag then walked outside to Poag&#39;s vehicle where he gave her a shoe box wrapped like a Christmas present supposedly containing the drug.
<P>   The pair were arrested moments later when Lester got back in Hamilton&#39;s vehicle.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
