<head>
	<title>1 indicted on weapons charges</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 08, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>1 indicted on weapons charges</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Randy Kenner, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">A</FONT> New Tazewell man who discussed blowing up the Cumberland Gap Tunnel connecting Kentucky and Tennessee was indicted Tuesday on federal weapons charges.
<P>   Gary Lee Seabolt, 25, who was arrested on a criminal complaint in late December, is charged with being a felon in possession of a firearm and with making false statements in the acquisition of a firearm.
<P>   He was also charged with receiving a quantity of explosive materials, &#39;&#39;. . . that is, a supplementary T.N.T. artillery charge, knowing or having reasonable cause to believe that such materials were stolen,&#39;&#39; the indictment states.
<P>   Mike Durham, an agent with the U.S. Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco & Firearms, confirmed that Seabolt discussed blowing up a tunnel.
<P>   The Cumberland Gap tunnel, which consists of two parallel passageways carrying traffic north and south, connects Bell County, Ky., to Claiborne County.
<P>   U.S. Magistrate Robert P. Murrian ordered Seabolt to undergo a mental competency examination during the hearing Tuesday.
<P>   According to the indictment, Seabolt was in possession of a .22-caliber rifle and a 20-gauge shotgun and has previously been convicted of crimes carrying a sentence of more than a year in prison. Seabolt, according to court papers filed by Assistant U.S. Attorney David Folmar, has multiple felony convictions including two commercial burglary convictions in Union County in 1994.   A search warrant was served on his residence in a New Tazewell trailer park on Dec. 20, 1996, and the firearms and the explosive device were discovered. 
<P>   
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
