	<title>Hundreds against hydropower facility</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 08, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Hundreds against hydropower facility</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By The Associated Press</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">C</FONT>HATTANOOGA -- Hundreds of people wrote federal regulators in protest to a Pennsylvania company building a $2 billion hydropower facility in the Sequatchie Valley.
<P>    Three federal agencies, which must issue permits before Armstrong Energy Resources of Butler, Pa., can build the plant, solicited public comments for the past few months as part of an environmental impact study. The deadline was Tuesday.
<P>    &#39;&#39;Generally, most of the comments were against,&#39;&#39; said Celeste Miller, spokeswoman for the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission. &#39;&#39;That&#39;s typical in this process to get more opposed comments because those who respond usually have a personal interest in it.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Miller said citizens&#39; responses will be read and cataloged before the environmental impact statement is completed, probably later this year.
<P>   About 1,000 comments were received collectively by the FERC, the Tennessee Valley Authority and the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers.
<P>    The comment period was slated to end in October, but the response from residents led the agencies to extend the period by 90 days.
<P>    Residents are worried about land seizures, pollution and the location of transmission lines along hundreds of acres in Sequatchie and Bledsoe counties.
<P>    Armstrong wants to pump water from area creeks to the top of a mountain for later release through a generator, making up to 1,500 megawatts of power. The electricity will be sold to TVA, which will then market it to power companies.
<P>    The plant could create about 1,000 construction jobs and 100 permanent jobs. If approved, construction could begin by 2000.
<P>    The protests from residents have apparently already made some impact.
<P>    Armstrong announced last month that it was cutting in half its plans from two plants worth $4 billion to one plant worth $2 billion. The plant would be built in Bledsoe County near Pikeville.
<P><font size=2><strong><p>Copyright 1997 by the Associated Press. All Rights Reserved. Unauthorized use is probihited. </p</strong></font>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
