<head>
	<title>Man convicted in 9 slayings didn&#39;t fit serial killer profile</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 08, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Man convicted in 9 slayings didn&#39;t fit serial killer profile</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Paul Nowell, Associated Press</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">C</FONT>HARLOTTE, N.C. -- A confessed killer who did not fit the established profile of a serial killer was convicted Tuesday of methodically raping and murdering nine women over a 20-month period.
<P>    Henry Louis Wallace was convicted of 28 felonies, including nine counts of first-degree murder. Prosecutors are seeking the death penalty.
<P>    Relatives of some of the victims were in court when the verdicts were read.
<P>    &#39;&#39;I am numb. My heart is beyond pain,&#39;&#39; said Dee Sumpter, whose daughter Shawna Hawk was among the victims.
<P>    Wallace knew his victims, while most serial killers target strangers, an expert testified during the trial. And he is black while most serial killers are white.
<P>    Wallace, 31, admitted raping and killing the women from 1992 into 1994. Seven of the women were strangled and two were stabbed to death.
<P>    Wallace has not yet been tried for two other killings, one in the Charlotte area and another in South Carolina.
<P>    The same jury that convicted Wallace will meet again Monday to begin hearing evidence for the sentencing phase and decide whether he should be sentenced to execution or to life in prison.
<P>    Defense attorneys did not dispute that Wallace killed the women, but argued he was mentally ill, driven by obsessional sexual fantasies that rendered him incapable of forming the intent to kill.
<P>    Wallace did not testify, but jurors heard the chilling recordings of his confession to homicide investigators.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
