		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><h3>Norris gets new mayor; surprise follows vote</h3>
<P>
<P>
<P>   NORRIS -- In a surprise move at the Norris City Council meeting Tuesday, former Norris mayor and top vote getter G. Richard Dyer declined the nomination for mayor and indicated his preference for Vice Mayor Jerry Crossno to be the new mayor of Norris.
<P>   By a vote of 5-0, the new council replaced incumbent Mayor Russ Manning with Crossno and Dyer as vice mayor.
<P>   The Norris mayor is elected by a majority vote of the five-member City Council and has traditionally been chosen from the highest votes of the Norris citizens.
<P>   New members of the council include Lester Murphy and Gene Bocknek. 
<P>
<P><h3>Acting CDF unit head is Maryville minister</h3>
<P>
<P>
<P>   CLINTON -- The Rev. Oliver &#39;&#39;Buzz&#39;&#39; Thomas has been named acting director of the former Alex Haley Farm in Clinton.
<P>   The farm is now operated by the Children&#39;s Defense Fund.
<P>   Thomas of Maryville is an attorney and Baptist minister.
<P>   
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Group home manager sentenced in rapes</h3>
<P>
<P>
<P>   ATHENS -- The former manager of an Athens men&#39;s group home has been given eight years in prison after filing a plea of no contest in connection with the allegeded rape of residents of the home in 1996.
<P>   Gary Hester, 33, of Athens, was originally to go on trial today on one of the five counts.
<P>   The agreement is not a guilty plea by Hester, but that he does not contest the charges, court officials said.
<P>   Criminal Court Judge Steve Bebb sentenced Hester to serve one year in prison with the remaining years suspended.
<P>   
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>McMinn records year&#39;s first traffic fatality</h3>
<P>
<P>
<P>    ETOWAH -- McMinn County recorded its first traffic fatality of the new year on Tuesday when an Etowah man died in a one-vehicle crash.
<P>    Greg B. Studdard, 26, was traveling south on County Road 775 about five miles west of Etowah when his truck left the road and struck a tree, troopers said.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Kingsport &#39;hacker&#39; is guilty in AF accessing</h3>
<P>
<P>
<P>    GREENEVILLE -- A Kingsport computer hacker pleaded guilty in federal court to illegally accessing a U.S. Air Force computer system.
<P>    Wendell Dingus, 29, of Kingsport pleaded guilty Monday to two counts of tapping into the computer at Maxwell Air Force Base in Montgomery, Ala.
<P>    Prosecutors say he apparently used a home computer connected with computers at Vanderbilt University and Middle Tennessee State University.
<P>   
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Three plead guilty to vandalism spree</h3>
<P>
<P>
<P>   Three Knox County men pleaded guilty Monday in Knox County General Sessions Court to about 40 charges of vandalizing three neighborhoods last month.
<P>   Bradley S. Kent, 20, William G. Ingram Jr., 19, and John D. Gratz, 22, were placed on two years&#39; judicial diversion in lieu of criminal convictions. They also were ordered to pay restitution for the damage, which authorities estimate to be about $15,000.
<P>   General Sessions Court Judge Geoff Emery rebuked the young men, who smashed mailboxes, vandalized cars and inflicted other damage over several hours Dec. 19 in the Barrington, Copperfield and Willow Oak subdivisions in the Karns area.
<P>  &#39;&#39;This isn&#39;t something that was done on a dare in 10 minutes,&#39;&#39; Emery said. &#39;&#39;This is something that took a long time to accomplish.&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
