	<title>Apple unveils plan to retool Macintosh and regain profit</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper Business News">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif" alt="Knoxville News-Sentinel Online -- Business News" align=bottom border=0 width=595 height=176></a><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td align=left valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 08, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Apple unveils plan to retool Macintosh and regain profit</B></font><basefont size=6><!--SUBHEAD--></basefont></FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By The Associarted Press</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">S</FONT>AN FRANCISCO -- Apple Computer co-founder Steve Jobs returned to the fold Tuesday, joining the company&#39;s current leader in describing plans to restore Apple to former glory as the industry&#39;s innovator.
<P>    Jobs, sharing the stage with Chairman Gil Amelio at the MacWorld Expo trade show, described how technology from his Next Software Inc. will help Apple develop a new operating system for the Macintosh personal computer. Apple is buying Next, which Jobs started after leaving Apple more than 11 years ago.
<P>    &#39;&#39;This is our mission: What we want to do is provide relevant, compelling solutions that customers can only get from Apple,&#39;&#39; said Jobs, who will advise Amelio on the new operating system, the critical software that controls the Mac&#39;s basic functions.
<P>    More than 4,000 people crowded into a hotel ballroom to hear Amelio and Jobs. Many in the audience gave Jobs, who guided the development of the original Macintosh, a standing ovation when he appeared near the end of Amelio&#39;s long presentation.
<P>    Amelio&#39;s talk at the biggest trade show devoted to the Macintosh drew intense scrutiny because of Apple&#39;s recent decision to buy Next, its stubborn financial problems and doubts both have raised about the company&#39;s long-term prospects.
<P>    One key question raised by Apple&#39;s plan to blend its technology with Next&#39;s in creating a new operating system is compatibility. Some Macintosh users and software developers have wondered whether their computers and existing Mac programs would soon be obsolete.
<P>    But Amelio assured them they won&#39;t be forgotten as Apple makes the complex transition, expected to take several years.
<P>    &#39;&#39;We simply don&#39;t want to abandon the installed base of users we have today,&#39;&#39; said Amelio, who wore a collar-less shirt and jacket in contrast to his usual suit-and-tie attire.
<P>    Next&#39;s software, used in computers for businesses, has a reputation of being easy for developers to work with, crash resistant and able to let the computer carry out several tasks at once. While Macintosh users are famed for their devotion to their computers, they have long wanted those features.
<P>    Apple plans to get the new operating system in developers&#39; hands by the end of the 1997 and to customers within a year after that. The new program, code-named Rhapsody, will run on current and future Macintosh computers and will include technology that will let it work with most applications now being used.
<P>    The company intends to make the transition as painless as possible by continually upgrading the current operating software, called System 7, for five to 10 years, according to Apple&#39;s chief technologist, Ellen Hancock.
<P>    The first upgrade, called Harmony, is due later this month, and a second, dubbed Tempo, is set for release in July. Two more are planned for 1998.
<P>    Amelio said Tuesday that while Apple&#39;s recent financial results are disappointing, the company is still fundamentally sound and will continue to recover.
<P>    &#39;&#39;It&#39;s sort of like hitting one of those air pockets in turbulence,&#39;&#39; he said. &#39;&#39;But we&#39;re going to stay the course.&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P><font size=2><strong><p>Copyright 1997 by the Associated Press. All Rights Reserved. Unauthorized use is probihited. </p</strong></font>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
