<head>
	<title>Miller Industries buys Greene plant for Vulcan</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper Business News">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif" alt="Knoxville News-Sentinel Online -- Business News" align=bottom border=0 width=595 height=176></a><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td align=left valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 08, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Miller Industries buys Greene plant for Vulcan</B></font><basefont size=6><!--SUBHEAD--></basefont></FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Pam Park, News-Sentinel business writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">M</FONT>iller Industries Inc., an Atlanta-based towing equipment company, has bought a Greeneville manufacturing plant formerly used by Greeneville Industries, a subsidiary of Newport News Shipbuilding & Dry Dock Co.
<P>   The 100,000-square-foot facility located on 10 acres of industrial property will house operations of Miller&#39;s newly acquired subsidiary, Vulcan Equipment Co. of Olive Branch, Miss.
<P>   The Greeneville plant will employ 30-40 people initially and up to 150 over time, said Adam Dunayer, chief financial officer.
<P>   Capital investment in plant and equipment is expected to reach $3 million to $4 million.
<P>   Vulcan will make car carriers -- tow trucks with flat beds on the back -- in Greeneville. The company has a similar facility in Pennsylvania. The addition of the Greeneville facility will double its production capacity.
<P>   Vulcan will also offer installation and painting capability at Greeneville. Vulcan expects to produce 500-600 car carriers per month when the facility is fully operational. Production is expected to begin by March.
<P>   Greeneville Industries shut down in mid-1994 after defense cutbacks reduced contracts from the U.S. Navy. Nearly 300 people lost their jobs.
<P>   Greeneville Industries used the facility to weld parts for the Navy&#39;s nuclear submarine program, and that was a help in attracting Miller Industries, said Tom Ferguson, president of the Greene County Partnership, a consolidated economic development agency.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We were able to convince them we have an available work force here and they&#39;re not going to have to spend a lot of money training people,&#39;&#39; Ferguson said.
<P>    Scott Niswonger, chairman, president and chief executive officer of Landair Service Inc., bought the building after the shutdown and has used it for warehousing, but he really bought it in hopes of attracting another manufacturer, Ferguson said.
<P>   A growth credit program that will give the company reduced electric rates over the next 3-5 years and a training program for new hires were offered as incentives, he said.
<P>   Ferguson expects a number of the welders who once worked for Greeneville Industries to apply for jobs with Vulcan.
<P>   Miller Industries has manufacturing operations located in Chattanooga and in Pennsylvania, Mississippi, France and England.
<P>   Miller was one of the top performing stocks on the New York Stock Exchange in 1996, Dunayer said, and was in the top 10 of Forbes magazine&#39;s list of the best 200 small capitalization companies. It was also picked to move to the Forbes list of the 400 largest companies, he said.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
