<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>Business Briefs</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper Business News">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif" alt="Knoxville News-Sentinel Online -- Business News" align=bottom border=0 width=595 height=176></a><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td align=left valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 08, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Business Briefs</B></font><basefont size=6><!--SUBHEAD--></basefont></FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<h3>Arnold Palmer Golf has loss</h3>
<P>
<P>   The Arnold Palmer Golf Co. reported Tuesday a net loss of $2.3 million, or 80 cents per share, for a seven-month transition period that ended Sept. 30.
<P>   That compares to a net loss of $1.1 million, or 42 cents per share, for the same period in the prior year.
<P>   The current earnings included a $900,000 charge from a defaulted loan repayment from DeLong Sportswear, the company said.
<P>   The transition period was from March 3 through Sept. 30, and is a result of a change in the end of the company&#39;s fiscal year from the Saturday closest to the end of February to Sept. 30.
<P>   Sales for the seven months reached $18.5 million, a $3.7 million increase over a year ago.
<P>   Based in Ooltewah, Tenn., the Arnold Palmer Golf Co. manufactures, markets and distributes golf products, including Palmer Golf Equipment and Hot-Z bags and luggage.
<P>
<P><h3>Shop At Home revenues rise</h3>
<P>
<P>   Shop At Home Inc. reported second-quarter revenues ending Dec. 31 rose 70 percent to $16.1 million over the previous quarter.
<P>   The Knoxville-based, 24-hour interactive home shopping company expects net income to substantially improve over the net loss of $942,842 in the comparable quarter of last year and the net income of $166,000 in the most recent quarter which ended Sept. 30. Final earnings results will be released by the end of January.
<P>   On a calendar year basis, the company generated $53.4 million in revenue, a 70 percent increase over last year&#39;s revenues of $31.5 million.
<P>
<P><h3>Burley averages $192</h3>
<P>
<P>   Tennessee burley sold for an average $192 per hundredweight Monday with a low of $190 at Columbia and a high of $192 at all other markets, the state Department of Agriculture said.
<P>   A total 4,249,871 pounds sold for $8,157,315 at 10 markets with no sales in Clarksville, Fayetteville, Gallatin, Morristown, Mountain City and Sweetwater.
<P>   Greeneville sold the most burley, 583,075 pounds, that went for $1,120,465. Columbia sold the least burley, 313,496 pounds, that went for $597,663.
<P>
<P><h3>Firm changes name</h3>
<P>
<P>   The board of Volunteer Capital Corp. in Nashville has voted to change the company&#39;s name to J., Alexaner&#39;s Corp. in order to more closely identify with the company&#39;s J. Alexander&#39;s restaurants.
<P>   A shareholder meeting has been called for Feb. 7 to act on the change. Plans are to change the company&#39;s New York Stock Exchange trading symbol to &#39;&#39;JAX&#39;&#39;.
<P>
<P><h3>Country record sales down</h3>
<P>
<P>   NASHVILLE -- Country music record sales slumped 12 percent last year and 18 percent in the fourth quarter, figures show.
<P>   Sales were $67 million for the year, down from $76 million in 1995.
<P>   For the quarter, albums and singles sold 23 million, down from 28 million for the last quarter of 1995.
<P>   According to SoundScan Inc., which tracks music sales nationally, sales of all music rose about 3 percent last year.
<P>
<P><h3>New Taco Express opens</h3>
<P>
<P>   A new Mexican restaurant, Taco Express, has opened at 270 N. Seven Oaks Drive in Windsor Square Shopping Center.
<P>   It replaces Burrito Loco, which opened in July 1996. The restaurant will seat 50.
<P>   Restaurant owners are Alex Rodriguez and his wife, Violeta. It will employ four. Rodriguez comes to Knoxville from Florence, Ala., where he managed various Mexican restaurants.
<P>   Lunch specials will start at $2.99.
<P>   Hours will be 11 a.m. to 9 p.m. seven days a week.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
