<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>Chill of an 8-3 defeat has Kees talking to themselves</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 08, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470><BASEFONT SIZE="6">
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Chill of an 8-3 defeat has Kees talking to themselves</B></FONT><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Nick Gates, News-Sentinel sportswriter</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">T</FONT>he Columbus Chill is perched atop the East Coast Hockey League&#39;s North Division and it&#39;s no mirage. They&#39;re swift and tough, make tape-to-tape passes, and are willing to drop their gloves when challenged.
<P>    The Chill, minus No. 1 goaltender Jeff Salajko, didn&#39;t miss a beat Tuesday night and destroyed Knoxville 8-3 at the Civic Coliseum to add to the Cherokees&#39; mounting miseries.
<P>   Knoxville coach Barry Smith again was the verbal target of fans. A few chanted for his ouster.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We have a lot of people in the stands yelling for Barry&#39;s neck,&#39;&#39; all-star center Jim Brown said. &#39;&#39;When they&#39;re yelling for Barry&#39;s neck, they&#39;re yelling for our neck. Barry&#39;s not the one out there playing the game.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Barry&#39;s done all he can do as far as teaching us what he wants us to do. The reason we&#39;re not winning is we aren&#39;t doing those things.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Joe Coombs had two goals in support of backup goaltender David Brumby, who made 30 saves and improved his record to 5-1-0. Derek Gauthier, Keith Morris, Derek Clancey, Dave Hymovitz, Matt Oates and Beau Bilek also scored for Columbus.
<P>    Salajko was called up by Indianapolis earlier in the day. He is tied with Roanoke&#39;s Dave Gagnon for the most wins (18).
<P>    The Cherokees (12-19-1) fell behind 4-1 after one period and never had a chance against the Chill, whose 10 road wins tops the ECHL. Columbus killed six of seven shorthanded situations and converted two of four power-play chances.
<P>    Knoxville lost for the 12th time in 13 games. The slumping Cherokees have dropped five in a row, four on home ice.
<P>    Vaclav Nedomansky, Chris Fess and Brown scored Knoxville&#39;s goals. Brown&#39;s came on a power play and was his 20th.
<P>   The Cherokees&#39; dressing room resembled a morgue. Heads were down and faces long. The players held a closed-door meeting without their coach.
<P>   &#39;&#39;This is as bad as it&#39;s been in my 21 years of hockey,&#39;&#39; a dejected Brown said. &#39;&#39;We&#39;ve pretty much said everything we can say.&#39;&#39;
<P>    It took only 50 seconds for the Chill (23-10-1) to score. Gauthier roared in on Brad Guzda unchecked. He faked the goalie off his skates and deftly put a backhander into the cage.
<P>    Goals by Morris and Coombs 1:39 apart made it 3-0 and the outcome was no longer in doubt.
<P>   Knoxville&#39;s run of bad luck also continued. Nedomansky, for the third consecutive game, had a goal disallowed. He stuffed the puck behind Brumby with 37 seconds left in the first period. However, it came a split second after referee Kevin Pollock lost sight of the puck and blew his whistle. But it hardly mattered.
<P>    If there was a glimmer of hope for the home team, it was the second period. The Cherokees limited the Chill to six shots on goal and outscored Columbus 2-1. But it was only a glimmer.
<P>    Goals by Hymovitz and Oates in the first 1:56 seconds of the third period made it 7-3 and finished Guzda. He was replaced by Trent Cavicchi.
<P>    
<P>    <B>ALL-STAR REPEATER: </B>Brown has earned a trip to the ECHL All-Star Game for the second consecutive season.
<P>  The 22-player squad -- one player from each team, excluding the Charlotte Checkers -- will play the defending ECHL champions Jan. 21 at 9,570-seat Independence Arena in Charlotte. Game time is 7:35.
<P>    Roger Neilson, associate coach of the St. Louis Blues of the National Hockey League, will coach the All-Stars.
<P>   
<P>    
<P>    <B>SUSPENDED:</B> Knoxville&#39;s attempt to trade forward Kyle Reeves to the Jacksonville Lizard Kings has failed. Reeves has indicated he will not report to void the four-player deal.
<P>    Reeves, the ECHL&#39;s second-leading scorer with 29 goals in 31 games, got into a shouting match with Smith during the first period of Knoxville&#39;s 5-2 loss to Roanoke on Saturday night. He changed into street clothes during the first intermission and left the arena.
<P>    Reeves was suspended Tuesday for not reporting to the Lizard Kings, who are in last place in the South.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
