<html>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>EPA lacks concern for public, canoeing group says</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 07, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>EPA lacks concern for public, canoeing group says</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Letters regarding Champion variance were 100% opposed</FONT></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Gina Stafford, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">W</FONT>hen it comes to pollution in the Pigeon River, the Environmental Protection Agency has &#39;&#39;little regard&#39;&#39; for the public&#39;s concern, according to officials with the 25,000-member American Canoe Association.
<P>   The ACA, described by a spokesman as a &#39;&#39;conservation-based recreation organization,&#39;&#39; reported Monday that public comment written to the EPA was 100 percent opposed to the variance recently issued to Champion International for operation of its Canton, N.C., paper mill.
<P>   In response to a request by the ACA for all public comments concerning the potential issuing of a variance or permit, the EPA provided 135 letters, according to David Jenkins, ACA&#39;s director of conservation and public policy.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I was quite amazed that EPA did not receive a single comment in support of Champion,&#39;&#39; Jenkins stated in a press release issued Monday. 
<P>   &#39;&#39;This clearly shows how little regard EPA has for the public&#39;s concern. One hundred percent of the people responding said deny the variance and EPA still approved it.&#39;&#39;
<P>   On Dec. 26, the EPA approved a new permit issued by North Carolina officials allowing Champion to continue operating the Canton mill and polluting the Pigeon River at a level above what is allowed under federal water quality standards.
<P>   Four days later, government officials and business advocates from three counties challenged Tennessee Gov. Don Sundquist to sue the Environmental Protection Agency. The group charged the EPA with shirking its duty in allowing Champion to continue polluting the Pigeon River, which flows into Tennessee.
<P>   Vice President Al Gore also declared in a statement on Dec. 30 that he was pleased that the state of Tennessee filed a formal objection to North Carolina&#39;s issuance of the permit. Gore further stated he has &#39;&#39;personally asked EPA Administrator Carol Browner to thoroughly and carefully review this objection and take appropriate action.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Public comment is required for issuance of a permit but not for a variance, according to EPA officials. Further, as a result of meetings with Tennessee environmentalists and the ACA, Champion&#39;s permit was significantly strengthened, officials said.
<P>   &#39;&#39;The EPA shares Tennessee&#39;s concerns about the Pigeon River and will fully support water quality standards set by the state,&#39;&#39; EPA spokesman Stephanie Cutter said Monday.
<P>   &#39;&#39;When we considered the North Carolina variance, we listened to the citizens of Tennessee and approved the North Carolina variance only after being assured it would meet current water quality and health standards of Tennessee.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Should Tennessee decide to strengthen its standards, as we have said repeatedly, the EPA will enforce at those levels.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Champion officials haven&#39;t previously been made aware of the public&#39;s letters, company spokesman Al Joyce said Monday.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We don&#39;t know the EPA procedure for handling public comment, and we haven&#39;t seen any of the letters. This is the first we&#39;ve heard of it,&#39;&#39; Joyce said.
<P>   &#39;&#39;The permit and the variance do require Champion to look for ways to continue to reduce the impact on the river, and we&#39;re committed to doing just that. I guess we respect the right of anybody to voice their opinion on any subject.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Jenkins said the 135 letters came from a mix of Tennessee state and local officials, fishermen, kayakers, representatives of church groups, outdoor clubs, environmental organizations and outdoor and tourism-related businesses.
<P>   Meanwhile, Attorney General Charles Burson on Monday declined to discuss Champion issues but said through a spokeswoman that various legal options &#39;&#39;are all under active consideration.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Burson declined to say whether he would accept an invitation to meet Jan. 14 with EPA Regional Administrator John Harkinson.
<P>   Harkinson had invited Burson to meet with him in Nashville at a planned session with the Tennessee Environmental Council.
<P>   Outgoing State Environment and Conservation Commissioner Justin Wilson planned to attend a meeting today in Atlanta between southeastern state officials and Harkinson, and Wilson said Champion issues may be discussed then.
<P>
<P>
<P><B>News-Sentinel Nashville bureau chief Tom Humphrey contributed to this sto÷ry.</B>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
