<head>
	<title>Gingrich rallies GOP supporters</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 07, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>Gingrich rallies GOP supporters</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> He presents his case during long caucus</FONT></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By The Associated Press</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">W</FONT>ASHINGTON -- Shrugging off calls from several Republicans to surrender power, Newt Gingrich lobbied the House GOP rank-and-file in private on Monday for a new term as speaker despite admitted ethics violations.
<P>    &#39;&#39;He was not contrite. He was not apologetic. He was sincere and persuasive,&#39;&#39; said Rep. Henry Hyde of Illinois. Republican leaders insisted after the 31/2-hour session that Gingrich would prevail when the votes were cast at the opening session of the 105th Congress today.
<P>    One lawmaker said that in the emotionally draining meeting, Gingrich told Republicans he expected no further embarrassing disclosures to come out in his case. Others said the Georgian accused Democrats of using the House ethics committee for political mischief.
<P>    &#39;&#39;Basically, he let the members know that this is not about Newt Gingrich. This is about political assassination,&#39;&#39; said Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas, the GOP whip.
<P>    Gingrich himself said little as he left the meeting. He told reporters it had gone &#39;&#39;very well. I had a great time.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Still, it was clear his critics were determined to follow through with their plans to oppose him. Rep. Jim Leach of Iowa, recently elected to his 11th term, issued a written statement saying the Georgian was &#39;&#39;ethically damaged&#39;&#39; and that &#39;&#39;for the country&#39;s sake&#39;&#39; should be replaced by another Republican.
<P>    Rep. Linda Smith of Washington said she also would oppose Gingrich because, once returned to office, &#39;&#39;he will take all the focus off the positive agenda and onto him.&#39;&#39; At least two other Republicans indicated plans to oppose Gingrich&#39;s re-election.
<P>    A public opinion poll showed two-thirds of Americans, including half of Republicans, believe Gingrich should be replaced as speaker. The same CNN-USA Today-Gallup survey found 41 percent of Americans said Gingrich should resign from Congress altogether.
<P>    A CBS News poll also released Monday found 51 percent of Americans saying the charges against Gingrich are serious enough to justify his replacement as speaker, 33 percent said they are not and the rest didn&#39;t know.
<P>    After the Republican caucus, Rep. John Boehner of Ohio, the fourth-ranking Republican in the House, flatly predicted Gingrich would be re-elected.
<P>    After two years of steadfast denials of wrongdoing, Gingrich conceded on Dec. 21 that &#39;&#39;in my name and over my signature, inaccurate, incomplete and unreliable statements were given to the (ethics) committee.&#39;&#39;
<P>    In addition, he agreed to an ethics committee statement that he had failed to &#39;&#39;seek and follow&#39;&#39; legal advice that would have told him he was improperly using tax-exempt organizations to further political aims.
<P>    The ethics committee is expected to meet in the next several days to determine Gingrich&#39;s punishment, and ultimately the issue will reach the House floor.
<P>    In comments echoed by other Republicans, Rep. William Goodling of Pennsylvania said Gingrich had assured fellow Republicans at the caucus that he believes there are no further damaging disclosures to emerge in his case.
<P>    Other lawmakers said Gingrich fielded questions about his case and blamed the Democrats.
<P>    Rep. Mark Foley of Florida told reporters that while Gingrich&#39;s critics spoke, they received a cooler reception that his supporters.
<P>    &#39;&#39;To those who suggested that Newt step aside there hasn&#39;t been any applause,&#39;&#39; Foley said. &#39;&#39;But to those suggesting Newt remain as speaker there have been strong ovations.&#39;&#39;
<P><font size=2><strong><p>Copyright 1997 by the Associated Press. All Rights Reserved. Unauthorized use is probihited. </p</strong></font>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
