<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>Panel wants to curtail number of felons entering state</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 07, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>Panel wants to curtail number of felons entering state</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Rebecca Ferrar, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">N</FONT>ASHVILLE -- More than twice as many murderers, rapists and pedophiles on probation move to Tennessee than leave for other states, a legislative committee concluded Monday.
<P>   A special House committee called by Rep. Doug Jackson, D-Dickson, hopes to remedy problems under the federal Interstate Compact, an agreement between 40 states regrading the movement of parolees and felons on probation.
<P>   The compact permits monitoring of these individuals from state to state, but Jackson, other state officials and victims rights&#39; groups say Tennessee is getting the short end of the stick.
<P>   In fact, persons convicted in other states are attracted to Tennessee.
<P>   &#39;&#39;The word on the street is that there are a lot of jobs in the state,&#39;&#39; said Bobby Halliburton, Department of Correction assistant commissioner and compact administrator. Felons &#39;&#39;said they have no family here; they said it is a low-property tax state, there&#39;s no income tax and there&#39;s a low crime rate.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Part of the problem may be in Tennessee.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We all know we have some problems with letting more offenders in than we send out,&#39;&#39; said Correction Commissioner Donal Campbell.
<P>   The Correction Department oversees felons on probation -- that is, felons who have not served time in prison but are under supervision for crimes committed elsewhere. In the 1995-96 year, 1,158 felons on probation entered Tennessee, compared to 515 that left the state.
<P>   In contrast, the Board of Paroles oversees parolees in Tennessee under the compact but gets about the same number from other states as leave Tennessee.
<P>   The Board of Paroles reported 599 parolees -- felons who have served prison time -- had moved here in November, compared to 572 that left that month.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We interpret the compact very strictly,&#39;&#39; said Donna Blackburn, executive director of the Board of Paroles.
<P>   The compact was approved at the federal level in 1934 and adopted in Tennessee in 1955.
<P>   Debbie English, Correction Department legal counsel, said it was intended to provide supervision of felons &#39;&#39;to protect the community&#39;&#39; and to provide &#39;&#39;rehabilitation through monitoring.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Under the terms of the compact, felons on probation and parolees in other states may enter Tennessee if they are residents, have family members here, have jobs waiting here or get Tennessee&#39;s approval, English said.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We have very dangerous individuals entering the state,&#39;&#39; Jackson said.
<P>   Campbell conceded his department could do a better job. Policies for probationers entering Tennessee, for example, are not up to date, as opposed to the policies of the Board of Paroles, which told the committee it has tough, written guidelines.
<P>   &#39;&#39;There are changes that will be made,&#39;&#39; Campbell said. &#39;&#39;We recognize that there are some problems.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Defining a felon&#39;s family in writing and requiring that the felon live within 20 miles of his family may be recommended, Campbell said.
<P>   Jackson and other committee members proposed legislation or Correction Department changes to:
<P>   * Adopt tough compact rules for admission to the state.
<P>   * Reject nonresidents.
<P>   * Reject applicants with proposed jobs that are inappropriate.
<P>   * Make it a felony in Tennessee to violate other states&#39; parole or probation.
<P>   * Make it a crime to give false information when applying to move under the compact, and make it an offense if the parolee/probationer violates Tennessee&#39;s probation and parole laws.
<P>   Now, the person may be sent to the convicting state if they violate parole and probation laws there.
<P>   The committee meets again in late January.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
