<head>
	<title>State crash data show 1 of every 4 16-year-olds involved in accidents</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 07, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>State crash data show 1 of every 4 16-year-olds involved in accidents</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By The Associated Press</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">N</FONT>ASHVILLE -- The 16th year is anything but sweet for Tennessee teenaged drivers and their parents, according to a survey.
<P>    The Nashville Banner examined 1993-95 reports of crashes involving drivers who were 16 years old, the minimum age for obtaining a driver&#39;s license.
<P>    The survey found that about one of every four licensed 16-year-olds was involved in a crash during each of those years.
<P>    That compared to one crash per 25 licensed drivers for all other age groups during the same period.
<P>    Of Tennessee&#39;s 95 counties, Sumner County ranked worst, the Banner reported.
<P>    Sixteen-year-old drivers accounted for about 1 percent of the state&#39;s licensed drivers during each of the years in question, yet annually they were involved in about 5.5 percent of the total accidents in the state.
<P>    While a majority of the crashes by 16-year-olds produced property damage only, the number of injury-producing crashes rose to 3,048 in 1995. There were 30 fatalities among 16-year-olds in 1995.
<P>   Diane Thorne, director of the Governor&#39;s Highway Safety Office, said novice drivers need to understand that an accident is no accident if it&#39;s preventable.
<P>    &#39;&#39;We need to quit calling them accidents,&#39;&#39; Thorne said. &#39;&#39;They are wrecks. They are crashes. They are not accidents.&#39;&#39;
<P>    State Rep. John Deberry, D-Memphis, blames Tennessee&#39;s licensing system.
<P>    &#39;&#39;It&#39;s too easy,&#39;&#39; said DeBerry, who tried unsuccessfully in 1995 to raise Tennessee&#39;s minimum licensing age from 16 to 17.
<P>    DeBerry complains that teens progress from bicycles to cars within a matter of a year.
<P>   &#39;&#39;If a kid can park a car, drive around the block with a driving inspector and he can see, then he can get an unrestricted license. That&#39;s where the problem is,&#39;&#39; he said.
<P>  Researchers say teens&#39; inexperience and willingness to take risks hamper them from the first moment they grip the steering wheel.
<P>    Their abilities to &#39;&#39;search and scan&#39;&#39; the roadway are less developed than more-experienced motorists, and they are &#39;&#39;more likely to perceive hazardous situations as less dangerous than they are,&#39;&#39; said Pat Waller, director of the University of Michigan Transportation Research Institute.
<P>    &#39;&#39;For instance, they&#39;re unable to recognize that they should move over when they see cars trying to merge,&#39;&#39; Waller says.
<P><font size=2><strong><p>Copyright 1997 by the Associated Press. All Rights Reserved. Unauthorized use is probihited. </p</strong></font>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
