<html>
<head>
	<title>Avi tells his story</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 07, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Avi tells his story</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Award-winning author serializes novel for newspapers</FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Amy McRary, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">A</FONT>vi, the author with one name and more than 90 awards for his children&#39;s books, has written a serialized children&#39;s novel for newspapers.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Keep Your Eye on Amanda&#39;&#39; tells the adventures of two young twins who happen to be raccoons. Amanda, as guessed by the title, is the curious rascal of the pair. The story&#39;s 21 chapters start today and will be published each Tuesday in The News-Sentinel.
<P>   Serializing a novel isn&#39;t a new concept, but it hasn&#39;t been done often in today&#39;s papers. &#39;&#39;I am of the age where I remember reading books serialized in newspapers as a kid,&#39;&#39; said Avi, an avid newspaper reader. &#39;&#39;It is something I have always wanted to do and it somehow all worked out.
<P>  &#39;&#39;It&#39;s an exciting opportunity to bring something wonderful to kids,&#39;&#39; said Avi in a recent telephone interview from his Boulder, Colo., home. &#39;&#39;I feel like there is some sort of mission involved here in the best sense of the word.&#39;&#39;
<P>   The idea for &#39;&#39;Amanda&#39;&#39; came from Avi&#39;s kitchen. &#39;&#39;I moved here a little more than a year ago to Colorado. Two days later, I walked down and there were a couple of raccoons in my kitchen. I had to chase them out. During the summer, I was having dinner and five raccoons walked in.&#39;&#39; 
<P>   A novel serialization is among the several different writing styles employed by Avi, whose first book was published in 1970. He&#39;s written a comic book -- &#39;&#39;City of Light, City of Dark&#39;&#39; -- and composed another book entirely in dialogue -- &#39;&#39;Who Was That Masked Man, Anyway?&#39;&#39; Well known for historical fiction like the Newbery Honor Book &#39;&#39;The True Confessions of Charlotte Doyle,&#39;&#39; Avi&#39;s also written the funny &#39;&#39;Romeo and Juliet -- Together (And Alive) and the spooky &#39;&#39;Something Upstairs.&#39;&#39; His new two-book &#39;&#39;Beyond the Western Sea&#39;&#39; novel about 1851 immigration from Europe to America was written in the style of the Victorian novel. Two new books -- &#39;&#39;Finding Providence&#39;&#39; and the story collection &#39;&#39;What Do Fish Have To Do With Anything?&#39;&#39; --  are scheduled to be released this year.
<P>     Although he is a prolific author who works on several books at once, Avi says writing is extremely difficult. &#39;&#39;Amanda&#39;&#39; took eight to nine months to complete.
<P>   &#39;&#39;It&#39;s a long, slow process of endless rewriting; I rewrite 40 to 50 times.&#39;&#39; He may get tired of retelling the story, &#39;&#39;but the fact is it gets better all the time.&#39;&#39; 
<P>   Growing up Avi dreamed of designing and flying airplanes, not of creating and writing books. He lives with a learning disability that makes writing and spelling a laborious process. &#39;&#39;I am still a bad speller,&#39;&#39; he says.
<P>   But at age 16 he dreamed of becoming a playwright after a tutor encouraged him. &#39;&#39;She looked through the dishevel and the mess and said, &#39;You&#39;re interesting. I like you.&#39; &#39;&#39;
<P>   A former librarian, Avi spends lots of time researching his books&#39; time period and/or subject. &#39;&#39;For every 100 pieces of information, you use one.&#39;&#39; He frequently reads his in-process books to school groups or shares them with writer friends. He&#39;s changed books after watching -- not hearing -- the reactions of young listeners.
<P>   &#39;&#39;You sense it&#39;s not working very well and you go back and change,&#39;&#39; he says.
<P>
<P>&#39;&#39;Kids are very polite, but they can get restless. And when there&#39;s all that squirming around, you know it&#39;s not there. If they are still, you know you have them. It&#39;s not their comments, but their body movement.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Avi worked as a librarian for years while writing, hoping his books would be published. He tried writing adult novels, none of which were published. &#39;&#39;I think I must have thrown those out,&#39;&#39; he now says. He left his librarian job to write full time 17 years after his first book -- a collection of stories he told his older son -- was published. 
<P>   His audience has likely changed in more than two decades &#39;&#39;but it&#39;s not something I&#39;m conscious of.&#39;&#39;
<P>   &#39;&#39;(Because of) the nature of television, the pace of it, you have to be able to tell a story that gets off the mark very quickly, that holds a kid&#39;s attention. But once you do that, it&#39;s not very difficult.&#39;&#39; 
<P>   He frequently speaks to school groups and is often asked for his advice about writing. He doesn&#39;t soft-peddle the nature of his craft.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I tell them the most important thing to do for writing is to read. Reading teaches you more about writing than anything else. 
<P>   &#39;&#39;I try to tell them it&#39;s very hard; I don&#39;t pretend it&#39;s easy. Simply because a lot of kids get very frustrated thinking that they don&#39;t write very well. If they are frustrated, that&#39;s a good sign. If they think they have written something really good the first time, they&#39;re in trouble.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Being discouraged is what writing is all about -- you look at it and think, &#39;That could be better.&#39; . . . But there is wonderful satisfaction in writing a story that works.&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
