<html>
<head>
	<title>Mother-to-be, who allegedly injected drug, to be charged</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 07, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Mother-to-be, who allegedly injected drug, to be charged</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Don Jacobs, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">P</FONT>olice will charge a 32-year-old pregnant prostitute with reckless endangerment because she allegedly injected herself with cocaine, prosecutors said Monday.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We think it probably fits the reckless endangerment statute,&#39;&#39; Knox County District Attorney General Randy Nichols said.
<P>   The prostitute, who gave a North Knoxville address, was listed Monday in serious condition at the University of Tennessee Medical Center. She was taken Saturday to the facility after she was found bleeding severely from the vaginal area.
<P>   At first, the woman told police she had miscarried the 7-month-old fetus. An examination by doctors revealed otherwise.
<P>   &#39;&#39;There&#39;s no evidence that she tried to self-abort,&#39;&#39; Nichols said. &#39;&#39;There was some problem with the pregnancy, and she thought she had miscarried.
<P>   &#39;&#39;The police probably saved the child&#39;s life. We&#39;re told the baby has a very healthy heartbeat.&#39;&#39;
<P>   When Knoxville officers encountered the prostitute on Milligan Street, she had been scuffling with another woman, records show. The other woman told police she was trying to help the prostitute, whose jeans were soaked in blood.
<P>   The other woman told police the prostitute had just injected herself with cocaine.
<P>   Nichols said state law allows a person to be charged if he or she engages in conduct that could cause serious bodily injury to an unborn child. Nichols said the charge would be a misdemeanor carrying a maximum of nine months in jail upon conviction.
<P>   Because the prostitute has other pending charges, including failure to appear in court and possession of drug paraphernalia, police said they probably won&#39;t charge the woman until she is released from the hospital. The woman has a criminal history with more than a dozen convictions -- including two for prostitution -- dating to 1984, records show.
<P>   &#39;&#39;If I can keep her in jail, she won&#39;t be able to smoke crack cocaine,&#39;&#39; Nichols said.
<P>   What happens after the baby is born?
<P>   &#39;&#39;I don&#39;t know the answer to that,&#39;&#39; Nichols said. &#39;&#39;I&#39;ve never attempted to take a child from a mother like this before.&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
