<head>
	<title>Selection of industrial sites under study in Hamblen</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 07, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Selection of industrial sites under study in Hamblen</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Jim Balloch, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">M</FONT>ORRISTOWN -- A proposed industrial park in south Hamblen County, which created a political firestorm and led to a citywide referendum in November, is the subject of a study committee.
<P>   The committee, appointed by Morristown Mayor J.B. Shockley shortly after city voters rejected a bond issue of up to $5.775 million to finance the park, will hold at least two public hearings, said council member Kay Senter, who is committee chair.
<P>   Other committee members are Councilman Luke Pack, who opposed the use of eminent domain to take land for the park; the Rev. Frank W. Houston; Carl Storms; and Lynn Elkins.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Some people think the committee&#39;s purpose is to pick a site, but that is not correct,&#39;&#39; Senter said. &#39;&#39;We were appointed to establish the criteria for selection of a site.&#39;&#39;
<P>   The date for the first public hearing has not been set, but it will be late this month, Senter said.
<P>   When Shockley appointed the committee, he said it was in part to heal division the industrial park issue had created.
<P>   &#39;&#39;One of the major bones of contention about the proposed site is, and was, what makes a site suitable for an industrial park,&#39;&#39; Shockley said. &#39;&#39;We need a good solid description of what qualities will and would make a good, successful industrial park site.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Several days after the committee was formed, an issue of Tennessee Town and City magazine published an interview Shockley had given after the referendum. His remarks indicate the city remains committed to the originally targeted site.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Our plan is the same as the initial plan -- to appraise, negotiate and purchase,&#39;&#39; Shockley said in the interview. &#39;&#39;This is a prime spot to locate an industrial park. The state of Tennessee will tell you that. Our industrial boards here will tell you that, even though we have a very few unwilling sellers.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Park supporters, organized as Citizens for Progress, argue that the site is the best suitable industrial site remaining in Hamblen County and that the park is critical to securing the area&#39;s economic future. That future, they say, is threatened by emotional anti-park arguments raised by a few landowners.
<P>   Some of the targeted landowners, organized as Stop the Industrial Park, are angry that they learned from news media that their property had been selected and could be taken by eminent domain if they did not want to sell. They also raised questions about the site selection process.
<P>   After a divided Morristown City Council approved the bond issue, STIP persuaded enough city voters to sign a petition calling for the referendum, which defeated the bond issue.
<P>   Tim Hopson, president of STIP,  said his group suspects pro-park forces have no intention of considering any other site.
<P>    &#39;&#39;They are for this one, do or die,&#39;&#39; he said. &#39;&#39;We believe the committee members are all sincere folks and will do the very best job they can.
<P>    &#39;&#39;But anything they come up with has to go through City Council, and (the pro-park forces) still have the majority vote there.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Senter said that while the committee &#39;&#39;was probably created as a public relations gesture . . . I believe we can take it a step further and produce some independent results of substance. For instance, I think we can produce some recommendations which, if followed, will improve the process used in the future to select any site for any project.&#39;&#39;
<P>   She said the committee can, among other things, independently evaluate a criteria list presented by the city&#39;s industrial development board, which selected the south Hamblen site.
<P>   &#39;&#39;If nothing else,&#39;&#39; she added, &#39;&#39;we will make sure everyone who wants to be heard on this will get to be heard.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Campaign financial statements, filed after the referendum, show that Citizens for Progress received more than $20,000 in contributions during the second reporting period -- including a $1,500 contribution from the Industrial Development Board of the city of Morristown.
<P>   Morristown&#39;s newspaper, the Citizen-Tribune, contributed $1,000. The Citizen-Tribune&#39;s publisher, Jack Fishman, is chairman of the city&#39;s Industrial Development Board.
<P>   Morristown City Administrator Mike Lutche contributed $1,000.   Other contributions include:
<P>
<P>   * $2,000 from Tenn-Rental.
<P>   * $1,000 from Barge Waggoner Sumner & Cannon Engineers Architects & Planners, which produced site maps for the project and whose engineer, Randy Corlew, is a member of the Industrial Development Board and chairman of the Chamber of Commerce&#39;s private industrial development board.
<P>   * $1,000 each from Wallace Hardware; Franklin Federal; Tuff Torq; Price and Price; First Tennessee Bank; Bacon, Jessee, Perkins and Swanson; United Southern Bank; Sun Trust; Greene County Bank.
<P>   * $500 each from ISU Agency; Tennessee Industrial Disposal; Lakeway Hotels; ACN Inc.; Toyoda TRW; United Cities Gas; Andrew Johnson Bank; Rusty Wallace Pontiac; Morristown Ford; Coffman Oil; Rogers Petroleum; Pioneer Petroleum; and McGuffin Truss.
<P>
<P>     For the same period, STIP contributions, largely from individuals, totaled $520. In the first reporting period, STIP was also heavily outfinanced by Citizens for Progress.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

