<head>
	<title>Murder defendant to be hospitalized for mental care</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 07, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Murder defendant to be hospitalized for mental care</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By John North, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">M</FONT>urder defendant Richard A. Tate was sent to a state mental health institute Monday after two experts found him incompetent to stand trial for killing his young son in 1990.
<P>   Knox County Criminal Court Judge Richard Baumgartner ordered Tate, 32, sent to Middle Tennessee Mental Health Institute in Nashville. He will remain hospitalized until his mental health improves enough for him to stand trial, the judge said.
<P>   Tate&#39;s institutionalization came seven years to the day that he allegedly slashed and nearly decapitated 13-month-old Michael B. Tate. Knox County prosecutors are seeking the death penalty.
<P>    The case is among the oldest active prosecutions in Knox County Criminal Court.
<P>   Knox County District Public Defender Mark Stephens and Assistant Public Defender John Halstead contend Tate is mentally retarded as well as mentally ill. Tate was evaluated last month in separate sessions by psychologist Eric Engumand Dr. Clif Tennison, a psychiatrist at Helen Ross McNabb Center Inc.
<P>   The experts noted Tate suffers from paranoia and recently tried to hang himself in the Knox County Jail. Engum and Tennison said Tate also suffers from hallucinations or misperceptions.
<P>   Tate has been beaten several times by jail inmates and has complained of poor treatment by guards. Stephens said jail authorities have worked with him to try to make his client&#39;s life better.
<P>   Tate appeared in court Monday with a large red scrape on his left cheek. Stephens said his client, who has served time in prison on other convictions, dug out the skin where prisoners once forcibly placed a beauty mark.
<P>   Tate&#39;s case has been delayed through the years in part because lawyers debated who should prosecute him. The Knox County district attorney general&#39;s office ultimately was removed from the case; 9th Judicial District prosecutors took over.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
