	<title>&#39;Cleaner&#39; coal set for Memphis TVA plant</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 07, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>&#39;Cleaner&#39; coal set for Memphis TVA plant</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By The Associated Press</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">M</FONT>EMPHIS -- An agreement between the Tennessee Valley Authority and Memphis health authorities means the agency will cut smog-producing pollution at one of its facilities.
<P>   Memphis Health Department officials want TVA to curb the release of nitrogen dioxide at the Allen Fossil Plant generating station in southwest Memphis. Nitrogen dioxide reacts with sunlight to form ozone, a lung-damaging component of smog.
<P>   The agreement requires that 65 percent of the coal burned between May 1 and Oct. 1 each year be of a cleaner-burning, low-sulfur variety mined in Western states.
<P>   Local officials will write the agreement into the operating conditions of the plant&#39;s air pollution permit, said Carter Gray of the Health Department. TVA air regulatory specialist Steven Strunk said the agency hopes to burn all low-sulfur coal at the plant and exceed the terms of the agreement.
<P>
<P><font size=2><strong><p>Copyright 1997 by the Associated Press. All Rights Reserved. Unauthorized use is probihited. </p</strong></font>
