<head>
	<title>3 lawmakers say no to medicinal marijuana</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 07, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>3 lawmakers say no to medicinal marijuana</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By The Associated Press</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">N</FONT>ASHVILLE -- Sen. Bill Frist and two Tennessee representatives are opposed to wider use of marijuana as medicine.
<P>   Voters in California and Arizona have approved exempting doctors from prosecution if they recommend marijuana for their patients.
<P>   But the Clinton administration said it will continue enforcing the federal ban on using marijuana as medicine.
<P>   Frist, a heart transplant surgeon, said Senate and House colleagues have sought him out for advice on the matter.
<P>   &#39;&#39;There is no demonstrated medical use of the drug,&#39;&#39; said Frist, a Republican. &#39;&#39;We do need more scientific studies. . . . I think it does boil down to science in terms of are there specific medical indications in which this is the only drug available.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Rep. Ed Bryant, R-Henderson, a former federal prosecutor in West Tennessee, said he found it incredible that a state could vote to legalize pot.
<P>   &#39;&#39;How a majority could vote that way? . . . Maybe they inhaled before they went, I don&#39;t know.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Bryant said he is against any effort &#39;&#39;under any guise, to legalize a very harmful drug.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Rep. Bart Gordon, D-Murfreesboro, shares Bryant&#39;s views.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I oppose any attempts to weaken our laws governing narcotics,&#39;&#39; he said. &#39;&#39;If any substance has medicinal value, the FDA (Food and Drug Administration) has a procedure to scientifically analyze the evidence and approve drugs accordingly.&#39;&#39;
<P>   But Grant Houston, past director of the Nashville chapter of the National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws, or NORML, said clear evidence has been presented about the value of marijuana.
<P>   &#39;&#39;The administration and the DEA (Drug Enforcement Administration) are impeding the understanding of the truth by playing with nitpick details and keeping smoke in the public&#39;s eye,&#39;&#39; he said.
<P>   &#39;&#39;It (the government) wants us to get our information from politicians and policemen. This government is more interested in vomiting in pain correctly rather than a puff of a marijuana cigarette.&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P><font size=2><strong><p>Copyright 1997 by the Associated Press. All Rights Reserved. Unauthorized use is probihited. </p</strong></font>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
