<P>
<P><B></B>
<P><B>ADAMS, RAY B. - </B>age 70, of Knoxville, died 5 a.m. Monday, January 6, 1997, at the family home. Member of Washington Pike Methodist Church. Driver for Lay&#39;s Packing Company for over 41 years. Preceded in death by wife, Trula Marie Adams; parents, Buford and Grace Adams; sister, Betty Vanosdale. Survivors: wife, Marion L. Adams; daughter and son-in-law, Rachel and Mike King; stepdaughters and husbands,  Pam and Ben Lane, Maryland, Carol and Rickie Harris, Tammy and Jimmy Bounds; stepdaughter, Cathy Hall; son and daughter-in-law, Michael R. and Shelia Adams; stepsons and wives, Greg and Minnie Hall, Joey and Lee Hall, both of Texas, Tony and Libby Hall; 18 grandchildren and two great-grandchildren; brother and sister-in-law, Roy H. and Helen Adams, all of Knoxville. Funeral service will be 1 p.m. Wednesday, Stevens Chapel, Rev. Bob Zavattieri and Rev. Sam Jollay officiating. Interment will follow in Lynnhurst Cemetery. Pallbearers: Billy Harris, Scott Ritch, Brett Palmer, Joe King, Ralph Lamb, Junior Ammons. The family will receive friends 7-9 p.m. Tuesday, Stevens Mortuary, Oglewood Ave. at Broadway.
<P>
<P><B>BAUMGARTNER, RALPH E. - </B>age 83, of Harriman, passed away Sunday, January 5, 1997, at the Athens Regional Medical Center. He was a member of South Harriman Baptist Church and retired from Burlington Mills after almost 50 years service. Survivors: wife, Lucy Baumgartner; son, Ronald E. Baumgartner of Austell, Ga.; stepson, David Reed of Harriman; stepdaughters, Linda Martin of Charlotte, N.C., Glenda Lantz of Harriman; brother, Rev. L.R. Baumgartner of Nashville; two grandchildren; four great-grandchildren and several other grandchildren. Funeral 2 p.m. Wednesday at South Harriman Baptist Church, Reverend Edsel West and Rev. L.R. Baumgartner officiating. Interment in Willard Park Cemetery. The family will receive friends 7-9 p.m. Tuesday at Kyker Funeral Home, Harriman.
<P>
<P><B>BURDEN, PEGGY WILSON HEADRICK - </B>age 54, of Knoxville, passed away January 5, 1997, at Ft. Sanders Medical Center. Member of Bethel Baptist Church, Pine Grove Rd., Knoxville. Preceded in death by her husband, Gabriel &#39;&#39;Don&#39;&#39; Burden; parents, George and Myrtle Wilson; brother, Benny Wilson; and brother-in-law, Danny Branch. Survivors: daughter and son-in-law, Candy and Paul Sellers; sons and daughters-in-law, Richard and Kelli Burden, Randall and Jennifer Burden; grandchildren, Sierra and Tori Sellers, Madison, Carolyn JoAnn and Crista Sky Burden; sister, Sarah Branch; sisters and brothers-in-law, Gladys and John Luttrell, Kathy and Don LaFollette; stepmother, Bobbie Wilson; special friend, Jack Reed; many nieces, nephews, cousins and friends. Funeral service 8 p.m. Tuesday, McCarty Chapel, Rev. Archie Elliott and Rev. Jack Oglesby officiating. Family and friends will meet 1:45 p.m. Wednesday at Pratt&#39;s Chapel Cemetery for a 2 p.m. graveside service and interment. Pallbearers: Scotty Runion, Brian Elliott, Dusty Kennedy, Frank and Jessie Sellers, Martin Headrick. A  special thanks to Dr. David Slutzker and Associates and the staff of Ft. Sanders Medical Center. The family will receive friends 6-8 p.m. Tuesday at McCarty Mortuary, 4004 Holston Drive.
<P>
<P><B>BUTTRAM, ELIZABETH DANIEL - </B>age 93, of Harriman, passed away Saturday, January 4, 1997, at Roane Medical Center. Member of Walnut Hill Baptist Church, Harriman. Lineage goes back to Marcus L. and Martha May Daniel / Edward and Pheby Mayes Hodge. Preceded in death by husband, C.E. Buttram, Sr.; brothers, Gene, Moss and Walter Daniel. Survivors: son and daughter-in-law, Claude E. and Lucille R. Buttram Jr. of Harriman; grandson and wife, Claude E. and Ann R. Buttram III of Knoxville; great-granddaughter, Heather Michelle Buttram of Knoxville; sister-in-law, Loretto Daniel of Southfield, Mich.; four nephews; three nieces. Funeral 8 p.m. Tuesday at Kyker Funeral Home Chapel in Harriman with Rev. Dennis Jarnagin and Rev. Mike Winters officiating. Interment 10 a.m. Wednesday at Roane Memorial Gardens. The family will receive friends 6-8 p.m. Tuesday at Kyker Funeral Home in Harriman. In lieu of flowers, donations may be made to Walnut Hill Baptist Church.
<P>
<P><B>BYERLY, ELMORE E. - </B>age 89, of Brakebill Nursing Home, passed away 12 noon Monday, January 6, 1997. Member of House Mountain Baptist Church. Preceded in death by his wife, Doshia Raley Byerly and son, Bobby Byerly. Survivors: son and daughter-in-law, Ted and Ruth Byerly; grandchildren, Danny and Mike Byerly, Thea Carter; six great-grandsons. Funeral service 8 p.m. Wednesday, McCarty Chapel, Rev. John Shepherd officiating. Family and friends will meet 9:45 a.m. Thursday at Lynnhurst Cemetery for graveside service and interment at 10 a.m. The family will receive friends 6-8 p.m. Wednesday at McCarty Mortuary, 4004 Holston Drive.
<P>
<P><B>COLEMAN, ELEANOR JEAN - </B>age 67, of Strawberry Plains, passed away Sunday, January 5, 1997, at Ft. Sanders Regional Medical Center. Retired from Electric Service Company. Survived by husband, Howard G. Coleman, Jr.; daughter, Linda Carver; grandchildren, Cara and Josh Carver; parents, Thomas C. and Eleanor Bigler; sister, Barbara Long; several nieces and nephews. Family and friends will meet 10:15 a.m. Wednesday at McCarty Mortuary and proceed to Caledonia Cemetery for an 11 a.m. graveside service with Rev. Robert McCray officiating. The family will receive friends 7-9 p.m. Tuesday at McCarty Mortuary, 4004 Holston Drive.
<P>
<P><B>DAVIS, LEETHA VIOLA - </B>of North Knoxville, died Monday, January 6, 1997. She was a member of First Baptist Church of Knoxville and the former Bell Ave. Baptist Church. The widow of Carl F. Davis, Sr., she is survived by son and daughter-in-law, Carl and Gladys Davis of Knoxville; grandchildren, David and Alice Davis, Danny Davis; great-grandchildren, Molly, Zackary and Amy Davis. Funeral service 8 p.m. Wednesday, Rose Mortuary Broadway Chapel with Rev. Dave Ward officiating. Family and friends will meet at Strawberry Plains Cemetery Thursday for an 11 a.m. interment service. Nephews will serve as pallbearers. The family will receive friends 6:30-8 p.m. Tuesday at Rose Mortuary Broadway Chapel.
<P>
<P><B>DeLANEY, RUBY AKARD - </B>age 83, of Knoxville, died Saturday, January 4th., 1997 at her home. Member of Second United Methodist Church and former member of Deaderick Avenue Baptist Churcb. She was retired from the Insurance Department of Valley Fidelity Bank/First Tennessee with over 30 years service. She was the oldest member of Omni Neighborhood Association. She was preceded in death by husband, Charles E. DeLaney. Survivors: nieces, Gail Copeland of Cookeville, Tenn., Barbara Drotos of Cheyenne, Wyo.; great-nieces, Greta Wallace of Charlotte, N.C., Beverly Drotos of Cheyenne, Wyo.; great-nephews, Jimmy Copeland of Columbia, Tenn., Greg Copeland; Fort Mill, S.C., Dan Drotos of Richmond, Va. Funeral services 2 p.m. Wednesday, Rose Broadway Chapel, Rev. J. Russell (Rusty) Taylor officiating. Interment Lynnhurst Cemetery. Family will receive friends 12:30-2 p.m. Wednesday at Rose Mortuary Broadway Chapel.
<P> 
<P><B>DICKERSON, JOHN RAY - </B>age 57, of Knoxville, passed away Saturday, January 4, 1997, in Jacksonville, Fla. Preceded in death by mother, Lillian Keeler, and father, John Dickerson. Survivors: children, Darlene Housewright, Donnie Ray, Connie, John Rayburn, Douglas Dewayne, Troy LaDon, John Davis and Michael Dean Dickerson; 12 grandchildren; sisters, Casey Daniels, Betty Pappas, Dorothy Turner and Carol Taylor; several nieces and nephews. Service 11 a.m. Wednesday, Mynatt&#39;s Chapel, Rev. Johnny Carver officiating. Interment Tennessee State Veterans Cemetery. Pallbearers will be sons. Military honors will be provided by East Tennessee Veterans Honor Guard. The family will receive friends 7-9 p.m. Tuesday at Mynatt&#39;s.
<P>
<P><B>FONDE, RHEA KING - </B>age 104, of Knoxville, died January 5, 1997, at Ft. Sanders Regional Medical Center at 6:20 a.m. She was a member of the Episcopal Church of the Ascension. Preceded in death by husband of 53 years, Charles Henry Fonde; and her daughter, Rhea King Nathan of Muscle Shoals, Ala.; and son-in-law, Calvin Walter of Knoxville. Survivors: son and daughter-in-law, Henry and Edith Fonde; daughters and sons-in-law, Frankie and Tom Brogan, Alice and Garnett Kincaid; daughter, Anne Walter; son-in-law, Robert Nathan, Muscle Shoals, Ala.; 21 grandchildren; 27 great-grandchildren. Funeral services 2 p.m. Tuesday, January 7, 1997, the Episcopal Church of the Ascension, Northshore Drive, The Rev. Gordon Temple officiating. Interment Greenwood Cemetery. Pallbearers: Bill Walter, Hank Walter, Martin Walter, Gary Kincaid, Will Walter, David Walter, Charles Fonde, Larry Nathan and John Nathan. In lieu of flowers, memorial gifts may be made in the name of Rhea Fonde to the library fund of the Church of the Ascension. Arrangements by Rose Mortuary Mann Heritage Chapel.
<P>
<P><B>HAYES, MARTHA LANE - </B>age 84, of Strawberry Plains, passed away January 4, 1997, at Ft. Sanders Regional Medical Center. She was a member of Midway Baptist Church. Preceded in death by her husband, Cecil Hayes; parents, John and Lillie Lane; brothers, Jess, John and Glen Lane; sister, Maggie Lane. Graveside service and interment 1 p.m. Tuesday at Cate Cemetery. Active pallbearers: James Disney, Thurman Stallings, Ronnie Poole, John Lane, Kenneth Cate and Jeff Lawhorn. Honorary pallbearers: Clyde Lane, Elijah Cate, Roland Stinnett, Joe Henry Hancock and Calvin Stinnett. The family wishes to extend their thanks to special nurses, Steve Norrod, Imelda Garcia and Jeff Dargan; special friends, Ella Mae Cate, Annie Hancock, Mildred Glen, Billie Stinnett and Gail Stinnett; special cousin, Betty Oglesby. Arrangements by Roberts Chapel of Berry Funeral Home, 2112 Magnolia Ave.
<P>
<P><B>HEWITT, DR. GLENN A. - </B>age 42, of Maryville, died Sunday, January 5, 1997, at Blount Memorial Hospital. He received his BA degree in religion and philosophy from Wake Forest University in North Carolina, his Master of Divinity degree from Southern Baptist Theological Seminary and his Ph.D. from the University of Chicago. His doctorate was in theological ethics. He joined the Maryville College faculty in 1988 and was associate professor of religion and philosophy. At Maryville College he had served as acting chaplain, associate dean and coordinator of the senior ethics course. He was the author of numerous articles and reviews, and a book, Regeneration and Morality (1991). Survivors include wife, Jeanine Hardin Hewitt; father and stepmother, Elwood and Lucy Hewitt of Baltimore, Md.; brother, Carey Hewitt of Ft. Collins, Colo.; sister, Jane Hewitt of Yorktown Heights, N.Y. A memorial service will be held at 10 a.m. Saturday in the Maryville College Center for Campus Ministry (CCM) with Rev. Stephen Nickle, family and friends participating. Those who wish may make memorials to the American Cancer Society, 871 Weisgarber Rd., Knoxville, TN 37909. McCammon-Ammons Funeral Home, Maryville, in charge.
<P>
<P><B>HODGSON, CATHERINE (KITTY) ROBINSON - </B>passed away on January 1, 1997, in Pensacola, Florida. She was a former resident of Knoxville and was an active parishioner at the Church of the Ascension (Episcopal). Born in England, she and her late husband, Bill Hodgson, came to the United States in 1952. Kitty lived a full life of 87 years and leaves a rich legacy of love and service to others. She was a devoted wife and loving mother, grandmother, and great-grandmother. She will be missed by all and we are grateful to God for sharing her with us. She leaves behind a brother and sister in England; daughters, Pat Fielden (Caroline, Alberta), Jean Gibson of Gulf Breeze, Fla. and Pauline Stevenson (Nanaimo, British Columbia); son, Jeff Hodgson (Lenoir City); ten grandchildren; three great-grandchildren and many other family members and friends. A memorial service will be held at the the Church of the Ascension (800 Northshore Drive) on Friday, January 10, at 10:30 a.m. the Reverend Gordon Temple officiating. In lieu of flowers, the family requests that donations be made in Kitty&#39;s name to the chartiy of your choice or the Church of the Ascension in Knoxville.
<P>
<P><B>JOHNSON, FLORA B. MILLER GINN - </B>age 81, longtime resident of Forest Avenue, passed away January 6, 1997, at Mariner Health Care, Norris, Tenn. She was of the Baptist faith. Retired fabric mill worker with Appalachian Mills and Breezy Wynn. Preceded in death by husband, C.O. Johnson, Sr.; brothers, John and Harold Miller; and sister, Alice McKnight. Survivors: daughter, Mildred &#39;&#39;Mickey&#39;&#39; Gregory; sons, Jerry Ogle Ginn, Charles W. Ginn, Jr.; six grandchildren; two great-grandchildren; brother, Charles Miller, Knoxville; sisters, Fannie Allen, Atlanta, Ga., Hazel Taylor, Titusville, Fla., Rosie Holloway and husband, Frankie, Linden, Texas; numerous nieces, nephews and friends. Graveside service 2 p.m. Thursday, Woodlawn Cemetery, Rev. Bill Romines officiating. The family will receive friends 7-9 p.m. Wednesday at Berry Funeral Home, Chapman Highway.
<P>
<P><B>KEEBLE, WILLIAM T. (BILL) - </B>age  84, of Maryville, died Monday, January 6, 1997. He was a member and deacon of Calvary Baptist Church, Alcoa and a member of the 25 Year Club at ALCOA. Preceded in death by wife, Willie (Billie) Mae Teague Keeble. Survivors: sons and daughter-in-law, Donna and Carl E. Halasy of Ohio, Betty and Eli Fields of Maryville; grandchildren, Greg and Keith Halasy, Jama Tarwater, Misty Keeble; brothers, Edgar Keeble of Seymour, Bob Keeble of Maryville; sisters, Belle Rhea of Knoxville, Maude Howell of Maryville, Bernice Blazer, Knoxville; several nieces, nephews and cousins. Funeral service 8 p.m. Wednesday in the Trinity Chapel of Smith Mortuary with the Rev. Danny Davis officiating. Family and friends will assemble at 11 a.m. Thursday at Grandview. In lieu of flowers, memorial donations may be made to Calvary Baptist Church Choir. Family will receive friends 6 p.m. until 8 p.m. Wednesday at Smith Mortuary, Maryville.
<P>
<P><B>KEELE, HULA MAE VINEYARD - </B>age 80, of Sweetwater, passed away suddenly Sunday evening, January 5, 1997, at Sweetwater Hospital. She was preceded in death by her parents, Tom and Mantie Stevens Vineyard; brother, Leslie Vineyard. She was a member of the Sweetwater Rebekah Lodge #25, and also a member of the Christianburg Baptist Church. Survivors: husband, William T. (Tom) Keele, Sweetwater; sister and brother-in-law, Polly and J.W. Starnes, Sweetwater; niece and husband, Alice and Larry Shade, Greenville, Ohio; nephew and wife, Chris and Pam Starnes, Sweetwater; several cousins. The body is at Kyker Funeral Home, Sweetwater, where the family will receive friends 6-8 p.m. Tuesday with the funeral service to follow in Kyker&#39;s Chapel with Rev. Darrell Cardin and Rev. Bernard Courtney officiating. Interment 11 a.m. Wednesday in the Christianburg Baptist Church Cemetery.
<P>
<P><B>LINDSAY, VERTA - </B>age 89, of Knoxville, died Sunday, January 5, 1997. The widow of Luther J. Lindsay, she was also preceded in death by two sons, Hugh Douglas Lindsay and Ray Lindsay. A member of Fairview United Methodist Church, she was a former employee of Holston Knitting Mills and was a licensed practical nurse. Surviving: daughter, Elizabeth Kitts, Knoxville; ten grandchildren and seven great-grandchildren. Funeral services will be held at 1 p.m. Wednesday at Fairview United Methodist Church, the Rev. John Jackson officiating. Interment service will be 2:30 p.m. Wednesday at Woodhaven Memorial Gardens (formerly Tennessee Valley), Claxton. Memorials may be made to Union Rescue Ministries. The family will receive friends 7-9 p.m. Tuesday at Rose Mortuary Broadway Chapel.
