<P><B>WEBB, MRS. BETTY L. - </B>age 71, of Augusta, Ga., died Jan. 5, 1997, at St. Joseph Hospital. She was born in Marion, Ind., and had lived in Augusta since 1955. She was of the Episcopal faith and was a retired post exchange manager. Survivors: husband, George E. Webb; son, John W. Webb, both of Augusta; daughters, Mrs. Sharon Lee W. Glazner, Stone Mtn., Ga., Mrs. Barbara Ann Phillips, Loganville, Ga.; sisters, Mrs. Marcia J. Woodall, Norcross, Ga., Mrs. Esta Raw Kerr, Houston, Texas; grandchildren, Stacey T. Phillips, Avondale, Ga., Todd M. Phillips, Loganville, Ga., and Amber R. Glazner, Stone Mtn., Ga. Funeral service 11 a.m. Wednesday, Jan. 8, 1997, Lumpkin Road Chapel of Elliott Sons Funeral Home, Rev. Forrest E. Stout officiating. Burial Westover Memorial Park. The family will receive friends 7-9 p.m. Tuesday evening at the funeral home.
<P>
<P><B>WOLFE, HAZEL VINEYARD - </B>age 75, of Knoxville, died 2:48 p.m. Monday, January 6, 1997, at St. Mary&#39;s Medical Center. Member of Lincoln Park Baptist Church and the Philethea Sunday School Class. Active at St. John&#39;s Cathedral. Retired from Georgia Marble Co. and A&B Distributing Co. She was a longtime community activist and was a charter member of the Oakwood/Lincoln Park Neighborhood Association dedicated in soliciting funds for the community. She had served as past president and was on the board of directors for several years. She was instrumental in saving and raising funds for the renovation and restoration of the Historic Christenberry Club House for the neighborhood. She had served as the chairperson and hostess for the OLPNA Annual Fall Festival Breakfast for a number of years. Preceded in death by husband, John N. Wolfe; parents, James Thomas and Ora Clark Vineyard. Survivors: daughter and son-in-law, Patti Huffaker Kagel and Norman Kagel; son and daughter-in-law, John (Scrappy) and Sharon Snow Wolfe; grandchildren, Bradley Scott Huffaker, Zachary Snow, Ashley Snow, all of Knoxville; devoted friends, Ellen Askew, Sharlene Witt Barlock, Sue Sharp, Dr. John Dawson and family, Larry Cox, Mayor Victor Ashe; and many, many more friends. Family and friends will meet at Stevens Mortuary at 1:15 p.m. Thursday to go in procession to Highland Memorial Cemetery for a 2 p.m. graveside service and interment, The Reverend Canon John Ross officiating. The family will receive friends 7-9 p.m. Wednesday at Stevens Mortuary, Oglewood Ave. at Broadway.
<P>
<P><B>YOUNG, JAMES NELSON - </B>age 69, of Merced, Calif., formerly of Rutledge, passed away Wednesday, January 1, 1997. He was preceded in death by parents, Pryor and Annie Young; sister, Ruby Donaldson; brothers, Ray and Holly. Survived by daughter, Larita Lindsey of New Market; brothers, J.E. of Indiana, Carroll of Virginia and Curtis of Bean Station; aunts and uncles, Mattie and Elijah Young of Knoxville, Hester Norton of Blaine, Rose Cabbage of Rutledge, and Carl Antrican of Knoxville; several nieces and nephews. Funeral services will be held at 7:30 p.m. Tuesday evening, January 7, 1997, from the Smith Funeral Home Chapel in Rutledge with Rev. Hollis Dunsmore officiating. Graveside services and interment will be at 11 a.m. Wednesday morning, January 8, 1997,  in the Helton Springs Cemetery. The family will receive friends from 6-7:30 p.m. Tuesday evening prior to services at the funeral home. Arrangements by Smith Funeral Home in Rutledge.
