<head>
	<title>Philips&#39; future in area laden with unresolved and worrisome &#39;ifs&#39;</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper Business News">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif" alt="Knoxville News-Sentinel Online -- Business News" align=bottom border=0 width=595 height=176></a><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td align=left valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 07, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Philips&#39; future in area laden with unresolved and worrisome &#39;ifs&#39;</B></font><basefont size=6><!--SUBHEAD--></basefont></FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Pam Park, News-Sentinel business writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">P</FONT>hilips Consumer Electronics recently clarified its intentions regarding its operations in Knoxville, Jefferson City and Greeneville, but there are still some short-term and long-term &#39;&#39;ifs&#39;&#39; remaining.
<P>   The Philips headquarters and 150 people move to Atlanta, but the engineering and support staffers stay in Knoxville. The customer service center stays in Jefferson City. GC Capital is poised to buy and operate the main manufacturing plant in Greeneville, and buyers are being sought for other facilities there.
<P>   The key &#39;&#39;if&#39;&#39; at this point is the sale of the Greeneville Plant 3 facilities to GC Capital LLC.
<P>   Plant 3 houses the television manufacturing, shipping and warehousing and injection molding operations. Right now, about 1,050 workers are employed there, according to their union. In peak production times, the number goes up 500-600.
<P>   Rather than abruptly closing a plant that is underutilized and putting hundreds of people out of work, Philips has sought a buyer. Philips management deserves credit for that. However, the potential new owners, trying to negotiate a deal that will allow them to compete with manufacturing plants across the Mexican border and in the Asia-Pacific region, have run afoul of workers.
<P>   In December, the Plant 3 workers soundly rejected a labor contract that would have cut their benefits significantly and shifted more of the payment burden for continuing benefits to them.
<P>   At an average of $8.55 per hour, Philips Greeneville plant wages were already lower than the $11.03 average manufacturing wage in the Knoxville area. Cuts would put some workers at the poverty line, their union said.
<P>   During the holidays, GC Capital principal George Taylor said he didn&#39;t know what else he could do and was not sure whether he would attempt further contract negotiations.
<P>   Philips has amended 60-day layoff notices for the plant -- originally issued Oct. 3 to be effective Dec. 31 -- until Jan. 13, when it still hopes to close the sale. If there is no immediate labor settlement, Philips could extend the notices still further.
<P>   Whether Philips will extend the notices &#39;&#39;is completely contingent on developing events,&#39;&#39; Philips spokesman Jayson Hill said.
<P>  Speaking of layoff notices, Philips&#39; Oct. 3 WARN (Worker Adjustment and Retraining Notice) Act notice was a blanket statement that indicated<B> </B>all the Philips Greeneville employees were to be permanently laid off in connection with the sale of the facilities. (This was supposed to be a technicality because the new owner was expected to rehire most of them.) After The News-Sentinel and others published a story to that effect, Robert Minkhorst, president and chief executive officer, issued a clarification, saying only the 500 or so seasonal employees were affected by the notice.
<P>   At that time, the Tennessee Department of Labor did not have a copy of the notice on hand. When I requested a copy last week, they said they only had the cover sheet -- they had requested the attachments that detailed the number and positions of workers to be laid off but had not received them. Later, a TDOL spokeswoman called to say the dislocated worker unit was told the notice affected 637 seasonal workers. Since the rest of the employees would be retained by the new company, the state would not need a notice for them, she said.
<P>   Next I asked union officials for a copy of their Oct. 3 WARN notice. It listed 1,933 people to be laid off. Since Philips now says it is extending its notice to Jan. 13, it looks like the Oct. 3 notice applied to the whole lot after all. Or not. Or maybe Philips gets to pick one. Or both.
<P>   In another piece of numerical confusion, Knoxville and Knox County economic development and government leaders were justifiably ecstatic about retaining 850 jobs when Philips decided to move only 150 executive and sales staff to new company headquarters in Atlanta. The engineers and support staff are to stay in Knoxville, at least for the time being. The only problem is that the 850 jobs so joyously cited appear to include about 300 people who work at the Jefferson City service center. That would mean Knoxville actually kept about 550 jobs.
<P>   That&#39;s nothing to sneeze at. Minkhorst seemed pleased to announce it, and we&#39;re definitely pleased to hear it.
<P>   State and local authorities worked hard to find some incentives they could legally offer Philips to keep them here -- most economic incentives are based on attracting new jobs rather than retaining existing ones -- but part of the reason for Philips&#39; decision is its continuing manufacturing relationships in the area. Philips is apparently guaranteeing GC Capital production contracts for four years. At the end of that time, who knows? And what if the GC Capital deal falls through?
<P>   We may be looking at another re-evaluation of Knoxville sometime in the future. All we can do is make sure we&#39;re ready, and competitive.
<P>
<P>Pam Park is a News-Sentinel business writer who follows Philips Consumer Electronics and other technology-related business issues.
<P><B></B>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

