<head>
	<title>DeRoyal purchases Costa Rican company</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper Business News">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif" alt="Knoxville News-Sentinel Online -- Business News" align=bottom border=0 width=595 height=176></a><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td align=left valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 07, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>DeRoyal purchases Costa Rican company</B></font><basefont size=6><!--SUBHEAD--></basefont></FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Pam Park, News-Sentinel business writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">D</FONT>eRoyal Industries Inc. has purchased the assets of a Costa Rican company that makes a key component of its temperature-monitoring medical devices.
<P>   Sensores Cientificos, a manufacturer of sensors with ceramic thermistor chips used to monitor core and surface body temperature during surgery, is now DeRoyal Central America.
<P>   The company has 60 employees in a 13,000 square-foot facility in San Jose, Costa Rica. Chips produced there will be shipped to the DeRoyal campus in Tazewell for completion.
<P>   The asset purchase, for which terms were not disclosed, was both a defensive and offensive move for DeRoyal, said Brian DeBusk, chief operating officer. 
<P>   Sensores Cientificos had been DeRoyal&#39;s supplier since about 1993.
<P>    Then DeRoyal learned the company wanted to sell the Costa Rican facility and consolidate its operations in Saint Kitts in the British West Indies, where it would focus on automotive sensors and generic printed circuit boards.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We looked at this as a threat because it could have interrupted our supply of a key product. On the upside, it was an opportunity to add this technology into our existing manufacturing processes,&#39;&#39; DeBusk said.
<P>   Control of the ceramic thermistor chip is important because it can account for 60 percent to 90 percent of the cost of a sensor component, DeBusk said.
<P>   &#39;&#39;It really is what drives the cost of the completed device,&#39;&#39; he said.
<P>   DeRoyal will use the chips in its products and sell chips to other medical companies. It is expected to improve DeRoyal&#39;s competitive position.
<P>   &#39;&#39;In health care today, the name of the game is becoming a low-cost producer,&#39;&#39; DeBusk said.
<P>   The chips are commonly used in esophageal stethoscopes, which are inserted down the esophagus to monitor heart sounds during surgery. When a sensor chip is included in the device, it can also be used to monitor core body temperature.
<P>    A temperature sensor can be included in Foley catheters for urinary drainage so the catheter can serve a double purpose. It&#39;s more comfortable for the patient, more discreet and more cost effective, DeBusk said.
<P>   Hospitals also use the thermistor chip in measuring the body temperature of babies. They hold it against a newborn baby&#39;s skin with a small pad and use measurements off the probe to control the temperature of an incubator or radiant warmer, he said.
<P>   The chips could be made anywhere, but the process does require &#39;&#39;somewhat skilled&#39;&#39; labor, DeBusk said. More than 90 percent of the Costa Rican work force is literate, by high standards, and they understand technical issues, he said.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I can see why it had been a favorite place for doing this kind of work,&#39;&#39; he said.
<P>   In December DeRoyal signed licensing agreements with Lockheed Martin Energy Research Corp. for the use of two inventions developed at the Oak Ridge National Laboratory.
<P>    Those inventions are expected to offer a better, less costly way to deliver radioisotopes used in medical diagnostic imaging and are also part of DeRoyal&#39;s move into the high technology sector.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
