<head>
	<title>Business Briefs</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper Business News">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif" alt="Knoxville News-Sentinel Online -- Business News" align=bottom border=0 width=595 height=176></a><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td align=left valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 07, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Business Briefs</B></font><basefont size=6><!--SUBHEAD--></basefont></FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<h3>Raytheon to buy TI defense unit</h3>
<P>
<P>   BOSTON -- As defense companies combined around it, Raytheon Co. faced a choice: Get bigger or get out.
<P>   On Monday, Raytheon put its money on the table with an agreement to buy Texas Instruments&#39; defense business for $2.95 billion. The deal increases its chances of being one of the surviving defense contractors.
<P>   Texas Instruments Defense Systems & Electronics Group employs about 12,000 people and had projected 1996 revenue of about $1.8 billion. Raytheon, which itself has about 75,000 employees, said the unit would remain based in Lewisville, Texas.
<P>   No significant job cuts were projected.
<P>   The announcement sent shares in both companies rising on the New York Stock Exchange, where Texas Instruments Inc. rose 621/2 cents to close at $67.621/2 and Raytheon was up 25 cents to close at $50.
<P>   The cash purchase, expected to be completed in the second quarter of 1997, would place Lexington, Mass.-based Raytheon second to Lockheed Martin Corp. in revenue from defense electronics.
<P>   Its overall defense revenue of $8 billion still leaves it a distant third to Lockheed and the company formed by last month&#39;s announced merger of Boeing Co. and McDonnell Douglas Corp. Raytheon&#39;s total annual revenue will be about $15 billion after the acquisition.
<P>
<P><h3>CSI announces senior managers</h3>
<P>
<P>   Computational Systems Inc. has announced four senior management appointments.
<P>   Kevin Carey, formerly vice president of sales and marketing, has been named vice president of acquisitions and mergers -- a newly created position to oversee strategic business alliances. Carey joined CSI in 1993 as director of sales and marketing.
<P>   David Lambacher has joined the company as vice president of North American sales and marketing. He was formerly the southeast regional general manager for Seattle-based Intermec.
<P>   Bob Wilson has been named general manager of Paragon Field Services. Wilson is a former national sales manager for CSI.
<P>   Grahame Fogel, previously senior management consultant, has been named general manager of Paragon Training. He will oversee training services provided by CSI, Paragon Services and newly acquired Maintenance & Diagnostics, a Philadelphia-based company.
<P>
<P><h3>Local wholesaler to handle pub brewing</h3>
<P>
<P>   New Knoxville Brewing Co., the city&#39;s first wholesale brewery since Prohibition, has signed an agreement to handle brewing operations for the Great Southern Brewing Co., a brewpub and restaurant at 424 S. Gay St.
<P>   New Knoxville brewer Al Krusen will do on-site brewing at Great Southern. New Knoxville also will formulate new brew recipes for the restaurant&#39;s menu. Krusen plans English, German and American style ales, as well as pilsners and other lagers, stouts, porters and seasonal offerings.
<P>   The New Knoxville Brewing Co.&#39;s beer is distributed throughout most of Tennessee, in northern Virginia and Orlando, Fla.
<P>
<P><h3>Capel joins M4 Environmental</h3>
<P>
<P>   William R. Capel has joined M4 Environmental as vice president and chief financial officer.
<P>   M4 is a partnership of Lockheed Martin Crop. and Molten Metal Technology Inc. The company was established in 1994 to provide high-technology solutions to environmental problems.
<P>   Capel graduated from General Electric Co.&#39;s Financial Management Program in 1973. In 1987, he left his position as manager of programs analysis and estimating to join Textron Inc as director of business management and contracts. In May 1992 he joined UNC Inc. as vice president and controller.
<P>
<P><h3>Denso names new vice president</h3>
<P>
<P>   Denso Manufacturing Tennessee Inc. has promoted Jack Helmboldt to vice president, production, maintenance, production control and manfacturing engineering, alternator/starter division.
<P>   Helmboldt joined Denso as a production manager for the instrument cluster division in 1989. He was promoted to senior manager, production and maintenance of that division in 1991, and to director in 1994. He moved to the alternator/starter division in 1996.
<P>   Helmboldt is to help manage the company&#39;s growth. Denso has $79 million in expansions under way at its Maryville facilities, where it employs 1,600. The company also has two new facilities under construction in Athens, Tenn.
<P>
<P><h3>Names in the news</h3>
<P>
<P>   <B>Chad W. Whitfield,</B> a graduate of East Tennessee State University and the St. Thomas School of Law in North Miami, Fla., has joined the Kingsport office of Klein & Associates. The law firm also has offices in Knoxville, Johnson City and Abingdon, Va.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
