<head>
	<title>Sports Briefs</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 07, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470><BASEFONT SIZE="6">
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Sports Briefs</B></FONT><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<h3>Summitt Show to begin Thursday on SportSouth</h3>
<P>
<P>   SportSouth will begin carrying the <B>Pat Summitt </B>Show at 3 p.m. Thursday. It will continue through Feb. 20.
<P>   The Summitt show will replace a women&#39;s basketball show by LSU&#39;s <B>Sue Gunter.</B>
<P>   SportsSouth will televise the Purdue-Tennessee women&#39;s game at 7 p.m. Jan. 17 -- 30 minutes earlier than it had been scheduled. That game will be followed by Women&#39;s Basketball Today, then a preview of Senior Bowl players at 9:30. 
<P>
<P><h3>Miscellany</h3>
<P>
<P>* Sports Illustrated announced that it will test a sports magazine for women in April as it tries to capitalize on growing interest in women&#39;s sports. The as-yet-unnamed magazine, which carries the working title &#39;&#39;Sports Illustrated Woman,&#39;&#39; will be published twice in 1997. After that, it will be determined how often to publish in 1998, SI president <B>Don Elliman </B>said.
<P>* The Tennessee Secondary Schools Athletic Association Umpires Association (softball and baseball) will hold an organizational meeting for the 1997 season Sunday at 2 p.m. at Fulton High School. New members are welcomed and urged to attend.
<P>
<P><h3>Basketball</h3>
<P>
<P>* Knoxville College (4-9) begins its second semester of action with a three-game homestand starting 7 tonight against Bellarmine College, Division II school out of Louisville, Ky. Bellarmine (8-4) is coached by <B>Bob Valvano</B>, brother of former North Carolina State coach <B>Jim Valvano</B>.
<P>* Walters State men&#39;s coach <B>Bill Carlyle </B>won his 400th career game as the Senators defeated host Cleveland State 86-80 in the championship game of the McDonald&#39;s/Coca-Cola tournament. Carlyle has been at Walters State for 20 seasons. <B>Robert Fears </B>had a team-high 31 points and <B>Ryan Osbourne </B>added 20 for the Senators (11-2).
<P>* Phoenix Suns forward <B>Robert Horry</B> was suspended for two games without pay for throwing a towel and searing at coach <B>Danny Ainge</B> during Sunday&#39;s game with Boston. He will miss games against Atlanta (tonight) and Washington (Wednesday), then rejoin the team Friday in Phoenix for a game against Charlotte. The problem arose when Horry was pulled in the fourth quarter in a 109-102 loss to the Celtics, and Horry was restrained by teammates.
<P>* Ten years after buying a 26 percent share of the Suns for $6 million, the Viad Corp. announced it had sold its interest back to the team for $31.5 million. 
<P>* Orlando guard <B>Anfernee Hardaway,</B> sidelined for 23 of the Magic&#39;s 28 games because of leg injuries, expects to return to the lineup tonight against Philadelphia. 
<P>* Hakeem Olajuwon,<B> Clyde Drexler </B>and <B>Otis Birdsong </B>soon will have their University of Houston jerseys retired.
<P>
<P><h3>Horse racing</h3>
<P>
<P>* Keeneland race course said Washington Redskins owner <B>Jack Kent Cooke </B>will sell all of his thoroughbred racing and breeding stock at sales later this year. Newspapers reported last week that Cooke would sell off his 150 horses, but no time had been established for the sales.
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Football</h3>
<P>
<P>* Former Pittsburgh Steelers quarterback <B>Joe Gilliam,</B> who has fought drug problems for years, was arrested in Nashville over the weekend on a misdemeanor charge of drug possession. Policeman <B>Mike Urquhart </B>reported that on Sunday he found Gilliam, 46, holding a pipe with a rock of crack cocaine in it. Gilliam admitted he had smoked from the pipe, Urquhart said. Gilliam also was charged with driving without a license and two misdemeanor counts of possession of drug paraphernalia. Gilliam was in jail Monday in lieu of $4,000 bond. A hearing was set for Thursday in General Sessions Court.  Gilliam starred at Tennessee State University in Nashville and was a quarterback with the Steelers during the early and mid-1970s.
<P>* <B>Doug Williams, </B>MVP of the 1988 Super Bowl as quarterback of the Washington Redskins, was hired as coach at Morehouse College in Atlanta. Williams, who played at Grambling, had been working as an NFL scout with the Jacksonville Jaguars. He succeeds <B>Mo Hunt.</B>
<P>
<P><h3>Tennis</h3>
<P>
<P>* Defending champion <B>Monica Seles</B> pulled out of the upcoming Australian Open because of a broken finger. Seles, who has never lost a match in Australia, has won the Australian Open four times. The left-handed-swinging Seles suffered two breaks in her right ring finger -- the fingertip and the knuckle. 
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
