<head>
	<title>City, county can&#39;t agree on how to split federal grant</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 06, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>City, county can&#39;t agree on how to split federal grant</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By David Keim, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">I</FONT>mprovements to Knox County&#39;s Juvenile Court facilities and laptop computers for the Knoxville Police Department are in limbo because the city and county can&#39;t agree on how to divide $815,500 in federal grant money.
<P>   Juvenile Court Judge Carey E. Garrett said Friday the county needs about half the money to replace computers that are &#39;&#39;10 years out of date&#39;&#39; and to fix security problems that are growing increasingly difficult.
<P>   &#39;&#39;It all depends on the county getting a fair share of the grant, as I understand it,&#39;&#39; Garrett said.
<P>   Fixing the problems will cost an estimated $581,100, but the federal Bureau of Justice Assistance awarded the county only $93,714 from the federal Local Law Enforcement Block Grants Program this year.
<P>   The city got $721,799 and has offered the county $100,000.
<P>    The county wants about $300,000 of city money, however, according to a chart provided by County Executive Tommy Schumpert.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We&#39;re still negotiating,&#39;&#39; Schumpert said Friday.
<P>   Knoxville Police Chief Phil Keith said the city needs most of its grant money to provide more laptop computers and other technology for officers.
<P>   &#39;&#39;It is part of our strategic plan to build the infrastructure of our organization to carry it into the 21st century,&#39;&#39; Keith said. &#39;&#39;It will help us do a better job in our investigations; it will help us track and preserve evidence better.
<P>  &#39;&#39;It will assist us in developing and training our officers in the computer technology business, and the bottom line is it will lower our operating costs, or at least contain our operating costs, which of course has a great deal of importance to me.&#39;&#39;
<P>   The original grant amounts were based on the violent crime rate in local jurisdictions, and most violent crimes in Knox County occur within the Knoxville city limits.
<P>   Federal rules, however, allowed the county to appeal to state Attorney General Charles Burson if a substantial city-county funding disparity was &#39;&#39;likely to threaten the efficient administration of justice.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Burson certified a funding disparity in September, leaving the city and county to settle the matter themselves.
<P>   Schumpert said a consultant who studied Knox County&#39;s justice system said the county should get half the grant money.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We really operate all of the justice system except law enforcement, and law enforcement is divided&#39;&#39; between the city and county, Schumpert said.
<P>   He argued his case in a Sept. 3 letter to Burson.
<P>   The original funding level &#39;&#39;threatens the efficient administration of justice as it gives only one player in the Criminal Justice System the majority of the financial power,&#39;&#39; Schumpert wrote.
<P>    &#39;&#39;The rest of the members of the system (for which Knox County alone has funding duties), the Knox County Sheriff&#39;s Department, the Clerks, the District Attorney&#39;s Office and the Public Defender&#39;s Office, have no voice without your certification&#39;&#39; of a funding disparity.
<P>   Keith and Knoxville Mayor Victor Ashe, however, argued the funding disparity didn&#39;t threaten the administration of justice, pointing out the county got the bulk of federal Byrne Block Grant Program money last year.
<P>   &#39;&#39;It is obviously clear if the juvenile records and information system were a priority and the court room security (was) part of an overall plan, that during the previous year of Byrne funds where 95 percent of those funds went directly to Knox County, these requested projects should have been considered but were not,&#39;&#39; Keith wrote to Burson.
<P>   The city helped the county get Byrne money this year, too -- $120,000 to $160,000, depending on whether one believes the city or county -- although Schumpert said that&#39;s a separate issue.
<P>   As for Burson&#39;s ruling that a disparity exists, Keith said:
<P>   &#39;&#39;He says there&#39;s merit to disparity. That&#39;s not saying he agrees. He made a political decision. He didn&#39;t want to referee local battles, and I don&#39;t blame him.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Keith and Schumpert both said they hope for a solution soon.
<P>    The money must be encumbered by Sept. 30, 1998.
<P>   The Juvenile Court judge said the new computers will help with sharing of information with law enforcement, lawyers and agencies that work with youths.
<P>   Also, Garrett said: &#39;&#39;The computer program is old and outdated. It doesn&#39;t keep the statistics that Nashvile requires, and we&#39;re in a bind all the time, getting the statistical records to Nashville accurately.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Security will include a metal detector and limited access to certain areas through use of electronic access badges.
<P>    Currently, security isn&#39;t a simple matter.
<P>   &#39;&#39;If there&#39;re any threats or any indication prior to the case being heard, we&#39;ll have people searched if we have any reason to believe there might be a weapon or a threat, but that&#39;s a slow process and hard to handle down here, because we have a big crowd in the waiting room,&#39;&#39; Garrett said.
<P>    &#39;&#39;On a busy day down here there&#39;s not even enough places for everybody to sit down.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Custody cases and others common to Juvenile Court tend to have high emotions, he said.
<P>    &#39;&#39;When you have juvenile fights, we have to separate them in the lobby pretty frequently.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We really are in serious need of some security.&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

