<head>
	<title>Storm downs trees, OR waste cover</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 06, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>Storm downs trees, OR waste cover</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> High winds rip roof off restaurant in Nashville</FONT></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Stephanie Spellers, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">H</FONT>igh winds and heavy rains ripped across the state early Sunday morning, toppling the canvas tent over a hazardous waste storage area in Oak Ridge and sending a tree limb crashing into an East Knox County home.
<P>   The spring-like storm also spawned at least one possible tornado near Nashville. The twister touched down at a shopping mall and tore part of the roof off a crowded restaurant.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We have had an extremely busy night,&#39;&#39; Knoxville Police Department Sgt. Greg Hoskins said. &#39;&#39;There have been numerous calls of trees down, wires down and some isolated power outages.&#39;&#39;
<P>   National Weather Service meteorologist Mike Propst said a cold front swept through the area early Sunday morning, mixing with unseasonably warm air and producing the nasty weather. Some wind gusts topped 60 mph, and some areas reported hail nearly an inch in diameter.
<P>   Today&#39;s weather should return to normal, Propst said, with partly sunny skies and highs in the 40s.
<P>   Officials at the Department of Energy&#39;s Y-12 Plant in Oak Ridge say they believe a strong gust of wind hit the tent-like canvas cover over one of two hazardous waste storage areas on Chestnut Ridge. The incident poses no threat to public health, according to Y-12 Public Affairs Manager Patricia Greeson.
<P>    &#39;&#39;There is no threat to the environment or people,&#39;&#39; she said. &#39;&#39;Because it is a storage facility, it is supposed to be kept in good order. Those storage facilities have undergone preventive maintenance as early as this summer. The wind must have been truly amazing.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Plant officials noticed around 2 a.m. that the tent-like canvas cover and the steel beams and tension wires supporting it had collapsed and fallen onto covered containers of hazardous waste, Greeson said.
<P>   By daybreak, Greeson said technicians and engineers had arrived to assess the damage, pump water out of the canvas, clean up debris and stabilize the containers of waste. Greeson said she is not sure how long the assessment and cleanup will take.
<P>   There are two storage facilities on Chestnut Ridge. Both hold a large number of drums filled with hazardous wastes, including some low-level radioactive materials, Greeson said. The actual containers of waste are still covered, but she said officials are taking every precaution. She said it&#39;s possible the drums of waste will be moved to another location.
<P>   Meanwhile, a couple was rudely awakened when a tree limb fell on their Rutledge Pike home. The Knoxville fire and police departments responded to the call, Hoskins said. No injuries were reported.
<P>   Propst said high winds also turned over a mobile home in Anderson County and blew the roof off a Harriman lumber company.
<P>   Residents of Middle Tennessee also suffered the sting of severe weather. In Nashville, patrons of the Olive Garden restaurant ate dinner under the stars when part of the roof went flying.
<P>   &#39;&#39;People started screaming,&#39;&#39; said waiter Jason Shinton, 23. &#39;&#39;We got under some tables, and people were screaming, &#39;Where do we go?&#39; &#39;&#39;
<P>    The incident was reported as a possible tornado, said Jean Ridley, a spokeswoman for the Metro Nashville Fire Department.
<P>    The storm also damaged three buildings near the restaurant, taking the facade off of another restaurant and damaging businesses in a nearby strip mall.
<P>   The Associated Press contributed to this <B>report.</B>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
