<head>
	<title>Prostitute may face charges of endangering fetus</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 06, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Prostitute may face charges of endangering fetus</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Jamie Satterfield, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">A</FONT> pregnant prostitute who injected herself with crack cocaine Saturday night and then fought with another prostitute when she tried to help the bleeding woman may face charges for endangering her 7-month-old fetus, authorities said.
<P>   If charged, it would be one of the first times the seven-year-old endangerment statute is used against a mother for drug use.
<P>   Knoxville Police Department investigators said Sunday they will take the prostitute&#39;s case to the Knox County District Attorney General&#39;s office on Monday to see if charges can be filed against the 32-year-old woman.
<P>   Police initially believed the woman had flushed her fetus at a public restroom in a convenience store on Cherry Street, but a medical examination at the University of Tennessee Medical Center revealed the woman still was pregnant.
<P>   Investigators Edd Stair and Cindy Gass said the fetus was alive and did not show signs of any overt trauma.
<P>   But if the fetus survives and the woman gives birth, her baby likely will be addicted to crack cocaine, the investigators said.
<P>   Police discovered the pregnant prostitute Saturday night after responding to a call of a fight on Milligan Street. KPD Sgt. Gary Moyers said officers found the pregnant woman and another prostitute in some bushes. The two women were &#39;&#39;dusting themselves off&#39;&#39; and indicated there had been a fight, he said.
<P>   Moyers said the pregnant woman&#39;s jeans were soaked in blood, and officers found a second pair of blood-soaked jeans near the scene of the fight. When they questioned the prostitute, she told them she had aborted her fetus in the Cherry Street bathroom, Moyers said.
<P>   Police found blood smears in the bathroom and evidence the woman had wiped up her blood. Moyers said the prostitute believed she had flushed her nearly full-term fetus.
<P>   After leaving the bathroom, the woman walked to Milligan Street, where she began injecting herself with crack cocaine, according to police. The other prostitute saw the pregnant woman and tried to convince her to go get medical treatment. Moyers said the pregnant woman then began fighting with the other prostitute. The fight had just ended when police arrived, he said.
<P>   Police called for an ambulance, and the woman was taken to UT Medical Center. Once at the hospital, the pregnant woman told police conflicting stories and, at one point, insisted she had tossed her baby into a trash dumpster, officers said. Moyers and other officers began a hurried search but soon learned the drugged woman was still pregnant.
<P>   When the prostitute was told her fetus was alive, police said she grew upset and insisted she did not want the baby.
<P>   Authorities said Sunday UT doctors planned to keep the woman at the hospital for a few days but likely would release her as soon as her medical condition is considered stable. There are no plans to deliver the woman&#39;s baby before her release from the hospital, according to police.
<P>   The state Legislature in 1989 voted to include in the criminal statutes a viable fetus as a possible victim of assault or homicide. A person also can be charged with endangering a viable fetus under the reckless endangerment statute.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
