<html>

<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="keywords"
content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>A time to give back</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i>January 06, 1997</i> </td>
        <td width="470"><font size="6"><b>A time to give back</b></font><font
        size="5"><br>
        `Blessed' children donate their money to Empty Stocking
        Fund; </font><font size="4"><em>I just wanted to give it
        away to somebody who didn't have anything.5-year-old
        Kassandra Hazard Daughter of a Mercy Fund recipient</em></font><p><font
        size="2"><i>By Brian Courtney, News-Sentinel staff writer</i></font></p>
        <p><br>
        <font size="5">A</font>bout six years ago, Sharon Hazard
        of Wears Valley received a special wheelchair purchased
        by The Knoxville News-Sentinel's Mercy Fund. </p>
        <p>Later, in 1990, News-Sentinel readers came to her aid
        again, this time donating money for a down payment on a
        specially equipped van that permitted even greater
        mobility and enabled Hazard to drive herself to work. </p>
        <p>Today, still paralyzed from the waist down from a rare
        connective-tissue disorder, Hazard is grateful as she
        remembers the kindness extended to her and her family in
        their time of need. </p>
        <p>Hazard's children, Kassandra and Kristopher, 5 and 10,
        are grateful, too -- so thankful, in fact, that they
        voluntarily turned over the $200 they were paid in
        December for appearing in ''A Christmas Carol'' to The
        News-Sentinel to help those less fortunate at Christmas. </p>
        <p>Their money, along with contributions from hundreds of
        other donors, ensured that more than 3,500 families
        received food baskets and toys this Christmas through The
        News-Sentinel's Empty Stocking Fund. </p>
        <p>''One time, we weren't doing so well and people helped
        us, so I decided to help back,'' Kristopher said,
        explaining what motivated him to give. ''I thought maybe
        if little kids help, some older people would say, 'Hey,
        if these little kids are giving it, then why shouldn't
        I?' '' </p>
        <p>Kassandra said she would have bought a new dress and
        ''stuff'' with her half of the $200, had she spent the
        money on herself. But she thought helping others was more
        important. </p>
        <p>''I just wanted to give it away to somebody who didn't
        have anything,'' she said in a shy and smiling 5-year-old
        way. </p>
        <p>When asked by her mom to describe the difference her
        $100 would make, Kassandra rattled off a list that would
        have bankrupted Santa. </p>
        <p>''I thought people could get toys, money to build a
        house, things to decorate the house, food, clothes, a
        bike and . . .'' </p>
        <p>Hazard laughed as her daughter continued. ''I told her
        that her $100 probably wouldn't buy all that, but if she
        gave a $100 and a bunch of other people gave a $100,
        together, maybe it would be enough,'' Hazard said. </p>
        <p>Even in the face of adversity, Hazard said her family
        will always give back. </p>
        <p>''In giving you receive, and we've been blessed a
        thousand million times over,'' she said. </p>
        <p>Like their mother, Kristopher and Kassandra also
        suffer from the connective-tissue disorder known as
        Ehlers-Danlos syndrome. The disorder has contributed to
        several health problems that include hemorrhaging and
        bleeding at the joints. </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

