<title>Prison problems</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i>January 06, 1997</i> </td>
        <td width="470"><font size="6"><b>Prison problems</b></font><font
        size="5"><br>
        State inmate population growing faster <br>
        than housing;</font><p><font size="5">N</font>ASHVILLE --
        A rise in state prison populations is fueling tension
        among inmates -- a condition that some prison watchdogs
        believe could lead to more escapes and riots. </p>
        <p>Spurred by get-tough crime initiatives, the state
        prison population has risen more than 40 percent between
        1992-95. </p>
        <p>But prison capacities haven't kept up with demand,
        increasing by only a third during that same time. </p>
        <p>With reports of inmate assaults jumping 82 percent
        during that same period, some are beginning to wonder if
        Tennessee prisons have reverted back to the troubled
        1980s of overcrowded prisons and increased inmate
        escapes. </p>
        <p>''It will show up in increased assaults and
        contraband,'' said Gordon Bonnyman, the former Legal Aid
        attorney who represented Tennessee inmates when the state
        prison system was declared unconstitutional in 1982. </p>
        <p>''Ultimately, it manifests itself in escapes and
        eventually riots. It's like predicting an earthquake: You
        know there's going to be a big one; you just don't know
        when.'' </p>
        <p>Tennessee prisons began to get crowded in the 1980s
        after former Gov. Lamar Alexander's Class X crime bill
        was passed by the Legislature. The bill lengthened some
        sentences and took away early release opportunities for
        others. </p>
        <p>A few years later, the prison system was taken over by
        federal courts after confinement in the state's prison
        was ruled an unconstitutionally ''cruel and unusual
        punishment.'' </p>
        <p>Prison riots followed in 1985, and inmate escapes
        climbed from 39 in 1978 to 140 in 1988. </p>
        <p>State Correction Commissioner Donal Campbell doesn't
        believe Tennessee's prisons are the same and the picture
        is not as bleak as other say. </p>
        <p>''The difference between then and now is we now have
        control,'' he said. </p>
        <p>Tennessee prisons are designed to house 16,668 inmates
        but are currently holding more than 18,000 prisoners. A
        new round of crime laws will again abolish parole for
        some offenders, ban furloughs and send criminals with
        ''two strikes'' or a violent offense and a previous
        conviction, to prison for life without parole. </p>
        <p>A new $50 million, 1,500-bed prison is slated to be
        built by 1998, but new inmate projections say the demand
        for prison space will fall short again in 1999. </p>
        <p>''We're certainly not back where we were, but we're
        headed in that direction,'' Bonnyman said. ''The snapshot
        of where we are now is not terrifying, but the direction
        we're heading is very frightening.'' </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

