<P><B>LASTER, WILLIE NELL (nee HAROLD) - </B>died Friday, January 3, 1997, at the age of 89 after a brief illness. Mrs. Laster was the wife of Rev. Dr. J. Hayden Laster who died in July. One of five children, and the daughter of a Presbyterian minister, Mrs. Laster was born in Missouri, but spent most of her youth in southern Ohio. After spending two years at Maryville College, she taught for two years in east Tennessee prior returning to Maryville where she graduated in 1930 with a major in Christian Education. It was at Maryville College that she met J. Hayden Laster, her husband of 65 years. Dr. and Mrs. Laster were a &#39;&#39;team&#39;&#39; in the truest sense. During Dr. Laster&#39;s pastorates in Aberdeen, Md. (1933-38), Birmingham, Ala. (1938-45), Union, Miss. (1945-48), French Camp, Miss. (1948-50), Milan (1950-52), Harriman (1952-59), New Johnsonville (1959-61), McMinnville (1961-66), and Clover Hill Presbyterian Church in Maryville (1966-72), she served as pianist, choir director, secretary, and in whatever church capacity was needed. Survivors include two sons, James Hayden Laster, Jr. and his wife, Madlon Travis Laster of Winchester, Va., and William Harold Laster of Snowmass Village, Colo.; grandchildren, Jonathan Harold and his wife, Jennifer S. Laster of Nashville, Tenn., James Travis and his wife, Rebecca Wells Laster of Holmes, Pa., Jennifer Ann Laster of Snowmass Village, Colo. A private burial of ashes will take place in the Maryville College Cemetery. A public memorial service will be held at New Providence Presbyterian Church 11 a.m. Tuesday, Jan. 7, 1997, with Rev. Kevin Frederick, Rev. Ann Owens Brunger and Dr. James Wilbanks officiating. The family will receive friends at New Providence Presbyterian Church after the memorial service. In lieu of flowers, the family requests memorial donations be sent to the J. Hayden and Willie Nell Laster Scholarship Fund already established at Maryville College. McCammon-Ammons Funeral Home, Maryville, Tenn., is in charge of arrangements.
