<head>
	<title>Sports Briefs</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 06, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470><BASEFONT SIZE="6">
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Sports Briefs</B></FONT><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<h3>St. Louis hires Avalanche assistant coach Quenneville</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>    The St. Louis Blues hired assistant coach <B>Joel Quenneville</B> of Stanley Cup champion Colorado as their new coach Sunday.
<P>    A source at the Kiel Center, where the Blues play, told The Associated Press a news conference has been scheduled for today. Quenneville confirmed the hiring to KSDK-TV in St. Louis.
<P>    Quenneville will be behind the bench as the successor to <B>Mike Keenan</B> on Tuesday night when the Blues are home against Edmonton.
<P>    &#39;&#39;It&#39;s been tremendously exciting,&#39;&#39; Quenneville said. &#39;&#39;It certainly is a big challenge for me. I look forward to coming to St. Louis. It should be a lot of fun. I want to be a hard-working club.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Quenneville, 38, was the only candidate who has had two interviews and the only candidate who met with <B>Jerry Ritter,</B> the team chairman. The other contender was <B>Paul MacLean</B>. Former Blues and Montreal coach <B>Jacques Demers </B>dropped out of the running last week.
<P>    It has been 18 days since the Blues dismissed Keenan. The team is 2-3-3 under interim coach <B>Jimmy Roberts</B>.
<P>  <h3> In other hockey-related news:</h3>
<P>
<P><B></B>Colorado Avalanche captai<B></B>n<B> Joe Sakic</B> has a leg injury and is expected to be sidelined for four weeks. Sakic sustained a deep laceration on his left calf muscle during Saturday night&#39;s 4-4 tie against the Philadelphia Flyers. Avalanche trainer <B>Pat Karns </B>said doctors recommended Sakic be sidelined after he underwent surgery. The injury means Sakic will miss the NHL All-Star game at San Jose Jan. 18.
<P><B></B>Knoxville Cherokees captain <B>Wayne Anchikoski</B>, who has been on injured reserve (concussion) for more than two weeks, will be examined by doctors today and should be cleared to begin skating. The Cherokees, who have lost four consecutive games, play the Columbus Chill on Tuesday night at 7 at the Civic Coliseum.
<P>
<P><h3>Tennis</h3>
<P>
<P><B></B>Marianne Werdel-Witmeye<B>r</B> of the United States upset fourth-seeded <B>Barbara Schett</B> of Austria 6-1, 6-3 in the opening round of the Tasmanian International in Hobart, Australia. In other matches,<B> Sabine Hack</B> of Germany, the eighth seed, beat <B>Lindsay Lee</B> of the United States 6-4, 7-6 (7-4), and American <B>Anne Miller</B> defeated <B>Karin Kschwendt</B> of Austria 3-6, 7-5, 6-0.
<P><B></B>At Doha, Qatar,<B> Jim Courier</B> won his 20th career title and deprived<B> Tim Henman</B> of gaining his first ATP trophy, beating the Brit 7-5, 6-7 (5-7), 6-2 in the final of the Qatar Open. Courier earned the $84,000 top prize. Courier said that his experience was an important factor in his victory. &#39;&#39;The first two sets were very close, but in the third I got going early and I played solidly,&#39;&#39; he said. &#39;&#39;I&#39;m happy with that.&#39;&#39;
<P><B></B><B>Todd Woodbridge,</B> the fourth seed, defeated fellow Australian <B>Scott Draper</B> 6-2, 6-1 in the final of the $328,000 Australian Hardcourt tournament in Adelaide. Aussie<B> Pat Rafter</B> and <B>Bryan Shelton</B> of the United States beat Woodbridge and <B>Mark Woodforde</B> of Australia 6-4, 1-6, 6-3 for the doubles crown.
<P>
<P><h3>Running</h3>
<P>
<P><B></B>At Lake Buena Vista, Fla., Irish masters competitor <B>Dick Hooper</B> won the Walt Disney World Marathon by more than a minute. Hooper, 40, of Raheny, Ireland, passed Delray Beach&#39;s <B>Paul Marmaro</B> at 251/2 miles and cruised to the overall victory in 2 hours, 31 minutes, 19 seconds. <B>Larisa Zyuzko</B> of Russia, the fifth-place finisher in last year&#39;s Boston Marathon, won the women&#39;s race in 2:41:13. She was followed by <B>Alla Doudaeva</B> (2:43:14) of Moscow.
<P>
<P><h3>Auto racing</h3>
<P>
<P><B></B><B>Frank Williams</B> said he will appear in Imola before Italian judges next month to face a manslaughter charge arising out of the death of Formula One world champion<B> Ayrton Senna</B> at the 1994 San Marino Grand Prix. Although the hearing could be heard in his absence, the wheelchair-bound head of the Williams team said he would be present. &#39;&#39;I will be there and I will be defending my company and myself,&#39;&#39; Williams said. Williams and five other members of the team, including design director<B> Adrian Newey</B> and technical manager <B>Patrick Head</B>, have been charged with manslaughter in Senna&#39;s death which occurred at Imola when his Renault-Williams car hit a wall after failing to take a bend.
<P>
<P><h3>Golf</h3>
<P>
<P><B></B><B></B><B>Greg Norman,</B> whose putter deserted him most of the day, found it again on the 36th hole of the world finals at the Andersen Consulting World Championship of Golf at Scottsdale, Ariz. Norman&#39;s 15-foot birdie putt on his second visit to No. 18 Sunday at the Grayhawk Golf Club&#39;s Talon course earned him $1 million in golf&#39;s richest tournament. He shot 3-under-par 69 in the first 18 holes and 1-over 73 in the second. <B>Scott Hoch,</B> who never led, made up four strokes from the 15th through the 21st holes, but wasn&#39;t able to take advantage of opportunities created by Norman&#39;s erratic short game. Hoch won $500,000, including $175,000 in the finals. <B>Hisayuki Sasaki</B> of Japan won $350,000 for third place and <B>Sam Torrance </B>$300,00 for fourth.
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>College basketball</h3>
<P>
<P><B></B>Maryville College&#39;s women defeated Thomas More 68-59 as <B>Jennifer Buck</B> poured in 30 points and grabbed 10 rebounds. The Lady Scots, who trailed by 11 at halftime, also got 16 points from<B> Melanie Shephard</B>.<B> Sherry Clinkenhead</B> led Thomas More with 15 points and 11 rebounds.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
