<head>
	<title>Upgraded TV station readies for broadcast</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 05, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>Upgraded TV station readies for broadcast</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Eleni Chamis, News-Sentinel business writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">A</FONT> full-power, over-the-air television station owned locally will begin broadcasting in the Knoxville market by the second quarter of this year, according to a local television executive.
<P>   The station, WINT-TV, Channel 20, was originally licensed in Crossville but is part of the Knoxville market, said Lewis Cosby, who was general manager for WKXT-TV, Channel 8, for eight years. 
<P>   The station is negotiating to affiliate with either Warner Bros.&#39;s WB Network or United Paramount Network (UPN), run by Paramount Pictures, Cosby said. A decision is expected next week.
<P>   The WB Network and UPN have both emerged in the past two years and enjoyed early successes in large urban markets. Much of the WB Network&#39;s programming is family-oriented and includes cartoons. UPN&#39;s most popular program is &#39;&#39;Voyager,&#39;&#39; a &#39;&#39;Star Trek&#39;&#39; spin-off.
<P>   Programming will be 24 hours a day, seven days a week, and the station might start a 10 p.m. local newscast as well as buy other syndicated programming. It will reach 1,276,000 people from Cleveland to Somerset, Ky., and from Newport halfway to Cookeville. About 40 percent of those viewers do not have cable, said Cosby.
<P>   The Crossville TV Limited Partnership, consisting of the family trusts of Cosby and Earl Taylor, formerly general sales manager for WKXT, and the Phipps family of Tallahassee, Fla., will own the station.
<P>   &#39;&#39;It&#39;s a great opportunity because of the programming that&#39;s available,&#39;&#39; said Cosby.
<P>   The partnership is constructing a broadcast tower atop Buffalo Mountain, just above Oliver Springs. At a height of 2,200 feet above average terrain, it will be the highest broadcast tower in the area and may be the tallest in Tennessee, said Cosby.
<P>   The tower and transmitter will cost about $3.5 million.
<P>   Cosby said an office building housing the station&#39;s 30 to 40 employees will be constructed, probably in West Knoxville. No site has been selected.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Knoxville is the 60th (largest) television market in the U.S.,&#39;&#39; said Cosby. &#39;&#39;It&#39;s very unusual to have only four TV stations operating.&#39;&#39;
<P>   WTNZ-TV, Channel 43, is airing UPN programming from 10 to 11 p.m. Mondays through Thursdays, according to the Fox channel&#39;s general manager, Michael Brunette. The station will be dropping it at the end of the year when its contract with UPN expires.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Our interest in him (Cosby) having it would allow us to have a 10 o&#39;clock newscast,&#39;&#39; said Brunette. &#39;&#39;The other benefit of him having UPN . . . the night they broadcast he can air it live, where we have to tape-delay it. He could air it like the network wants him to.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Cosby anticipates negotiations with individual cable operators before the network will be broadcast on local cable systems.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We would look at them like any new potential programming,&#39;&#39; said Barbara Lewis, general manager of Scripps Howard Cable TV Co., which recently completed a merger with Comcast Corp. 
<P>   &#39;&#39;It all depends on what the programming is, and is it a good value?&#39;&#39;
<P>   In July 1995, the partnership purchased WINT for about $800,000 from John and Helen Cunningham of Crossville.
<P>   The station first signed on in the 1970s but since has been on and off the air for years. It signed back on in October 1996 and has been airing a video catalog channel out of Powell.
<P>   Two years ago, the Federal Communications Commission approved a petition to upgrade the station.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
