<head>
	<title>State seeking stricter limits on Pigeon&#39;s color</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 05, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>State seeking stricter limits on Pigeon&#39;s color</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Appearance of waters top priority</FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Morgan Simmons, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">U</FONT>nder Tennessee&#39;s water quality laws, a stream that&#39;s suitable for recreation must have &#39;&#39;no objectionable color.&#39;&#39;
<P>   And while the color standard is expressed as a narrative -- not numerically, as the Environmental Protection Agency suggests it should be -- state officials say it nevertheless establishes a benchmark the Pigeon River fails to meet.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We think our standard is objective even if it&#39;s not numerical,&#39;&#39; said Paul Davis, director of the Tennessee Division of Water Pollution Control. &#39;&#39;Our position is that even during normal flows, the water color is clearly objectionable.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Champion International&#39;s new discharge permit calls for 50 color units at the state line -- the same standard EPA set eight years ago when it took authority of Champion&#39;s permit from North Carolina.
<P>   Davis said Tennessee&#39;s main priority is that EPA impose stricter limits on color, adding that the state would be satisfied with improvements at the state line, not at the paper mill&#39;s discharge pipe, in Canton, N.C.
<P>   &#39;&#39;At this point our agency is concerning itself with the appearance of Tennessee waters,&#39;&#39; he said. &#39;&#39;If Tennessee waters looked clean, we would leave conditions in North Carolina to them.&#39;&#39;
<P>   In a recent letter to Tennessee Attorney General Charles Burson, John H. Hankinson Jr., EPA Region IV administrator, wrote: &#39;&#39;When Tennessee promulgates objective water quality standards, EPA will be in the best position to assure full consideration of Tennessee&#39;s concerns.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Davis said that like other states, Tennessee sets both numerical (objective) and narrative water-quality standards, depending on the pollutant.
<P>   &#39;&#39;When we regulate compounds that might have a toxic effect on fish, we tend to use numerical standards,&#39;&#39; said Davis. &#39;&#39;In other areas, our standards are expressed in the narrative form, such as no objectionable color or odor.&#39;&#39;
<P>      Davis said that at this point, the state has not reached a decision on when it will formulate a numerical limit for color on the Pigeon River.
<P>   On the Tennessee side, the Pigeon River varies in color from a green to brown, depending on the rain. Davis said that while upgrades to Champion&#39;s paper mill have produced a 70 percent improvement in color, the river is still too dark.
<P>   &#39;&#39;A mountain river like the Pigeon should look something like the Little River below Townsend,&#39;&#39; he said. &#39;&#39;At this point our position is that our standard is being violated. You don&#39;t have to have a number to tell that.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Fishery biologists say that while color improvements have resulted in increased smallmouth bass reproduction on the Pigeon&#39;s lower end, the overall number of fish species is about half what the river would support if unpolluted.
<P>   In terms of recreation, pollution on the Pigeon River means wasted whitewater potential. According to an economic study released by Walters State Community College, a thriving rafting industry on the Pigeon would generate $7.3 million a year.
<P>   Twelve companies currently run raft trips down the Pigeon&#39;s gorge section, where the size and quality of the rapids are comparable to the Ocoee River.
<P>   Robert Platte, operations manager for Wildwater Ltd. and president of the Pigeon River Permittees Association, said improved color in the Pigeon River could boost the whitewater industry by 30 or 40 percent.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Fifty percent of our guests comment on the water quality,&#39;&#39; said Platte. &#39;&#39;The river itself is exciting, but because of the color, some of our customers have reservations about coming back.&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

	<P><center><font size=2>Return to </font><a href="/"><font size=2>Main</font></a><font size=2>. Copyright &#169; 1996 The Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size=2>webmaster</font></a><font size=2>.</font></center></p>
