<html>
<head>
	<title>Sundquist, union head differ on layoff figures</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 05, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Sundquist, union head differ on layoff figures</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Rebecca Ferrar and Tom HumphreyNews-Sentinel Nashville bureau</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">N</FONT>ASHVILLE -- Gov. Don Sundquist lashed out at the state employees&#39; union chief Friday over layoffs that may result from the budget crunch.
<P>    Linda McCarty, Tennessee State Employees Association president, says she believes next year&#39;s $300 million estimated shortfall will result in &#39;&#39;thousands&#39;&#39; of layoffs.
<P>    But Sundquist says those numbers are way off base.
<P>    &#39;&#39;All I would ask is that TSEA be patient,&#39;&#39; the governor said. &#39;&#39;My experience with TSEA is that they tend to take a view that is not realistic and embellish it somewhat.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Of the $14 billion budget, there&#39;s only $1 billion available from which the administration says it will cut. Areas the governor plans to keep intact include education, transportation, TennCare and prison security.
<P>    Sundquist has said there likely will be more layoffs. So far, about 100 people have lost jobs because of this year&#39;s budget shortfall.
<P>    &#39;&#39;It literally could be thousands of people,&#39;&#39; McCarty said. Both she and personnel officials estimate an average state employee&#39;s salary costs the state about $26,000, including benefits.
<P>    Sundquist has asked all departments to cut their budgets before any layoffs are announced to balance the 1997-98 budget. But he said he cannot yet say what savings would result from layoffs.
<P>    McCarty, in a separate interview, criticized the $120,000 being paid each to Nancy Menke and Fredia Wadley in the newly reorganized Department of Public Health.
<P>    &#39;&#39;No wonder they can&#39;t say it&#39;s saving any money,&#39;&#39; McCarty said. &#39;&#39;This administration has stated time and again that it is looking at state government from a business perspective. Generally, when a business reorganizes, they can point to the nickels and dimes that will be saved. . . . That hasn&#39;t happened here.&#39;&#39;
<P>    The Legislature must sign off on abolishment of the Department of Mental Health and Mental Retardation as part of Sundquist&#39;s reorganization. McCarty said TSEA must decide whether to oppose the move during the upcoming legislative session.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>   State Environment and Conservation Commissioner Justin Wilson left office on his birthday Saturday, giving his successor the oath of office as a final act.
<P>    The new commissioner, Milton Hamilton, said he planned to present Wilson with a birthday gift after the ceremony -- a T-shirt bearing the words &#39;&#39;Happy Birthday to the Wonderful One.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Not long ago, Wilson got a set of cap pistols from his staff at the department. That was based upon Wilson&#39;s pledge to go after Champion International Paper Co. with &#39;&#39;blazing guns,&#39;&#39; said department spokeswoman Melissa Miller.
<P>    There was no word on whether the effectiveness of the cap pistols was proportional to the effectiveness of his dealing with Champion on Pigeon River pollution.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>    Hamilton, by the way, will be doing a lot better financially as commissioner than as a legislator -- both now and in the future.
<P>    His state salary goes up from $16,500 as a state senator to $81,267 as commissioner of Environment and Conservation.
<P>    Further, as a state legislator, he would be entitled now to an annual pension of $26,880 -- though legislators elected after 1976 cannot make more in pension than they do in pay.
<P>    (Hamilton was elected before the cap was adopted.)
<P>    According to officials at the State Retirement Office contacted by The Commercial Appeal of Memphis, Hamilton would boost his annual pension to $49,068 if he stays in his new post for five years -- possible if Sundquist wins re-election in 1998 and keeps Hamilton on the job.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

