<head>
	<title>&#39;TNG&#39; star convention&#39;s a-Trek-tion</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 05, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>&#39;TNG&#39; star convention&#39;s a-Trek-tion</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Space series' fans land in city</FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Brian Courtney, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">S</FONT>aturday was a special day for Adam Shapira of Oak Ridge.
<P>   Instead of watching, reading about or joining Internet discussions about &#39;&#39;Star Trek&#39;&#39; and the three other television series spawned by it, he had the opportunity to share his keen interest and knowledge with other enthusiasts firsthand.
<P>   Shapira was one of several hundred people who paid anywhere from $16-$20 to attend a Star Trek celebration at the Knoxville Convention and Exhibition Center. 
<P>   &#39;&#39;I&#39;m a big Star Trek fan,&#39;&#39; Shapira said, proudly wearing a Star Trek uniform top he purchased several months ago at a local costume shop. &#39;&#39;The main reason I came here is to be with other people who are into Star Trek like I am.&#39;&#39;
<P>   While he&#39;s glad the convention came to town, Shapira said he&#39;s a little baffled about why he didn&#39;t hear about it sooner. Apparently, all the Star Trek mailing lists Shapira subscribes to on the Internet made no mention of a Knoxville convention.
<P>   &#39;&#39;My mom showed me about this convention in the paper last night. Otherwise, I would have missed it,&#39;&#39; he said.
<P>    Joe Kindle, owner of Trek Productions, which stages Star Trek conventions nationwide, said his company hosts about 30 conventions every year. The average attendance is between 700-1,000, according to Kindle. But if &#39;&#39;things really go well,&#39;&#39; the conventions can attract between 2,000-3,000 people, he said.
<P>    What goes on at a convention?
<P>    Fans meet and snap photos with Star Trek celebrities such as Marina Sartis. Sartis is better known to fans as Counselor Deanna Troi on &#39;&#39;Star Trek: The Next Generation.&#39;&#39; They also buy and collect Star Trek goods that include T-shirts, uniforms, coffee mugs, pins, videos, clocks, books and action figures. 
<P>   Aaron Shumate trekked all the way from Massachusetts to attend Knoxville&#39;s Star Trek convention.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Thirteen hours just for this,&#39;&#39; Shumate said as he surveyed the array of vendors selling Star Trek memorabilia and the line of people waiting to get an autographed picture from Chase Masterson. Masterson portrays &#39;&#39;Leeta the Dabo Girl&#39;&#39; on &#39;&#39;Star Trek: Deep Space Nine.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Shumate, who has been to four other conventions in the last two years, said TNG, trekkie speak for &#39;&#39;Star Trek: The Next Generation,&#39;&#39; is his favorite.
<P>   However, Shumate said he religiously tapes &#39;&#39;Star Trek: Voyager&#39;&#39; and enjoys watching &#39;&#39;Star Trek: Deep Space Nine.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Star Trek conventions give Alex and Teresa Bradley of Knoxville a chance to show off their uniforms from &#39;&#39;Star Trek: The Next Generation.&#39;&#39;
<P>   &#39;&#39;We don&#39;t get that many opportunities to wear these uniforms,&#39;&#39; Alex Bradley said with a laugh.
<P>   &#39;&#39;But they&#39;re usually a hit,&#39;&#39; Teresa Bradley added.
<P>   She said they wore them to dinner while attending a Star Trek convention in Huntsville, Ala., and the restaurant&#39;s manager jokingly said told them the establishment served Romulan ale. 
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
