<head>
	<title>Wallace Memorial, steelmaker wrangle over construction project gone awry</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 05, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Wallace Memorial, steelmaker wrangle over construction project gone awry</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Randy Kenner, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">S</FONT>ix years after dedicating its new sanctuary, Wallace Memorial Baptist Church and a now-defunct steel fabricator are battling in court over the construction in a case that&#39;s been dragging on since 1993.
<P>   Now in U.S. Bankruptcy Court, the case originated in Knox County Chancery Court when Associated Services/68 Steel Inc. filed a lawsuit accusing the church, one of its members and a Nashville construction firm of causing it to go out of business.
<P>   The company, which was located in Knoxville, signed on to do the steel fabrication and erection work on the project in late 1989.
<P>   It contends that it was misled on the project, forced to overcome shoddy construction plans and an inadequate budget before finally being used as the scapegoat when things went wrong and the construction fell behind schedule.
<P>   The company claims it was eventually forced off the job and ultimately collapsed because of the costs it accumulated during the project.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Upon information and belief, it became the intent of the defendants to force 68 Steel to leave the project, so that any cost overruns, or difficulties with the project could then be blamed totally on 68 Steel,&#39;&#39; the action in bankruptcy court states. &#39;&#39;Expecting 68 Steel to be put out of business by their actions, the defendants believed this would prevent the revelation of the real reasons for the project&#39;s problems.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Wallace Memorial and the other defendants, however, contended in the chancery court case that 68 Steel&#39;s problems were the result of its ineptitude, and the church suffered cost overruns.
<P>   &#39;&#39;The shop drawings prepared by 68 Steel were defective and were not submitted in a timely manner,&#39;&#39; states the answer of Wallace Memorial and its trustees in 1994.
<P>    &#39;&#39;Furthermore, the steel fabricated by 68 Steel and furnished to the project had numerous defects and was not delivered in a timely manner.
<P>   &#39;&#39;These failures of 68 Steel constitute negligence and a breach of the fabrication contract and caused substantial damage to the church,&#39;&#39; the answer by Wallace Memorial&#39;s attorney, Reggie Keaton, states.
<P>   The church also contends that it didn&#39;t force 68 Steel -- owned by Richard J. Hunt, Scot T. Chrisman and G. Burgan and Marifrances Chrisman -- off the project.
<P>   &#39;&#39;68 Steel ultimately abandoned the project,&#39;&#39; it states.
<P>    Named as defendants along with Wallace Memorial are its trustees; Knoxville businessman Tom Jensen, a member of the church&#39;s expansion committee; the Nashville-based Equitable Church Builders Inc.; and Jimmy Earl Kelley, who worked as a construction superintendent.
<P>   The case was a day away from going to trial in Chancery Court on Nov. 27, 1995, when 68 Steel withdrew its lawsuit. It filed for Chapter 11, or reorganization, bankruptcy protection the following day, admittedly to escape a trial on the church&#39;s counter-claim for damages.
<P>   The bankruptcy case was later converted to a Chapter 7, or liquidation, bankruptcy by U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Richard Stair, who appointed Maurice Guinn to serve as its trustee.
<P>   The current action, which seeks $1.5 million in damages, was filed by Guinn to recover money that would be distributed to 68 Steel&#39;s creditors -- if the company won.
<P>   Wallace Memorial has a claim of more than $450,000 against 68 Steel firm&#39;s estate, according to documents filed in the case.
<P>   The dispute arises out of the project in which 68 Steel, established in 1989, successfully bid on the fabrication work. It did the erection work, also.
<P>   Problems quickly arose, according to the adversary case, because the plans and specifications were &#39;&#39;so inaccurate and impossible to interpret that they prevented 68 Steel&#39;s timely and effective preparation of structural steel shop drawings.&#39;&#39; The company also contends the building was laid out incorrectly. 
<P>   Kelley and Jensen were informed of the problems but ignored them, according to 68 Steel&#39;s action, opting instead to blame the problems on the steel company and demand revisions. It states that Kelley and Jensen refused to pay for the extra work.
<P>   Wallace Memorial and the various other defendants have filed motions to dismiss the case and have not filed answers to it yet.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

	<P><center><font size=2>Return to </font><a href="/"><font size=2>Main</font></a><font size=2>. Copyright &#169; 1996 The Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size=2>webmaster</font></a><font size=2>.</font></center></p>
