<head>
	<title>College has high hopes for telethon</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 05, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>College has high hopes for telethon</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Brian Courtney, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">O</FONT>ne hundred thousand dollars in six hours -- that&#39;s how much money Knoxville College hopes to raise during this year&#39;s local broadcast of The College Fund/United Negro College Fund annual telethon known as the Lou Rawls Parade of Stars.
<P>   The telethon, now in its 17th year, will air at 7 p.m. Saturday, Jan. 11 on WBIR-TV, Channel 10. It will be hosted by WBIR news anchors Cassandra McGhee and David Nelson.
<P>   Proceeds from the telethon benefit the 40 private, historically black colleges and universities supported by The College Fund/UNCF. Knoxville College is one of them.
<P>   Dr. J. Harvey Gillespie, vice president for institutional advancement at Knoxville College, said he and local telethon co-chairs Dr. Dhyana Ziegler, broadcasting professor at the University of Tennessee, and Bill Willis, retired general manager of TVA, are optimistic that they will meet and possibly surpass the $100,000 goal.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We are optimistic in the fact that the Knoxville community has rallied around KC in the past and supported our various fund-raising endeavors,&#39;&#39; Gillespie said. &#39;&#39;We wouldn&#39;t expect anything less from this community because of the spirit of philanthropy that exists here.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Last year&#39;s Knoxville telethon campaign raised $86,000 -- $1,000 more than the goal.
<P>   KC will benefit two-fold from the telethon, according to Gillespie. The college will keep 75 percent of the funds that are raised locally. The other 25 percent is added to the national College Fund/UNCF fund-raising pool, where it is divided among the 40 schools.
<P>   For the 1995-96 academic year, KC received a total of $1.3 million from The College Fund/UNCF, Gillespie said. Of that amount, about $45,000 provided support for more than 20 students who are enrolled with College Fund/UNCF scholarships. The remaining money was earmarked for operational costs, building improvements and faculty development, he said.
<P>   This year, Gillespie said he expects Knoxville College to receive even more money, since the amount each school receives is related to how much money they contribute to the fund.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Raising $100,000 for UNCF seems small when you consider how much we receive in return,&#39;&#39; he said.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

	<P><center><font size=2>Return to </font><a href="/"><font size=2>Main</font></a><font size=2>. Copyright &#169; 1996 The Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size=2>webmaster</font></a><font size=2>.</font></center></p>
