<head>
	<title>Knox Briefs</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 05, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Knox Briefs</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><h3>Man charged in attack of South Knox couple </h3>
<P>
<P>   Police on Saturday charged a man with attacking a South Knoxville couple after they awoke to find the alleged burglar inside their home, authorities said.
<P>   Knoxville Police Department Investigator Larry Vineyard charged Michael S. Gattis, who gave a South Knoxville address, with especially aggravated robbery in connection with the New Year&#39;s Day incident.
<P>   Vineyard said he questioned Gattis Saturday after determining Gattis, who has a &#39;&#39;lengthy history&#39;&#39; of theft-related charges, was a suspect. Gattis allegedly confessed to the Jan. 1 incident &#39;&#39;after a long interview&#39;&#39; with Vineyard, the investigator said.
<P>   Gattis is accused of breaking into the Stratford Road home of Cliff D. Bridges, 69, who was awakened New Year&#39;s Day by his wife&#39;s screams. Police said the wife woke up first and saw a man in the bedroom. When Bridges tried to come to his wife&#39;s aid, the burglar attacked Bridges and his wife, police said. Bridges was bitten on the stomach and his wife was hit in the face.
<P>   Vineyard said he has a second suspect in the case who may be charged later.
<P>    
<P>
<P><h3>Bybee driver dies as truck hits parked rig </h3>
<P>
<P>   NEWPORT -- A Cocke County man was killed Saturday when his pickup truck struck another truck, troopers said.
<P>   The victim was identified as James C. Stone, 50, of Bybee.
<P>   Troopers said Stone was driving on Industrial Road when his truck struck a tractor-trailer parked on the side of Industrial Road.
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Public can review plans for highway changes </h3>
<P>
<P>    An open house to allow the public to review and comment on preliminary design plans for the intersection of Interstate 640 and Broadway  will be held Tuesday, Jan. 7.
<P>   The time is 5 to 7 p.m. The state Department of Transportation will conduct the open house at Whittle Springs Middle School, 2700 Whiteoak Lane. The design calls for reconfiguring the ramps and improving connections to Old Broadway.
<P> 
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Knoxville police arrest six in drug operations </h3>
<P>
<P>   A 16-year-old boy was among the six people arrested Friday night in an undercover operation that targeted street dealers in and around the city&#39;s housing projects, authorities said.
<P>   The teenager allegedly sold crack cocaine to a Knoxville Police Department patrol officer who was posing undercover, Sgt. Greg Hoskins said. The boy was one of six alleged street dealers arrested in the operation, labeled a &#39;&#39;buy-bust,&#39;&#39; and charged with sell and delivery of cocaine. In a buy-bust operation, an undercover officer buys illegal drugs from the dealer, who then is arrested for making the sale.
<P>      The operation was conducted by officers with KPD&#39;s Repeat Offenders Program unit and the patrol division, Hoskins said.
<P>   
<P>
<P><h3>Morgan County prison escapee caught Saturday </h3>
<P>
<P>
<P>     WARTBURG -- Florida authorities captured a Tennessee inmate Saturday who had escaped from the Morgan County Regional Correctional Center in September.
<P>   Christopher A. Wells, 28, of Knoxville was taken into custody early Saturday morning after Florida police spotted him driving a stolen vehicle with North Carolina license plates.
<P>   Wells walked away from his work site at the Morgan County Recycling Center on September 9, 1996. Authorities said Wells stole a car that had a shotgun inside.
<P>   Currently jailed in Florida, Wells will be returned to Tennessee. He could face up to five more years in prison for his escape. Wells was serving a 12-year sentence for burglary and grand larceny at the time of his escape.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
