<P><B>McKINNEY, MRS. T.G. (MAE) - </B>who would have celebrated her 102nd birthday in May, died Saturday morning, Jan. 4, at Brakebill Nursing Home in Knoxville where she had been a resident for about 18 months. She was the oldest living member of Central United Methodist Church in Lenoir City where in her early years she had been active in the church&#39;s music and women&#39;s programs. On May 28, 1995, the Chancel Choir and the United Methodist Women of the church sponsored a celebration of her 100th birthday with &#39;&#39;Mae McKinney Day,&#39;&#39; dedicating the morning service to her honor, followed by a reception Sunday afternoon at the Family Life Center. There are two sons, G. Eugene (Gene) McKinney, who with his wife, Helen, lives in Farragut, and Vernon McKinney. He and his wife, Peggy, live in Knoxville. Daughters of Gene McKinney are Sarah McNabb of Louisville, Ky., and Nancy Romanus of Roanoke, Va. Daughters of Vernon McKinney are Karen McKinney of Knoxville and Janet Scott of Nashville. There are three great-grandchildren, Joel, Justin and Daniel Scott of Nashville. She also is survived by nephews, Herbert Hicks of Texas, Robert McConnell of Knoxville, and Jimmy McConnell of California; and nieces, Mrs. Sibyl Coleman of Sneedville, and Mrs. Clare Hanna of California. Mrs. McKinney was the widow of T.G. McKinney, and for years beginning in the early 1930s, the family home was a farm next to what is now the Cedar Hills Golf Course in Martel. In 1963 they sold the farm and moved to 400 West First Avenue. Mr. McKinney died in 1979. Funeral services will be 11 a.m. Monday, Jan. 6, at Central United Methodist Church with the Rev. C. Mark Gooden officiating. Burial will be in Lenoir City Cemetery. Pallbearers: Ralph Dial, David Ghormley, Dr. Walter C. Shea, Harvey Sproul, Ralph Blackburn, Walter Hedge, Jack Denton, Larry Hawk. In lieu of flowers, memorials may be made to Central United Methodist Church Music Dept. The family will receive friends 2-4 p.m. Sunday at Click Funeral Home, Lenoir City.
