<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>Small ski resorts falling by the wayside</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper Business News">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif" alt="Knoxville News-Sentinel Online -- Business News" align=bottom border=0 width=595 height=176></a><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td align=left valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 05, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Small ski resorts falling by the wayside</B></font><basefont size=6><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Shifting economic climate takes toll</FONT></basefont></FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Anne Wallace Allen, Associated Press writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">W</FONT>EST DUMMERSTON, Vt. -- The Maple Valley ski area in West Dummerston has all the ingredients it needs for the coming season: trimmed trails, working chairlifts, an inventory of rental skis and a spruced-up base lodge.
<P>   &#39;&#39;All you need to do is press a button and it could go,&#39;&#39; said Terry Tyler, who founded the modest ski resort 35 years ago.
<P>   But no one is pressing the button this year. Like dozens of other small ski areas, Maple Valley will stay closed this winter, at least for now. It will be the first season in 30 that the ski area hasn&#39;t opened.
<P>   Like many other small ski areas, Maple Valley is the victim of a changing economic climate. A few decades ago, Vermont had about 80 ski areas, said Bill Scheer, a spokesman for the Vermont Ski Areas Association. This season, only 18 will open, according to the White Book of U.S. Ski Areas, an industry guide.
<P>   Nationwide, ski areas are going out of business or consolidating all over the United States. Their numbers have shrunk from about 745 in the mid-1970s to about 520 now, said Michael Berry, president of the National Ski Areas Association in Lakewood, Colo.
<P>   &#39;&#39;It&#39;s almost like regional malls, if you will,&#39;&#39; Berry said. &#39;&#39;The mom-and-pop stores are gone, and regional malls have replaced them.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Industry analysts say the small ski areas are dying out largely because they can&#39;t afford the snowmaking, high-speed chairlifts and other amenities most skiers want.
<P>   &#39;&#39;It&#39;s economies of scale more than anything,&#39;&#39; said Alphonse Gilbert, a professor of ski area management at the University of Vermont&#39;s School of Natural Resources. The big areas, Gilbert said, also offer better rental equipment, accommodations and instruction.
<P>   &#39;&#39;These big areas get a name that helps attract people, also,&#39;&#39; Gilbert added. &#39;&#39;That&#39;s part of skiing: where you ski. All of those things play a role.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Skiers these days expect more than they did 20 years ago.
<P>   &#39;&#39;When people go skiing today, they don&#39;t expect to hit a rock, and they&#39;re surprised when they do,&#39;&#39; Berry said.
<P>   With 50 acres of trails, a vertical drop of 1,000 feet and just two double chairlifts and a T-bar, Maple Valley 
<P>
<P>can&#39;t compete head-to-head with close neighbors like Mount Snow-Haystack, Stratton and Bromley.
<P>   Mount Snow, the largest of those three, has 760 skiable acres and 24 alternatives for getting up the mountain, including two high-speed quads. Up north, Stowe, Smugglers&#39; Notch, Jay Peak and Sugarbush all have a vertical drop of more than 2,000 feet.
<P>   But small areas that dominate a niche do prevail.
<P>   One is the friendly, family-run Cochran Ski Area in Richmond, with three rope tows and 850 feet of drop.
<P>   &#39;&#39;They make a real effort to introduce skiing to young people; a lot of families feel comfortable taking their children there for lessons,&#39;&#39; Gilbert said of Cochran. &#39;&#39;The other areas that don&#39;t have that kind of niche are going to find it very difficult to compete with the bigger, full-facility areas.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Another is Mad River Glen, which is evolving into a cooperative owned by skiers.
<P>   Mad River&#39;s management sells the resort on its natural snow, and the resort doesn&#39;t allow snowboards.
<P>   Tyler, 64, a former professional ski-jumper who worked for decades as a contractor building chairlifts all over New England, said he believed Maple Valley, which is beset by financial and legal problems, could survive with different management.
<P>   Recent managers, Tyler said, overextended the area&#39;s finances by putting in night skiing and trying to run it seven days a week.
<P>    He said he would have kept its hours to a minimum to limit payroll costs, focusing on weekends and holidays and times when school children would use it.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I feel if I was running it today, I could make a go of it,&#39;&#39; he said.
<P>   The decline of the smaller areas doesn&#39;t necessarily help the ones that remain. In fact, the larger ski areas draw their customers from a population that learned to ski and snowboard at smaller, inexpensive areas near home.
<P>   &#39;&#39;As they go out of business, it becomes a more complex task to become a skier and a snowboarder,&#39;&#39; Berry said.
<P>   &#39;&#39;The industry is very concerned with it.&#39;&#39;
<P>   The large ski area that can provide a busy visitor with a smooth, all-inclusive ski vacation will continue to attract people who have plenty of money but very little time. And small areas will continue to be a casualty of an overall free-time shortage that often drives modern life, Berry said.
<P>   &#39;&#39;People&#39;s time is very valuable, and they want an absolute guaranteed investment return for their time,&#39;&#39; Berry said.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We&#39;re nostalgic about their passing and we&#39;re saddened by their passing, but to some extent it&#39;s a sign of the times.&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
