<head>
	<title>Newspaper joining Internet-access partnership</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper Business News">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif" alt="Knoxville News-Sentinel Online -- Business News" align=bottom border=0 width=595 height=176></a><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td align=left valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 05, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Newspaper joining Internet-access partnership</B></font><basefont size=6><!--SUBHEAD--></basefont></FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Pam Park, News-Sentinel business writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">T</FONT>he Knoxville News-Sentinel is closing KnoxLink, its computer bulletin board service, and becoming an Internet access provider in partnership with InfiNet, a national Internet company that works with newspapers.
<P>   Jack Lail, manager of online publishing for The News-Sentinel, said KnoxLink will close Jan. 31. Internet access through Knoxnews.com is available now by calling 1-800-391-7497.
<P>   Partnering with InfiNet will allow The News-Sentinel to focus on its strengths while offering customers the benefits of greater resources and technical experience available through a national Internet service provider, Lail said.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We&#39;re a newspaper. We&#39;re content people and running a bulletin board service is very customer service oriented,&#39;&#39; Lail said. &#39;&#39;This allows us to do content and still offer people a way to get to the Internet. We hope to compete very aggressively with the other people around town who are doing Internet service.&#39;&#39;
<P>   KnoxLink was launched on Labor Day 1995. It had as many as 3,000 user accounts and handled more than 287,000 calls and 3.8 million messages, but in analyzing user preferences, Lail discovered people wanted Internet access rather than a &#39;&#39;sort of local AOL (America Online) service.&#39;&#39;
<P>   The Knoxnews.com service will offer unlimited surfing for $19.95 and a basic surfer plan that costs $9.95 per month for 10 hours. Each additional hour costs $2. A 24-hour help line is available, and subscribers get a registered copy of the Netscape Navigator Internet browser software. The company is offering one month of free access for people who would like to try it out, Lail said.
<P>   The News-Sentinel online publishing staff will devote itself to the company&#39;s three Web sites -- Knoxnews.com, GoVols.com and GoSmokies.com, Lail said.  It will continue to offer custom Web-site development and related services.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We think it lets us concentrate on what we do best,&#39;&#39; he said.
<P>   The News-Sentinel is the second newspaper in the Scripps Howard chain to partner with InfiNet. The Naples (Fla.) Daily News was first, Lail said. More are expected to follow.
<P>   InfiNet has relationships with more than 130 newspapers, 65 of which are affiliates. It is the only Internet company that devotes itself to developing publishing tools and revenue streams for newspapers, said Peter Ill, vice president of affiliate services.
<P>   InfiNet was founded by a group of U.S. Navy retirees as Wybern Technologies, a local Internet service provider in Norfolk, Va. Landmark Communications Inc., a private media company based in Norfolk, bought 80 percent of Wybern Technologies in 1994. In May 1995, Landmark bought the remainder and formed a 50-50 partnership with Knight-Ridder Inc. Gannett Co. Inc. joined the group in February, and InfiNet is now an equal partnership among the three media companies, Ill said.
<P>   InfiNet offers a number of services to help newspapers publish on the World Wide Web. In an Internet-access arrangement, InfiNet handles equipment installation and maintenance, arranges and maintains phone lines, and offers 24-hour technical support using 800-number and other services.
<P>   The local affiliates handle the sales and marketing and split the money with InfiNet, Ill said.
<P>   InfiNet has a full set of publishing products, including real estate, classified, automotive and other programs on the Web to establish new revenue streams, Ill said. Some newspapers use InfiNet&#39;s services to sell access to their archives, he said.
<P>   The three InfiNet partners saw the Internet coming, realized it would have an impact on publishing, and set out to get involved and develop an effective strategy, Ill said. They continue to explore how the Internet will affect newspapers in the future, he said.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
