<head>
	<title>Computer briefs</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper Business News">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif" alt="Knoxville News-Sentinel Online -- Business News" align=bottom border=0 width=595 height=176></a><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td align=left valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 05, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Computer briefs</B></font><basefont size=6><!--SUBHEAD--></basefont></FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<h3>Wired Ventures gets big jolt of money</h3>
<P>
<P>   SAN FRANCISCO -- After twice planning to go public, and twice thinking better of it, new-media company Wired Ventures Inc. announced it has nailed $21.5 million in equity financing from private institutional investors.
<P>   Wired wouldn&#39;t say who the new investors are or disclose the terms of financing. Company officials waxed optimistic about the new capital and said it would allow the 4-year-old magazine publisher, Webcaster and book publishing firm to take its game to the next level.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We&#39;ve got the money we need to go forward,&#39;&#39; said Don Markley, Wired Ventures spokesman.
<P>   In addition to the monthly Wired print magazine, Wired Ventures operates HotWired, a cluster of sites on the World Wide Web, and recently launched HardWired, a book publishing division.
<P>   Privately held Wired Ventures canceled planned IPOs last summer and fall, the latter a $66.5 million offering. The cancelations came amid leaked internal e-mail memos and press reports that the company&#39;s online ventures were bleeding money.
<P>
<P><h3>Long-distance firms oppose Ameritech plan</h3>
<P>
<P>    WASHINGTON -- Ameritech&#39;s request to provide long-distance service to its local customers in Michigan is drawing protests from long-distance carriers, which contend the company has not satisfied federal requirements.
<P>    Chicago-based Ameritech asked federal regulators this past week for permission to provide long-distance service in part of its local telephone region. Ameritech is the first of the nation&#39;s Bell companies to make such a request, and it took federal regulators and potential long-distance rivals by surprise. A law enacted last February permits local Bell companies to provide long-distance service, and Ameritech is either offering or plans to offer such service in more than 40 states where it does not provide local phone service.
<P>    The real fight is over the Bell companies providing long-distance service to their own states, where they see their biggest opportunity to offer one-stop communications shopping most cheaply and efficiently.
<P>    The Federal Communications Commission, with input from the Justice Department, has 90 days to act on the Ameritech request.
<P>
<P><h3>Detailed Internet game directory published</h3>
<P>
<P>    Lycos Press has distributed to bookstores the Internet Games Directory, a guide to such resources on the Internet.
<P>    While reviews, hints and strategy guides are some of the resources available online for the game enthusiast, locating useful, relevant or even game-specific information can be difficult. The book claims to provide details on how to locate even the most esoteric game information, from online real-time games on the Internet to downloadable games for teenagers and adults.
<P>    Authors Marc Saltzman and Sean McFadden are online gaming experts.  Saltzman hosts &#39;&#39;Marc&#39;s Web Watch&#39;&#39; on &#39;&#39;The Edge,&#39;&#39; a popular radio show in Toronto, and has also reviewed games for Maclean&#39;s Magazine, Electronic Arts Canada and Canada Computes! McFadden is a senior editor and writer for Lycos, where he reviews Web sites for the Games and Hobbies section of the Sites by Subject directory.
<P>    Lycos Press is a three-year effort between Lycos Inc., an Internet search and guide company, and Macmillan Publishing USA&#39;s QUE imprint.
<P>
<P><h3>Rapid growth predicted for DVD-Video</h3>
<P>
<P>   DVD-Video players, expected to be introduced in the United States in 1997 at prices of $599 and up, will appeal primarily to high-end home theater enthusiasts, a new market study by InfoTech, the Woodstock, VT-based market research firm.
<P>   About 820,000 units will be sold worldwide, the study predicts.
<P>   By 2000, however, the expected rapid acceptance of DVD-ROM on the PC desktop will drive down the costs of shared components dramatically, InfoTech predicts. This should enable DVD-Video players to reach mass market pricing (in the $250 range) and should stimulate a tenfold increase in demand that will culminate in a worldwide installed base of over 80 million units by 2005, according to the predictions.
<P>    DVD-Video is expected to benefit from the active support of four studios behind their respective hardware partners&#39; launches: Time-Warner (Toshiba), Columbia-TriStar (Sony), Polygram (Philips) and MCA (Matsushita).  Based on an analysis of the release plans of both major studios and independents, InfoTech projects that more than 600 DVD-Video titles will be available worldwide by year&#39;s end; that is projected to increase to more than 8,000 by 2000.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
