	<title>Sports Briefs</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 05, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470><BASEFONT SIZE="6">
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Sports Briefs</B></FONT><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<h3>Norman, Hoch will play today for the &#39;World Championship&#39; </h3>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>    <B>Greg Norman </B>vs. <B>Hisayuki Sasaki </B>was little more than a walkover. <B>Scott Hoch </B>against <B>Sam Torrance </B>took longer.
<P>    In the end, though, the inevitable happened Saturday in semifinal matches of the Andersen Consulting World Championship of Golf in Scottsdale, Ariz.
<P>    Norman, the white-thatched Aussie who has won more PGA money than anyone in history, needed 14 holes to defeat Sasaki, the Japanese champion, 5 and 4.
<P>    He ended the match with typical brilliance, chipping in from a bunker about 18 feet from the pin for his seventh birdie. The ball arced, bounced twice and hit the stick and dropped into the hole.
<P>    Hoch beat Torrance, a Scot who won the European section, 4 and 2, with his seventh birdie in a round that also included an eagle. He was 9-under when the match ended two shots shy of a full round.
<P>    Norman and Hoch will play a 36-hole match today, with the winner pocketing $1 million for winning the tournament in its second year. Sasaki and Torrance have an 18-hole match for third place.
<P>    The $3.65 million event offers golf&#39;s largest purse, with $2.28 million already distributed to contestants and winners of Japanese, European, United States and International sectionals last spring and summer.
<P>
<P><h3>College basketball</h3>
<P>
<P>* The Tennessee Tipoff Club begins its second season on Monday. The club meets weekly at 11:30 a.m. at The Foundry on the World&#39;s Fair site. Ex-Georgia coach <B>Hugh Durham </B>will be the first guest speaker. Call <B>Ron Rochelle</B> at 470-8444 for information.
<P>* <B>Brandy Reed </B>of Southern Mississippi, the Conference USA player of the year in 1995-96, has been suspended again for continuing academic problems. The 6-foot-1 junior forward was suspended after the fall semester.
<P>
<P><h3>Baseball</h3>
<P>
<P>* The names of Cincinnati Reds executives and relatives were among those that General Motors said Reds owner <B>Marge Schott </B>used to falsify 57 auto sales at her dealership, The Cincinnati Enquirer reported. The people whose names were used were unaware of the situation and weren&#39;t involved, the newspaper reported.
<P>* The Atlanta Braves&#39; new stadium will have to undergo repairs even before the baseball season starts. Concrete concourses at the stadium -- which was built for the Olympics but is now being converted to a 49,800-seat baseball park -- already have noticeable cracks. And on the upperdeck, concrete has chipped away, leaving scars a half-inch deep.
<P>* The Boston Red Sox have raised ticket prices for the 1997 season, breaking the news to season ticket-holders in an apologetic letter from general manager <B>Dan Duquette</B>. The news may be a signal that the Red Sox will not be able to sign free agent pitcher <B>Steve Avery</B>.
<P>
<P><h3>Football</h3>
<P>
<P>* <B>Robert Irsay&#39;s </B>wife will collect his $25,000 monthly salary from the Indianapolis Colts and his son will get to see his medical reports as a result of the latest court appearance by the bickering relatives. The Colts&#39; owner has been in poor health since suffering a massive stroke in November 1995.
<P>* Hall of Famer <B>Lee Roy Selmon </B>has been selected the Walter Camp Football Foundation&#39;s 1996 Alumnus of the Year. Now an associate athletic director at South Florida, Selmon will be honored at the annual Walter Camp dinner Feb. 15 at Yale.
<P>
<P><h3>Tennis</h3>
<P>
<P>* <B>Justin Gimelstob,</B> a late replacement who had never played mixed doubles before this week, teamed with <B>Chanda Rubin</B> to give the United States its first title in the Hopman Cup in Perth, Australia. Gimelstob and Rubin beat <B>Wayne Ferreira </B>and <B>Amanda Coetzer </B>3-6, 6-2, 7-5 in the decisive mixed doubles match to earn a 2-1 victory over South Africa in the final. Rubin defeated Coetzer 7-5, 6-2 in the opening women&#39;s singles, before Ferreira tied the match with a 6-4, 7-6 (7-4) win over Gimelstob.
<P>* Fourth-seed <B>Todd Woodbridge </B>and <B>Scott Draper </B>won their semifinal matches  to set up an all-Australian final since 1988 at the Australian Hardcourt  championships. Woodbridge topped Sweden&#39;s <B>Mikael Tillstrom </B>to win 6-7 (6-8), 7-6 (7-3), 6-3; Draper beat American qualifier <B>Jeff Tarango </B>6-1, 3-6, 6-2.
<P>
<P><h3>Correction</h3>
<P>
<P>* Farragut&#39;s <B>Brooke Burnett</B> hit the 3-pointer that sent the Lady Admirals&#39; basketball game with West into overtime Friday night. Another player was listed as making the shot in a story in Saturday&#39;s News-Sentinel.
<P>
<P>
