<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>3 vehicles are seized under new DUI law</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 04, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>3 vehicles are seized under new DUI law</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Don Jacobs, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">U</FONT>sing a drunken driving law less than 72 hours old, area law enforcement agencies already have seized three vehicles.
<P>   &#39;&#39;When you take their car, it&#39;s just like taking their weapon,&#39;&#39; Knox County Sheriff&#39;s Department spokesman Chuck Denney said Friday.
<P>   Sheriff&#39;s deputies have seized two cars using a law that became effective Jan. 1. The Tennessee Highway Patrol has seized one vehicle in Campbell County.
<P>   &#39;&#39;What you&#39;re going to see at first is a lot seized on driving on revoked charges, and that&#39;s what we have here,&#39;&#39; Denney said.
<P>   Under the new law, anyone who lost driving privileges because of a drunken driving conviction can have their vehicle seized if they are caught driving.
<P>   That&#39;s what happened Wednesday to Charles Wesley Kiestler, 23, of Whittaker Road in East Knox County.
<P>   According to court documents, KCSD Deputy Tim Laycock saw Kiestler allegedly speeding in a 1984 Honda Prelude. Laycock determined Kiestler&#39;s driving privileges had been revoked in December 1994 because of a drunken driving offense, so he seized the car.
<P>   Kiestler was released from Knox County Jail after posting a $500 bond on the driving on a revoked license charge. He could not be reached for comment.
<P>   At 12:43 a.m. on Friday, Dennis Wade Hutchison, 47, of Brushy Valley Road in Powell became the second person in Knox County to feel the bite of the new law.
<P>    According to court records, the unemployed Hutchison was seen &#39;&#39;weaving in and out of his traffic lane&#39;&#39; on Central Avenue Pike by Deputy J.H. Lane. When Lane stopped the 1979 Oldsmobile Cutlass, Hutchison admitted drinking &#39;&#39;about six beers,&#39;&#39; records state.
<P>   Hutchison failed field sobriety tests administered and refused to submit to a breath-alcohol test, records show. Hutchison was charged with a fourth offense of drunken driving and a second offense of driving on a revoked license. Hutchison was jailed on a $3,000 bond, and the car was seized.
<P>   &#39;&#39;In the past, if you revoked someone&#39;s driver&#39;s license, that was meaningless to them,&#39;&#39; Denney said. &#39;&#39;But when you seize their car, they know you mean business.
<P>   &#39;&#39;It&#39;s not our intent to go into the used-car business, but it sends a strong message to drunken drivers.&#39;&#39;
<P>   According to the Tennessee Department of Safety, there were 7,830 convictions last year for driving on a license revoked because of a drunken driving conviction.
<P>   Anthony Kimbrough, spokesman for the state Department of Safety, said the vehicles are being seized under the same guidelines used for years under drug laws.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Innocent owners are protected,&#39;&#39; Kimbrough said.
<P>   If a bank has a lien on a seized car, the loan will be repaid with proceeds from the auction of the vehicle, he said. If the car belongs to someone other than the charged driver, the vehicle can be reclaimed by the owner as long as they didn&#39;t know of and consent to the illegal use of the car.
<P>   Administrative law judges appointed through the Tennessee Secretary of State&#39;s office will hear evidence about forfeiture of seized cars, usually within 30 days of the confiscation.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
