<html>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>Health programs may be combined</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 04, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>Health programs may be combined</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Tom Humphrey, News-Sentinel Nashville bureau</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">N</FONT>ASHVILLE -- Gov. Don Sundquist moved on Friday to put the state&#39;s mental and physical health programs into a single bureaucracy, predicting a reduction of state employees and taxpayer costs over the long term.
<P>    &#39;&#39;There will be less confusion, less overlap,&#39;&#39; said Sundquist.
<P>    The governor stressed, however, that the overhaul was not driven by the state&#39;s current financial problems but by his longstanding goal of increasing government efficency without reducing services.
<P>    In the short term, he said there will be little impact on the budget or employees -- though that will change &#39;&#39;over a long period of time.&#39;&#39; He declined to predict the amount of long term savings or the number of layoffs of state workers.
<P>    The realignment comes with the state facing a $100 million shortage in funds for the current fiscal year and a projected $300 million shortfall for the 1997-98 fiscal year that begins July 1.
<P>    All commissioners have been asked to find ways to cut spending, but Sundquist said the reorganization is a separate matter designed to eliminate &#39;&#39;disjointed efforts&#39;&#39; in the present bureaucratic setup.
<P>    Under the governor&#39;s plan, the present Department of Mental Health and Mental Retardation will be abolished and its functions placed under a new Department of Public Health.
<P>    The new department will continue work of the present Department of Health and will also take over administration of the state&#39;s TennCare program.
<P>    The Department of Finance and Administration has been overseeing the TennCare program. It has also taken responsibility for many mental health and mental retardation programs under a reshuffling announced last year.
<P>    The state Legislature, which goes into session next week, must approve the plan to abolish the Department of Mental Health and Mental Retardation. The other changes were accomplished by an executive order, effective on Friday, the governor said.
<P>    Together, the consolidated Department of Public Health will have about 10,000 employees.
<P>    Nancy Menke, who previously has served as Sundquist&#39;s legislative lobbyist and chief policy adviser on children&#39;s services and prisons, will serve as commissioner of the new, consolidated department.
<P>    The current health commissioner, Dr. Fredia Wadley,  will have the title of &#39;&#39;chief health officer.&#39;&#39; She said the job will include all her present duties plus input into TennCare &#39;&#39;from a medical policy standpoint.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Both Wadley, a pediatrician, and Menke will be paid the same salary -- $120,000 per year.
<P>    &#39;&#39;The consolidation recommended by the Tennessee Commission on Practical Government will eliminate duplication of services, provide more effective services and eventually save money,&#39;&#39; Sundquist said.
<P>    The commission was a group of businessmen appointed by Sundquist that recommended an array of changes in government structure -- few of them implemented so far.
<P>    The governor said he anticipates another announcement on restructuring government soon but declined to give details. Previously, he has expressed interest in consolidating various work-force job-training programs that are now housed in the Department of Labor, the Department of Employment Security and some other agencies.
<P>    &#39;&#39;I believe very strongly that we need to restructure state government to face the new challenges of the 21st century,&#39;&#39; Sundquist said in a statement at his Friday news conference. &#39;&#39;Increasingly, our state -- and all states -- are facing the prospect of more responsibility but less revenue from the federal government. . . . We have to operate more effectively and more efficiently.&#39;&#39;
<P> 
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

