	<title>Miami man&#39;s case sent to grand jury</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 04, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Miami man&#39;s case sent to grand jury</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Randy Kenner, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">T</FONT>he case of a 58-year-old Miami man accused of delivering two kilograms of cocaine to a U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration informant in Knoxville has been sent to a federal grand jury.
<P>   U.S. Magistrate Robert P. Murrian also ordered Verma D. Powell held without bond pending his trial following preliminary and detention hearings Friday in federal court.
<P>   Powell, who has a 1982 federal conviction for heroin trafficking, was arrested Dec. 18 after allegedly delivering cocaine to the unidentified informant in a motel parking lot.
<P>   According to an affidavit by DEA Agent David E. Lewis, the case grew out of a Dec. 16 telephone conversation between the informant and Powell.
<P>   &#39;&#39;During this conversation, Powell agreed to come to Knoxville from Miami and deliver to the (informant) at least one kilogram of cocaine,&#39;&#39; Lewis wrote.
<P>   Lewis testified Friday that the two men had done business on previous occasions but conceded when questioned by Powell&#39;s attorney, Albert Levin, that he had only observed this one delivery.
<P>   But Lewis also noted he monitored the phone conversation and a tape of the alleged delivery, adding, &#39;&#39;It certainly appeared that they had done this before.&#39;&#39;
<P>   He wrote in his affidavit that Powell arrived in Knoxville on the morning of Dec. 18, 1996, and paged the informant using a pre-arranged code.
<P>   &#39;&#39;This code would indicate that Powell was at the East Towne Mall parking lot and was awaiting the (informant),&#39;&#39; Lewis wrote.
<P>   The two men met at the mall and then Powell, in a gold Cadillac, followed the informant to the Days Inn hotel on Asheville Highway, where the two men pulled around back and parked, according to Lewis.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Approximately 30 seconds later, Powell was observed at the rear of his vehicle holding a plastic bag which contained two brick-shaped packages,&#39;&#39; Lewis wrote. &#39;&#39;Powell handed this package to the (informant), at which time Powell was arrested.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Assistant U.S. Attorney Ed Holt argued that Powell, who is still on probation for his prior drug conviction, is both a danger to the community and a risk to flee and urged that he be held without bond. He also noted that Powell had jumped bond at least once before.
<P>   Levin, a Miami lawyer, countered that Powell works and has a house and family in Miami and hasn&#39;t been in legal trouble in the 11 years since he was released from prison on his prior drug offense.
<P>   Murrian agreed with Holt and ordered Powell held.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
