<head>
	<title>Knox to study work of development agencies</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 04, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Knox to study work of development agencies</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> City Council refuses to help pick panel</FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By David Keim, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">A</FONT>lthough the city of Knoxville rejected the idea, Knox County will move forward with a study of whether taxpayers are getting their money&#39;s worth from at least seven local economic development agencies.
<P>   The city and county together spend approximately $3 million annually on the groups, which include the Greater Knoxville Chamber of Commerce, The Downtown Organization, the Knoxville/Knox County Convention and Visitors Bureau and the Greater Knoxville Sports Corp.
<P>   County Commission unanimously approved a resolution last month asking County Executive Tommy Schumpert to name a five-member task force to evaluate the agencies&#39; effectiveness, as well as that of the city&#39;s Department of Economic Development.
<P>   The commission&#39;s resolution also &#39;&#39;encouraged&#39;&#39; Mayor Victor Ashe and City Council to name five members. On Thursday, however, the council declined, voting instead to ask Ashe and Schumpert to do the work themselves.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I just don&#39;t know why they didn&#39;t want to participate,&#39;&#39; Schumpert said, but he planned to proceed as county commissioners directed and present his selections to the commission&#39;s Intergovernmental Committee in two weeks.
<P>   Commissioner Mike Ragsdale, who proposed the task force with Commissioner Scott Davis, was &#39;&#39;disappointed&#39;&#39; with the city&#39;s decision not to take part.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I&#39;m going to encourage Mr. Schumpert to appoint individuals from the city,&#39;&#39; Ragsdale said. Asked if council members might be invited, Ragsdale said, &#39;&#39;I don&#39;t think there&#39;d be a thing in the world wrong with that.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Two council members supported the task force idea -- Nick Pavlis and Carlene Malone. Malone said outsiders should study economic development efforts.
<P>    The county task force will include &#39;&#39;business, labor and industrial representatives,&#39;&#39; according to the resolution passed by County Commission.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I feel somewhat concerned we&#39;re not willing to open the process up a little bit and have outside eyes as well as inside eyes look at it,&#39;&#39; Malone said, pointing out that &#39;&#39;people are very protective of their turf in the economic development arena.&#39;&#39;
<P>   She expressed some amusement that &#39;&#39;45 agencies with straight faces take responsibility for every hamburger job that comes to town,&#39;&#39; but her colleagues said they just don&#39;t want another committee.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I think it&#39;s an administrative matter which can be recommended to us,&#39;&#39; Councilman Ed Shouse said, pointing out that the mayor can move faster than a committee to make recommendations in time for a February budget workshop.
<P>   Ashe said he would follow the council&#39;s wishes.
<P>    He&#39;s already indicated he would consider incrementally reducing Chamber of Commerce funding by $25,000 a year, from the current $125,000.
<P>   As for the county task force, Ashe said, &#39;&#39;Whatever recommendations they have I will certainly seriously look at.&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
