	<title>Ray will not be making confession, lawyer says</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 04, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Ray will not be making confession, lawyer says</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">A</FONT>n attorney for James Earl Ray says his client is not about to make a deathbed confession on the slaying of Martin Luther King Jr. as some civil rights leaders have called for.
<P>   Andrew N. Hall, Ray&#39;s attorney in Wartburg, said Ray will not make any kind of confession since he has said all he intends to say in the book he wrote about his life and the shooting of King in 1968 in Memphis.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Ray wrote a book (&#39;&#39;Who Killed Martin Luther King&#39;&#39;) a few years ago in which he purports to tell all he knows about Dr. King&#39;s assassination,&#39;&#39; Hall said in a letter to reporters.
<P>   Hall also took issue with Jesse Jackson asking Ray for a confession, saying he was disturbed &#39;&#39;by his (Jackson&#39;s) lack of compassion and feeling for Mr. Ray and his family.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Ray initially confessed to the slaying but later recanted and has continued to maintain his innocence while serving a 99-year sentence.
<P>   Ray lapsed into a coma last month and appeared near death from complications of liver disease. He was moved from a Nashville hospital to a special-needs prison Dec. 30.
<P>   Hall also said that he will amend Ray&#39;s lawsuit against the state in trying to get him health care.
<P>   He said that Ray had complained for a year that he was sick and could not get Prison Health Services Inc., which dispenses medical care to inmates for the state, to give him proper medical attention.
<P>   Hall said Ray&#39;s condition (cirrhosis of the liver) should have been diagnosed earlier.
<P>   &#39;&#39;That should have been done a year ago when they could have done something about it,&#39;&#39; Hall said. &#39;&#39;Now he has something that is serious. What I contend all along is that if he had been given treatment when he began asking for it, he wouldn&#39;t be there (hospital) today. He would be back at Riverbend being a model prisoner.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Hall said the prognosis for Ray&#39;s recovery is not good.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
