<head>
	<title>East Tennessee briefs</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 04, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>East Tennessee briefs</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><h3>Kingsport woman killed in Kentucky car wreck</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>   An East Tennessee woman was killed in southeast Kentucky on Thursday night when her car ran off a road and went into a creek.
<P>   Kentucky State Police said Paulette Smith, 41, of Kingsport was driving east on Kentucky 197 in Pike County near Hylton when her car left the road.
<P>   A dispatcher at the Kentucky State Police post at Pikeville said police didn&#39;t know what caused the woman&#39;s car to leave the road.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Federal grant will aid East Tennessee&#39;s jobless</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>   NASHVILLE -- The Tennessee Department of Labor has gotten a $370,000 federal grant to help laid-off workers in East Tennessee.
<P>   The money is to help about 365 workers in Cocke, Greene, Grainger, Hamblen, Jefferson and Washington counties.
<P>   The grant money will provide services such as skills assessment, job-search and placement assistance and counseling.
<P>   Walters State Community College in Morristown will administer the grant.
<P>   The workers were from Pillsbury, Asarco New Market Mine and Mill, Hunt Foods and BTL.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Workshop on college aid scheduled for Thursday</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>   Outreach Tennessee will host a financial aid workshop at 7 p.m. on Thursday, Jan. 9, at the Educational Resource Center, which is in the edsouth building at 255 N. Peters Road.
<P>   The workshop will give parents and students early financial aid information to help them plan for college.
<P>    It&#39;s the fourth in a series of monthly workshops, and it&#39;s free.
<P>   Presenters will be Dick Smelser and Jeff Gerkin, assistant directors of financial aid at the University of Tennessee.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Monterey board supports chief amid &#39;back-biting&#39;</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>   MONTEREY -- The mayor and board of aldermen have voted to support police chief Bruce Breedlove amid &#39;&#39;back-biting&#39;&#39; in his department.
<P>   Alderman Keith Davis, chairman of the police committee, said he wanted officers in the police department to begin working together.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I know morale is low in the police department. I don&#39;t know what the problem is, but there seems to be a lot of back-biting going on,&#39;&#39; he said Thursday night.
<P>   One example of apparent trouble within the department was the defacing of a &#39;&#39;wanted poster&#39;&#39; circulated statewide by the TBI.
<P>   A name under one of the photos was scratched out and Breedlove&#39;s name was penciled in.
<P>   Breedlove told the board he didn&#39;t know who did the defacing, but he said he knew it was from &#39;&#39;within ranks.&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Good weather, bad news, say ski team members</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>   CHATTANOOGA -- For the last 10 years, members of a zany local water ski team have rung in the new year by water skiing through the elements: rain, sleet, snow and ice.
<P>   This year, the skiers had to settle for one of the warmest New Year&#39;s Days in memory for Tennessee.
<P>   &#39;&#39;A little disappointing,&#39;&#39; Chattanooga skier Rob Lemmons said of his run Wednesday in 66-degree weather. &#39;&#39;It takes a little of the fun out of it.&#39;&#39;
<P>   The traditional New Year&#39;s Day water ski run on the Tennessee River began in 1986 amid 20-degree temperatures and flurrying snow.
<P>   About 30 members of the Greater Hiwassee Ocoee Ski Team were looking for a fun, and slightly challenging, way to celebrate the holiday.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We do this to start the year off correctly,&#39;&#39; said Don Bowker, an eight-year member of the club.
<P>   Although 1997 started out balmy, the water was still chilly.
<P>   &#39;&#39;When we get in there, we won&#39;t mind (the weather),&#39;&#39; said Tommy Newman of Cleveland, Tenn. &#39;&#39;But you like it to be cold and spitting snow. Makes it more challenging.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Chattanooga&#39;s high temperature of 70 degrees Friday tied a record. In Knoxville, Friday&#39;s high was 68 degrees.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
