	<td align=left width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Business briefs</B></font><basefont size=6><!--SUBHEAD--></basefont></FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<h3>ValuJet wins partial FAA approval</h3>
<P>
<P>    ATLANTA -- The Federal Aviation Administration granted ValuJet a partial victory on Friday, approving the airline&#39;s flights to Florida, but denying an expansion of its fleet.
<P>    The airline had struggled to win the FAA&#39;s approval for flights to West Palm Beach and Fort Meyers in Florida and Dallas since it was allowed to return to the skies in September.
<P>    FAA spokeswoman Kathleen Bergen said ValuJet has not formally sought approval to resume service to Dallas. In addition, the FAA did not grant ValuJet&#39;s request to add five planes to its current fleet, but Bergen said the request is still being reviewed by the FAA.
<P>
<P><h3>Government to monitor Texaco</h3>
<P>
<P>    WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. -- Federal regulators will have power to monitor Texaco&#39;s treatment of blacks under an agreement reached Friday that gives a federal agency a role in the company&#39;s anti-discrimination settlement.
<P>    The agreement &#39;&#39;reflects our serious concerns with the employment practices at Texaco,&#39;&#39; said James Lee, regional attorney for the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission.
<P>    The EEOC had investigated Texaco&#39;s hiring and promotion practices and found them to be racially discriminatory. That was before the separate civil suit became a national embarrassment to Texaco with the release of tape recordings in which executives mocked blacks and plotted to destroy documents.
<P>    Shortly after Texaco announced a tentative $176 million settlement of the suit in November, the EEOC asked federal Judge Charles Breiant to let it intervene &#39;&#39;to protect the public interest.&#39;&#39; The agreement is contingent on final court approval of the civil settlement, which includes back pay and raises to black employees and various programs to diversify Texaco&#39;s work force and improve working conditions for black employees. The agreement allows the EEOC to monitor the progress of those programs.
<P>
<P><h3>Burkhart proposes added facility</h3>
<P>
<P>   The Army Corps of Engineers&#39; Nashville District soon will consider whether to permit additions to Burkhart Enterprises&#39; barge unloading facilities at mile marker 1.0 on the French Broad River in Knox County.
<P>   The District said Burkhart proposes building five mooring cells, each 16 feet in diameter, as base for an added unloading station at terminals that now handle steel, salt and coke shipments. Burkhart also proposes riprapping 600 feet of shoreline behind the new cells, and it seeks a 10-year maintenance dredging permit to remove up to 2,000 cubic yards of material from a 100-by-1500-foot area of the river near the dock.
<P>   The public may file comments on the proposal by writing Bradley N. Bishop of the Corps Regulatory Branch by Jan. 27 at P.O. Box 1070, Nashville, TN 37202-1070. Comments also may be mailed to TVA&#39;s Land Management Team at Suite 300, 804 U.S. Highway 321 North, Lenoir City, TN 37771-6440.
<P>
<P><h3>NOC acquires rafting operations</h3>
<P>
<P>   Nantahala Outdoor Center, based in Bryson City, N.C., has purchased Carolina Wilderness operations on the French Broad and Nolichucky River and will incorporate them into NOC&#39;s Hot Springs, N.C., and Erwin, Tenn., operations.
<P>   In addition to its rafting operations in the Southeast, NOC operates adventure travel programs, canoe and kayak clinics, a mountain bike program and an &#39;&#39;Action Learning Program&#39;&#39; for youth, student and corporate groups.
<P>
<P><h3>Names in the news</h3>
<P>
<P>   <B>Mark A. Gamble</B> has been promoted to executive vice president of First Community Bank in Rogersville, Tenn. He is the bank&#39;s senior lending officer, and was with First American National Bank before joining the Rogersville bank when it opened in 1993. . . .<B> Perkins Family Restaurant and Bakery</B> has opened a location at the Knoxville Travel Center, 615 Watt Road. The restaurant will seat 142 and be open 24 hours, seven days a week.
<P>
