<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>Wamp undecided about his vote on Gingrich</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 03, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>Wamp undecided about his vote on Gingrich</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Richard Powelson, News-Sentinel Washington bureau</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">W</FONT>ASHINGTON -- U.S. Rep. Zach Wamp emerged Thursday as the first Tennessee House member undecided on Newt Gingrich&#39;s re-election as speaker after Gingrich admitted filing inaccurate statements with the House Ethics Committee.
<P>   Wamp, a Chattanooga Republican, wants to get more information about the Ethics Committee&#39;s investigation of Gingrich before the House&#39;s leadership election Tuesday, Wamp aide Dick Kopper said.
<P>   &#39;&#39;He has not yet made a commitment on this vote,&#39;&#39; Kopper said.
<P>   About a dozen of the 226 House Republicans in the next Congress so far have declared themselves undecided about Gingrich&#39;s re-election.
<P>   The full Ethics Committee is to meet Wednesday, the day after the election for speaker, to discuss the form of punishment for Gingrich&#39;s admitted inaccurate statements that his former fund-raising political committee, called GOPAC, was not connected to a college course that he taught.
<P>   Republicans are saying he likely will be given a reprimand that will be embarrassing but would not be the most severe penalty of &#39;&#39;censure,&#39;&#39; which would require him to give up the speakership.
<P>   The Associated Press Thursday quoted unnamed sources as saying that the ethics panel&#39;s subcommittee will recommend only a reprimand and not censure for Gingrich. But some key Democrats told reporters their members on the ethics panel so far have not agreed to that proposed deal.
<P>   Wamp plans to attend a meeting of Republicans and their leaders Monday to discuss any concerns they have about Gingrich&#39;s case.
<P>   Most House members are not returning to Washington until Monday to prepare for Tuesday&#39;s swearing-in ceremony and other organizational meetings.
<P>   Rep. John J. Duncan Jr., R-Knoxville, has said he wants more information about Gingrich&#39;s ethics case before making public comments and has not stated a position on whether Gingrich should remain speaker, aide Bob Griffitts said. Duncan was on vacation Thursday and could not be reached, Griffitts said.
<P>   Also, Rep. Van Hilleary, a Grandview Republican, has not expressed any reservations about re-electing Gingrich as speaker, aide Ed Frank said. Hilleary also was on vacation and could not be contacted.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Right now, I have no reason to believe that he will not be voting for Newt,&#39;&#39; Frank said of Hilleary.
<P>   Rep.-elect William Jenkins, a Rogersville Republican, was traveling in the state Thursday and could not be contacted, Rep. Jimmy Quillen&#39;s staff said. Jenkins, who won&#39;t get House office space until Monday, was elected to succeed Quillen, who is retiring.
<P>   Another Tennessee Republican, Ed Bryant of Henderson, has said he will vote for Gingrich&#39;s re-election.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

