<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>DOE wants to continue probing OR melt project</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 03, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>DOE wants to continue probing OR melt project</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Treating contaminated soil is technology's aim</FONT></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Frank Munger, News-Sentinel Oak Ridge bureau</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">O</FONT>AK RIDGE -- Despite high-profile problems with two Oak Ridge projects that turn radioactive waste into glass, the U.S. Department of Energy remains interested in  vitrification technologies and would like to proceed with testing. 
<P>    Funding shortfalls and other issues, however, have jeopardized future developments that will require millions of dollars. 
<P>    One of the demonstration projects -- &#39;&#39;in situ vitrification&#39;&#39; -- involves the melting of old nuclear waste pits at Oak Ridge National Laboratory. The technique is supposed to convert the soil and waste into a volcanic glass, sealing the hazardous constituents inside for thousands of years. 
<P>    An ISV operation was halted in the spring after a &#39;&#39;burp&#39;&#39; in the underground melt zone spewed shards of molten glass and damaged the massive hood that covers the pit and collects gaseous emissions. A planned March 17 restart is no longer feasible because of cuts in DOE&#39;s environmental budget, and the project has been placed on indefinite hold. 
<P>    &#39;&#39;It&#39;s not dead, but it&#39;s not alive,&#39;&#39; said John Sweeney of DOE&#39;s environmental restoration staff. If new funds become available, a 1997 restart is still possible, he said. 
<P>    Earl Leming, Tennessee&#39;s environmental oversight chief in Oak Ridge, said state officials would like to see DOE complete the melt in order to gauge the technology&#39;s merits. The effectiveness is still unclear, he said. 
<P>    The other Oak Ridge project -- termed &#39;&#39;transportable vitrification system&#39;&#39; or TVS -- is a waste-treatment experiment located at DOE&#39;s K-25 Site. The system is supposed to melt mixed wastes containing hazardous chemicals and radioactive elements. The molten glass then would be poured into stainless steel containers and sent elsewhere for disposal. 
<P>    The TVS project was shut down in November after more than a ton of molten glass leaked from the system&#39;s melter during a preliminary test. No toxic waste was involved in the early operation, but the problem caused about $850,000 in damage and created a new realm of uncertainties. The system won&#39;t be restarted until mid-summer at the earliest. 
<P>    Leming said vitrification technologies are attractive because they could help stem the migration of contaminants in groundwater. But the state also wants questions on glassification projects to be resolved. 
<P>    The state has approved restart of TVS testing, but Leming said he has asked DOE to evaluate how much it will cost to decontaminate the melt facility. DOE needs to weigh that cost against the potential benefits, he said, because if the upcoming demonstration fails then a cleanup must follow. 
<P>    Leming said the technology has promise, &#39;&#39;but obviously they need to demonstrate it.&#39;&#39; 
<P>    Dave Hutchins of DOE said investigators believe the leak of molten glass was a combination of several factors, all of which can be fixed. 
<P>   One problem was the system had been shut down and restarted too many times, which affected the seal on tiles that form walls of the octagonal melter. The experimental system was operated at Clemson University and DOE&#39;s Savannah River Site in South Carolina before it was brought to Oak Ridge last year. 
<P>    If the prototype facility operates successfully, it could be modified for long-term use to treat a backlog of wastes stored at Oak Ridge, Hutchins said. 
<P>    There are skeptics who question the process. Ralph Hutchison, coordinator of the Oak Ridge Environmental Peace Alliance, said he wonders why there are so many problems in Oak Ridge vitrification tests. 
<P>    &#39;&#39;Making glass isn&#39;t rocket science,&#39;&#39; he said. 
<P>    OREPA has serious questions about TVS and is adamantly opposed to any restart of ISV, which Hutchison said has proved a failure in East Tennessee, partly because of the area&#39;s high water table. 
<P>    &#39;&#39;We consider in situ vitrification to be dead, and DOE should not waste more tax dollars trying to resurrect it,&#39;&#39; Hutchison said. 
<P>    Sweeney said if DOE decides to restart the ISV project, there will be plenty of advance notice and discussions with &#39;&#39;stakeholder&#39;&#39; groups, including environmental activists. 
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

	<P><center><font size=2>Return to </font><a href="/"><font size=2>Main</font></a><font size=2>. Copyright &#169; 1996 The Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size=2>webmaster</font></a><font size=2>.</font></center></p>
