<head>
	<title>Deaths in Smoky Mountains down in &#39;96</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 03, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Deaths in Smoky Mountains down in &#39;96</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Marti Davis, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">G</FONT>ATLINBURG -- The Great Smoky Mountains National Park has had the safest year on record since 1990.
<P>   Four people died in the park during 1996 year, compared to six or seven in most years during the past decade and 10 deaths inside the park during 1993.
<P>    &#39;&#39;It&#39;s been quite a peaceful year, there have been no major searches and no plane crashes,&#39;&#39; said Miller.
<P>    The four deaths that occurred in the Smokies this year all happened during the summer months.
<P>    The first resulted from a motorcycle crash in early June on the park&#39;s heavily traveled Newfound Gap Road June 3.
<P>    Gary Paulis of Miami, Fla., died from massive internal injuries.
<P>    The other three occurred in a three-week period in August and early September.
<P>   The first occurred on Aug. 25 when Charles Barry of Alcoa died after being stung by a swarm of yellow jackets in the Tremont area.
<P>    One week later, Jerry Taylor of Cocke County died when he and the horse he was riding fell from a bridge into Big Creek. Taylor suffered massive head injuries.
<P>    The following week, Michael Chad Bickle of Pigeon Forge died when the 1989 Pontiac Fiero he was driving struck a stone wall and overturned on the section of Highway 441 commonly referred to as the &#39;&#39;spur.&#39;&#39;
<P>    In 1995 the park had seven deaths; 1994, six deaths; 1992, six deaths; 1991, five deaths and in 1990, four deaths.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
