<head>
	<title>East Tennessee briefs</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 03, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>East Tennessee briefs</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">C</FONT>OOKEVILLE -- Investigators are seeking clues in the shooting death of a carpenter whose body was found on the kitchen floor of his home.
<P>   Danny Johnson, 33, was found dead by his girlfriend Wednesday after partying at local bars New Year&#39;s Eve, police said.
<P>   Investigators said they believe Johnson knew his killer and probably let that person into the house not long after taking a cab home.
<P>   Coroner Randy Porter said Johnson had been shot four times. He was not robbed.
<P>   There was no sign of a struggle, officers said.
<P>
<P><h3>Three charged with drug offenses in raids</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>   JACKSBORO -- Three people have been charged with drug offenses by the Campbell County Sheriff&#39;s Department following raids over the New Year&#39;s holiday, Sheriff Ron McClellan said.
<P>   Loretta Maye Baker, 47, of LaFollette was charged with possession of marijuana, possession of cocaine and possession of drug paraphernalia. Sgt. Ted Williams searched Baker&#39;s home and found the alleged drug items, McClellan said.
<P>   K.C. Evans, 36, and Sharon Henegar, 29, both of LaFollette were charged with possession of cocaine and possession of drug paraphernalia. Sgt. Williams found a bag of what was believed to be cocaine in the plumbing. Scales also were found, McClellan said.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Good weather is bad news for good year</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>   CHATTANOOGA -- For the last 10 years, members of a zany local water ski team have rung in the new year by water skiing through the elements: rain, sleet, snow and ice.
<P>   This year, the skiers had to settle for one of the warmest New Year&#39;s Days in memory for Tennessee.
<P>   &#39;&#39;A little disappointing,&#39;&#39; Chattanooga skier Rob Lemmons said of his run Wednesday in 66-degree weather. &#39;&#39;It takes a little of the fun out of it.&#39;&#39;
<P>   The traditional New Year&#39;s Day water ski run on the Tennessee River began in 1986 amid 20-degree temperatures and flurrying snow. About 30 members of the Greater Hiwassee Ocoee Ski Team were looking for a fun, and slightly challenging, way to celebrate the holiday.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We do this to start the year off correctly,&#39;&#39; said Don Bowker, an eight-year member of the club.
<P>   Although 1997 started out balmy, the water was still chilly.
<P>   &#39;&#39;When we get in there, we won&#39;t mind (the weather),&#39;&#39; said Tommy Newman of Cleveland, Tenn. &#39;&#39;But you like it to be cold and spitting snow. Makes it more challenging.&#39;&#39;
<P>   
<P>
<P><h3>Wilson man claims he is horse dentist</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>   NORENE -- A Wilson County man has been accused of practicing veterinary medicine without a license by being a horse dentist.
<P>   David Pride of Norene has been ordered before the Board of Veterinary Medical Examiners Jan. 10. He faces a possible fine of $100,000.
<P>   Pride said local vets often recommend him to horse owners.
<P>   &#39;&#39;That&#39;s why I&#39;m here. I&#39;m out here to help the animal, not to hurt the animal,&#39;&#39; he said.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
