<head>
	<title>Sports briefs</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 03, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470><BASEFONT SIZE="6">
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Sports briefs</B></FONT><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<h3>Suleymanoglu, Indurain announce retirements</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>    &#39;&#39;Pocket Hercules&#39;&#39; needed only a few seconds to win his third Olympic title. <B>Miguel Indurain </B>was in the spotlight for three whole weeks for his fifth Tour de France triumph.
<P>    Yet <B>Naim Suleymanoglu,</B> the extroverted Turkish weightlifter, and Indurain, the modest cyclist from Spain, had much in common, and on Thursday both announced their retirements.
<P>    They were national heroes. Suleymanoglu would be carried through the streets on the shoulders of his countryman after he had triumphed at Olympics or world championships. Equally, the Spaniards loved Indurain and would chant his name whenever he appeared in public.
<P>    They both won their last major titles at the Atlanta Olympics -- Suleymanoglu in the 141-pound competition and Indurain in the time trial.
<P>    Both appeared unbeatable in their specialty.
<P>    Indurain won his first world championship title in 1995 and an Olympic gold medal a year after. He became the first rider to win the Tour de France five times in a row when he triumphed in 1995 by his biggest margin.
<P>    He became Spain&#39;s most famous sports figure and some would argue the greatest sportsman the country has ever produced. That in a country where soccer is easily the dominant sport.
<P>
<P><h3>Basketball</h3>
<P>
<P>Hiwassee&#39;s women&#39;s team will play No. 1-ranked Central Florida (16-0) today in the McDonald&#39;s Classic in Ocala, Fla. Hiwassee (13-0) beat Hillsborough, Fla., 103-65 Thursday to advance.
<P>
<P><h3>Hockey</h3>
<P>
<P>* Boston goaltender <B>Bill Ranford</B>, who lost his off-season arbitration case and grumbled about his salary ever since, signed a three-year contract extension with the Bruins. An arbitrator set Ranford&#39;s salary at $1.75 million this year, making him the 16th-highest paid goalie in the league.
<P>* <B>Keith Primeau </B>of the Hartford Whalers was suspended indefinitely by the NHL for a slashing incident. The center, who sat out a Thursday night game, will have a hearing today with the league. Primeau slashed Washington Capitals center <B>Joe Juneau </B>on Wednesday and was assessed a major penalty and a game misconduct on the play.
<P>* Dayton Bombers goaltenders <B>Derek Herlofsky </B>has been named the East Coast Hockey League player of the month for December. Herlofsky, 25, set a team record with 10 consecutive victories, three shy of the league record.
<P>
<P><h3>Miscellany</h3>
<P>
<P>* Heisman Trophy winner <B>Danny Wuerffel</B> is among eight athletes being honored by the NCAA for their achievements in athletics, academics and leadership. Wuerffel, the All-America quarterback from Florida, will join the other winners at an NCAA awards dinner Jan. 12 in Nashville. The other winners are <B>Atim Barber,</B> football-track, Virginia; <B>Adam Burgasse</B>r<B>,</B> diving, California-San Diego; <B>Jennifer Clarkson,</B> basketball, Abilene Christian; <B>Michael Fisher</B>, soccer, Virginia; <B>Berit Puggaard,</B> 1996 Olympic swimmer, SMU; <B>Jennifer Kenola,</B> soccer, Notre Dame, and <B>Annette Salmeen</B>, Olympic gold medalist in swimming, UCLA.
<P>
<P><h3>Horse Racing</h3>
<P>
<P>* <B>Allen E. Paulson,</B> who kept Cigar racing in 1996, is the recipient of the 1996 Eclipse Award of Merit.  The Thorughbred Racing Associations said that Paulson&#39;s &#39;&#39;extraordinary sportsmanship and dedication to thoroughbred racing was demonstrated by his decision to race Cigar as a 6-year-old rather than retire him to stud.&#39;&#39; Cigar&#39;s value as a stallion soared when he won all 10 of his starts in 1995 and was voted Horse of the Year.
<P>
<P><h3>Tennis</h3>
<P>
<P>* Top-seeded <B>Thomas Muster</B> of Austria won his second-round match in the $635,000 Qatar Open, setting up a quarterfinal match against <B>Jim Courier.</B> Muster defeated <B>Christian Ruud </B>of Norway 6-2, 3-6, 7-5 and Courier topped Romanian qualifier <B>Razvan Sabau </B>6-3, 6-4. Defending champion <B>Petr Korda </B>rallied to beat <B>Magnus Norman</B> of Sweden 6-7 (3-7), 6-4, 6-2, and <B>Sergi Bruguera</B> defeated fellow Spaniard <B>Javier Sanchez</B> 6-0, 6-1 in other second-round matches.
<P>* <B>Justin Gimelstob,</B> a 19-year-old UCLA student, defeated Australia&#39;s <B>Mark Philippoussis</B> 7-6 (7-4), 4-6, 7-6 (7-5), leading the Americans into the final of the Hopman Cup mixed team championship at Perth, Australia. Gimelstob&#39;s success followed a 7-5, 6-0 victory by <B>Chanda Rubin </B>over Australia&#39;s <B>Nicole Bradtke </B>in women&#39;s singles and gave the U.S. team an insurmountable 2-0 lead.
<P>* Slovakia&#39;s <B>Karol Kucera</B> upset second-seeded <B>Mark Woodforde </B>6-3, 6-4, ending the Australian&#39;s hopes of winning the Australian Hardcourt championships for the third time. American qualifier <B>Jeff Tarango </B>also advanced to the quarterfinals in the Australian Open tuneup, beating sixth-seeded <B>David Prinosil </B>of Germany 6-2, 6-4. Tarango will face Sweden&#39;s <B>Jonas Bjorkman</B>, a 6-3, 6-4 winner over American <B>Jonathan Stark.</B>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
