<head>
	<title>Fire at E. Knox party kills 2</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 02, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>Fire at E. Knox party kills 2</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> 1 hurt; Cigarette thought to be the cause</FONT></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Jamie Satterfield, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">A</FONT> New Year&#39;s Day party turned deadly when a fire broke out in a bedroom at an East Knoxville house, authorities said.
<P>   Two people were killed in the 7:11 p.m. blaze at 2204 Chester Ave., near Dandridge Avenue, including the sister of the woman who claimed responsibility for the fatal fire, said Knoxville Fire Department spokesman Norman Hammitt.
<P>   The house had two smoke detectors, Hammitt said, but they lacked batteries.
<P>   The dead were identified as: Christine Dumas, 41, and David Cowan, 43.
<P>   Hammitt said four people -- homeowner Willie Mae Hudson, 68, her two daughters, Dumas and Rosella Dumas, 43, and Cowan -- were inside the house when the fire started.
<P>   Rosella Dumas and Cowan had been &#39;&#39;drinking and smoking&#39;&#39; in a bedroom of the home when both &#39;&#39;passed out,&#39;&#39; Hammitt said. The eldest daughter apparently had a lit cigarette in her hand, he said.
<P>   When Cowan and Rosella Dumas woke up, they discovered a mattress was on fire, he said. They yelled for Hudson to get out of the house, according to Hammitt.
<P>   Hudson, Rosella Dumas and Cowan were able to escape, but once outside realized Christine Dumas was still inside, Hammitt said. Cowan ran back inside to try to rescue her, but Hammitt said the two made it only as far as the front door. That&#39;s where firefighters found their bodies.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Evidently, they were trying to get out,&#39;&#39; he said.
<P>   A KFD firefighter, Capt. Royal Dodsen, was injured trying to battle the blaze, Hammitt said. Dodsen was treated and released at Fort Sanders Regional Medical Center for smoke inhalation.
<P>   One of Hudson&#39;s neighbors, Margaret Boyd, said she was alerted to the fire by a &#39;&#39;popping sound&#39;&#39; she heard from her house, which is directly across the street from Hudson&#39;s home.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I thought it was somebody shooting firecrackers,&#39;&#39; she said.
<P>   When she looked outside, Boyd said she saw flames &#39;&#39;shooting everywhere,&#39;&#39; especially around the bedroom window where firefighters believe the blaze started.
<P>   Hudson was running from the house toward a next-door neighbor&#39;s home, Boyd said.
<P>   &#39;&#39;She was trying to get somebody&#39;s attention,&#39;&#39; Boyd said.
<P>   Boyd and other neighbors said Hudson repeatedly asked police and firefighters if her daughter was dead in the hour following the discovery of the fire. A chaplain was requested to help Hudson with the death.
<P>   &#39;&#39;It&#39;s not real to her yet,&#39;&#39; Boyd said of Hudson&#39;s reaction.
<P>   Hammitt said Hudson&#39;s small house was packed with furniture, and that hindered both the two victims&#39; efforts to get out of the burning house and firefighters&#39; efforts to save them.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We had a very difficult time getting in the house because of the unusual amount of furniture,&#39;&#39; Hammitt said. &#39;&#39;Once we got in, we had to go through all that furniture. There was a great deal of fire and smoke. Heavy smoke alone will blind you and then trying to maneuver around all that furniture.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Firefighters tried to enter the home through the front door but wound up using a side entrance on the opposite side of the house from the bedroom where the fire was concentrated, Hammitt said.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
