<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>Baby New Year: 1st baby of 1997 born 12:05 a.m.</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i>January 02, 1997</i> </td>
        <td width="470"><font size="6"><b><img
        src="../images/newbaby.jpg"
        alt="Lesha and Terry Self with son Daniel Franklin"
        width="250" height="135"><br>
        <img src="../../images/v3/credits/MPcredit.gif"
        width="144" height="21"><br>
        </b></font><font size="2"><strong><b>Lesha and Jerry Self
        sit with their son, Daniel Franklin, in the intensive
        care unit of East Tennessee Children's Hospital.</b></strong></font><p><font
        size="6"><b>Baby New Year: 1st baby of 1997 born 12:05
        a.m.<!--SUBHEAD--></b></font></p>
        <p><font size="2"><i>By David Keim, News-Sentinel staff
        writer</i></font></p>
        <p><br>
        <font size="5">K</font>noxville's first baby of 1997
        wasn't exactly a surprise. </p>
        <p>Daniel Franklin Self was delivered three weeks early
        by Caesarean section at 12:05 a.m. at Fort Sanders
        Regional Medical Center. </p>
        <p>''Dr. (Tammy) Baker said it'd probably be fun to try
        for the first baby of the new year,'' Daniel's mother,
        Lesha Self, said Wednesday afternoon. </p>
        <p>Said father Jerry Self: ''We were trying for 12:01,
        but it was 5 after.'' </p>
        <p>The baby was breathing faster than normal and had an
        infection, so he was transferred immediately to the
        Neonatal Intensive Care Unit at East Tennessee Children's
        Hospital, where he was in good condition. </p>
        <p>Fort Sanders spokeswoman Teresa Gross said the new
        year wasn't the driving factor behind the early birth. </p>
        <p>The doctor ''recommended they go ahead and do a
        C-section because of a condition called intrauterine
        growth retardation,'' Gross said. ''That's a condition
        where the baby's head is growing larger than the rest of
        the body. Also, she (found) decreased fetal movement. The
        baby wasn't moving very much, and the doctor suspected
        some fetal distress.'' </p>
        <p>Gross said it was her understanding the doctor was
        going to be at the hospital Tuesday night for other
        births, so it made sense to schedule Daniel's entrance
        into the world. </p>
        <p>The hospital will give the couple a gift certificate
        to the Baby Superstore. </p>
        <p>Daniel is the couple's first baby together. They'll
        mark their first anniversary March 8, and each had a boy
        when they married. </p>
        <p>Jerry Self, 27, works for Kern's Bakery, doing
        ''whatever they ask me to do.'' </p>
        <p>Lesha Self, 21, is a licensed practical nurse at
        Blount Memorial Hospital. </p>
        <p>They hope to take Daniel home to Maryville soon. </p>
        <p>''He's doing good,'' the mother said. ''He's getting
        better. He's doing a lot better today than he was last
        night.'' </p>
        <p>Her husband has hopes for their son already, that he
        might be a doctor, a professor, a musician. ''Something
        that's got money involved,'' he said, laughing. ''We've
        got a nice boy. Proud of him,'' Jerry said. ''I'm happy I
        got him.'' </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

