<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>UT arts, sciences dean takes over with optimism</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i>January 02, 1997</i> </td>
        <td width="470"><font size="6"><b><img
        src="../images/Deanmc.jpg" alt="Lorayne Lester"
        width="275" height="176"><br>
        <img src="../../images/v3/credits/MCcredit.gif"
        width="144" height="21"><br>
        </b></font><font size="2"><strong><b>Lorayne W. Lester,
        the new dean of the UT College <br>
        of Arts and Sciences sits in the lounge area of her <br>
        office in Ayres Hall. Lester is the first woman to head<br>
        UT's largest college.</b></strong></font><p><font
        size="6"><b>UT arts, sciences dean takes over with
        optimism<!--SUBHEAD--></b></font></p>
        <p><font size="2"><i>By Stephanie Spellers, News-Sentinel
        staff writer</i></font></p>
        <p><br>
        <font size="5">W</font>hile the rest of Knoxville whoops
        over bowl games and toasts a new year, Lorayne Lester is
        busy plotting the future of the University of Tennessee's
        largest college. </p>
        <p>UT Vice Chancellor John Peters has tapped Lester for a
        three-year term as dean of the College of Arts and
        Sciences. She is the first woman to serve in the post. </p>
        <p>''Dr. Lester is an extremely capable, articulate and
        visionary person,'' said Linda Maxson, the dean for
        undergraduate affairs and associate vice chancellor for
        academic affairs. </p>
        <p>''She cares passionately about this institution. One
        needs to have that kind of commitment to the faculty, the
        students and the institution to lead in these challenging
        times.'' </p>
        <p>Lester takes the helm as UT officials begin to grapple
        in earnest with budget woes expected for the 1997-98
        school year. Though there's no final word yet, Maxson and
        other officials say the state Legislature may allocate
        the university the same funding as last year, if not
        less. </p>
        <p>But Lester said she has spent her life around UT and
        has gained the insight to help the school navigate rough
        waters. </p>
        <p>''There will be no question of having to learn the
        ropes, having to wonder who to call for what,'' Lester
        said. ''There's no time for that right now. It's going to
        take serious concentrated efforts to get through the next
        few years.'' </p>
        <p>Lester served as associate dean under former Dean
        Lorman Ratner for six years. Before that, she was head of
        the Department of Speech Communication and
        president-elect of the Faculty Senate. A faculty member
        since 1960, she earned her bachelor's, master's and
        doctoral degrees at UT. </p>
        <p>When Ratner retired from his post last spring, Maxson
        said UT officials planned a national search to find his
        replacement. </p>
        <p>Then Maxson said budget worries forced the school to
        call off searches for several open positions. </p>
        <p>Lester was appointed interim dean. </p>
        <p>Peters finalized the appointment in November. </p>
        <p>Lester said she and her team will immediately kick
        into high gear their plans for the 27 academic
        departments, more than a dozen interdisciplinary programs
        and countless institutes and centers under her control. </p>
        <p>''We'll be helping them devise ways of reducing their
        budgets -- if necessary changing the focus of their
        programs to balance the budget of the college,'' Lester
        said. </p>
        <p>Lester said she will begin budget hearings with
        department heads as early as mid-January. She has asked
        them to lay out sample budgets in the event that 1997-98
        state funding gets chopped either 3, 6 or 9 percent. </p>
        <p>''The presumption is that everybody will have to think
        in terms of reducing,'' she said. </p>
        <p>Though there are sure to be some serious cuts in the
        coming years, Lester said she hopes to keep the college
        focused on its mission: providing high-quality graduate
        and undergraduate programs, sustaining research and
        reaching out to the community. </p>
        <p>''We will be challenged in the forseeable future,''
        she said. ''But I don't want to see the mission change
        because we're going through a bad patch.'' </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

<hr size="5">

