content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>I Resolve</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i>January 02, 1997</i> </td>
        <td width="470"><font size="6"><b>I Resolve</b></font><font
        size="5"><br>
        To pamper myself and learn to relax<br>
        <br>
        </font><font size="3">See also: </font><a href="3816.htm"><font
        size="3">Pamper yourself with the perfect bath</font></a><p
        align="left"><font size="2"><strong>(Editor's Note: Today
        continues I Resolve, a six-part look at New Year's
        resolutions people commonly make. Pampering yourself is
        the today's topic. Earlier segments were on pampering
        yourself with a makeover on </strong></font><a
        href="../../122996/EAST_TEN/EAST_TEN.HTM"><font size="2"><strong>Sunday</strong></font></a><font
        size="2"><strong>, how to lose weight on </strong></font><a
        href="../../123096/EAST_TEN/EAST_TEN.HTM"><font size="2"><strong>Monday</strong></font></a><font
        size="2"><strong>, getting your finances in order on </strong></font><a
        href="../../123196/EAST_TEN/EAST_TEN.HTM"><font size="2"><strong>Tuesday</strong></font></a><font
        size="2"><strong> and eating right on <br>
        </strong></font><a href="../../010197/FOOD/food.htm"><font
        size="2"><strong>Wednesday</strong></font></a><font
        size="2"><strong>. The last part is on improving family
        relationships (Saturday). </strong></font></p>
        <p><font size="2"><i>By Rebecca Simmons News-Sentinel
        staff writer</i></font></p>
        <p>Keys can be found in massage and meditation </p>
        <p><i>This year I resolve to relax. <br>
        I will make more time for myself and my needs. <br>
        I will take care of my body and mind. <br>
        I will relieve that pressure from between my shoulder
        blades. </i></p>
        <p>Relieving stress and creating personal time have
        become the mantra of the 90s. </p>
        <p>There are devices and potions to aid you in your quest
        for stress reduction. In every bookstore, there are
        self-improvement books aimed at relieving tension, but
        let's face it, we're too busy to read them. </p>
        <p>We're hauling the kids to and from ball practice.
        We're grocery shopping and meal planning. We're cleaning
        the house, parenting and trying to maintain our
        friendships. Not to mention working. </p>
        <p>Creating personal time -- time to reconnect the mind
        and body -- is one of the biggest challenges we face --
        especially for women. </p>
        <p>Pamela J. Free, author of ''Come Home To Your Body''
        writes, ''Body, mind and spirit all must be connected and
        acknowledged in our daily lives for us to feel joy and
        inner peace, health and vitality.'' </p>
        <p>Finding and enjoying personal time can help us lead
        more focused and creative lives. </p>
        <p>Massage and meditation are two methods some people use
        to balance the needs of mind and body. </p>
        <p><b><img src="../../images/logos/resolvelogo.gif"
        alt="I Resolve" align="left" hspace="7" vspace="7"
        width="177" height="203"></b><b>Massage</b>. ''Part of
        massage is training your mind not to react to stress in
        the same old ways,'' says Teresa Holley, state
        chairperson of the Tennessee Massage Therapy Association
        and owner of Knoxville's Healing Touch Therapeutic
        Massage. </p>
        <p>''Stress can make you sick in so many ways,'' says
        Holley, ''massage helps you cope with everyday stimuli in
        a healthy way.'' </p>
        <p>Massage is the manipulation of tissues by rubbing,
        stroking or kneading, either with the hands or other
        instruments for remedial or therapeutic purposes.
        Different massage techniques are used for a variety of
        needs. </p>
        <p>Holley cites recent research from the University of
        Miami that suggests, massage is critical to the
        development of infants, an improved sense of well-being
        and belonging among the elderly, and adjunct to good
        health in all people. </p>
        <p>An on-site massage, generally a five to 15 minute
        massage at work, helps keep you alert and focused.
        Companies are beginning to recognize the advantages that
        an on-site massage can offer employees. Holley says the
        purpose of the on-site massage is to eliminate the
        problems the body has worked itself into during the
        course of a day. These range in cost from about $5 to
        $15. On-site massages are given to fully-clothed clients
        on a special chair. </p>
        <p>Someone balancing the rigors of work and family who
        has lots of decision-making responsibilities may enjoy a
        relaxation massage. This type would be given at a spa or
        salon. Holley says the relaxation massage generally lasts
        from 30 minutes to an hour and in Knoxville ranges in
        price from $30 to $50 depending on the business and the
        length of the session. This type is a ''table'' massage
        with the client lying in a relaxed position. </p>
        <p>For herself, Holley likes a deep tissue massage. It's
        more intense than the relaxation massage. She generally
        indulges herself once or twice a month. She says an
        enhanced immune system, a more alert mind, and an
        improved mental image are a few of the benefits. </p>
        <p>According to Holley, a mid-week massage, ''catches you
        when you are starting to feel taxed by all the things you
        have to do. It relaxes you and gets you through the
        week.'' </p>
        <p>As of 1996, any massage therapist providing massages
        for compensation without a Tennessee license is in
        violation of the law. To verify a license call the
        Massage Licensure Board at (615) 532-5083. </p>
        <p><b>Meditation</b>. ''Meditation increases our
        awareness of the continuity of body, mind and spirit. It
        brings us home to these three essential aspects of
        being,'' says Dr. Joan Harrigan, a clinical psychologist
        in private practice in Knoxville and Oak Ridge. She is
        also a meditation instructor. </p>
        <p>She says, ''We sometimes tend to polarize the body,
        mind and soul as if they were separate, in reality, to
        me, they exist on a continuum.'' </p>
        <p>Harrigan describes meditation as the ability to
        concentrate the mind ''so that the individual is
        simultaneously calm and alert.'' She describes this
        feeling as ''a peaceful inner awareness.'' </p>
        <p>There is a form of meditation practiced by every
        religious tradition, according to Harrigan. For example
        the eastern tradition known as meditation is often called
        contemplation in the Christian tradition. </p>
        <p>''The human being by nature loves to experience the
        meditative state,'' Harrigan says, ''we experience it
        quite spontaneously while engaged in activities that we
        love.'' The skill, she says, comes from the ability to
        meditate at will. </p>
        <p>Meditation begins by relaxing the body, then by
        regulating the breathing. Then focus inward on the mind.
        Harrigan says meditation is a step-by-step process. </p>
        <p>''The key,'' she says, ''is the breathing and
        regulating it. A simple breath awareness is an easy way
        to begin to learn how to meditate. Sit quietly and be
        aware of the blow of the breath. </p>
        <p>''It's very helpful to select an appropriate
        contemplation device,'' says Harrigan. ''People often use
        a word or phrase such as peace or love...This steadies
        the mind and gives it a focus.'' </p>
        <p>The new focus moves the ''mental chatter, instant
        replays of yesterday, and previews of tomorrow'' to the
        mind's background. This allows the mind to focus on the
        point of contemplation. </p>
        <p>Ultimately, she says, an experienced mediator is able
        to go beyond the contents of the mind and hover in the
        peaceful stillness found in that state. </p>
        <p>There is, she says, an increased awareness. ''It is
        tremendously refreshing, comforting and,'' she hesitates,
        ''blessed.'' </p>
        <p>The practice, says Harrigan, who conducts periodic
        seminars in Vedanta meditation, an Indian approach, is
        effective in managing high blood pressure, stress, and
        anxiety. It reduces recovery time from physical trauma,
        helps relieve headaches, and phobic reactions. It also
        increases self-awareness, self-acceptance and
        concentration. </p>
        <p>Harrigan says she makes time to meditate, usually in
        the evening before bed. Choose a quiet, uninterrupted
        place. </p>
        <p>''I recommend to students that they select a place to
        use every time they meditate so that it becomes
        associated with a peaceful, open state of awareness.'' </p>
        <p>Meditation has to be made a priority, she says, and it
        isn't for everyone. Harrigan suggests students try it
        before making up their minds. There are many books on the
        market about different philosophies of meditation. For
        more instruction in the spiritual tradition of Vedanta
        meditation, Harrigan offers a course in February. The
        one-day instruction is $150. For more information call
        539-2361. </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

