<head>
	<title>Fort Campbell civilians to fight collection of Kentucky income tax</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 02, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Fort Campbell civilians to fight collection of Kentucky income tax</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By The Associated Press</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">F</FONT>ORT CAMPBELL, Ky. -- A group of civilians, who work on the Kentucky side of Fort Campbell, have hired a lawyer and say they plan to sue to block collection of a Kentucky tax they claim is unfair.
<P>    The base straddles the Tennessee-Kentucky border. A recent effort by Kentucky&#39;s Revenue Cabinet to crack down on Tennessee residents who work on the Kentucky side of the base but don&#39;t pay Kentucky income taxes has prompted protests from the workers. Until about a month ago, many of the Tennesseans had been able to dodge the state&#39;s income tax.
<P>    About 2,000 civilian employees who live in Tennessee but work in Kentucky owe Kentucky income tax. But Tennessee residents who work in Tennessee pay no income tax because the Volunteer State doesn&#39;t have one.
<P>    Military personnel do not pay the tax.
<P>    The tax issue literally divides Fort Campbell. The airfield, most of the public school buildings and many training facilities are in Kentucky.
<P>    Anytime there is talk of moving an office at Fort Campbell, anxious Tennessee residents fear having to pay the tax that Kentucky has collected for 42 years.
<P>    Conversely, there is jubilation when an office moves from Kentucky to Tennessee and the paycheck deduction disappears. Moving just a few feet can add thousands of dollars a year to a paycheck.
<P>    The cabinet has cracked down on those who have avoided the tax. It has notified dozens of Fort Campbell employees that they owe back taxes, according to leaders of a group opposed to the tax.
<P>    In recent months, Revenue Cabinet auditors have reviewed Fort Campbell&#39;s payroll records, and the agency has begun billing scofflaws for back taxes, interest and penalties, according to leaders of Concerned Citizens of Tennessee.
<P>    One worker was assessed $14,000, said George Kaelin of Clarksville, an air traffic controller at Campbell Army Airfield and one of the leaders.
<P>    Kaelin said the mandatory withholding will cost him $150 a month.
<P>    &#39;&#39;Kentucky takes income tax from me, yet makes me pay out-of-state college tuition and out-of-state fees for fishing and hunting and boating licenses. It&#39;s as unfair as you can get.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Citing state confidentiality laws, Revenue Cabinet spokeswoman Janis Stewart said she could not confirm or deny an investigation but said there is &#39;&#39;not a program targeting anyone at Fort Campbell.&#39;&#39;
<P>    About 400 of the Tennesseans vow to challenge the tax in court. Worth Lovett of Clarksville, a teacher at a post school who says he has grudgingly paid the tax, said he expects as many as 800 Fort Campbell workers may join a class-action suit.
<P>    He said the group intends to ask a Kentucky judge to exempt Tennessee residents, or if that effort fails, to limit the number of years the state could recover any back taxes.
<P>    Kentucky has reciprocal agreements with most border states so that people who commute across state lines to work are taxed in just one state. But because Tennessee has no income tax, there is no reciprocity.
<P><font size=2><strong><p>Copyright 1997 by the Associated Press. All Rights Reserved. Unauthorized use is probihited. </p></strong></font>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
