<html>
<head>
	<title>Trail open to disabled via all-terrain wheelchairs</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 02, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Trail open to disabled via all-terrain wheelchairs</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By The Associated Press</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">N</FONT>ASHVILLE -- Rangers didn&#39;t want to pave the woodsy trail circling Radnor Lake. But how could disabled folks use it otherwise?
<P>   The answer: all-terrain wheelchairs.
<P>   Two new ones are now available for free at the state natural area.
<P>   &#39;&#39;As long as the weather is reasonable, you can take them out,&#39;&#39; said Mike Carlton, manager of Radnor Lake State Natural Area.
<P>   Carlton, who has negotiated the 2.6-mile trail in one of the chairs, said the deep-grooved tires -- much like mountain bike tires -- allow the chairs to make it through the wood chips that cover the trail.
<P>   And the front ends lift up to move over small sticks in the way.
<P>   Donations made the project possible. Columbia-HCA gave the money to rework parts of the trail and build a new bridge, Carlton said. Xerox paid for the two chairs.
<P>   A third chair had been bought earlier by Friends of Radnor.
<P>   &#39;&#39;This way people can get out and see the birds and the colors of the trees and not expend too much energy for it to be pleasurable,&#39;&#39; said Will Clark, an employee of Holland Medical Equipment.
<P>   He said he has been out to Radnor, but trying to get around the trail in his own wheelchair is too difficult.
<P>   The two nonmotorized chairs, which Carlton said his company sold at a substantial discount, make it possible. And the chairs don&#39;t have to be pushed, so a visitor can be independent.
<P>   Reworking the lake trail, which included some route changes to make it more level, was critical, too.
<P>   &#39;&#39;The old bridge was too narrow. It would bark the skin off your knuckles,&#39;&#39; Carlton added.
<P>   Floyd Stewart Jr., 48, said he is pleased to have a chance now to make the lake loop -- and is glad to do it without the help of asphalt.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We just can&#39;t go in and pave every nook and cranny,&#39;&#39; said Stewart, who became a quadriplegic after his neck was broken in a car wreck almost 13 years ago.
<P>   Taking advantage of technology to go out in nature the way others have at Radnor -- on a wood chip-lined trail -- is a boon, he said.
<P>   An employee at the nonprofit Center for Independent Living, Stewart said paved trails also have their place and that the disabled need to be able to get into the out-of-doors.
<P>   Already some special education classes have come to take the Radnor trail and watch canvasback, bufflehead and other ducks found on the lake at this time of year, Carlton said.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Kids who wouldn&#39;t normally be able to go around the lake trail can now go around it,&#39;&#39; he said.
<P><font size=2><strong><p>Copyright 1997 by the Associated Press. All Rights Reserved. Unauthorized use is probihited. </p></strong></font>
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
