	<title>East Tennessee Briefs</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 02, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>East Tennessee Briefs</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><h3>South Knoxville couple injured in intruder attack </h3>
<P>
<P>
<P>   A South Knoxville couple fought with a burglar in their home early Wednesday morning, according to a Knoxville Police Department report.
<P>   The 69-year-old husband, Cliff D. Bridges, told officers he was awakened by his wife&#39;s screams and discovered a man in the bedroom. During the ensuing scuffle, the husband was bitten on the stomach, and his wife, who was not identified in the report, was struck in the face.
<P>   The burglar, who escaped with about $100, had apparently broke into the Stratford Road home by prying open a front window, the police report stated. The victims were treated at Baptist Hospital of East Tennessee.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Man, 33, killed by train ID&#39;d as Etowah resident </h3>
<P>
<P>
<P>   A man struck and killed by a train in Northwest Knox County was identified Wednesday as a 33-year-old Etowah, Tenn., resident.
<P>   Terry Martin Thompson died about 4:30 a.m. Tuesday when a train struck him near the intersection of Amherst and Piney Grove Church roads. The Knox County Sheriff&#39;s Department released his name Wednesday morning.
<P>   The train engineer saw Martin sitting on the tracks and repeatedly sounded his whistle. He slowed the train but could not avoid the man.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Two employees on leave after Nashville drowning </h3>
<P>
<P>
<P>   NASHVILLE -- A group home has placed two employees on administrative leave following the bathtub drowning of a 20-year-old woman resident.
<P>   Nashville&#39;s medical examiner has ruled the weekend death of Vikki Sublett accidental. But the Open Arms Care Corp. has placed two of its employees on leave without pay while conducting an internal investigation.
<P>   The home houses people with mental retardation and other developmental disabilities.
<P>   Sublett was found floating in a bathtub at about 11 p.m. Saturday by an employee, the police report said.
<P>   Attempts were made to resuscitate Sublett. She was taken to Southern Hills Hospital, where she was pronounced dead.
<P>   &#39;&#39;This is just a terrible tragedy, an unfortunate tragedy and something we have never experienced before and hope to never experience again,&#39;&#39; said Brian Durbin, administrator of the 6-year-old facility housing 64 men and women.
<P>   The home has notified the state departments of Human Services and Mental Health and Mental Retardation about the death.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>UT administrator struck, cut by man with knife</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>   A University of Tennessee administrator and community activist told police he was attacked Tuesday by a knife-wielding assailant.
<P>   Dennie Littlejohn, 49, a manager in UT&#39;s space and facilities management department, was treated and released at the University of Tennessee Medical Center.
<P>   According to a Knoxville Police Department report, Littlejohn said he was at an apartment on Townview Drive when someone knocked at the door between 4 and 4:30 p.m.
<P>   Littlejohn stated when he opened the door, his assailant, a 55-year-old man, charged him, knocked him down, cut him on the arm and back with a knife and struck him in the face and head, the report stated.
<P>   No motive for the attack was stated in the report. The alleged assailant was identified, and Littlejohn was advised how to obtain a warrant and prosecute.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Prehistoric Indian bones discovered at state park</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>   NASHVILLE -- State Archaeologist Nick Fielder believes bones found in Long Hunter State Park are those of a prehistoric Indian.
<P>   The bones were found Tuesday near the shore of Percy Priest Lake in the park east of Nashville.
<P>   Fielder said he believes the lake may cover part of an ancient Indian burial ground.
<P>   A partial jaw, lower leg and tooth were found by a couple and a child.
<P>   Fielder said he will search for more remains at the site.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
