<P><B>BAKER, JAMES (JIM) ROBERT - </B>age 66, of Corryton, passed away December 31, 1996, at his home. Member of Marantha Baptist Church. Preceded in death by: father, Nero E. Baker; brother, John A. Baker; stepsons, John Leroy Stellate (Jackie Baker). He was a retired heavy equipment operator with 30 years service with Operating Engineers Local 917. Survivors: wife, Marie Baker; son and daughter-in-law, Mike and Le Anna Baker; daughter, Karen Baker; mother, Jewel Baker; sisters and brothers-in-law, Mary and Howard Phillips, Teena and Hurchel York; brother and sister-in-law, Fran and Marion Baker; stepchildren, Chris and Beth Matthews; grandchildren, Jacob and Crystal Baker; mother and father-in-law, Mary and C.L. Creswell; sisters and brothers-in-law, Jo Ann and Larry Kiser, Linda and Larry Creswell, Carolyn and Kenneth Lacy, Shirley and Mike Mynatt; sisters-in-law, Darlene Creswell and Rhonda Lowery. Funeral services 1 p.m. Friday, McCarty&#39;s Evergreen Chapel, Rev. Kenneth Lacy and Rev. Roger Lee will officiate. Interment to follow in Mt. Herman Methodist Church Cemetery. The family will receive friends 7-9 p.m. Thursday at McCarty&#39;s Evergreen Chapel, 7426 Asheville Highway.
<P>
<P><B>BIGGS, DALE LEROY - </B>age 78, of Knoxville, passed away December 30, 1996, at St. Mary&#39;s Medical Center. Veteran of the U.S. Army. Preceded in death by daughter, Mary Biggs. Survived by wife, Helen Biggs; son, Michael Biggs, both of Knoxville; brother, Herschel Biggs of Pigeon Forge, Tenn.; and sister, Chloral Scott of Las Vegas, Nevada; several nieces and nephews. Family and friends will meet at 1:45 p.m. Thursday at Tennessee State Veterans Cemetery for a 2 p.m. graveside service, Rev. R. Herschel Chevallier officiating. Arrangements by Weaver Funeral Home.
<P>
<P><B>BROWDER, CLYDE HENDERSON - </B>age 88, of E. North Street, Sweetwater, passed away Sunday, December 29, 1996, at the family home. He was a member of Sweetwater United Methodist Church, which he served faithfully over a period of 72 years. A member of the Lions Club, where he was chosen as a Melvin Jones Fellow, the highest distinction in Lions Club International. He was preceded in death by his wife of 71 years, Del Oran Browder; parents, Will and Martha Fite Browder; sisters, Lela Aldridge, Nettie Pardue, Beulah Bright, Anna Lynn Sherlin, Maude Henderson; brothers, Tom, Clarence, and Neal (Pat) Browder. Survivors: sister, Mabel Langley; a host of nieces and nephews. The body is at Kyker Funeral Home, Sweetwater, where the family will receive friends from 5:30 until 8 p.m. Thursday. Funeral services 8 p.m. Thursday in Kyker&#39;s Chapel with Rev. Julian Walton officiating. Interment 11 a.m. Friday in West View Cemetery. Nephews will serve as pallbearers. Members of the Lions Club will serve as honorary pallbearers. Memorials may be made to Sweetwater United Methodist Church.
<P>
<P><B>BURKHART, ELSIE R. - </B>age 82, of Knoxville, died December 27, 1996. Member of Central United Methodist Church and retired from R.T. Clapp Co. Friends will meet Friday at Greenwood Cemetery for a 10 a.m. graveside service with Rev. Dan Moore officiating. Friends may call at their convenience at Rose Mortuary Broadway Chapel.
<P>
<P><B>BURLESON, THOMAS M. - </B>age 90, of West Knoxville, died Tuesday, December 31, 1996, at U.T. Hospital. Member of Rocky Hill Baptist Church. Preceded in death by first wife, Gladys Elizabeth Medlin Burleson. Survivors: wife, Omma Hankins Smith Burleson of Knoxville; sons and daughters-in-law, Howard and Joann Burleson, David and Nancy Burleson, Jack and Bunny Burleson, all of Knoxville; stepdaughter, Rosemary Bdeir of Amman, Jordan; stepson, Don Smith of Okechobee, Fla.; grandchildren, Cindy and Andra Lettieri, Clearwater, Fla., Gary Burleson, Sherron Burleson, Susan and Jim Adkins, Pam and Donovan Stewart, all of Knoxville, Patty Burleson, Fort Worth, Texas; brother and sister-in-law, Ted and Ruth Burleson, Knoxville; half-brothers and sisters-in-law, John and Thelma Burleson of Knoxville, Paul and Iris Burleson, St. Louis, Mo.; half sister and husband, Nora and Erby Cheatham, Texas. Family will receive friends from 2-4 p.m. Thursday with funeral service to follow at 4 p.m. at Rose Mortuary Mann Heritage Chapel, Rev. Philip Nations and Rev. John Burleson officiating. Family and friends will meet by 10:45 a.m. Friday at Highland Memorial Cemetery for an 11 a.m. interment service. Pallbearers: Donovan Stewart, Gary Burleson, Jim Adkins, Walter Harrington, Tyson Burleson, Jimmy Merritt. Honorary pallbearers will be Everyready Sunday School Class at Rocky Hill Baptist Church. Arrangements by Rose Mortuary Mann Heritage Chapel.
<P>
<P>CORNWELL, MARTHA ELLEN FOR<B>RESTER - </B>age 75, of Alcoa, passed away Wednesday afternoon, January 1, 1997, at Asbury Acres Health Care Center. Member of Faith Baptist Church. Preceded in death by: husband, Pearlie Cornwell; parents, David and Lydia Flowers Forrester. Survivors: daughters and sons-in-law, Linda and George Sneed of Murphy, N.C., Jeana and Oliver Margetin of Alcoa; grandchildren, Chasity, Brandon Arden, Tabatha Hughes, Tiffany, Corey Sneed; sisters, Alice Jarnigan of Jefferson City, Alcie Moore of Murphy, N.C.; brother, Dallas Forrester of Spring City; several nieces and nephews. Funeral service 12 p.m. (noon) Friday at Miller Funeral Home Chapel, Rev. Herman Helton officiating. Interment to follow in New Providence Primitive Baptist Cemetery (Six Mile Road, Maryville). The family will receive friends from 11 a.m. to 12 p.m. (noon) Friday at Miller Funeral Home, Maryville.
<P>
<P><B>CREEKMORE, ROBERT VANGILDER, SR. - </B>age 64, of Plantation, Fla., died December 29, 1996, at Haywood Regional Medical Center in Clyde, N.C. He was the son of the late Robert Elmond and Evelyn Vangilder Creekmore. He was born and educated in Knoxville, graduating from the University of Tennessee in 1954. He was a veteran of the United States Army. Following his Army service, he embarked on a 35 year business career, during which he served as a marketing representative and executive for the IBM Corporation, the First National Bank of Atlanta and American Express. He was regional vice president for American Express at the time of his retirement in 1989. He was a member of Sigma Alpha Epsilon Fraternity and Ft. Lauderdale County Club, where he served as a member of the board of directors until shortly before his death. He is survived by his wife, Donna Rankin Creekmore of Plantation; son and daughter-in-law, Robert V. &#39;&#39;Rip&#39;&#39; Creekmore, Jr. and Joann of Kannapolis, N.C.; sisters, Eleanor Dickinson and Louise Senatore, both of San Francisco; seven nieces and nephews. Funeral service will be 10 a.m. Thursday, January 2 at St. John&#39;s Cathedral, The Rev. Canon John C. Ross officiating. Interment Highland Memorial Cemetery. Memorials may be made to the Humane Society or American Heart Association. Arrangements by Rose Mortuary Mann Heritage Chapel.
<P>
<P><B>DICKSON, ALBERT QUINTIN - </B>age 81, of Halls Cross Roads, passed away Tuesday, December 31, 1996, at Baptist Hospital. He was a member of Fountain City Christian Church where he had his last ministry and retired after 60 years in the ministry. Graduate of Johnson Bible College. Preceded in death by his first wife, Margaret Dickson. Survivors: wife, Mildred C. Dickson; daughters and sons-in-law, Martha Ann and Don Martin, Mary Ruth and Bud Wandrei; step-sons, Billy and wife, Bonnie Corey, Raymond and wife, Debra Corey; 3 grandchildren; 6 step-grandchildren; 2 great-grandchildren; brother, Richard Dickson; sisters, Frances Hillis and Constance Cummins. Funeral service 8 p.m. Thursday, Lynnhurst-Greenwood Chapel, Minister Larry Woods officiating. Interment 11 a.m. Friday, Gap Creek Christian Church Cemetery. The family will receive friends 6-8 p.m. Thursday before the service at Lynnhurst-Greenwood Chapel of Berry Funeral Home, 2300 W. Adair Drive.
<P>
<P><B>ESTES, BETTY JOE - </B>65, of Dandridge, passed away Tuesday, December 31, 1996. She was a member of Rocky Valley Baptist Church and the former owner of Betty&#39;s Restaurant in Dandridge. Survived by: mother, Carrie Kerr; sister, Bobbie Seals; brother, Don Kerr, all of New Market; half-sisters, Nell Denton and Mary Petree, both of Knoxville, Cindy Rowl of Ohio; several nieces, nephews, and cousins. Funeral service 8 p.m. Thursday, Fielden Chapel with Revs. George Johnson and Robert Griffin officiating. Interment 1 p.m. Friday, Hillcrest Cemetery. The family will receive friends Thursday, 6-8 p.m. at Fielden Funeral Home, New Market.
<P>
<P><B>FERGERSON, NELLIE A. - </B>age 87, of Lake City, Fla., formerly of Grainger County, passed away Friday, December 27, 1996, in Florida. Preceded in death by husband, George Ferguson; parents, William and Kate Turner; and a son, Lee Fergerson. He was a lifelong member of Avondale Baptist Church. Survived by sons, Bennie Fergerson and Howard Fergerson; daughter, Glenda Stephenson and sister, Dora Martin; 11 grandchildren; and 22 great-grandchildren. Graveside service will be 1 p.m. Thursday at Avondale Cemetery, Rev. Sammy Murray officiating. Arrangement by McCarty Mortuary, 4004 Holston Drive.
<P>
<P><B>FOSTER, DIXIE VICTORIA BARNES (NANNIE) - </B>age 79, of Knoxville, went home to be with the Lord and her other family members already awaiting her arrival. She was a member of St. Mark United Methodist Church. Left behind to join her later are her daughter and son-in-law, Frances and James Edwards; special niece and nephew, Maxine and Jimmy Hartsell; grandchildren, Cyndy Wright, Chris and David Wilcox, Susan Major, Nancy and Craig Mellen, Greg Nelson; great-grandchildren, Casey, Jessica, Brooke, Taylor, Grayson, Derrick, Kori, Victoria, Jordan, and Lindsay. Service 11 a.m. Friday, Mynatt Funeral Home Chapel, Rev. Bob Edmonds officiating. Interment Highland Memorial Cemetery. Pallbearers will be grandsons. Family will receive friends 7-9 p.m. Thursday at Mynatt&#39;s.
<P>
<P><B>FULFORD, LEONARD G. JR. - </B>age 72, of Knoxville, died Tuesday, December 31, 1996. Member of Messiah Lutheran Church, Shekinah Masonic Lodge #0524, 32 degree Scottish Rite Mason, and member of Kerbela Shrine Temple. Past director Court 57 Royal Order of Jesters. Survivors: wife, Peggy Baker Fulford; son, Leonard G. Fulford III; daughter, Mary Katherine Fulford Ward; son, Charles Luther Fulford; daughter-in-law, Ronna Fulford; son-in-law, Ward Ward; grandchildren, Kyle Westin Fulford, Mary Katelyn Ward, Kathryn Victoria Fulford and Ruby Nicole Ward. Funeral service 11 a.m. Saturday, January 4, 1997, at Messiah Lutheran Church, Rev. David S. Bradford officiating. Mr. Fulford will be removed to Harris Funeral Home, Kings Mountain, N.C. for graveside service and interment. In lieu of flowers, memorials may be made to the American Heart Association. The family will receive friends 6-8 p.m. Friday with the Masonic service at 8 p.m., provided by Shekinah Masonic Lodge #0524 at Rose Mortuary Mann Heritage Chapel.
<P>
<P><B>GOLDEN, JAMES RICHARD - </B>age 95, of Holston Hills, died Wednesday, January 1, 1997. He was a member of First Presbyterian Church, an active member of Holston Hills Country Club, an avid golfer, a fisherman, and a strong Republican. He was a native of South Carolina and grew up in Atlanta and began driving a delivery truck at age 12. He graduated from Tech High in Atlanta and attended the University of Georgia. He later raced automobiles and played professional football and was a professional boxer. Prior to WWII he worked at the Washington Post. He was advertising manager at the Knoxville Journal for 19 years and while there, during WWII, he met Lt. Kathryn Sherer, who was heading the local Women&#39;s Army Corp., and they were later married. He later became advertising manager for JFG Coffee for 35 years until he retired at age 92. Survivors: wife, Kathryn Sherer Golden of Holston Hills; daughter and son-in-law, Carolyn Golden Lowe and Nathen Ted Lowe of Spokane, Wash.; son, James R. Golden of Knoxville; grandchildren, Elizabeth, Matthew, and Cari Lowe, Spokane, Melissa Golden Stedina, Knoxville. In lieu of flowers, contributions may be made to Knoxville Convalescent Center, Buchman Home for Children, or the United Jewish Appeal. Funeral arrangements are incomplete and will be announced later by McCarty Mortuary, 4004 Holston Drive.
<P>
<P><B>HILL, ALICE JOWITT - </B>age 89, passed away Monday, December 23, 1996, at the Hillcrest West Nursing Home. She grew up in Hillside, N.J., moved to Florida in 1948, and moved to Knoxville in 1973. She is survived by her four sons and their wives, Jeffrey and Suzanne Hill of Knoxville, Larry and Beth Hill of Galveston, Texas, Don and Vesta Hill of Moorestown, N.J., Richard and Scott Hill of Durham, N.C.; 12 grandchildren; 10 great-grandchildren; a brother, Norman Jowitt of Naples, Fla.; and a sister, Edith Casera of Springfield, N.J. Burial was in Elizabeth, N.J., on December 28, 1996. Memorial service to be Friday, January 3, 1997, at 1 p.m. in the chapel of the First Presbyterian Church of Knoxville with Dr. John H. Bell Jr., a grandson-in-law, officiating. Arrangements by Rose Mortuary Mann Heritage Chapel.
<P>
