<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 02, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470><BASEFONT SIZE="6">
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Sports Briefs</B></FONT><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<h3>Earl apologizes, returns to LSU basketball team </h3>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>   Highly touted freshman <B>Lester Earl </B>is back on the LSU basketball team after quitting for two days.
<P>    Earl quit on Sunday, apologized Tuesday and rejoined practice Wednesday.
<P>    Coach <B>Dale Brown </B>interrupted practice 30 minutes after it began Tuesday to let Earl apologize to his teammates for leaving. He spoke to teammates on the court and watched practice for a few minutes, but would not talk to reporters.
<P>    Brown said Earl had come to him to apologize earlier, saying he felt that he had been selfish -- not as a player, but as a person.
<P>    He quoted Earl as saying he was very disappointed in his own play, especially against Fresno State, which LSU upset 79-75 on Sunday.
<P>    He scored a game-high 23 points, but played only five minutes in the second half, when the Tigers rallied from a 22-point deficit.
<P>    &#39;&#39;He said he should have been more receptive to the team&#39;s feelings for the great win and how well people played and he&#39;s really sorry about it,&#39;&#39; Brown said.
<P>    Brown said Earl will not start in Saturday&#39;s SEC opener at Mississippi State.
<P>    Brown and Earl&#39;s older brother and teammate, <B>Louis Earl,</B> said the Parade All-American&#39;s frustration has been building because of inconsistent play this year.
<P>    He was second on the team in average minutes played (26.6) and in scoring (9.3) and third in rebounding (5.7), but had been accustomed to more at Glen Oaks High in Baton Rouge, which he led to three consecutive state  championships.
<P>    Colorado freshman guard <B>Allen Barksdale,</B> also from Baton Rouge, attended Tuesday&#39;s practice and said he is planning to transfer to LSU. Barksdale said he has left Colorado, and LSU is trying to determine when he is eligible to practice.
<P>    If he transfers, Barksdale could not play for LSU for one calendar year.
<P>
<P><h3>NFL</h3>
<P>
<P>* Vanderbilt University Medical Center has decided against competing for a contract to be the sports medicine provider for the Houston Oilers when the team moves to Nashville. Vanderbilt decided it could not be competitive with bids from Baptist Hospital and Columbia-HCA Healthcare Corp.
<P>
<P><h3>Hockey</h3>
<P>
<P>* <B>Victor Gervais </B>of the Hampton Roads Admirals was selected the East Coast Hockey League player of the week after contributing two goals and six assists in a 2-0-1 week for his team. <B>Jim Brown </B>of the Knoxville Cherokees was nominated after getting three goals and six assists in four games.
<P>* Goaltender <B>Guy Hebert </B>of the Anaheim Might Ducks bested <B>John Vanbiesbrouck </B>of Florida, stopping 28 shots for his 13th career shutout as Anaheim beat the Panthers 3-0. It was Hebert&#39;s fourth shutout of the season, tying his career best set last season.
<P>* <B>Jeremy Roenick,</B> who had 267 goals and 329 assists in eight seasons with the Chicago Blackhawks, returns to play in Chicago tonight for the first time since he became a free-agent signee with the Phoenix Coyotes.
<P>
<P><h3>Tennis</h3>
<P>
<P>* <B>Justin Gimselstob </B>and <B>Chanda Rubin </B>scored a dramatic mixed doubles victory to lift the U.S. to a 2-1 victory over defending champion Croatia in a Hopman Cup match in Perth, Australia. Rubin beat <B>Iva Majoli </B>6-3, 3-6, 7-6 (7-3) in  women&#39;s singles before <B>Goran Ivanisevic,</B> ranked No. 4 in the world, downed Gimelstob 7-6 (7-4), 4-6, 7-5. Then Gimelstob teamed with Rubin to win the decisive doubles 3-6, 6-3, 7-6 (9-7). The victory gave the U.S. a 2-0 record in the round-robin tournament and it can earn a spot in the final by beating Australia tonight.
<P>* Russia&#39;s <B>Andrei Cherkasov,</B> given a controversial wild-card berth when defending champion <B>Yevgeny Kafelnikov </B>asked for him to be included, beat Australia&#39;s <B>Patrick Rafter </B>6-2, 7-6 (15-13) in the second round of the Australian Hardcourt championship. Cherkasov, ranked 149th in the world, is Kafelnikov&#39;s training partner.
<P>* Britain&#39;s <B>Tim Henman,</B> ranked 29th in the world, advanced to the quarterfinals of the $635,000 Qatar Open with a 6-3, 6-2 victory over Egyptian qualifier <B>Tamer El Sawy</B>. <B>Thomas Muster </B>is top-seeded in the event.
<P>* Defending champion <B>Sandra Cacic </B>of the U.S. advanced to the quarterfinals of the New Zealand Classic, beating third-seeded compatriot <B>Linda Harvey-Wild </B>6-4, 7-5. Top-seeded <B>Anke Huber </B>of Germany also advanced, beating <B>Ann Grossman </B>of the U.S. 6-4, 6-2.
<P>* Top-seeded <B>Brenda Schultz-McCarthy </B>of the Netherlands beat compatriot <B>Miriam Oremans </B>7-6 (7-5), 6-0 in the second round of the Gold Coast Classic in Australia.
<P>
<P><h3>Track and field</h3>
<P>
<P>* Olympic 100-meter champion <B>Donovan Bailey </B>says he has been slighted by the American media. He is upset that he didn&#39;t receive a single vote for AP male athlete of the year. &#39;&#39;That&#39;s just the total ignorance of Americans,&#39;&#39; Bailey said. &#39;&#39;They think they&#39;re the world. They don&#39;t know what&#39;s going on in the rest of society.&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
