<head>
	<title>EPA agrees to review Champion permit</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 01, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>EPA agrees to review Champion permit</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By John Stiles, News-Sentinel state editor</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">T</FONT>he Environmental Protection Agency has agreed to &#39;&#39;review&#39;&#39; a variance for Champion International&#39;s wastewater permit, a good start to the New Year for supporters of the Pigeon River who rallied Wednesday, vowing to see the stream flow clear.
<P>   In a letter to Tennessee Attorney General Charles Burson, John H. Hankinson Jr., Region IV administrator wrote Tuesday: &#39;&#39;I will review whether additional actions are necessary in view of the new information in your letter.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Burson, on instructions from Gov. Don Sundquist, had written EPA criticizing the federal agency for granting a variance to the Clean Water Act that allows the North Carolina paper mill to dump tea-colored water into the river.
<P>   Hankinson wrote that the EPA will review Burson&#39;s contentions about errors in the manner in which EPA issued the permit.
<P>   Also Tuesday, EPA Administrator Carol M. Browner, in a letter to Burson, pledged to &#39;&#39;work closely&#39;&#39; with Sundquist.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I believe it is critical to honor the choices made by a state to protect its health and environment through the federal backstop created by the Clean Water Act,&#39;&#39; she wrote.
<P>   Hankinson also wrote that he will meet in Nashville on Tuesday, Jan. 14, with the Tennessee Environmental Council to discuss the issue.
<P>   The council is comprised of 44 environmental organizations that deal mainly with air and water issues, Alan Jones, executive director, said.
<P>   Browner&#39;s letter to Burson came one day after Vice President Al Gore told her to &#39;&#39;carefully review&#39;&#39; Tennessee&#39;s objections.
<P>   On Tuesday night the Dead Pigeon River Council gathered with other proponents of a clean river and renewed their pledge to pressure the EPA to force Champion to stop polluting the river.
<P>   An organizer, Gay Webb, said the council has been battling Champion for 10 years, and the New Year&#39;s Eve rally was to &#39;&#39;rededicate&#39;&#39; supporters.
<P>   Also Tuesday, the Tennessee Environmental Council took EPA to task for granting the variance.
<P>   Champion&#39;s paper mill in Canton, N.C., last week was awarded a variance to its wastewater permit by North Carolina. The variance calls for water to be monitored at the state line some 37 miles downstream from the plant at the Tennessee-North Carolina line.
<P>   Lifelong residents of Cocke County, Tenn., where the river flows into the state, say the water often is tea-colored and has an odor. They say it&#39;s time Champion was required to measure the color at the plant.
<P>   Supporters in recent weeks have become increasingly critical of politicians who have promised to take action on their behalf.
<P>   The waters of the Pigeon River empty into Douglas Lake and eventually make their way into Knoxville in the Tennessee River.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
