<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>Eleven eligible for attorney general</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i>January 01, 1997</i> </td>
        <td width="470"><p align="left"><font size="6"><b>Eleven
        eligible for attorney general</b></font><br>
<!--SUBHEAD-->        </p>
        <p><font size="2"><i>By Tom Humphrey, News-Sentinel
        Nashville bureau</i></font></p>
        <p><font size="3"><!--dateline--></font><br>
        <font size="5">N</font>ASHVILLE -- Eleven lawyers applied
        to become Tennessee's attorney general by the New Year's
        Eve deadline set by the state Supreme Court, which will
        pick among them in a new and more open selection process.
        </p>
        <p>If the court wants on-the-job experience, it can look
        to three lawyers who have already served as top aides to
        Tennessee attorneys general. They are Patsy Cottrell, the
        current chief deputy attorney general, and two men who
        previously held similar posts -- John Knox Walkup and
        William Hubbard, both now practicing law in Nashville. </p>
        <p>At least three other applicants are well-known to the
        Supreme Court justices and thus rated in speculation as
        strong contenders for succeeding Attorney General Charles
        Burson, who has announced his resignation effective Feb.
        14. They include: </p>
        <p>* Court of Criminal Appeals Judge Paul Summers, a
        former district attorney general from Somerville in West
        Tennessee. </p>
        <p>* Margaret Behm of Nashville, who has chaired the
        Judicial Selection Commission that nominates lawyers for
        appointment as judges by the governor. </p>
        <p>* Shelby Grubbs of Chattanooga, who served as chairman
        of the Supreme Court-appointed Alternate Dispute
        Resolution Committee, a panel that helped develop a
        system for settling squabbles through mediation rather
        than trial. </p>
        <p>Other applicants include Charles Fleischmann,
        president of the Chattanooga Bar Association; Phillip
        Noblett, also a prominent Chattanooga attorney; Michael
        Roden, an assistant U.S. attorney in Nashville; Susan
        Short Jones of Nashville; and Larry Parrish of Memphis,
        who is best-known publicly for leading a crusade for
        anti-pornography legislation in the 1970s. </p>
        <p>By non-binding tradition, the Supreme Court has chosen
        an attorney general who resides in whichever grand
        division region of the state that is home to the fewest
        Supreme Court justices. Currently, that is East
        Tennessee. Only one of the five justices -- Riley
        Anderson of Oak Ridge -- is from the eastern grand
        division. West Tennessee has two -- Justices Lyle Reid of
        Brownsville and recently appointed Janice Holder of
        Memphis. Middle Tennessee also has two -- Chief Justice
        Aldolpho A. Birch and Justice Frank Drowota, both of
        Nashville. </p>
        <p>There is also much speculation that the justices would
        like to appoint a woman as attorney general, since only
        men have held the post throughout Tennessee history and
        four of the five justices are male. </p>
        <p>In the past, the court has picked attorneys general --
        including Burson -- in a secretive, closed-door process.
        Among leading critics of that process has been Knoxville
        Mayor Victor Ashe, who has also pushed to have the
        attorney general chosen by popular vote. Tennessee is the
        only state with an attorney general selected by its state
        Supreme Court. </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

<hr size="5">

