<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>Checks keep some afloat, sink others</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 01, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>Checks keep some afloat, sink others</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Jesse Fox Mayshark, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">A</FONT>t the Interfaith Health Clinic in the 4th and Gill neighborhood, Dr. Rob McDonald and his staff see 1,000 or more working poor patients a month who don&#39;t have health insurance.
<P>   Many adults ask the doctor to give them a physical evaluation so they can apply for a federal disability check. McDonald says no.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I try to point out the importance of working and being productive because a lot of people I know who are on disability wind up becoming quite frustrated and depressed, and they don&#39;t know why,&#39;&#39; he said.
<P>   &#39;&#39;But I think it&#39;s because we were meant to work. . . . I have told people right to their face, &#39;I do not like disability because of what it does to you.&#39; &#39;&#39;
<P>    There are two kinds of disability checks: Social Security Disability Insurance (SSDI), paid to adults who have worked but become disabled, and Supplemental Security Income (SSI), a welfare program for disabled people with little or no work history.
<P>   The Social Security Administration is making changes in both programs this year to assure the checks are given to people who need them, that they&#39;re spent properly and, when possible, that they&#39;re temporary.
<P>   Starting today, the government no longer will pay people for being drug addicts or alcoholics. This summer, some children on SSI -- primarily those classified with attention deficit disorder or other behavioral disabilities -- will face re-evaluations.
<P>   And with 10.8 million Americans drawing $5.1 billion in disability checks each month, the agency wants to do what it can to be sure people don&#39;t draw a check without trying to get better.
<P>   Tom Margenau, a spokesman at the Social Security Administration&#39;s headquarters in Baltimore, said the agency is considering proposals to get more people off disability and back to work.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We&#39;ve frankly stated that we haven&#39;t done a very good job of that in the past, and the statistics bear that out,&#39;&#39; he said.
<P>
<P>Will to work?
<P>
<P>   Margenau said only 1 to 2 percent of people approved for disability leave the program because they find full-time work.
<P>   In many cases, people are permanently disabled and unemployable.
<P>   But officials think a lot of people currently on disability could be retrained for work if they&#39;re willing.
<P>   &#39;&#39;If they&#39;re interested, we will take them,&#39;&#39; said Bruce Brown, a field director for the state&#39;s Vocational Rehabilitation program. &#39;&#39;But &#39;if they&#39;re interested&#39; is the $64,000 question. A lot of times they&#39;re not.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Jim Rovere, Social Security district manager for Knox, Loudon, Sevier and Union counties, said his office refers disability applicants to Vocational Rehabilitation if there&#39;s a chance they can be retrained.
<P>   He said many people with physical disabilities can no longer do manual labor but could learn other less strenuous skills.
<P>   People on SSDI can have trial work periods of up to nine months during which they still receive their disability checks.
<P>   If they are able to keep &#39;&#39;substantial employment&#39;&#39; after nine months, the disability checks stop.
<P>   But Brown said many people referred to Vocational Rehabilitation don&#39;t participate. He said counselors contact each person at least twice to offer their services.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Since we&#39;re completely a voluntary program, a person has to want our services before we provide them,&#39;&#39; he said.
<P>   Last year in the entire state, Vocational Rehabilitation offices found full-time employment for just 186 people from SSI or SSDI programs, according to state officials.
<P>   That&#39;s not to say other people on disability don&#39;t work. James Farr, a Social Security fraud investigator, said he often finds people working and not reporting it so they can keep their disability checks.
<P>   They sometimes get caught only because they get cocky.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Sometimes it&#39;s a disgruntled spouse or relative,&#39;&#39; Farr said. &#39;&#39;It could be someone working with that person, and they&#39;re bragging about how they&#39;re ripping off the government.&#39;&#39; 
<P>
<P>Community approach
<P>
<P>   Margenau said the Social Security Administration is looking at a number of ways to get more disabled people to try working.
<P>   For one thing, the agency wants to raise awareness of the trial work period.
<P>   &#39;&#39;(People) are afraid that if they go to work, they&#39;ll automatically lose their benefits,&#39;&#39; Margenau said.
<P>   Also, the adminstration recently put out a request for proposals to coordinate resources in communities to encourage retraining and re-employment.
<P>   One of the companies offering a bid is Maximus, a for-profit social-services agency based in Virginia. Maximus has worked for Social Security before, most recently monitoring the discontinued drug and alcohol disability program.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We would come up with a nationwide list of clients who are receiving these (disability) benefits and who could benefit from vocational rehabilitation services, and then subcontractors would sign up to work with them,&#39;&#39; said Bob Muzzio, project director for Maximus.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We think that has a lot of potential because . . . it&#39;s trying to get people who are on disability into the work force. The focus would be not so much on reassessing (medical conditions) as on finding skills that would match the disability.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Muzzio said Maximus has been successful with a similar program in northern Virginia which matched up welfare recipients with agencies that can help them find employment.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We&#39;ve placed so many clients that we don&#39;t have any clients left on welfare rolls,&#39;&#39; he said.
<P>   In addition to the money saved by putting more disabled people to work, Brown said a more aggressive rehabilitation program would lift the self-esteem of those receiving the checks.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Someone once said the best therapy is a job. That&#39;s not our official motto, but it&#39;s really true,&#39;&#39; Brown said. &#39;&#39;People can have a physical disability of some sort that they&#39;re eligible (for payments) on, but the real disability would be just feeling so bad about themselves.&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

	<P><center><font size=2>Return to </font><a href="/"><font size=2>Main</font></a><font size=2>. Copyright &#169; 1996 The Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size=2>webmaster</font></a><font size=2>.</font></center></p>
