<html>
<head>
	<title>Lead story: Poll shows ouster of Justice White top story of &#39;96</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 01, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Lead story: Poll shows ouster of Justice White top story of &#39;96</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Steve Baker, Associated Press</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">M</FONT>ost Tennesseans had never heard of<B></B> <B>Richard Odom</B> when 1996 began. But as the year played out, the man convicted of murdering a 78-year-old woman played a central role in the biggest news story of the year.
<P>   Odom is the man whose death sentence was appealed to the Tennessee Supreme Court. Three of the five justices voted to overturn the sentence, ruling that the law had been wrongly applied in Odom&#39;s case.
<P>   One of those justices -- <B>Penny White </B>-- was up for re-election in August 1996, and the case became a cause for people who feel the judicial system is too soft on criminals.
<P>   In a first for the state Supreme Court, a sitting justice was voted off the bench.
<P>   &#39;&#39;People are tired of soft-on-crime judges who will look for the tiniest of technicalities to let scum go free,&#39;&#39; said <B>John Davies</B>, a Chattanooga man who campaigned for White&#39;s defeat.
<P>   The staffs of TV and radio stations and of newspapers who are members of The Associated Press in Tennessee voted White&#39;s defeat the top news story of 1996.
<P>   White&#39;s election loss beat out some big stories in balloting taken in mid-December. The rest of the top 10:
<P>
<P>F-14 Crash
<P>
<P>   Navy Lt. Cmdr. <B>Stacy Bates </B>had been visiting with his Chattanooga parents before he and another crewman climbed into their F-14 Tomcat for a return flight to California on Jan. 29.
<P>   The fighter climbed steeply from Nashville International Airport before falling into a neighborhood. Three people in a house struck by the jet were killed.
<P>   The Navy probe faulted Bates&#39; squadron commander for not grounding him after a series of mistakes months before the crash. Lawsuits against the Navy have been filed by families of the three victims killed in the house.
<P>
<P>The Oilers
<P>
<P>   After weeks of clandestine meetings, months of negotiating and a referendum, the NFL Houston Oilers are headed to Tennessee, which can count itself a player in the big leagues.
<P>   Memphis, which spent years and thousands of dollars trying to land a team, may well be the first home for the NFL franchise while a stadium is built in Nashville. Oilers owner <B>Bud Adams </B>has pitched the team as a Tennessee team, and said he wants to attract fans from Knoxville, Chattanooga and Huntsville, Ala.
<P>   A new nickname and team colors must be picked. Fans had to buy licenses for their seats in the new stadium plus tickets to the games.
<P>
<P>Gary Dockery
<P>
<P>   In 1988, police officer <B>Gary Dockery </B>was answering a call in Walden, Tenn., when he was shot in the head. The brain injury left him mute, motionless and in a nursing home.
<P>   In February 1996 he was moved to a hospital for treatment of pneumonia. His family believes he overheard them discuss whether they should let the pneumonia run its course or risk surgery.
<P>   Suddenly, Dockery began to talk. He described his Jeep, told his sons -- now 20 and 12 -- how much he loved them, recited the names of his horses and recalled camping trips he&#39;d been on.
<P>   Dockery&#39;s story inspired a nation, and especially families with relatives in comas and semi-comatose states. While Dockery didn&#39;t maintain that level of alertness, doctors say he can follow instructions and has learned to operate a motorized wheelchair by listening to a nurse&#39;s instructions.
<P>
<P>Church Arson
<P>
<P>   When the Inner City Church in Knoxville burned Jan. 8, the nation quickly riveted its attention on a series of arson attacks against black churches.
<P>   The Rev. <B>Jesse Jackson</B> came to its empty parking lot to plead for a unified defense against the attacks.
<P>   A federal task force reported that 22 Tennessee churches had been burned since January 1995, second only to the 29 destroyed in Texas. But only nine of the Tennessee churches had black congregations.
<P>   The outrage may have been re-directed, but it did not subside. Gov. <B>Don Sundquist</B> appointed a task force to devise its own strategy for fighting back. Donations poured in from people who wanted to see churches rise from the ashes.
<P>
<P>Clinton, Gore
<P>
<P>   The &#39;96 presidential election wasn&#39;t supposed to be the big event it became. Republicans made a determined run against President<B> Clinton</B>, some said to send a message to<B> Al Gore </B>that 2000 wouldn&#39;t be a cakewalk.
<P>   There were dozens of visits to Tennessee by <B>Bob Dole</B>, <B>Jack Kemp</B>, Clinton and Gore, who often took the opportunity to spend the night at his home in Carthage, Tenn.
<P>   In the end, the margin wasn&#39;t as close as expected. Clinton and Gore won four more years.
<P>
<P>Welfare Reform
<P>
<P>   Welfare reform proposed by Gov. Sundquist became effective in September, setting an 18-month limit on aid payments.
<P>   Recipients now are recertified every six months to ensure their job status and earnings haven&#39;t changed.
<P>    To help welfare recipients get work, the state has begun such programs as Fresh Start classes. Most recipients are required to take the four-week classes to increase their self-esteem, motivation and preparation for the job market.
<P>
<P>Watts Bar
<P>
<P>   Twenty-three years and $7 billion after appearing on the Tennessee Valley Authority&#39;s drawing boards, the Watts Bar Nuclear Plant in Spring City, Tenn., is producing power.
<P>   It is the last reactor on line from the agency&#39;s grand plans of the 1970s to build a network of 17 nuclear power reactors. TVA ended with five, and they produce enough power to run a million homes.
<P>
<P>The Ocoee Olympics
<P>
<P>   Cities spend millions competing for the Olympics, and when Atlanta won the &#39;96 Summer Games, some of the good fortune spilled into Tennessee.
<P>   The kayak and canoe competitions were held on the Ocoee River in the southeastern corner of the state.
<P>   Four years of preparation went into the week&#39;s activities that drew 42,000 visitors and 134 competitors from 30 countries.
<P>
<P>Lamar Alexander
<P>
<P>   The former Tennessee Republican governor&#39;s race for president didn&#39;t succeed, but it probably paved the way for another <B>Lamar Alexander</B> candidacy in 2000.
<P>   Alexander, who also was president of the University of Tennessee and U.S. secretary of education under President <B>George Bush</B>, may have company. Republicans are promoting the chances of Sen. <B>Fred Thompson</B>, R-Tenn. The lawyer-actor won a full six-year term in 1996 and has a recognizable face.
<P>
<P><font size=2><strong><p>Copyright 1996 by the Associated Press. All Rights Reserved. Unauthorized use is probihited.</p></strong></font>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
