<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 01, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Attention, shopper: Your pureed prunes are ready</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">W</FONT>hat&#39;s ahead in food trends for 1997?
<P>   The Meredith Corp., which publishes Better Homes and Gardens, offers these opinions in a press release: 
<P>   * <B>Herbs are everywhere.</B> Consider basil sorbet, cardamom scones or rosemary-orange pound cake. Mint goes in everything from marinades to soups, salads and desserts.
<P>   * <B>Tortillas.</B> Crossing all ethnic boundaries are tortillas, now being used to wrap everything, from crispy salads to teriyaki chicken and rice.
<P>   * <B>Flavored milk.</B> Milk consumption is way up. This year, make your own variety.
<P>    Blend milk with fruit, flavored syrup or chocolate peanut butter cups.
<P>   * <B>Newest coolers.</B> Iced cappuccino, coffee cola and soft-serve frozen herbal fruit teas are the latest ways to cool down.
<P>   * <B>Chef in store.</B> Some specialty supermarkets are featuring a chef who will whip up a meal from the ingredients you pick out. You get a beeper to carry so you can shop while your meal is prepared.
<P>   * <B>Fat substitutes.</B> We&#39;re hungry to know more about new releases such as olestra and fruit-based creations, including pureed prunes.
<P>   * <B>The real thing.</B> Authentic recipes, reflecting cultural heritage, are making a comeback.
<P>
<P>
<P>
