<head>
	<title>Encourage children&#39;s active play</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 01, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Encourage children&#39;s active play</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">Q</FONT><B>.</B>
<P>   My child, 10, thinks she is too fat. How can I help her lose weight without interferring with her ideal growth and development?
<P><B>A.</B>
<P>    More children are overweight now than at any other time in our nation&#39;s history. To their credit, they are expressing interest in losing the extra pounds.
<P>   Parents should encourage children to make healthy food choices -- at home and when eating at restaurants and school cafeterias. The Food Guide Pyramid offers a suitable eating pattern for children as well as adults.
<P>   Besides known health benefits of physical activity, exercise also provides children with opportunities for fun, social interaction and skill development. Substitute active play for television viewing and other sedentary activities, such as computer and video activities. The American Academy of Pediatrics recommends those activities be limited to one to two hours a day.
<P>   Parents need to be good role models and make healthy choices themselves.   Success in helping children develop healthy lifestyles depends on promoting good nutrition and providing physical activities they enjoy.
<P>
<P><B>
<P>   Information prepared by</B> Gail <B>Brooks, registered dietitian.</B> <B>Have a question for a dietitian? Send it to Ask-A-Dietitian, Knoxville District Dietetic Association, P.O. Box 50142, Knoxville, TN 37950-0142 or call</B> Dial-A-Dietitian, 524-4541.
<P>
<P>   The American Dietetic Association hotline is open 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Monday through Friday. Call 1-800-366-1655.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
