<head>
	<title>ET Briefs</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 01, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>ET Briefs</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><h3>Blaze destroys Claiborne newspaper office, records</h3>
<P>
<P>   TAZEWELL -- A fire destroyed two apartments and a Claiborne County newspaper&#39;s offices Tuesday, authorities said.
<P>   The early morning blaze heavily damaged the offices of the Claiborne Progress.
<P>   The blaze may have started in one of the apartments, authorities said.
<P>   The newspaper&#39;s archives also were heavily damaged.
<P>   Some of the archives that were destroyed had been spared in a fire at the newspaper in the 1930s, authorities said.
<P>   The Tazewell-New Tazewell Fire Department was called about 3 a.m. and remained on the site until after noon.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Middle Tennessee man accused of killing pets</h3>
<P>
<P>
<P>   FRANKLIN -- A 20-year-old Lewisburg man has been charged with beating to death five pet chickens and two rabbits.
<P>    Philip McCorkel Jr., also known as Phillip M. McCorkle, is charged with seven counts of intentional killing of an animal.
<P>    General Sessions Judge Al Nations set bond at $500 when McCorkel made a brief court appearance Friday.
<P>    A warrant signed by Animal Control Officer Bobbi Zupan said McCorkel went to the rural Williamson County home of Tammy R. Kelly on Oct. 11 without the owner&#39;s knowledge or consent.
<P>   Once there, he allegedly killed the chickens and rabbits.
<P>    The chickens and rabbits &#39;&#39;were a child&#39;s pets,&#39;&#39; said Judy Ladebauche, director of Williamson County Animal Control.
<P>   &#39;&#39;They were kept in a large fenced area on the back of the property.&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Wilson school official sued over payment of ads</h3>
<P>
<P>
<P>   MOUNT JULIET -- A newspaper is suing the Wilson County school superintendent over payment for campaign advertising.
<P>    The Mount Juliet News, a weekly newspaper, claims James Francis has not paid a $254 bill for advertising purchased in mid-July for an August election.
<P>    Francis also may face proceedings from the state Election Commission for failing to disclose a $158 advertising bill on his campaign finance statement, said Martha Ann Sutherland, Wilson County assistant election registrar.
<P>    Sutherland said her office would issue Francis a warning letter giving him 10 days to respond to the omission.
<P>   If Francis fails to file the proper forms within the required time period, it would be a violation of state campaign finance laws, she said.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
