<P><B>HARRISON, F. ALBERT - </B>age 72, of Newport, died Sunday evening in the Veterans Administration Hospital, Mt. Home, Tenn., following a short illness. Albert was a veteran of the U.S. Navy serving during WWII. He was an accomplished craftsman, who according to most of his friends, could make anything. During his career as an electrician, he wired many buildings in the Newport area plus working in various parts of the United States as a certified electrician. His latest project was to help re-wire the Belk&#39;s Building that was being renovated for use by Manes Funeral Home. He was a member of the Newport Masonic Lodge No. 234, the Kerbela Temple, Knoxville Scottish Rite Bodies, Cocke County Shrine Club, the Cocke County Scottish Rite Club. He was member of Lincoln Avenue Baptist Church. He was a member of IBEW Local No. 934, Labor Union. He was a graduate of the Bliss Electrical School, Takoma Park, Md. He is survived by his wife, Betty Harrison of the home; daughters, Mrs. Gary (Rosa Jane) Fowler of Jonesborough, Mrs. Doug (Frances) Miller of Salisbury, N.C.; son, Albert Earl Harrison of Mobile, Ala.; daughter, Susan Hardy of Kingsport; grandchildren, Jane Anne Fowler, Nathan Fowler, both of Jonesborough, Frederick and Victoria Hardy of Kingsport, Luke Miller of Salisbury, N.C.; sisters, Mrs. James E. (Emma) Wilson and Mrs. Robert (Anna) Wilson, both of Belvidere, Ill.; aunt, Zola McGaha of Newport; several nieces and nephews. Funeral services will be held at 2 p.m. Wednesday at the Manes Funeral Chapel with the Rev. Robert Walker and the Rev. Richard Willis officiating. Burial will be in Union Cemetery. The family will receive friends 6 p.m. until 8:30 p.m. Tuesday at the funeral home. Masonic Services will follow at 8:30 p.m. In lieu of flowers, donations may be made to the Cocke County Shrine Club Paper Sale to Benefit Crippled and Burned Children. Manes in charge.
